<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW,UP FOR RENEWAL, FACES TOUGH SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.199 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Senate has been using phrases like ``end game'' as it
prepares for a final vote this week on articles of impeachment
against President Clinton, but Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr
has made clear his game is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   As Starr presses ahead with prosecutions _ possibly including
Clinton _ Congress must decide the fate of the Independent Counsel
Act, the Watergate-era law used by Starr to investigage the
president.
</P>
<P>
   The law is in trouble, say both supporters and opponents, in
large part because of perceived overzealousness in Starr's 53-month
investigation of Clinton, an inquiry that has covered everything
from 1970s land deals to the president's sex life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken Starr is a poster child for killing the law,'' said
Charles Lewis, head of the Center for Public Integrity in
Washington, D.C., which monitors the influence of money in
politics. ``The whole concept could go out the window with what
this nation has been through.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr has done ``great damage'' to chances the act will be
renewed when it expires in June, agreed Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich.,
who is trying to change the law.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Clinton signed a reauthorization of the Independent
Counsel Act, hailing it as ``a foundation stone for the trust
between the government and our citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton more recently has railed against Starr for ``prying into
private lives.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the act's strong backers in Congress in 1994 was Rep.
Mike Espy of Mississippi, who later became Clinton's agriculture
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   After winning acquittal on bribery charges brought by
independent counsel Donald Smaltz, Espy vowed to be the leadoff
witness in Congress against extending the law as written.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., who voted in 1994 to renew the act,
said: ``Sometimes the cure is worse than the disease. Our
experience with Mr. Starr means at minimum massive changes when the
law comes up for renewal.''
</P>
<P>
   The public clearly has turned against the independent counsel
and his tactics. National surveys show that 60 percent of Americans
believe Starr's investigation is politically motivated. A recent
CBS News/New York Times poll found Starr with a personal approval
rating of 22 percent. A few days earlier, another national survey
gave a 40 percent approval to ``Hustler'' publisher Larry Flynt.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion seems to have come to the view given in a
much-quoted 1988 dissent by Supreme Court Justice Antonin Scalia to
a challenge to the act. In it the conservative judge warned about
the ``vast power and the immense discretion'' bestowed on
independent counsels.
</P>
<P>
   The ``most dangerous power'' of a special prosecutor, wrote
Scalia, is that ``he will pick people that he thinks he should get,
rather than cases that need to be prosecuted. With the law books
filled with a great assortment of crimes, a prosecutor stands a
fair chance of finding at least a technical violation of some act
on the part of almost anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Spawned by the Watergate scandal that brought down President
Nixon, the Independent Counsel Act was adopted in 1978, designed to
create a mechanism for evaluating evidence of wrongdoing by
high-level federal officials that would free prosecutors from
political interference.
</P>
<P>
   If the attorney general, a political appointee, found evidence
of wrongdoing, he or she is required to refer the matter to a
three-member panel of federal appellate judges. The judges pick the
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows independent prosecutors to operate virtually
without supervision, with limitless resources and unlimited time to
investigate high public officials.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the Independent Counsel Act has led to the most
costly investigations in American history. Independent Counsel
Lawrence Walsh spent $47.2 million on his probe of the Iran-Contra
scandal. Starr's investigation had cost $40.8 million through the
end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz spent more that $17 million investigating Espy for such
alleged indiscretions as accepting Super Bowl tickets and dinners.
Last year, he produced a 32-count indictment against the former
agriculture secretary. A jury acquitted Espy of all charges after a
trial in which the defense called no witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say sweeping powers can cloud independent
counsels' judgment. Investigations are sweeping up small fry and
prosecuting ``crimes the Republic can afford ot to litigate'' said
Joshua Rosenkranz of the Brennan Center for Justice at New York
University.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel David Barrett has spent three years
investigating former housing secretary Henry Cisneros for allegedly
lying to the FBI about how much money he paid a former mistress. In
addition to indicting Cisneros, Barrett has jailed the former
mistress for making false claims on a mortgage application.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have is an unlimited license with an unlimited budget
for unlimited time to rove around and dig up whatever dirt a
prosecutor can find,'' Rosenkranz said.
</P>
<P>
   Although designed specifically to remove partisanship from
investigations, politics nonetheless play a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Views of this law change with the political season,'' noted
Kevin Hamilton, a partner at Perkins Coie, Washington state's
largest law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats fervently supported independent counsels during the
Reagan-Bush years.
</P>
<P>
   An election-eve leak out of Walsh's investigation helped derail
President Bush in the 1992 campaign. Before leaving office, Bush
pardoned former defense secretary Caspar Weinberger and others
indicted by the Iran-Contra prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The law's potential for casting suspicion, even without
indictments, was already apparent. When an independent counsel
found ``insufficient credible evidence'' to indict him, former
Labor Secretary Raymond Donovan asked a memorable question: ``What
office do I go to to get my reputation back?''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have become as aggressive in demanding appointment
of special prosecutors as Democrats were in the 12 years that
Republicans held the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Five independent counsel investigations of Clinton
administration officials are under way.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has investigated the Clintons since August 1994. Smaltz
tried and failed to convict Espy. Ralph Landcaster is investigating
an allegation that Labor Secretary Alexis Herman solicited $250,000
in illegal campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett has brought a perjury indictment against Cisneros. And
Carol Elder Bruce is investigating allegations that Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt lied to Congress over Clinton campaign
contributions and rejection of a casino proposal by a Wisconsin
Indian tribe.
</P>
<P>
   The investigations have cost an estimated $70 million, and piled
up millions of dollars in costs among those caught up in the
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have expressed outrage when, in several recent
cases, Attorney General Janet Reno rejected appointment of
independent counsels.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has found no grounds to appoint an independent counsel to
investigate Clinton's role in 1996 Democratic fund raising, or to
probe whether Vice President Al Gore lied about his role in putting
together the campaign's warchest.
</P>
<P>
   She declined last week to recommend a special prosecutor to
investigate allegations of perjury against former deputy White
House chief of staff Harold Ickes.
</P>
<P>
   That marked the ``final nail'' in the coffin of the Independent
Counsel Act, said Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn. Thompson was chairman
of a Senate panel that took Ickes' testimony denying that the
administration had done favors for the Teamsters Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demise of the Independent Counsel Act when it expires this
year may be the most notable achievement of her tenure,'' Thompson
said, referring to Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's investigation has raised questions on three major
counts:
</P>
<P>
   _ Politicized prosecutors: Starr was named independent counsel
in 1994 by a panel headed by Judge David Sentelle of the U.S. Court
of Appeals for the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Sentelle is a former Republican Party official and a protege of
North Carolina Sen. Jesse Helms. Two days before Starr's
appointment, he lunched in the Senate Dining Room with Helms and
fellow North Carolina Sen. Lauch Faircloth. The men later claimed
to have talked about their prostates, not special prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they discussed, investigation of Clinton was entrusted
to a political enemy who had already given advice to Paula Jones'
lawyers in her sexual harassment suit against the president.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expandable probes: Once appointed, Starr controlled the scope
of his investigation. Were the Justice Department to object to any
expansion of his investigation _ or that of any other special
prosecutor _ Sentelle's panel makes the final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has gone far beyond his original charge of investigating a
land deal in Arkansas made while Clinton was governor. Starr was
looking into Clinton's sex life long before Linda Tripp informed
Starr's office of her taped conversations with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   _ Checks and balances: No procedures or rules have been
published dictating how an independent counsel's office should
operate. Starr has insisted his office has followed ``ordinary
prosecutorial practice.''
</P>
<P>
   But major questions have been raised about his tactics. Public
hostility toward Starr's probe has been fueled by the prolonged
imprisonment of Clinton's Whitewater business partner Susan
McDougal, the sight of Marcia Lewis _ Lewinsky's mother _ shaken
after a grand jury grilling, and explicit sexual detail in Starr's
impeachment referral to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At the Center for Public Integrity, Charles Lewis has what he
calls ``one of the most unpopular jobs'' in Washington as he argues
for reauthorization of the Independent Counsel Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starr exercised abysmally poor judgment in terms of
partisanship, and giving the impression that he was a man on a
mission,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I am not content to have attorney generals, appointed by
the president, decide on prosecutions at high levels of the
government. The issue is how to reform the (independent counsel)
act. If you overreform it, you render it useless. If you don't
reform it at all, you run the risk of another Ken Starr.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
