<P>
   SONGBOOK-ARLEN (New York) _ In inaugurating its highly
anticipated American Songbook series, Lincoln Center couldn't have
chosen more astutely than to devote its first program to the music
of Harold Arlen. Within the pantheon of pre-rock songwriters the
series was created to celebrate, Arlen, who died in 1986, is
probably the most underappreciated composer as well the one most
deeply connected to contemporary pop. By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   PINTER-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ If you doubt that there's
still major theatrical life to be derived from Harold Pinter's
version of the prototypical Woman as Sphinx, you need only see
Lindsay Duncan's quiet, shattering performance in ``Ashes to
Ashes'' at the Gramercy Theater. By Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMS-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ In his declining years, as
the spark of his genius fired less frequently and less brightly,
Tennessee Williams sought inspiration in the simpler themes that
had brought him his first success as a playwright. As evidenced in
``A Lovely Sunday for Creve Coeur,'' a 1979 play that is being
staged by the Chain Lightning Theater, he never really found it. By
Wilborn Hampton.
</P>
