A5733 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CLIPNOT-LADN-(SLA     02-08 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CLIPPERS MAKE CHICAGO HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Michael Jordan up and retires on you, don't get
worried. Get an ex-Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Bulls have done, twice. The first Air apparent
was Ron Harper, who left the Clippers after the 1993 season to play
shooting (and missing) guard in Chicago while Jordan was waving at
curveballs.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls filled their backcourt opening _ the one next to the
persevering Harper _ by hiring Brent Barry, who was a Clipper a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tough act to follow, eh?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not filling anybody's shoes but my own,'' Barry said from
the Bulls locker room before Sunday's game with his old Clippers
pals.
</P>
<P>
   When the Clippers traded soon-to-be-free-agent Barry to Miami
for soon-to-be-free-agent Ike Austin last season, it left a void in
their backcourt and highlight reel. Meanwhile, on a bench in south
Florida, Barry watched his contract expire while cooling his heels
in Pat Riley's doghouse.
</P>
<P>
   The lockout came and went. Rumors flew that the Northern
California native was supposed to be re-signed by the Heat, then
traded to the Golden State Warriors. But when the air cleared,
Barry _ a one-time winner of the NBA's slam-dunk contest _ was part
of the severe rebuilding program in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought after last season was over, I'd be going back to
Miami,'' he said. ``But I think I've found a home in Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sports Arena, which used to be home, is no more than another
office now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another game,'' Barry said, ``just another business
trip. Still, it feels a bit strange. I came here and worked very
hard. I thought I did everything I could to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's doing everything he can to prove he's a solid
all-around player.
</P>
<P>
   Riley openly questioned Barry's commitment to defense. On
Sunday, Clippers assistant Rex Kalamian said the former Oregon
State star has the quickness and instincts to lead the league in
steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least one person in the league thinks I can play defense,''
Barry said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Taylor-made injury: The right knee of Rodney Rogers bothered
the Clippers forward during training camp and kept him out of the
lineup Sunday. But teammate Maurice Taylor gets an assist.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's practice, Taylor was knocked off balance during a
drill and regained his balanced while banging into Rogers' knee.
The official wound is ``sprained right medial collateral
ligament.'' The bump was completely unintentional, by the way. But
Taylor was expected to start in Sunday's game against Chicago, in
place of the injured Rogers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
