<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5738 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-STAR-SPI &LR;      02-08 1752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-STAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON RETURNS TO SEATTLE FOR SPORTS STAR TRIBUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ We had Keith Jackson all to ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   With his soft Georgia drawl and precise manner, he stared into a
KOMO-TV camera nightly and gave us news and sports. He was on the
radio at all hours. He entered our homes from Husky Stadium, Sicks'
Stadium, Lake Washington, even the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, from the end of the Korean war to the start of
Vietnam, Jackson told Seattle who won and who died.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The networks beckoned and he would talk his way to the top of
his profession. But like a newborn, his first meaningful words were
spoken here.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the recently retired Jackson, 70, will come full
circle to connect with his broadcasting roots, receiving the
Publisher's Award at the Post-Intelligencer's 64th Sports Star of
the Year banquet at the Sheraton Seattle Hotel &AMP; Towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's where you started,'' he said. ``It was our first big
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is known as the voice of his beloved college football, a
sport he described from every national vantage point for 31 of the
past 32 years. He covered 10 Summer and Winter Olympics, major
league baseball and the first year of Monday Night Football, all
for ABC-TV.
</P>
<P>
   But before he was everyone's household guest, before there was
Coverage You Can Count On, before there were blow dryers, Jackson
diligently provided headlines and insight from a studio at Fourth
and Denny.
</P>
<P>
   He got tough with the University of Washington. He got silly
with the weatherman.
</P>
<P>
   Part of him never left.
</P>
<P>
   On a hillside overlooking Lake Washington, his stenciled name
still adorns a rusty mailbox. Badly faded, yet visible.
</P>
<P>
   The Kenmore home has changed hands at least three times. A
garage has been added, a deck extended. Another remodel is under
way. But for 40 years, the original owner's name hasn't left the
letter box _ K.M. Jackson _ providing an unofficial landmark.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson came to the city in 1954, just as local television was
getting its legs. KOMO-TV had been on the air for less than a year
when he was hired, as a recent Washington State University grad who
had spent a few months at radio station KLER in Lewiston, Idaho.
With the move, he doubled his $82.50 per week salary. He had star
quality from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the most self-assured people I've ever met in my
life,'' said Herb Robinson, Jackson's KOMO-TV co-anchor. ``He had
supreme confidence. He was a helluva find.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson regularly worked 16-hour days, chasing news and making
inroads.
</P>
<P>
   He and Robinson formed the West's first two-person TV news team.
They came on at 6:30 and 10:30 p.m., later shifting the second
newscast to 11. Jackson looked serious in his crew cut. Robinson
knew better, fighting on-air giggles as his partner made faces
off-camera.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was the first in Seattle to banter with his weatherman.
He made the other guy do a forecast from the alley as good-natured
punishment for missing a coming snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   To fulfill advertising commitments, Jackson smoked cigars and
drank milk on his newscasts. He was witty and hard-working, and
well-received by the viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won every kind of award,'' he said. ``We put Channel 4 on
the map.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and his wife, Turi, first lived in Lake City, in a small
rambler with a big back yard on 27th Avenue Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Their next-door neighbors, Lloyd and June Hughes, still reside
there. They played badminton in Jackson's back yard, monthly games
of Scrabble inside. They had chuckhole-filling parties in the
street, shared the birth of their children.
</P>
<P>
   Life in North Seattle was simple then. It was a time for dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I helped him fix his fence, just to talk to him,'' Lloyd said.
``I told him I thought he would go clear to the top in
broadcasting, and I don't remember what he said back, but it was
true.''
</P>
<P>
   After five years, Jackson moved his family a few miles north, to
a new two-story home with a lake view. It was close to Inglewood
Country Club, where he would become a member with his 7 handicap.
</P>
<P>
   He was much more famous now, but it wasn't always apparent. Not
to his new next-door neighbor in the Kenmore neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first moved in, I didn't recognize him and struck up a
conversation in the back yard,'' said Bill Guy, a retired UW
bioengineering professor. ``I didn't realize he was Keith Jackson
until I saw him on television.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson wasn't always charming and unassuming. Not when his work
was threatened.
</P>
<P>
   For eight of his 10 years in Seattle, he was the voice of Husky
football. He called back-to-back Rose Bowl victories, and reveled
in the resurgence of Jim Owens' program.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson seems most proud of battling the UW over reporter
access in 1955. He took the issue to the state Supreme Court in
Olympia, forcing the school to back down and open its doors to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The University of Washington said, `You can't come in here
with your television camera; we've sold the rights and you can't do
this,''' he recalled. ``I said, `Horse----, I'm a legitimate
newsman and, if you don't like it, throw me out,' and they did.
Guess how long that lasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson could be plenty tough. In 1956, the Husky athletic
program was about to be penalized for having a football slush fund,
and the UW tried to delay the bad news. Jackson was in no mood for
damage control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat in a hallway and (athletic director) Harvey Cassill
said, `Go away, we're not telling you anything and we're going to
get away with it,''' Jackson remembered. ``I said, `If you don't
tell us something, this is a live camera and we're going to tell
the public you won't tell us something.'''
</P>
<P>
   He earned people's respect. He was asked to broadcast Seattle
Rainiers baseball games, Seattle University basketball and the Gold
Cup hydroplane races. There was opposition to him taking the
Rainiers job; Jackson was asked to replace an ousted legend, Leo
Lassen. But he pushed ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's crowning moment came when he accompanied the UW men's
crew team to Russia. Against great odds, he did the first live
radio broadcast of a sporting event from the then-communist
country. He also taped footage with KOMO cameraman Howard Ramaley
to be shown when they returned home.
</P>
<P>
   They were hassled bringing broadcast equipment through the
Moscow airport. They were detained approaching the reservoir race
site. There were censorship tactics to sidestep. But Jackson eased
his way past each obstacle, smoothly pulling out a Seattle Police
Department press card to gain race-day entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later we talked to local press people and they started naming
off people, contemporaries, who had disappeared,'' Ramaley said,
``and they said, `You were lucky.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson ranks the groundbreaking Russian moment among his
greatest broadcasting experiences. And anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   ``That story is as good as Mark Spitz winning seven gold medals,
or Eric Heiden and five medals, or as good as two successive Super
Bowl wins,'' he said. ``It was a glorious thing. I'll never forget
it because it told me about the fiber of society. People said, `To
hell with you,' and we did it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was good. But he wasn't perfect.
</P>
<P>
   One summer, co-anchors Jackson and Robinson covered the
hydroplane races. They announced the winner and signed off. KOMO
was minutes into a movie when viewers were returned dockside for a
correction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules of the Gold Cup were complicated and we announced
the wrong winner of the race,'' Robinson said. ``We scrambled back
on the air from the lake to get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was otherwise meticulous in his work. He did a one-hour
Husky football show and often met with Owens at 2 a.m. in the
studio to rehearse.
</P>
<P>
   He was a stickler for doing things right. Johnny O'Brien, the
former Seattle University basketball standout, teamed with Jackson
to do Chieftain broadcasts. They would review game tapes together
the day after.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's ego or emotions never got in the way. He stayed
neutral at a time when broadcasters acting as team boosters or
cheerleaders was an accepted practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he tried to get extremely close to anything
where it would affect his impartiality,'' O'Brien said. ``Now I
can't speak for Washington State.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pullman, Jackson was a Georgian farm boy fresh out of the
Marines who planned to study police and political science, maybe
become a career military man. Instead, he reversed his field,
finding his livelihood and true love.
</P>
<P>
   Unimpressed by a campus broadcast of a Pullman High football
game, Jackson brazenly told WSU professor Burt Harrison he could do
better. Harrison handed him a tape recorder, sent him to another
Pullman game and said, ``Show me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in those days, I got a lot of kids who came in and
thought they were the world's greatest damn sports broadcaster, and
most weren't,'' said Harrison, now 81 and living in Albion. ``The
tape came back and, my God, he was great, absolutely great.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a self-described dreamer with no legitimate broadcast
experience, said, ``I had it in my soul all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Between broadcasts, the southerner would meet and marry Turi,
the daughter of a couple who served as clubhouse managers at the
Pullman golf course. The courtship play-by-play went like this: An
introductory conversation, movie dates and a whirlwind romance.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson started doing college football broadcasts for campus
radio station KWSC, beginning a five-decade association with the
sport. His first game was a 14-13 Cougar loss to Stanford in 1952.
He still sighs with disgust when recalling how a WSU quarterback
fumbled an extra-point snap, and that wound up making the
difference in the game.
</P>
<P>
   He recreated Cougar road games in a campus basement with Art
McDonald, a classmate who later worked with him at KOMO. They tore
wire copy _ stuff like, Smith up the middle, three yards _ and
turned out imaginative three-hour broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson impressed everyone with his style and ambition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of us knew Keith Jackson was going to be a
monumental success when he left school,'' said Geri McDonald, a WSU
classmate who owns a Seattle public-relations firm and is Art's
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has become legend, but he's still Keith. He hasn't
forgotten anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor has the Northwest forgotten him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
