<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS RALLY LATE TO DOWN BLAZERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ His name rhymes with Gucci. But Moochie Norris is no
brand-name point guard.
</P>
<P>
   He is just a journeyman insomniac, which means Norris has
difficulty sleeping most nights. The 6-foot-1 Norris might have
been ripe for a nap by game time Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And Norris might as well been sleep because for a stretch during
the Sonics' 91-88 win against Portland, he lived out a dream.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' strongest point in two regular-season games is that
they are sufficient at point guard. Clearly, all-star Gary Payton
is in midseason form after Friday's 28-point game, with Sunday's
30-point effort.
</P>
<P>
   Norris is not quite stitched with the same fiber, but he is the
real thing.
</P>
<P>
   If for only one night, Norris squelched skeptics with an
outburst that turned the game around for the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Norris single-handedly erased the Sonics' 71-61 deficit at the
start of the fourth quarter. He drained three consecutive
3-pointers. And after Dale Ellis interceded the spotlight with a
3-pointer, Norris buried a fourth bomb that tied the score at
78-78.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics outscored the Trail Blazers 30-17 in the fourth
quarter. With the game knotted at 86-86 and 2:10 left in the game,
the Sonics pulled away for good.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's jumper with the shot clock running down put the Sonics
ahead 89-86. Portland lost its shooting touch down the stretch.
Then, Dale Ellis' free throws iced the win with 2.4 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   It was Norris' four-minute flare-up got the Sonics back into a
game otherwise dominated by Portland's size and athleticism. It
also gave Norris a lifetime worth of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do whatever it takes to win a championship or make
the playoffs,''said Norris, who poured in a career-high 12 points
in the fourth-quarter comeback.
</P>
<P>
   The postseason is still three months a way. Sunday, though,
provided Norris with the most vindication he's had in a Sonic
uniform. Although he performed well throughout training camp,
Norris has heard more about the team needing a veteran backup point
guard.
</P>
<P>
   All Norris has done is methodically dispel what are considered
his weakness. He answered the notion that he can't shoot jumpers by
canning 4-of-6 crucial field goals in 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't tonight, it would have been another night,''
Sonics coach Paul Westphal said. ``The little fella can play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' coaching staff changed the mechanics of Norris' jump
shot. He no longer jumps as he releases the ball. Instead, Norris
fires his jumpers from a flat-footed stance, only bending his knees
and following through.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I took the first one, I was like, I can learn to like
this,'' said Norris, who is getting his first real chance to play
in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The experience will come with time.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talking about we need this and we need that, and he's
not supposed to be a backup to me,'' Payton said. ``And when he
goes out there and prove it like that, it's great to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris started out the game as slow as the Sonics, who trailed
49-44 at halftime. The deficit was 64-50 with 6:28 left in the
third quarter because Portland owned the paint. The Trail Blazers
scored mostly with layups and shots taken less than five feet from
the basket.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were flat. They relied mostly on jump shots and
Payton, whose fiery play and 11-of-18 shooting kept the Sonics in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Payton was on the bench when the Sonics made their
run.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal gave his superstar a break just before the third
quarter ended. Moochie, who was sluggish in his eight minutes
before entering in the fourth quarter, received a pep talk from
Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he has got to stop playing like a wimp,'' Westphal
said. ``He has to figure he's the best guy on the floor when he's
out there. You're the point guard and you're in control. Make it
your game.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the same message Payton has been sending to Norris since
he arrived in training camp two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Norris said part of his motivation has been earning Payton's
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to go anywhere and just stay on his mind,'' Norris
said. ``I want Gary to believe in me. And he's been telling me that
I belong, that I'm doing a good job. It's meant a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris realizes there is long road ahead, but he is steadily
making believers along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to see Mooch do so well because he works so hard
in practice,'' Sonic forward Vin Baker said. ``He was saying the
other day that he wanted to have a breakout game and he certainly
helped us win tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
