<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER SHIFT TO PORTLAND? NO ONE TOLD SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The high-tension, playoff-feeling,
is-this-really-only-the-first-weekend-of-a-nutball-NBA-season game
between the Sonics and Blazers proved at least one thing:
</P>
<P>
   The combined vertical leap of the Blazers' roster does indeed
exceed the height of the Space Needle.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, it is impossible at this particular time to
figure whether the Jacques Cousteau-deep Blazers can make good on
all that enviable talent.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, it did not mean squat. Or Squatch.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers' starting five of Brian Grant, Walt Williams,
Arvydas Sabonis, Isaiah Rider and Damon Stoudamire does not even
include Jimmy Jackson or Rasheed Wallace. Behind them, there is a
wave of young guns and veterans like Stacey Augmon, Greg Anthony,
John Crotty, Bonzi Wells, Kelvin Cato and Jermaine O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in a weird season like this you need depth,'' Williams
said, thinking ahead to the 49 games left to be played in 87 days.
</P>
<P>
   For just such depth, NBA pundits have the Blazers finishing
either No. 7 in the West or as NBA champs. This would mean that the
jury is not only out on Portland, it may also be smoking some of
the stuff that once got Rider arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, judging from the first three quarters of the showdown
with the Interstate-5 rival Sonics, this is not a Pacific Division
team anybody would want to mess with.
</P>
<P>
   Stacked with talent from 1-through-14, the Blazers are almost as
flush as Bill Gates and Paul Allen.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe not that flush; it's just that both Microsoft
co-founders were in the house at KeyArena, where Allen, the
Seahawks and Blazers owner, looked like he was having some fun, at
least until the fourth quarter, when the Sonics soared to a 91-88
comeback win.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Blazers have Wallace and Mighty Mouse, Rider and Grant
as testimony to aggressive drafting and signing of young guns who
could make Portland a power base again in the West.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, the Lakers have Kobe Bryant, the Nuggest have Antonio
McDyess, the Timberwolves have Stephon Marbury, and the Nets,
Celtics and Sixers have Keith Van Horn, Antwan Walker and Allen
Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, not to be left out of the sweepstakes to sign
big-name, high-priced talent, have Moochie Norris.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, Moochie.
</P>
<P>
   In one of nightcaps for the NBA's first prime-time Sundays of
this nutball season, the league forgot to send network TV cameras
to the game where the league's latest, greatest saving grace was
getting it done.
</P>
<P>
   The call was ``Moochie for three!'' as the little man drained
`em to his own delight and to the packed (and unapathetic) KeyArena
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   In the mind-bending vacuum created by the departure of You Know
Who, the lords of the hardcourt went to great lengths to come up
with a suitable replacement, be it Kobe or Keith or whoever.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Blazers have sought that angle with the $81
million signing of Stoudamire _ a terrific playmaker who still
needs time to get Rider to stop trying to perform 360-degree spin
moves that result in offensive fouls or long-range bombs that waste
as many possessions as he can turn into gold.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, despite a lack of big-name free agent deals in this
fax-and-cell-phone post-lockout signing period, the Sonics were not
to be outdone by the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were willing to go to great lengths, too, which
explains why most of the coaching staff took a little trip east
over Snoqualmie Pass to The Palm Springs of the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   People, the sacred land we are talking about is Yakima. And in a
CBA game between the Sun Kings and Fort Wayne Fury, the Sonics
found their back-up point guard, Moochie, who torched the Blazers
in the first eight minutes of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Norris hit four treys, grabbed a big rebound and fed Detlef
Schrempf on a crucial assist to lead the Sonics back from a 71-61
deficit to the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, we took a road trip to Yakima,'' Sonic assistant
coach Dwane Casey said after Norris and Gary Payton (32 points, 6
assists) broke down the Blazers in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little scary going over the pass with (head coach)
Paul (Westphal) driving. He's from Phoenix, so I don't think he's
ever driven in snow before. But I knew Moochie's college coach and
I had seen him play. We knew he was an NBA point guard. We knew
about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mighty Mouse vs. Moochie.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly an NBA ratings match-up like Gary Payton vs.
Sir Air, but the Sonics will take the advantage and run with it.
For at least one game, the Sonics showed they have the firepower to
stave off the franchise most pegged to be the NBA's up-and-comer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got a great group of guys. They have a great team, but
I'm not around them. Those predictions are just people putting
things on them, but what does it mean?'' Payton said.
</P>
<P>
   If the NBA power shift from the Emerald City to the Rose City is
underway, someone forgot to tell the Sonics. And, more important,
they forgot to tell Moochie.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 0100EST &QL; 
