<HEADLINE>
EASING TENSIONS, DISNEY GAINS O.K. TO SHOW `MULAN' IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Ending a de facto ban on new Walt Disney movies here,
China announced on Monday that it was allowing theatrical release
of ``Mulan,'' the cartoon feature based on a Chinese myth.
</P>
<P>
   The recent agreement to show ``Mulan'' in China marks the
apparent smoothing over of high-stakes tensions between the Walt
Disney Co., which is anxious to enter the China market in a major
way with its films and other products, and the government, which
keeps a firm grip on the movie industry.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's efforts to cultivate Chinese officials were suddenly
derailed in 1996, when Chinese officials expressed anger over
Disney backing of ``Kundun,'' a film sympathatic to the Dalai Lama.
Disney refused to back down and distributed the film directed by
Martin Scorcese.
</P>
<P>
   But Disney executives have sought to regain favor ever since,
among others things holding out the carrot of a possible Disney
theme park in China, and their success was reflected in Monday's
official announcement.
</P>
<P>
   According to the New China News Agency, ``Mulan'' will open
later this month in the port city of Tianjin, then in April in
Beijing. The announcement did not say when the movie would open in
other major cities.
</P>
<P>
   Only about ten foreign films are allowed to play commercially
here each year, as the government tries to protect the domestic
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Disney had applied to distribute ``Mulan'' in China last year,
when it opened elsewhere, but was turned down. ``The film was well
shot but importing `Mulan' is a complicated issue,'' a Chinese
official said then.
</P>
<P>
   A recent issue of China Entertainment Network News, a newsletter
published in Shanghai, said that as part of its strategy during the
last year of regaining favor in China, Disney bought the foreign
distribution rights to two Chinese feature films and hired a
Chinese performance troupe to participate in the European release
of ``Mulan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Disney chairman, Michael Eisner, visited China last October
to meet with top officials. A major topic of discussion, say people
familiar the matter, was the possibility of building a Disney theme
park in China.
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts, Disney said it preferred to locate such a park
in the relatively prosperous enclave of Hong Kong, formally part of
China. But Chinese officials said any park must be built on the
mainland. Shanghai made a strong play for the park to Eisner during
his visit.
</P>
<P>
   Disney is reportedy now actively considering locating a park in
the more prosperous, capitalist areas of southern China. If the
park were located near Hong Kong, tourists could be attracted from
there as well as the mainland. Another site under discussion is
Hainan Island, a semi-tropical tourist destination off of southern
China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
