</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-RANGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON SNAPS BRUINS OUT OF DOLDRUMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A year ago, heck, a few months ago, Joe Thornton
wouldn't have been the center on a checking line against Wayne
Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of this season, his second in the NHL, the
19-year-old Thornton wouldn't have had the patience or experience
late in a tie game to wait out veteran Rangers goalie Mike Richter,
shift to his backhand, and bury a beauty of a shot to give his team
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   That was then, this is now. Thornton, whose education has been
chronicled daily since he was selected by the Bruins with the first
overall pick in the 1997 draft, has begun to blossom into the
player the team had hoped for. That was perfectly illustrated
Sunday when Thornton took a pass from Antti Laaksonen and scored,
rescuing the Bruins from the Rangers, 3-2, at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   It was Thornton's 10th goal of the year but the biggest of his
young career.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first victory for Boston since Jan. 18, ending the
club's winless skid at eight games (0-6-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``Antti made a good play, just chipping it by the two
defensemen,'' said Thornton. ``I came through and was lucky to beat
Richter. The two defensemen went right at Antti and just left me
wide open. I don't know if I would've made it last year or not. In
a 2-2 game like that, I think I would've stayed back. I don't think
I would've forced that play like that last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins jumped out to a 2-0 lead on goals by Sergei Samsonov
(No. 18) and Dmitri Khristich (No. 21). Samsonov scored on the
power play at 15:01 of the first and Khristich beat Richter at
16:27 of the second, a period in which the Rangers vastly outplayed
the Bruins as well as outshot them, 13-3.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble really started for Boston midway through the third.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Brian Leetch took a centering pass from Brent Fedyk
and beat goalie Byron Dafoe to pull within 2-1 at 9:36. The Rangers
tied it during a Boston power play. Defenseman Jeff Beukeboom tried
to clear the puck out and wound up with a fortuitous bounce for New
York. Bruins captain Ray Bourque put his hand up to his face, the
puck glanced off his glove, then his helmet, and Adam Graves took
off down the ice on a breakaway, tying the game at 12:21.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit my glove first,'' said Bourque. ``I thought I had it. I
put my glove right in front of my face and kind of blinded myself.
It caught me in the side of the head and bounced right towards him.
I was praying (Dafoe) would make the save and I could get the
rebound, but he made a good shot and scored a nice goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came Thornton's moment in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tim Taylor went down early in the game,'' said coach Pat
Burns, referring to Taylor getting hit in the face with the puck,
requiring him to have stitches, ``I put Joe back out there with
(P.J.) Axelsson and (Rob) DiMaio and said, `No. 99 is your guy
now.' He took the challenge, which is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton knew he would have to play very responsibly with
Axelsson and DiMaio, with whom he had played before.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Timmy got hurt, I had to fill in Timmy's spot,'' said
Thornton. ``Whenever you go against Gretzky, it's a fun time. I've
never played against him so it was extra special for me. To get the
game-winner was special also.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said he was impressed by the poise Thornton showed
Sunday and by his overall development. As up and down as the season
has been so far, Bourque said Thornton's emergence has been very
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of happened bang-bang,'' said Bourque of Thornton's
goal. ``Last year he probably would've shot it from the high slot
or something like that. But he took control and made a really nice
move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really seen a big difference in Joe. He's been given a
bigger role. He wants to be a good player. He knows there are
certain things he has to go through and there are more he'll have
to go through. I think he's going to be a real good player for a
lot of years in this league. He's only going to get better and
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Against Gretzky), you saw how he just picked up his game when
he got with those two guys. I noticed it right away. It kind of
opens your eyes as to what's there and what's going to be there for
years to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
