<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO NEEDS MJ?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Several years ago, then-Clipper Ron Harper defined
another tact-numbing defeat with a deep breath, a furtive glance
around the Sports Arena and this declaration:
</P>
<P>
   ``We stink.''
</P>
<P>
   For Harper, Sunday's return to Clippers central must have felt
like a whiff of ambrosia. After 48 minutes of basketball, he and
his Chicago Bulls teammates smelled like . . . victory, an 89-84
victory.
</P>
<P>
   To the veteran guard, there should be no place like this old
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should burn it down,'' said Harper of the vintage hoop
venue.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team generated the requisite temperature for that, but
any win will be appreciated by the three-time defending NBA champs.
Under first-year coach Tim Floyd, they were expected to tour the
league while developing an overpowering need for Michael Jordan
cologne.
</P>
<P>
   During a ripe first quarter, it might have been wise to give the
Clippers an aroma-altering blast. Their inertia on the glass
enabled the Bulls to snag 11 offensive boards and post a rebounding
margin of 20-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were done in by our lack of rebounding from the very outset
of the game,'' Clippers coach Chris Ford said. ``Our defense was
not that bad; it was our lack of rebounding.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense wasn't so hot, either. While the Bulls shot just 40
percent from the floor, the Clippers' percentage was a scalding 37.
Their muddled offensive flow and subsequent chilly shooting was
underscored by a dubious Clippers record of five team assists.
Right, five for the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford couldn't block out the recent memory of that dismal
rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be more physical,'' he said. ``There's no reason
why we shouldn't be a good rebounding team; we've got size, we've
got bulk.''
</P>
<P>
   What they didn't have was power forward Rodney Rogers, who has a
bit too much bulk and a gimpy right knee. Maurice Taylor started in
his place and willed 14 points but contributed only 4 rebounds in
32 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago finished its first victory since a recent superstar
purge with a 50-37 rebounding edge. Toni Kukoc, Chicago's new
leading man, scored 22 points, had 11 assists and grabbed 9
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player,'' said Clippers forward Lamond Murray,
who bagged 20 points. ``The guy's 6-11, he's out there handling the
ball; that's gonna present some problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they (Bulls) are still solid. But what killed us was
not boxing out well.''
</P>
<P>
   Those 11 offensive rebounds provided an opportunity for Kukoc to
throw in 14 first-quarter points. At the end of the period, Bulls
backup center Bill Wennington drilled the fifth 3-pointer of his
career to leave the home team in a 33-16 hole.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Harper sliced to the hoop for two of his 20
points, giving Chicago its largest advantage of the night at 45-25.
</P>
<P>
   But playmaker Darrick Martin and rookie center Michael
Olowokandi had nine and seven points, respectively, as the Clippers
rallied to outscore the Bulls 23-20 in the second quarter.
Olowokandi finished with 12 points and six rebounds in 28 minutes.
But he didn't finish his work day until spending a few postgame
minutes pumping iron in the weight room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys played hard,'' Ford said. ``They didn't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   And they closed to within a deuce, at 70-68, when Murray hit a
15-foot fadeaway over Kukoc with 10:24 left in the game. The Bulls
extended the lead to nine, but another Murray-over-Kukoc bucket cut
it to 82-80 with 1:50 remaining. Martin drove for a score and the
Clippers trailed 85-84 with 24 seconds to play. Harper made a free
throw with 17.2 left, but the Clippers ran out of rally juice when
Martin missed on a 3-pointer with 10 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we're a sorry team,'' Harper said, ``but that's
not true. We'll be all right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
