u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-B     02-08 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE? GIVE MORE ICE TO THORNTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ It's time to play the legs off Joe Thornton. Get him
out there. Now. Every second shift. Every power play, not as the
second-line center, but as a wing on the No. 1 unit.
</P>
<P>
   Play him, play him, play him. Play him until he comes back to
the bench, oxygen-starved, rubber-legged, every muscle burning,
looking like he just took on Heartbreak Hill in Byron Dafoe's full
metal jacket.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins do that, they'll make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And if they don't do that ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' said Bruins coach Pat Burns, pulling on his overcoat
after Sunday's exciting 3-2 win over the Rangers, ``right now I'll
take all suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 suggestion: Knock Dmitri Khristich off right wing of the
do-nothing/-nothing-doing power play (Burns: ``I don't know what it
is, but he's not firing'') and park Jumbo Joe there, with Jason
Allison in the middle and Sergei Samsonov on the wing. Watch the
back half of a penalty-kill box deal with that trio. After a minute
of that _ provided the puck isn't already in the net _ keep Allison
out there and sub in two other wings (the ones who are skating the
best that day).
</P>
<P>
   ``Allison could do that, he could play the full two minutes,''
said Burns. ``And, yeah, Joe could play the wing ... no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Allison can't hack the extra 60 seconds, see if Thornton
is up to working the full advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Now halfway through his second big-league season, Thornton shows
every sign of _ and this is the most important part, folks _
wanting to be out there. I'm not saying that because of his winning
goal Sunday _ which in itself was a pretty piece of work, a nice
backhand pop off the rush _ but because of the way he is skating.
Whether he's on the puck or just simply on the ice, Thornton is now
using his legs and making the obvious connection between cerebral
matter and stepping on the gas.
</P>
<P>
   He's no longer the kid on a field trip, staring out the bus
window. He's 19, skating, and he's got game. This is why he was the
No. 1 pick in the June 1997 draft. He's gone from franchise
credentials to looking franchise-ready.
</P>
<P>
   Give him the minutes. See how he runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play a lot,'' said Thornton. ``Every game I want to
play a lot. And I am playing more.''
</P>
<P>
   More, but not enough. He finished with 18 minutes 16 seconds on
his stat sheet Sunday. I know it's apples and oranges, but
defenseman Dave Ellett finished with 21:02. There are 12 forwards
and only six defensemen. But I want to look up each night and see
that Thornton's time on ice is equal to the likes of Ellett and Hal
Gill (21:55). I want to see him dead even with Allison (23:03).
Cheating him of minutes is cheating his growth, and possibly
cheating the chance of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Taylor needed some stitch work in the first period Sunday
and Thornton had to move into his slot spot between P.J. Axelsson
and Rob DiMaio. Guess what? He thrived on it. Opposite Thornton was
Wayne Gretzky, who was once The Kid, once the unproven phenom
craving, and then devouring, the minutes handed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-nine's your guy now,'' said Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton held his own against the Great One and also put an
obvious charge into his wingers. He didn't sag back, stand there,
look to reload the bus on the field trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you go against Gretzky it's a fun time,'' said
Thornton. ``Actually, that's the first time I've ever done that.''
</P>
<P>
   If Burns &AMP; Co. buy into the Full Joe program, there are bound to
be some embarrassing moments. To play the legs off him now
undoubtedly will bring some flat-out failure(s). At a time like
this, with their fingertips barely touching that No. 8 playoff
spot, the risk will bring painful results.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Joe wasn't so Jumbo in Saturday's 2-2 tie in
Philadelphia. And why? He forgot to skate. For 65 minutes, he was
barely visible. Is that going to happen again? Of course. But the
bet here is, the hotter his legs are, they'll retain the heat.
Asked to skate more, he will skate more. Put in more pressure
situations, he'll turn into the go-to guy everyone was hearing and
dreaming about not even two summers ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on him, every day we talk to him about it,'' said Burns,
referring specifically to Thornton's skating and his overall on-ice
awareness. ``We want him to skate first and then do the play.''
</P>
<P>
   The last month or so, in which the Bruins have gone an abysmal
2-8-3, has shown that the players here, playing in the line
combinations and defensive pairings in which they've played, cannot
make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Bruins go out and make big trades? No.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Bruins call up more minor leaguers and expect a rainbow
to appear over the bench? Uh-uh.
</P>
<P>
   What they can do, what they have to do, is take the parts on
hand and use them differently. The key to that _ and perhaps the
only answer _ is to make sure Thornton plays every minute over
every game that he can play.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sense in waiting any longer. He's here. He's ready.
</P>
<P>
   And so is a legion of fandom that has been waiting for something
like this for a very, very long time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
