<SLUG> BC-GLF-NATIONAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT A TOTAL WASHOUT FOR STEWART 
</HEADLINE>
 PRO AM-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ At least this year, they didn't have to
wait six months to crown a champion. And for that Payne Stewart can
be thankful.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in four years, rain was a factor in the final
round of the AT&AMP;T National Pro Am at Pebble Beach, as play was
suspended at 9:30 Sunday morning because of standing water on the
greens and was not resumed, although tour officials waited until
2:10 p.m. before making an official announcement.
</P>
<P>
   With the forecast calling for more rain all day Monday _ storms
waiting to hit the West Coast were lined up all the way across the
Pacific to Japan _ officials decided to conclude the tournament
after 54 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Which was good news for Stewart, whose 10-under-par 69-64-73_206
through three rounds was good enough to earn him a one-shot victory
over Frank Lickliter, giving him his first win since the Shell
Houston Open in 1995 and only his second tour win since taking the
US Open in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-am portion of this unique tournament format, which
allows amateur partners to participate in the final round, ended in
a three-way tie between Lickliter and Bob MacDonnell, Craig Stadler
and Glenn Frey, and Neal Lancaster and Robert Scott, at 22-under
194.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the way I played,'' said Stewart, who never even
teed off Sunday since play was suspended before the final three
groups could get under way. ``I'm hitting the ball well, the best I
have in years.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspension of play was disappointing for several golfers who
began playing before conditions worsened. It was particularly
maddening for defending champion Phil Mickelson, who birdied two of
his first three holes before play was stopped.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, the world's hottest golfer who shot a 13-under
final-round 59 two weeks ago to win the Bob Hope Classic, began his
round with an eagle on the par-4 373-yard first hole, holing out an
8-iron from 135 yards to go to 5 under.
</P>
<P>
   And Lickliter, just a shot off at the start of the round, got no
opportunity to catch up. ``I don't feel cheated,'' he said. ``I
just feel disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather has become a Pebble Beach tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, Mickelson and the field were able to
play only nine holes during the first two rounds on Thursday and
Friday before an El Nino-caused storm moved in after Saturday's
third round, forcing postponement of the final round until Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who picked up a check worth $504,000 for his three
rounds of work, was not apologizing for his good fortune. ``I've
been on the short end of 54,'' said Stewart, who concluded his play
by hitting a 5-iron within a foot of the cup on the 18th Saturday
that gave him a tap-in for a birdie at Spyglass, which had the most
benign conditions of three courses used for the first three rounds.
``It evens itself out.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was referring to the rain-shortened 1986 tournament in
which Fuzzy Zoeller was declared a winner after three rounds when
rain washed out Friday's second round and Monday's fourth, giving
Zoeller a five-shot win over Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the mystique of Pebble Beach is the weather, which can
humble even the greatest golfers. Saturday, for example, with a
steady rain in the afternoon accompanied by 40-m.p.h. hour winds,
the average score was 79.3, with not one golfer able to break par
72.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said he wanted to win a four-round tournament, but he
also understood the circumstances. ``I know it's not tainted. You
come here, you know the possibility exists the weather is liable to
be bad, so you have to go out and score early.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of a real downpour, it became clear that the
greens rapidly were becoming unplayable. Duval, who played only one
hole, knew what to expect. ``He came back in and said, `We're not
going out there again,''' said Stewart, who was 20 minutes away
from his tee time when play was suspended. For Stewart, it's a
starting point for a season that he hopes includes a trip to The
Country Club in Brookline in September as a member of the Ryder Cup
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win again,'' said Stewart. ``And I want to be on the
Ryder Cup team because I'm tired of losing. The last two times, I
wasn't on the team and we didn't win. So I need to get on the team.
I've got a lot of enthusiasm and when I play the Ryder Cup, it
shows. I can bring that back to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's results didn't hurt those chances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
