<SLUG> BC-SKI-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE MEDALS FOR AUSTRIA 
</HEADLINE>
 ALPINE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ The headline on a Viennese newspaper story Sunday
read: ``Where's the competition?'' in reference to Austria's
dominance of the World Alpine Championships.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared after Hermann Maier's devastating run down the
fearsome Birds of Prey downhill course Saturday, which boosted
Austria's medal count to seven of 12. Maier also tied for gold in
the Super-G last week.
</P>
<P>
   So what will Monday's headline read?
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Austrian women downhillers bettered the men by winning
the top four spots in the race, wiping out any hope of the Germans
and French. Medal count after the event: 10 of 15.
</P>
<P>
   Renate Goetschl, a 27-year-old who was favored to win, came
through with flying (red and white) colors, taking the lead from
two teammates who were waiting anxiously in the finish area.
</P>
<P>
   Michaela Dorfmeister took the silver, nipping Stefanie Schuster
by 17/100ths of a second.
</P>
<P>
   The best United States finish came from Alaska's Megan Gerety,
who placed eighth. Despite her Top 10 finish, Gerety said, ``I'm
really disappointed. I was hoping for a podium finish, or at least
a top six. I skied great over the top of the course, but then lost
some time lower when I made a couple of mistakes in the jumps.''
</P>
<P>
   A boisterous crowd estimated at 20,000 packed the finish stadium
and snowshoed up along the high-speed race course down the
International Trail. From the oompah band and the clanking of
dozens of cowbells every time an Austrian kicked out of the start,
it was clear that country brought its own fan contingent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand,'' said Goetschl, ``ski racing in
Austria is like basketball or football here. It is the No. 1 sport.
We have great support.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in second position, Schuster, a 29-year-old veteran who
skied in the '89 Vail Worlds, held a lead while several big guns
took shots at her time. But the top Norwegians, Swiss, and Germans
kept missing the mark, particularly on the lower technical part of
the course, and nobody threatened until Dorfmeister. Running 18th,
the Olympic silver medalist nipped Schuster's time by 15/100ths of
a second, and both watched as Goetschl kicked out of the start.
</P>
<P>
   Already having won two silver medals here this week, Goetschl
was nearly perfect over the flats on top, and charged through the
technical part, reminiscent of Maier's hard-charging, high-risk
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was just to win a medal,'' said Goetschl. ``But this
is just unbelievable. This has been just an unbelievable week for
me. I stood in the start and said I was going to fight really hard.
I skied well and made no mistakes. We three Austrians had really
good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the Austrians are so dominant is the talk of these
``off-year Olympics.'' Heavy government support and a large
organization are two reasons, say Austrian coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, we are competitive with one another,'' said Dorfmeister.
``We support each other a great deal, but when we are racing for
points, we ski for a result.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten Clark, from Raymond, Maine, finished 16th. While this
year has been disappointing so far, Clark said her finish ``gives
me a boost of confidence for the rest of the season.'' The next US
finisher was Jonna Mendes in 25th.
</P>
<P>
   But as the oompah band pumped away and the Austrians basked on
the podium in the Colorado sunshine, it was clear that the US _ and
all the other teams _ have a long way to go before ``Where's the
competition?'' has an answer.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the greatest rivalry is cross-gender. ``Today I
heard the boys say that the women won three medals,'' said
Schuster. ``So they say, `We will have to be stronger to stay with
them.'''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the men's downhill combined runs on the Birds of Prey
course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
