<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5788 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-NEWBALANCETRACK-B     02-08 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BALANCE MEET PROVES EVENTFUL 
</HEADLINE>
 BALANCE TRACK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Woman No. 1, the one with her heart set on breaking the
American indoor record for 3,000 meters, didn't get to so much as
try. Woman No. 2, the one who broke the US pole vault record Friday
night, broke it again. Woman No. 3, the one who chopped off her
signature ponytail when she turned 30 recently, won the 800 meters
in what might be an American record but, then again, it might not.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and the men's 60 meters was the fastest ever run in the US,
while the hometown hero in the 400 fell and didn't finish.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing quite like a track meet, and the 1,800 or so
fans who rocked the Reggie Lewis Track and Athletic Center for
Sunday's fourth annual New Balance Invitational got a chance to
experience firsthand the sport in all its glorious quirkiness.
</P>
<P>
   First, the men's 60 meters, which Maurice Greene blistered in
6.45 seconds despite the race being called back twice by false
starts. ``I'm kind of glad,'' said Greene, who last year set the
world record of 6.39, ``because the first time I wasn't reacting
well. It kind of woke me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, the reigning world champion at 100 meters, ran 6.51
Friday night in winning at the Millrose Games in Madison Square
Garden after a bad start. ``I believe if I run my race, the record
will come, but it's still early in the season,'' he said after a
giddy victory lap. Vincent Henderson ran 6.67 for second.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 400, the spotlight was on Calvin Davis, the
Dorchester native who won a bronze medal in the 1996 Olympics as a
newcomer to the 400-meter hurdles. Sunday, while rounding the first
turn midway through the 400 flat, he fell after being jostled,
rolling into the infield and out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indoors, contact's bound to happen,'' said Davis, back in
Boston from Columbia, S.C., to compete in front of family and
friends. ``But that was really rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman No. 1 is Regina Jacobs, who won the mile Friday night at
the Millrose Games in 4 minutes 31 seconds and had planned an
assault on the US mark at 3,000 meters here until she woke up with
a temperature of 101 degrees, a victim of the flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really disappointing,'' said Jacobs, who appeared
briefly to apologize to the spectators after being forbidden from
running by her coach and husband, Tom Craig, on doctor's advice.
``After racing the other night in New York, I knew the record was
gone. It was going to be broken, and it was going to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs wasn't the only competitor in the 3,000 to turn up ill,
so the race was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   After her winning jump of 14 feet 8 3/4 inches at Millrose broke
Stacy Dragila's US record by a half inch, Woman No. 2, Melissa
Mueller of Phoenix, bettered herself Sunday when she vaulted 14-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was coming and that I was going to do it pretty
soon,'' said the 26-year-old Mueller, who while attending the
University of Wisconsin-Oshkosh was the Division 3 national
champion at both the hurdles and high jump. Three years ago, she
switched to the pole vault, a relatively new event for women.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing new about the women's 800 record of 1:58.9,
set by Mary Slaney in 1980. And therein lies a mystery to Suzy
Hamilton's victory Sunday, in which Woman No. 3 ran on the shoulder
of Harvard graduate Meredith Rainey Valmon until the last lap,
overtaking her on the turn coming out of the backstretch to triumph
in 1:58.92. Because Slaney's race 19 years ago was hand-timed, a
method much less sensitive than today's electronic devices,
Hamilton's time will be submitted to USA Track &AMP; Field for their
review as the American record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
