   D. Concern and Hope in Jordan
</P>
<P>
   By Ben Lynfield. From The Jerusalem Post. 800 words
</P>
<P>
   E. The Best Tribute to King Hussein of Jordan : Peace
</P>
<P>
   By Mikhail Gorbachev. From La Stampa. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   F. The Enduring Work of King Hussein
</P>
<P>
   By James Baker III, former U.S. Secretary of State. NYT Op-Ed.
800 words.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE MYSTERIES OF BILL CLINTON Article on the Clinton scandal
by Gabriel Garcia Marquez, who knows Clinton personally. From
Cambio magazine. 2,000 words. (English translation available.) Not
available Colombia, Brazil, Mexico, Venezuela, Spain, Italy, Peru,
Chile and Argentina. 3. FINDING ANTIBIOTICS IN UNEXPECTED PLACES :
FROGS Like many other researchers, Michael Zasloff made his
discovery as a fortuitous accident. He was doing genetic research
on frogs when he noticed that after he operated on them in a
non-sterile environment, the wounds never became infected. Guessing
that something in their skin was protecting them from bacterial
attack, he discovered a peptide, which he named magainin. He
proceded to find peptide antibiotics in a host of other animals.
Zasloff is turning these peptides into antibiotic drugs for humans
in the hope of providing an alternative or an adjunct to existing
drugs. Clinical trials are now taking place. By Josie Glausiusz.
From Discover magazine. 1,000 words + photos. 4. From NATURE NEWS
SERVICE (N/A France and Spain)
</P>
<P>
   A. Sticky Situations Why is sticky tape sticky? Why does a
toffee apple stick to the paper bag? Researchers in France claim to
have solved the puzzle of what makes a substance tacky. By Phillip
Ball. 500 words. (For immediate release.)
</P>
<P>
   B. Counting the Cost of Cyclosporine An increased risk of cancer
is one of the most feared side-effects of the powerful
immuno-suppressant drugs which have improved the success of organ
and bone marrow transplantation. Researchers have found that
cyclosporine, one of the most effective and commonly used
immuno-suppressant drugs, may be acting on the cancer cells
themselves to render them more invasive. By Eleanor Lawrence. 600
words. (Embargo 19h00 GMT, Feb. 10)
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
LOOK WHO'S TALKING The Amish communities of Pennsylvania in the
United States are famous for shunning technology. But their secret
love affair with the cell phone is causing an uproar. By Howard
Rheingold. WIRED magazine. 2,500 words. (N/A Japan.)
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
From MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE :
</P>
<P>
   A. Link Between Stroke, Clotting Gene Defect A gene defect that
alters the blood-clotting process has been linked to an increased
risk of strokes that occur at an early age. By Charles Bankhead.
500 words. B. Diet Tops Vitamin Pills For Healthy Heart Taking
vitamin pills to protect against heart disease is no substitute for
a balanced diet, researchers in the U.S. have found. By Suzanne
Leigh. 500 words. C. Hand Transplants Unlikely to Bring Wave of
Imitators The world's two (so far) successful hand transplants have
left medical experts puzzling over how to view a procedure that
can't save a life, but can conceivably end it. By Amy Norton. 500
words. Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81 I
