<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 08:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5879 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-CONTEST-KAN &LR;      02-08 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-CONTEST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE RELIGION AND SCIENCE ONLY IF IT'S FOR A PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can, if you want, make the argument that science has brought
us the possibility of nuclear destruction. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, you can make the argument that religion has brought
us such horrors as ethnic cleansing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying I would make those arguments, though I might. In
fact, I prefer not to tell you what I would say about those matters
in case I decide to compete against you in this year's Great
American Think-Off, which will focus on this question: ``Which Is
More Dangerous: Science or Religion?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The GATO, as I like to call it, is a slick national philosophy
contest that results in a debate held in New York Mills, Minn.,
which claims a population of 972. Each year the GATO invites
ordinary people (what it likes to call ``thinking citizens'') to
write 750-word essays about the selected topic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the contest has been around for several years, I have
yet to enter it. I have not wanted to take advantage of my
profession as a columnist who strings together veritable necklaces
of lovely words every day. Well, it's either that or my fear that
my traditional approach to these weighty subjects _ an approach
that includes rambling around through one digression after another
_ would not find favor among the muckety-muck judges of the GATO. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, I'm tempted. Science and religion, after
all, are two of my favorite subjects. My stock of opinions about
them has gotten so crowdy _ despite my shoveling them into public
print with regularity _ that I may never get them all out if I
don't take advantage of opportunities like this. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't tell you that to scare you away from entering. But I do
want you to be aware that if I leap into the contest this year you
will be hard pressed to come up a winner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you want to try, here is what you need to know: Essays
must be postmarked by April 5. Send them to Think-Off '99, Box 246,
New York Mills, Minn., 56567. Or e-mail them to
nymills(at)uslink.net, though not as an attachment. (Or go to
www.kulcher.org.) If you are one of the four finalists you will get
a free trip to New York Mills for the June 12 debate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   June 12? I know what you're thinking. That's when the Buzzard
Days Festival takes place in Glendive, Mont. Yes, and it will also
be George Bush's 75th birthday. But you've simply got to make
choices. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rules also say that essays ``should be based on personal
experience and observations rather than on philosophical
technicalities.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to help you out here and explain what is meant by
philosophical technicalities, but I'm pretty sure I would not know
a philosophical technicality if it faxed itself to me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is because it's been 36 years since I took a philosophy
course in college and about all I remember is that the late Plato
and the late Aristotle were Greeks. Unless I'm thinking of the late
Spiro T. Agnew, which I might be, even though I've made it a point
to try to think about the late Spiro T. Agnew as little as
possible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So when if you inadvertently include some philosophical
technicalities in your essay and they disqualify you, don't blame
me. I've given you enough warning for you to have time to search
for the term on the Web. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You may, like me, feel some reluctance about entering because
you'll have to criticize either science or religion and, like me,
you have a soft spot in your head (and maybe your heart) for both
of them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, get over it. No one's going to hold your judgments against
you in the end. Uh, except maybe God. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
