<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 09:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5902 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CENSUS-REDSTRICT-RE     02-08 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CENSUS-REDSTRICT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO (MANY) CHOICES FOR 2000 CENSUS
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review) 
(bl)  
By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With just a few words, the Supreme Court has made
what's been called ``the purest of all political bloodsports''
potentially bloodier. Officially, the sport is called redistricting
_ the drawing of political boundaries. But because elected
officials might lose their seats, it is known better as incumbent
protection.
</P>
<P>
   The next round of redistricting will rely on census data
gathered next year. But in a 5-4 decision in January, the court
ruled out using a method of counting called statistical sampling in
doling out the 435 House seats among the states in 2001. This kind
of sampling, which is used by pollsters and advocated by the
Clinton administration, would help account for the
disproportionately large number of blacks, Hispanics, immigrants,
poor people and city dwellers who have been overlooked by
census-takers. Instead the court said federal law requires that the
traditional method be used for distributing the House seats.
</P>
<P>
   But the court did not rule out sampling entirely. The justices
left the door open for the states to use it to apportion their own
legislatures and to draw congressional district boundaries within
each state. The Census Bureau now plans to release two sets of
numbers. The Republicans have vowed to fight the release of any
data adjusted by sampling, saying the figures can be manipulated
for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Redistricting is already the purest of all political blood
sports,'' said Tim Storey, a redistricting expert with the National
Conference of State Legislatures. ``The court's ruling just
provides another layer of uncertainty on top of all the others.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislatures or commissions that draw the district lines
within each state are already burdened by complex and sometimes
contradictory laws, court rulings and political pressures: federal
law requires that ethnic minorities' voting strength not be
diluted; incumbents expect to be protected, and neighborhoods want
to remain intact.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Clinton administration is proposing to give the states
a choice of using either the traditional count (which in addition
to the door-to-door effort includes mailed forms and other means)
or the adjusted version based on sampling. Many legislators are
saying they prefer no choice at all.
</P>
<P>
   In large states like Illinois, New York, Ohio, Texas and
California, the fighting has already begun. Democrats are pushing
to use sampling and Republicans are vowing to fight it. Losers can
be expected to take winners to court. And divided legislatures are
likely to deadlock over the issue, which would leave the map
drawing to judges. ``No matter what legislatures do, there will be
a race to the court house,'' said Storey.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 census said it missed 8.4 million people. In cities
like Chicago, Los Angeles and New York City, where the Census
Bureau determined _ using sampling _ that Hispanic and Asian groups
were undercounted in the 1990 census, sampling could be a boon to
Democrats, probably at the expense of white Republican suburbs.
Experts say that sampling in New York City could help create two
new Democratic Assembly seats and one Democratic state Senate seat.
It could also cause two marginally Republican Senate districts to
become marginally Democratic, and prevent the city's loss of a
congressional seat to the suburbs. (The state itself is projected
to lose two congressional seats in 2000.)
</P>
<P>
   In California, sampling could add one or more legislative and
congressional seats to Democratic-leaning Hispanic neighborhoods in
Los Angeles and possibly San Diego, experts said. And in states
where Republicans hold narrow majorities _ the Texas Senate and the
Houses in the Pennsylvania and Illinois Legislatures _ sampling
might even help Democrats recapture majorities. ``An adjusted
census could provide Democrats the crucial edge needed to prevail
in close contests to control several state legislative chambers,''
warned Republican National Committee chairman Jim Nicholson in a
1997 memo.
</P>
<P>
   Many political scientists and demographers discount such dire
predictions. Elections, they say, turn more on voter turnout and
other factors than redistricting. They also say creative Republican
line drawers can probably blunt the worst effects of sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Some redistricting experts say the fight over sampling could
also set off feuding among Democrats. White Democrats might oppose
using sampling data lest it would draw districts that favor
minority candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Connor, a Brooklyn Democrat who is the New York state
Senate minority leader, said that if an adjusted count had been
used for redistricting in 1991, it would have enabled the Democrats
to win control of the Senate. But it might also cause his district
to be so thoroughly redrawn he could not be re-elected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Connor, who is white, said he wants to take his chances on
sampling in 2000. ``If I get thrown out of office, so what,'' he
said. ``The party can give me one hell of farewell dinner thanking
me for bringing them to the promised land, even if I don't make it
there myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 0913EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
