<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 09:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5907 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-IMPEACH-ENGLAND-REV     02-08 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-IMPEACH-ENGLAND-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT: WHAT A ROYAL PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(bl)  
By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In 1386 _ which was a long, long time ago _ one Michael
de la Pole, Earl of Suffolk, confronted a destiny in medieval
England that resonates to this day.
</P>
<P>
   He was impeached.
</P>
<P>
   And there began a long and tangled process of legal challenge to
executive authority by representative body that, somewhat
circuitously, brought William Jefferson Clinton to trial on the
floor of the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Earl of Suffolk, let it be said, was not impeached on
accusations related to sexual dalliance, so far as is known. His
crimes related more to misusing public funds and other offenses.
</P>
<P>
   But he was, like President Clinton, accused of ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' _ the first appearance of that vague and contentious
phrase in the canon of English law. The words provided a starting
point for the Framers of the U.S. Constitution almost four
centuries later, according to Professor Gary McDowell, an American
expert on impeachment at the Institute of United States Studies at
London University.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt,'' McDowell said in congressional testimony
as the impeachment proceedings got under way in Washington in
November, ``that when the Americans turned their attention to
fashioning procedures for impeachment, they had the history of
Great Britain in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, the British lessons serve as much as a warning of
impeachment's abuses as a guide to its benefits. ``History shows us
that in England, impeachment has been an engine more of passion
than of justice,'' he quoted Thomas Jefferson as saying.
</P>
<P>
   It is, possibly, one of the abiding ironies that the Framers of
the Constitution transplanted the notion of impeachment from an old
monarchy to a new republic just as the British themselves were
abandoning it. The Constitutional Convention began its
deliberations in Philadelphia in 1787. The last major impeachment
in British history began in 1788, when Warren Hastings, the first
governor-general of India, was charged with ``maladministration,
corruption in office and cruelty towards the people of India,''
according to McDowell. (His trial lasted seven years and he was
acquitted.)
</P>
<P>
   The reason impeachment withered in Britain was simply that the
growing strength of Parliament and the waning of despotic
monarchial rule allowed legislators to remove ministers through
confidence votes. ``As soon as the British system evolved into a
parliamentary system,'' said Professor Bernard Capp, a historian at
Warwick University, ``impeachment fell away.''
</P>
<P>
   So what remained from Britain's tradition in the new American
model of impeachment? Capp said impeachment in Britain had largely
been used as ``a means of attacking unpopular ministers'' put into
office by the king _ especially in the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   Raoul Berger, a leading authority, wrote in his study,
``Impeachment: The Constitutional Problems'' (Harvard University
Press, 1974), ``Direct attack on the king being unthinkable save by
the path that led Charles I to the block, Parliament indulged in
the fiction that the king could do no wrong but was misled by its
ministers.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment gave Parliament a means to establish supremacy over
``absolutist pretensions,'' Berger wrote, and hence to erode the
power of the monarchy on the way to democracy. As in the United
States today, it thus represented a weapon in the perennial battle
between executive and legislative branches of government, an arrow
from a quiver of checks and balances supposed to hold democracy in
equilibrium and protect it from abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say British tradition is the source of the process by
which the lower legislative house levels the charges to be tried by
the upper house (in Britain's case, it was the House of Commons and
House of Lords, respectively).
</P>
<P>
   And just as in the United States, impeachment in Britain was
long used for the removal of judges _ like Chief Justice William
Scroggs, impeached in 1680 on charges including excessive drinking
and bringing ``the highest scandal on the public justice of the
kingdom'' through irresponsible rulings.
</P>
<P>
   It was the British practice that enshrined the notion of ``high
crimes and misdemeanors'' as going beyond common law to a broader
sense of the betrayal of public trust.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the British system worked on a definition similar
to that provided by former President Gerald R. Ford when, as a
congressman in 1970, he said that ``an impeachable offense is
whatever a majority of the House of Representatives considers it to
be at a given moment in history.''
</P>
<P>
   The Duke of Buckingham, for instance, was impeached in 1626 on
charges that included procuring ``titles of honor to his mother,
brothers and kindred,'' according to Berger's study.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Pett, the commissioner of the navy, was impeached in 1668
for ``negligent preparation for the Dutch invasion'' and ``loss of
a ship through neglect to bring it to mooring.''
</P>
<P>
   The Earl of Oxford, Viscount Bolingbroke and the Earl of
Strafford were impeached in 1715 for giving ``pernicious advice''
to the Crown regarding the terms of the Peace of Utrecht, ending
the War of the Spanish Succession.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the prescribed punishment is the biggest difference
between the British and American impeachment procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, removal from office is the sole penalty.
But in Britain, possible penalties once included ``corruption of
the blood,'' meaning the disinheritance of the offender's
descendants, said James McClellan, a retired professor of political
science and law in Indianapolis. Sentence could be meted out
through a ``bill of attainder,'' a legislative act allowing
punishment without trial. Treason, according to most authorities,
was punishable by death.
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the charges against him, Clinton might also draw
comfort from other turns of history.
</P>
<P>
   Sir William Blackstone, the principal British legal authority
available to the Framers, identified the obstruction of justice as
``at all times an offense of a very high and presumptuous nature.''
Perjury, he said, was a ``detestable'' offense, ``punished with six
months' imprisonment, perpetual infamy, and a fine, or to have both
ears nailed to the pillory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 0916EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
