<HEADER>
A5927 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KING-HUSSEIN-GORBACHE     02-08 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-HUSSEIN-GORBACHEV-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 THE BEST TRIBUTE to KING HUSSEIN of JORDAN: PEACE  
 &HT;     (This tribute has already moved to clients of Mikhail
Gorbachev's monthly column on foreign affairs. To publish it as a
``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    With the passing of King Hussein, the people of Jordan are
losing a wise and tested leader and a strong and courageous
advocate of the cause of peace in the Middle East.
 &HT;    King Hussein made a great contribution to the history of the
Jordanian nation. His achievements for the benefits of his people
and other Arabs, as well as his global stature, were
internationally recognized during his lifetime. The king truly
deserved that recognition.
 &HT;    I recall my very first meeting with the king in Moscow, in 1987.
What a personality, what a strong and lively mind! Immediately, I
saw in him a wise and experienced statesman and a warm and friendly
man, a great human being. We talked at length about how best to
travel the road to peace in the Middle East. Political,
intellectual and personal courage were needed to reach that goal,
and the king clearly had it. As I worked to re-start the peace
process in that troubled region, King Hussein's advice was always
welcome and very important to me.
 &HT;    In his many years at the helm of Jordan, the king had his share
of frustrations and setbacks. He knew how to take those blows _ he
persevered, he went forward and led others. This ability will be
greatly missed.
 &HT;    As I was traveling in the United States last October, I watched
with admiration as the king left his hospital bed to help resolve
the difficulties in the negotiations between the Israeli and
Palestinian leaders. He looked frail, but I wanted to be hopeful
for his health. So it was a great shock for me to learn that King
Hussein was losing his battle to cancer.
 &HT;    Last April I visited Jordan. The king and Queen Noor invited me
and Raisa to the Royal Palace. It was a most memorable day for us.
It was as though we had seen each other and talked just a few days
before. The king and I discussed the Middle East and the many
political and psychological obstacles still to be overcome to make
peace a durable reality. He was full of ideas and vigor.
 &HT;    We met as old friends. We reminisced about our first talk in
Moscow, in 1987. Back then, I was struck by the king's total
commitment to peaceful methods of solving the Middle East problem.
I saw how concerned he was about the fate of the Middle East peace
process.
 &HT;    The king had done a great deal to preserve stability in
Jordanian society amid the turmoil in the region; yet in Jordanian
society, particularly among intellectuals and young people, there
was a growing disenchantment. Many people were viewing the peace
process as hopelessly deadlocked. Frustration was turning into
despair and a feeling of helplessness, which can be quite
dangerous.
 &HT;    It was clear to both the king and myself that, first of all, the
peace process must be carried forward, despite all setbacks. The
foundations laid down in Madrid and Oslo, we agreed, must be
preserved, for it was the only framework not just for the
resolution of the Palestinian problem but for creating a durable
system of security and cooperation in the region.
 &HT;    King Hussein and I discussed such a system in some detail. It
should encompass, among others, such countries as Iraq, Iran and
Turkey. Without it, the Middle East would not be able to respond to
the challenges of the new century, which include the issues of
security but also the environment, the water crisis and the problem
of terrorism.
 &HT;    In working for a peaceful solution of any issue it is very
important never to despair, always to remain optimistic. The
momentum for peace, set in motion by true leaders such as Yitzhak
Rabin, Shimon Peres, Yassir Arafat, Hosni Mubarak and King Hussein
is still strong. The severe setbacks of recent months have not
destroyed it.
 &HT;    But now my sympathy and condolences must go to the people of
Jordan, who I am sure will rally around their new leader, Crown
Prince Abdullah; to Queen Noor, whom Raisa and I remember fondly;
to the king's children and family. My thoughts today are about
them, and about peace in the Middle East. Its triumph will be the
best tribute to King Hussein of Jordan.
 &HT;     c.1998 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow, with a new
office at Northeastern University, in Boston. He also writes a
monthly commentary column for La Stampa, a newspaper in Turin,
Italy.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------- &QC;
</P>
