<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Congress must clarify role of future independent
counsels
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One section of the independent counsel law, curiously overlooked
by Congress, ought to be activated. It calls for congressional
oversight of the conduct of the office:
</P>
<P>
   ``The appropriate committees of the Congress shall have
oversight jurisdiction with respect to the official conduct of any
independent counsel appointed under this chapter, and such
independent counsel shall have the duty to cooperate with the
exercise of such oversight jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   In the post-impeachment era _ coming soon _ Congress has an
obligation to examine the conduct of Kenneth Starr on at least two
counts: first, the incessant leaks from his office that have made a
mockery of grand jury secrecy. Judge Norma Holloway Johnson
demanded some months ago that Starr show cause why he should not be
held in contempt for alleged violations of grand jury
confidentiality. Those rules are important to the fairness of our
system, since evidence can be given to a grand jury that is
hearsay, not corroborated and not admissable in court.
</P>
<P>
   Now a second contempt claim has been filed by the White House
counsel against Starr for the alleged leaking of information
relating to a possible grand jury indictment of President Clinton
before he leaves office. That leak occurred just before a crucial
Senate vote in the trial _ construed by many as an effort by
Starr's office to influence the outcome of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Starr promised once more to conduct an internal investigation.
Congress should demand to know the results.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Congress should examine whether Starr went beyond the
statutory grant of power by inserting himself in the Senate trial
phase of the process. The law only grants him the authority to send
to the House of Representatives ``substantial and credible
information ... that may constitute grounds for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The forefathers did not envision a government appointee with
unlimited public funds siding with one political party in an
impeachment hearing. They did not imagine an appointed prosecutor
using an immunity grant obtained by virtue of a grand jury
investigation to force a witness to testify in a Senate impeachment
trial. The law gives Starr no advocacy powers, nor any power at all
beyond sending a report to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the independent counsel law is renewed or not, Congress
should clarify for posterity the line separating the House and
Senate roles in impeachment. No appointed government power, other
than the courts, can be allowed to dilute or supercede the power of
the people's elected representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional oversight has nothing to do with exonerating the
president. His dishonor is written indelibly in the history books,
as surely as is the intent of the framers that removal can only
occur for actions that endanger the nation, no other.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress doesn't act to curb the abuses of this prosecutor _
drunk with the excesses of his unchecked power _ who will?
</P>
<P>
   Not Attorney General Janet Reno, so absorbed with the literal
definitions of the law as to miss its larger meaning. Not the
three-judge panel that approved Starr's appointment knowing of the
past partisan connections that should have disqualified him.
</P>
<P>
   Only Congress can clarify for posterity that no power, other
than the elected representatives of the people, can interfere with
the constitutional process of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
