</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Wavering on the death penalty _ again
 &HT;    (For release Wednesday, Feb. 10, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've lost track of how many times I've flip-flopped between
favoring and opposing the death penalty. Presently, I'm in my
pro-death penalty mode, but something happened last week that may
reverse that position _ again.
</P>
<P>
   Likely, there are many others such as me, torn between
permanently ridding society of criminal monsters yet fearful that
sometimes we've got the wrong guy.
</P>
<P>
   In Illinois last week, a man who has been in prison for 17
years, and was two days away from being executed last September,
was released when information, much of it obtained by a college
journalism professor and his students, surfaced that he did not
commit the murders of which he was accused.
</P>
<P>
   Critical to it was the videotaped confession of a Milwaukee man,
Alstory Simon, in the 1982 murders of two teenagers for which
Anthony Porter was convicted and sentenced to death. And critical
to that was the fact that the Milwaukee man's ex-wife came forward
to say she was present when Simon killed the two people in a
Chicago park.
</P>
<P>
   Porter was freed from prison over the weekend. He walked out,
instead of being carried out in a wooden box.
</P>
<P>
   Porter always maintained his innocence, but a jury and a judge
thought otherwise. And that's the problem with the death penalty.
Once carried out, there is no recourse. In fighting execution all
these years, Porter has been spared. Those who often argue for
swifter justice would have been dealing with a posthumous situation
today.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, I feel no apprehension about executing an open-and-shut
case; one in which a person admits to slaughtering a family, or
who, through solid scientific evidence, is found guilty.
</P>
<P>
   I am not naive enough to believe that the death penalty is a
deterrent, but I have no problem with using it as punishment _
unless we have the wrong guy. And how do we truly figure out who is
and who isn't?
</P>
<P>
   For years I had been a rigid proponent of the death penalty,
until a Florida case turned me in the other direction. In 1963, two
young blacks were arrested and charged with the murders of two
service station attendants. Under physical duress at the hands of
the police, they confessed, were convicted and sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   As they later declared their innocence and lodged claims of
police abuse, their case reached the public, also via probing
journalists. Freddie Pitts and Wilbur Lee spent a decade on death
row until another person confessed to the crimes. In the past year,
each received $500,000 in compensation from the Florida Legislature
for their ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   For every case of the wrong guy or guys, there are plenty of
right guys. Ted Bundy, the serial killer, couldn't have been
anything but the right guy. I shed no tears over his execution,
although the placard wavers outside the prison did.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose, to be on the safe side, I should be opposed to the
death penalty (again) _ as one wrongful execution would be a crime
in itself. But I continue to waver. Violent crime has a
stranglehold on our society and must be dealt with. While there are
those who wave off a wrongful execution as just one of those
things, I can't.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, I have no solution. Nor do our courts, our political
leaders, our law enforcement people, or the general population. It
is something we will continue to wrestle with until the last days
of civilization, which, according to some people, isn't too far
away anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
