<HEADER>
A5938 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN10-COX     02-08 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A new performer on Jordan's high wire
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The death of King Hussein of Jordan adds even more importance to
the pending Israeli national election that already was carrying
heavy political freight. The always too-eagerly centrifugal Middle
East has lost one of the key figures working effectively to keep it
from flying completely apart.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli election tests whether the strong majority of
Israelis who want peace secured can find the domestic political
means to that end. They will have to do so now in an atmosphere of
uncertainty about future relations with the one Arab treaty partner
who seemed a genuine rather than, like Egypt's Hosni Mubarak, a
grudging companion in the task.
</P>
<P>
   By temperament and training, Prince, now King, Abdullah is
committed to his father's policies. He is untested, however, and
little rehearsed in a region aprowl with political carnivores.
Syria's Hafez Assad and Iraq's Saddam Hussein, for instance, would
rather have a pliant Jordan next door than the independent Jordan
King Hussein created over nearly five decades.
</P>
<P>
   As it was of his father, a dicey balancing act will be demanded
of Abdullah, leading a population now more Palestinian than Bedouin
in a nation of few natural resources caught not just at the seam of
Arab-Israeli issues but at a crossroads of Arab national and
personal rivalries in which alliances shift and loyalties are
fungible.
</P>
<P>
   His father has left Abdullah a surprisingly strong state.
Hussein took a dubious shard from the collapsed Ottoman Empire and
by his own statecraft and will developed a genuine national
identity among peoples with no historical imperative to common
statehood.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish that, Hussein had to survive attempted coups and
assassination plots and defeat the effort of the Palestine
Liberation Organization to take over Jordan like a parasite
engorging its host.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, Hussein was clever, or at least lucky, even in his
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   The doomed decision to join the Arab war against Israel in 1967
cost Jordan the West Bank and East Jerusalem, but it is doubtful
Hussein could have kept the throne if he had stayed out. And he
successfully gambled that Israel and the United States,
understanding his vulnerability to Iraq and the demands of his own
population, would forgive his neutrality in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The Arabist bona fides he banked with those decisions helped
Hussein bring off his decision in 1994 to surface from years of
secret contacts with Israeli leadership and sign an open peace
treaty. The pact is steadied, too, by Hussein's sound calculation
that the limited democracy he had allowed _ too limited, but that
is another story _ would do more to contain than to inflame
contrary Islamist and nationalist passions.
</P>
<P>
   In a region much bloodied from armed bravura, King Hussein
offered at the end the bravery of peace-making. His swashbuckling
rush from his sick bed last fall _ his death bed, we now know _
secured the Wye River accords and saved the failing Mideast peace
process. There was, in that one transcendent gesture, far more
heroism than in all the missile-rattling of foolish Arab
bravehearts.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
