<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTHERS NOT SO COMPASSIONATE ON BUSH LABEL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The scene at the back gate of the Governor's
Mansion one otherwise-pleasant afternoon last week was an annoyance
for Gov. George W. Bush's security detail and a potential challenge
for his political consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Public Safety officers were wrestling _ as
compassionately as could be expected _ more than a dozen
wheelchair-bound protesters who had ignored their orders to clear
the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Hands were pried off metal bars, and, in the struggle, some
people fell from their wheelchairs to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, who objected to Texas' official stand in a
lawsuit over living options for the disabled, were arrested and
bused off to face criminal trespass charges, and Bush's favorite
political expression was ridiculed once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is compassionate conservatism, he (Bush) is in a lot
of trouble,'' said a protest leader, sitting in his wheelchair,
hands cuffed behind his back, in a can't-miss opportunity that news
cameras eagerly devoured.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush started applying the ``compassionate conservative''
label to his personal politics, he may as well have hung a ``kick
me'' sign on his back as well.
</P>
<P>
   Would-be opponents for the Republican presidential nomination
soon started taking shots at the expression, apparently believing
that ``compassionate'' was too suspicious a word for strongly
conservative Republicans who will be a major factor in nominating
their party's next presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weasel words,'' one White House hopeful said.
</P>
<P>
   The expression also has been attacked from the opposite
direction by Vice President Al Gore, who is gearing up for the
Democratic presidential nomination and may eventually meet Bush
one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   Gore didn't decry ``compassionate conservatism'' as such, but he
questioned Bush's credentials _ without mentioning Bush by name _
for transforming a ``pretty word'' into positive results.
</P>
<P>
   Without using the phrase, several Democratic members of the
Texas Senate also indirectly attacked Bush's ``compassionate''
capacity when they held a news conference immediately after his
State of the State speech last month to criticize the governor's
budgetary priorities.
</P>
<P>
   They said Bush, in his eagerness to enact modest tax cuts, was
giving insufficient attention to the health-care needs of children
and other important public programs.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the wheelchair protesters outside the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Bush, at least one group represented in the
protest was staging demonstrations in Austin long before Bush ever
moved into the governor's office. Calling itself ADAPT _ Americans
Disabled for Attendant Programs Today _ this group, in fact, has
long been one of the more aggressive advocacy groups in town.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, members in wheelchairs even staged an
all-night sit-in in the public reception room outside then-Gov. Ann
Richards' Capitol office. At least on one particular issue, they
were as unimpressed then with Democrat Richards' so-called ``New
Texas'' as they are now with Bush's ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   ADAPT, a strong advocate of community care for the disabled,
went to the Governor's Mansion last week to protest Texas' decision
to support Georgia's appeal of a lower federal court ruling that
promotes community care.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters fear that the appeal, if upheld by the U.S.
Supreme Court, could force more people into nursing homes and other
institutions against their will.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to back Georgia in the case actually was made by
Texas Attorney General John Cornyn. But ADAPT, like many other
advocacy groups, prefers to direct its attention to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the record, Bush supported Cornyn's decision. Both men
said they didn't want the federal courts to tell Texas officials
how to plan for treatment of disabled citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The best that I can figure out is that Bush believes a
``compassionate conservative'' is someone who believes it's OK for
government to help those who need help, provided those who need
help also are willing to be ``personally responsible'' _ another
key phrase of the governor's _ and help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   I also suspect that Bush is using the label to appeal to a broad
cross section of Texans and other Americans without using the word
``moderate,'' a much-hated term on his party's right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, particularly the handful out there who still admit to
being ``liberals,'' will define the label differently from Bush. So
will advocacy groups and less-compassionate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind what the dictionary may say. Whether Bush runs for
president or decides to serve a full second term as governor,
political differences over the label will remain inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
