<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5966 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTOS-PRIVACY-HNS &LR;      02-08 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTOS-PRIVACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES RAISE OBJECTIONS TO ID COMPANY BUYING DRIVER'S LICENSE
PHOTOS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looked like just the latest retailing gimmick _ use a check
or credit card at a store equipped with ``True ID'' and the clerk
could call up a tiny, computerized photo to verify the identity of
the purchaser. Very high-tech, very clever.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past two weeks, residents in South Carolina, Florida
and Colorado were infuriated to learn that this new system is built
on driver's license photos and related personal information
purchased from the states' motor vehicle bureaus.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the states are now in court and all three are trying to
cancel contracts that critics say were at best ill-advised, and
perhaps unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Image Data, the fledgling New Hampshire company
marketing the True ID system, say it's all a misunderstanding. Only
people's photographs will be available to retailers, said company
spokeswoman Lorna Christie _ not the other information printed on
the driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the controversy has been based on misperception of
what our company is providing,'' Christie said. ``We understand
we've got a unique business model.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tulane University law professor and constitutional privacy
expert M. David Gelfand predicted the squalls surrounding True ID
may result in laws that could prevent states from selling this
information _ regardless of assurances as to how it will be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on here ... is not too different from what people
are complaining about their credit cards _ that they're selling
information about them,'' Gelfand said. ``It seems particularly
questionable for government to be engaged in the same process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal (between citizen and government) is in order to get a
driver's license, you have to give up this information. Then this
information is being distributed well beyond the group that needs
it. You can understand why a police officer needs it.''
</P>
<P>
   Company lore says founder Bob Houvener hatched the plan for True
ID after being victimized by credit-card fraud. Identity fraud has
cost consumers more than $25 billion in the United States, Christie
said, and the crime continues to grow at 12 percent to 17 percent
per year.
</P>
<P>
   While the most frequent situation may be simple credit card
theft, Christie said, a thief will sometimes take on the
card-holder's entire identity, buying a house or even landing a job
under the assumed name.
</P>
<P>
   Image Data sought legislative changes in Colorado, Florida and
South Carolina to pave the way for buying the driver's license data
and photos. Image Data has since contracted to pay $140,000 to
Florida for the driver's license information, $128,000 to Colorado
and $5,000 to South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The True ID system is in place only as a pilot program provided
at no charge to 10 retailers in South Carolina. Clerks either use a
credit card or check to call up a small photo that Image Data
claims cannot be printed or downloaded before it disappears within
eight seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the information (addresses and, in some cases,
Social Security numbers found on driver's license applications)
would be used by Image Data only to verify that the correct photo
is being displayed, company spokeswoman Christie said.
</P>
<P>
   Unauthorized users would not be able to ``hack'' either the
photographs or the data, Christie said, adding that Image Data uses
the same level of encryption used by international banks and
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, three lawyers filed suit recently to block the
contract, and say they will pursue the case as a class action. Gov.
Jeb Bush canceled the contract a few hours after a Seminole County
judge issued a temporary injunction prohibiting Image Data from
using the license photos.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, legislative leaders have agreed to introduce
legislation to repeal the 1997 law that authorized the state's
Division of Motor Vehicles to sell the photos. Gov. Bill Owens has
said he thinks they can legally suspend the contract until a
legislative ban is passed.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Attorney General Charlie Condon went to court
last week to request a temporary injunction blocking his state's
contract, but a ruling is not expected until next week. Condon
learned of his state's agreement with Image Data after reading
about it in local news coverage, an office spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Condon spokesman Tom Landes said South Carolina's enabling
legislation was passed as part of a general appropriations bill,
and that many state lawmakers now say they did not know it was
included.
</P>
<P>
   But Christie said, ``I can tell you that we had numerous
meetings with officials and organizations in each state that talked
about our service.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie said she could not comment on whether the company is
considering its own legal action to enforce the contracts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
