<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     02-08 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT ENTERS WILD BUT PREDICTABLE ENDGAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's apparent that U.S. House managers _ and even lead
prosecutor Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill. _ finally see that President
Clinton won't be a convicted on either of the two articles of
impeachment. So, they have begun a whisper campaign. The managers
imply that the House impeachment investigation turned up
``evidence,'' now kept in sealed documents, about Clinton groping
Kathleen Willey and about other women who were sexually harassed by
Clinton when he was the governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Sure. And there's a man outside a casino in Las Vegas who will
sell you a fool-proof way to win at roulette.
</P>
<P>
   In one of Hyde's rare moments of being candid, last week, he
pleaded for live testimony saying, ``We just need new evidence.''
New evidence for what? To convict, obviously. In other words, even
Hyde admits that the case the House brought to the Senate doesn't
have sufficient proof that Clinton committed perjury or obstruction
of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The House impeachment managers were hoping something dramatic
would break in live testimony before the Senate, but that door was
shut tight by a vote of the Senate. Then they hoped something would
leap out of the depositions taken of Monica Lewinsky, Vernon Jordan
and Sidney Blumenthal. Nothing did. No new evidence.
</P>
<P>
   House manager Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., in order to ratchet up
moral outrage, described Lewinsky in the videotape of her
deposition as ``a young woman, very much like a family member we
might know.'' Other impeachment managers spoke of her innocence and
youth. Not one mentioned that Lewinsky had a lengthy affair with a
married man while she attend college at Lewis and Clark in
Portland, Ore. Not one mentioned, as the Oregonian reported in late
October, that Lewinsky had forged a dean's name on a letter to get
extra paid work for her married lover.
</P>
<P>
   Innocence?
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks various right-wing kooks have sprayed their
warped email across the Internet. They claim that Clinton fathered
a child with a black prostitute. That he had Vincent Foster killed.
That Clinton raped several women before he became president. That
he is guilty of treason for trading missile technology to China.
Worse, that Clinton is a womanizer _ and for such a sin alone
should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr let it be known that he may
decide to bring criminal charges against Clinton before the
president leaves office. His timing was critical to turning up the
heat on the president and the Senate. In effect, Starr was saying
to those senators who are reluctant to convict Clinton on the
unconvincing evidence presented to them: Look again, there's more
than enough to convict Clinton in a criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   If Starr really intends to bring criminal charges against
Clinton while the president is still in office, he is wading in
unknown waters. While some constitutional scholars may consider
that possible, the intent of the framers is clear _ impeachment is
the only way to topple a sitting president. A criminal trial will
have to wait until Clinton is no longer president.
</P>
<P>
   And now GOP Senate conservatives want to have Clinton found
guilty _ without convicting him of the articles of impeachment.
That's what a ``finding of fact resolution'' means _ and a
resolution only needs a majority vote to pass. In other words, the
55 Republicans in the Senate can vote in favor of a resolution that
claims the president is guilty since they can't convince enough
Democrats to vote to convict the president. Guilty, but not guilty.
Clearly, such a resolution would go beyond the impeachment
authority granted to the Senate by the U.S. Constitution _ and far
beyond America's sense of fair play. Either Clinton is guilty or
he's not guilty. He can't be both.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the American public has quietly been telling the
Republican Party to knock it off or pay the consequences in the
next election.
</P>
<P>
   Listen up, Republicans. This isn't an idle threat. Shut the
impeachment down, or be shut down yourselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
