A5999 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     02-08 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV10-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEEZERS ON THE GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesay Feb. 10)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While you were napping, the United Nations declared 1999 the
International Year of Older Persons.
</P>
<P>
   As someone who is hurtling toward Older Person status at the
speed one normally associates with rogue asteroids, this
declaration does not come a moment too soon. If the United Nations
had waited much longer, I might have whizzed right past Older
Person status and gone directly to Gibbering Geezer or, worse yet,
Lawn Bowler.
</P>
<P>
   Sarasota, of course, is absolutely lousy with Older Persons to
the point that you can hardly throw an empty Metamucil bottle out
your car window without smacking one in the head. (Lame joke: If
you want to start a stampede in a Sarasota movie house, you don't
yell ``Fire!'' You yell ``Viagra!'')
</P>
<P>
   Older Persons, at least of the Sarasota variety, are quite
active and engaged and much too busy to give the United Nations a
day of their time, much less a year. If your idea of an alert Older
Person is someone who can rock and drool at the same time, you need
to get a load of the old folks from Sarasota. They run marathons,
play championship golf and tennis, write novels, play in jazz
bands, go to college and just generally make us younger folk feel
like soggy Kleenex.
</P>
<P>
   I used to look forward to being an Older Person, but now I'm not
sure if I have the stamina. As someone who gets dizzy bending over
to pick up the morning newspaper, it's hard to imagine turning 65
and suddenly feeling the urge to skydive, water-ski or scuba-dive.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement, Sarasota-style, is a lot more than wandering around
in your bathrobe mumbling to yourself; it's a full-time job that
requires energy and commitment. The situation is only going to get
worse once the United Nations' message of empowered
senior-citizenship gets around.
</P>
<P>
   The way I look at it, there is already too much pressure on
Older Persons without the United Nations getting into the act. The
first question that's asked of a person approaching his or her 65th
birthday is, ``What are you going to do when you retire?''
Somewhere along the line the definition of retirement changed from
``to stop doing'' to ``to start doing'' and the whole idea of
retirement has been a lot less attractive ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The old notion of retirement as ``long days of nothing special
interrupted by frequent naps'' has no relevance in today's society.
Retirees often find themselves working harder for longer hours
(and, of course, lower pay) than they did when they held the
stressful, full-time jobs they were so anxious to quit.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to think of retirement as a time when the most
strenuous thing you have to do is scuff out to the kitchen for a
fresh cup of tea, but the reality is far less relaxed. In Sarasota,
many Older Persons fill their time doing volunteer work, performing
in community theater, becoming active in local politics or
otherwise flitting about in a decidedly un-old-fogeyish way. While
I have no quarrel with Older Persons who wish to remain active to
the point of carrying their own coffins, I don't think there should
be a stigma attached to Older Persons who prefer that their
retirement years proceed at a more leisurely pace.
</P>
<P>
   Although the folks at the United Nations may think otherwise,
there is nothing wrong with an Older Person going through an entire
day without doing anything that promotes his or her physical or
mental well-being or results in the betterment of mankind. If all
you managed to do in the last 24 hours was feed yourself and hit
the mute button when the Jerry Springer show came on, you should
not feel that you squandered your time.
</P>
<P>
   Life, after all, can be very pleasurable if you don't let your
retirement get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
