<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6021 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN09-C     02-08 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aging population will change America's `youth' culture
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thousands of years ago, when cave-dwelling families
clustered around glowing fires, they could see that life had a
natural order: Young adults did most of the hunting and gathering
for food. Lots of children scampered around. And a few old gray
heads helped watch over the babies.
</P>
<P>
   That's the order most people still want to see, with the family
focused on parents and children. Grandparents and elderly aunts and
uncles are in the picture, but toward the edges.
</P>
<P>
   But as we move into the 21st century, that ``natural'' order
will be overturned in industrialized countries, where the elderly
soon will outnumber the children.
</P>
<P>
   As we advance further into the new century, family trees may no
longer branch out with siblings and cousins. Instead, they could
grow like tall, skinny pines, with parents, grandparents,
great-grandparents and even great-great-grandparents stacked up on
top of just a few children.
</P>
<P>
   This megachange is coming because people with access to modern
medical care are living much longer. At the same time, our
urban-oriented economy, with its plentiful jobs for women, is
discouraging young adults from planning big families. As the 20th
century comes to an end, we are moving into a world that has never
existed, one where old people will dominate and babies will be
rare.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``Gray Dawn: How the Coming Age Wave Will
Transform America and the World,'' economist Peter G. Peterson
calls this shift one of the ``great hazards in the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   But why are old people a hazard? Because they do not work as
much as young people, which means they don't contribute much in
income taxes. Economists say it's not possible for a small number
of workers to support a large numbers of retirees collecting
benefits from Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike global warming, says Peterson, this hazard is not just a
hypothesis. It's an inevitability. The key players already are
here: They're the baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   In the affluent countries of North America and Western Europe,
and in Japan and Australia, the enormous generation born in the two
decades following World War II is making its way through middle
age. In another decade, this massive group will begin to retire.
And because of medical advances, many of them will live for decades
beyond age 65.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, fertility rates have fallen so sharply that many
industrialized countries are now running below the ``replacement
rate'' necessary to replenish today's population.
</P>
<P>
   The imbalance between the number of old people and young will
become extreme in the first half of the new century. Just 40 years
from now, the United States will have four retirees for every one
person of college age. If our state and federal coffers are being
used to support those retirees, will there be any money left to
help students with tuition?
</P>
<P>
   This year, Congress may finally begin to grapple with this
immense demographic problem when it addresses Social Security
reform. Most economists say that unless old-age benefits are
trimmed or taxes are raised, the system will collapse in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   But the aging of the population will do far more than just crimp
Social Security. Culturally, it may be difficult to adjust to
living in a society with far more grandparents than grandchildren,
far more funerals than baptisms.
</P>
<P>
   Americans may have an especially hard time giving up their youth
culture. As a nation of immigrants, we have always had a steady
supply of young workers to fill farms and factories. The relative
youth of our population contributed to a risk-taking culture, with
high levels of worker mobility and optimism. With its population
aging, the country may become less entrepreneurial.
</P>
<P>
   As the gray dawn breaks, we will wake up in a new world where
family life will be radically different from anything ever
experienced by humans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
