<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6023 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN09-COX     02-08 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Driver photos on a screen near you
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The Mark Lane photographed by the Florida
Department of Highway Safety and Motor Vehicles had just come in
out of the wind. Judging from his hair, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike me, he always wears a tie. That's because people who need
to look at driver's licenses are usually seeking reassurance. We
live in a society that finds men in ties reassuring. At least,
compared to men in, say, Metallica T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   This Mark Lane's signature appears beneath him. That is not
reassuring. You could mistake it for an electrocardiogram with bad
news for a heart patient.
</P>
<P>
   The driver's license Mark Lane exists not only in my wallet but
in the vast data storehouses of the Florida Department of Highway
Safety and Motor Vehicles. That Mark Lane is in demand right now.
He's worth only a penny, but he has lots of company.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, the Florida Department of Highway Safety and
Motor Vehicles was selling driver's license photos to Image Data
Corp., a New Hampshire-based company. The contract would have sold
14 million bad photographs of Florida drivers for $140,000. About
35,000 were delivered. I don't know if the dapper, tie-wearing Mark
Lane made the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Image Data has been buying driver's license photos in South
Carolina, Colorado and Florida. It plans to create a computerized
system to help retailers make sure that customers opening their
checkbooks and wallets are who they they claim to be.
</P>
<P>
   I could show up at a cash register unshaven and wearing a black
Metallica T-shirt, but when the clerk punches my name in the
system, the respectable if wind-blown, tie-wearing Mark Lane would
appear on the screen. Check approved.
</P>
<P>
   This all seems very Jetsonslike and probably represents huge
progress. But, there are buts.
</P>
<P>
   So many, that Florida Gov. Jeb Bush last week ended the state's
contract with the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's decision won applause because most folks felt a line had
been crossed. Not a bright yellow line, but one of those fuzzy,
foggy frontiers. Privacy lines tend to be like that.
</P>
<P>
   Driver's license information already is available to anyone who
wants it. Insurance companies and mass mailers have been buying
lists of drivers for years. It's public record. Everyone paid for
it. Everyone can look at it.
</P>
<P>
   All true. But now photographs are involved and the issues
somehow aren't the same. Your face. Your photograph. Taken on a
bad-hair day. Eyes stupidly wide because the flash went off a
moment before you expected. This photo miniature now can appear at
a moment's notice whenever a teen-age discount-store clerk beckons
it. She will tap in your name and giggle to herself at the image
filling the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of humbling, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   An average person who has lived a tolerably full life has far
more damaging documents hidden somewhere than a driver's license
photograph taken on a windy day. My taxi driver's license, my
divorce papers, my high school Permanent Record ... . But they're
different. They're in file cabinets. Safe from store clerks.
</P>
<P>
   Computerization means bad things that used to be safely entombed
in musty basement file cabinets can be in the electronic equivalent
of thousands of file cabinets in thousands of places.
</P>
<P>
   In the file-cabinet era, judges and lawyers talked about privacy
as ``the right to be left alone.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't quite cover it. We are left alone when our mugs
are whizzing though cyberspace. But it still doesn't feel right.
</P>
<P>
   In the clerk-laughing-at-your-driver's-license-on-a-screen era,
privacy means something else. The right to be anonymous. The right
not to be turned into electronic data without our knowledge. The
right not to be embarrassed at cash registers.
</P>
<P>
   And the right not to have your face turn up as a commodity,
bought and sold by people you don't know. Unless you're Cindy
Crawford or somebody like that. And I'm not.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of luggage for one small word to carry. Like art
and pornography, a privacy violation is something you recognize
when you see it. And seeing my tie-wearing, wind-blown, smiling
self on a little screen at the Pump `N' Pay qualifies. But don't
ask me why.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at))n-jcenter.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
