<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking a cue from the 'gators
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ It's just after sunrise beside a still lake
in central Florida. My companion and I are sitting on the end of a
weather_beaten dock, sipping the morning's first cup of decaf and
settling in for some serious 'gator watching. It doesn't take long.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one,'' he whispers and hands me the binoculars as he
points. ``Over there in the sawgrass.'' I focus on what looks like
a log with a big knot on one end and can't help thinking how
natural it seems to be silent in such a place. I wonder if it's
because we don't want to spook the wildlife or if it's just
reverence for the serenity we might be disrupting.
</P>
<P>
   The log swings a little to its right and blinks an eye. ``Don't
move,'' my friend cautions. ``If we're still, he'll think we're
just part of the scenery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Or breakfast,'' I can't resist adding under my breath as I
ease my feet up under me.
</P>
<P>
   My old friend chuckles soundlessly. ``You've been away from home
too long,'' he says with a grin. ``That 'gator isn't going to
bother you. He's got other things on his mind.'' I ask him like
what and he says like maybe girl 'gators. I zoom in for a better
look and shake my head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too ugly,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe by people standards,'' he says, ``but to some lady
'gator, he could be a crusty old dreamboat.'' I refocus for a
double check. No way.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few feet away we hear a gentle ``ploosh'' as a great blue
heron wades into the reeds. Soon, a coot paddles past, just inches
from the 'gator. I hold my breath but nothing happens. The bird
swims on unmolested.
</P>
<P>
   As we sit still and watch, I can't help thinking how lucky we
are _ two Florida crackers enjoying what remains of our home
state's wild country. It's sad to know there are whole generations
of folks growing up where we did, on the edge of the Everglades,
who have never experienced the nature we took for granted. The
smart creatures, the lucky ones, have retreated deeper into the
swamp _ the less adaptable ones into oblivion. I can't help
thinking that could be true about people too. My friend and I have
known both kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the days when alligators were on the endangered species
list (along with scrub jays, Key deer, and the Florida panther), my
friend tells me that poachers used to meet late at night in the
many hammocks that ring the Everglades, under the pretense of going
frog gigging. He says it was easy to tell the poachers from the
giggers _ poachers always had new pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Florida alligators, I'm told, are now considered a renewable
resource. I guess that means there are enough to go around so folks
can start wearing them on their feet again.
</P>
<P>
   Another bumpy log moves into sight, not too far from where an
anhinga stands knee-deep in a floating island of hyacinths,
apparently uninterested in the two water snakes undulating past
him. ``He's a snakebird,'' I whisper, ``so why isn't he grabbing
one of them for breakfast?'' My companion tells me the bird may not
be hungry and, unlike humans, doesn't view his lake as the
drive-thru lane of a fast food restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The second 'gator is a lot bigger than the first. I ask if he's
going to eat the snakebird. Probably not, my friend says and
reminds me these creatures don't kill for pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. The big bird is obviously alert but unafraid as he
opens his wings to dry in the warming sun. The 'gator watches for a
few minutes and then closes both eyes as the rest of the lake gets
on with the business of daily living.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lesson to be learned here, but the morning is too
relaxed for deep thought. Instead, I make like a 'gator and stretch
out in the sun, chuckling as I conjure up a picture of alligators
wearing ``people-skin'' shoes to the yacht club dance. Quickly, I
remind myself that'll never happen. They're way too smart to go
around acting like humans.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Address mail to:
320 West Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email:
eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
