<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web site nurtures democracy
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Griping is easier than doing. Action is tougher than
apathy. If you're frustrated with your congressional
representative, the school board or the condition of your roads,
you can write a letter to the editor of your newspaper or to an
elected official, or you can call. It doesn't get easier.
</P>
<P>
   Or does it? http://www.e-thepeople.com is a Web site devoted to
giving people voice. The free site has links to online petitions
that have been started concerning local and national issues. There
is also a database of 140,000 federal, state and local officials in
more than 7,000 cities. To start a petition or lodge a complaint,
enter your ZIP code, choose a topic and the site lists all the
officials relevant to your issue.
</P>
<P>
   3-D FOR CAMCORDERS
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when shooting your own video was impressive
enough. How can you beat pictures that move? 3D Video Inc. is
selling a camcorder attachment that lets your record video in 3-D.
</P>
<P>
   The NuView SX-2000 adapter, with 3-D glasses and the equipment
to make it play 3-D images on your television, sells for $499. The
adapter requires one AAA 1.5-volt battery, which will work for more
than 60 hours.
</P>
<P>
   A reviewer in the February 1998 issue of Camcorder magazine
compared using the adapter to ``the same as seeing color television
for the first time back in the '50s ... the addition of color was a
quantum leap in enhancing the believability of the medium.''
</P>
<P>
   More information about the adapter can be found at
http://www.3-dvideo.com.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ, EBAY CUT A DEAL
</P>
<P>
   In a move that might make online auction sites as popular as
anything on the Internet, Compaq Computer will start putting eBay
icons on its PC desktops.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq will put the icon on the desktops of its Prosignia
Desktop 310 and Notebook 210 PCs. eBay will promote Compaq's
Prosignia line at trade shows this year.
</P>
<P>
   eBay is a 24-hour-a-day online auction site. It has more than
1.3 million registered users and more than 1 million items for
sale, including books, sports memorabilia and toys.
</P>
<P>
   WEB USE FIGURES TO BROADEN
</P>
<P>
   The Web might be a resource for the well-off, but that will
probably change as it grows in popularity, according to a report by
2CAN Media, an interactive media company.
</P>
<P>
   From April 1998 to October, the number of Web users grew by 17
percent to a total of 62 million, according to Media Metrix, a New
York company that tracks Web usage. About 24 percent of American
households use the Web, and it's a wealthy group. The average
household income of Web users is more than $50,000, according to
2CAN Media. Of those using the Web, 40 percent are college
graduates and 40 percent are in management or professional
positions. All figures are above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   The report states as the Web attracts more users, its
demographics will start looking more like America, with all income
levels represented.
</P>
<P>
   Web use is measured by companies like Media Metrix, which tracks
the Web action of a sample group of 40,000 users. The report
challenges the Internet industry to come up with measurement
standards more reflective of actual Web use.
</P>
<P>
   A LOOK, BUT NO SALE
</P>
<P>
   People are willing to check the Web to find out what flights are
available and other general flight information. But a study by NPD
Online Research found less than 33 percent of those who access
airline sites buy their tickets there.
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at the activities of 13,000 visitors to sites
for American, Canadian, Continental, TWA and United. Of those
polled, males were more likely to have bought a ticket from an
online site, as were people who have flown six or more flights in
the most recent 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The study found most people were moderately satisfied with
airline sites. Only 18 percent of those polled could find the
information they were looking for every time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
