<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web sites also a good place to start
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For some, the arrival of February _ Black History
Month _ used to mean countless hours in the library searching for
information on such figures as Paul Robeson, Madame C.J. Walker and
Bessie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But today, students and parents have another reference point _
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people are trying to have a career and be parents at the
same time,'' said Camille Binder, whose 5-year-old son, Chaunce,
uses his computer to learn more about notable black personalities.
``You can't pick your child up at 6 p.m. and then head to the
library. It's easier to do it at home on the Internet. It works
better for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Binder recently used the Internet to help Chaunce, who attends
private school, find information on poet/author Maya Angelou.
</P>
<P>
   A number of sites have special Black History Month issues.
Others that typically target African-American users and just expand
their offerings this month are good resources anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone puts special emphasis on February.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's black history every day with us,'' said Patrick McElroy,
president of the Atlanta-based Freedom Group, an Internet
consulting firm that launched EverythingBlack.com in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The site, which McElroy claims get 2,500 visitors daily,
contains information on such areas of interest as Africa, black
history, literature, politics and business.
</P>
<P>
   ``When major corporations turn their focus away from
African-American history at the end of the month, we will still be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   SITES OF INTEREST
</P>
<P>
   http://scriptorium.lib.duke.edu/collections/African-American-women.h
tml _ Collection of letters and memoirs of 19th century slave woman
from Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.msn.com/schoolhouse _ For Black History Month, this
site will offer lessons and lesson plans. Also gives links to
related sites, including Encarta Africana.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.blackfamilies.com _This Cox Interactive Media site
focuses on the black family. Each day during Black History Month,
the site will feature a historical figure. Personalities to be
profiled this month include Mary McLeod Bethune and Alex Haley.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.afroam.org/history/history.html _ Afro-Americ(at)'s
