<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to get the maximum out of your PC
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You've just bought a new PC, but it's no time to relax
and celebrate. At least not until you've probably souped it up like
a jalopy of yesteryear. The February issue of Maximum PC features
an article with 30 tips on how to sharpen the performance of a new
PC. Among the magazine's tips: Removing little-used files,
scheduling regular tune-ups and deleting a program called AOL
Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 17 years, Mike Bloomberg has turned himself into a
``baron of real-time financial news.'' But has the baron lost his
touch? Is he in danger of losing out to new up-and-comers? The
February issue of Wired magazine raises that question about
Bloomberg and the financial computers that carry his name.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Bulldog Productions doesn't pull punches in describing the
latest version of its computer CD game ``Populous.'' Its promotion
tag line says, ``Feel the divine power, enforce your omnipotent
influence.'' In this game, players create their own world, command
its subjects and punish them if they get out of line. What's new
about this latest version of ``Populous'' is 3-D graphics and lots
of new powers.
</P>
<P>
   Keep track of the maintenance of your car through a CD-ROM
called Peak Performance v4.11. It lets you record and schedule all
service appointments. You can track oil changes and monitor the
wear and tear on your car. Peak Performance also lets you print out
customizable reports on maintenance history.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Preschoolers can learn about animals at a nifty new site
maintained by Public Broadcasting. It's called ``Zoboomafoo,''
based on the TV show of the same name. You'll find the site at
http://www.pbs.org/zoboo/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
