<HEADER>
A6039 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHNOBUDDY09-COX     02-08 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buy the rice, stock the pantry and sleep well at night
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I was at a party the other night where most of the
guests were from other countries, including many from small
countries in what used to be the Communist bloc. I'm not good at
parties _ even when they are held in English _ because I am shy and
hard of hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But this was even stranger, since most of those at the party
were very formal and polite _ it's one of the cultural differences
between Americans and Eastern Europeans that seem real to me _ and
they tried hard to make me feel at home. So I wasn't suprised when
a graduate student named Vladimir found me somewhere over near the
pirogies and said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that you are a computer expert. Tell me please,
whether the Year 2000 computer problem will create world
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   I explained to Vladimir I was a computer writer, not a computer
expert. I told him being a computer writer is very much like a
sports writer. Most of us know more than the average hobbyist and a
lot less than a real computer professional. After all, when was the
last time you heard of a football team hiring a sports writer to be
the coach?
</P>
<P>
   But, with that qualification, let me tell you what I think about
the Year 2000 problem. Maybe that way, if you bump into Vladimir,
who had as much trouble understanding my thick Southern English as
I did understanding his Bulgarian-accented English, you can tell
him for me.
</P>
<P>
   First, since this is a computer column for beginners, let's be
sure you haven't lived in a cave for the past couple of years and
have somehow avoided learning about the Year 2000 problem.
Programmers, in the old days, didn't use all four digits when they
needed to include a date in a computer program. In those days,
computer memory was as scarce as June bugs in a chicken yard, so
programmers used just two digits.
</P>
<P>
   That worked reasonably well during the middle of the century,
but now that 02 could logically mean 1902 or 2002, computers get
confused. This digital confusion _ just like the human variety _
can cause all sorts of problems unrelated to the reason for the
confusion. The computer can freeze up, destroy data, do all sorts
of crazy things when it is confused. And, since computers live in
communities, just like people, one confused computer on the
network, way off in Des Moines, can wreak havoc with the others on
either the Internet or internal network.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there have been predictions of massive power outages,
food shortages, water supply problems _ it sounds very much like
the end of the world. And, to make things more frightening, many of
the predictions come from people who understand and work with
computers at a high level. So, Vladimir's question isn't a foolish
one.
</P>
<P>
   But, as it is with a lot of good questions, there is no clear
answer. Governments and big businesses are spending billions of
dollars to fix the problem (and for reasons way too complex for me
to explain in the space I'm given, the problems aren't as easy to
fix as choosing ``find and replace'' in your word processor). The
problem isn't limited to software. Chips that live in your car and
in missile systems and in kids' toys also can and do have the
problem. And since it is impossible to duplicate the software and
conditions that will exist in the future, dress rehearsals like
setting the clock forward on a computer aren't perfect ways of
predicting what will happen.
</P>
<P>
   From what I hear and understand, most personal computer owners
will face only minor problems at worst. Be most concerned if you
have old spreadsheet or financial management software. Either
replace it with software marked ``Year 2000-compliant'' or look on
the company's Web site for tiny programs intended to fix the Y2K
problems in older programs. These programs are usually free for the
downloading.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the big question. The one Vladimir (his real name) asked
about. Should you put this column down and head for the survivalist
supply store to stock up on dried beans, bottled water, rice and
dried pasta?
</P>
<P>
   My answer is a serious one, the best one I can give you under
the circumstances. Heck yes, stock up. I don't think, Vladimir, the
end is near. I think planes will fly, grocery stores will function,
utilities will provide. But a lot of smart people truly worry there
will be supply disruptions. Why not buy the rice? Worst case,
you'll have a well-stocked larder and a healthy diet.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
