<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHTOOLS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This just in: Author now uses Windows 98
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A few months ago, I received a nasty little electronic
screed from a computer expert who had evidently wandered into this
space by mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are you related to?'' he began, making me think it was yet
another inquiry about genealogical computing.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, what he meant was that I was so stupid that I would
have to be related to somebody very important around here to be
anointed a computer columnist. That's pretty insulting. If I was
related to somebody important, I think I could do better than
part-time computer columnist.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, what laid bare my incompetence to him was a passing
remark that I was still using Windows 95 and, perhaps worse,
Netscape instead of Explorer. What if he knew I drive a 10-year-old
pickup truck and use a razor so old the blades have to be bought at
flea markets?
</P>
<P>
   In my defense, I was intending to upgrade to Windows 98 sometime
before Windows 2000 appears. After all, Chairman Bill didn't spend
a billion or so whipping up hype over it, so why should I get all
aquiver about it?
</P>
<P>
   I was using Netscape chiefly because I resented Microsoft's
constant attempts to stuff Explorer down my throat.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, licking my wounds and begging forgiveness, I
upgraded the other day to Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, wow, as the hippies used to say.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing I've discovered about Windows 98 is that instead
of another attempt to force me to use Explorer, it just sort of
dangles it in front of me. Other than that, and the fact that the
menus sort of drool down now instead of popping down, and the
program list has to be scrolled, I haven't found much difference.
To be sure, there are some differences under the surface, but most
people probably won't notice their effects.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged, I decided to give Explorer, which I've used before,
another run, and also try Outlook, Microsoft's mail and news
reader.
</P>
<P>
   Explorer is quite all right, but I still prefer Netscape. I
don't see myself using most of the bells and whistles that Explorer
offers, such as channels. Outlook is weak. I definitely prefer
Eudora Pro and Agent as mail and news readers, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Now, had I been using Explorer for several years and tried
Netscape, I'd probably prefer Explorer. They both do the same thing
and in the same general way.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot to be said for the simple truism that the best
program is the one you know how to use. I would guess that the bulk
of the people who read this column are still using Windows 95.
There's not a program out there that insists on association with
Windows 98. Unless you can see some clear advantage to a new
program, why switch?
</P>
<P>
   One reason, I suppose, would be to have all the most recent
bells and whistles so some geek won't sneer at you for not staying
on the same page with Chairman Bill.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
