<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A09-COX     02-08 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: If the Senate convicts President Clinton, does he retain
retirement benefits after leaving office? My husband and I are
divided on this. _ Sharon Geanuleas
</P>
<P>
   A: If removed from office, a president loses more than face. Out
go any government payments such as retirement dollars and Secret
Service protection, says Don Ritchie, associate historian for the
U.S. Senate. Loss of these generous retirement benefits may have
figured into Richard Nixon's decision to resign. The presidential
benefits were introduced in the 1950s as part of the pension
package (a modern-day benefit of being the leader of the free
world). Q: How do they make the fabulous pictures that cover an
entire bus and the smaller ones that advertise businesses? What
company does the work? How much does it cost? Who pays for it? _
Suellen Jones
</P>
<P>
   A: The ads are made by Obie Media, an Oregon-based company
specializing in transit advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The full wrap, an ad covering the entire bus, is made on vinyl
sheets (solid for the lower portions and ``Swiss cheese-like'' on
the windows) and placed on the bus. This takes about 80 pieces of
sticky backed vinyl (ever deal with shelf liner?).
</P>
<P>
   Q: A couple of weekends ago, at my uncle's birthday party, I
found out that my sister and her on-again/off-again fiance got
married on New Year's Eve in Las Vegas. (I found out from a cousin
whom I see once or twice a year.) My entire family _ fiance
included _ was at our parents' house for Christmas, yet I wasn't
told of the upcoming wedding. I have received an invitation to a
reception in their honor. Am I being petty for feeling that I
should snub the reception since I was snubbed about the wedding
announcement? I realize that an invitation to the wedding would
have been out of the question, since it was out of state, but still
...
</P>
<P>
   _F.G.
</P>
<P>
   A: This wedding was not an accident. Your sister, for her own
reasons, clearly did not want the family there. Hey _ you were in
good company since no one was invited. That is her decision and, in
my opinion, her loss. Water under the bridge. Do not snub the
reception. You will regret it later and miss a good party. (What's
a little swallowed pride when there is free food and drink?)
Whether you bring a gift to the couple is up to you. In any case,
find a quiet moment (not in front of others _ no husband, no
cousin) in the next few months and tell your sister how you feel _
in the least accusatory tone you can muster. For all you know, this
could be a complete shock to her. Let her know you want your
relationship with her to continue in a positive manner. With any
luck she will realize the fallout from her thoughtlessness. But be
prepared, she may not. Then it is over. She had her way; you had
your say.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to write to Shel Silverstein. I think he is a great
poet. Will you please give me his address?
</P>
<P>
   _Joscelyne Schroeder
</P>
<P>
   A: ``The Giving Tree'' is one of my favorite books. Hard to
believe this man also composed the Johnny Cash hit ``A Boy Named
Sue,'' but he did. This very private author penned one of
Publishers Weekly's all-time best-selling hardcover books, ``Where
the Sidewalk Ends.'' Write to him in care of HarperCollins
Children's Books, 10 E. 53rd St., New York, NY 10022. Remember, he
is famous for not replying to mail or making personal appearances,
so if your letter goes unanswered, don't take it personally.
Silverstein believes that no child should receive something if all
children cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Many years ago our family played a word game named Scribbage.
It was made up of a cup, a timer and 13 lettered cubes or blocks.
We could build words crossword-style. I believe it was the
forerunner of Scrabble. Scribbage was made by the same company that
made another popular word game, Yahtzee, which we still play
sometimes. The E.S. Lowe Co. at 200 Fifth Ave., New York, NY 10010
was the manufacturer of both games. I read your column in Omaha.
Can you tell us if this game is still available and where? _Don
Bailey
</P>
<P>
   A: Found one _ and only one _ at Hog Wild, 100 E. N Loop Blvd.,
here in Austin. Call (512) 467-9453. This shop specializes in
vintage toys, and this game, in good condition, will be in the $20
range.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Within one week I have seen four dead robins in my South
Austin neighborhood. One day, I was out in my yard when a robin
fell out of a tree and hit the ground with a thud. When I walked
toward it to investigate, it jumped up and tried to fly back up
into the tree but didn't quite make it and fell back to the ground
with another loud thud. I carefully approached it again. It laid on
its back for a moment before jumping to its feet, hopping across
the yard and finally finding enough strength to fly into a low
branch, where it sat for several minutes. Can you tell me what is
going on? _ Jennifer Sanders
</P>
<P>
   A: A rockin' robin. ``The robin in question had likely eaten
fermented fruit and was feeling a bit tipsy,'' says Paul Sunby,
biologist at SWCA Inc., an environmental consulting firm. That is
actually a fairly common occurrence for frugivores (fruit eaters)
such as the robin and cedar waxwings. The sugar in berries can
ferment if the berries stay on a tree too long. When eaten, they
create a buzz for the bird. These party animals may not react
quickly enough when faced by a predatory cat, a dog or an oncoming
SUV. Sunby adds robins should ``never drink and fly.'' There seems
to be a much higher than average number of robins wintering in
Austin this year. You might just be seeing a few dead ones because
so many robins are around. Sunby adds compassionately, ``That
little robin ticker has to give out sometime.'' Q: I was told
Gerber is settling a lawsuit by giving children a $500 savings
bond. I would like to know if the lawsuit settlement is legitimate
before we send information about our child to the address listed
for Gerber. _ W.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: This is one of those Internet legends with no basis in fact.
None. Like the one asking well-intentioned folks to send business
cards to a nonprofit to help an ill child. (Make-a-Wish has
disavowed this one.) The Gerber rumor is more dangerous because
information like your child's Social Security number and birth
certificate can be the basis for establishing a false identity.
Vest your cards. The first Gerber baby products? In late 1928,
strained peas, prunes, carrots, spinach and beef vegetable soup
appeared on the national scene. Q: I have a 1950s-era Chambers
range and it would be helpful to have a source for parts. These
ranges are built like battleships. Do you or your readers know of a
Chambers graveyard for parts? _ David Anderson
</P>
<P>
   A: Contact Macy's Texas Stove Works in Houston, where ``all
parts known to mankind'' for Chambers ranges are stocked. Call
Macy's at (713) 521-0934.Upshot/Update/Uproar_ Reader Bob Reim
saves time and money by wrapping packages in brown kraft paper
produced to protect flooring while painting _ heavy and wide. Pick
up a 36-inch-wide roll for $6 in the paint department of Home Depot
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane S. Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas 78767;
(512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512)
445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
(800) 424-6291.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
