<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO BE GRUNTLED, KEMPT AND COUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 14)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In wordplay you can sometimes get word understanding. Phrases
like ``If vegetarians eat vegetables, what do humanitarians eat?''
and ``Why do we put suits in a garment bag and put garments in a
suitcase?'' have been knocking about the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Such  &UR; double-entendres &LR;  can be funny. For example, two meanings
of  &UR; funny &LR;  are the basis for the line ``Is it true cannibals don't
eat clowns because they taste funny?'' Because  &UR; season &LR;  has several
meanings, we can ask, ``If it's tourist season, why can't we shoot
them?''
</P>
<P>
   These one-liners, spuriously attributed to the word players
George Carlin and Steven Wright, neither of whom claims credit,
cause us to take another look at what we're saying.
</P>
<P>
   The word to be examined today is treated in a similarly
thought-provoking phrase: ``How come you don't ever hear about
 &UR; gruntled &LR;  employees?''
</P>
<P>
   Those of us in the scandalmongering dodge rely heavily on
``disgruntled former employees'' for leaks, tips and other
often-slanderous leads; in gratitude, we change their designation
to the more upbeat  &UR; whistle-blower &LR; . But they are surely in a state
of disgruntlement, and the time has come to get to the bottom of
the word.
</P>
<P>
   It begins, as great armies and New England dessert makers do,
with  &UR; grunts &LR; . These are the short, deep, guttural sounds made by
hogs, especially when eating. The word seeks to imitate the sound;
a Roman farmer was probably responsible for the Latin  &UR; grunire &LR; ,
``to grunt; to sound like a rooting pig or sickly cow.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gruntle &LR;  is what lexicographers call a frequentive, a verb that
describes repeated or recurrent action. (Some call it
``frequentative,'' but they need preventive, not preventative,
medicine.) The frequentive of  &UR; wrest &LR;  is  &UR; wrestle &LR; ; of  &UR; prate &LR; ,
 &UR; prattle &LR; ; of  &UR; spark &LR; ,  &UR; sparkle &LR; ; and the frequentive of  &UR; grunt &LR;  is
 &UR; gruntle &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford English Dictionary defines  &UR; gruntle &LR;  as ``to grumble,
murmur, complain,'' and cites a 1589 sermon by Robert Bruce: ``It
becomes us not to have our hearts here  &UR; gruntling &LR;  upon this
earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes Goddard of Cincinnati writes to suggest that the verb
 &UR; disgruntle &LR;  means ``to deprive of the opportunity to register
dissatisfaction and complaint'' _ that is, to deny the release of a
good, loud grunt, and thereby to make the would-be gruntler sullen.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know; the OED mysteriously lists  &UR; disgruntle &LR;  as
appearing in 1682 and meaning ``to put into sulky dissatisfaction
or ill humor.'' You might think that if the old  &UR; gruntle &LR;  meant
``complain,'' then  &UR; disgruntle &LR;  would mean ``to stop from
complaining,'' but language is not always logical.
</P>
<P>
   However, thanks to a comic writer,  &UR; gruntled &LR;  _ having died as
obsolete _ has indeed made it back into the dictionaries. P.G.
Wodehouse, creator of Jeeves, wrote, in his 1938 ``Code of the
Woosters,'' ``If not actually  &UR; disgruntled &LR; , he was far from being
 &UR; gruntled &LR; .'' The OED and Merriam-Webster list that play on a word
as a back-formation from  &UR; disgruntle &LR; , and the word  &UR; gruntle &LR;  is
born again _ meaning ``to put in a good humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Wodehouse has answered the comedic question. There are, indeed,
 &UR; gruntled &LR;  employees. They're the ones with the soaring 401(k)
accounts, and those fat kittens rarely blow their whistles to
scandalmongers.
</P>
<P>
   While we're at it, and to save each other mail, let's look at
the humorous use of  &UR; couth &LR;  and  &UR; kempt &LR; , wordplay on  &UR; uncouth &LR;  and
 &UR; ill kempt &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   As the current millennium began,  &UR; kempt &LR;  meant ``combed.'' Such
personal tidiness was not always taken to be a positive: ``If a man
have a  &UR; kempt &LR;  hed,'' John Wyclif warned young women in 1380,
``thanne he is a leccherous man.'' (That same suspiciously
slicked-down hair gave rise to the pejorative  &UR; city slicker &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   In the 16th century,  &UR; kempt &LR;  divided into  &UR; ill kempt &LR;  (slobs a
girl could trust) and  &UR; well kempt &LR; , as in James Joyce's
``Ulysses'': ``a wellkempt head, new-barbered'' and still
lecherous. Today, the seldom-used  &UR; kempt &LR;  is neutral, as if with
hair hastily combed by the fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Also a thousand years ago,  &UR; couth &LR;  meant ``known, familiar'' and
 &UR; uncouth &LR;  was ``unknown, foreign, strange'' (as the admonition to
young women later went, ``uncouth, unkissed'').  &UR; Couth &LR;  faded out,
but was back-formed and born again, thanks to Max Beerbohm in 1896.
It was popularized in a funny line delivered by a shrewd dumb-blond
character, played by Judy Holliday in Garson Kanin's 1946 ``Born
Yesterday.'' When criticized by her overbearing lover as  &UR; uncouth &LR; ,
she replied, ``I'm every bit as  &UR; couth &LR;  as you are!''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the comic spirit of language, we still have  &UR; couth &LR; ,
 &UR; kempt &LR;  and  &UR; gruntled &LR; . Like a stand-up comedian on a sit-down
strike, I am still working at 186,300 miles per second on the
cosmological-linguistic question ``So, what's the speed of dark?''
</P>
<P>
   LOWERING THE RUSH
</P>
<P>
   Two metaphors that Democrats and Republicans were able to agree
on during the impeachment proceedings: We must not  &UR; lower the bar &LR; 
and yet we must not  &UR; rush to judgment &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   What bar? Is there a nurturing tavern on Capitol Hill known as
``the Lowered Bar''? No. Is this, as some congressional wags have
suggested, a reference to the limbo, a West Indian dance in which
the dancer bends backward and seeks to shuffle under an ever-lower
bar? Again, no.
</P>
<P>
   The old figure of speech was introduced into recent hearings by
Arthur Schlesinger Jr.: ``The  &UR; lowering of the bar &LR;  ... creates a
novel, indeed revolutionary, theory of impeachment.'' Presumably _
but not certainly _ the metaphor is derived from the high jump, in
which lowering the bar or pole makes it easier for a jumper to
clear.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa! What about the  &UR; rush to judgment &LR; ? Mark Lane, a Washington
lawyer, immortalized the phrase in a 1966 book suggesting a vast
conspiracy in the Kennedy assassination. His source was Lord
Chancellor Thomas Erskine, speaking for the defense in an 1800 case
about the attempted assassination of King George III.
</P>
<P>
   ``An attack upon the king is considered to be  &UR; parricide &LR; 
against the state,'' said Erskine, using a word meaning ``the
murder of a close relative,'' and added, ``There should be a solemn
pause before we  &UR; rush to judgement &LR; .'' Being British, he used an
extra  &UR; e &LR; . When you consider the original subject, this year's use
of the metaphor seems apt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
