<HEADLINE>
THE COLD, HARD REALITIES OF CASH 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ There are, I suppose, some institutions still
revered in this society _ pharmacies, maybe, or dog pounds. But
with such widespread public distrust of every institution from
hospitals to public schools to courtrooms, it always astonishes me
that so many people are so trusting of operations that survive on
loaning money.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's because I once lived in a neighborhood where most
transactions involving personal finance were conducted in the back
booth of a luncheonette. And Jimmy, the guy lending the money,
employed an interesting collection agent.
</P>
<P>
   The collection agent's name was Rocky. His tailor always left
room in Rocky's purple suitcoats for a Smith &AMP; Wesson .38-caliber
police special.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Oliveri is, to his regret, a trusting guy. He's on
disability. He lives in the Albany suburb of Greenfield Center with
his wife, Donna, who manages a motel in the suburb of Saratoga
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Oliveri hit the drive-through of his local
bank to make a deposit.
</P>
<P>
   It was for $493.54, some in checks but most of it in cash. The
teller handed him a receipt for his money. Then he drove away. Not
long after that, he paid some bills. Oliveri was disturbed to
discover that some of the checks he'd written turned out to be what
Rocky the collector would have called ``leapers.'' They bounced
higher than an NBA first-round draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   The precise amount of the shortage: $493.54. Oliveri promptly
went to his bank. He produced his deposit receipt. At which point,
it was pointed out to him, the deposit slip was not stamped. His
account number had been handwritten on the receipt, and the amount,
but the receipt had not been run through the computer printer at
the drive-up window.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me that anybody could have written that stuff on the
receipt,'' Oliveri said. ``I'd driven through quickly, with a crowd
behind me, and I'd never noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line? The bank had no record of the deposit. Oliveri
can't prove a thing. He's just out the money.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Jerry Goldberg. He's a retired gentleman in
Colonie, another Albany suburb. A few years ago, he went to a
finance company to take out a mortgage on his house. So every
month, like most of us, he writes a check for his mortgage payment.
Unlike most of us, however, he hand-delivers the check.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he found out that the finance company had no record
of the mortgage check he delivers on the third of every month. So
Goldberg went to the finance company office with his receipt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't find the check,'' he told me. ``The girl said
the check was definitely lost. They searched all over. So I called
my bank on the automated thing there. It hadn't cleared. So that
same day, I gave them another check for $925.52. It made up for the
check they'd lost.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which was fine until, a few weeks later, some other
checks Goldberg has written began leaping like Michael Jordan. He
called his bank to discover that both checks he'd given the finance
company had been deposited. He'd never stopped payment on the lost
check. That, after all, costs 25 bucks. And the finance company had
assured him that the first check was nowhere to be found. Now
Goldberg faces an overdraft charge of $85.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of these stories? One, never leave a bank line, no
matter how many people are waiting impatiently behind you, without
closely inspecting your deposit receipt. And never, ever leave a
lost check floating around out there. It's just bound to come back
to bite you in the butt.
</P>
<P>
   One other piece of advice, too. Don't ever borrow money from
anybody with a collection agent who wears a purple suit. That's
experience talking.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
