<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-INVESTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLITCHES DON'T DOUSE ENTHUSIASM FOR ON-LINE TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There's a twist of irony in the recent computer
crashes at one popular on-line brokerage business: Rather than a
sign of failure, the problems were an indication of how successful
Internet trading has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are running 100 miles an hour to keep pace,'' said
Bill Burnham, an Internet analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston in
San Francisco. ``Given the spectacular growth of on-line trading,
it's difficult for them to maintain 100 percent performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Chung, an on-line analyst at Williams Capital Group in
New York, said, ``A lot of firms underestimated the attractiveness
of on-line trading to the general public and they weren't quite
prepared for the onslaught of trades.''
</P>
<P>
   On-line investing has exploded in recent months, with total
volume soaring to 340,000 trades in the fourth quarter of 1998, CS
First Boston said. That represents a phenomenal one in every seven
stock trades made in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As cyber-trading transforms the financial world, on-line
brokerage companies are struggling to absorb the crush of trading
by hundreds of thousands of investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology and the Internet are growing at such a tremendous
pace that it's breaking new ground at every level,'' said Tracey
Gordon, a spokeswoman at Charles Schwab in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going from the Stone Age to the Space Age in a matter of
minutes, rather than centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, nearly all of the top on-line brokers _
including ETrade of Palo Alto, Calif., Charles Schwab and
Ameritrade Holding Corp. of Omaha, Neb. _ have each endured several
crashes of their trading systems.
</P>
<P>
   A glitch in new software caused the trading page on ETrade's Web
site to crash several times last week, frustrating customers.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Nash, ETrade's vice president for customer management, said
the new software didn't ``fit well in its new environment,'' even
after rigorous testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Internet systems, you've got the potential for so many
different combinations, and they can go right or wrong,'' Nash
said. ``We take all kinds of precautions, but this was just one of
those things. We're learning a tremendous amount from our
experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the technology is strong enough to handle the
onslaught of trading. On-line brokerages, though, must more quickly
adapt their computer and communications systems to the rapid growth
of their industry.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham said it could be several months before the on-line
brokers catch up to the growing demand from consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ETrade, which is spending $75 million this year on new
technology, can handle up to 170,000 trades a day _ four times its
daily average of 43,000 trades. Next month, the company will open a
third technology center near Atlanta that will triple its trading
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Charles Schwab can handle up to four times its
average volume of nearly 1 million trades a day, Gordon said. The
brokerage has five mainframe computers to handle the load.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, hundreds of investors have complained to the
Securities and Exchange Commission, which regulates the securities
industry, about problems they've endured with on-line brokerage
houses. The most common complaints include delays and errors in
processing trade orders.
</P>
<P>
   The New York state attorney general has said his office will
investigate the on-line trading industry because of consumer
complaints about Web site crashes and delays in stock trades.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the chaos of the October 1997 market crash, scores of
on-line investors found they couldn't get through for hours to make
trades on ETrade, Charles Schwab and other on-line sites.
</P>
<P>
   Angry investors sued ETrade, claiming the brokerage cost
customers money by failing to handle heavy volume trading ``around
the clock,'' as promised in its television and print advertising.
ETrade officials would not comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the electronic brokerages have spent millions of
dollars to upgrade their services.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Web site crashes, analysts Burnham and Chung said the
brokerage companies deserve praise. No other companies in
electronic commerce are executing transactions with customers at
such a rapid pace, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry keeps steamrolling ahead,'' Chung said. ``People
realize there will be these glitches, but they're still attracted
to the overall benefits of trading on-line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
