<HEADER>
A6099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN09-RESEND     02-08 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN09-RESEND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas has chance to improve on schools' 'end-all' measurement
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ This is a message best screened from
schoolchildren in Texas, lest they stampede in the streets, turn
over cars and set enough victory bonfires to blind a space shuttle
crew.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the next three years, TAAS will be no more.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills, the bane of
every school child, rich or poor, bright or struggling, the bane of
parents, of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that TAAS _ the same one viewed by some observers as the
best thing Texas has done for education in a millenium or so.
</P>
<P>
   If current legislation before the Texas Legislature passes,
Texas will take a pencil and mark through TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   I meant it when I told you to screen the children from this. For
now, kids, comes the bad news. As TAAS fades to No. 2 black, a
successor will emerge, likely under a new name. It will be more
comprehensive, involving more subjects, and testing 120,000 more
students.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the contingency for which officials here at the Texas
Education Agency now prepare.
</P>
<P>
   Reforms in Senate Bill 103 would expand and broaden state
testing in the fall of 2002. The current exit test is given
starting in 10th grade. Under SB 103, authored by Sen. Teel Bivins,
R-Amarillo, and promoted by Education Commissioner Mike Moses,
graduation would hinge on a new 11th-grade exit test. Other reforms
would include testing for science in grades five, seven, and 10
(currently science is tested only in grade eight), and social
studies in grades four, eight and 10 (currently only eighth-graders
take a social studies TAAS.)
</P>
<P>
   Students would be tested at reading and math in grades three
through 11. Currently ninth-graders statewide do not take TAAS. The
writing portion would be expanded to include grade six (in addition
to the current testing in grades four, eight and 10.)
</P>
<P>
   As with everything involving TAAS, this carries as much dread as
promise, and potentially as much drag as it would provide a boost.
Most educators, if they are honest, will assert that TAAS has
become the engine that drives most wheels in Texas public schools,
and that's not good. It's dehumanizing for teachers. It undermines
the lively arts and the study of history, science and all else that
would take time away from ``the basics'' _ as if history, science
and social studies don't qualify as that.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, by focusing so heavily on the basics, and making a
test of minimum grade-level skills the holy grail of
accountability, Texas by design deprives students who would thrive
in more rarefied conditions. Texas thinks it is doing its best when
it rings the bell with rising TAAS scores. Actually it is only
bragging that more and more students can rise to a common
denominator that's too low to rank as excellence.
</P>
<P>
   So what do we do?
</P>
<P>
   We raise the common denominator, for one, make TAAS more
rigorous, even if it means lowering the score needed to pass.
</P>
<P>
   For another, we make it possible for some students to shed the
back-to-basics yoke throughout the year if they can demonstrate off
the bat in the fall that they have a command of grade-level basics.
Yes, let them test out of eight months of TAAS preparation.
</P>
<P>
   We make math tests that reflect true grade-level mastery. We
make composition tests real tests of real writing rather than the
gauge used today that amounts to grading a child for a rough draft
and encourages formula regurgitation.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, we need to come to grips with the rampant,
blood-sucking, mind-numbing plague that is education driven by a
test, and return to testing that's driven by education.
</P>
<P>
   Any of these objectives, if met, would be worth victory
bonfires. In three upcoming columns, I will light a few candles.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
