A6116 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMOUS-MOVIE-LOVE-SCE     02-08 1435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMOUS-MOVIE-LOVE-SCENES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOMENTS OF THE HEART: THE STORIES BEHIND HOLLYWOOD'S FAVORITE LOVE
SCENES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Michelle Pfeiffer and Jeff Bridges in a
scene from ``The Fabulous Baker Boys.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Love scenes mean never having to say you're sorry.
 &HT;    Except when your elbow blocks someone's closeup. Or you're
rubbing your co-star's lips raw by take 30.
 &HT;    Or if you're curled up in a car trunk with George Clooney and
having major leg cramps, as Jennifer Lopez learned making ``Out of
Sight'' (1998).
 &HT;    ``After 45 takes,'' she says, ``I was praying, `Please, let all
this cuddling be over.'''
 &HT;    In reality, not all of the movies' most celebrated love scenes
were all that romantic, at least to the stars who made them. 
 -0- 
 ``PRETTY WOMAN'' (1990)  
 &HT;    The scene: A wealthy businessman (Richard Gere) and his
enchanting hooker (Julia Roberts) relax in the tub in his luxury
hotel suite.
 &HT;    ``The bathtub scene wasn't as fun as it looked,'' Roberts
recalls. ``No one wants to spend a day in water, even if it's with
Richard Gere. Your body stocking is pinching. At one point I'm
lathering up Richard's chest for the 20th time and he goes, `Julia,
my skin is cracking open. You've got to stop using the soap on
me.'''
 ``DIRTY DANCING'' (1987)  
 &HT;    The scene: A poor dance instructor (Patrick Swayze) and a rich
college girl (Jennifer Grey) crawl passionately toward one another
across the floor of a Catskills dance studio.
 &HT;    ``A few days before we did the scene, my knee mysteriously
filled with fluid,'' Swayze says. ``I had to have it drained with a
needle. Needless to say, it was no picnic crawling on it. I might
look like I'm happy and in love, but I was in horrible pain.''
 ``A STAR IS BORN'' (1976)  
 &HT;    The scene: A singer on his way down (Kris Kristofferson) and his
wife, a singer on her way up (Barbra Streisand), express their love
in a tub.
 &HT;    ``It's my favorite scene of the film,'' Kristofferson says,
``but it was tough. I remember our producer, Jon Peters, was also
Barbra's boyfriend at the time. He wanted me to wear a wetsuit in
the tub _ I guess he was jealous. I would have been jealous of me,
too.
 &HT;    ``In the end, I did wear some boxer shorts in the tub. It's
disappointing, because it would be a better story if I wore
nothing.''
 ``BULL DURHAM'' (1988)  
 &HT;    The scene: An aging baseball player (Kevin Costner) and a
philosophical fan (Susan Sarandon) finally get up close and
personal with each other.
 &HT;    ``We approached these scenes from a perspective of fun,''
Sarandon says with a laugh. ``Kevin and I knew we had to have movie
sex in a tub, sex on the kitchen table and so on. We wanted to look
like it was the best time in our lives.
 &HT;    ``I remember being nervous and hoping he moved in the right
angles to hide parts of my body.''
 ``THE BRIDGES OF MADISON COUNTY'' (1995)  
 &HT;    The scene: An Iowa housewife (Meryl Streep) and her photographer
lover (Clint Eastwood) realize that she can never leave her family.
On his way out of town, they spot each other and gaze longingly
across the road neither will cross.
 &HT;    ``It's my favorite scene,'' Streep says. ``I remember we shot it
in the rain. Clint is standing there with his hair plastered to his
forehead, and the entire time I was wishing the script could change
and my character would go to him.
 &HT;    ``But that would have ruined the movie.''
 ``OUT OF SIGHT'' (1998)  
 &HT;    The scene: A fugitive (George Clooney) breaks out of jail,
stuffs a federal marshall (Jennifer Lopez) in the trunk of the
getaway car and slips in next to her. His buddy drives off, leaving
the two to get acquainted.
 &HT;    ``We did 45 takes, which took two days,'' Lopez says. ``What I
remember the most is that I could curl up like that for about four
hours and then I needed a break. I needed to stretch.''
 &HT;    Clooney has a different take on the scene.
 &HT;    ``We rehearsed the scene on the very creaky couch in my office,
which was fun,'' he says roguishly. ``Later, it was funny because
we had to do reshoots on the trunk scene. I was like, `Yes! Yes!
Yes!'
 &HT;    ``Then I said, `Really? That's too bad.'''
 ``AS GOOD AS IT GETS'' (1997)  
 &HT;    The scene: Nasty Melvin Udall (Jack Nicholson) finally softens,
telling his might-be girlfriend (Helen Hunt) why they belong
together: ``You make me want to be a better man.''
 &HT;    ``I loved doing this scene,'' Nicholson says. ``We didn't have
to do too many takes, but I remember thinking, `This is one of the
most beautiful things I've ever heard one human being say to
another.'''
 &HT;    Hunt agrees: ``I teared up for real every time he said the
line.''
 ``THE MASK OF ZORRO'' (1998)  
 &HT;    The scene: The dashing Zorro (Antonio Banderas) matches swords
with a beautiful maiden (Catherine Zeta Jones) and, in the
processes, whittles away at her dress until it finally comes off.
 &HT;    ``My dress was attached by wires,'' Jones recalls. ``All of a
sudden someone offstage pulled a string and, whoosh, I was almost
nude. Antonio had this devastating smirk the entire time.''
 &HT;    ``The only bad part is that Catherine slashed my back a little
bit during the scene,'' Banderas adds jokingly. ``Also, I came home
and told my wife, Melanie Griffith, about it and ... well, I still
have the bruise.''
 ``THE FABULOUS BAKER BOYS'' (1989)  
 &HT;    The scene: A sultry singer (Michelle Pfeiffer) slithers across a
piano singing ``Makin' Whoopee'' to her handsome pianist (Jeff
Bridges).
 &HT;    ``I thought that either I would look like the biggest fool alive
or the scene would be cinematically great,'' Pfeiffer says. ``I
trusted the director, who said, `I promise I won't make you look
like a fool.' I said, `But I'm standing on top of a piano. How can
I not look like a fool?'
 &HT;    ``Plus that dress was very slippery. I was worried about falling
off the piano, which thankfully didn't happen.''
 ``SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE'' (1998)  
 &HT;    The scene: The Bard (Joseph Fiennes) and his lady love (Gwyneth
Paltrow) spend a day in bed, reading to each other from his new
play, ``Romeo and Juliet.''
 &HT;    ``I remember thinking during the filming that we were getting
it,'' Paltrow recalls. ``We were conveying the passions of these
people in a beautiful, seamless way.''
 &HT;    Fiennes takes a less romantic view, however.
 &HT;    ``Oh, it wasn't as glamorous as one might think,'' he says.
``Let's start with the fact that Gwyneth's boyfriend, Ben Affleck,
is in the movie, and he's a big guy. You don't want to get on the
wrong side of Ben and say, `Guess what? I will be spending the
duration of the day in bed with your girlfriend.''
 ``PRETTY IN PINK'' (1986)  
 &HT;    The scene: The high-school prom. The poor girl (Molly Ringwald)
dances with the school geek (Jon Cryer) who's always been madly in
love with her.
 &HT;    ``The day we shot the big dance scene I had the flu,'' Ringwald
says. ``Every single time poor Jon would twirl me around, I would
have to say, `Excuse me.' Then I would run in the corner and throw
up. It wasn't exactly romantic.''
 ``JERRY MAGUIRE'' (1996)  
 &HT;    The scene: A sports agent (Tom Cruise) returns to his estranged
wife (Renee Zellweger) and tells her, ``You complete me.''
 &HT;    ``The day Tom looked in my eyes and said that line was
fantastic,'' Zellweger says. ``We did 15 takes. When it was over, I
was actually shaking.
 &HT;    ``I remember I sat down in this fake kitchen and Tom came in. He
sat down next to me and smiled, and then said, `Renee, just think _
we'll be together forever.'
 &HT;    ``Of course, he meant on the screen.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
