<SLUG> BC-FAREWELL-TO-GEORGE-CLOONEY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ER'S' GEORGE CLOONEY ANSWERS HIS FINAL CALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of George Clooney in a scene from ``ER.'' 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he prepares to leave NBC's hit series ``ER,'' George Clooney
is being showered with praise for his acting abilities. After all,
dozens of critics say, it's his talent more than anything else
which has made the show television's highest-rated drama.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't expect him to agree. When I interviewed Clooney in
his trailer outside the ``ER'' soundstage a couple of years ago, he
did his best to convince me he wasn't much of an actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an actor, I'm somewhat of a hack,'' he said, perfectly
seriously. ``I find myself stealing from the actors that I really
like, as opposed to coming up with interesting choices of my own.
The truth is, you don't have to be a great actor on a show that's
this well written.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled appearing on stage before an audience which included
his uncle, Oscar-winning actor/director Jose Ferrer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crying and yelling and spitting and doing everything in
it,'' Clooney said. ``Jose was sitting in the back, and afterward I
went to him and said, `What do you think?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said, `Get the scenery out of your mouth, you don't
know where it's been!'''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney freely admitted that the constraints of a television
production schedule make series acting much different from film or
stage work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're working on a TV series and a director comes in,
you can't really do what they tell you,'' he said. ``They come on
the show and want to make their episode something special _ `This
is the one where Dr. Ross cries.' But you can't do every one of
those. So you learn how to direct yourself and not pay attention to
the director.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll say, `Do it this way,' and you'll say, `Yeah, yeah,
yeah' _ and you'll do it your way, and everything is moving too
fast for them to notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Doing it his way has worked out for Clooney. He's leaving ``ER''
to focus on a film career which so far has drawn critical praise
more often than box-office gold.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for Dr. Ross to have a memorable death scene, a la
Det. Bobby Simone's much-hyped departure from ``NYPD Blue'' in fall
1998. Clooney isn't burning any bridges _ he's already made it
known that he's up for an occasional return to the series. There
may be a few golden eggs left in the proverbial goose, and the
canny Clooney isn't ruling anything out.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, executive producer John Wells has opted not to make
the actor's departure part of any sort of season-ending
cliff-hanger, but to incorporate it into the season's natural arc
of stories, much as the series did when Sherry Stringfield left
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney comes by that show-business savvy naturally. He hails
from a show-business family _ besides Ferrer, singer Rosemary
Clooney is his aunt and actor/television host Nick Clooney is his
father _ and has paid his Hollywood dues. Before scoring with
``ER,'' he had done his share of failed pilots, had been jettisoned
from 1990's ``Baby Talk'' before it even hit the air and had done
time as a supporting player on a few successful series, ``The Facts
of Life,'' ``Roseanne'' and ``Sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   So he came in knowing how Hollywood works, how something as
simple as a lucky break or a good time slot can make the difference
between obscurity and global stardom, and he was able to maximize
the benefits of his success on ``ER,'' neither bailing out at the
first opportunity _ as, for example, David Caruso did with ``NYPD
Blue'' _ nor staying so long on the series that it stifled his
big-screen potential.
</P>
<P>
   And to date ``potential'' is the key word for Clooney's career
as a movie star.
</P>
<P>
   His two most impressive performances _ opposite Michelle
Pfeiffer in the slight-but-charming romantic comedy ``One Fine
Day'' (1996) and as a raffish criminal in ``Out of Sight'' (1998) _
both suffered from bad timing: The former was bulldozed at the box
office by Tom Cruise's ``Jerry Maguire,'' which was released a week
later, while ``Out of Sight'' was a subtle, intricately paced crime
comedy/drama that foundered amid the leviathans of summer 1998.
</P>
<P>
   His other films have been less distinguished. ``The Peacemaker''
(1997) was a turgid political thriller, heavy on technobabble and
light on chemistry between Clooney and co-star Nicole Kidman.
``From Dusk Till Dawn'' (1997) was a cheesy B movie _ one with some
style, but a cheesy B movie nonetheless _ while ``Batman &AMP; Robin''
(1997) was a brain-dead behemoth swamped in the kind of lavish
special effects that are antithetical to an actor like Clooney,
whose appeal lies in his relaxed, easygoing charm.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the stakes are high as he leaves ``ER.'' His viability as
a leading man will probably be determined by his first couple of
post-television films, which makes it all the more troubling that
he isn't sure exactly what they'll be.
</P>
<P>
   Recently ``Leatherheads,'' an early-days-of-football piece that
would have reunited him with ``Out of Sight'' director Steven
Soderbergh, was cancelled before it went into production.
</P>
<P>
   He's currently working on ``Three Kings,'' a film about a trio
of Gulf War soldiers with a little time on their hands who decide
to hunt for a lost gold reserve. His unlikely co-stars include
rapper/model-turned-actor Mark Wahlberg and rapper Ice Cube. Behind
the camera is David O. Russell, who wrote and directed Ben
Stiller's knockabout, love-hurts comedy, ``Flirting with Disaster''
(1996).
</P>
<P>
   Shrewdly, however, Clooney is hedging his bets. He may be
dreaming of movie stardom, but he's keeping his hand in on the
television front as well. His production company is developing
``Blood Brothers,'' an hour-long mob drama, for CBS, as well as
``Double Helix,'' a drama written by Mike Werb and Michael
Colleary, who wrote ``Face/Off'' (1997).
</P>
<P>
   The actor also has a production deal with HBO and Warner Bros.
Television, which produces ``ER,'' to mount ``Kilroy,'' a
laugh-track-free comedy in which a fictional aspiring actor will
visit the sets of real-life television shows. His fictional
``gigs'' will be actual appearances on the real shows _ a
mind-bending wrinkle reminiscent of ``The Larry Sanders Show,''
which clearly appeals to Clooney.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he's fascinated by the retro-possibilities of live
television. Clooney was one of the principal movers behind ``ER's''
famous live episode, and has several live television movies in the
works for CBS. Possible subjects include a remake of Sidney Lumet's
``Fail-Safe'' (1964) and ``Murrow and Me,'' a biography of the
famed television-journalism pioneer Edward R. Murrow. He plans to
appear in the former, and perhaps in the latter as well.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``ER,'' Clooney's departure comes at an awkward time, the
same season that NBC agreed to break the bank and fork over a
not-even-close-to-precedented $13 million an episode.
</P>
<P>
   The show's biggest star will not be replaced, at least not in so
many words. The series' ratings have remained strong, and the
producers will play up existing characters and story lines rather
than importing a new actor or an established star to take up
Clooney's slack.
</P>
<P>
   Noah Wyle would seem to be the biggest benefactor of Clooney's
exit, which leaves open the position of resident hunk. But don't
count out Eriq La Salle, who has never gotten the attention that
the caliber of his performances ought to warrant. That may be
changing, however _ the week after Clooney leaves, ``ER'' will
showcase La Salle in one of those periodic episodes that focuses on
one character.
</P>
<P>
   In short, fans of ``ER'' and of George Clooney need not worry,
at least initially. Neither the series' staying power nor the
actor's career shows much sign of a weakening pulse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is the Los Angeles-based senior writer for TV
Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
