<HEADLINE>
HOME, SWEET HOME FOR THE BIRDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Danby, Vt., about a dozen miles north of Manchester, Vermont
Country Bird Houses manufactures stylish homes for your tweety
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Jim Kardas, who began the business after retreating
from 20 years in advertising, the handmade bird houses are designed
and sized to accommodate the needs of specific birds. Features
include removable panels for seasonal cleaning, ventilation and
drainage.
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration comes from historic Vermont structures: churches,
schools and cottages. Also available are three- and five-structure
bird villages. During the company's winter sale, on through the end
of March, prices range from $89 to $175; village sets cost up to
$500. Order by calling 888-440-0226, visiting the Web site,
http://www.vermontcountry.com or stopping by the shop, on Danby's
Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EASIER LISTENING: A company called RangeStar makes a little
gizmo that clips onto the antenna of digital (PCS) mobile phones
and promises to improve the phone's performance significantly, in
several ways: by increasing the range by 100 percent or more,
decreasing the number of dropped calls by 80 percent, improving
call clarity and extending battery life by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the product changes the shape of the outgoing
signal to reduce, by 86 percent, the amount of signal going into
the user's head. In 1997, the mobile-phone market was split almost
evenly between conventional cellular (analog) and digital mobile
phones; digital will, by 2001, account for 90 percent of the
estimated $55 billion worth of business worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Order the $30 RangeStar PCS Antenna by calling the company
directly, at 877-966-3371, or visiting its Web site,
http://www.rangestar.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WALLET ALERT: We're not sure what a beeping billfold has to do
with the year 2000, but that's how a company called Kopel Inc. is
trumpeting its new entry into that field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit card protection for the new millennium,'' reads the
headline of its news release. Peculiar pitch notwithstanding, the
product sounds like a good idea: When a card (debit, ATM, charge,
credit) or passport is removed from its slot, the wallet beeps a
few times every 20 seconds until the card is replaced. The wallets,
which resemble standard moneyholders, come in various sizes and
styles, for men and women, priced from $14 to $38.
</P>
<P>
   Because each slot must be filled, the wallets come with filler
cards, in case you're short of plastic. The wallet's beep is
controlled by a tiny microchip and a replaceable watch battery with
a three-year warranty. To order, call 800-988-6255 or visit the Web
site, http://www.beepingwallet.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
