<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAVING ONE'S RELIGION AT THE DOOR?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A column about the pope will always stir up readers _ which is
why I only write one every 20 years or so. The latest was last
week's offering criticizing Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan for
commuting a convicted killer's death sentence at the urging of Pope
John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   To buttress my argument that public officials should not kowtow
to religious leaders on matters of public policy, I cited the
example of President John F. Kennedy, a Roman Catholic who promised
the voters during his 1960 campaign that he would follow the
dictates of the Constitution, not the pope, in carrying out his
presidential duties.
</P>
<P>
   Some readers agreed; some didn't. A few of the dissenters were
fans of the pope; some had no apparent interest in the pope but had
plenty of interest in capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the most interesting responses came from a reader who
took issue with my contention that public officials should park
religion at the door when doing the public's business:
</P>
<P>
   ``This week is National Catholic Schools Week. During this week,
we celebrate the many accomplishments of our Catholic schools,
students and teachers. I personally take great pride in having
attended Catholic schools for twelve years. My parents made many,
many sacrifices to send my eight siblings and me to Catholic
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children, and all my nieces and nephews, have attended or
are currently attending Catholic schools. Obviously, my siblings
and I think that a Catholic education is a tradition we want to
pass on to the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now, that brings me to why I am writing to you. My whole
purpose in sending my children to Catholic schools is to make
certain that the values that I teach at home are reinforced at
school. I want to make certain that those values permeate every
facet of their lives. I want to make certain that every thought,
that every decision, and that every action they take is made after
thoughtful consideration of the values that define Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to know that in life you don't compartmentalize
the secular vs. the religious, and the public vs. the private. You
don't leave your values at home. You are who you are, regardless of
whether you are conducting business at church, at home, at school,
or at work. This is true even if that work is government or
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell my children that if they run for public office and win,
the victory should be for who they are _ not because they will
mindlessly carry out today's perception of what is popular. When
you vote, you should vote for the individual who most closely
believes what you believe, and who values what you value.
</P>
<P>
   ``You then trust, unless presented with facts to the contrary,
that the individual will make the right choice when presented with
facts that the general public does not know. ... you believe that
the individual is a person of honor and integrity, and will
represent you accordingly. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``If JFK chooses to divorce himself from his Catholicity to win
public office, then so be it. If you choose to divorce yourself
from your Catholicity to sell newspapers, then so be it. But don't
tell my children or those of other Catholic parents that that is
the only way. It is NOT.''
</P>
<P>
   That all sounds pretty good _ especially the part about
``compartmentalizing,'' which has recently become a popular catch
phrase for the rationalization that a politician's private conduct
has nothing to do with his or her fitness for public office. Surely
a moral society has a right to expect that its leaders will respect
and adhere to that society's values.
</P>
<P>
   And we certainly should expect our leaders to bring their values
to bear in making decisions that affect the public. What we don't
expect public officials to do is impose any particular religious
beliefs or the rules of any church on a citizenry that may not
subscribe to those specific beliefs or rules.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution of the United States guarantees the separation
of church and state. In America, that is the only way.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
