<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LeBRUN-ACQUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S END THE IMPEACHMENT CHARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With: LYNCH-CONVICT)  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED LeBRUN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Heaven help us, it's almost over and not a day
too soon.
</P>
<P>
   About the only memorable moment from the Republicans' endless
impeachment trial of the president was that scream of angst from
the Senate gallery on Thursday. An ordinary citizen, neatly dressed
and bearded and clearly frustrated, couldn't stand it anymore and
finally shouted down to the proceedings: ``God almighty, take the
vote and get it over with.''
</P>
<P>
   That unidentified individual spoke for Americans from coast to
coast, for the vast majority of us. Which is a great deal more than
you can say for the Republicans in Congress who deliberately turned
their backs on the people to indulge themselves in a relentless
partisan hounding of President Clinton while cloaking the shameless
process with a mythical higher calling.
</P>
<P>
   It's also more than you can say about those pundits and
supporters of the hypocritical Republicans, including newspaper
columnists like my pontificating colleague Dan Lynch. For a year
now we've been regularly treated to ever shriller and more strident
denunciations of the president. ``Impeach, impeach'' has been his
steady cranky subtext, well-larded with hokum Constitutional wisdom
for justification. He has tried to shepherd us with a two-by-four
into the Republican camp, and he too has failed.
</P>
<P>
   His reaction, and those of fellow travelers like national
columnist George Will, are amusing. They blame the people for not
getting it. Here they are, columnists paid to persuade with their
superior intellects. Yet when the public instead embraces Clinton
with the highest popularity rating of any president in peace time,
they fault the American people as too dumb to figure out what they
ought to think. Namely: Don't you understand that this is a
critical moment in our nation's history and that the president is a
criminal?
</P>
<P>
   Well, no, we don't. Along with not telling the people they're
too stupid to have the right opinion on the impeachment, maybe it's
also not a good plan to insist on what the news is. News, like
cream and less elegant organic matter, rises to the top. The
American people have spoken resoundingly on what the news is here.
Wall Street is mercurial, but not because of the soap opera in
Washington, and continues in its bullish ways. Folks go about their
business forgetting for days at a time that only the second
impeachment trial in our history is taking place.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the people are showing by their behavior that
it's a nice sideshow going on inside the Beltway, but it is not
significant enough to bump ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   History will vindicate the Republican position, says the chief
House prosecutor, Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois. Talk about the last
bastion of the crackpot, it has to be ``no one understands I'm a
genius, but future generations will.
</P>
<P>
   Please. I will not presume what history will say about all this,
but if the contemporary reaction is at least a clue, I think we can
expect a footnote and an asterisk and that's about it. Another
pathetic testament to how badly the self-righteous right misjudged
how the rest of us would react to the presidential affair.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, an affair. Sex. That's what it was always about
from the beginning, rant as much as you like about perjury and
obstruction of justice. The naked truth is that every aspect of
every charge against the president is within the context of a
sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky. Lying about sex is about
sex. Gifts, jobs and all the rest _ sex. The American people
figured that out right off, shrugged their collective shoulders,
generally agreed Bill Clinton had the morals of a smarmy brush
salesman on the road, but also decided that seamy personal behavior
isn't impeachable, or our problem.
</P>
<P>
   It's Hillary's problem. No Harvard law degree necessary. End of
story. We should be so lucky. This week, maybe, the windbags can
pull themselves from the keyhole and end this travesty. Then after
a cold shower perhaps Congress can do what it hasn't done for some
time _ get back to work.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Fred LeBrun writes for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box 15000,
Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
