<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-CONVICT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GUILTY GUY WINS, AMERICA LOSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (With: LEBRUN-ACQUIT)  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Barring some miracle, the Senate will vote this
week against throwing President Clinton out of the White House.
This probably will be your fault.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more precisely, it will be the fault of people who think the
way you think, which is most people. When you pluck away the
feathers _ and, man, have we had feathers flying around in this one
_ the naked corpse of their argument shapes up like this:
</P>
<P>
   1. He didn't really lie under oath. And if he did it wasn't
perjury. And if it was perjury it was perjury over sex. And if it
was perjury over sex it doesn't count. And I would have done that,
too. And if you wouldn't have done it, too, then you're really
stupid.
</P>
<P>
   2. Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., and his buddies are vicious, vengeful
creeps. And who needs some uptight, modern-day version of Cotton
Mather launching a federal investigation every time somebody the
religious right dislikes unzips his fly? And I hate those people so
much that I don't care what Clinton did as long as he didn't leave
a bleeding carcass in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   3. They're all hypocritical lowlifes. They're all chasing babes.
And my 401(k) is doing great. And, hey, there's an NBA game on, and
do we have enough chips and dip?
</P>
<P>
   Madness, all of it. Sure, senators are supposed to be immune to
such outbreaks of public insanity. They read the polls, though.
They see these attitudes enduring for a solid year, regardless of
the facts. And they say, ``OK, this is what the people want.''
</P>
<P>
   So just as there was really no quest for truth in the House
impeachment hearings, there's no quest for truth in the Senate
trial of the president. Nobody wants the facts firmly fixed in the
record on the Senate floor. The Senate is galloping away from this
thing like it's a lion and they're zebras.
</P>
<P>
   We, the people, will pay for it, too. Not right away, but those
chickens are circling up there, in search of a roost. Once you
permit anybody who takes the presidential oath to commit felonies _
serious crimes, high crimes by any reasonable definition _ and
remain in office, then you're setting the stage for disaster down
the road.
</P>
<P>
   First you dismiss perjury over a sexual encounter. Then you
dismiss it over something like a third-rate burglary. Then you
dismiss it over a well-intentioned lie to Congress over, say,
whether we really need 500,000 guys in uniform in some
inconsequential rathole like Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   If we reject the highest standards of conduct for the occupants
of the Oval Office, then we're just begging them to screw us
collectively instead of individually. And some of them will, too,
just wait.
</P>
<P>
   One of the tactics of the Clinton spin team _ the Chicago Bulls
of American politics, by the way _ has been to paint everybody who
wants him ousted as a right-wing loon. But I'm with distinctly
non-right-wing loons like Lowell Weicker, the former governor and
senator from Connecticut, and A.M. Rosenthal, the retired editor of
the New York Times. They both bemoan the public's determination to
keep a criminal in the White House, whatever his virtues and
however scary his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   To me, that has always been the issue _ not Clinton the man,
just Clinton the president. I never found him all that
objectionable politically or even personally, despite his
skirt-chasing. In fact, I've admired his immense gifts as a
politician and supported his stand on issues like the Family Leave
Act. I just want him bounced out for committing felonies, is all.
</P>
<P>
   But I know a good many bright, decent, thoughtful people who
think as you do, and I've convinced precisely none of them on this.
And, as Johnny Cochran might say, if you cannot convict, you cannot
evict. So, whatever happens down the road as a result of this won't
be my fault.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be yours.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
