<HEADER>
A6173 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-FAT-BOS &LR;      02-08 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-FAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE BULL BY THE HORNS IN BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO _ Like a king on his throne, Antonio de Oliveira
Bemvindo leaned back in a rickety metal chair in the hot, dimly lit
basement of a local government building and grinned over his good
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   The amiable, broad-shouldered electrician, called ``Bull''
around the halls of the local Legislature, knows that no matter how
bad the Brazilian economy gets, his job is guaranteed by law for
life. He makes roughly $2,100 a month, about three times more than
the average private sector wage.
</P>
<P>
   Bemvido only has to work 10 days a month. And if he stays on the
job for another 10 years he qualifies for six months vacation. ``We
make good money because the people upstairs make good money,''
Bemvindo, 48, said while pointing with his thumb to the
representatives' offices above him. ``And the reason they get money
is because this is a house of power.''
</P>
<P>
   His job represents the kind carefree public-sector spending that
Brazil's government has enjoyed for years. Now, however,
international lenders and investors are demanding that Brazil
sharply reduce its deficit, which has swollen to about 8 percent of
its gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   ``(There) . . . is an attitude thatcomes from colonial times
that the state can do whatever it wants,'' said Geraldo Carbone,
president of BankBoston Brazil. ``But if this country is to be part
of the international community, we cannot have this kind of fiscal
deficit anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian leaders and representatives of the International
Monetary Fund hammered out a revised agreement this week for a
$41.5 billion aid package that among other things includes strict
targets to reduce government debt.
</P>
<P>
   Observers predict that unless Brazil sharply cuts these
expenses, its economy could slip back into the nightmarish days of
widespread unemployment and 2,000 percent annual inflation it saw
during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Government facilities in Rio de Janeiro aren't plush, but they
are rife with inefficiencies and lessons in how the country's
public sector operates.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Bemvido is a ``legislative assistant,'' a title
given to him 17 years ago when he started working as a lawmaker's
bodyguard. But he said he didn't like that job, so he was
transferred to the higher paying assignment in the basement, where
he's now responsible for making sure the building's air
conditioners work. His title was never changed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the government paycheck isn't enough to raise three
children, Bemvido says, so he is allowed to supplement his income
by teaching classes in the Brazilian martial arts known as
capoeira.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Marcelo Fernando, a 27-year-old refrigeration
technician for a private company that is under contract to the
city, makes about $270 a month working next to Bemvido.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bothered that Bull makes more,'' Fernando said, adding
that he occasionally joins Bemvido and other government workers for
a beer after work. ``But there are great salaries when you work for
a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   The average private sector salary is $200 to $250 a month,
whereas the largest portion of workers in the federal executive
branch _ about 26 percent _ received monthly wages of $470 to $550,
according to the federal administration agency. The government
employs about 5.5 million of Brazil's roughly 71 million workers,
the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, local and state governments by law aren't supposed to
spend more than 60 percent of their budgets on salaries. But last
year 17 of Brazil's 27 states exceeded that limit, according to
federal figures.
</P>
<P>
   The state government in Rio de Janeiro, for example, spent 80
percent of its budget on personnel in 1998. All the state houses
combined owe loans to the federal government that come out to
roughly $500 for each of Brazil's 163 million citizens.
</P>
<P>
   During his reelection campaign last year, President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso promised several cost-cutting reforms. Some of
them have been grudgingly approved by Congress, such as a reduction
in pension benefits and a requirement for employee evaluations to
determine whether someone can be fired for poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the new law, Leile Moreira, a 36-year-old federal
Justice Department employee, will have an additional $300 deducted
from her pay. But she will still net $2,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind making a sacrifice because I have so many friends
who don't even have a job,'' Moreira said while walking downtown
carrying a stack of legal papers. ``The problem is the government
often doesn't use the money for good things. I think things will
get worse before they get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as new reforms begin to take effect, some analysts believe
that government layoffs _ once an unthinkable idea in Brazil _ will
be unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson Mello e Souza, a former planning director for the
Organization of American States and now vice chancellor at the
private University Estacio de Sa in Rio de Janeiro, said that
cutting government spending too much could make things worse by
dramatically increasing unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government is an easy target to pick,'' said Mello e Souza,
``but it could put people out on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   A more important strategy, the sociologist added, was the
Cardoso administration's decision last month to allow Brazil's
currency, the real, to float freely against the dollar. But that
policy has created a feeling of betrayal among many Brazilians that
their government, long a staunch defender of its currency, had
conceded defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is making all these decisions about our money
and we can't even buy bread,'' said one woman in Rio de Janeiro who
identified herself only as a federal employee. ``It's not that
there's no money, it's that the money we have is poorly
administered. The whole system is to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston's Carbone and others are optimistic that the country
can avoid an economic meltdown through a regimen of free-floating
currency exchange, increased exports and tighter government
accounting. Despite inflation predictions this year of betweeen 10
and 20 percent, there is even talk of new growth here within two
years.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bemvindo, an avowed leftist, is not so cheerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to worry about my job, but the others here do,''
Bemvindo said, as he wheeled his chair in front of a
floor-to-ceiling-high stack of idle air conditioners. ``This is not
a fair system. But Brazil is that way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Correspondent Karen de Sa contributed to this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
