<HEADER>
A6175 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIULIANA-PATAKI-BOS &LR;      02-08 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANA-PATAKI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHUMMING UP TO GEORGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Empire State is a vast land but, it seems these
days, not big enough for Rudolph Giuliani and George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of New York City and the governor of the state: Both
are Republicans, both hold similar views on the major issues of the
day. But both also have ambitions for national office _ even for
the highest office in the land _ and they know New York can offer
up only one contender at a time.
</P>
<P>
   So, the biggest drama in New York politics now has little to do
with President Clinton's impeachment trial or with the tantalizing
rumors that his wife, Hillary Clinton, may consider a run for the
US Senate. Rather, it's the feud between Giuliani and Pataki _ and
the guns both are toting to the showdown are getting bigger by the
day.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani was in Albany last week, lobbying the state
Legislature for more money, he did not even meet with Pataki _ nor
did Pataki ask him to.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, one of Giuliani's agencies attacked Pataki's
appointee to the city's school-construction board, blaming him for
the death of a Brooklyn schoolgirl who was hit by a falling brick.
The appointee was forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Almost instantly, Pataki launched an official probe not only of
the board but of corruption throughout the city's school system,
invoking the Moreland Act, which gives state investigators the
power to subpoena witnesses and documents.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani erupted, and unleashed his schools chancellor, Rudy
Crews, to denounce Pataki publicly for using the city's
schoolchildren as a prop for his own presidential ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   And the list goes on: Shortly before this episode, Giuliani
announced plans to build a huge stadium on the West Side of
Manhattan, not for the New York Yankees, which, he now concedes,
will probably stay in the Bronx, but for the New York Jets, which
he hopes to lure back from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   He did not inform Pataki ahead of time, even though the governor
would have to approve such a project.
</P>
<P>
   The two have also recently disagreed about plans and funding for
the Javits Convention Center, the Coliseum, the Holocaust Museum,
and a rail line to John F. Kennedy Airport.
</P>
<P>
   At bottom, many observers believe, Pataki and many other state
Republicans have never forgiven Giuliani for endorsing his
opponent, the Democratic incumbent, Mario Cuomo, in the 1994
governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, both men dismiss talk of a feud. Privately, though,
associates of both men acknowledge a mutual animosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clear to everyone around them that these two guys
can't stand each other,'' one business executive who deals with
both officials said, asking, like most people in such
circumstances, not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Both men also claim they are no great ambitions to higher
office, though they have been gallivanting around the country,
speaking at Republican fund-raisers, and forming their own
political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki told the New York Observer last year that he cannot help
but contemplate the White House. Giuliani, who must retire as mayor
in 2001 due to term-limit laws, has lately downplayed the idea of
running for president, but is known to have an eye on two other
possibilities: the US Senate seat that Democrat Daniel Patrick
Moynihan is vacating in 2000 (the same one Hillary boosters want
her to seek) _ or teaming up with Texas governor and likely
presidential candidate George W. Bush _ either as a running mate,
or as a possible future member of a Bush Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, son of former president George Bush, is widely seen as a
front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination. He and
Giuliani met at City Hall last year, and talked about national
politics. Bush has invited Giuliani to spend the night at his
governor's mansion on Feb. 11, when the mayor is scheduled to be in
Texas delivering a speech.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's camp believes having Giuliani on the ticket would
help Bush win New York. But statewide polls indicate that, while
many like him as mayor, few New Yorkers want to see Giuliani in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of Pataki. A survey released last week by the
Quinnipiac College Polling Institute showed 18 percent of New
Yorkers would be more likely to vote for a Republican presidential
candidate if Pataki were the running mate _ but 25 percent would be
less likely.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters think Giuliani would have an easier shot at the Senate
seat, unless Hillary Clinton runs. The Quinnipiac poll suggests
Hillary Clinton would beat him, 51-42.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has given no sign that she might _ or might not _
run. State Democratic chairwoman Judith Hope, who had previously
discounted the idea, said Wednesday she now sees a ``50-50'' chance
of her running after all. Hope spent time with Mrs. Clinton at a
fund-raiser here Tuesday night, though she declined to say whether
the two talked about the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Bush, whose actions might also shape Giuliani's and
Pataki's fate, has not yet declared his intentions, either. So the
two New Yorkers sit and wait for the horizon to clear, and their
jockeying for position intensifies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
