<HEADER>
A6180 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINCOLNS-ADVERSITIES-     02-08 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLNS-ADVERSITIES-(PRESIDENTS-DAY)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABE LINCOLN: MAKING THE MOST OF THE LEAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased. For purchase
information and to obtain photos, when available, contact New York
Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 By HAL MALEHORN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    In the century and more since his death, Americans have come to
regard Abraham Lincoln arguably as our most beloved political
figure, and inarguably as one of our most effective presidents.
 &HT;    From the thousands of Lincoln books and articles penned by
scholars over the years one unifying theme has emerged: He made the
most of the least, and he turned the worst into his best. Indeed, a
lesser man would not have been so patient in the face of adversity,
nor so persistent in pursuing his goals.
 &HT;    There were dozens of circumstances that could have turned him
aside from his purposes, and thus cost him the admiration and
respect that he subsequently earned. Consider these:
 &HT;    He was born to poor parents who could neither read nor write. He
got his schooling a little at a time, which amounted to less than a
year of formal instruction all added up.
 &HT;    His younger brother died as an infant, his older sister died in
childbirth and his mother, Nancy Hanks, died when he was but 9.
 &HT;    The lad was raised by a stepmother who could scarcely scratch
out her own name. For a spell he and up to a dozen of his kin lived
together, crowded into a small, primitive cabin.
 &HT;    As he grew into manhood Abraham was never much to behold. He had
a spare frame and angular face. His hair was thick and coarse, and
it would hardly stay put. His nose was large and his ears stuck
out. His adult voice was thin and high-pitched, and it grated on
listeners' ears. At every age he towered over all.
 &HT;    As a boy and man, Lincoln survived several of life's perils. As
a child he nearly drowned in Knob Creek; as a teen he lay
unconscious a long time after being kicked in the head by a horse.
He was almost slain by brigands on his first flatboat trip to New
Orleans, and he was robbed at knifepoint in Louisville.
 &HT;    Socially, he was awkward in polite company, and his early
relationships were tentative and melancholic. Ann Rutledge, his
first close female friend, died suddenly of a fever. His initial
engagement to Mary Todd was canceled by mutual consent. He shortly
after proposed to Mary Owens, but she turned him down.
 &HT;    Lincoln's business ventures were similarly unspectacular. He
bought a New Salem store, and then a second enterprise, but both
went bust. It took him 20 years to pay off all he owed; he ruefully
called that obligation ``the national debt.''
 &HT;    Although he eventually earned a more than adequate cash income,
he never owned much real estate. From time to time he helped out
his folks in Coles County, Illinois, but his lazy stepbrother
frittered away most of the funds Lincoln sent.
 &HT;    Lincoln eventually married Mary Todd, who turned out to be much
more than a handful. She was jealous and resentful of other women,
she was rude to Lincoln's colleagues and she had a tart tongue for
tradespeople. Mary squandered much of her husband's modest earnings
on extravagant furnishings and clothing.
 &HT;    By his own admission, Lincoln was not much of a disciplinarian
to his four growing sons. Mary ran the household, and the offspring
pretty much ran themselves. Sadly, two of the children died young,
sending Mary into unending grief.
 &HT;    Lincoln's political career took many disappointing turns among
its few key successes. He was defeated for the Illinois Assembly
his very first try, defeated twice for speaker of that house later
on, defeated for presidential elector, defeated for Congress and
defeated in a vice presidential bid.
 &HT;    And, because in 1858 U.S. senators were chosen by the various
state legislatures, Lincoln lost that year's Senate race to Stephen
A. Douglas, even though Lincoln had polled more popular votes.
 &HT;    Finally elected to the White House by only a plurality among
four strong national candidates, Lincoln presided during this
country's most perilous and tragic period. He became one of the
most reviled figures in American history at the time, among both
his own and the opposing political parties.
 &HT;    During the four-year Civil War that began six weeks after he
took office, he was frequently at odds with his own cabinet. And
his generals on the battlefield were all too often either
incompetent or reluctant to fight the enemy.
 &HT;    Seven members of Mary Todd's own Kentucky clan fought for the
Confederacy. Mary herself during the war was investigated by a
congressional committee for possible treasonable activities.
Lincoln had to personally assure the members of Congress of her
abiding loyalty to the Union.
 &HT;    By the day Lincoln was assassinated he had received dozens of
death threats. Sadly, the Union he had helped preserve could not
protect its chief.
 &HT;    Many years after Lincoln had died, poet Rosemary Benet mused,
``If Nancy Hanks came back as a ghost/Seeking news of what she
loved most/She'd ask first, ``Where's my son?/What happened to Abe?
What's he done?''
 &HT;    Americans past and present could proudly answer that inquiring
ghost by slightly paraphrasing the rest of that poem: ``Yes, Nancy
Hanks, we knew your son/He did grow tall, he did have fun./He
learned to read. He got to town. We knew his name./In spite of it
all, he did get on.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Hal Malehorn  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Hal Malehorn, a resident of Charleston, Ill., is a retired
teacher and professor with a lifelong interest in history.) &LR; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased. For purchase
information and to obtain photos, when available, contact New York
Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 1336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
