<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6181 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNFRIENDLY-SKIES-HNS &LR;      02-08 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNFRIENDLY-SKIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES FACE RISING FRUSTRATIONS FROM PASSENGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Trapped on the tarmac. Dazed by delays. Slapped
silly with surcharges. Constrained by carry-on rules. Starved for
snacks, even in first-class. Flummoxed by fare increases.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the travails of airline passengers. A potent mix of
problems has emerged to frustrate fliers both well-known, like San
Francisco Mayor Willie Brown _ who vented recently at United
Airlines for delays and carry-on luggage rules at San Francisco
International Airport _ and unknown, like the millions crammed into
Lilliputian coach seats. This is the winter of our discontent.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines are frustrated, too. Although most are awash with
profits, the money, airline officials say, is earmarked for new
aircraft, high-tech landing gear, sleek airport lounges and roomier
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Executives say the public doesn't understand how hard they are
working to make the pain go away, and are overlooking the
industry's consumer-friendly innovations of recent years such as
expansive frequent-flier programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're handling lots of people, buying lots of planes. It's all
leading to something. There's an eventual benefit to the
consumer,'' said Jack Evans, the manager of corporate
communications for Alaska Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there's turbulence ahead for the major U.S.
carriers, which boarded 615 million passengers on packed planes
last year. Vexing consumers the most are rising fares, flight
delays, vanishing food and carry-on policies.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 28, the major U.S. airlines _ including United,
American, Delta, U.S. Airways, Continental, TWA, Alaska, America
West, Southwest and Northwest _ raised fares 4 percent in domestic
economy and 2 percent for domestic business class.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has tried more than a dozen times to raise prices
since the fall of 1997, the last successful fare increase, but was
always thwarted by Northwest, which wouldn't support it. This time,
Northwest _ recovering from a strike by pilots _ went along.
</P>
<P>
   According to analysts such as Atlanta-based author Christopher
McGinniss, the airlines are raising fares because demand is high.
</P>
<P>
   McGinniss, author of ``The Unofficial Business Traveler's Pocket
Guide,'' observes that the airlines can have their way right now
because ``The planes are so full, and there's no competition except
on a few routes.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinniss said the hub system that allows a single major airline
to dominate a given airport has helped weaken competition.
</P>
<P>
   According to American Express consultant Bob Harrell, business
fares, which produce 45 percent of airline revenue, ``are at
historic high levels since we began tracking them in 1992.''
Harrell said business-class fares had risen 44 percent since early
1996, driven by airline confidence that the consumer will pay and
robust business.
</P>
<P>
   David Fuscus, a spokesman for the Air Transport Association, the
major lobbying arm of the major airlines, counters that leisure and
business fares have declined an average of 36 percent since the
industry was deregulated in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, airline profits were $5.1 billion in 1998, off just
slightly from a record $5.2 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines say that these prosperous times follow the lean early
'90s, when high fuel costs, a recessionary economy and the Persian
Gulf War instilled a fear of flying, especially among leisure
travelers. Some airlines lost hundreds of millions of dollars; this
is an attempt to recoup those losses and build stability.
</P>
<P>
   Recent weather-related delays at such busy airports as San
Francisco International and Detroit have created a backlash.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 2-3, a powerful winter storm brought airport operations
to a deal halt in Detroit. Some Northwest passengers were stranded
in planes on the tarmac for up to 8 hours in a snowstorm without
adequate food, water or working toilets, according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather knocked us out, along with the rest of the
community, and severely affected the airport,'' said Northwest
spokesman Jon Austin. To make amends, Austin said Northwest ``sent
personal letters of apology and coupons for a free trip'' to
affected travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit incident mobilized organizations such as the
American Society of Travel Agents, which has proposed a ``bill of
rights'' for passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, airlines such as United have declared war on
oversized carry-on bags, especially of the wildly popular wheeled
variety. Airline officials say they jam overhead bins, slow
boarding and deplaning and fray tempers as gate agents increasingly
demand that bags be checked.
</P>
<P>
   Because there is no size standard for the 10 major U.S.
airlines, fuming fliers find that a bag that is perfectly
acceptable to one airline has to be lugged back to the ticket
counter and checked in at the behest of another.
</P>
<P>
   To ease the confusion, the Association of Flight Attendants,
which represents 43,000 of the nation's 110,000 attendants, asked
the Federal Aviation Administration in December to impose a uniform
standard. Union spokeswoman Cynthia Kain said the AFA supports
restrictions because full overhead bins can cause injuries and
delays.
</P>
<P>
   Kain acknowledged that an AFA plea to the airlines to
voluntarily come up with a standard just hasn't flown. Indeed, some
airlines _ notably Continental _ are honing a competitive edge by
being more permissive than rivals. Of Continental, she said: ``We
call it the carry-it-all-on airline.''
</P>
<P>
   Continental's director of public relations, David Messing, said
more-relaxed rules are more people-friendly, adding that
Continental is enlarging overhead bins and ``taking a lot of new
aircraft deliveries with larger bins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a flight with a light load factor, not an eyebrow will
be raised'' at big, bulging carry-ons, Messing said. If the plane
is full, the policy tightens up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another gripe is the quality of airline food. While celebrity
chefs fuss over meals for first-class passengers, others forage for
nuts and soda in the cheap seats. Now, on some Delta flights, even
high-paying first-class passengers have to tighten their belts.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has downgraded full meals to snacks in first-class on 80
short flights and snacks to beverages on another 160 flights. The
cutbacks, Delta spokeswoman Katie Moussouri said, will save $14
million a year. Delta reported profits of $1 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Such stress points have resonated with consumers, travel
industry organizations and politicians, who are proposing a wide
range of actions. Proposed remedies include voluntary endorsement
by the airlines of a bill of rights, more federal regulatory
oversight and court-ordered airline policy changes.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Travel Agents has asked Secretary of
Transportation Rodney Slater to call a national conference to
``restore public confidence in the air transportation system'' and
``examine deteriorating levels of customer service.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization _ which claims 26,500 members _ is already at
war with the airlines, charging that global alliances that allow
carriers to code-share, link frequent flier programs and share
airport lounges may violate antitrust laws. As it is, the
Department of Justice is suing to challenge Northwest's $465
million acquisition of a stake in Continental.
</P>
<P>
   If that wasn't enough, last week two U.S. senators announced
plans to introduce legislation for more oversight of the airline
industry, which was deregulated in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation by Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., and Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., would give passengers 48 hours to cancel nonrefundable
tickets. The bill also would require airlines to explain why
flights are delayed and tell frequent fliers how many seats are
available if they want to cash in their miles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
