<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW DO DE-ICING COMPOUNDS WORK? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How does de-icer on planes work?
</P>
<P>
   D.M., Dedham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Tony McClary, manager of safety and training for Hudson
General, a major de-icing contractor at Logan International
Airport, has de-iced thousands of planes, and says with no small
amount of pride that it's a complicated procedure that involves a
lot more than squirting hot water on a plane so its surfaces will
be smooth and perform the way they're supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he says, de-icing is only one step. Step two is
anti-icing, to keep the frozen stuff from building back up as the
plane sits in the snow/sleet/freezing rain, waiting to take off.
Both steps use fluids that contain glycols, chemicals that have a
lower freezing point than water.
</P>
<P>
   De-icers use either ethylene glycol or propylene glycol in a
50-50 mix with water, heated to 180 degrees Fahrenheit and sprayed
onto the plane. The heat and powerful spray do some of the de-icing
work. But the key are those glycols, which lower the freezing point
of moisture on the plane's surface to as low as 60 degrees below
zero.
</P>
<P>
   After spraying the de-icing fluid on the plane, the ``holdover
time'' during which the plane stays clean is only 6 to 15 minutes,
depending on weather conditions. So sometimes they do a second
step, called anti-icing, in which they spray the plane with a mix
of glycol and non-Newtonian fluids. That's just a fancy name for
fluids too thick to run by themselves, like ketchup or honey.
</P>
<P>
   The thicker fluid stays on the plane longer and lets the glycols
keep things from refreezing while the plane is waiting. Holdover
time after a step two anti-ice treatment is as much as an hour and
twenty minutes, depending on the specific fluid used and the
weather conditions. Usually they only spray the thicker stuff on
the critical control surfaces of the plane, the wings, and the
tail.
</P>
<P>
   Non-Newtonian fluids designed for anti-icing are not really like
ketchup or honey. ``They have the unique ability to change
viscosity when confronted with aerodynamic forces acting on the
fluid,'' McClary says. That's a fancy way of saying that when the
plane speeds up as it takes off, the force of the wind on the fluid
makes it get thinner, making it more like water than honey, and it
drips right off the plane. By the time the plane exceeds 156 miles
per hour, the fluid is gone, the plane's surface is clean, and
takeoff (at 180 miles per hour for your average jetliner) is safe.
</P>
<P>
   Step One fluids are pinkish. The Step Two fluids are greenish.
Both consume oxygen when they get into aquatic ecosystems. Both
biodegrade quickly. In five days they're 70 percent gone. After 20
days they're 96 percent broken down.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why is water in the gas tank a problem particularly in
winter, and how does adding moisture (dry gas) to two liquids (gas
and water) remove moisture from the tank?
</P>
<P>
   M.P., Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. David Williams, a chemist with the Coastal Unilube Company,
says you've usually got water in your gas tank and your gas lines.
Small amounts aren't a problem most of the time. But in the winter,
water can condense and freeze up in your gas line. Then you've got
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The water comes from humidity condensing into liquid, either in
your car's fuel system or in the underground tanks at the gas
station.
</P>
<P>
   Water is heavier than gasoline and normally settles to the
bottom of the filling station's underground tanks. But when the
tanks are refilled, the water is stirred up. The more recently your
filling station has been resupplied, the more water you'll be
getting in the gas you buy.
</P>
<P>
   Once it's in your car, water settles to the bottom of your gas
tank, too, but driving around mixes everything up. Small amounts
vaporize out into the fuel lines, and in the winter that condensate
can freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Now, how does a liquid added to two liquids remove a liquid? It
doesn't. Williams says so-called dry gas-type products are
alcohols, usually isopropyl alcohol or methanol. (The molecular
composition of isopropynol, made up of carbon, oxygen and hydrogen,
is set up in such a way that one end bonds with the carbon and
hydrogen in gasoline, and the other end bonds with the hydrogen and
oxygen in water. You end up with one long chain. . .the gasoline on
one end, the water on the other, and the alcohol in the middle
holding them together. The methanol doesn't bond with the water,
but it reduces its surface tension so it stays suspended in the
gasoline, kind of like little globs of oil in vinegar after you
shake up salad dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the fuel pump draws gasoline to the engine, it draws
the water along with it, where everything gets burned up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 1337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6184 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-UNIVERSE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     02-08 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-UNIVERSE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 ANAHEIM, Calif.: ... such things.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sir Martin Rees, professor at Cambridge University and author of
``Before the Beginning,'' explained that ``if there were many
universes, each triggered by a separate `big bang' or `genesis
event,' then we would naturally find ourselves in one of the
special subset that permitted complex evolution. There would be
nothing coincidental or providential about the apparent `fine
tuning' on which life depends.''
</P>
<P>
   The case for that explanation may become clear as data flows in
from new satellites designed to study the traces of the earliest
remnants of the newborn universe, and from atom-smashers probing
the properties of matter under conditions that have not existed
since the instants after the universe's birth.
</P>
<P>
   Just with the information already available, the picture keeps
getting more exotic. In the early decades of this century, the
debate was whether the universe was eternal and unchanging (the
Steady State theory) or was all created at a specific momentin a
huge cosmic fireball. This view came to be known by a label coined
by its critics to ridicule the idea: the Big Bang.
</P>
<P>
   When, in the early 1960s, a kind of cosmic radio static was
discovered radiating from all directions in the sky _ considered a
relic of the heat of that cosmic explosion _ that seemed to seal
the case in favor of the Big Bang. Additional evidence since then
has only strengthened that view _ although a handful of scientists
continue to hold out for the steady state.
</P>
<P>
   There are some problems in the prevailing view, though. The
standard Big Bang cannot explain why the bang wasn't completely
smooth and uniform in all directions. If it had been, all of the
particles of matter would simply have continued to hurl apart, and
even whole atoms _ not to mention larger objects like stars and
planets _ could never have formed. How to resolve the paradox?
</P>
<P>
   That led to the idea of cosmic inflation, which several
scientists, including Alan Guth of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, began to develop in the 1970s and early 1980s. This
idea held that instead of a steady expansion, the universe went
through a sudden, much-faster explosive period just after its
birth, and it seemed to solve the problem, and became the most
widely-accepted cosmological theory.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, however, there were some problems. For one
thing, nobody could explain why this ``inflationary'' period of
rapid growth stopped, leaving the steady expansion of the universe
astronomers observe today. In addition, the theory predicted a
universe much ``lumpier'' than it really is.
</P>
<P>
   Linde's version, by contrast, includes ``eternal inflation,''
which gets around the problem of the abrupt end of inflation
predicted by Guth's theory. In Linde's scenario, instead of an
abrupt end, the inflation just gradually slowed down. And his
theory predicts exactly the amount of lumpiness _ the variations in
the cosmic background radiation that echoes the state of the
universe soon after the Big Bang _ observed by satellites.
</P>
<P>
   These observations don't prove the theory is right, Linde says,
but no other theory at present can account for the observations
made by satellites such as the Cosmic Background Explorer, or COBE.
Its observations could easily have disproved all versions of
inflationary theory; the fact that they didn't is an encouraging
sign that the theory may be on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the findings reported last year that seem to show
that the universe will continue to expand forever _ that the
universe is ``open'' _ cannot be explained by any cosmology other
than some versions of this inflationary theory.
</P>
<P>
   The scale of that initial burst of inflation is almost
impossible to grasp. According to Linde's calculations, in a period
of time that was literally shorter than the blink of an eye, a
microscopic speck of space itself expanded to become larger than
the visible universe.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the part of the universe that we inhabit has settled down
to a steady expansion in which galaxies, stars, planets and people
can exist. But somewhere out there in space, at this moment, the
energy of a region of space may be building up again to the level
needed to spawn another Big Bang. And from that region, another
universe _ maybe similar to ours, maybe one with completely
different basic characteristics _ will burst into existence . . .
and immediately lose contact forever with our universe.
</P>
<P>
   But through one of the trickier implications of relativistic
space, even though the new universe expands exponentially to
tremendous size, it continues to occupy only a tiny point in space
from our perspective _ and therefore can pose no danger to its
``parent'' universe. It's a bit like the time machine in the old
``Dr. Who'' television series, which was tiny outside but huge on
the inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this way,'' Linde says, ``the universe reproduces itself.''
One question this theory does not answer, however, is whether there
was one original Big Bang, with nothing before it, or whether the
process has been going on forever. Either is possible, according to
this view.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it is impossible to detect or communicate with the
new baby universes that arise, Linde says, their existence may give
some comfort for those who worry about the really, really long view
of things: ``Our part of the universe has been created, but other
parts of the universe are still being created. If life in our part
of the universe were to disappear, then it will appear again
someplace else. So the universe as a whole becomes immortal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 1339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6186 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-ATLANTA-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     02-08 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATLANTA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (a and s coding)  
 ATLANTA: ...any rules.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We did it the Canadian way and they did it the American way,''
said Paul Henderson, who headed the Toronto committee. ``They set
the standard. But I can't nail Atlanta. They put on a full-court
press and they won. Our position is that we shot ourselves in the
foot. To point fingers or blame something that happened on somebody
else is not our style.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahmoud El Farnawani, an Ontario businessman who was a paid
consultant and lobbyist for cities bidding for the last four
Olympics awarded, told the Toronto Star in 1998 that Atlanta used a
``special way'' to land the 1996 Games. ``This cannot be told
because it would be very damaging,'' El Farnawani said, ``but
everyone around the world knew what was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   El Farnawani, who was paid $160,000 by the Salt Lake committee
to influence IOC members from northern Africa, would not comment on
the Atlanta bid last week, saying the ongoing IOC scandal had left
him ``physically and emotionally drained.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever he heard or saw, it's all innuendo, etc.,'' said
David Goodman, El Farnawani's attorney. ``And I don't think it's in
his interest to comment about it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Young's `African strategy' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the avalanche of souvenirs, free travel, hotel stays and
five-star meals, there were the unique efforts of Young, the former
UN ambassador and civil rights leader who was Atlanta's mayor from
1981-89. Young developed what might be called an ``African
strategy,'' parlaying his longstanding personal ties there into
votes for his city.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with each African and Caribbean IOC member, roughly
20 in all at the time, Young stressed that two-thirds of Atlanta
residents were black, making it the only ``African'' city bidding
for the Games that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics has been transformed from a $700 million deficit
event in 1976 to a $5 billion asset in 1996. I think some poor
Africans ought to have some influence in the way that money is
spent,'' said Young, who is now chairman of Good Works
International, which seeks to create business links between
developed and under-developed countries.
</P>
<P>
   One month before the September 1990 vote, Young went to visit
Jean-Claude Ganga of The Republic of Congo _ one of the IOC members
now facing expulsion over the Salt Lake scandal _ bearing gifts of
soccer balls, basketballs, and athletic clothing. Ganga, among the
most influential African IOC members, switched his support from
Toronto to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Young also organized a training camp for African athletes _ just
as he had done before the 1984 Summer Games in Los Angeles _ at
LaGrange College about an hour southwest of downtown Atlanta. The
camp opened in 1991, after Atlanta had been awarded the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our generosity was an attempt to counteract the perception
that the Americans were only interested in the Olympics because it
was big money,'' Young said. ``Everybody who is bidding ought to be
called on to help countries that are less fortunate, and that's
what the Olympic movement stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, an Australian Olympic official has accused
Young of directing US government aid to African nations during the
1996 bid process, but the official, John Coates, has offered no
evidence and named no countries. Young denied the allegation, but
said he would have supported such aid.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's winning bid also gave rise to lingering questions
about the role played by corporate sponsors, including Delta
Airlines, NationsBank, Bell South, Georgia Power, and Home Depot,
among others. Some provided in-kind contributions, such as Delta
airline seats, that Atlanta Olympic officials said were not
included in their $7.8 million spending total.
</P>
<P>
   But the most attention has focused on the role played by
Atlanta-based Coca-Cola, one of the Olympics' oldest and biggest
sponsors, in the surprise defeat of Athens, the sentimental
favorite to host the centennial Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta was considered a long shot because the Summer Games had
been held on United States soil just 12 years earlier, because it
was a first-time bidder, and because Atlanta was associated in the
minds of some IOC members with Ted Turner, the mogul who launched
the Goodwill Games as a competitor to the Olympics, and Jimmy
Carter, who as president ordered the US boycott of the 1980 Summer
Games in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's local bottler contributed about $300,000 to
Atlanta's bid effort _ in addition to $250 million spent by the
corporation during 1996 on Olympic-related promotions, including
the torch relay. But the parent corporation has a strict policy
against favoring one city over another in Olympic bidding, and
local Coca-Cola bottlers contributed to at least three other cities
that sought the 1996 Games, said Ben Deutsch, spokesman for
worldwide sports at Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsch said that although Coca-Cola was proud to have the
Olympics in its hometown, the company gained little from its
presence. ``The real opportunity for us as a business is in the 134
other countries where we did marketing promotions in 1996 in terms
of the Olympics,'' Deutsch said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Olympics still a presence &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two-and-a-half years after the closing ceremonies of the 1996
Olympics, the Games are still an ever-present memory here. Visitors
are greeted at the airport with a sign welcoming them to Atlanta,
``Home of the Centennial 1996 Olympics.'' Five-ring Olympic flags
still fly, and every day at noon, Centennial Olympic Park downtown
_ scene of the bombing that cast a shadow on the Games _ comes
alive with dancing fountains and blaring music, from the Olympic
theme to Neil Diamond singing ``Coming to America.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the controversy swirling from Salt Lake to IOC
headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland, some local memories have
become tarnished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Atlanta did a great job getting the Olympics, and they
leveraged it into great benefits for me as an Atlanta resident in
terms of the infrastructure and the venues left behind,'' said
architect Eric Brock, spending his lunch hour at the park last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm completely jaded in terms of the whole Olympic
organization,'' he added, ``how it operates, how votes get sold,
all of that, and it's embarrassing to think Atlanta had to play by
those rules to get it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
