<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6189 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PENGUIN-NURSE-ART-BOS     02-08 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENGUIN-NURSE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S ALL THAT MATTERS AT TUXEDO JUNCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IRENE SEGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Heather Urquhart's mornings start early, with the 7
a.m. feeding of a baby penguin who consumes as much pureed herring
and shrimp daily as, say, a 150-pound man would if he ate 90 pounds
of food. Urquhart is senior aquarist at the New England Aquarium,
and the chick is the smallest of the 61 penguins in her charge.
</P>
<P>
   Usually little DY2xPE/98-17/3B _ hatched Jan. 14, gender and
name as yet undetermined _ would be cared for by his (or her)
parents in the aquarium's ground-floor penguin area, where the baby
would be kept warm in the nest and fed regurgitated fish from mom
and dad's own beaks. But the exhibit is under renovation, and all
the other penguins are crowded into temporary quarters.
</P>
<P>
   So Urquhart is hand-raising the African penguin chick in a
heated tank in her office. It's one way her job's changed since
construction of an expanded penguin area began a month ago. With
the exhibit's expected reopening next Saturday, the colony of 40
African penguins (DY2xPE, No. 41, will still be in its tank) and 14
rockhoppers will be joined by six little blue penguins from
Australia, the smallest of the world's 17 penguin species.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Urquhart, 35, was a girl growing up in Bellingham,
watching Jacques Cousteau on television and snorkeling in Cape
Cod's Waquoit Bay, she dreamed of a career tending marine animals.
She volunteered with the aquarium's penguins when she was a student
at Salem (Mass.) State College, and was hired in 1988 to dive in
the giant ocean tank as well as work with the tuxedoed birds.
Gradually managing the growing penguin colony became her a fulltime
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being involved with an animal from the day it's born until it
grows and finds a mate and has offspring of its own is a pretty
wonderful experience,'' she says. ``These are like my surrogate
children, I guess. They're kind of like a family.''
</P>
<P>
   On this morning, DY2xPE weighs 134 grams (4.7 oz.), up from a
birth weight of 53 grams (1.9 oz.). The downy gray chick is so
small it fits in the palm of Urquhart's freshly washed hand.
</P>
<P>
   With a syringe in one hand and two fingers of the other forming
a snug ``V'' around the chick's beak to mimic the parental beak,
Urquhart squirts in 13.4 grams of warm mush. She thinks it's a jinx
to name a chick before the 40th day.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop is the holding area, which Urquhart enters after
dipping the soles of her shoes in two trays of disinfectant. As she
hoses down the rubber drydock on the floor, she notices clumps of
regurgitated food in the rockhoppers' corner, which she removes.
She notes the unusual activity in the log because this bears
watching.
</P>
<P>
   Manual labor is as much part of Urquhart's job as the
stimulation of hand-raising chicks and traveling Each year she goes
to South Africa to work with penguin researchers, and she went to
Australia in 1997 to pick up the little blues and to learn to care
for them. each year to South Africa to work with penguin
researchers and going to Australia to pick up the little blues and
learn to care for them. ``People think what we do is glamorous,''
Urquhart says, ``but when you're taking care of animals, 85 percent
of it is cleaning.''
</P>
<P>
   The holding area is a cacophony of African (a.k.a. jackass)
penguins braying, rockhoppers honking, and little blues trilling.
The center is chilly, with 34 African penguins in metal cages _
``They're burrowing animals, so they're pretty comfortable,''
Urquhart says _ and the rest of the birds on the floor. The little
blues, who've been here since 1997 getting acclimated and awaiting
their own fiberglass island in the exhibit, have cat litter boxes
fashioned into makeshift burrows. The rockhoppers' corner is
furnished with steps and overturned milk and bread crates
reminiscent of the rocks on which these orange-crested penguins
like to hop.
</P>
<P>
   All the birds have names, mostly educational appellations such
as Gur-Roo-Mul, which is an aboriginal word for penguin, or Beach
Donkey, which is a nickname for African penguins.
</P>
<P>
   Each penguin has an identifying band, the same color for mated
pairs, right wing for females, left for males. Penguins don't have
the external characteristics that make telling a male from a female
easy, so the aquarium determines gender via blood test when a
penguin is a few months old. But Urquhart says she can tell a
penguin's gender by its size and demeanor. ``Usually when I guess
the sex,'' she says, ``I'm 100 percent on.''
</P>
<P>
   She knows these birds so well that she doesn't look at the bands
to tell who is who. The little blue named Melbourne, she says, is
``kind of shy'' and the little blue Tasmania is ``pretty bold and
very curious.'' The African penguin named Robben, at 30-plus the
aquarium's oldest penguin, was morose when her mate, Mr. Shorty,
died in 1994, until she took up with a young male named Lambert who
was only 2.
</P>
<P>
   The little blues, who weigh only 1 1/2-2 1/2 pounds apiece, must
be happy, Urquhart says, because Tomeranaray laid two eggs, and she
and her mate, Martidekker, took turns sitting on them. Alas, both
eggs were infertile, which often happens the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Soon it's time to check on preparations for the 9 a.m. general
feeding. In the top-floor dive room, Vivian Ng, a Northeastern
co-op student, and three volunteers use crochet needles to hide
vitamins and antifungal medication into the gills of 60 thawed
smelt, one for each bird; the vitamins are necessary because
freezing robs fish of nutrients, and the medicine because the
stress of moving could make penguins susceptible to molds and
spores.
</P>
<P>
   At 9, it's down to the holding area for the first of three
meticulously orchestrated daily feedings. In pairs, one person
offers fish while another keeps count of how much each bird eats..
Yet another person rotates the fed birds through the area's three
pools so each will get a daily 15-minute swim, which is extra work
because when the exhibit is open, the penguins swim whenever they
want.
</P>
<P>
   When Mercury balks at eating, Urquhart cuddles him in her lap.
``There's more distraction here,'' she says, ``so they need a
little more prodding.''
</P>
<P>
   It is 10 a.m., time for Urquhart to dash upstairs for DY2xPE's
next feeding. The chick eats 10 percent of its body weight six
times a day. Urquhart gently lifts the baby and settles it on the
scale. Weight gain in three hours? Five grams.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's back to the holding area where volunteers and staffers
are scrubbing mats and scouring cages and rotating penguins through
the pools before the 1 o'clock feeding, as the cycle continues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
