<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !!! &LR;  ``Children of Heaven'' An exquisite miniature from Iran's
Majid Majidi about children _ a brother and sister _ who cope
resourcefully with the loss of a pair of shoes the family can't
afford to replace. The film doesn't rely on cuteness (though its
young leads are more than cute); it allows the children to make
moral choices and follow through on them. (PG)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !!!! &LR;  ``The General'' John Boorman's entertaining and
startlingly audacious biofilm about a Dublin crime lord played by
Brendan Gleeson, whose hand conceals his face by reflex but who
plays to his anti-authoritarian neighborhood's love of
theatricality as he rules his patch of turf like an ancient tribal
chief. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !! &LR;  1/2 ``Payback'' Mel Gibson as a bad guy this time _ a crook
who was double-crossed and left for dead and returns with a
we'll-bury-you-before-you-bury-us attitude as he works his way up
the criminal food chain. You've never seen him take as much
punishment as he takes here, but of course he just keeps on coming
in this kinetic but pretty soulless and mechanical outing. (R)
</P>
<P>
   (FR)  &UR; !!!! &LR;  ``Rushmore'' Invigoratingly original and flat-out
delightful comedy about two unlikely buddies in love with the same
pretty schoolteacher. Jason Schwartzman is a find as an obsessive,
precocious, and overextended prep-schooler. Bill Murray gives the
performance of his career as an unhappy steel tycoon aching to
remake his life. Going deep, Murray makes us realize what a master
of weighty deadpan glances he is in Wes Anderson's endearingly
unpredictable comedy. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ! &LR;  ``Simply Irresistible'' Eminently resistible. Formulaic,
foody romantic comedy that slights both romance and comedy.
Struggling restaurateur Amanda (Sarah Michelle Gellar, of ``Buffy
the Vampire Slayer'') meets uptight yuppie restaurateur Tom (Sean
Patrick Flanery) and invisible sparks fly. Dead on arrival. (PG-13)
(Jim Sullivan)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !!! &LR;  ``The Swindle'' Claude Chabrol goes lightly Hitchcockian
in his 50th film. The mystery here is the exact nature of the
relationship between a longtime scam team played by Isabelle
Huppert and Michel Serrault. Are they husband and wife? Lovers?
Father and daughter? Or just business partners? The shifts in
dynamic are more intriguing than her scheme for a big score.
(Unrated)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
