<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-CARROLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROVING POET WANTS TO SHARE YOUR LETTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass._ Last year, Andrew Carroll was crisscrossing
the country handing out books of poetry. This year, he's asking
people to send him their family's wartime letters.
</P>
<P>
   So strongly does Carroll feel about his dual mission to make
poetry accessible and to prompt people to write letters more often
that he's handing out copies of his book ``Letters of a Nation: A
Collection of Extraordinary American Letters,'' and is looking for
new places to hand out books of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Over lunch last week, Carroll _ who is 28 and lived in Wellesley
before moving to Washington as a teenager _ talked of the
connection he sees between poetry and letters. ``They're really
alike,'' he said. ``Both of them give such great insight into the
human experience, and they offer to others so much of who and what
we are ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting together ``Letters of a Nation,'' published this month
in paperback by Broadway Books, involved working with dozens of
librarians and archivists to obtain about 200 letters that deal
with public issues and personal matters _ and many that express
personal views on public matters, such as President Clinton's
correspondence with his draft board and the essayist E. B. White's
missiveabout not paying a local dog tax. Another letter, by
Boston-bred humorist Fred Allen, is a droll treatise on the
problems of writing long letters.
</P>
<P>
   The many wartime letters in the collection, such as Civil War
General William Tecumseh Sherman's letter to the mayor of Atlanta
explaining why he had ordered the burning of the city, and a letter
from a World War I infantryman ``to be opened if I am killed,'' so
affected Carroll that last fall he began the Legacy Project,
seeking other wartime writings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought people would be possessive about those wartime
letters,'' Carroll said, but he has received hundreds, ``so many of
them the last ones that were received'' before the embattled writer
_ son, husband, brother _ was killed in action.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's goal in soliciting these letters is ``first, just to
get people to look for them because every day they're being
destroyed in fires'' _ as happened with his own family's letters _
or are just being thrown out. Beyond that, Carroll wants to get as
many as possible donated to museums and archives for use by
scholars and researchers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Legacy Project, Carroll also heads up the
American Poetry and Literacy Project, a nonprofit organization that
he founded with the late Nobel laureate Joseph Brodsky.
</P>
<P>
   The poetry project is best known for distributing hundreds of
thousands of books of poetry. This year, it will give a collection
of poems dealing with adventure and travel to Peace Corps workers
and others.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll says he has been touched deeply himself by his
experiences as a poetry-nurturer and letter-collector. Giving away
copies of a collection of love poems at the Wedding Chapel in Las
Vegas last year was ``pure fun,'' Carroll said, but then a few
weeks later he was at the Angola State Prison in Louisiana. ``I was
out in the exercise yard with them _ there was no protective shield
between us _ and these guys would come up to me and recite poems
they knew. It was a powerful experience to see them engaged in
something so passionate as poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   Next weekend _ for Valentine's Day _ sleeping-car passengers out
of Boston on Amtrak's Twilight Shoreliner will receive copies of
the ``Letters of a Nation'' collection. Along with the book,
Carroll said, the travelers will receive stationery, envelopes
stamped with the cupid ``love'' stamp, and a pen as an incentive to
write love letters.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll acknowledges that in the age of the e-mail, the
hand-written love letter may be a thing of the past. ``E-mail is a
wonderful way to flirt,'' he said, admitting that he carried on a
relationship with a former girlfrind by e-mail _ and was dumped by
her via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can present yourself as a great wit in e-mail, even if
you've slaved over the message for hours,'' Carroll said. ``But
when you're in a real relationship, it's important to write an
honest-to-goodness love letter,'' because, he said, ``the implicit
message of a letter is that you matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
