<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROTH IRA STRATEGY FOR STRUGGLING FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am presently enrolled in a 403(b) plan, and included in
this portfolio are holdings in Fidelity's Latin America and
Emerging Markets funds. Would it be a good investment strategy to
roll over these positions into a traditional IRA, and then convert
that IRA into a Roth IRA, thereby lessening the tax bite and giving
the funds time to recover?
</P>
<P>
   J.H., Worcester, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I like it. I presume your thinking is that while these two
battered funds are now fairly cheap, a true long-term investor will
be well rewarded by sticking with them. If that thinking is
correct, by switching the holding from a tax-deferred to a tax-free
status, you'll be paying taxes to Uncle based on the current
depressed value. (Three-year returns for Latin America fund show
average annual gains of only 5.26 percent, and Emerging Markets
shows a horrifying 19.80 percent average annual loss for the same
period.)
</P>
<P>
   You should, however, remember a few things. One is that you'll
have to have the cash on hand to pay the taxes on the conversion to
the Roth IRA; if you withdraw some of the funds to take care of the
tax liability, that counts as a premature withdrawal and is subject
both to taxation as income plus a 10 percent premature withdrawal
penalty (unless you're over age 59 1/2). Another thing to keep in
mind is that all of the taxliability for this move will fall in
tax-year 1999; the provision allowing taxpayers to spread the tax
liability for a traditional IRA-to-Roth IRA transfer expired at the
end of last year. Finally, you should remember that once this money
has been put into a Roth IRA, it must remain there at least five
years before withdrawal; even if you're over age 59 1/2 you'd face
a penalty if the money is withdrawn before five years have expired.
And in this arithmetic, it doesn't matter how long the money might
have been in a traditional IRA before being transferred to the
Roth; the five-year clock starts ticking upon the deposit into the
Roth account.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy can be applied more broadly by other retirement
savers. If there are segments of your retirement portfolio which
you expect to produce the best results _ either temporarily
distressed holdings such as these or other holdings for which the
long-term prospects seem particularly bright _ the Roth is the best
place for them. To draw an exaggerated example, suppose your
retirement portfolio is evenly divided between GNMA fund shares and
shares of a fund focusing on sectors such as health care or
computer technology. Over a long period, it's reasonable to assume
that the GNMA fund will plug along with average annual total
returns in the 7.5 percent to 8.5 percent; it's also reasonable to
presume that after a pretty bumpy ride, the long-term owner of the
two sector funds will see average annual total returns in double
digits. By using Roth accounts for the riskier but potentially more
rewarding holdings, the owner would be likely to achieve his or her
greater gains in the tax-free account. It seems to me that even for
those who don't go to extremes such as I outline above, the best
strategy for holders of Roth IRAs as well as tax-deferred accounts
is to have the more conservative holdings in the tax-deferred
accounts, and those with a higher risk-reward profile in the Roth.
(But also remember that a Roth is no place to speculate, because
you pay the taxes up front, and if you then lose the money _ tough
beans.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 21-year-old full-time college student, and had a son
last August. I have about $2,000 saved that I want to put in some
kind of Education IRA to build a fund that in 18 years will be near
the $100,000 mark. For the next couple of years, until I get out of
college, I will only be able to invest $50 a month. Do I have
enough money to start a fund? Where might I invest?
</P>
<P>
   J.Q., South Boston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure you have enough money, but you might want to think twice
about the educational IRA. First of all, given the $500-a-year
limitation on contributions, it's likely that an educational IRA
would only take you about a quarter way to your goal. But the more
important message is that sometimes there are more important thing
than saving money on taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The big feature of the Education IRA is that the entire amount
accumulated in an account can be withdrawn tax-free, provided the
owner or a sibling uses it for qualified postsecondary education.
In effect, Uncle Sam promises to overlook taxes on the earnings
generated by the account. Let's suppose you made the full $500
annual contributions to such an account for 18 years and the
account produced average annual returns of 8 percent. In the end,
your son would have $19,413, of which $9,000 would be your
contributions and the remaining $15,413 would represent earnings
from the account.
</P>
<P>
   But the accumulation would also represent assets owned by the
student and which would be deemed by the agencies which handle
financial aid applications to be available to meet his college
expenses. While these agencies also consider the parents' assets,
only a low percentage of parents assets _ currently 5.65 percent _
is treated as available for educational costs. For that reason,
experts on saving money for college generally suggest that saving
always be done in the parents name, even if it means a higher tax
burden during the accumulation period. The exception is for parents
who are very very wealthy and who expect very little or nothing in
the way of financial aid for their children. Moreover, the current
edition of Paying For College Without Going Broke by Kalman A.
Chany suggests it will likely prove that Education IRAs are only
appropriate for upper-income families with relatively young
children who are absolutely certain that they will not qualify for
financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   Given the fact that you're still in college and your future
financial status is likely more a matter of conjecture than
analysis, I'd err on the safe side and stay away from the
educational IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to accumulate $100,000 over an 18-year period, beginning
with two years of $50 monthly contributions, you would have to
raise the monthly savings level to $253 for the last 16 years,
again presuming 8 percent average portfolio returns. (I use that
figure, rather than the 10 percent I usually plug into retirement
portfolios, because while you might start out with an all-stock
fund, about the time of the student's ninth or tenth birthday
you'll want to begin moderating risk, until by the time the student
enters college the bulk of the money is in very conservative
holdings.) As a savings vehicle, I'd start out with a solid growth
and income fund, of which there are hundreds of examples. An easy
choice is a fund such as Vanguard Index 500, which simply seeks to
track the results of the Standard and Poor's 500 Index. This fund
has a minimum investment of $3,000, so you'd have to save a little
more before beginning. Or you could shop around among the large-cap
blend funds in the Morningstar Mutual Funds reports, seeking a fund
which might produce similar results but which has a lower minimum
initial investment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are in a quandary about the diversification of
our mutual funds. We've been investing in stocks and mutual funds
through 401(k)s and with saved-up cash for eight years now. When
reviewing our finances this year, we look at the diversification
and found that almost all of our money is in large company stocks
and funds. We are wondering if we should sell some of our holdings
and diversify to mid-cap and/or small-cap funds, and if so to what
degree. This would have a significant tax impact, as about half of
the accumulation in most of our taxable accounts represents
unrealized capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   J.F., Newton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Although you're right that your portfolio is
over-concentrated in large-cap stocks and funds with portfolios
dominated by large-caps, you don't need to worry about short-term
tax liability when you rebalance the portfolio. That's because the
breakout you supplied showed that 61 percent of the total portfolio
(excluding funds set aside for your children's education) is in
401(k) accounts and IRAs. You can make any changes you want within
those portfolios _ at least any changes you want within the
limitations of the options available through the 401(k)s _ and
there will be no tax consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is true that about 95 percent of your taxable
holdings are in large-cap stocks, I suggest you simply treat those
holdings as collectively representing your core portfolio holding.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can adjust your tax-deferred holdings so that the
overall portfolio is better diversified. My suggestion for overall
portfolio balance is 50 percent large cap, 20 percent small cap,
and 10 percent each in mid-cap, international and health care
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Since you're quite young _ both of you 34 years old _ that final
suggestion of a good health care fund (such as the Fidelity and
Vanguard offerings) should prove a big winner over the long term,
and given your youth, I might be tempted to bump that allocation up
to 15 percent, reducing the small-cap position accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   The net tax effect of all these moves? Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
