<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (Updated Sunday night, on eve of King Hussein's funeral)  
  
 EDITORS: IN LIGHT OF THE DEATH OF JORDAN'S KING HUSSEIN, WE OFFER
YOU THE FOLLOWING EXCELLENT ARTICLES FROM THE INDEPENDENT OF
LONDON. AT TIMES POIGNANT, AT TIMES PROVOCATIVE, THESE ARTICLES
SHOULD BE ``MUST-READS'' FOR YOUR COMMENTARY PAGES.)  
  
 (These TIMELY compelling ``separate buy'' articles are from the
Independent of London, distributed by the New York Times
Syndicate.)  
  
 (To publish any of these articles, they must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; `HE WAS A GOODLY KING...WE SHALL NOT LOOK UPON HIS LIKE
AGAIN' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY!...ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Fisk &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To the end, he was a king.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein ibn Talal had spoken of his own mortality many times,
and his last journey Friday _ six thousand miles from an American
deathbed to the land he ruled for 46 years _ became him. Soldiers
prefer to die at home.
</P>
<P>
   He was an honorable man. He believed that if he trusted enough
in another person, his good faith would be returned; he was cruelly
rewarded...
</P>
<P>
   What king would ever turn up at his own state security jail to
drive his most vociferous political prisoner home?
</P>
<P>
   Leith Shubailath had infuriated the monarch _ he was a man
easily riled _ and was imprisoned for asking why the queen wept at
Yitzhak Rabin's funeral. When the king arrived at the prison,
Shubeilath delayed him ten minutes while he said goodbye to his
fellow inmates. Hussein waited patiently for him.
</P>
<P>
   Would Saddam (who prefers to string his prisoners up) have done
that? Would King Fahd? Would President Mubarak? Would Benjamin
Netanyahu?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is this which distinguished the king: among the
monsters of the Middle East, he appeared such a reasonable man.
</P>
<P>
   He was, in a very real sense, the region's political Bomb
Disposal Officer, the one man who could be relied on to calm
nerves, order bystanders to open their windows and then gently,
firmly, withdraw the detonator of war.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Arabs and Israelis fear for the future. What are they
going to do now that there is no one to defuse the bombs? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,000 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-A-KING-TO-THE-END-HUSSEIN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LEGACY OF KING HUSSEIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Fisk &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMMAN _ Through the fog, you could hear the voices from half a
mile away.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our blood, with our soul, we sacrifice ourselves to
you!'' And as the mist swept around me _ such wind, such very thick
fog _ I could see tiny squares above the thousands of shrouded
figures outside Al-Hussein Medical Center in Amman: posters
portraying the dead king who lay only a few hundred feet from us.
</P>
<P>
   You only had to watch the uncontrollable grieving of these
people to understand how heavy will be the burden for Jordan's new
king, Abdullah... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE OFFERS A
350-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 625; TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS 1,075
WORDS.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-LEGACY-KING-HUSSEIN-625&AMP;ADD-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A PALL OVER AMMAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Patrick Cockburn &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMMAN _ Signs of outward grief are everywhere in the Jordanian
capital. Outside the Al-Hussein Medical Center where King Hussein
had just died women braved the driving rain to sob; some fell
fainting to the ground as they waited for the king's body to leave
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Even more moving than the tears, though, was the way in which
Jordanians, who are not used to cold, groped their way forward in
the white banks of mist to express sorrow for their beloved king.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Amman, people looked worried more than
grief-striken. King Hussein had always protected them from the dark
forces around Jordan; what will happen to their tiny, vulnerable
kingdom now that he is gone? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-TEARS-'N'-FEARS-JORDAN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PROFOUND GRIEF OVERWHELMS JORDANIANS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Patrick Cockburn &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMMAN _ As news of the death of King Hussein spread through
Amman, the Jordanian capital, just before noon Sunday thousands of
Jordanians, many carrying black flags of mourning, drove in cars
and trucks through the driving rain and thick, ominous mist to
tearfully wait for his body to be removed from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Shopkeepers pulled down the metal shutters of their shops,
closing up as a sign of respect for the beloved king _ and father
figure _ who had ruled Jordan for a staggering 46 years.
</P>
<P>
   In Jordan King Hussein was a benevolent autocrat, ultimately
controlling everything but avoiding extreme repression. As one
member of the opposition said: ``You could try to overthrow him but
he would still forgive you in the end.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DO NOT SQUANDER KING HUSSEIN'S LEGACY OF PEACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By The Editorial Board of The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the West pays its respects to the memory of King Hussein of
Jordan, it should pause to acknowledge a conundrum.
</P>
<P>
   The King has been a good leader, of his own people and of wider
Arab interests in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   It is to be hoped that the rather Shakespearian deathbed
maneuvers, dashing at the 11th hour his brother's 34-year
expectation of inheriting the crown in favor of his eldest son,
Abdullah, will come to good... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-COMMENTARY-KINGHUSSEIN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAN JORDAN HOLD TOGETHER WITHOUT KING HUSSEIN? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY!...ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Patrick Cockburn &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMMAN _ It was always a balancing act. Jordan is a buffer state
between more powerful countries, notably Israel and Iraq. King
Hussein's political career was spent playing off his enemies
against each other.
</P>
<P>
   He played both ends against the middle because he believed
(correctly) that Jordan's weakness _ 4.4 million people and no
natural resources or defenses _ left him no choice.
</P>
<P>
   His death, comes at a bad moment for Jordan. His neighbors _
indeed, the world _ awaits to see if the house King Hussein built
will hold together. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-CAN-JORDAN-SURVIVE?-UPDATED-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY JORDAN'S SUCCESSION PLAN MEETS UNIVERSAL APPROVAL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Fisk &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ From across the Middle East, there has come an
intriguing _ not to say astonishing _ chorus of approval for Crown
Prince Abdullah of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The ulterior motives behind all the praise are even more
intriguing... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-WHY-ABDULLAH-APPLAUSE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KING'S FUNERAL UNITES FRIENDS AND FOES: A GUEST LIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Kathy Marks &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In death, he has accomplished what he worked so tirelessly to
achieve throughout his life: forging links around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   King Hussein's funeral in Amman Monday will bring together sworn
political enemies such as U.S. President Bill Clinton, senior Iraqi
politicians, Israeli prime ministers past and present, and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat _ a fitting testimony to the
indefatigable peacemaker. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (350 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-AMMAN-FUNERAL-WHO'S-WHO-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMMAN PALACE INTRIGUE BEGAN 43 YEARS AGO _ JUST ASK GLUBB
PASHA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY!...RESLUGGED from BC-HASHEMITE-CURSE-JORDAN) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Fisk &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When King Hussein began his initial six months of cancer
treatment at the Mayo Clinic last year, his younger brother Hassan
should have cast his mind back to the day, 43 years earlier, when
another trusted servant of the monarchy believed he was secure in
his job.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein was only 21 but had already argued brusquely with
Lieutenant General Sir John Bagot Glubb, commander of his Arab
Legion and principal military adviser to his majesty.
</P>
<P>
   Persuaded by his own confidants that Glubb Pasha should be
dismissed, and convinced that the British were trying to control
Jordan's armed forces, the king fired the 59-year old British
general. Glubb Pasha was taken to the airport the next morning in
Hussein's own car.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring this historical precedent, Crown Prince Hassan used his
regency last year to boost his own image, to project his rule in
the Jordanian press and to demand the firing of Hussein's chief of
staff.
</P>
<P>
   To the sick king in Minnesota, his brother Hassan was trying to
take over the army _ just as Glubb was trying to do in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   But Hassan could not be packed off to Amman airport. Instead,
the king came home, disgraced his brother and picked another
Sandhurst graduate as regent _ a man, ironically, of whom Glubb
Pasha would have approved _ Hussein's eldest son, Abdullah... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE OFFERS THREE
