<P>
   &UR; WHY WE PROP UP AGING ARAB-WORLD TYRANTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Provocative Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Fisk &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All across the Arab world, age and sickness haunt the lands.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's King Hussein is dead, having succumbed to his toughest
enemy, cancer. Saudi Arabia's King Fahd can barely stand, and
stumbles on the simplest sentences. Yasser Arafat suffers ever more
from the brain tumor inflicted after a near-fatal air crash.
Syria's Hafez Assad suffers from a heart condition, and has lost
his heir-apparent son, Basil, in a road accident. Egypt's Hosni
Mubarak has never appointed a vice-president, let alone a
successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Succession'': it's the Middle East's unspoken crisis. The
great unmentionable. But it is real.
</P>
<P>
   We in the West, of course, accept the Arab world's odd,
dangerous system of inheritance. Why? Because we like
dictatorships. We know how to do business with the kings and
generals _ how to sell them our arms, fighter-bombers and missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that we, as well as the Arab regimes themselves,
have produced and maintained this archaic drama of crown princes
and beloved sons, of gulf sheikhdoms that are no more than the
private property of individual families... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,100 words; 1,050 with 50-word optional trim) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVED AS BC-ARAB-SUCCESSION-FARCE-UPDATED-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
