   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-FAT (Rio de Janeiro) _ Looking for fat in government,
things to fix in an economy that threatens to spiral out of
control? Here's a guy who works 10 days a month in a government
office, gets his meals for free there, and his only task is to make
sure that the air conditioners are turned on. By Richard Chacon.
1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Washington) _ The Senate finally decides to
pull the plug. By Thomas Oliphant. (w and k coding.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-ATLANTA (Atlanta) -- Amid revelations of payoffs in Salt
Lake City, questions have turned to suspicions, and Atlanta has
found its Olympic memories under scrutiny. By Mitchell Zuckoff and
John Powers. (2 takes; a and s coding)
</P>
<P>
   GIULIANI-PATAKI (New York) _ The Empire State is a vast
territory, but it seems more and more that it isn't big enough for
Rudy Giuliani and George Pataki. By Fred Kaplan. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-GENE (Undated) _ So what happened to that research on
whether there is a gay gene? By Matthew Brelis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JACOBY-COLUMN (Undated) -- UMass is richer than ever, but the
taxpayer gets no relief. By Jeff Jacoby.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ As the impeachment trial of President
Clinton approaches its end, it appears that this episode will
continue to be far more costly to the GOP than to Clinton. By
Robert A. Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   NOLAN-COLUMN (San Francisco) -- NBC takes a lame look at the
Sixties. By Martin F. Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Eileen McNamara is writing on a local topic today; her
column will not move.).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH/SCIENCE (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-UNIVERSE (Anaheim, Calif.) _ In a mind-bending analysis of
what the cosmos is all about, Andrei Linde says new universes are
constantly being born all around us; but at the very instant they
emerge, we lose contact with them forever. By David L. Chandler. (2
takes)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-TWINS (Chicago) _ Massachusetts twins born with AIDS
and among the first treated with new triple-drug cocktails now
offer one of the most promising leads on how it might be possible
to teach the human immune system how to defeat the insidious virus.
By Richard A. Knox. 1450 words.
</P>
<P>
   HAZARD-WORRIES (Undated) _ Study of how seriously people take
various possible environmental and technological hazards _ from the
ozone hole to radon to electromagnetic fields _ finds that women
are more worried than men, and lay people more worried than
scientists. By Richard Saltus. 740 words; includes comparison text
table.
</P>
