<HEADLINE>
GENDER CALLED FACTOR IN SCIENTISTS' VIEW OF TECHNOLOGICAL PERILS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes comparison text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to the hazards of technology and environmental
perils, men and women do not always see eye to eye, not even when
they are both scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Women are a bit more likely than men to believe there is good
reason to worry about technological hazards widely publicized in
the media, like global warming, pesticides on food, and exposure to
magnetic fields, a study has found. The study included two surveys;
one questioned laypeople, the other targeted scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Previous studies have shown that women tend to be more concerned
about such hazards, but the new research is the first to reveal a
gender difference even among scientists, said the author of the
study, John D. Graham of the Harvard School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   Though the surveys did not ask for the ``why'' element of the
responses, Graham said he and his colleagues have some theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is that women may feel more vulnerable in terms of the
consequences of these hazards than do men,'' he said. ``Women may
feel more responsible for the health of the household, and take
more seriously claims for these hazards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Another is that men may have jobs that are more
technologically oriented, and they may have more of a protechnology
bias,'' said Graham, who directs the Center for Risk Analysis at
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Two reports on the study are being published in the February
issue of the journal Technology. They are based on two surveys, one
of 1,000 laypersons reached through random phone calls, and another
that questioned 260 scientists who belong to the prestigious
National Institute of Medicine and have published articles on
technological hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Only 52 of the scientists were women, which Graham acknowledged
could weaken the findings of that part of the study.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys asked respondents to rate eight technological
hazards on a 10-point scale as to how confident they were that the
threats existed. A score of 10 would mean complete confidence that
the hazards were real and a 0 would indicate complete confidence
that they did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   The hazards, chosen from two years of national print media
stories, were: global warming from carbon dioxide pollution;
particulate air pollution; electromagnetic fields from power lines;
natural radon gas in homes; medical X-rays; second-hand tobacco
smoke; depletion of the ozone layer of the atmosphere; and
pesticides on foods.
</P>
<P>
   Laypeople and scientists had similar ratings of some hazards,
such as second-hand smoke and threats to the ozone layer, but
laypeople were more troubled by pesticides on foods and
electromagnetic fields.
</P>
<P>
   For three of the eight hazard questions, women scientists were
significantly more sure than male scientists that the risks
existed: electromagnetic fields, pesticides on foods, and
second-hand smoke. Overall, the women scored the eight hazards at
6.41 on the confidence rating scale, while men put it at 5.82,
though this difference was not statistically significant.
</P>
<P>
   From the point of view of one woman scientist not involved in
the survey, the findings could be subject to dangerous
misinterpretation. ``We don't want this to be seen as women being
hysterical'' on the subject of technological risk, said Ellen
Silbergeld, professor of epidemiology and toxicology at the
University of Maryland Medical School in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   She also questioned the research methods, saying that other
factors might have been just as important as gender in respondents'
ratings _ such as socioeconomic status, employment in a
technology-oriented job, or their health status.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Silbergeld emphasized there is no ``right'' answer
about controversial hazards like those on the survey. ``We don't
want to turn over our democracy to a priesthood of people who have
PhD's,'' she said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RATING HAZARDS &QL; 
(! used as column separator; view at 80 chars/line) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Respondents rated each purported hazard on a 10-point scale as
to how confident they were that the hazard is real. A score of 10
meant they were totally confident it did exist; 0 meant they were
certain it did not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ! Lay sample ! ! Scientist sample &QL; 
Hazard ! Men ! Women ! Men ! Women &QL; 
Second-hand smoke ! 7.20 ! 8.01 ! 7.00 ! 7.98 &QL; 
Ozone depletion ! 6.40 ! 7.69 ! 6.94 ! 6.79 &QL; 
Outdoor particles ! 6.55 ! 7.40 ! 6.77 ! 7.29 &QL; 
X-rays ! 5.37 ! 6.00 ! 6.85 ! 6.17 &QL; 
Radon ! 5.63 ! 6.85 ! 5.84 ! 6.40 &QL; 
Global warming ! 5.74 ! 7.02 ! 5.73 ! 6.60 &QL; 
Food pesticides ! 6.42 ! 7.43 ! 4.24 ! 5.52 &QL; 
Magnetic fields ! 4.95 ! 6.06 ! 3.16 ! 4.54 &QL; 
All hazards ! 6.04 ! 7.05 ! 5.82 ! 6.41 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOURCE: Dr. John Graham, Center for Risk Analysis, Harvard School
of Public Health. &QL;
</P>
