<HEADLINE>
TWINS ARE PIONEERS IN AIDS RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A pair of nearly 4-year-old Massachusetts twins may
show researchers how the immune system can keep the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV) in check, just as it normally disarms
the lifelong viral infections that cause measles and cold sores.
</P>
<P>
   University of Massachusetts researchers conducting a novel,
$250,000 experiment with the twins say its success would achieve
the Holy Grail of AIDS research _ immune system control of HIV _
and point the way for adult therapy as well. The researchers, Dr.
John Sullivan and Dr. Katherine Luzuriaga of the UMass Medical
School in Worcester, described the project in an interview last
week during a conference here on HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at Therion Biologics, a Cambridge, Mass.
biotechnology firm, are at work fabricating a vaccine from pieces
of the particular HIV strain the twins acquired from their mother
before or during birth. The UMass researchers are betting heavily
that the vaccine will ``teach'' the children's immune systems to
recognize and attack the HIV that lurks somewhere in their bodies,
even though the most sensitive blood tests have been unable to
detect it for years now.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to be sure the vaccine has worked will be to
suspend the triple-drug regimen the twins have been on since
infancy to see if the virus comes out of hiding. The twins were
among the first anywhere to receive potent anti-HIV ``cocktails''
that have transformed AIDS over the past three years into a
treatable chronic disease _ at least for many in affluent nations.
</P>
<P>
   The bold Umass experiment is one of many signs that AIDS
researchers are turning their attention to immune control as the
glimmering best hope _ most likely the only hope _ of beating HIV
in the long run. It is now plain that drugs alone won't do the job.
Many if not most AIDS researchers are convinced that immune
responses specifically directed against HIV need to become ``our
other drug,'' as Dr. Stefano Vella of the Italian National
Institute of Health puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Research presented at the Sixth Conference on Retroviruses and
Opportunistic Infections, as the Chicago meeting is called,
demonstrates that:
</P>
<P>
   --Current drug regimens are not potent enough to suppress HIV
below detectable levels in 30 to 50 percent of patients.
</P>
<P>
   --Treatment eventually fails in a substantial fraction of HIV
patients who respond to drug-treatment initially (one-third in one
large three-year study) because the virus ``breaks through.''
</P>
<P>
   --HIV strains quickly emerge that are resistant to all three
classes of antiviral drugs (and will eventually to new drugs in the
pipeline, scientists expect), and resistant strains are being
transmitted from one person to another.
</P>
<P>
   --Severe metabolic side effects, such as fat deposits, high
cholesterol, and diabetes, afflict about 10 percent of long-term
users of triple-drug treatment; less-severe side effects appear in
up to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Counterbalancing these gloomy reports, however, are many new
signs that the immune system can fight HIV and win. This has set
researchers on a quest for strategies that combine drugs and immune
boosters. The drugs limit HIV's damage to the immune system and
keep the virus suppressed, while the boosters would keep immune
cells on lifelong alert for any HIV that re-emerges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we now have the evidence that the immune system works
and can be a good companion to anti-retroviral therapy,'' Vella
says. ``Even a few months ago, we didn't think the immune system
did anything in HIV disease.''
</P>
<P>
   One line of evidence comes from studies of ``long-term
non-progressors,'' the lucky few individuals who can keep the virus
in check for years without any drug treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a group, these `non-progressors' have extremely low viral
loads 15 years after being infected with HIV,'' says Dr. Thomas C.
Greenough of UMass.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are learning what sets the immune systems of these
non-progressors apart. For instance, Greenough notes, their blood
contains high levels of so-called CD8 cells in an activated state,
a sign they are on constant alert against HIV. Scientists believe
CD8 cells, one of the body's main lines of defense against viruses,
secrete a chemical factor that kills HIV, but so far the factor has
not been identified.
</P>
<P>
   Also in non-progressors, critical immune cells, called CD4 or
``helper'' cells, invariably maintain their ability to recognize
HIV proteins, reported Dr. Eric S. Rosenberg of Massachusetts
General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the vast majority of HIV patients who can't
control the virus on their own? Other new evidence shows that
HIV-damaged immune systems slowly recover with Highly Active
Anti-Retroviral Treatment, or HAART, as the multidrug therapy is
known. The proof is in studies of patients who are deliberately
taken off other medications given to prevent ``opportunistic''
infections such as cytomegalovirus (CMV), which can cause blindness
and pneumocystis, a frequent cause of fatal pneumonia among
patients in the pre-HAART era.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 47 HAART patients whose anti-CMV drugs were
stopped, ``the data indeed suggest restoration of immunity
sufficient to protect against CMV relapse in 90 percent,'' says Dr.
Brigitte Autran of the Pitie Salpetriere Hospital in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly encouraging is a Spanish study of 400 patients
randomly assigned either to stay on, or stop, drugs that prevent
pneumocystic pneumonia. There were no cases of pneumonia in either
group.
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of evidence that patients' immune systems
can be reconstituted after damage by HIV, the most intriguing new
research shows that brief holidays from HAART may be key to keeping
the virus in check. This runs counter to the prevailing dogma that
it is dangerous for HAART patients to miss a single dose of drug,
lest the virus seize the chance to develop mutations that make it
drug-resistant.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence so far is still anecdotal, but a few patients
around the world have mounted immune defenses against HIV after
stopping all multidrug therapy. The most famous case, the so-called
``Berlin patient,'' stopped HAART twice for medical reasons; he
remains healthy and without detectable HIV in his blood 25 months
after the second cessation, says Dr. Franco Lori of Project RIGHT,
an AIDS research program in Washington and Pavia, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Lori has studied three other patients who have stopped HAART for
brief periods, and in each case it took longer for HIV to reappear
in their bloodstreams _ from one week after the first holiday to as
long as eight weeks after the third interruption.
</P>
<P>
   Lori repeated the experiment with three macaque monkeys infected
with the simian version of HIV. After several treatment
interruptions, all three monkeys have undetectable blood levels of
virus after about 100 days without drug treatment. Lori plans
larger experiments with monkeys and humans this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the new evidence suggests that HAART may be too
effective. By suppressing HIV so well, the regimens apparently
deprive patients' immune systems of HIV proteins needed to mount a
specific immune response to the virus.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, the UMass researchers think, the little girl in
their twin pair has no antibodies to HIV, nor do her immune cells
recognize the virus in the test tube. But her brother has low
levels of antibodies and at least a weak cellular response to HIV _
because his virus briefly broke through the drug barrier 17 months
ago with a burst of replication that his immune system still
``remembers.''
</P>
<P>
   Once they have a vaccine custom-made against the twins' virus,
the Umass researchers plan to administer it in hopes the children's
immune system will make both antibodies and immune cells
specifically targeted to any of the virus that emerges from
sanctuaries within their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan and Luzuriaga hope they can use a therapeutic vaccine,
rather than treatment interruptions, to tweak the twins' immune
systems into effective vigilance against HIV. If the signs are
good, they hope to try it on 10 other children who are long-term
HAART successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea,'' Sullivan says, ``will be to try to convert these
kids into long-term non-progressors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 1354EST &QL; 
