<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6236 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-UNIVERSE-2TAKES-B     02-08 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-UNIVERSE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO MY UNIVERSE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Since our earliest ancestors first began to
form abstract questions, the most fundamental one of all has been
this: Where did we, and everything around us, come from _ and what
is our ultimate fate?
</P>
<P>
   To many people, worrying about such things may seem as relevant,
and the answers as believable, as medieval theological arguments
about how many angels could dance on the head of a pin. But as
solid new evidence is mounting, that could change very soon.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years Andrei Linde, a Soviet emigre physicist
who now works at Stanford University, along with a few colleagues,
has been gradually developing a mind-bending answer to that
question. He suggests that the universe we live in, and the Big
Bang that most scientists think spawned it, are just one of a
nearly infinite number of such places and events that may have been
going on forever and that will continue for all eternity.
</P>
<P>
   There may be some comfort in this scenario for anyone troubled
by last year's finding by several astrophysicists that our universe
seems destined to run out of steam, expanding forever but gradually
becoming cold, sparse, and totally lifeless. Even though this
universe that began with a bang may go out with a cosmic whimper,
according to Linde's views, billions of other universes will carry
on forever. And, in one of his theory's more exotic possibilities,
some of those new universes could be ones that someday our human
descendants will, in god-like fashion, deliberately create.
</P>
<P>
   Linde's ideas were once considered among the more exotic
variations of a set of theories known as inflationary cosmology,
but a variety of discoveries in recent years have greatly
undermined the competing notions. ``Ten years ago, it was
completely crazy. Today, it explains many observations,'' Linde
says. It's beginning to look as if Linde's cosmology which he calls
``the eternally self-reproducing universe'' _ or some new variation
of it _ could soon be the last theory left standing.
</P>
<P>
   But what some cosmologists, including Linde, find even more
remarkable is this: We may be right on the verge of being able to
answer these ultimate questions _ which not long ago seemed
unanswerable _ once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a special time in which we live,'' said Linde recently
at a meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of
Science. While theories have come and gone or been modified beyond
recognition over the last few decades, ``in the next 10 or 20
years, we're going to have a fairly complete picture of the
universe that is not going to change for billions of years.''
</P>
<P>
   A new generation of orbiting telescopes and earthbound particle
accelerators should provide the data that can decisively answer
some of the most fundamental questions about our origins, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing that sentiment, physicist Joel Primack of the University
of California, Santa Cruz, also speaking at the AAAS meeting, said
``it's an absolutely incredible moment that we're living through.''
</P>
<P>
   It's something like the era when North America was mapped for
the first time: It went from a complete unknown to a very specific
outline within a short time; while many details have continued to
be filled in since then, the basic picture, once discovered, has
not changed.
</P>
<P>
   Primack said ``the questions that we were able to ask early in
this century are beginning to be answered.'' Humanity is finally
reaching a time, he said, when we are ``beginning to see the
outline of the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Linde, ``We waited for this moment for perhaps 15
billion years.''
</P>
<P>
   The emerging answers may well turn out to be a surprise, even
for many physicists and astronomers. The origin of the universe may
have been far more complex and bizarre than the usual view of a
single, explosive Big Bang that started everything in a colossal
fireball.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, some cosmologists say the evidence is now pointing
toward a view in which our Big Bang was just one of a nearly
infinite number of such events. Each of these bangs may create an
entirely different universe, with different basic laws and even
different kinds of space with more or fewer dimensions than the
four (three of space and one of time) that we are accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Linde acknowledges, maybe all the theories will be
knocked down by new evidence that comes in, and cosmologists will
be forced to go back to the drawing board and start over.
</P>
<P>
   Astrophysicist Virginia Trimble of the University of California
at Irvine said the new finds could, among other things, answer a
question that has been troubling theorists for the last few
decades: Why is it that some of the most basic characteristics and
physical laws of our universe seem to have been ``fine tuned'' to
produce exactly the conditions needed for stars, planets and living
things to exist. If a few of the basic principles had been just the
slightest bit different _ differences that according to current
physical theory are just as likely as the way things actually are _
then we might have had a universe in which no matter ever formed,
or one in which no elements but hydrogen and helium, and none of
the building blocks needed for planets and people, could ever have
arisen.
</P>
<P>
   The question is ``Whether we are very lucky, or incredibly
lucky,'' to be living in a universe whose basic laws are ``just
right'' for us to exist, Trimble said. In other words, she said,
``Why should it be that we live in a universe that we can live
in?''
</P>
<P>
   In Linde's view, the answer is simple: It may be that all of the
different possibilities that could have arisen actually did arise,
each in their own universe (or region of the universe, depending on
how one chooses to define the term). But only those universes whose
laws permitted the existence of life ended up producing beings
capable of wondering about such things.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
