</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LAME LOOK AT THE '60S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO &UR;  &LR;  _ The previews for NBC's saga of the 1960s,
resembled ads for a theme park: Welcome to our safely sanitized
recreation of that rollicking time. Critics call the miniseries
tame and lame, but in ``sweeps'' time on television, a demographic
imperative tries (again) to woo baby boomers, the 76 million
Americans born between 1945 and 1964.
</P>
<P>
   In politics, the 1960s ``culture wars'' is overused shorthand
for later trends. Just as a few years at the decade's end dominate
popular recollections of it, so do its older, highly educated,
politically motivated protestors. These cultural and political
pioneers dominate, but however many said they were at Chicago
and/or Woodstock or hallucinated that they were, the figure does
not add up to 76 million.
</P>
<P>
   The full baby boom portrait is more homespun Americana than
Woodstock Nation. It's no stretch to suggest that while most baby
boomers are not fundamentalist Christians, most fundamentalist
Christians are baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Early baby boomers, now in their mid-50s, had more educational
opportunity than their younger siblings because classrooms were
less crowded and had better jobs in an expanding economy that later
faced downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   Like many older siblings, top-tier boomers became lecturers.
They were right on civil rights, right on the war in Vietnam, and
right on Richard Nixon, so on other issues they were sure they knew
best.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is also a 1960s theme park, sometimes stuck in
1967's ``summer of love.'' At a sale of donated books from the
Friends of the San Francisco Public Library last week, I counted 22
copies, many in pristine condition, of ``The Greening of America,''
a 1970 ode to that decade.
</P>
<P>
   One notable San Franciscan, Robin Williams, warns that if you
can remember the 1960s, you must not have been there. But the lure
is still powerful, which explains the presence of white kids from
the suburbs panhandling on Haight Street near Ashbury Street.
</P>
<P>
   That fabled intersection is now adorned by a Ben &AMP; Jerry's
franchise, fighting fascism, war and injustice with Vermont
cholesterol. Nearby is another enduring legacy of the 1960s, a Gap
store.
</P>
<P>
   In American culture, clothing matters. In 1969, the first Gap
store opened, selling San Francisco's Levi jeans. The proprietors
whimsically named the shop after the great culture clash of the
time, the ``generation gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gap Inc. reported worldwide sales of more than $9
billion in 1998. The company went public in 1976. Adjusted for
stock splits, a share of stock then was worth 17 cents. Last week,
it was worth $44. In American economics, duds do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been John O'Hara'd, McNamara'd,'' sang Simon and
Garfunkel, the Manhattan minstrels of the late 1960s. ``I've been
Rolling Stoned and Beatled 'till I'm blind.'' Rock 'n' roll is not
only the Muzak of the theme park, but its politics, economics,
cuisine, and couture, as the NBC series makes clear in its
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted to return to the 1960s since Dec. 31, 1969,''
Lynda Obst, executive producer of the miniseries, was quoted as
saying. ``The iconic events of the birth of the counterculture _
Dylan going electric, the sit-in at Columbia, Woodstock, and many
others _ provide this film's narrative drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Dylan going electric? When Robert Allen Zimmerman, a/k/a Bob
Dylan, the asthmatic warbler from Minnesota, discovered kilowatts
in 1965, a generation was apparently McNamara'd, if not O'Hara'd.
</P>
<P>
   Simon and Garfunkel sang of an infidel who thought Dylan ``meant
Dylan Thomas. The man ain't got no culture.'' If culture is a
serious business, then ``culture wars'' are not for the faint of
heart.
</P>
<P>
   When someone mentions culture, I reach for my revolver, Herman
Goering, the head of the Nazi air force, once said. Those who can
never know the 1960s, along with those who can never forget the
1960s, may want to remain noncombatants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
