<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATLANTA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC SCRUTINY NOW FOCUSES ON ATLANTA'S AGGRESSIVE EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF AND JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A shiver of surprise coursed through the ballroom of
Tokyo's New Prince Takinawa Hotel when International Olympic
Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch announced that Atlanta
had won its long-shot bid to host the 1996 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Whispers of influence peddling lingered for years after that
September 1990 IOC vote. Now, in the wake of revelations of payoffs
in Salt Lake City, surrounding the Utah capital's selection as the
site of the 2002 Winter Games, the questions have turned to
suspicions, and Atlanta has found its Olympic memories under
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Hodler, the Swiss IOC official who set off the Salt Lake
scandal, triggered the inquiry when he suggested that Atlanta also
engaged in bribes and vote-buying. In December, when asked if he
thought Atlanta was clean, Hodler said, ``Certainly not.'' He said
it was hard to believe ``Atlanta could have been facing this
blackmail'' and won the Games without ``doing something.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, no specific evidence of wrongdoing has surfaced, and
Atlanta Olympic organizers spent the past week combing through
4,000 boxes of documentary history of the 1996 Games to prepare a
response to an IOC inquiry letter. That response will firmly
maintain they violated no laws or Olympic rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``No bribes, no scholarships, direct or indirect. No, sir,
absolutely none,'' Billy Payne Jr., the chief organizer and
visionary behind Atlanta's Olympic bid, said in an interview. Not
only were no offers made, Payne said, no payoffs or inappropriate
gifts were sought by IOC members or middlemen.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Olympic organizers here have refused to expedite the release
of the documents that reveal in excruciating detail the nearly
10-year effort to land and stage the 1996 Games. Payne said the
documents will be made public only after a lengthy archiving
process, though he would release some sooner if needed to refute
specific allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta organizers, however, have acknowledged lavish
gift-giving and pampering that raised Southern hospitality to new
heights. It was an effort that cost $7.8 million, plus millions
more in donated services, raised largely from local corporations,
philanthropies, and wealthy individuals. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Symptomatic excess? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say Atlanta's effort to land the 1996 Games
demonstrated the climate of excess within the entire Olympic
movement, paving the way for corruption in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ethics here are fuzzy, and no one in Atlanta dares to get
righteous,'' Steve Hummer, a columnist with The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, wrote last month. ``There is no innocence,
only varying degrees of guilt in these crimes of influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Those criticisms got an added lift last week when Tom Welch, the
former president of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee, claimed
that former Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young was among those aware of the
cash and scholarships allegedly exchanged for votes from certain
IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who acted as an unpaid advisor to the Utah committee,
said in an interview he was aware of the program, but did not know
to whom the scholarships were given. Young also lashed out at the
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems naive or racist that the American press, and the
world press, should have put so much focus on humanitarian
assistance to poor people and label that as corruption, and not say
a word about the influence of $5 billion or $6 billion television
contracts, or the hundred-million-dollar marketing contracts,''
Young said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be real _ the influence in the Olympic movement is not
in the hands of a few poor Africans or Asians or Latins,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Atlanta has made no secret of its aggressive
attempts from 1987 onward to influence IOC members, using
enticements large and small as a way to cement ``friendships'' that
would pay off in the form of a winning bid at the IOC's September
1990 site-selection meeting in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to build the best relationship you can, to win these
people's trust and confidence,'' said Charlie Battle Jr., a lawyer
who was the Atlanta bid committee's chief international emissary.
``We did what we thought was appropriate and accepted and
recognized as the thing to do to put your best foot forward, within
the parameters of the regulations as we understood them.''
</P>
<P>
   There were the obligatory first-class airplane tickets,
exquisite meals, and rooms at the Marriott Marquis hotel; silver
mint julep cups; Cabbage Patch dolls; homespun touches like Claxton
fruitcakes and Vidalia onion relishes; limited-edition quilts and
embroidered ``Georgia on my mind'' pillow cases; video copies of
``Gone With The Wind''; visits by private jet to Savannah; and
yacht rides aboard The Highlander, owned by the family of Malcolm
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   There also were personalized gifts _ chosen with help from
individual dossiers compiled on each IOC member. They included a
print of a building at Amherst College for Prince Albert of Monaco,
an alumnus; a carved walking stick for an IOC delegate from San
Juan who walked with a cane; a meeting with famed architect John
Portman for a Mexican IOC member in the same profession; symphony
tickets for music lovers and outings to the exclusive Augusta
National Golf Club for golf enthusiasts; and a bulldog for a Cuban
IOC delegate who grew enamored of the University of Georgia mascot.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta organizers also helped pick up the tab when David
Sibandze, an IOC member from Swaziland, spent four days at Piedmont
Hospital after collapsing with a heart ailment. Sibandze resigned
from the IOC last month when it was revealed his son received
scholarships and a job through the SLOC. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `They didn't break any rules' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, Atlanta organizers insist they were far less excessive
than other bid cities, which in some cases spent twice as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in our past that would dampen our fond and
wonderful memories. It is only a question of when are we finally
believed,'' said Ginger Watkins, an original bid committee member
who oversaw all IOC delegates' visits to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Though rival candidate cities found it suspicious that a
first-time bidder could defeat favored Athens and four other cities
for the coveted Centennial Games, none has accused Atlanta of
providing Salt Lake-style payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran a very bold and brassy and slick campaign _ all the
things we did not want to be,'' said Norman Seagram, who was
financial chairman of the Toronto bid committee. ``But they didn't
break any rules.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
