<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-CAMPAIGN (Manchester, N.H.) _ Elizabeth Dole gives first
political speech since indicating she might run. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-AVIATOR (Camp Lejune, N.C.) _ Opening arguments in the
court martial of Marine pilot who hit a ski lift cable in Italy. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   WIDEMAN-RETRIAL (Pittsburgh) _ Robert Wideman's part in a
killing a generation ago might have been forgotten by now, except
by the family of a 24 year old man who was shot in the back on a
November night in 1975. Instead, the crime has become one of the
enduring literary images of black America. It was the subject of an
acclaimed 1984 book, ``Brothers &AMP; Keepers'' by Robert Wideman's
brother, John Edgar Wideman. One brother in the non-fiction work
was the noted author who had escaped the ghetto. The other was the
street tough who embodied the cycle that claims many young black
males. At 25, Robert Wideman was imprisoned for life with no
possibility of parole after an accomplice fired a fatal shot in a
robbery that went wrong. Now, Robert Wideman's case is no longer
alive only in literature. A judge has ordered a new trial, angry
prosecutors are appealing, and a debate has broken out over the
effect of race and fame on justice. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-DOCTOR (Savannah, Ga.) _ Profile of a black doctor who
works in a neighborhood that like many other poor urban and rural
communities is short of physicians, black or white, and in a wider
community with few black physicians. Nationally, in a population
that is 13 percent black, less than 4 percent of all physicians are
black. In Savannah, which is more than 50 percent black, 30 of 540
physicians are black, or less than 6 percent. Lately, these
disparities have stirred concern among African-American advocates
and historically black medical schools like Morehouse in the face
of waves of new research showing disparities in the health of black
and white Americans. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other International &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Rambouillet, France) _ Developments in peace talks
on the restive Yugoslav province. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-JOURNALISTS (Johannesburg) _ Government arrests three
more journalists. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-TRIAL (Kuala Lumpur) _ Anwar Ibrahim, the deposed
deputy prime minister, takes the stand in his corruption trial. By
Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-VOTE (Mexico City) _ PRI, the ruling party, and leftists
split two gubernatorial elections. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-GUARD (Rome) _ The Vatican closes the case of the Swiss
guard who killed his commander, commander's wife and himself in the
Vatican. The finding: He went nuts. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was down
43 points, or half a percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 8 points,
or 0.3 percent. Elsewhere, prices increased 0.7 percent in Tokyo
and fell 0.6 percent in Hong Kong. They decreased 0.9 percent in
Frankfurt and half a percent in London. Shares were little changed
in Brazil and up 0.7 percent in Mexico. On the American debt
market, the long bond was up 16/32 point, with the yield at 5.32
percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   SBC-WILLIAMS (Undated) _ SBC Communications will invest $500
million in the phone unit of the Williams Cos. The Bell company
will use the network of the unit, Williams Communications Group, to
provide long-distance and international voice and data services and
to link SBC's international networks with Williams's American
network. The alliance is the latest effort by SBC, which is buying
Ameritech, to expand beyond being a provider of local phone
services in several states into a global phone and data company. By
Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REORG (Undated) _ Microsoft plans a broad
reorganization that will put much more focus on the Internet, and
it has asked Brad Silverberg, who led Microsoft's MS-DOS and
Windows operating systems upgrades through the past decade, to
return from an extended leave of absence to help make the changes.
Microsoft also announces an agreement with British
Telecommunications to develop and market wireless-Internet and
corporate-data services overseas, the latest in a series of
alliances between the software company and telecommunications
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ William Poole, Microsoft's
head of business development for Windows, takes the stand and will
face questions from the government about the company's restrictive
contracts with Internet service providers. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Undated) _ Developments: The real weakens to a
level of 1.87 against the dollar from 1.83 on Friday. Stocks are
flat. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   AMR-PILOTS (Undated) _ More about the dispute between American
Airlines and its pliots. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-AIRPLANES (Shanghai) _ China extands a freeze on new
aircraft purchases. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-MUSIC (Undated) _ IBM and five major music companies,
including BMG, announce a trial of a digital music-distribution
system that is intended to counter the MP3 format, the
controversial technology that compresses songs into small packages
for easy transfer over the Internet. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   DERIVATIVES (Chicago) _ The Chicago Mercantile Exchange, the
Singapore International Monetary Exchange and the French Stock
Exchanges plan a common electronic trading system for derivatives
to boost volumes and cut costs. The alliance will compete with
rivals including the London International Financial Futures and
Options Exchange and Eurex, the German-Swiss futures exchange
group. On Jan. 27, members of the Chicago Board of Trade voted
against an alliance with Eurex. By David Barboza.
