<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6244 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-08 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY COULDN'T FIND THE FACTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ As plug-pullings go, it has to be the fastest on
record.
</P>
<P>
   What finally set the Senate on a course to tell the House of
Representatives _ as politely as humanly possible _ that its
impeachment case does not deserve to succeed, was not its lopsided
vote to spare Monica Lewinsky the torture of live testimony for no
probitive purpose.
</P>
<P>
   It was a more private judgment _ leadership guided but
membership supported _ to stop an almost comically ill-advised
effort to turn the Senate into the House.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, the impeachment body still twitched; two
hours later it was dead.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the ``findings of fact'' _ the last gasp of
pure partisanship in a proceeding that cooler heads in the Senate
kept from becoming a full-fledged trial _ were not that at all.
</P>
<P>
   The best that seven designated Republican finders could find
were argumentative conclusions, essentially that President Clinton
was indeed responsible for the conduct alleged in the two
impeachment articles that can now be swept into history's dustbin;
the G word (guilty), the P word (perjury), and the O word
(obstruction) were avoided, but saying that the president
``willfuly'' testified falsely and ``wrongfully,'' and tried to
disrupt lawful court proceedings is a distinction without a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   As such, the seven turned off the only Democratic senator who
had even expressed interest in the idea, Connecticut's Joseph
Lieberman; and they halted any chance of the idea spreading to
others.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, as Democrats from Minority Leader Tom Daschle on down
made clear, they could have been the basis for filibuster by
amendment _ like adding a ``finding'' that Ken Starr's mother wears
combat boots, or that Lucianne Goldberg and Linda Tripp are poor
role models for 21st century women.
</P>
<P>
   But behind all that was the most important fact of all, that
there were as many as 14 Republican senators fully prepared to
oppose findings of anything.
</P>
<P>
   For those counting, that is slightly more than 25 percent of the
GOP membership, meaning that the so-called findings, no matter
their shape or form, never had as much as a prayer of passage.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, to a person, was principled. A few senators _
Phil Gramm of Texas and Bob Smith of New Hampshire, for example _
tend to oppose anything not specified, or enumerated, in the
Constitution. And the rest _ including moderately conservative
types like Mike DeWine of Ohio, Gordon Smith of Oregon, and Richard
Shelby of Alabama _ opposed any fudging of the explicit
constitutional obligation of the Senate to convict or not convict.
</P>
<P>
   But the evening before the Republicans met, a final straw was
added to the camel's back in the form of a CBS News poll that found
the public viewing the Senate with the same distaste with which it
had viewed the House back in December _ as a den of squabbling,
posturing partisans unable to work together.
</P>
<P>
   The members were already convinced, but the poll hit the big
shots where they live, especially Majority Follower Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   An hour before the Senate convened to vote down the subpoena for
Lewinsky (splitting the GOP caucus almost in half), Lott yanked the
plug on the fact-finders, claiming, ``I have felt all along that
really what we ought to do is do what the Constitution and the
rules provide _ go through the impeachment trial, get to the
articles of impeachment, vote on those, and then move on.''
</P>
<P>
   In a pig's eye.
</P>
<P>
   It was Lott himself who had encouraged the original fact-finder,
Senator Susan Collins of Maine, back in December; and it was Lott
two weeks ago who named two other senators to run a seven-person
GOP operation to come up with a draft.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, in particular, was left holding the bag, though she was
hardly in a position to complain.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into the Senate proceedings, she had strongly supported
the calling of witnesses to the floor as the only way information
that could inform a vote could be presented, and she was pushing a
separate procedure to find ``facts'' because of her theory that an
acquittal under the Constitution might send the wrong ``message.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end she voted against hearing the only requested
witness, and yet she helped draft two findings of ``fact'' claiming
that the president did what he was accused of doing.
</P>
<P>
   The composite of Collins's positions was that she looked like a
pretzel.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of her idea, however, like the demise of live
witnesses, was but a metaphor for the end of impeachment itself.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will limp on to its anticlimactic conclusion this
week, but the real end came Thursday with a genuine jolt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
