<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT TAKES ITS TOLL ON THE GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the impeachment trial of President Clinton approaches its
end, it appears that this episode has been _ and will continue to
be _ far more costly to the Republicans than to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The only casualties to date have been Republicans, including
some of the key leaders of the GOP's assault on the president.
Instead of destroying Clinton as they had hoped, they ended up
destroying themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Among the battlefield casualties are former House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, who was forced to resign after the GOP lost six seats in
November; former Speaker-elect Robert Livingston, who resigned
after published reports of his adulterous history; and, of course,
those who lost their seats in Congress in the last election. Among
them were such Clinton foes as Senator Alfonse M. D'Amato of New
York, who lost his seat to Charles Schumer, and presidential
nemesis Senator Lauch Faircloth of North Carolina, who lost to John
Edwards. In Indiana, the race to succeed another anti-Clinton
incumbent who was retiring from the Senate was won by Evan Bayh, a
Democrat and Clinton defender.
</P>
<P>
   There are also the walking wounded of the impeachment episode.
These include US Representative Henry Hyde, who chaired the House
impeachment drive against Clinton. Hyde may have survived the
publicity about his self-described ``youthful indiscretion'' in
which, at age 46, he was involved in an adulterous affair that cost
a woman her marriage and family. But his unrelenting efforts to
push the Senate toward convicting Clinton apparently did not sit
well with voters in his own district. Recent polls show that Hyde's
negative ratings overshadow his positives in his own district.
</P>
<P>
   Hypocrisy was the weapon that caused some GOP casualties _ such
as when Hustler publisher Larry Flynt had a hand in revealing
Livingston's affairs, and then revealed that one of the impeachment
managers, Georgia Representative Bob Barr had sought and paid for
his wife's (now his ex-wife) abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Barr and Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, garnered some
public notoriety for their appearances before, and apparent ties
to, the Council of Conservative Citizens, which many critics view
as a racist organization, connected to the Ku Klux Klan and the
White Citizens Council. Both Lott and Barr have tried to distance
themselves from the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the revelation that Tom DeLay, the majority whip and
leader of the House drive for Clinton's removal for ``lying under
oath'' _ had lied under oath in a civil deposition in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   For other Republicans, the damage may be yet to come. For
example, Senator John Chafee of Rhode Island, although a moderate,
has reportedly lost ground with his constituents after siding with
conservative Republicans on key issues during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans may find their support for a controversial
``finding of fact'' against Clinton comes back to haunt them. Faced
with strong Democratic protest, Republicans have abandoned this
thinly-veiled attempt to have Clinton branded a ``criminal'' before
his expected acquittal by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, all these factors give Democrats _ who have
already gained significant ground in the last two elections _
reason to be optimistic about 2000. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the
House minority leader who decided just last week not to run for
president, knows that, given voters' anger at Republicans, he has a
good chance of being the next speaker.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the many GOP casualties during independent
counsel Kenneth W. Starr's inquisition against Clinton is because
the party's right-wing went against the electorate. It attempted to
undo the people's election of Clinton by its blatant attempt to
throw him out of office on flimsy charges drawn on his private, if
scandalous, affair with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   People made it clear that the these Republicans did not
represent their views, and that, by trying to remove Clinton, they
were negating the wishes of the very voters who chose Clinton in
two successive elections.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the Republicans attempted a political coup d'etat not
only against Clinton, but against the people who elected him. And
the people judged these Republicans accordingly, as demonstrated in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans say voters will retain only a faint memory of
these events when they go to the polls in two years, but that is
wishful thinking. The voters who elected Clinton sent a strong
message in the last election. Apparently the Republicans just don't
get it. That's why voters are likely to send a stronger, and
simpler, message to the GOP next time: Get out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
