</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-GENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHATEVER HAPPENED TO THE `GAY GENE'? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The research project in 1993 that indicated many gay men shared
a common genetic marker in the X chromosone was hailed as a
momentous scientific discovery _ one that would help transcend
bigotry, heal family wounds and lay to rest a question for the
ages: is sexual orientation genetic?
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a ``gay gene'' offered an ironclad defense of
homosexuality; if it was genetically predetermined, then being gay
could not be cast as ``deviant'' behavior, something that could be
``corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for the Genes, Mom!'' T-shirts were sold in gay and
lesbian bookstores. Many gay activists and newspaper editorial
writers predicted the discovery would give homosexuals greater
legal standing to fight discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, however, the gene has still not been found and
interest in _ and enthusiasm for _ the ``gay gene'' research has
waned considerably among both activists and scientists. There is a
growing consensus that sexual orientation is much more complicated
than a matter of genes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Pillard, a professor of psychiatry at Boston
University School of Medicine who was involved in a study of twins
and sexual orientation, has done research showing that sexuality is
greatly influenced by environment, and that the role of genetics
is, in the end, limited.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pillard's findings, a gay man's fraternal twin had
about a 22 percent chance of being gay; an adopted sibling had a
roughly nine or 10 percent chance; and a person selected by random
draw has a three our four percent liklihood. The message:
environment _ in this case, the environment that adoptive siblings
share _ clearly helps shape sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Pillard offers a further bit of evidence on the limited
(although still significant) influence of genes: With identical
twins, if genes were everything, you would expect a 100 percent
overlap in sexuality; in other words, if one twin was gay, so, too,
the other. But identical twins shared sexual orientation only 50
percent of the time, he reports, and that statistics for lesbian
women are similar.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dean Hamer, the National Cancer Institute molecular
biologist who lead the 1993 study (and its validation study in
1995), believes a gay gene does exists and will be found within
five years. But he also acknowledges the limites of genetic
predisposition. For example, he has been unable to find in women
the same genetic marker found in some gay men. ``Clearly,'' he
says, ``there is a lot more than just genes going on.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he says, ``It is the same for every human behavior _
environment matters for extroversion, smoking cigarettes, just
about anything you can name.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is not known,'' he says, ``is what about the environment
is important. And for that, we are just as clueless as we were 100
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the gay community has cooled to the idea of a
`gay gene' is that a justification of sexuality is no longer seen
as so important. Indeed, a fuller picture of civil rights has
emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that to us it (the gene) may be a scientific
question, but it is not a political one,'' says Kerry Lobel,
executive director of the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force.
``Gene or no gene, every person deserves full civil rights under
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is another reason for the second thoughts. Not only is
there plenty of historical precedent to suggest that discovery of a
``gay gene'' would do nothing to ease discrimination against
homosexuals, there is also some reason to think it could make
matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that James Watson, the Nobel laureate who with Francis
Crick, discovered DNA, said that if the gene was discovered and a
woman decided not to give birth to a child that may have a tendency
to become homosexual, she should be able to abort the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, says Lobel, going to the doctor, finding out you have
the gene and then that information is given to your insurance
company. ``Perhaps you are denied benefits,'' she adds. ``Or
perhaps your employer finds out you have the gay gene and you are
fired from your job. Maybe, in a court, you are fighting for
custody of your child and someone says you are a lesbian and you
don't get custody because the court orders a genetic test.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Hubbard, a board member of The Council for Responsible
Genetics, a Harvard Univerity biology professor emeritus and author
of ``Exploding the Gene Myth,'' says history is replete with
discrimination for biological reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people to feel that because it is biological makes it
unchallengeable and takes people off the hook from right wing
criticism is very short-sighted. Both being Jewish and being black
is considered biological by some people, and it has not stopped
discrimination against either group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the job is to widen the range of acceptable behaviors
and not to discriminate on the basis of who people choose to love
and live with and not invent biological reasons for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Searching for a ``gay gene,'' says Hubbard, is not even a
worthwhile pursuit. ``Let me be very clear: I don't think there is
any single gene that governs any complex human behavior. There are
genetic components in everything we do and it is foolish to say
genes are not involved, but I don't think they are decisive.''
</P>
<P>
   John D'Emilio, co-author of ``Intimate Matters: a History of
Sexuality in America,'' agrees. ``I don't want to be in a position
to say scientists should not do research, but it is not something
that I would look for.''
</P>
<P>
   And the federal government may not want to look for it either.
Pillard said he sought funding for a study to replicate Hamer's
work and was denied. ``Research in this area has stalled for a
couple of years,'' he says. ``I really think the government is not
interested in fanning the flames of this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Emilio says he is skeptical about a genetic key unlocking
understanding to sexual orientation because of cultural and
historical evidence which points to ``an immense maliability of
human sexuality. In Western society, in the classical world, there
were huge numbers of men who were married and also had ongoing
homosexual relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite there being very little evidence for a biological
basis for homosexuality _ one group of Canadian researchers could
not replicate Hamer's findings _ it is something many Americans are
rushing to embrace.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, says D'Emilio, that feeling comes from a
``very noble and generous place. On the one hand, many American
people, I think, would really like to embrace gay people and feel
things that have happened to gay people are wrong. In open
democratic societies people should be accepted for who they are,''
he says. ``Culturally, however, homosexuality makes people
uncomfortable. If people can be persuaded you are born this way,
that you have no choice, it resolves a complicated moral issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But if genetics plays only a supporting role in determining our
sexual orientation, it means there are no easy answers about where
our sexual orientation comes from, only questions about how we
respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not matter to me where it comes from,'' says Lobel.
``Even for people who currently believe that you are born that way,
my colleagues on the right who belive that think the issue is: what
do you do? Act out on your orientation or stifle it? I'd like to
think we live in a world where we want people to have consentual
relationships with each other, but reasonable people disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   Science aside, says D'Emilio, ``We are left with the question,
of `Do we accept people who are sexually different?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
