<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6255 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-08 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMASS IS RICHER THAN EVER, BUT THE TAXPAYER GETS NO RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF JACOBY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When William Bulger became president of the University of
Massachusetts three years ago, the public was unimpressed. In a
Boston Globe poll, only 20 percent thought the vindictive president
of the state Senate, a man with no scholarly credentials and a
deeply etched reputation for not tolerating dissent, ought to be
running a university.
</P>
<P>
   But the muckety-mucks of the UMass system were thrilled. In
Bulger's appointment they beheld dollar signs, and that mattered
more to them than mere scholarship. ``We need somebody who can get
us the money to do what we need to do,'' said the president of the
UMass-Amherst faculty Senate. ``Obviously, he would be helpful . .
. in terms of funding,'' said the governor who appointed him.
Bulger ``will be able to acquire the resources,'' said the trustee
who chaired the presidential search committee.
</P>
<P>
   What they really needed was a director of development, but
Bulger, who craves prestige, would never have considered any
position but the top one. So he got the UMass presidency and the
perks that went with it, including a $189,000 salary _ $107,600
more than he was making as Senate president _ and the
10,500-square-foot office on Tremont Street in downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It was a start, but Bulger wanted more. And whatever Bulger
wants, Bulger usually gets. Which is why his office today is a
marble-foyered palace overlooking the State House, three times the
size of the Tremont Street complex (at nearly six times the rent).
And it is why his salary has risen to $238,000 _ and will soar to
$282,000 next year. At that point, the president of one of the
nation's least distinguished public universities will be drawing
down one of the highest salaries in academe.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Bulger is doing the job he was hired to do:
fund-raising. UMass is pulling in dollars almost faster than they
can be counted. Alumni giving has quintupled. Donors eager to bask
in Bulger's glow paid $10,000 and up to reserve a table at his
lavish inaugural in 1997. Overall giving has rocketed from $25
million in 1994 to $62 million last year, a 150 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done his job unbelievably,'' says the chairman of the
UMass board of trustees, ``and we have an obligation to pay him
what he deserves.'' Not so; the obligation was Bulger's. He was
hired with no relevant experience, and owed it to the trustees to
prove that he deserved to be paid $189,000 a year. Do they _ and
the taxpayers _ really owe Bulger a 49 percent raise merely because
he met his job description?
</P>
<P>
   But then, who really cares about the taxpayers' interest in all
of this? Certainly not Bulger; his tenure on Beacon Hill was one
long picking of the public pocket. Not the trustees, either; one
indication of their regard for the taxpayers who pick up much of
the UMass tab is that they kept Bulger's gluttonous pay hike secret
for months. Not even Governor Cellucci, a one-time fiscal
conservative. Last week, as he promoted his elephantine $20.4
billion budget, the governor let it be known that Bulger's bonanza
was OK by him.
</P>
<P>
   What was not OK by him was the trustees' vote to increase the
price of a UMass education by an average of 1.4 percent in the
coming year. The actual effect on student bills would be minimal.
The largest increase any UMass student would face is $175 (at the
Boston campus), while some students would actually enjoy a $2
decrease (at UMass-Lowell). But Cellucci was outraged. ``We should
be committed to lowering the cost,'' he said. ``To do that, you
have to lower tuition and fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Terminology is important here. When tuition and fees at a state
school go down, the taxpayer's cost goes up. UMass students are
heavily subsidized by the working men and women of Massachusetts,
who will lay out nearly $450 million next year so those students
can attend college on the cheap. Even after the slight fee
increase, a year at UMass-Amherst _ tuition, fees, room, board _
will cost just $10,097. That is a terrific bargain, as anyone
wrestling with the cost of a private college well knows.
</P>
<P>
   Why should a taxpayer struggling to put a child through
Northeastern or Boston University also be forced to help put 48,000
students through the University of Massachusetts? It isn't as if
everyone who goes to Northeastern and BU is wealthy, while plenty
of students whose families are wealthy attend UMass. Students at
UMass enjoy a highly lucrative form of middle-class welfare. That
may be tolerable in a state where the vast majority of college
students are educated by the state. But in Massachusetts, where
three out of five students attend independent colleges and
universities, it raises questions of basic equity.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of questions, here's another. Cellucci's budget for the
upcoming fiscal year increases the UMass appropriation by $20.4
million. By what logic does a university that can raise huge sums
from private donors need a larger state subsidy? With Bulger at the
helm, contributions are pouring in as they never have before.
Increasingly, UMass can stand on its own. Shouldn't the taxpayers
be allowed to reduce their level of support?
</P>
<P>
   Well, somebody else will have to think about those questions;
Paul Cellucci is busy pandering to the UMass lobby. ``I am very
upset that the board apparently has decided to raise the fees,'' he
fumed last week. That is another way of saying: I am very upset
that the taxpayers of Massachusetts might get a bit of relief.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jeff Jacoby is a Globe columnist. His e-mail address is
jacoby(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
