A6261 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CARLIN-BOS &LR;      02-08 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CARLIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARLIN GIVES ANECTDOTES, ANTIDOTES FOR SOCIAL DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
GEORGE CARLIN: YOU ARE ALL DISEASED 
Directed by: Rocco Urbisci 
Produced by: Kimber Rikabaugh 
On: HBO, Saturday, throughout February 
Rating: TV-MA (adult content, adult language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a general rule, comedians grow more conservative as they grow
older. Robert Klein still does material from his album ``Child of
the '50s,'' and the Smothers Brothers' political satire of the '60s
has evolved into a rather timid sibling rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Not Carlin. In his 11th HBO special, the gray-haired, wild-eyed
stand-up philosopher raves on. In the live cablecast of his latest
special, `George Carlin: You Are All Diseased,'' Carlin stalks the
audience. Using logic as his primary weapon, Carlin rationally and
hilariously rips and claws his way through America's conventional
wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, as Carlin might observe, if it's conventional, it
can't be wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If honesty were introduced, this country would collapse,'' he
says. That observation may not be that funny, but it's true. And
the same could be said for ``You Are All Diseased.''
</P>
<P>
   Be forewarned, this is not the sweet Mr. Carlin who plays the
pleasant Mr. Conductor on PBS's ``Shining Time Station.'' This is
the lunatic Mr. Carlin who'll stop at nothing to cut through the
brainless cultural morass exemplified by incessant reruns of
``Little House on the Prairie'' and idiotic advertising slogans.
Carlin despises convention and hypocrisy. And, if it takes
profanity to cut through audience complacency, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   His thinning gray hair pulled back, giving him a manelike
appearance that reinforced his predatory nature, Carlin tore
through America's consumer culture, dependence on mainstream
religion, and treatment of children. He took no prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Jabbing and cutting and weaving across the faux New York rooftop
set like a shadowboxer, Carlin didn't settle for belly laughs. This
was head-to-head combat.
</P>
<P>
   He took on the myth of airport security, a setup he said that's
``only there to make white people feel good'' and suggested we
begin to see terrorism as entertainment. Carlin lampooned our mad
rush to stay healthy, concluding with the ultimate absurdity that
on death row they wipe your arm with a cotton swab before
administering a lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   A recitation of Carlin's masterful observations doesn't do them
justice. They must be administered by the man himself as he spits
out a venom of undeniable logic and humor.
</P>
<P>
   And, while he castigates religion, his delivery owes more to
Elmer Gantry than to Bertrand Russell. In fact, if MTV had any
imagination, they'd promote a Celebrity Death Match between Carlin
and Jerry Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   For those who might object to the dozens of words and
expressions not often heard on television: you're missing the
point. The way Carlin sees it, we are a nation asleep _ lulled into
somnolence. To cut through generations of cultural conditioning,
Carlin hauls out the heavy artillery.
</P>
<P>
   This is double-barreled comedy that goes back to the form's
earliest roots _ to poke fun of the rich and powerful. There are no
real jokes. Just a real joker, a guy who brings an uncomfortable
smile to our faces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
