<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6270 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-RUSHMORE-BOS &LR;      02-08 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RUSHMORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE ROAD FOR `RUSHMORE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Wes Anderson does not fly.
</P>
<P>
   This was the explanation for the big yellow tour bus parked
recently in front of Boston University's student union building on
a gray, snowy January morning. It was also the reason Anderson
looked like an extra from ``Night of the Living Dead'' _ his eyes
at half-mast, and his body slouched on a hideously upholstered
couch of sorts in the back of the aforementioned bus, one of those
cushy, fully equipped 45-foot things frequented by rock bands and
John Madden.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, and Jason Schwartzman, star of Anderson's offbeat
comedy ``Rushmore,'' arrived in Boston at 6 a.m. after a five-hour
drive from New York fraught with black ice, cops with radar guns,
and precious little sleep. The cross-country bus tour, which began
in Los Angeles Jan. 21 and was scheduled for 11 cities, was
arranged by Disney, parent company of Touchstone Pictures, the
distributor of ``Rushmore.'' Sitting across from Anderson,
Schwartzman was considerably more animated, still stoked from an
appearance on ``The Late Show with David Letterman.'' And he
certainly wasn't too fried to take a jovial poke at Anderson's fear
of the unfriendly skies.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' said Schwartzman, smirking at his weary director and
fellow road warrior. ``Do you think you wanna fly now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to fly,'' Anderson reiterated. ``Hey, it was
really nice of them to set this whole thing up _ I mean, they've
been really helpful. But none of us realized what it would be like
out here. It's long and lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is what one must do when one's film is regarded as
one of the year's best. Spin magazine anointed ``Rushmore'' ``the
best comedy of the year,'' a phrase that, just in case anyone
missed it, is emblazoned on the back of the tour bus. Already, Bill
Murray, who also stars in the film, has picked up a fistful of
critics' awards and has had his name bandied about as a possible
Academy Award nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which opened Friday &UR;  &LR; (Feb. 5), stars Schwartzman as
Max Fischer, a sophomore at prestigious Rushmore Academy who
becomes involved in a would-be love triangle with his 50-year-old
mentor, billionaire Herman Blume (Murray), and a young teacher,
Rosemary Cross (Olivia Williams). It all erupts into an unholy war
of revenge in which no ten-speed bike or Rolls-Royce is sacred. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Where the boys are &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 28, wrote ``Rushmore'' with Owen Wilson, who also
cowrote and starred in Anderson's 1996 debut, the well-received
``Bottle Rocket.'' Both knew they wanted to do a film set in an
elite boys' school, not unlike St. John's School in Houston _
Anderson's alma mater, and the stand-in for the fictional Rushmore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoyed the school. I didn't do very well in it, but
I enjoyed it as a place to go and work,'' said the lanky,
bespectacled Anderson. ``So I thought it would be a nice place to
do a movie set in the school with this nice atmosphere. The movie
really doesn't have anything to do with school in the end, but we
knew that would be the setting. One of the things that was most
appealing to us was the initial idea of a 15-year-old kid and a
50-year-old man becoming friends and equals.''
</P>
<P>
   And the perfect character for such a setting is the singular Max
Fischer, who is unlike any other teenage boy portrayed in recent
films.
</P>
<P>
   With his glasses, braces, dopey haircut, and high-water,
impossibly wrinkled khakis, Max looks the quintessential nerd, the
kind of geeky guy on whom bullies can practice their wedgie skills.
But looks are deceiving. Max is droll and smart and popular, even a
big man on campus. He's involved in a host of extracurricular
activities _ so many, in fact, he's on the verge of flunking out of
school _ from beekeeping to the French Club to the wrestling team.
He even founded the school's dramatic group, the Max Fischer
Players, for whom he writes edgy plays drawing on such influences
as ``Serpico'' and ``Apocalypse Now.'' As a second-grader, he was
admitted to the school on the strength of a one-act play based on
Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max isn't a geek. He's cool in his own world, and where he is
is fine,'' Schwartzman said. ``He's not out of time, because he's
not in any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1,500 and 1,800 young actors auditioned for the role of
Max. When Anderson was asked what he looking for, Schwartzman
chimed in, ``Not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman, 17, has always wanted to act, feeling ``cosmically
drawn to it.'' That shouldn't be a surprise _ his mother is actress
Talia Shire, best known for her work in the ``Godfather'' and
``Rocky'' films, and his uncle is director Francis Ford Coppola. A
native of Los Angeles, Schwartzman auditioned for lots of roles,
including Tom Hanks's matchmaking son in ``Sleepless in Seattle,''
but he always came up empty. &QL; 
 &QL; 
More Hoffman than Jagger &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then he attended a dinner party where one of the guests was a
``Rushmore'' casting director.
</P>
<P>
   ``She saw me, started talking to me, and said, `You look like
you could be great for this part in this movie.' I said, `Great,
send me the script.' I thought it was all a joke my brothers were
playing on me. It was a family dinner, so I thought it was like,
`Hey, let's make him think he's being cast in a movie.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was no joke. Three days later, Schwartzman received the
script. ``I rehearsed all week long, I auditioned for Wes, and it
worked. It worked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically I was picturing Mick Jagger at age 15,'' said
Anderson in describing an actor to play Max. Schwartzman took that
as a cue to strike his best Jagger-esque poses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason came in, and was nothing like Mick Jagger, but he
reminded me much more of a Dustin Hoffman type,'' Anderson
continued. ``And I started thinking, `Well, that's a way we can do
this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Think of Hoffman in his star-making role as Benjamin Braddock in
``The Graduate,'' if Braddock had grown up listening to Nirvana's
``Nevermind,'' watching ``South Park,'' and reading The Economist.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman has the slouchy, thick-browed looks of Oasis's Liam
Gallagher, and more than his share of snarky wanker whimsy. And,
like Gallagher, Schwartzman is in a band, Phantom Planet, which
released its debut album, ``Phantom Planet Is Missing,'' last year.
For four years, he's been the band's drummer. On the Web site for
Geffen Records, the band's label, Schwartzman's star turn in
``Rushmore'' is mentioned, and there's even a link to the film's
Internet site. For his part, Schwartzman is more reluctant about
cross-promoting his film and band.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange thing. As much as I want to plug my band, my
band wouldn't be too happy if I was plugging `Rushmore' during my
band stuff,'' he said. ``That's the way I see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys in the band are OK with this, but obviously they're a
bit freaked out by it all,'' he said. ``And obviously every time
I'm doing `Rushmore,' I can't be doing Phantom Planet. But they're
happy for me. They wanted to see me do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman wants to get back to his band, but is enjoying the
fruits of his first acting gig, such as his Letterman appearance,
which he described as ``freaky and amazing.'' He will again work
with Anderson, on the writer-director's next film, a comedy about a
family of geniuses set in New York.
</P>
<P>
   No word yet on whether that publicity tour will duplicate this
on-the-road-again odyssey set to wind up in Denver Feb. 9 _ if
Anderson can hold out that long. The bus, Schwartzman said, ``is
like a vampire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this gets people to go see `Rushmore,' then it's all worth
it. That's why we're doing this, and that's what's important,''
Anderson said, as he stifled a yawn. ``It's been kind of fun, but
I'm really exhausted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 1415EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6273 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-MORALITY-BOS &LR;      02-08 1390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-MORALITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRUTH IS OUT THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the media and political swirl around Bill Clinton and Monica
Lewinsky turned into a maelstrom last year, writer Tim O'Brien
noted, ``It's as if `The Scarlet Letter' had never been written.''
Indeed, the same issues that Nathaniel Hawthorne dealt with in his
19th-century novel are being hashed over today in both the
political and the cultural dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   The political clash is being played out in Congress, with the
Republicans assuming the role of Puritan prosecutors. But they have
been helped along for the past year by the media, which for the
most part posited l'affaire Lewinsky as a simple matter of good and
evil, truth and lies, at least until the populace revolted by
supporting Clinton. The cultural clash extends throughout the arts
_ witness the National Endowment for the Arts controversy and
Republican antipathy for any modern art that smacks of, well,
modernism. But perhaps it's most instructive to look at
contemporary movies and television shows over the last few years,
specifically at the growing acceptance in film for more complex
moral landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood film has long been the bastion of unambiguous
moral dichotomies. From ``The Ten Commandments'' to ``Forrest
Gump,'' life is presented as a matter of good and evil, truth and
lies. These films give their viewers a sense of easy transcendence,
as Mark Edmundson calls it in his book, ``Nightmare on Main
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   The past five years, though, have seen the rise of the
independent film, which presents, almost across the board, a more
complicated moral universe and a less secure sense of truth. Movies
as diverse as ``Hilary and Jackie,'' ``Affliction,'' ``The Sweet
Hereafter,'' ``Eve's Bayou,'' ``Lone Star,'' and ``The English
Patient'' all present a world in which conventional notions of
morality are eventually set on their head. These, of course, are
all ``art films,'' as they're called, and reach an audience much
smaller than that for blockbusters. It may be, though, that their
growing popularity represents a dissatisfaction with the Hollywood
worldview, just as the president's approval ratings reflect a
rejection of the moralism practiced by independent counsel Kenneth
Starr, lead impeachment manager Henry Hyde, and political columnist
David Broder.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, ``Hilary and Jackie,'' the film about musician
Jacqueline du Pre and her sister, plays provocatively with the
audience's notion of truth and morality. When Jackie tells Hilary
she wants to sleep with Hilary's husband, the woman sitting behind
me in the theater gasped ``What a monster!'' and then tsk'd her way
through the rest of the section of the film that tells the story
from Hilary's point of view. But the movie moves on to a segment in
which we go back and live many of the same events from the
cellist's perspective. We may still balk at the menage a trois, but
no longer do Jackie's actions seem the jealous, vengeful acts of a
monstrous woman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ambiguity on TV
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One finds that same kind of moral ambiguity in many of the best
television programs. One of the trademarks of ``Homicide,'' for
example, is its ability to upset the good-guy/bad-guy underpinnings
of most police shows. On the other hand, ``The X-Files,'' for all
its brooding mystery, makes a point of saying that the world is not
ambiguous _ that ``the truth is out there.'' One only need decode
the conspiracy, much as the House managers believe that they have
decoded Clinton's conspiracy to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   No one upsets this kind of absolutism as deftly as novelist
Russell Banks, and that goes for the two fine films based on his
books, ``The Sweet Hereafter'' (1997) and the new ``Affliction.''
The video release of ``The Sweet Hereafter,'' like the movie's
original posters, uses the slogan ``There's no such thing as the
simple truth.'' Speaking like one of the House impeachment
managers, the lawyer played by Ian Holm says, ``It's now up to me
to ensure the moral responsibility in this country'' in the wake of
a bus accident that took the lives of several children in a small
town. And sounding like a member of the public polled about the
president, a member of the community replies skeptically, ``You
want us to believe you know what's best for us?''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Affliction,'' Nick Nolte's character becomes convinced,
like Agent Mulder of ``The X-Files,'' that a vast conspiracy has
taken over the town and that he, through his moral authority as
sheriff, is going to bring the perpetrators to justice. (Skip the
next sentence if you don't want to know the outcome.) Ultimately,
his conspiracy theory is only half true; the other half is a
symptom of his psychological unraveling.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most haunting movies of recent years have dealt with
the issue of relative vs. absolute truth _ in fact, they derive
their power from showing us the ``truth'' from a variety of
perspectives. In ``Eve's Bayou,'' for example, we think that the
attempted rape of the daughter is what precipitated a family
tragedy, but when we see it from the father's perspective, it's the
daughter who did the seducing. (Shades of Bill and Monica.)
Finally, when a psychic demands to hold the girl's hands, it turns
out that father and daughter kissed simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hatred of relativism
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Devices like this are as old as ``Rashomon,'' but their
acceptance as standard elements of storytelling signals a widening
acceptance of a relativistic morality that drives absolutists on
the left and right bonkers. The hatred of relativism is one of the
reasons Republicans despise much of the art subsidized by the NEA
and that ardent feminists boycott Woody Allen movies.
</P>
<P>
   The same values, though, have crept into the mainstream. Take a
look at ``A Civil Action.'' In a traditional Hollywood movie, the
attorney played by John Travolta would have gone through a moral
transformation, from greedy, bottom-feeding lawyer to champion of
the underdog. But under Steve Zaillian's skillful direction, we're
never quite sure what's motivating this character _ doing the right
thing or playing power games with the legal opponent played by
Robert Duvall. As Travolta himself has explained, the lawyer
himself doesn't know. David E. Kelley has mined this motherlode of
ambiguity on his television legal shows: ``L.A. Law,'' ``Ally
McBeal,'' and ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' gets under one's skin by undermining the
John Wayne-Gary Cooper legacy of World War II as a noble war and
making it as horrific as Vietnam became in the films of Stanley
Kubrick, Michael Cimino, and Oliver Stone. (Alas, ``Ryan'' director
Steven Spielberg backed away from that nightmarish vision in the
easy transcendence of the movie's second half, when it becomes a
celebration of Wayne-like absolutism.)
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, at least those in the House and Senate, seem to be
the last group in America to refuse to accept a complicated moral
landscape. Another, to judge by the best new TV program of the
year, is the Mafia. The head of ``The Sopranos,'' Tony, is no
Michael Corleone. Felled by fainting spells brought on by anxiety
attacks, he's driven to a psychiatrist. Bitterly he laments,
``Whatever happened to Gary Cooper?'' _ Coop never had to worry
about breaking into tears or worrying about the effects of ``a
formidable maternal presence'' in his life. Tony longs for the good
old days, when a code of silence kept gangsters from ratting to the
police; ``nowadays people have no values.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony's lament, meant to be ironic, is mirrored by those who long
for more absolutist days. Cold warrior novelist Tom Clancy recently
complained to USA Weekend (presumably without an ounce of irony)
about the shift from Cooper/Reagan to Travolta/Clinton: ``There are
250 million people whom your decisions will affect _ you better
have a strong sense of what's right and what's wrong.
Unfortunately, we live in a country where that's no longer the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right that it's no longer the case. He's wrong about why.
Most Americans have decided that truth is elusive, particularly in
matters amorous, and that they don't need Tom Clancy, Cokie
Roberts, or Ken Starr to tell them right from wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 1417EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6274 &Cx1f; tth-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-BENEFITS-SPI &LR;      02-08 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-BENEFITS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIANS ON THE BRINK OF REDEFINING `SPOUSAL' BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty-one years have passed since Canada's justice minister,
Pierre Elliott Trudeau, gave a bit of a start to his staid country
by telling a conference, ``The state has no place in the bedrooms
of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The remark helped propel Trudeau into the prime minister's
office. It also heralded criminal-code revisions that removed
penalties against private sexual acts between consenting adults.
</P>
<P>
   Canada is at the brink of making another startling move, one
that many religious conservatives have furiously resisted in the
United States. Federal Cabinet ministers have said the Canadian
government will act to erase all legal differences between
homosexual and heterosexual couples.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Minister Anne McClellan recently announced that the
government will not appeal the so-called Rosenberg ruling, a 1998
court decision in Ontario that ordered that ``spouse'' be redefined
to include gay partners in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   British Columbia already has acted along the same lines for the
province's 225,000 public employees. Last year, it passed
legislation that added same-sex partners to the list of people who
can be designated recipients of pension benefits. In the early
1990s, the city of Vancouver adopted a same-sex benefit policies
for its employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the first, and we've done two very significant
things,'' said the Rev. Tim Stevenson, a United Church of Canada
minister who represents downtown Vancouver in the B.C. Legislature.
He also is gay and in a long-term relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first was to change the definition of spouse to include
same-sex couples. They are treated the same as heterosexual married
couples and common-law couples who have been together for at least
two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1998, we extended pensions to same-sex couples in the
public service, anyone who in any way works for the provincial
government or crown (government-owned) corporations. We want
private companies to take similar action of their own accord, so we
don't have to bring in legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   In British Columbia, the pension legislation was supported not
only by the ruling, left-leaning New Democratic Party, but also by
a majority of opposition legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's Liberal Party has a majority in Parliament, and
likewise can count on some lawmakers from other parties if it
redefines ``spouse'' and extends pension benefits to same-sex
couples.
</P>
<P>
   But Prime Minister Jean Chretien has hesitated, even after his
Cabinet ministers announced the change. Chretien said he did not
know whether more legislation would be required.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's hesitation may relate to Canada's most
outspoken conservative prelate, Vancouver's Catholic Archbishop
Adam Exner.
</P>
<P>
   Exner was vociferous in condemning British Columbia's
redefinition of spouse. He raised the specter of ``special rights''
being extended to homosexuals, and claimed that a same-sex couple
cannot be considered married because ``biologically, such couples
are not equipped to be husband and wife.'' The archbishop warned
that Catholics, to whom he referred as ``our people,'' would make
their voices heard ``when election time comes about.''
</P>
<P>
   Exner took a similar strong position in a Jan. 27 letter to
Chretien. Speaking for Canada's Catholic hierarchy, he wrote: ``We
are deeply concerned that equating homosexual partners with married
and common-law couples could lead to a redefinition of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely the government can think of a way to respond to the
legal challenges it faces from same-sex partners without redefining
terms that millions of Canadians cherish and undermining an
institution that plays a pivotal role in society.''
</P>
<P>
   Exner has also come up with an alternative. Instead of
same-gender couples, he suggested that pension and social benefits
be granted to anyone in a long-term, caring relationship _ such as
elderly siblings caring for each other.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop is supported by such groups as the Langley,
B.C.-based Citizens Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Its executive director, Kari Simpson, has stumped British
Columbia with a pro-family message reminiscent of the Christian
Coalition in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that the Canadian way is to let courts rule the
country,'' Simpson said. ``It brings political correctness to a new
height.''
</P>
<P>
   But other major religious groups have taken a different stand.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the United Church, the Anglican Church and the Canadian
Jewish Congress strongly backed the Canadian government when it
outlawed discrimination against gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The same groups have lined up behind giving social benefits to
same-sex couples. Vancouver's Anglican Bishop Michael Ingham told
the Vancouver Sun that the traditional, heterosexual family is not
threatened by society's decision to recognize a variety of
``long-term relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People's attitudes have changed in our society, and are far
more accepting of equality for gays and lesbians,'' said Stevenson,
the United Church of Christ minister from Vancouver. ``We don't
have the extreme religious right you have to deal with in the
states.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
