<HEADER>
A6317 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     02-08 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Feb. 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HERBAL MEDICINE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a 2{-page package of stories on the
increased popularity of herbal medicine.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HERBS (Undated) _ Herbal medicine, the mainstay of
therapeutics for centuries before modern purified drugs relegated
it to the status of near-quackery, has in the last five years
emerged from the fringes of health care with an astonishing
flourish and now shows clear signs of joining the medical
mainstream. Despite many cautionary tales about adulterated and
even dangerous products, herbs formulated as capsules, tinctures,
extracts and teas _ and increasingly as additions to common foods
like potato chips and fruit drinks _ are now routinely used by a
third of American adults seeking to enhance their health or
alleviate their illnesses. By Jane E. Brody. (3000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: Experts
warn that an ill-informed foray into the ever-expanding world of
botanical medicines can end up causing more problems it they
solves. By Jane E. Brody. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HERBS-DRUGS (Undated) _ Patients often lose out when a
prescription drug also is available as a supplement. Insurance
companies frequently refuse to pay for such prescriptions because
the same thing is available for sometimes a tenth of the cost. The
problem for consumers is that because supplements are unregulated,
there's no way short of chemical analysis to determine if the
substance actually contains what the label says it does. And,
that's a serious problem for people who rely on the treatment for
potentially lethal diseases. By Gina Kolata. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HERBS-FOOD (Undated) _ Dozens of foods are landing on the
market to capitalize on America's soaring enthusiasm for herbal
remedies. No longer content with fortifying products with vitamins
or minerals, food companies are starting to add herb-based
substances that purport to offer particular health benefits,
benefits that in some cases have not yet been proven. At the same
time, companies are reaching to redefine existing foods _ oatmeal
is one _ in terms of their health benefits. By Constance L. Hays.
(1750 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER SCIENCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COSMOS (Chicago) _ In a kind of summit conference on the
universe, the world's leading cosmologists have assessed their
theories and pronounced them healthy, saying that a wealth of new
research that at first seemed puzzling turns out to strengthen the
intellectual framework that has shaped decades of cosmological
debate. The astonishing discovery last year that the universe's
expansion is not slowing down, as assumed, but seems to be speeding
up jolted theorists of the Big Bang, whose theory for the explosive
beginning and expanding evolution of the universe had ``lived
dangerously for 30 years,'' as Sir Martin Rees of Cambridge
University in England put it. By John Noble Wilford. (2500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MATH-CRANKS (Undated) _ With nothing more than a pencil and
paper, and maybe a compass and straight edge, even an amateur can
explore the mathematical netherworld, stumbling across important
new truths. That, anyway, is the dream or obsession that drives
would-be Ramanujans all over the world to send mathematicians
letter after letter crammed full of diagrams and equations
promising answers to unsolved problems ranging from squaring the
circle or proving (in a simpler way) Fermat's Last Theorem to
revealing, through the wonders of mathematics, the meaning of life.
And some of these cranks, on first impression, turn out to be
geniuses. By George Johnson. (1990 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EMBRYO-CELLS (Undated) _ Six years ago, scientists in Canada
published a remarkable paper. In it, they reported that they had
grown entire mice from individual cells that they had plucked from
an mouse embryo. At the time, it was seen by those in the small
world of mouse researchers as a technological tour de force. But
now, as scientists are eyeing human embryo cells as material for
research, the experiment is giving rise to a thorny philosophical
question. If you can grow a mouse from a single embryo cell, you
should, in theory, be able to grow a human from a single human
embryo cell. And if you can grow a human from a single embryo cell,
is that cell the moral equivalent of an entire embryo? Where, in
other words, does the potential for human life lie? By Gina Kolata.
(1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEPAL-LOVE (Undated) _ In an isolated village in Nepal
ancient traditions are changing, foremost among them, the ritual of
courtship. Young people now are writing love letters _ for a
reason. The practice of parental matchmaking is being abandoned,
and in its place come love letter that reach out to grab the
future. By Erica Goode. (1370 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PLANET-PLUTO (Undated) _ A rose by any other name would
smell as sweet, and Pluto by any other name (``Minor Planet No.
10,000,'' for instance,) would still be a no-account little dot in
the sky you can't see without a good telescope. But in recent weeks
astronomers have been partially agog over rumors that planetary
cataloguers were plotting to send Pluto back down to the minor
leagues. By Malcolm Browne. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on science: leaded gasoline
and trash dumps, solar winds and the Bering Strait land bridge.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-PLAY (Undated) _ The concept of exercise as recess
for adults is coming to fitness clubs, which are now are organized
classes at which participants do jumping jacks while playing
``Simon Says,'' jump on a mini-trampoline or go hopscotching
through hula hoops. By Malia McKinnon. (635 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Short items on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ A study shows many people cheat on the blood pressure readings
they take on themselves and turn over to their doctors. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Car surfing is a dangerous game in which participants stand on
top of moving vehicles and pretend to surf or hook onto the backs
of cars, trucks or buses while rollerblading, skateboarding or
sliding on ice. It is not all that common but very deadly,
according to a report published in this month's issue of the Annals
of Emergency Medicine. (250 wors)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-READING (Undated) _ The best approaches to teaching children
reading vary based on the needs and level of the child, according
to recent studies. Children whose vocabulary skills are already
fairly advanced benefit more when an adult reads the pages and
poses questions afterward. Less advanced children benefit more when
the narrative is interrupted for discussion. By Erica Goode. (400
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STROKE-TREATMENT (Undated) _ The window of opportunity for
treating stroke patients with clot-busting drugs has been doubled,
from three hours to six hours, without significantly raising the
risk of hemorrhage, according to a Cleveland Clinic study of the
enzyme prourokinase. By John O'Neil. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: How do
archeologists estimate past populations?
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin American points:
contact Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX:
310-996-0089).
</P>
