<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6333 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-SURVEILLANCE-HN     02-08 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SURVEILLANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FIGHTING CRIME, THE EYES HAVE IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When frustrated residents of ``The Hilltop''
neighborhood approached the police in Tacoma, Wash., about
installing video cameras to deter crime, ``we resisted it,''
Officer David Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   But neighborhood activists persevered: In 1992, they got a
$150,000 state grant and pressured the police into accepting it.
Soon seven cameras were mounted in plain view on utility poles.
``Almost immediately, calls from The Hilltop, where we had an
outrageous homicide rate, went down by half,'' Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of video camera surveillance of streets, subway systems
and parks has taken hold. More than 50 police departments operate
such systems. Elsewhere, cameras are mounted at key intersections
to catch red-light runners.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how many surveillance and security cameras
there are, but Richard Chace, spokesman for the Security Industry
Association, regards a figure of 2 million as a conservative
estimate. Indeed, in Manhattan alone more than 2,400 cameras record
the behavior of people in public places, according to a recent
survey by the New York Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   As public safety trumps privacy in the hierarchy of priorities,
civil libertarians express dismay. Even the secrecy-conscious
security equipment industry is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward relying on cameras instead of officers to deter
crime and catch crooks ``is the antithesis of community policing,''
said John Crew, an attorney with the American Civil Liberties Union
of Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said the intrusiveness of video cameras and growing
affordability of surveillance technology should force a
re-examination of the old slogan that there is no expectation of
privacy in a public place. Since people can now be photographed by
a camera that can read small print from a mile away, people ``need
to start thinking about where we want to draw the zone of
privacy,'' Crew said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the explosive growth of the video surveillance business
in the 1990s, ``there is no coherent public policy on the use of
this important crime-fighting tool,'' said Chace, whose Security
Industry Association represents 360 companies around the world that
make or distribute security equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great technology, it's there and the industry isn't
going to stop (selling) it, but it's getting a little out of
hand,'' Chace acknowledged. Consequently, the association has
scheduled an ``industry summit'' April 8-9 in Washington, D.C., to
develop protocols with input from law enforcement and civil
libertarians.
</P>
<P>
   James Dempsey of the Center for Democracy and Privacy in New
York said his organization sees ``a rising swell of public concern
about privacy generally, which is translating into legislative
concern. I think that (the industry's) self-regulatory efforts are
in many cases likely to be succeeded by legislative efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Video surveillance systems were first installed in the United
States in the early 1970s to assist in traffic management and deter
bank robbers. In the hands of civic-minded amateurs, the video
camera has proved a useful law enforcement tool. In 1991, one
caught the police beating Rodney King in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the trend, the City Council in Oakland, Calif., killed a
proposed video surveillance pilot project in September 1997 after
the Police Department dropped its support.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no conclusive way to establish that the presence of
video surveillance cameras (results) in the prevention or reduction
of crime,'' Oakland Police Chief Joseph Samuels said.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Police Chief Fred Lau said that although the
cameras ``can be good tools if properly used, they present a lot of
First Amendment concerns. Something of this magnitude would have to
go through a widespread hearing process. For the department to
become involved in one of these programs, the community would have
to be interested, and that's a big if.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns have not stopped Pinole, Calif., a community of
18,000. Forty cameras oversee streets and parking lots in the
Police Department's surveillance network, which started at one
senior center across from a park that had a chronic crime problem.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, cameras have been installed in the new Pinole Vista
shopping center, and in the town's redevelopment areas. Still, no
cameras look over residential streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had groups that say they want the system in our
neighborhoods, but we've resisted that because of privacy issues,''
said Pinole police Lt. John Minor.
</P>
<P>
   As for the effectiveness of the cameras, Minor said: ``The
deterrent effect is a hard animal to track down with any
quantitative measure. But our feeling is that with all the
publicity the system's been getting, the crime has been less than
in other comparable areas. Our incidence of drunkenness and
disorderly conduct and assaults are down in that park. People know
the camera is there and they go elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it may be hard to demonstrate the deterrent effect of
video cameras, people believe the devices work. Security 2020, a
company in Nashville, Tenn., that makes an imitation security
camera for $39, reports that business is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people use one real one and 10 fake ones,'' Security
2020 President Ron Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the real thing is cheaper than hiring more police officers
or security guards.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore, which reaped national publicity in 1996 with its
``Video Patrol'' program covering the city's high-crime area,
doubled the program's size recently, turning on the cameras along
Charles Street in the heart of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The cost? Just $80,000, said Richard Cross, spokesman for the
Downtown Partnership, an entity of merchants, a foundation and the
city police and public works departments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
