<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERSONAL-RECORDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LICENSES MAY BUY MORE THAN THE RIGHT TO DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ An Atlanta credit rating company knows if your
eyes are blue or if you need corrective lenses. It also knows when
to send a birthday card.
</P>
<P>
   A similar company in Allen, Texas, knows a lot about the
snowmobiles, motorcycles or boats you own and where you might park
them.
</P>
<P>
   And a Southfield, Mich., auto research firm knows enough about
your buying habits to remind you that the latest model of your
favorite car is about to roll out.
</P>
<P>
   These companies, and thousands more, also may know your date of
birth, address and other personal information New Yorkers provide
on vehicle registration and drivers license applications.
</P>
<P>
   They are among more than 3,500 firms and organizations paying
$49 million to the New York Department of Motor Vehicles each year
for such data. In many cases, the information is shared with
marketing companies, credit providers and insurers and then perhaps
resold.
</P>
<P>
   DMV possesses information from 10.5 million licenses and 10
million vehicle registrations.
</P>
<P>
   All of the registration data is sold in bulk to the highest
bidders. Two such bidders paid about $1.8 million this year
combined for a year's worth of information.
</P>
<P>
   One of the bidders, R.L. Polk, paid $3.2 million to get car
registrations during a two-year period from the state. The Michigan
company collects statistics about the number of cars and trucks
Americans buy each year and sells its research to car dealers and
manufacturers who use it for recalls and sales marketing.
</P>
<P>
   James Miller, a Polk spokesman, said the company finds out
enough about brand-loyal customers it can say ``the last two
vehicles you bought.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, since 1989, registrants could check a box to opt
out of having their address provided for marketing purposes. About
23 percent do so, according to DMV officials.
</P>
<P>
   Some states don't allow the motor vehicle information to be sold
at all and others _ about a dozen _ only allow aggregate data about
registrations to be sold without names and addresses of
registrants.
</P>
<P>
   New York's license data, sold only on a case-by-case basis at $4
a record, is provided to some 3,500 different companies. The
biggest customers are insurance companies, credit reporting
companies, car rental agencies and driver employment services.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest purchasers are Choice Point, an Atlanta credit
rating bureau, and the Insurance Information Exchange of College
Station, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Enterprise Rent-A-Car, Avis, National and Hertz all are top-10
customers, as is State Farm Insurance. Private investigation
companies, insurance agencies, banks, newspaper companies and
charities also purchase the lists.
</P>
<P>
   The individual sales of registration, license and title records,
total about $46 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We treat this information as if everyone has said they don't
want the information released and only the people with permissible
uses get that information,'' said Jennifer Post, a DMV spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   She and other DMV officials said they make sure their bulk sales
customers are eligible according to federal laws created to
frustrate stalkers. The law contains a list of permissible
customers for the state data and DMV applies that list to its
non-bulk sales. The list allows use by marketers.
</P>
<P>
   License information, however, is considered public information
and the state tries to control its dissemination by requiring
companies to make individual requests.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Freeman, chairman of the Committee on Open Government,
said that it is important to keep information open on all state
licenses so that a licensee's qualifications can be checked.
</P>
<P>
   ``DMV is doing what it can to provide the broadest possible
access within the framework of the law,'' he said. ``There's a
thousand good reasons to keep it public.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the controls, the license data released provides users
the information individuals share with DMV and more: address,
height, eye color, restrictions, defensive driver course
information, and violation records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the state's discretion to sell the database information
or not,'' said Linda Lewis, a spokeswoman for the American
Association of Motor Vehicle Administrators. ``Some do, some don't
... This is a revenue generator.''
</P>
<P>
   DMV revenues might have climbed by another $1 million a year or
more had a proposal to sell drivers license images panned out.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after objections were raised by Sen. Joseph Bruno,
R-Brunswick, the photo sales idea was dropped by Gov. George
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration considered selling license pictures of
people who requested the photos be provided to credit card
companies as a security feature.
</P>
<P>
   Image Data, a New Hampshire company that markets a system to
prevent check and bank fraud, has been attempting to contract for
photos with other states. Those contracts have become the subject
of controversy in South Carolina, Colorado and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``If state agencies are already releasing personal information
without our consent, we must put a stop to it,'' Bruno said when he
heard about the photo sales proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
