r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWO-FACED-JORDAN-FUNE     02-08 2029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWO-FACED-JORDAN-FUNERAL-550&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO JORDANS BURIED KING HUSSEIN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This TIMELY, provocative ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at
1-816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS THREE USER-FRIENDLY OPTIONAL TRIMS: AT 550 (150 WORDS), AT
975 (275 WORDS), AND AT 1,500 (250 WORDS). TOTAL UNCUT VERSION RUNS
1,750 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN _ Two Jordans buried their king Monday.
</P>
<P>
   There was the formal, westernized nation with its Scottish-style
bagpipers and new, English-accented monarch who invited the world's
statesmen to bury the ``fallen warrior'' on his polished gun
carriage, Hussein's Arab steed _ empty boots reversed in the
stirrups _ clopping obediently behind the coffin.
</P>
<P>
   And what the world saw _ indeed, what the world was supposed to
see _ was the adoration of kings, presidents, prime ministers and
princes: Clinton, Bush, Blair, Assad, Yeltsin, Chirac, Charles,
Shamir, Netanyahu, Mubarak, Weizman, Arafat, Sharon, Carter,
Ford... After all, was this not the man whom the American president
had already consigned to paradise?
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the other Jordan. Outside the gate, sweating and
shrieking to God, smashed back by gun butts, sworn at by the
descendants of Glubb Pasha's Arab Legion as they clawed their way
towards King Hussein's coffin, the other Jordan didn't quite fit in
with the pageantry on the other side of the palace wall.
</P>
<P>
   When the Jordanians broke through the troops and charged in
their thousands towards the gates, they were confronted by hundreds
more armed soldiers. ``In the name of God, help me,'' an old woman
moaned as the crowd stamped her into the mud.
</P>
<P>
   So which was the real Jordan? Was it the nation enshrined just
above the marble floor of the Rhagadan Palace, where the coffin of
the king was honored, prayed to, watched and nodded at by all the
dangerous, untrustworthy allies who had variously loved, hated or
plotted against him?
</P>
<P>
   Such sincerity, such affection they all showed Monday. There was
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who sent his killer
squad into Jordan only a few months ago to assassinate a Hamas
official, bowing stiffly before the coffin.
</P>
<P>
   There was American ex-President George Bush who just eight years
ago regarded Hussein as little more than an enemy agent.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, whose gunmen once sought to
destroy Hussein's kingdom, snapped to attention in his olive
fatigues and kuffiah scarf, twice saluting the flag-draped wooden
box in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   And behind the coffin, scarcely moving, was the studied, often
frowning face of King Abdullah the Second and his two
half-brothers, Crown Prince Hamzeh and Prince Hashem.
</P>
<P>
   They stood there, hands out in prayer from time to time, all
dressed in immaculate suits and ties and all wearing the same kind
of checkered red-and-white kuffiah as Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   It was if they were acting out some kind of unusual ritual, more
like English public schoolboys in an unfamiliar play than Arab
warrior princes, trying to cut a dash among the tall men of the old
Arab Legion _ Hussein renamed them the Jordan Arab Army after he
dismissed Glubb _ who guarded the coffin and its royal standard.
</P>
<P>
   Vulnerable was the word that came to mind. The princes didn't
look old enough or hard enough or cynical enough to handle the
sleek men who passed before them to honor their father.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them gentlemen, others venal dictators, quite a few with
an awful lot of blood on their hands, the harmless and the harmful
one after the other, they paraded before the coffin as if waiting
for group passport pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Carter and Ford and Bush. Snap. Prince Charles and
Blair and Ashdown and Hague. Snap. Netanyahu and Sharon and Barak.
Snap. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 150 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 550) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I suppose it wasn't surprising that history was being rewritten
for the watching world. On the satellite television channels, the
dead king was being eulogized as the man who freely made peace with
Israel, whose country was praised _ this from CNN _ because it was
now closer to Israel than to many Arab states.
</P>
<P>
   So forget what the king once privately called the ``manacles''
of the Oslo agreement _ which forced Jordan into an unpopular peace
treaty with Israel _ and remember what President Clinton told us on
Sunday: that King Hussein is now in paradise. Which is where we
were told Egyptian President Anwar Sadat had gone after his death _
that being the destiny, it seems, of all Arab leaders who make
peace with Israel at our behest. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for the crowds, whose voices could be heard baying beyond the
palace gates by the beautifully-groomed kings and presidents
inside, they had somewhat different ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they loved the king, some of them. But there was less
enthusiasm for Abdullah and much less for Prince Hamzeh, Hussein's
son by his last wife, the half-American Queen Noor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamzeh was chosen as new crown prince by the United States,''
a girl insisted. She was a Palestinian Jordanian.
</P>
<P>
   Rubbish, I snorted. You shouldn't believe in the ``moammarer,''
the plot, I told her. But then, an hour later, I saw the full list
of dignitaries at the palace and was struck by the list of State
Department men, the boys from the Washington ``peacemaking''
department led by Martin Indyk _ former head of the largest Israeli
lobby group and the man who somehow couldn't manage to persuade
Netanyahu to stop building Jewish settlements on Arab land but
insists that Arafat must ``crack down on terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   So was the real Jordan, then, among the swaying mass of
shabbily-dressed, shouting youth on the highway to the royal
palace, many of them poorly educated, some of them pathetically
adorned with crinkled pictures of the dead king glued to their
shirts and scarves?
</P>
<P>
   If Jordan has a 90 percent literacy rate _ thanks, of course, to
the late king _ then I had come across an oddly unrepresentative
sample of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   They were peasant families, many of them, the old women's faces
covered in tattoos, the men sitting quietly on blankets under the
trees alongside the palace road. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 275 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 975) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But when the king's coffin approached, a kind of ripple, half
sound and half movement, spread through the lines of tired, somehow
broken faces, as if a stone had been thrown into a human pond.
</P>
<P>
   There was no signal from them in advance, no instruction or
indication save perhaps for a line of children who suddenly moved
from the trees into the road. Then en masse the people swarmed
towards the coffin and its jeep-loads of head-scarved Jordanian
troops, tears streaming down their faces, hands outstretched to
touch, even to seize the flag or perhaps the coffin itself.
</P>
<P>
   I remember thinking, before a panicking soldier struck two men
with his rifle and punched me in the chest as the crowd fell on us
that it was like throwing petrol onto a kitchen stove.
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange, frightening kind of hysteria because it
combined both love and fury in almost exactly equal measure,
intense loyalty married to absolute rage.
</P>
<P>
   When I rolled over, I found the soldier lying beside me and
helped him to his feet. He shrugged as the crowd surged past him,
shouldered his rifle and walked after them in resignation.
</P>
<P>
   At the Teheran funeral of Ayatollah Khomeini, the crowds pulled
their Imam's body to the road and tore at his shroud. And if the
Arab Legion's descendants had not shouted in the name of their dead
king, and if the other soldiers had not laid into the first of the
young Jordanians who tried to clamber onto the carriage, it might
have happened in Amman, too. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Violence is portrayed so differently when its progenitors are
behind palace walls.
</P>
<P>
   How, one wondered, did the mass outside feel about the large
presence of Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon in front of their
king's coffin, the very man who sent Israel's Lebanese Phalangist
allies into the Sabra and Chatila Palestinian refugee camps in 1982
to ``hunt down terrorists,'' militiamen who then proceeded to
murder _ Serb-style _ hundreds of Palestinian civilians?
</P>
<P>
   What did they think of the presence of Liamine Zeroual, the
outgoing president of Algeria whose security forces _ in their
battle against ``Islamic'' killers _ have been accused of
systematic torture of men and women?
</P>
<P>
   What did they make of the arrival of President Hafez Assad of
Syria, who ordered his soldiers to ``eliminate'' an Islamic
uprising at Hama in 1982, an operation that left the dead in their
thousands?
</P>
<P>
   Or of former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres, another of
Clinton's ``champions of peace,'' whose 1996 offensive against
Lebanon culminated in the Israeli massacre of 106 Lebanese
civilians in a U.N. camp at Qana?
</P>
<P>
   In every case, the victims had been Muslims, just as they had in
the war unleashed by the one man who most astonished the world by
turning up in Amman Monday and who may soon end up in a state
similar to the late King Hussein: Boris Yeltsin, whose butchery in
Chechnya is rarely mentioned in the West, waved to the cameras _ I
am alive, I am alive, he was trying to tell us _ and walked
falteringly into the palace. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 1,500. 250-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   There were a few intriguing moments. Clinton paused to talk
briefly to Assad before the Syrian leader took a car to the palace
mosque rather that walk behind the coffin with the others. He
didn't want, I suppose, to be seen with Sharon and Netanyahu and
Shamir.
</P>
<P>
   But few outside saw more than a glassed-over vision of the men
who rule the world.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the pavement by a motorway bridge, the people of the
al-Nuzhah area of Amman just caught the briefest of glimpses of
Clinton's shock of grey hair in the back of a black limousine,
Arafat's frozen, sick features, a gaggle of robed Saudis in their
racing Mercedes, Prince Charles staring straight ahead as if
studying the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Al Nuzhah had sat there for hours after leaving
their concrete homes and their scruffy streets of mud and litter.
</P>
<P>
   Now all this is to be Abdullah's, his father's inheritance and
his father's victory.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein created a nation out of a country and left it with a
peace treaty that binds its people forever to Israel and America.
For the poor, frightening crowds outside the palace gates Monday,
it seemed a chilling embrace.
</P>
<P>
   What the old king had done could not be undone. Peace, it was
called. And inside the palace walls, Hussein's favorite white
stallion ``Amr'' briefly reared up on her hind legs behind the
coffin. As a mark of respect, it was said, she would never be
ridden again. &QL; 
