<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VULTURES-AMMAN-750&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VULTURES HOVER OVER WEAKENED JORDAN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This TIMELY, excellent ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at
1-816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A 275-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 750; TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS
1,150 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By PATRICK COCKBURN  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN _ As the solemn procession of world leaders walked past
the body of King Hussein Monday, many of them must have remembered
they had attended a similar ceremony sixty miles away across the
Jordan River in Jerusalem just three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is an ominous precedent. In 1995 it was King Hussein himself
who was among the leading mourners to stand by the coffin of
Yitzhak Rabin, the assassinated Israeli prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Monday it was his turn to receive the same florid tributes from
President Clinton and the leaders of half the world as a
``visionary and peacemaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Television correspondents spoke piously of Jordan, as they had
of Israel, as ``a nation in mourning.''
</P>
<P>
   One Jordanian, noting the parallel between the two funerals,
said nervously that he hoped King Hussein's political legacy would
last longer than Rabin's.
</P>
<P>
   Six months after the death of their leader, Israelis chose
Benjamin Netanyahu, a man whom Rabin detested, to be their prime
minister. They voted even more decisively for a parliament which
opposed the peace terms with the Palestinians signed by Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   People in Jordan were flattered by the sight of President
Clinton and three former U.S. presidents arriving for the king's
funeral followed by Boris Yeltsin, the Russian president and the
leaders of half the world.
</P>
<P>
   They also noticed that in one of the most politically turbulent
regions of the world there was no threat to their safety. ``It is a
problem of logistics, not security,'' said one Jordanian official.
</P>
<P>
   In the longer term, however, Jordanians have an acute sense of
the vulnerability of their country.
</P>
<P>
   Though the television cameras zoomed in immediately on mourners
in tears as they lined the streets, the real mood of Jordan is of
anxiety about their future as much as grief for the dead king.
</P>
<P>
   Jordanians understand that King Hussein never had much room to
maneuver. He ruled a small country surrounded by more powerful
neighbors. Nobody knew this better than himself.
</P>
<P>
   He was once asked why he had grown a beard. He replied: ``I grew
it because it is one of the few decisions I can take without having
to ask somebody else if it is OK to go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   His ceaseless diplomatic activity was at bottom a sign of
weakness. He needed to insert himself into every problem in the
Middle East, win for Jordan an influence it could not command
through its own strength and prevent his country from becoming the
victim of events it could not control.
</P>
<P>
   His dilemma was the same as that of Yasser Arafat, though the
king escaped the Palestinian leader's reputation for
untrustworthiness.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man ever had many political cards in his hand. Both
balanced uneasily between the needs of their own people and the
demands of outside powers. Both switched alliances repeatedly. They
cultivated the U.S. but tried to avoid becoming its pawn. Neither
was entirely successful.
</P>
<P>
   The king balanced between Arab nationalism and the need to
conciliate Israel and keep Washington friendly. It was ultimately a
defensive policy. He could not afford to take too many risks.
</P>
<P>
   He needed to ensure that Jordan was not cut out of negotiations
between Israel and the Palestinians, but not to the point where
Palestinians thought he was presenting himself as their sole
leader.
</P>
<P>
   King Hussein's ambivalent policies were not only the result of
the ever-present threats facing Jordan from Israel, Iraq, Syria and
Saudi Arabia. The country itself is a buffer state created by
Britain after the First World War. Some 60 percent of its
population is of Palestinian origin.
</P>
<P>
   A survey carried out by the Center for Strategic Studies at the
University of Jordan several years ago shows that Palestinians
resent the control of most government jobs and all sensitive
military and security posts by citizens of Jordanian origin.
</P>
<P>
   They believe they are under-represented in the cabinet and
parliament and that the bureaucracy discriminates against them.
</P>
<P>
   For their part Jordanians resent Palestinian control of private
business. They fear more Palestinian refugees entering the country;
some 350,000 Palestinians expelled from Kuwait came to Jordan in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   They see Palestinians with Jordanian citizenship as ungrateful
and having dual loyalty to Jordan and the Palestinian leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In Jordan every change in its complicated relations with its
neighbors has the potential to create a crisis at home between the
two main groups in the country. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (275-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a further problem. Television commentary Monday
stressed that King Hussein was much loved by his people. This is
true. But the commentators forbore to mention that the king's
popularity in Jordan was at its peak in 1991 when he maintained a
friendly neutrality towards Saddam Hussein and Iraq during the Gulf
war. Official policy and the popular mood were for once at one.
Democratization was at its height.
</P>
<P>
   It could not last. Jordan was diplomatically isolated.
Then-President George Bush would not even see his old friend King
Hussein. James Baker, the U.S. secretary of state, told the king:
``It's a tough row to hoe to repair Jordan's relationship with the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact it was repaired more quickly than he thought. The U.S.
needed Jordan to deal with Israel and the Palestinians. Jordan
moved back into U.S.-Israeli orbit.
</P>
<P>
   King Hussein signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994. A year
later he broke definitively with Saddam Hussein. He felt, rightly,
that he had no choice. But neither move was popular at home. The
treaty with Israel was commonly called ``the king's peace'' and
seen as an Arab defeat.
</P>
<P>
   An anti-Iraqi and pro-Israeli policy abroad meant less tolerance
of dissent at home. The king responded to riots in 1989 in the
Jordanian heartland in the south of the country by granting greater
freedom of expression and more democracy.
</P>
<P>
   From the mid-1990s these policies went into reverse. In the last
two years a stringent press law and government ownership of part of
the media has meant that Jordanians once again turn to foreign
radios and television for their information. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF 275-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   King Hussein could get away with veering between democracy and
repression, mild though it was by regional standards, because
Jordanians believed at heart that he knew what he was about.
</P>
<P>
   He was personally moderate and skillful at conciliating enemies.
It is by no means clear that King Abdullah, his army officer eldest
son and successor, will have such leeway with Jordanians or
Palestinians to conduct such an unpopular foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan sees itself as surrounded by vultures with those from
Israel and Iraq considered the most predatory. Monday they were on
their best behavior, but both are quick to sense political weakness
and equally merciless in exploiting it. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
