<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6379 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HUSSEIN-0209-     02-08 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HUSSEIN-0209-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH HUSSEIN'S DEATH, CLINTON'S LOSES A 'PARTNER' FOR PEACE
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 700 words.
 &HT;    With HUSSEIN-FUNERAL-0209.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Last October, with his efforts to broker an
Israeli-Palestinian peace accord ''about to come apart,'' at a
remote retreat on Maryland's eastern shore, President Clinton
summoned Jordan's King Hussein from his Mayo Clinic sickbed to help
rescue the flagging talks.
</P>
<P>
   Late on a frosty night, his once-sturdy frame left gaunt by the
ravages of a disease that would soon take his life, the ailing
monarch strode into a large dining room where weary negotiators
were picking at plates of fish and veal.
</P>
<P>
   There, Hussein delivered an impassioned plea, summing up with
persuasive eloquence both the challenges and the imperatives for
peace, and helping to prod Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat the last grudging
inches toward what became the Wye River accords.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the icy atmosphere of those tense talks would immediately
disappear when Hussein walk in the room,'' Clinton recalled on
Monday. ''It was almost as if the more frail his body became, the
more powerful the essence of his spirit was.''
</P>
<P>
   During six years of on-again off-again efforts to end half a
century of enmity and bloodshed in the Middle East, Clinton has
known no more steadfast a companion in the peace process than King
Hussein, whose remains were laid to rest here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Never was that partnership more needed, Clinton said, than
during those difficult days last October, when Hussein offered to
lend his assistance to keeping the negotiations alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, 'Well, I would be willing to come down there if you
think it would help,''' Clinton recalled to a group of U.S. Embassy
personnel here Monday night. ''I said, 'If I think it would help?
This whole thing is about to come apart. Of course it would
help.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the peace process stalled and lurching toward a
potentially disastrous May 4 deadline for the resolution of a
thorny set of outstanding issues between Palestinians and Israelis,
the White House is contemplating the absence of a man National
Security Adviser Samuel E. Berger called, ''the transcendent voice
for war and peace in the Middle East over the past several years.''
</P>
<P>
   One year after Arafat and Yitzhak Rabin, then-prime minister of
Israel, signed their historic peace agreement on the White House
lawn in 1993, Hussein came to the White House to ink Jordan's own
peace treaty with Israel -- a bold move that embittered some of
both his Arab neighbors and his own loyal subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, he has stood by Clinton's efforts to advance peace
eforts ever since, always available by telephone or in person to
provide the advice or diplomatic aid of a polished and widely
revered senior Arab statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein's own long career, after all, depended upon a precision
act of balance between the interests of his U.S. allies, his Arab
neighbors and the Palestinians who make up the majority of Jordan's
4.4 million populous.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the peace process must survive Hussein's death, as
it has outlived other pioneers for peace in the region, such as
former Egyptian President Anwar Sadat and Rabin, both of whom were
assassinated by zealous countrymen who opposed the risks each man
took to make peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've lost other towering figures in this peace process,''
Berger said. ''But the process has gone forward ... this is a
region that can ultimately make progress only if there is peace.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hussein's son, King Abdullah, assumed power over the weekend,
Clinton moved quickly to try to shore up the 37-year-old monarch's
position. He announced that he would work with Congress to
accelerate the $300 million -- over three years -- in economic aid
promised to Jordan as part of the Wye accords.
</P>
<P>
   That's in addition to the $225 million in economic and military
aid the United States is to provide Jordan this year, and an equal
amount Clinton has asked Congress for in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said he would back increased development aid to
Jordan from the World Bank and expanded economic support from its
sister institution, the International Monetary Fund -- more
recognition of the importance he continues to attach to Jordan's
role in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jordan remains a major part of the equation in how we will get
to a comprehensive peace in the Middle East,'' said National
Security Council spokesman P.J. Crowley. ''Its links with Israel,
its ability to expand trade with Israel, that will be critical to
providing the economic incentive for all of the parties to learn
that they really have no alternative but to live in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   That message faces new tests in the weeks ahead. Under the 1993
Oslo accords, Israelis and Palestinians agreed to complete, by May
4 of this year, negotiations on a final, comprehensive peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Such talks would center on some of the most difficult
outstanding issues, including Palestinian statehood and the future
of Jerusalem, parts of which are claimed by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Those negotiations haven't even begun in earnest, however, and
even the Wye accords -- essentially an agreement by Israel to
withdraw troops from parts of the occupied West Bank and turn over
territory to Palestinian control in exchange for Palestinian
security guarantees -- have been frozen since December amid a
political crisis in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   With Israeli parliamentary elections scheduled for May 17, the
situation is stalled. There's no prospect for meeting the Oslo
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has threatened to unilaterally declare a Palestinian
state on May 4 -- with or without a comprehensive peace pact -- and
Israel has said such a move could spark war.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief meeting in Washington last week, Clinton urged
Arafat to be patient in the face of Israeli political ferment.
Privately, U.S. diplomats have their fingers crossed that Arafat
has embraced that message.
</P>
<P>
   As a final tribute to the life and work of King Hussein, the
three surviving principals of the Wye River accords -- Clinton,
Arafat and Netanyahu -- were on hand here Monday when the late
monarch's body was laid to rest.
</P>
<P>
   With the White House caught in the middle, once again, of the
region's enduring strife, observers say Hussein's passing is, for
Clinton, one more Mideast burden to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
