<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ House prosecutors and White House
lawyers make final pitches to the Senate in President Clinton's
impeachment trial amid signs that the chief executive may escape
censure by the Senate. Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.,
concedes uphill battle to overcome threatened GOP filibuster
against censure resolution. By STEWART M. POWELL, JUDY HOLLAND And
JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CENSURE (Washington) _ With 60 votes needed to cut off a
threatened filibuster led by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, Democrats
would have to recruit about 20 Republicans for a censure resolution
to prevail. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-FUNERAL (Amman, Jordan) _ As King Hussein's body was
buried in the royal cemetery, the low wail of verses sung by the
royal imam mixed with the overhead roar of Jordanian air force
jets. Outside the palace grounds filled with family and world
leaders, the streets were crowded with mourners who arrived before
dawn, from towns and villages and Bedouin tents in the desert. By
DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HUSSEIN (Amman, Jordan) _ President Clinton joins an
international cast of mourners at the funeral of King Hussein, then
sees a few fellow leaders privately in sideline meetings. By NANCY
MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-CONSERVATION (San Vicente del Caguan, Colombia) _ After
a night of fishing, Nilson Rojas' skiff was filled with bass and
catfish. ``Two years ago, you couldn't catch anything,'' he says.
``But since they imposed the new rules, you can catch enough to
make a living.'' Rojas was referring to environmental decrees by
Colombia's largest Marxist guerrilla group, which has banned
fishing with explosives, unfettered logging and hunting endangered
animals. Their conservation crusade appears to be paying off. By
JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-GANGS (Undated) _ Three prison inmates have been given
life sentences for their role in the murder of a 20-year-old
prisoner at the Terrell Unit in Livingston, Texas. The beating and
stabbing of Ryan Osgood in October 1997 was the result of a feud
between rival white supremacist gangs. Trial dates have not been
set for the six other inmates accused in the attack. By ALLAN
TURNER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Houston) _ For those who run a business from home,
there are steps that can be taken to increase the chances of
getting individual disability insurance, protection that is tough
to buy. By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The polls indicate the Republicans
may be hurt by the impeachment charade in the year 2000 elections.
But public memory is short. Can the Democrats keep the rumpus alive
by denouncing the GOP as the party of intolerant snoops and the
Republicans neutralize their image by calling the Democrats the
party of immorality? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ For the first time in nine months, the
Houston Rockets will take the court at Compaq Center for a real,
live NBA game in Monday night's home opener against the Denver
Nuggets. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
