<HEADER>
A6395 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HERBS-FOODS-2TAKE     02-08 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HERBS-FOODS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT JUST FOOD, BUT HEALTH IN A BOTTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., Ill.)   (af)  
 (Eds: The (asterisk) in ad should be replaced by the symbol)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They look an awful lot like 15-ounce cans of soup. With labels
like ``Chicken Broth and Noodles With Echinacea'' and ``Creamy
Split Pea With St. John's Wort,'' and instructions to ``Heat 'N
Serve,'' what else would they be? But no. The label says: This is a
``Kitchen Prescription Herbal Supplement,'' not a soup.
</P>
<P>
   The soup-style supplements, made by the Hain Food Group of
Uniondale, N.Y., are among dozens of foods, or foodlike products,
landing on the market to capitalize on America's soaring enthusiasm
for herbal remedies.
</P>
<P>
   No longer content with fortifying products with vitamins or
minerals, food companies are starting to add herb-based substances
that purport to offer particular health benefits, benefits that in
some cases have not been proved. Companies also are reaching to
redefine older foods _ even foods as humdrum as ketchup _ in terms
of their health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers can become confused because such products often fall
into a gray area created by a 1994 federal law governing the
labeling and sale of dietary supplements.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Kitchen Prescription'' was being marketed as a food with a
new additive or a new drug, the Food and Drug Administration could
require Hain to provide a raft of studies before the product got on
the market or put forth any claim of boosting health.
</P>
<P>
   But under the 1994 law, the FDA cannot restrict a dietary
supplement unless the agency receives complaints of harm. As a
result, many companies are deciding to market such products as
supplements, taking their chances with the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   Food companies regard ``functional foods'' _ those that offer
some highlighted health benefit, affecting disease or mood _ as
their biggest opportunity to increase sales since the fat-free
movement of the early 1990s. For an industry that over the last
decade has slogged along, growing just 5 percent in a good year,
the functional-foods business looks especially promising.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was anything that could add a needed dose of growth
to the food industry, this is it,'' said John M. McMillin, a food
analyst for Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   While some experts voice concern about too much St. John's Wort
or calcium's getting into the food supply, others say such
overexposure is unlikely. ``If people consume these foods in
reasonable quantities, then safety is not the issue,'' said Dr.
Maureen Storey, a faculty fellow and assistant research professor
at Georgetown University's Center for Food and Nutrition Policy.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers have started to see a variety of interpretations,
ranging from older foods repackaged with claims on labels, to foods
with substances like herbal extracts added. Herbs like St. John's
Wort, touted as a mild anti-depressant, and ginkgo, advertised as
aiding memory, are turning up in cereals, soups and snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Companies see the interest in herbal medicine as a new way to
sell old products. ``They see it as product positioning,'' said
Clare Hasler, executive director of the functional foods for health
program at the University of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies will use ingredients based on the kinds of claims
they can make,'' said Scott Bass, a lawyer with Sidley &AMP; Austin in
Washington who helped write the 1994 Dietary Supplement Health and
Education Act. ``They will look for claims and then find the
ingredients, not vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say the FDA has lagged behind the surge in interest in such
foods, which began in earnest about two years ago. The subject is
not specifically addressed in regulations, although certain
substances acceptable in dietary supplements do not meet government
standards for food additives, which must be ``generally recognized
as safe.'' What is left is a large area of uncertainty, into which
companies are launching products like trial balloons.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has strict regulations governing ``health claims,''
specific claims about a food or ingredient's ability to prevent or
affect disease. Companies are less eager to make health claims,
which require elaborate research and clinical trials to prove.
</P>
<P>
   But some say the FDA has not been specific enough about what
constitutes a ``structure-function claim,'' which purports to
influence certain functions, like those of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   A food that claimed to prevent heart disease would be making a
health claim; one that said it could lower cholesterol, which
affects heart function, could be making either a health claim or a
structure-function claim. Any health claim would require extensive
studies to support it. But for a structure-function claim, the
requirements would be less certain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The FDA is in the middle of sorting out what's the difference
between a structure claim and a health claim,'' said Steven L. Ink,
director of nutrition for the Quaker Oats Company in Chicago,
which, after a two-year process, got permission to use a health
claim on its oatmeal labels last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Grocery Manufacturers of America, a trade group, has made
clarifying the functional-food definition a priority, said Brian
Sansoni, a spokesman. The group is trying to stop the FDA from
adding regulations, fearing more cost and delay. ``We don't want
them to put functional foods in a special box with special
regulations, because it would be way too difficult for companies to
bring their products to the market,'' Sansoni said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, many companies are taking the easier path of marketing
foods as dietary supplements. ``They need to fit into the
established categories, and people are pushing them into the
dietary-supplement rules,'' Dr. Hasler said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that are not specific to the drug or natural-food
business have noticed consumer interest in functional foods. In
1997, Campbell Soup Co. introduced a mail-order line of frozen
foods said to combat high blood pressure, high cholesterol and
diabetes, called Intelligent Quisine.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell dropped the line last year after a brief test period
suggested it would not be profitable. H.J. Heinz unveiled an
advertising campaign last month that discusses the benefits of
lycopene, an anti-oxidant found in processed tomatoes, in
``reducing the risk of prostate and cervical cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass and others note that the Dietary Supplement Health and
Education Act steered around regulating foods, because the FDA has
historically been strict about the food supply, fearing the
possible dire side effects of ``overfortification.'' But that
concept has been overridden, he says, by changes in the ways and
reasons people eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the days of the fortification law, in 1972, the thinking
was that people eat for nutrition, and that's not why people eat
anymore,'' Bass said. ``People eat because they want to get
nutrition and also want to prevent ill health and stay out of
managed-care hospitals, which is what functional foods are all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Without better definition of functional foods, the gate is open
for loose interpretations under the supplement law, which was not
its intent. ``It's not valid to have a box of cereal that says
`Dietary Supplement,' '' Bass said.
</P>
<P>
   At Hain, the decision to market supplement soup was made with an
awareness that the supplement law did not cover foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very cautious in our label preparation to follow the
rules as closely as we could,'' said Myron Cooper, the company's
chief researcher and head of product development. ``I'm not saying
that in the eyes of the FDA we are right. We are putting these
supplements into products that are regularly consumed by people on
a moderate basis. There are other people putting it into candies
and snacks, and the FDA is concerned about overconsumption.''
</P>
<P>
   The label says ``Support your immune system(asterick) with a cup
of Kitchen Prescription today!'' The asterisk leads to this
postscript: ``This statement has not been evaluated by the Food and
Drug Administration. This product is not intended to diagnose,
treat, cure or prevent any disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The Quaker Oats Co.'s experience illustrates the financial
impact a health claim can have. In order to jump-start its
hot-cereal business, Quaker executives decided in 1995 to invest
the time and money required to get the FDA's approval for claiming
that its oatmeal contained nutrients that could lower cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   The process included compiling research and sponsoring human
clinical trials. By 1997, the company had been cleared to add the
cholesterol-lowering claim _ the first specific one the FDA had
approved _ to its packaging, Ink of Quaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Quaker hot-cereal sales had declined in 1994 and 1995. In 1996,
with news of the health benefits circulating, sales rose 5 percent,
he said. The next year, with the claim on the package, sales rose
another 6 percent to 7 percent, he said. ``For a very mature
business, that was a pretty nice gain,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
