<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHEELCHAIR-BANDIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEELCHAIR-BOUND MAN HELD IN THREE ROBBERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They call him the Wheelchair Bandit, a
paraplegic and ex-convict accused of three Chinatown robberies in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But to Cuong Vinh Tran, the nickname and the notoriety are
nothing to brag about. He said he was innocent and his arrest was
more damning than any conviction or jail time he might face.
</P>
<P>
   Tran is a convicted felon and former gang member who took a
bullet in his back during a 1991 shootout with a rival gang. But
the Vietnamese refugee gets misty-eyed when he talks about his
elderly mother and the shame his publicized arrest has brought to
his family.
</P>
<P>
   In Asian culture, he said, bringing shame to the family name is
the ultimate crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I disgraced my family and disgraced my mom,'' Tran, 27,
said at the San Francisco County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   His arms and neck are covered with tattoos, some of them
insignias from gang days. The long sleeves of his jailhouse orange
sweat shirt conceal them. But there is no covering the most
prominent one, on his left thumb: MOM.
</P>
<P>
   Since his arrest on Feb. 1, Tran said, his biggest concern has
been his mother, and how worried she must be. ``I don't have the
face or guts to call her right now,'' he said in a jailhouse
interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tran denies that he is the Wheelchair Bandit. But according to
police reports, two victims have identified him from a photo spread
of six young Asian men sporting thin mustaches like his. The third
set of victims, a couple, would not cooperate with the police.
</P>
<P>
   In one of these incidents, on Jan. 26, the bandit brandished a
black semi-automatic handgun, the police said. In the other two
cases, on Jan. 20 and Feb. 1, he warned his victims that he was
going to shoot them.
</P>
<P>
   In all three robberies, the police said, the suspect approached
and fled in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   All of the victims were Chinese, and the bandit spoke to them in
Cantonese.
</P>
<P>
   Two victims described the suspect as speaking with a Vietnamese
accent. It is the same description a victim gave in 1997, according
to a police report at that time, when Tran was arrested and pleaded
guilty to robbing a man of $300 in Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   In that crime, the suspect was driving a car, and had robbed a
pedestrian he had motioned to his window. Tran said he didn't
commit that crime either, but copped a plea for a shortened jail
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Tran served eight months in jail for the 1997 robbery, and got
out on Dec. 6, he said. Since then, he has been staying with his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Tran was a member of the Wah Ching, a Chinese street gang, and
later, the Viet Ching, an offshoot made up of young Vietnamese,
said Inspector Wayne Hom of the San Francisco Gang Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   Hom, who has been with the Gang Task Force since 1980, remembers
when Tran was a gang member.
</P>
<P>
   Tran was a follower, Hom said, a foot soldier who would
dutifully take orders but was neither ambitious enough nor ruthless
enough to be a leader.
</P>
<P>
   Tran stayed with the gang until he was 20. He quit the day he
was shot, on Aug. 29, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During a fight with a rival gang, he was shot in the back. The
bullet from the .44-caliber Magnum shattered his spine and pierced
his kidney and colon. For a month he was in the hospital near
death, Tran said, battling infections and high fevers.
</P>
<P>
   When he regained consciousness, he learned he was paralyzed in
both legs and had received a colostomy.
</P>
<P>
   His father was sick with worry _ and anger. He died two years
ago of cancer. Tran is certain that he is the malignancy that
killed his father.
</P>
<P>
   But his mother was always understanding, Tran said. She loved
him, no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting, he tried to stay out of trouble. But it was
hard, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although paralyzed, Tran said he still has gruesome pain in his
legs. He said he's taken crack cocaine to soothe the pain and
forget his troubles. He had to quit the habit in jail, but as soon
as he got out, he couldn't stay away.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they found a crack pipe in his wheelchair when
he was arrested Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Tran said friends help him pay for the crack, that he didn't
need to rob people. The three robberies by the Wheelchair Bandit
were not lucrative: $17, $10, $8, and a silver necklace worth $20.
In one of the holdups, the bandit only asked for $10 to get some
food, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Tran had pledged to his mother to stay off the streets and off
the drugs once he got out of jail, but he couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sweet-talk her when I'm in jail. Then I come home, I don't
follow her rules,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in a wheelchair, with no high school diploma and no job
skills, he couldn't stay home and do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I just stay home, I just go crazy,'' said Tran, who added
that he would like to become an auto mechanic.
</P>
</TEXT>
