<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-PORNOGRAPHY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORN BECOMES TOPIC A IN BAPTIST SUNDAY SCHOOL CLASSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An X-rated Sunday school lesson? Not exactly. But Southern
Baptists have been talking about the ``secret sin'' of pornography
in their Sunday school classes nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   A Sunday school lesson on ``How to Reject Pornography'' for
young adults and those older says that many church members _
particularly men _ are consumers of pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize pornography is an issue facing society. And given
the number of users of pornography, we know people in the church
use it, too,'' Ross McLaren of Nashville, a Baptist biblical
studies specialist, said last week. ``Even children have access to
it now, through the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren quotes a finding from U.S. News &AMP; World Report that 41
percent of men and 16 percent of women purchase erotic materials
each year. He also cites James Lambert's ``Porn in America,''
published in 1997 by Huntington House, which says that pornography
is an $8 billion-a-year business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since men are 90-95 percent of the users of porn ... the
church needs to recognize that many men in our congregations have
the same problems with porn that many outside the church have,''
Lambert wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Pornography is a bigger problem than most people think, the
Sunday school lesson contends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pornography is no longer a back-street industry limited to
inner-city bookstores or sleazy movie theaters,'' it declares. ``It
is available in your local video store, at the convenience store in
your community and on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson adds: ``Some may still think of porn as the `girlie
magazine' they discovered in junior high school. Others may feel
that pornography is OK if not viewed by children. Still others may
view pornography as harmless entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Pornography does seem to be more available to those who don't
normally visit bookstores specializing in erotic materials.
Advertisements for porn sites are showing up on E-mails in the
workplace. People are worried about children calling up
pornographic offerings on home computers.
</P>
<P>
   But discussing pornography in Sunday school?
</P>
<P>
   ``We had teachers who were not comfortable with it,'' said
McLaren, a staff member of Lifeway Resources, formerly the Southern
Baptist Sunday School Board, which published the lesson. The lesson
wasn't presented to Sunday school class embers under 18. But boys
ages 12 and 13 are frequent users of pornography, the lesson says.
</P>
<P>
   The Bible is quoted often in the lesson. One section titled
``Discipline Your Eyes'' quotes Job 31: ``I made a covenant with my
eyes not to look lustfully at a girl. ... Does he not see my ways
and count my every step.''
</P>
<P>
   Pornography is powerful, the writers note, because it builds off
a natural sexual desire.
</P>
<P>
   Baptists, as might be expected, have a broad definition of
pornography, They include so-called soft porn, such as Playboy
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Pornography, the lesson says, is ``any portrayal of the human
body or human behavior that cheapens human sexuality, condones or
encourages sexual immorality, and degrades the God-given value of
men, women and children by identifying them merely as sources of
sexual gratification.''
</P>
<P>
   The messages of pornography listed in the lesson include: ``Sex
anywhere, anytime with anybody is a good thing. Sex has no
consequences. Fidelity is boring.''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson includes an article by John E. Wolf III, a
businessman and civic leader from Oklahoma City, who says his
secret love for pornography almost wrecked his marriage. He tells
of being hooked on pornography as a child and then continuing the
habit as an adult after he became a faithful Baptist churchgoer.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf's article, titled How to Live a Porn-Free Life, says he
conquered the problem through prayer, Bible study and counseling
after his pornography obsession was discovered by his wife. He
urges others fascinated by pornography to follow the same course.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience is that pornography is one of the biggest secret
sins of the church,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
