<SLUG> BC-TUPPERWARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALES GIANT SEES TUPPERWARE AS TICKET TO A `NORMAL LIFE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There is Tupperware made out of Lexan, the same
stuff used in the windshields of fighter planes and in bullet-proof
glass.
</P>
<P>
   Tupperware is not what it used to be. Just ask Denise Lum-Kan, a
San Francisco woman who has turned her dedication to the kitchen
containers into a near-six-figure salary and two company vans _ not
to mention all the trips to headquarters in Orlando, Fla., and
visits to the Tupperware museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Tupperware gets into your blood,'' Lum-Kan said, ``it
never leaves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds toxic, but given the way the product has transformed her
life in less than three years, she said: ``With Tupperware, you can
have it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Between her Tupperware demonstration skills, her charm, her good
looks and her obvious dedication to the product, it was no surprise
that the company picked her to star in its first infomercial.
</P>
<P>
   Lum-Kan's meteoric rise to Tupperware Goddess began innocently
enough. Always a hustler, she was taking business classes at San
Francisco State University while running her own enterprises. She
decided to host a Tupperware party _ the hostess gets a free set
worth maybe $50 _ and once things were organized, jokingly asked
her Tupperware connection what she was making on Lum-Kan's $300
worth of sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she would make $100, and I realized I was in the
wrong end of the business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With that, she became a ``consultant,'' helping three friends to
host parties while she pocketed more of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I just figured I would take the money and run,''
she admitted. ``I was still running my other businesses and had no
idea that Tupperware was going to be my ticket out of the rat
race.''
</P>
<P>
   She progressively climbed the ladder _ Tupperware promotion is
based solely on sales and doesn't involve any kind of corporate
approval. Move the goods and move up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great. You don't have to wait for someone to die or
retire to get ahead. That's one of the things I like about it the
most,'' Lum-Kan said.
</P>
<P>
   Before she knew it, she was named to her current position as
senior executive manager. Next, she aspires to diamond crown
manager, and the only rung left after that is an area
distributorship.
</P>
<P>
   So what is the secret to her success? Perhaps the answer comes
when Lum-Kan is asked if her own house is filled floor to ceiling
with Tupperware.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no,'' she said. ``I hardly have any at all. That's what I
always tell people, not to buy more than they will really use. If
you end up selling them a ton and they never use it, there is a
good chance they will feel resentful. This way, if they are happy,
it makes for much better word-of-mouth references.''
</P>
<P>
   Lum-Kan said the main reason she is so dedicated to the company
is the freedom it gives her. She can set her hours, there is nobody
telling her what to do, and any pressure to succeed is
self-imposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can lead a normal life. My husband and I are talking about
having kids, and I want to be a stay-at-home mom,'' she said. ``And
there are other parts of my life I've been interested in pursuing,
maybe some modeling or acting, and this gives me the time to have a
life. I really feel incredibly lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Lum-Kan even has a social theory about what she calls ``the
resurgence of Tupperware'' in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '80s people were more wrapped up in themselves, they
were more focused inward, socializing wasn't as important to
them,'' she said. ``In the '90s, people are coming back to being
sociable, so a Tupperware party is a natural extension of that.
That's what's so great about this job _ going to work is like going
to a party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
