<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6434 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-STROKE-TREATMENT-     02-08 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-STROKE-TREATMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENZYME OFFERS HOPE FOR REDUCING DEVASTATION OF STROKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The time frame for treating stroke patients with clot-busting
drugs has been doubled, from three hours to six hours, without
significantly raising the risk of hemorrhage, according to a
Cleveland Clinic study of the enzyme prourokinase.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, presented at last week's American Heart
Association stroke conference in Nashville, suggest that more
patients could benefit from treatments that could reduce or reverse
the effects of strokes as they are happening.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, most stroke victims have in theory been eligible for
treatment with another clot-dissolving drug, tissue plasminogen
activator, or TPA. Many physicians thought TPA would revolutionize
the field, but its usefulness has proven limited because it is
effective only within three hours of the stroke's onset.
</P>
<P>
   Stroke victims sometimes wait days instead of hours to report
symptoms. In Cleveland, only 19 percent of patients reach hospitals
within three hours, and researchers estimate that only 5 percent of
stroke victims in the United States are receiving the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to extend the time for using TPA have failed, and three
trials of another enzyme, streptokinase, were halted when they
appeared to be causing more deaths without any clear benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Anthony Furlan, the lead researcher in the prourokinase
study, said that those results ``had a lot of people thinking we
would never get beyond three hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Furlan's research team took a different approach with
prourokinase. They studied only patients with one of the most
serious forms of stroke, blockage of the middle cerebral artery.
Unlike TPA, which is administered intravenously, prourokinase is
injected directly into the artery in the brain close to the site of
the clot. The presence of the clot causes the prourokinase to break
down into the enzyme urokinase, which dissolves the obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was conducted at 51 medical centers nationwide. Of
12,000 stroke patients, 180 that met the study's narrow criteria
were randomly given either prourokinase or a placebo injection.
</P>
<P>
   Furlan said that subsequent tests showed that 67 percent of the
blocked arteries were cleared by the prourokinase. But the most
important measure of success in stroke treatment is recovery: 40
percent of those treated were judged to have little or no
impairment three months after their stroke compared with 25 percent
of the control group.
</P>
<P>
   The prourokinase treatments did cause slightly more hemorrhaging
than had been found with TPA, Furlan said, but no additional
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Mayberg, the chief of neurosurgery at Cleveland Clinic
and the chairman of the stroke conference, pointed out one other
limitation of prourokinase: It can be administered only in medical
centers where a type of surgeon called a neuroendovascular
specialist is on hand to insert a catheter into the brain artery.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Mayberg and Furlan said they hoped the new findings
could spur a breakthrough in stroke treatment by giving patients
and emergency medical workers stronger reasons for prompt response.
Their Cleveland survey found 27 percent of stroke victims receiving
treatment within six hours and 34 percent within 12 hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 1635EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
