<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-CONSERVATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIA'S REBELS ESPOUSE NEW CAUSE: CONSERVATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent mark needed over second a in Caqueta and a in
Bogota) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN VICENTE DEL CAGUAN, Colombia _ After a night of fishing on
the Caguan River, the bottom of Nilson Rojas' wooden skiff was
filled with smallmouth bass and a 30-pound striped catfish with
six-inch whiskers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, you couldn't catch anything,'' said Rojas, as
he gathered up his nets. ``But since they imposed the new rules,
there has been a lot more fish reproduction. You can catch enough
to make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas was referring to a series of environmental decrees by the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, Colombia's largest
Marxist guerrilla group. Since the rules took effect about two
years ago, Rojas said, the river has made a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   With forests, rivers, fish and wildlife under siege from an
expanding frontier population, many FARC fighters also act as
gun-toting park rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have banned such practices as fishing with
explosives, unfettered logging and hunting endangered animals.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are hesitant to call the rebels ``ecoguerrillas,''
because some of the FARC's own practices have caused environmental
havoc. But here in Caqueta state, a FARC stronghold in southern
Colombia, the rebels' conservation crusade is paying off, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guerrillas have played an important role. They have helped
to preserve the natural resources,'' said Octavio Garcia, forestry
engineer in this bustling, cattle-ranching town on the Caguan
River. ``They have stopped 80 percent of the illegal cutting of the
forest.''
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla's green policy apparently comes from the top.
</P>
<P>
   FARC commander Manuel ``Sure Shot'' Marulanda has lived
clandestinely in the mountains and jungles of Colombia for nearly
50 years and has turned into a nature lover, said a former
government minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure Shot is obsessed with protecting the environment. He
really feels it deep in his heart,'' the former official said. ``He
says things like: `See this river? I remember when it was clean.
Now look at it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's 35-year-old civil war and violent disputes between
peasants and large landowners have led to mass migrations to
Caqueta state and other jungle frontiers. In such remote regions,
there is scant government presence, and environmental rules are
often ignored.
</P>
<P>
   In Caqueta, such abuses led to a ``radical drop'' in the number
of animal species, said Javier Munera, director of CEUDES, a Bogota
research center.
</P>
<P>
   Poachers wiped out much of the deer population. Logging led to
erosion. Rivers filled with silt, making navigation by commercial
barges impossible much of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen dumped tick poison or tossed sticks of dynamite into
the rivers, then scooped up hundreds of dead fish. Accidents were
common.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people without arms who live down by the
river,'' said Oscar Tellez, a Roman Catholic Church worker.
</P>
<P>
   To halt the destruction, the FARC ordered people to attend
meetings to discuss the problem and encouraged the formation of
environmental associations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They try to give people a vision and an introduction to the
defense of ecosystems,'' said Miguel Angel Lopez, a city official
in San Vicente del Caguan.
</P>
<P>
   The FARC announced a ban on hunting deer, wild boar, turtles and
five other species. The rebels ordered anglers to use only lines or
small nets to catch fish.
</P>
<P>
   Violators face the possibility of huge fines. But since most
people in the area are poor, the rebels often demand community
service instead. Rojas, the fishermen, said one of his errant
neighbors was forced to carry 200 buckets of sand from the river's
edge to the construction site of an elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never disobey,'' Rojas said. The guerrillas ``are watching
the river. They are watching you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have listened to us,'' added Camilo Lopez, a FARC
spokesman in San Vicente del Caguan. ``Turtles are reappearing. In
some parts of the mountains, the deer have come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics claim that the FARC, which is holding peace talks with
the government, is more concerned with public relations than saving
the Earth. People, they say, comply with the rebels' rules mainly
out of fear.
</P>
<P>
   Leonel Narvaez, a Catholic priest, said the FARC _ which has
come under increasing criticism for financing its war through
kidnappings, extortion and taxes on drug traffickers _ is trying to
attract funds from gullible foreign environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guerrillas have realized that the environment is a good
way to bring in donations and improve their image,'' Narvaez said.
``But you can't expect military men to get involved in such serious
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the civil war has wreaked havoc on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas and right-wing paramilitary groups have carried
out massacres and offensives that have displaced thousands of
people. And though it claims to have given up the practice, the
FARC has sabotaged oil pipelines, contaminating rivers and crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to do that,'' Lopez said. ``But now our policy is
totally different.''
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's smaller rebel group, the National Liberation Army,
still targets oil pipelines nearly every week.
</P>
<P>
   But because there are only a handful of government regulators in
Caqueta, officials rely on the rebels to help promote sound
environmental practices, said Omar Garcia, mayor of San Vicente del
Caguan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is cooperation between the state and the guerrillas,''
Garcia said. ``They contribute. But not as much as they think they
do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
