<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6441 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-08 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW ON TO THE 2000 ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From the beginning to the final days of the
impeachment follies, the thinking of a majority of voters has been
consistent and clear.
</P>
<P>
   They don't like President Clinton's disreputable behavior but
they do like his policies and don't want him removed from office.
And, significantly, the majority doesn't like the intemperate glee
with which congressional Republicans have pursued him.
</P>
<P>
   The common wisdom now holds that the Republicans have shot
themselves in the foot and are so politically crippled they will
lose the 2000 presidential and congressional elections. Yet those
elections are nearly two years away. Won't voters _ notorious for
having the attention span of a spaniel _ have forgotten all this
nasty impeachment stuff by then?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Democratic candidates would be foolish to campaign
overtly against hypocritical impeachment overkill lest they seem to
be defending adultery and ignoring the impropriety of the
president's affair and attempted cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   If they bring up the name of Monica Lewinsky, they are as apt to
remind voters of a Democratic president's sexual excesses as of
self-righteous Republican partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders are already muttering about labeling their rivals as
agents of the party of immorality and sin. This could be a potent
weapon in today's tumultuous political climate, buffeted by
competing public concepts of acceptable cultural standards. The
last thing Democrats want is to be seen as ratifying sexual
harassment and lying.
</P>
<P>
   But there are underlying themes here that will influence the
coming campaigns. Questions will persist about the legitimacy of
the impeachment process, independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
inquiries and the duplicative array of congressional probes into
Democratic campaign fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are in danger of looking as though they have become
the party of intolerant snoops, not only in their drive to oust the
president but also by embracing policies that pry into private
choices about abortion, family planning, religious observance and
child-rearing.
</P>
<P>
   And the Democrats are already portraying congressional
Republicans as so consumed by right-wing plots to bring down the
president that they neglected the nation's business. The
Republicans are charged with ignoring the will of the voters, who
told pollsters in no uncertain terms they would rather hear about
Social Security than Monica.
</P>
<P>
   This approach, however, works only if the GOP devotes this year
to internecine warfare and fails to produce any substantial
legislative achievements. Dropping the interparty hostility and
compiling a record of reaching out across the aisle could wipe out
some bad memories and make everybody look good.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, however, the internal GOP battle over tax cuts _ how
large, and in what form _ has resulted in sending a confused
message, undercutting the party's traditional advantage over
Democrats on that issue. And the religious right is making
ideological demands that moderates cannot accept, forcing party
leaders to espouse strangely schizophrenic policies on such issues
as abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that while Republicans nominally control both
congressional houses, it is with the smallest House party margin in
44 years and a Senate margin that is not filibuster-proof. They can
no longer afford the arrogant strutting of the Gingrich years. It
is in everybody's interest to bury the hatchet and take up a plow.
</P>
<P>
   One sign that this may actually happen is the fresh working
relationship between Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and Minority
Leader Tom Daschle, fueled by their astonishing discovery that they
could confidentially level with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Another is that new House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert may soon
eliminate a special fund through which Gingrich financed an
unusually large number of investigations of the Clinton
administration and Democratic political allies, such as labor
unions. That is expected, among other things, to close down Rep Dan
Burton's lengthy, comic and unproductive probe of alleged White
House fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of resentment and animosity will linger between the White
House and Congress and between the two parties after the Senate
trial is finally concluded. A great deal of tidying-up is still to
be done. But a new chapter in American politics is about to unfold,
inevitably full of surprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
