u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-08 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T STAY HOME WITHOUT INSURANCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When Joyce Berger tried to buy individual disability
insurance, she ran into a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Big underwriters, including Northwestern Mutual Life Insurance
Co., rejected Berger because they didn't like the fact that she and
her husband, Allan, were running their business
communications/public relations firm from home.
</P>
<P>
   That's troubling to insurance companies because it's harder for
them to decide when a business owner is really unable to work.
</P>
<P>
   The insurers said that ``with 80 percent of our time spent in
our home office, there was no way they could be sure we were not
able to work within our own home if we claimed we were disabled,''
Allan Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies agree it's tough for home business owners to
buy protection to cover their income when they are physically
unable to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, we don't really feel comfortable selling to
people in their homes,'' said Kiah Townsend, regional sales manager
in Houston for Provident Life and Accident Insurance Co., the
largest seller of individual disability insurance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DISABILITY POLICY HARD TO GET &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Individual disability insurance is hard to get to begin with
because of the huge potential for fraud. It's hard to precisely
determine whether a person is healthy enough to earn a living. It's
also expensive because the claims are high and there are not as
many buyers, so it's harder for underwriters to spread the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disability is the most strictly underwritten insurance of all,
in general,'' said Stanley Horn, a certified financial planner at
Investors Mutual Agency in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies said there's a simple reason why they're
reluctant to sell disability coverage to self-employed people who
spend most of their work time at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you verify if someone's disabled if they never leave
the house?'' Townsend said.
</P>
<P>
   Proving this can come down to some hair-splitting details.
</P>
<P>
   The deal killer for the Bergers was their telling Northwestern
they worked only 20 percent of the time outside of their home. The
company wanted the couple to spend close to 75 percent of the time
outside their office.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Northwestern Mutual) also told us that if our office were in
our garage as a stand-alone building, or if we had to leave the
non-office part of our home and have to walk around the house in
order to go into our home office through a dedicated outside door,
we would have qualified,'' Allan Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern Mutual officials said that was correct.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers are known for often making absurd character judgments
of people based on the most esoteric of details. But the
self-employed are the last people you have to motivate to work
because their economic survival depends on their ability to drum up
business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INCREASE THE CHANCES OF COVERAGE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you run your business from home, there are steps you can take
to increase your chances of getting individual disability
insurance:
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep a detailed log of how much time you spend out of your
home office visiting clients. List names of clients, their company
and the purpose of the visit. That would enable you to prove to an
insurance company that you don't spend most of your time in your
home office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more information you can give them, the better off you
are,'' said Anne Day, an insurance broker who specializes in
disability insurance at the Shaw Co. in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep impeccable business records. Especially important are
contracts that you've signed with clients to show insurance
companies that you have a viable business going and that you have
income to verify.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're just starting your business, put together a detailed
business plan. State your goals for the business and how your work
experience will enable you to reach them. You want to show
stability.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consider putting your home office in an area detached from
your house, or look at leasing an office near your home.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make efforts to visit your clients more often.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shop for more limited disability coverage. For example,
Provident's 475 disability policy covers only accidents and not
illness. To get sickness coverage, you would have to pay extra for
an endorsement on the policy that would cover cancer, stroke or
heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tap trade groups and associations in your field, which often
offer group disability insurance plans.
</P>
<P>
   What you don't want to do is to go without disability insurance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 1646EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
