<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6447 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     02-08 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS DENNIS HASTERT'S BIG OPPORTUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let us all wish the best for Dennis Hastert, the new speaker of
the U.S. House of Representatives. He may have taken on the biggest
challenge in Washington today. This 57-year-old former teacher and
restaurateur from Illinois has been handed, quite suddenly, the
daunting task of directing that bitterly divided and increasingly
unmanageable institution.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has said he wants to restore a friendlier atmosphere in
the House and is willing to work with Democratic leaders toward
this end. Hooray! There are further reports that he is moving away
from one particularly onerous practice attributed to his
predecessor. Newt Gingrich, while speaker, is said to have given
arbitrary political fund-raising goals to House committee chairmen
with jurisdiction over taxes and other matters vital to big
business lobbying interests. If these reports be true, Hastert's
decision is worthy of applause.
</P>
<P>
   There must be absolutely no nexus, real or implied, connecting
public policy responsibilities with campaign contributions, unless
we're prepared to sacrifice even the pretense of being a government
of, by and for the people. Both parties have skated dangerously
near the edge. It's time that someone in authority blew the
whistle. If Hastert has done that, my hat is off to him.
</P>
<P>
   For the good of the country, I want to see Dennis Hastert
succeed as a fair and effective speaker. And I know from experience
some of the sand traps along the fairways.
</P>
<P>
   My advice, for what it's worth, would be to divorce himself
entirely from the partisan quarrels and petty intrigues that have
so disgusted the public during the past two years, both intra-party
and inter-party. Abandon the goal of trying to ``get'' President
Clinton. It's polarizing and counterproductive and helps nobody.
</P>
<P>
   Concentrate instead _ and immediately, I'd advise _ on three or
four carefully chosen legislative goals that fill important needs,
enjoy public backing and can command bipartisan support. Solicit
the cooperation of House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt in
appointing bipartisan task forces, and let Democrats share some
responsibility in drafting and planning these initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   That advice is not really new. But its actual implementation
would be new _ or at least so old that it would seem new.
</P>
<P>
   High above the speaker's dais in the House chamber is a
prominent plaque with these words by Daniel Webster: ``Let us
develop the resources of our land, call forth its powers, build up
its institutions, promote all its great interests and see whether
we also in our day and generation may not perform something worthy
to be remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Webster's ancient admonition be a useful guide for the new
speaker? It might, if undertaken without undue jockeying over who
gets credit. Let the House itself have credit. There are, among
Congress's mound of unfinished business, several national goals
that fit Webster's description.
</P>
<P>
   Those that develop our resources, whether natural or human,
would seem likely candidates for a venture into bipartisanship. In
years past, the interstate highway program and the clean-up of our
streams were roundly embraced by both parties. The first was a
brainchild of President Eisenhower, the second a creation of
Democratic lawmakers. Both parties had a hand in the draftsmanship
of each, and everyone claimed paternity.
</P>
<P>
   There've been a few recent instances _ like welfare reform,
decentralizing government and balancing the budget _ in which
Clinton initiatives co-opted Republican rhetoric. What, except an
obstinate disinclination to see one's political opposition get some
of the credit for a good thing, is to keep Hastert's party now from
sponsoring legislation that carries out such current Democratic
battle cries as improving public education? Or salvaging Social
Security? Or strengthening our infrastructure?
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the speaker needs to change the focus, if he can,
from the shrill denunciations of the recent past. It's in his own
party's interest, as well as the nation's, to do so.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy. Never in modern times has the House been so
angrily divided along sharp-edged partisan lines. Nor has a
majority party had such a razor-thin margin, vulnerable to a
defection of only six votes on any issue. I cannot recall such
deep-seated outrage on either side as each feels now over perceived
unfairness by the other. Or such an apparently insatiable thirst
among members for personal revenge against one another.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this the public backlash against the House itself over
its handling of impeachment, which two-thirds of all Americans
apparently opposed. That this happened in December before the new
speaker was installed is in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   The way to surmount these destructive fixations is by making a
convincing demonstration that Congress can put all that behind it
and produce an agenda of positive, substantive legislation. This is
the speaker's primary responsibility _ and his present opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert begins with a few advantages. He enjoys the respect of
his colleagues, including many Democrats. Although sufficiently
orthodox to satisfy the GOP's conservative wing, he hasn't pursued
personal vendettas against other colleagues or engaged in
mean-spirited harangues. He has expressed a willingness to work
with House Democrats and did not glower and grimace at Clinton
during the State of the Union address. So he starts with a fairly
clean slate. But symbolism goes only so far. Now the public is
demanding substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Develop the resources of our land,'' advised Webster. The
speaker's task, it seems to me, is to show that the House, though
riven by fracticidal hatreds, can work together this year to
``perform something worthy to be remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 1650EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
