<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALENTINE-CYNIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CYNIC'S GUIDE TO VALENTINE'S DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every cynic knows that Valentine's Day is merely a merchandising
campaign run by, to paraphrase the Peanuts characters, a big
eastern syndicate. That doesn't mean that cynics can't find ways to
celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   _ MAKE YOUR OWN ANTI-LOVE-SONG TAPE. For starters, we recommend
ABC's sarcastic ``Valentine's Day''; David Gilmour's ``All Lovers
Are Deranged''; Devo's ``Love Without Anger''; the Who's ``How Many
Friends Have I Really Got''; and Joe Jackson's ``Is She Really
Going Out With Him?''
</P>
<P>
   _ RENT AN ANTI-ROMANTIC MOVIE. You can't beat 1989's dark
divorce comedy ``The War of the Roses.'' Also good: ``In the
Company of Men,'' Neil LaBute's 1997 movie about a misogynistic
duo, and 1994's acid-etched comedy ``The Ref,'' although its ending
might be too happy for a true cynic.
</P>
<P>
   _ MAKE YOUR CYNICISM WORK FOR YOU. SendWine.com
(www.sendwine.com) is sponsoring a Great Valentine's Disaster
Contest. The rules and how to enter are on the Web site, but the
gist is: Send in a brief description of your worst Valentine's Day
experiences, and you're eligible for a Valentine's Day weekend next
year at the Meadowood Resort in Mount Helena, Calif. We know, you
can think of all sorts of reasons this won't work, but try it
anyway. You might even be able to narrow it down to one bad
experience.
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 1650EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6450 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HALBERSTAM-JORDAN-200     02-08 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALBERSTAM-JORDAN-2000(4Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR JOURNALIST DAVID HALBERSTAM, MICHAEL JORDAN IS JUST THE LATEST
SLAM DUNK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In print, he's ferocious. From the Kennedy/Johnson
best and brightest to the head-in-the-sand leaders of the U.S. auto
industry, too many powerful people to count have been skewered in
print by David Halberstam. Bestselling books and Pulitzer
Prize-winning magazine and newspaper stories decorate Halberstam's
resume like still-dripping scalps.
</P>
<P>
   But at home in his New York City apartment, decked out in white
shirt and dark slacks and the color of pink sweater that gets men
beaten up in biker bars, Halberstam is a 64-year-old pussycat. His
latest book, ``Playing for Keeps: Michael Jordan and the World He
Made'' (Random House, $24.95), has received rapturous reviews and
will top bestseller lists beginning Sunday. At this point in his
storied career, Halberstam can approach any publisher with book
ideas on any subject and walk away with a seven-figure advance.
</P>
<P>
   So on a recent Thursday afternoon he's financially secure, he's
famous and he's really, really sorry that the apartment's kitchen
is being renovated and coffee can't be offered.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years _ ``The Best and the Brightest,'' his first
blockbuster, hit store shelves and ruined political reputations in
1972 _ Halberstam has earned a reputation as a grouch, probably
because he disdains uninformed questions from interviewers who
don't share his dedication to exhaustive research. But on this day
there's been a new, glowing review of ``Playing for Keeps'' in USA
Today. According to its critic, the greatest compliment to Michael
Jordan would be calling him ``the David Halberstam of basketball.''
Despite so much previous acclaim, Halberstam seems delighted by
this latest gush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more fun than ever,'' he admits, leading the way into a
cluttered study and sweeping unopened mail, CD cases and crumpled
faxes off a battered couch so visitors can sit down. Halberstam
himself plops down into a well-worn chair; he sits in it so often
there are slight indentions on the armrests where he places his
elbows. Whatever negative attributes Halberstam may have,
pretension isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, what do you want to talk about?'' he asks, and the
afternoon stretches into a long conversational ramble. Having
interviewed so many people himself, Halberstam has mastered the art
of expressing himself colorfully and completely. It's fun to
listen.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Halberstam dislikes Robert McNamara, TV pundits and
self-obsessed journalists, probably in that order. When his outrage
with the Vietnam War boiled over from newsprint into ``The Best and
the Brightest,'' McNamara emerged as the book's great villain.
Halberstam never could reconcile the war he witnessed as a foreign
correspondent with the one relayed to the public by the man who was
secretary of defense for John Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm his Darth Vader,'' Halberstam says. ``I won't go away. He
was a liar, he's still a liar and I track him. Diane Sawyer put him
on TV and he cried. I guess that was good TV. Now when he talks
about the war he says, `We couldn't get information.' I document
how he had all the information he needed. He just didn't want to
hear it. For political reasons, he was willing to slay anybody in
his way. But this is an unusual case for me. I don't know anyone
else I feel this way about.''
</P>
<P>
   He uses ``The Best and the Brightest'' to illustrate his writing
philosophy. ``Every nonfiction book should be written to answer a
question, and the question in `The Best and the Brightest' was
this,'' Halberstam says, furrowing his brow. ``The Kennedy
advisers, who went on to serve Johnson, were ostensibly the ablest
group ever to serve in American government. But Vietnam was the
greatest American tragedy since the Civil War. How could that
happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam's answer was that McNamara, Dean Rusk and company
simply considered Asians inferior to Americans. Without paying
sufficient attention to history, they underestimated North
Vietnam's resolve to win the war at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam was already unpopular with the Johnson administration
for his stinging newspaper stories in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnson even called me a traitor to my country,'' Halberstam
says, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   In the decades since, Halberstam has written about many famous,
influential people, often to their detriment. He claims no
animosity toward anyone but McNamara.
</P>
<P>
   And the TV ``talking heads.'' He despises them, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned down chances to get on TV as a commentator,'' he
says. ``I don't want one of those TV minds like the Powder River, a
mile wide and an inch deep. People with superegos, the ones who
think they are the story, are the ones on TV. Look at Sam
Donaldson, calling attention to himself all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for writing books in the first person; Halberstam
believes the very best journalists, the best writers, try most of
the time to avoid using the word ``I.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I used the phrase `this writer' twice when I
absolutely had to,'' he growls, ``but journalists as people
themselves are usually not interesting. You have never seen and
heard as much as you think you have.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a sunny afternoon, and the rays cast shadows around
Halberstam's nose and mouth. When he talks, though, you
automatically watch his bushy eyebrows. They're in constant motion:
up, down, seemingly sideways. Halberstam is never still. His hands
wave, his voice rises and falls. He CARES.
</P>
<P>
   This may be what makes his books so special. Halberstam brings
his readers into real-life scenes so thoroughly that the actual
sense of reading is lost. Instead, we are there, right inside the
boardrooms and on the playing fields and behind closed doors in the
Oval Office. No journalist is better at including the small,
telling details than Halberstam. In ``Playing for Keeps,'' one
glittering paragraph about Michael Jordan teaching himself to play
pingpong tells us more about Jordan's unhealthy competitiveness
than dozens of other complete books by lesser writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything might be important,'' Halberstam explains. ``You've
got to take the time to look.''
</P>
<P>
   And he does. It's rare for a new Halberstam title to appear more
often than once every three or four years. It takes time, he says,
to do the job right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liken it to graduate school,'' Halberstam says. ``Someone
else goes to grad school for four or five years and leaves as a
doctor or lawyer. I concentrate on some subject for the same amount
of time and at the end of it I have another book. It is a constant
learning process. You have to be curious. You can't assume you
already know everything about your subject. If you pretend to be an
instant expert, you cheat your readers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon moves on. Halberstam, enjoying himself, makes a
couple of calls to postpone appointments. He feels like talking
about his roots. The son of a doctor and a second-grade teacher,
Halberstam always intended to become a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   World events, and the way they were reported, served as topics
of discussion at the Halberstam dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalists like (Edward R.) Murrow were heroes in our home,''
Halberstam notes, rocking back and forth in his chair. ``So that
was my plan, to write like them and eventually take the next step
to writing books.''
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, Halberstam developed new writing heroes. John
Gunther and Theodore White were writing important books about
Africa and China, not heeding the conventional '40s and '50s
mainstream journalism that avoided placing blame on elected
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy White had guts,'' Halberstam says. ``I loved the fact he
left Time magazine when the editors screwed around with him, that
he went out on his own and wrote great books like `Thunder Out of
China' and `The Making of the President 1960.' He wrote books about
things that had happened where the reader knew how they were going
to end, but they still felt like thrillers. And Gunther is so
underappreciated. A few years ago, the Boston Globe called me our
generation's equivalent of John Gunther and Teddy White. What a
thrill for me.''
</P>
<P>
   After college graduation in 1955, Halberstam followed his career
plan to a newspaper in Mississippi. He didn't last long, getting
fired when his questions and subsequent stories offended
conservative white readers and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam moved to a newspaper in Nashville, and his civil
rights coverage there became the basis for his book ``The
Children.'' In it, Halberstam tracks down the men and women he
initially wrote about as student participants in sit-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Halberstam found his almost inevitable way to New
York and the Times. His reporting from Vietnam earned a Pulitzer
Prize, with dispatches that brilliantly captured the war's
senseless violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't know or didn't care what was happening,'' he
says. ``The great strength of America, and its greatest weakness,
is we think history isn't important. We think we are a constantly
new society, that we can always reinvent ourselves and leave the
past completely behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at Harper's magazine, Halberstam was assigned a profile
of a relatively anonymous, but important, member of the Johnson
administration. The idea of presidential advisers controlling
America's destiny began to obsess him. He ended up giving up half
his annual salary (''from $18,000 I went down to $9,000'') to work
part time while writing ``The Best and the Brightest.''
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam's sixth book, published in 1972, was a sensation. It
dominated bestseller lists and party conversation, because
Halberstam painted devastating word portraits of leaders whose
pigheadedness condemned America to pursue an unwinnable war. The
book's success allowed Halberstam to turn his full attention to a
career as an author.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam's subsequent books, ``The Powers That Be'' and ``The
Reckoning,'' were heavyweight tomes that investigated the media and
the automotive industry, respectively. Other recent Halberstam
forays into complex subjects include ``The Next Century,'' ``The
Fifties'' and ``The Children.'' He claims the last of the three as
his personal favorite among all the books he has written.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   But sports fascinates Halberstam, too. Nearly 15 years ago, he
wrote ``The Breaks of the Game,'' a study of one season of the
Portland Trailblazers pro basketball team. ``The Amateurs,'' one of
the author's favorite books (''No book is perfect, but to the
degree I can do something perfect within the limits of my skills,
`The Amateurs' is it''), is about rowing. ``Summer of '49'' and
``October 1964'' concern baseball. In each case, Halberstam didn't
confine himself to games themselves; he exhaustively examined
sports economics, its fixated fans, the stars who encapsulate the
society that chooses to worship them.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, then, seems a natural subject for Halberstam,
but he says ``Playing for Keeps'' came out of compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at a standoff, Random House and I,'' Halberstam says.
``I was finishing up `The Children' and had one book left on a
four-book contract. I wanted to do my next one on the Korean War,
but they weren't ready for that. My former editor there suggested
Jordan because he loves basketball and knows I do, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam was already acquainted with Jordan; he'd written a
long cover story about him for Sports Illustrated in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet in 1997, '98, if anyone was written almost too much about,
it was him,'' Halberstam says. ``With Michael Jordan, the question
to answer, the one that hadn't been answered, was not exactly why
he became such a great player, but why the most famous American in
the world became a bald black man who plays basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan first promised to give Halberstam private interviews,
then reneged. But he did follow through on a pledge to allow his
family and closest friends to speak to the author.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't necessarily blame Michael for that,'' Halberstam says.
``How many interviews can one person do? I took on this project at
a time Michael was clearly media-ed out. He's charming, that's for
sure. He is really a modern American prince. But he happened along
at the right time for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   1984, Halberstam believes, was a watershed in American sports
history. Jordan had just joined the Chicago Bulls, but it was also
when fledgling cable network ESPN gained its first real national
prominence; canny marketing genius David Stern became commissioner
of the National Basketball League; and Nike decided it wanted to
build a massive new national advertising campaign around a fresh
new pro basketball face. As skilled in public relations as in
basketball, Michael Jordan took full advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing for Keeps'' is, overall, positive in its analysis of
Jordan. The book doesn't spare glimpses of Jordan's nastiness with
teammates or fixation on winning at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I haven't heard any reaction from Michael, and I don't
expect to, at least in terms of saying something public,''
Halberstam says. ``He's extremely intelligent. He doesn't do
anything that could end up hurting himself. I certainly appreciate
him. He is special.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam is entering what he calls ``a new stage of my life.''
Besides writing books, it is to include new kinds of culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I are going to the opera tonight, my first time at
the opera,'' he says. ``So I've been reading up on opera, trying to
learn some things. The more you learn about almost anything, the
more you want to learn. I guess that's what pleases me, that I
haven't lost my sense of curiosity after all these years. If you
lose that, you're not a journalist anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam hopes his next book will focus on medical science,
and then there's the Korean War. After those books, he'll think of
some more. The journalistic fire still burns in Halberstam's belly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being older actually helps,'' he says. ``I think I have a
better grasp of scope. Maybe my curiosity about things is more
subtle. And I'm certainly a better listener. Journalists ought to
listen more and talk less.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   But sports fascinates Halberstam, too. Nearly 15 years ago, he
wrote ``The Breaks of the Game,'' a study of one season of the
Portland Trailblazers pro basketball team. ``The Amateurs,'' one of
the author's favorite books (''No book is perfect, but to the
degree I can do something perfect within the limits of my skills,
`The Amateurs' is it''), is about rowing. ``Summer of '49'' and
``October 1964'' concern baseball. In each case, Halberstam didn't
confine himself to games themselves; he exhaustively examined
sports economics, its fixated fans, the stars who encapsulate the
society that chooses to worship them.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, then, seems a natural subject for Halberstam,
but he says ``Playing for Keeps'' came out of compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at a standoff, Random House and I,'' Halberstam says.
``I was finishing up `The Children' and had one book left on a
four-book contract. I wanted to do my next one on the Korean War,
but they weren't ready for that. My former editor there suggested
