<HEADER>
A6455 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HALBERSTAM-JORDAN-4th     02-08 0209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALBERSTAM-JORDAN-4thTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: talk less.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The approval of his peers means a lot, but not so much that he
believes every good thing he hears about himself. Told that an
informal Fort Worth Star-Telegram poll of several dozen prominent
authors named him as the best American writer, he smiles, but
notes, ``My wife finds that kind of thing hard to accept. She
reminds me I'm good at what I do, but so are lots of other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Halberstam wants to remain the kind of
journalist he looked up to as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I think of myself as one of the journalism infantry
members who was able to tell some stories,'' he concludes. ``My
family has been able to live well, though we're not wealthy. A lot
of the money I make from each book goes into the next one; if I fly
to Chicago for three days to work on the Jordan book, I end up
spending $3,000-$4,000 on plane fare, hotels, meals. People don't
realize that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've been able to do what I always wanted to do, and
though I'm not the best writer around, I think I'm in the top
group. You know, it's more fun now than ever. That's what pleases
me most.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
