<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6459 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PEBBLE-BEACH-HNS &LR;      02-08 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PEBBLE-BEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEBBLE BEACH REIGNS DESPITE THE WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ The CBS gang was furiously filling dead
air. The network gave us interviews with Craig Stadler and pro-am
partner Glenn Frey. It gave us panoramic views of gray skies over
the Pacific. It gave us pictures of puddles on the greens at Pebble
Beach. It gave us the Weather Channel without the cool maps.
</P>
<P>
   You would think CBS would have been better prepared, after
repeated dousings on the Monterey Peninsula in recent years. When
rain forced golfers off the course at 9:30 a.m. Sunday, the network
should have been frantically searching for real filler material. A
movie (``Caddyshack''?) would have been nice.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Jim Nantz could have asked Frey to perform an
old Eagles hit. ``Hotel California'' would have been a natural.
``You can check out any time you like, but you can never leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that would have been more appropriate for last year's
AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am, which started in January and
ended in August. This time around, the end came quickly and
relatively painlessly. Less than five hours after play was
suspended, the tournament called the 54-hole result a keeper. The
same cannot be said for any tape of the CBS broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The networks call the shots at so many sporting events, often to
the detriment of athletes. Midnight college basketball games. The
San Francisco 49ers in a playoff on six days' rest, and at 9:30
a.m. body-clock time. But since Mother Nature doesn't collect
rights fees, she doesn't have to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   At Pebble Beach, three of the last four years, she's thumbed her
nose, done an end-zone dance and slashed a finger across her
throat. She's quickly replacing MCI as AT&AMP;T's biggest adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Payne Stewart, the winner of the abridged tournament, said he
felt sorry for the long-distance moguls who pay so much for
advertising here. Maybe that's why when a reporter's cell phone
rang during his press conference, he said he'd be happy to pause
and let the journalist take the call.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, it turns out, had a little face-to-face chat during
Saturday's storm with an AT&AMP;T executive, an amateur in the
tournament. The champ asked whether the executive had any thoughts
about how to reduce the odds of rainouts.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said the executive recommended a slight remedy, which
has been suggested in the past. The PGA Tour's West Coast swing
lasts until the end of February, and moving the tournament back by
three weeks would push it closer to the end of the rainy season in
Northern California. The scheduling shift wouldn't lower the risk
substantially, but the tournament is whiffing at a .750 clip on
Sundays since 1995. Any little change is worth exploring.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, a late February date means more daylight, more time for
the greens to dry when the wet stuff does arrive.
</P>
<P>
   There are other options, too. Stewart said that during the long
delay, Stadler had kicked around the idea of coming to Pebble in
July, two weeks after the British Open. Other people have mentioned
swapping tour slots with the Las Vegas Invitational, which brings
players west in October.
</P>
<P>
   The drawback to both of those times? Asking Pebble to shut down
during peak tourist times, when the days are long enough to permit
a generous log of expensive tee-offs.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it may not be worth it to try to outsmart nature.
Although the tournament has taken a beating the last four years,
it's still a strong draw and a great show. The soggy history didn't
keep Bill Murray or Clint Eastwood or Ken Griffey Jr. or Jack
Lemmon away. And CBS, for all its travails, got a lot of mileage
out of them on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The pros don't seem to be turned off, either. For established
players, this is a great event. Spread over three courses, quirky
as the dickens, the AT&AMP;T favors veteran savvy. Stadler and Stewart
both feel that they've had some of their best rounds in years here,
and they've both walked away with well-lined pockets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the abbreviation has a cost. The gate will be
diminished, and even the most ardent fans may start to question the
prudence of setting aside time and money to visit Pebble Beach. For
the players, frustration would be only natural.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lickliter, a stroke behind Stewart, had a chance for the
first win of his young career. David Duval, the hottest man on the
tour, eagled the first hole on Sunday and then had to leave the
course. Phil Mickelson, the defending champ, birdied the first two
before he was beckoned indoors. Who knows what these two might have
done?
</P>
<P>
   But Lickliter, no hothouse flower, said he accepted the perils
of playing in the beautiful but finicky environment at Pebble
Beach. ``If you told me it was going to rain here for the next 20
years, I'd still come back every year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's all the organizers need to hear. And they must believe
that, like an athlete in a slump, they're due for a good run now.
</P>
</TEXT>
