<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6465 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCAR-PREVIEW-TEX     02-08 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPECT `PRIVATE RYAN' TO LEAD THE CHARGE AT THE OSCARS
</HEADLINE>
 For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One reason the Golden Globes are so much fun to watch is the
show's cocktail-fueled looseness; the participants couldn't
possibly care less. Everyone's game and irreverent _ the way it's
said the Oscars were in the '30s and '40s, before people began to
take them way too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Globes, announced in late January, generally give
some indication which way the Academy Award nominations are likely
to go. And when they're announced Tuesday, this year's Oscar bids
are likely to include at least two crowd-pleasing films honored by
the loopier Globes voters _ ``Saving Private Ryan'' and
``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Key nominations from the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and
Sciences should assuage those ``Ryan'' fans upset that the film was
ignored by every organization that gave out awards last year,
except the Golden Globes. (The ``Ryan'' backlash emerged late last
year, when several critics' groups selected ``The Thin Red Line''
and ``Out of Sight'' over Steven Spielberg's masterful
entertainment.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love is the picture most likely to join
``Ryan'' with a pocketful of Oscar nods. The deviously constructed
comedy stars Joseph Fiennes as a brooding, creatively constipated
William Shakespeare and Gwyneth Paltrow as the woman who frees his
talent.
</P>
<P>
   With their long, pale patrician necks, Paltrow and Fiennes are
like a pair of swans flirting with each other. Their rebellious
nuzzling makes up for Fiennes being such an anachronistic actor;
those bright, brimming eyes of his, so close together, make him
look like a handsome ant from ``A Bug's Life.'' Overall, the film
is fluent and self-mocking _ complete with a cameo by its
sharp-witted co-author, Tom Stoppard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan'' star Hanks could probably get more competition from
Paltrow in the Best Actor category than he will from Fiennes. The
real threat will come from Ian McKellen, the best _ maybe the only
_ reason to see ``Gods and Monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   The direction is prosaic, but McKellen's reedy, focused job of
playing down the anguish spooned over his character, director James
Whale, is a marvel. Hanks is also likely to feel the breath of Nick
Nolte on his neck. Nolte gives the performance of his career in
Paul Schrader's adaptation of ``Affliction.'' Full of heart and
heartbroken, Nolte's instinctive bellowing as the lost soul is
chief among the elements that give the movie gracefulness.
</P>
<P>
   Both Nolte's and McKellen's performances were noticed by
critics' organizations _ McKellen's by the Los Angeles group and
the National Board of Review, Nolte's by the National Society.
</P>
<P>
   And as usual, there's a surfeit of good actors' work this year.
Nolte has two pictures for which he could be nominated,
``Affliction'' and ``The Thin Red Line.'' It's even possible,
though not probable, that Sean Penn could receive Academy attention
for both ``Line'' and his disharmonious, broken-down casting agent
in ``Hurlyburly.''
</P>
<P>
   But the pickings are so slim for actresses this year that, in an
act of willful perversion, the New York critics' group gave Cameron
Diaz its Best Actress award for ``There's Something About Mary.''
Which means that, somewhere, RuPaul is tearing his wig _ er, hair _
out, thinking that if he'd only done the ``Brady Bunch'' sequel
THIS year, he, too, would have been nominated.
</P>
<P>
   Though she won't directly compete with Hanks, the odds are that
Paltrow will receive a nomination for ``Shakespeare.'' (Though her
best acting this year, and possibly to date, was in the
phenomenally neurotic ``Great Expectations,'' in which she fixed on
a character in a way that she never had.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is because few roles for women have demanded much
in the way of full emotional extremes. Cate Blanchett, in
``Elizabeth,'' served as a hood ornament _ her head resting on one
of those elegant alabaster necks that are de rigueur in costume
dramas this season. As history swirled around her with more ax
blades than in all of Wes Craven's movies put together, she had not
much more to do than bolt upright and keep her eyes from popping
out of her head. (This may be the year of doubles, as Geoffrey
Rush, who plays Sir Francis Walshingham, the knife in Elizabeth's
right hand, also does fine, knockabout comic work in
``Shakespeare.'')
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Supporting Actor/Actress is almost always the most
fun category _ this year there's Bill Murray in ``Rushmore'' and
Michael Caine in ``Little Voice.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the films, ``Elizabeth'' is a gore-packed melodrama,
although everyone has enough taste to not bleed all over the
Indian-influenced colors _ curry oranges and greens _ that much of
the cast is adorned with.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the low-key lesbianism in ``High Art,'' which is
vaguely tasteful. Or, more to the point, vague and tasteful. Ally
Sheedy's first big splash in the independent film world, as a
tortured gay artist courted by a knowing young acolyte, sounds like
a ripe piece of melodrama. But, in the end, she gets to learn about
herself instead.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the real Oscar surprise will come if ``Life Is
Beautiful,'' Roberto Benigni's swing for the fences, gets a Best
Picture nomination AND a Best Actor nomination. (It's guaranteed a
nomination for Best Foreign Language Film and will undoubtedly win
in that category as well.) His attempt to show the power of comedy
in the most grim situation _ a Nazi concentration camp, where his
family has been interned _ has won him acknowledgement.
</P>
<P>
   And there's Jim Carrey's well-meaning turn in the grindingly
obvious ``The Truman Show,'' another venture to show us the
indomitability of the human spirit. (Although the same thing was
done much more successfully on the old ``Twilight Zone'' and ``The
Prisoner.'')
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Truman's'' director, Peter Weir, received a Director's
Guild Award for the least interesting work in his entire career, we
should assume that the movie has a shot at Best Picture as well.
Which brings the circle back to ``Ryan'' and ``Shakespeare in
Love.'' In the movies as well as everywhere else, what goes around
comes around. And around and around and ...
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
