   &UR; KING HUSSEIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-FUNERAL (Amman) _ United in loss and grief, a vast array
of presidents, prime ministers and princes gathered here Monday to
join the late King Hussein on his final journey, as his body was
buried in a humble white shroud. The mourners included the
bitterest of foes, most notably the leaders of Syria and Israel, a
tribute in death to a Jordanian monarch who in life, over nearly
half a century's reign, had sought to bridge even the most
rancorous of disputes. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-SCENE (Amman) _ A view from the streets as Jordanians
watch the king's body pass and wonder what comes next for a kingdom
facing economic hardship and worries about neighboring iraq. By
William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-MURDOCH _ Iris Murdoch, one of the most prodigiously
inventive and idiosyncratic of modern British writers, whose 26
novels offered a blend of lively plots; complex, wayward
characters, and intellectual speculation, died yesterday after only
three weeks in a nursing home in Oxford, England. She was 79 and
had been suffering from the effects of Alzheimer's disease. Her
struggle was documented recently in ``Elegy for Iris,'' an
acclaimed memoir by her husband, John Bayley, who was at her
bedside when she died.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GUN-LAWS (Atlanta) _ The National Rifle Association and the
firearms lobby won their first victory against cities that are
suing gun makers when the Georgia Legislature passed the first bill
in the nation barring cities from filing such suits. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   WIDEMAN-RETRIAL (Pittsburgh) _ Robert Wideman's part in a
killing a generation ago might have been forgotten by now, except
by the family of a 24 year old man who was shot in the back on a
November night in 1975. Instead, the crime has become one of the
enduring literary images of black America. It was the subject of an
acclaimed 1984 book, ``Brothers &AMP; Keepers'' by Robert Wideman's
brother, John Edgar Wideman. One brother in the non-fiction work
was the noted author who had escaped the ghetto. The other was the
street tough who embodied the cycle that claims many young black
males. At 25, Robert Wideman was imprisoned for life with no
possibility of parole after an accomplice fired a fatal shot in a
robbery that went wrong. Now, Robert Wideman's case is no longer
alive only in literature. A judge has ordered a new trial, angry
prosecutors are appealing, and a debate has broken out over the
effect of race and fame on justice. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-DOCTOR (Savannah, Ga.) _ Profile of a black doctor who
works in a neighborhood that like many other poor urban and rural
communities is short of physicians, black or white, and in a wider
community with few black physicians. Nationally, in a population
that is 13 percent black, less than 4 percent of all physicians are
black. In Savannah, which is more than 50 percent black, 30 of 540
physicians are black, or less than 6 percent. Lately, these
disparities have stirred concern among African-American advocates
and historically black medical schools like Morehouse in the face
of waves of new research showing disparities in the health of black
and white Americans. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
</TEXT>
