<SLUG> BC-NFL-BRONCOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THREE-PEAT' UNLIKELY FOR THE DENVER BRONCOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While the Denver Broncos certainly seem well
stocked to make another run at the Super Bowl, they should know
that it's easy to be seduced by the prospect of a ``three-peat.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams in NFL history managed to win three straight
championships, and neither did in the full Super Bowl era.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay won in 1965-'66-'67, with its first title preceding
Super Bowl I. Before Vince Lombardi's Packers did it, Curley
Lambeau's Packers did it first, winning in 1929-'30-'31, before the
league had a championship-game format.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the Dallas Cowboys failed to three-peat in 1994
in part because of the split between Jerry Jones and Jimmy Johnson.
That, and a pretty good San Francisco 49ers team that year.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers were poised to three-peat in 1990 _ until Lawrence
Taylor's helmet dislodged the ball from Roger Craig's grasp in the
NFC Championship Game at Candlestick Park.
</P>
<P>
   The great Pittsburgh teams won back-to-back Super Bowls on two
occasions but could not string together a third straight in 1976
because of injuries to Franco Harris and Rocky Bleier and a
resolute Oakland Raiders team.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, something always seems to happen to teams in their
quest for a third straight championship. In today's NFL, two years
is a long time to remain dominant over everybody else; three years
seems to be the breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's the lure for Denver. The Broncos are expected
to retain their full coaching staff and most of their offensive and
defensive stalwarts in 1999. Even the commissioner, Paul Tagliabue,
tried to get John Elway jazzed for '99 by saying he could be the
only player named MVP in the Super Bowl in two different centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely 30 teams will spend their offseasons trying to figure
out a way to beat the Broncos. The odds are one team will arrive at
a solution.
</P>
<P>
   For Elway, the decision whether to retire or return is one of
romance vs. history. Few players in any sport manage to go out on
top, on their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   Elway has a chance to make his last game (not counting the Pro
Bowl, the most irrelevant sporting event in America) a Super Bowl
victory.
</P>
<P>
   It's either that or a mad dash tilting at the windmill of
history, with every sweeping blade designed to block a three-peat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
