<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6522 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      02-08 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THE LEAD OUT  
 SPYING ON THE SOLAR WIND  
 FOSSIL DATES LAND BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, leaded gasoline was an environmental bad boy, blamed
for high atmospheric lead levels in urban areas. The introduction
of no-lead at the pump in the 1970s and its eventual universal use
were thought to be responsible for declines in levels of the metal
in the atmosphere and in the blood of urban residents.
</P>
<P>
   But a new study shows the knock on leaded gasoline might not
have been wholly deserved. The work, by scientists from Columbia
University, Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute and the New York State
Department of Environmental Conservation, suggests that, in the New
York area at least, the burning of garbage, not gasoline, spewed
most of the lead into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers examined core samples from the bottom of Central
Park Lake and ended up with a record of heavy-metal pollutants
beginning in the 1860s that showed lead levels reaching their peak
from the late 1930s to the early 60s. This was before the heyday of
leaded gasoline, and corresponded with a rise in incinerator
construction and use in the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   The peak use of leaded gasoline in the late 60s and early 70s
added only a relatively small fraction to the lead deposits.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, whose study appears in the journal
Environmental Science and Technology, noted that the use of waste
incinerators declined in the New York area as environmental laws
were passed in the mid-1960s. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The origin of the solar wind is no mystery. But not much has
been known about precisely how the wind _ the high-speed stream of
electrically charged gas that can interfere with electronic
instruments on and above Earth _ emanates from the Sun. It has long
been thought to originate from open magnetic fields, called coronal
holes.
</P>
<P>
   New observations using instruments aboard the Solar and
Heliospheric Observatory spacecraft, which sits a million miles out
from Earth with an unobstructed view of the Sun, have helped flesh
out the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The observations, reported in the journal Science by a team of
researchers from five countries, show that the wind flows outward
through these coronal holes, along magnetic field lines surrounding
cells in the chromosphere, the part of the Sun's atmosphere just
below the corona.
</P>
<P>
   In this way the Sun is a little like a pasta machine that makes
ziti by extruding dough around a circular die. The magnetic field
lines in the chromosphere delineate many such ``dies,'' with the
``dough,'' the solar wind, emanating from around them. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forget about that bridge to the 21st century. Of greater
interest to scientists is a land bridge that existed millions of
years ago, when Eurasia and North America were joined across what
is now the Bering Strait, allowing terrestrial animals and plants
on the continents to mix, while marine organisms were segregated
between the Arctic-North Atlantic and the Pacific oceans.
</P>
<P>
   The date the bridge first disappeared _ through tectonic shifts
or rising sea levels _ is important because the situation suddenly
was reversed. A fossil found in southern Alaska has put the date of
the first opening as at least 4.8 million years ago, and perhaps as
much as 7.3 million years ago, which is up to 4 million years
earlier than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   The fossil, described by American and Russian scientists in a
recent issue of Nature, is of a type of mollusk, called Astarte,
that had been known to exist only in the Arctic and North Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers noted that the mollusk appeared in the Pacific
much earlier than Pacific mollusks show up in the Arctic and North
Atlantic. They speculate that the flow through the opened strait
may at first have been predominantly southward, from the
Arctic-Atlantic to the Pacific. Then about a million years later,
when the isthmus of Panama closed, the flow reversed to bring
Pacific organisms to the Atlantic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
