<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-PLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUBS MAKE FITNESS CHILD'S PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By MALIA McKINNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is hard not to feel like a child in Blake Mays' recess class
at Crunch Fitness in New York City. While doing jumping jacks
during a game of Simon Says, heaving a ``hot potato'' and
kickboxing a Weeble-Wobble-like clown beanbag, participants are
transported back to the grade-school playground. At the end of
class, everyone gets a gold star in the form of a red apple.
</P>
<P>
   What is the goal of all this playful activity? ``Recess is about
having fun, getting a great cardiovascular workout and toning and
sculpting the body,'' Mays said as he blew a shrill Daffy Duck
whistle, signaling that it was time to switch to leapfrogging over
step platforms, jumping on small trampolines and hopscotching
through the hula hoops of an obstacle course. ``It's play time
without the bully,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other fitness clubs around the country are offering similar
kinds of classes, hoping that this trend of play as exercise can
make fitness more fun and entice people into the gym. ``Health
clubs are striving to bring back a carefree spirit of exercise in
their classes, and most of us look back on our childhood days in
gym class as just that,'' said Cathy Masterson McNeil, spokesman
for the International Health, Racquet and Sports Club Association,
a trade organization for health clubs based in Boston. ``Children
don't view exercise as an obligation, and that's the challenge of
many health clubs _ making people see fitness as taking a break and
not as a burden.''
</P>
<P>
   On the West Coast, Gorilla Sports, a health club in San
Francisco, offers a version of play time called speed camp.
``Working out should be entertaining and physically challenging,
not something you have to force yourself to get through,'' said
Dave Fox, founder of the gym and speed camp's instructor. This
two-hour class includes stretching and conditioning drills during
the first half, all in preparation for the second part of class,
``game hour.'' Dodge ball, the 40-yard dash, broad jumps and
suicide runs (running to the middle of a basketball court, then
back to the baseline, then all the way to the end of the court and
back to baseline) are designed to increase speed and agility, Fox
said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, on Saturdays in Chicago, people line up for PE 101 at
the East Bank Club. ``This class runs the gamut of calisthenics,
athletic drills and races using medicine balls, jump ropes and
slide mats to do relay races, crab crawls and play dodge ball _
basically, all the things you did in PE,'' said Nancy Fudacz, the
instructor of the class and director of exercise programs at the
club.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kids at Heart class at Sportslife Fitness in Atlanta,
leap frog, double-dutch jump rope, freeze tag and wheelbarrow and
potato sack races are standard activities. ``The members really get
into it,'' said Melissa Layne, instructor and executive director of
Group Fitness.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the motivational factor, these kinds of classes
offer undeniable fitness benefits. ``In an hour-long class that's
focused on cardiovascular activity, your heart rate is going to be
elevated for at least 20 minutes, and you'll easily burn 150
calories,'' said Dr. Michele S. Olson, an associate professor of
exercise science at Auburn University in Montgomery, Ala. ``Your
heart doesn't care whether it's stimulated by treadmill jogging,
playing hopscotch or running relays,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Thayer, 41, the operations manager for an Atlanta job
recruitment firm, agrees: ``At first the group I work out with at
the gym thought Kids at Heart would be a joke. Then we got there
and were surprised to find just how out of shape we really were.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
