<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUSSEIN-JORDAN-0209-C     02-08 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUSSEIN-JORDAN-0209-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HUSSEIN, A FAMILIAR FIGURE, TRAVELS AMMAN'S STREETS FOR THE LAST
TIME
 &HT;    With Photo in the International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    With HUSSEIN-FUNERAL-0209; CLINTON-HUSSEIN-0209.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Grief washed across the crowded streets of this
downcast capital in waves Monday. The waves swelled with the cries
of ``God is Great'' as a motorcade bearing the casket of Jordan's
King Hussein slowly approached waiting crowds. And they crested in
the sobs of the old and young, farmers and Yuppies, as their
familiar leader passed for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hundreds of thousands(CQ) lining the streets and
overpasses, many had trouble letting go of their king. Hundreds
tried to run along side of the slow-moving military Land Rover that
carried him. Thousands swarmed the vehicle as it approached the
gates of his palace grounds. They were barely held back by
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Along the route, the stern soldiers lined the roads wielding
M-16 rifles. But, by the time Hussein's motorcade passed, carrying
its wave of emotion, even many of them were in tears.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein, who died of cancer Sunday at the age of 63 and after 46
years as king, was carried to his resting place in the royal
cemetery where his father and grandfather are buried.
</P>
<P>
   He was escorted by red military Land Rovers with mounted machine
guns. His vehicle was khaki, and his coffin, draped in the
Jordanian flag, sat amid a bed of white flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting him at his destination were dozens of the world's
leaders, some of them officially enemies with each other. They had
come together to honor a man who had built his tiny country into
the centerpiece of Middle Eastern stability and worked tirelessly
for peace.
</P>
<P>
   But, on the streets of Amman, the attachment was personal and
spiritual, rather than political.
</P>
<P>
   Bystanders tossed flowers toward Hussein's casket and longed for
other ways to touch their fallen monarch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to reach out to his coffin and take his hand and kiss
it,'' said Jordanian Marlene Khoury, 42. She and her two daughters
were dressed in black and sobbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like an orphan,'' said daughter Jan Khoury, 26.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein holds an almost demi-God status with his people.
</P>
<P>
   Old women with black flags wailed their mournful chants -- ``I
wish it were my brother or father instead of him!'' People called
him their brother and father and glorified his bloodline's direct
descent from the Moslem prophet Mohammad.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jordan's economy is a shambles and, under Hussein, the
country has lost wars and had bread riots, he was held largely
blameless. His people remember him for keeping the vulnerable
country together and in relative peace while conflagrations have
raged around it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not like in America, where you blame everything on the
president,'' said Sulieman Nader, a 20-year-old Jordanian who
attends the Michigan Technological College. ``We all know how hard
it is for Jordan to exist in this volatile region.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader held the red, green, black and white Jordanian flag and
gazed at a glossy billboard-sized picture of Hussein. In it, the
King's face glows against a red sunset. In the foreground is the
needle nose of a shiny jet fighter -- evocative of the dashing
leader's hobby as a pilot infatuated with fast airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in a state of shock,'' Nader said. ``I'm only 20
years old. Unfortunately, the youth here didn't get our share of
King Hussein. It's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to mingle with the dignitaries behind the gates of the
palace, bystanders gave personal, roadside eulogies. They talked
about nephews who received special medical treatment after requests
for help from Hussein's palace, or widows that received salaries
from him.
</P>
<P>
   Those touches of personal generosity -- from a king who also
loved the high-life of sports cars and European palaces -- cemented
his peoples' loyalty. A large portion of the population had met the
king personally.
</P>
<P>
   Adnan Kosmar remembered a previous time he encountered the king
on this city's roads. During a rare snowstorm in 1992, Kosmar's car
got stuck on a median strip. He was astonished to see Hussein pull
over and personally help push his Oldsmobile back onto the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``He smiled at me,'' Kosmar said. ``And I kissed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hussein's greatest feat was unity, sewing together a country
from a mix of varied and displaced people. Those demographics were
visible on the roadsides Monday.
</P>
<P>
   There were Bedouin vegetable farmers with their faces covered in
red-and-white head scarves -- a sign of mourning. There were trendy
Palestinians, in leather jackets and loafers looking at the king
who integrated their people after they lost their homes in what is
now Israel. There were wealthy Jordanians with Armani sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous about their country's future, they welcomed the
dignitaries behind the gate of the castle -- even U.S. President
Bill Clinton, who is often criticized on Jordan's streets for his
bombardments of neighboring Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who respect our king, respect us. We respect them,''
Mohammad Al-Boty, a stocky, 47-year-old accountant. He was composed
and analytical until Hussein passed. Then he started sobbing.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
