<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6546 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUSSEIN-PRESIDENTS-02     02-08 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUSSEIN-PRESIDENTS-0209-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE AIR FORCE ONE CLUB: EX-PRESIDENTS SHARE TALES, ADVICE ON
FLIGHT TO JORDAN
 &HT;    With HUSSEIN-FUNERAL-0209.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ It was, by any measure, a night to remember
aboard Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   For gathered in the cabin devoted to senior White House staff
were the most senior such officials imaginable -- Presidents
Clinton, Bush, Carter and Ford, spinning tales from their
respective administrations and batting around global issues deep
into the night, as the Carolina blue 747 soared high above the
Atlantic Ocean en route to this Middle East capital.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a very friendly, serious, substantive discussion of
the Middle East peace process, Kosovo, Russia,'' said National
Security Adviser Samuel Berger, who participated in the two-hour
senior seminar. ''It was really quite an extraordinary, a very
interesting discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   What brought the elite leadership club together was the funeral
here Monday of King Hussein, who ruled Jordan for 47 years until
his death from cancer on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The irony wasn't lost on the presidential group.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hussein really did bring people together,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here we are, two Democrats, two Republicans,'' Clinton said.
''We've agreed on many things, we've disagreed on a thing or two
over time.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing the men all agreed on, though, was the the loss of
Hussein's statesmanship in pursuit of Mideast peace was a blow to
global diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think I've ever seen a greater outpouring of the
world's appreciation and the world's love for a human being that
I've seen today,'' said Carter, speaking with his presidential
peers to a group of U.S. Embassy personnel here Monday night.
''It's a true expression of what King Hussein has meant to all of
us personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's own efforts to bring about Mideast peace -- efforts he
worked closely with Hussein on -- stretch back to the earliest days
of his presidency, in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   He'd only been in office two weeks, Carter recalled, when
Hussein's third wife, Alia, was killed in a helicopter crash.
</P>
<P>
   That spring, Hussein came to visit Carter in the White House,
primarily to urge the new president to take on a bold pursuit of
Mideast peace, an initiative that would eventually lead to Carter
brokering the Camp David accords between Israel and Egypt in
September, 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a peanut farmer who had never met a king,'' Carter
recalled, explaining how he had worked with his daughter Amy, then
nine, about how to address His Majesty the king.
</P>
<P>
   ''And when we met the royal family the first thing Amy shouted
was, 'Hi Prince,''' Carter said, kicking off what was to become an
enduring personal relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Carter also recalled during that visit standing on the Truman
Balcony with Hussein and gazing out across the South Lawn one
evening, watching the airplanes take off and land from what is now
Reagan National Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``He began to tell me about his recent tragic loss, and he began
to weep,'' Carter said. ''He said he was just exhausted from his
sorrow and from the duties on his shoulders. And I suggested that
he spend a couple of weeks in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   King Hussein did go, taking a vacation near Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   ''He hunted and fished and swam,'' said Carter. ''And I gave
him, without asking anybody's permission, since I was the
commander-in-chief, a helicopter to fly around in. And I think he
enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
