<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Feb. 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Cloudy skies and a few snow showers will mark the passage of a
cold front in western New England. Only a few clouds along with
shifting winds will be noted along the North Atlantic coast. It
will be blustery and cool in the northern and eastern Great Lakes
as high pressure builds over the upper Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A large fair weather system in the southwest Atlantic will
circulate unusually mild air into the Southeast. Sunshine will be
dimmed by some clouds away from the coast, but temperatures will
rise to near record levels in many sections. Florida will stay
balmy with ample sunshine and gentle winds.
</P>
<P>
   Showers will develop in the lower Mississippi and Tennessee
Valleys as humid air flowing northward from the Gulf of Mexico is
acted on by a jet stream disturbance. Fog will be dense in some
sections of the South. A couple of strong thunderstorms may form in
eastern Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Mild weather will dominate the central and northern Plains
despite limited sunshine. A cold front will approach from the
Rockies late in the day. Increasing winds from the south should
scour out pockets of gelid air in the eastern Dakotas.
</P>
<P>
   Much colder air from the North Pacific will surge across the
Northwest. Snow levels in the northern Cascades will reach near the
surface in Washington. A disturbance on the front will cross
central and southern California producing heavy rain and chilly
winds. Showers will reach into the deserts late. Snow levels will
decrease substantially in the southern Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Southeast Simmers
</P>
<P>
   The mercury rose to a record 80 degrees on Sunday afternoon in
Columbia, S.C. This reading was just a few degrees shy of the
all-time February maximum. A few weeks ago, Asheville, N.C.,
reached 80 degrees, setting a new all-time January record. Since
the frigid weather left the northern tier of the nation in the
middle of January, a ridge of high pressure has dominated the
Southeast. This atmospheric feature has prevented the development
of northeasters. However, a surge of chilly air will reach the
Southeast this weekend, perhaps reversing the recent trend.
</P>
</TEXT>
