</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEREWOLVES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WEREWOLVES IN THEIR YOUTH': MARRIAGE AND OTHER THINGS THAT CAN GO
WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (Publication notes at end of review)  
 (HLW)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are no happy families in ``Werewolves in Their Youth'' _
just different varieties of marital distress, filial rage, paternal
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   In his earlier work (``The Mysteries of Pittsburgh,'' ``A Model
World''), the talented Michael Chabon has tended to focus on boys
trying to come to terms with their fathers, children trying to make
sense of their parents' fractured lives. Though there are stories
in this disappointing volume that do just that _ both the title
story and ``The Harris Fetko Story'' concern sons, sorting through
the emotional wreckage of their fathers' mistakes _ most of these
tales are about marriages in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   ``House Hunting'' concerns an angry young couple looking for a
new home for their deteriorating marriage. ``Son of the Wolfman''
depicts another disaffected couple, whose marriage unravels when
the wife is raped and decides to give birth to the rapist's baby.
And ``That Was Me'' portrays a husband and wife trying in vain to
pick up strangers in a local bar.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Chabon's characters cherish the idea of control. The
quarterback renowned for his ``serene, arctic blankness''; the
little boy trying to remake reality with his fantasy games; the
couple who diligently save all their receipts and subscribe to
Consumer Reports _ all would like to find some way to ward off
chaos and disaster, but find themselves submitting to the gathering
disorder in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Green's Book,'' a family therapist known for his kindness
and reliability not only sees his own marriage come to an end but
also finds himself reliving a long-ago night when he molested a
young girl. And in ``Mrs. Box,'' a bankrupt optometrist fleeing his
ruptured marriage and failed business visits his ex-wife's
grandmother and contemplates stealing her jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Chabon writes with enormous fluency in these pages,
captivating the reader with his descriptive and metaphoric powers.
He's able to give us vivid snapshots in a phrase or two, showing us
a man's ``brushed-aluminum hair'' or making us hear the ``Eeyore
voice'' of an annoying boy's annoying mother. He likens a group of
Little League players sitting clumped along the bench to ``pigeons
on the arm of a statue'' and describes a football coach's cologne
as smelling like ``the tiny red cardboard pine trees that dangle
from the rearview mirrors of taxicabs.''
</P>
<P>
   When Chabon turns to more emotional matters, however, his prose
tends to grow labored, prolix and self-conscious. He describes
marriage, for instance, as ``a container for the madness between
men and women,'' ``a fragile hedge against it, as religion was to
death, and the laws of physics to the immense quantity of utter
emptiness of which the universe was made''; it was ``a doubtful
enterprise, a voyage in an untested craft, across a hostile ocean,
with a map that was a forgery and with no particular destination
but the grave.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar problem afflicts the stories as a whole. Just as many
of his characters are control freaks, so Chabon, as a writer, tends
to overmanage their fates. He is constantly pushing his narratives
into neatly packaged, O. Henryesque shapes, decking out his ironies
with neon lights, and festooning his symbols with glitter and
tinsel.
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough in ``Son of the Wolfman'' for a woman to get
pregnant with a rapist's child; Chabon has to add that the woman
and her husband were trying, in vain, to have a child for years.
It's not enough in ``Mrs. Box'' for the hero to try to steal the
jewelry of his ex-wife's grandmother; he has to be punished for
this act by having his own car stolen. It's not enough in ``House
Hunting'' for a couple to be having sexual difficulties; while
touring a house with a real estate agent, they have to find a
sexual aid that solves their particular problem.
</P>
<P>
   In ``In the Black Mill'' _ a horror story supposedly written by
August Van Zorn, a character in Chabon's last novel, ``Wonder
Boys'' _ an archeologist researching an ancient tribe of cannibals
just happens to stumble across evidence that a modern cult with
equally bloody habits has taken over a town. And in ``Spikes,'' a
man whose marriage has unraveled after the death of his baby son
skips a meeting with his wife's divorce lawyer to play father to a
neighbor's 11-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   The reader cannot help wondering why Chabon is trying so hard.
Indeed, these stories recall many of the weaker aspects of his
first book, ``The Mysteries of Pittsburgh'' (1988), a charming but
mannered novel that was eclipsed by the lucid and wonderfully
nuanced Nathan Shapiro stories in ``A Model World'' (1991) _
stories that demonstrated Chabon's ability to write about love and
loss with precision and wisdom, and without the sort of contrivance
that mars this latest collection.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   WEREWOLVES IN THEIR YOUTH
</P>
<P>
   Stories
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Chabon
</P>
<P>
   212 pages. Random House. $22.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
