<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING DOCTOR, AND CHEATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN O'NEILL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Devices that let people measure their blood pressure at home are
inexpensive and simple. But there is a problem: A recent German
study found that about half the patients using the devices cheated
when it came to writing down the results.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, patients who are given the increasingly popular
devices are asked to record their blood pressures in logbooks their
physicians review periodically. These results can give a more
comprehensive picture of hypertension than single measurements in
an office visit can, and avoid ``white coat hypertension'' _ high
blood pressure caused by the anxiety of seeing a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   In a study published recently in the American Journal of
Hypertension, researchers at the University Clinic in Bonn came up
with a simple method of checking on the accuracy of the
self-monitoring routine: They gave 30 randomly selected patients
devices that contained a memory chip that was recording the results
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody fudged: 11 patients, in fact, wrote down their
pressure readings faithfully. The other patients generally strayed
by recording results only part of the time. ``The measurements most
prevalently left off were the high readings,'' Dr. Michael A.
Weber, an editor of the journal, said in a telephone interview.
``People would decide they had gotten a high reading because they
were nervous or upset or that it wasn't the `right time' for a
reading. So they would leave it out, or go back and repeat the test
until they got a lower reading.''
</P>
<P>
   This kind of distortion is based on a misunderstanding, said
Weber, the head of medicine at Brookdale University Hospital in
Brooklyn and president of the American Society of Hypertension.
``It's perfectly appropriate to have high blood pressure from time
to time, say after a conflict with your boss, or readings that are
falsely low, like after a large lunch,'' he said. ``The point of
the monitoring should be to present a patient's full range as well
as the average.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber said that physicians and researchers could not rely on the
head-in-the-icebox-feet-in-the-fire averages indicated by the
study. ``It's important to remind doctors that ultimately it is
their own measurements that have to guide them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John O'Neil
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
