<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6596 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYLITE-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      02-08 1605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYLITE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Fiona McKinney.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Penny Kemp and Linda Falk had trekked out to Southern California
for the Rose Bowl. On the drive to Malibu for a pregame party, they
spotted a car with the vanity plate ``OYGRWUP.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Linda, look! That license plate says, `Oy, Grow up,' Ms.
Kemp exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in California, not New York,'' Ms. Falk retorted. ``It
says, `Oh, why grow up?'''
</P>
<P>
   The worst time in Manhattan is a rainy cold winter day at rush
hour in midtown trying to get home. But last week, because of a bus
driver, I felt like a tourist just enjoying the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   The crosstown M42 bus was packed with tired commuters. People
were growing irritated at the slow traffic and being squeezed into
inches of space. The bus driver picked up the microphone to
announce what we thought would be the next stop.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, his announcement went something like this: ``Fifth
Avenue is the next stop. Look out the window. It's the magnificent
Fifth Avenue with everything your heart desires. Go up to see the
one and only Central Park and enjoy Museum Mile with the best
museums in New York and in this world, from the Metropolitan Museum
to MOMA, from ancient Egyptian arts to contemporary paintings. Now
turn to your left and you will find the beautiful New York Public
Library. Farther down is the famous Empire State Building and the
World Trade Center. Now you are here _ Fifth Avenue, Fifth Avenue,
everyone who wants to get off, please use the rear door.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, sir.
</P>
<P>
   _ KARLEEN CHIU
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Puckett, in a midtown card store, heard a woman asking
the clerk: ``Don't you have any cheap Valentine's Day cards for
husbands?''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Antonoff was standing inside the door of a pizzeria in
the theater district, awaiting the arrival of his lunch date. A
deliveryman walked in, carrying two bags of Chinese food. The
maitre d'hotel shook her head, suggested that the food must be for
the office upstairs and pointed to the next door.
</P>
<P>
   After the deliveryman insisted that he had the right address,
the maitre d' checked with the kitchen. A minute later, the cook
emerged, took possession of the food and disappeared back into the
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Antonoff couldn't help but exclaim, ``It's a bad omen.''
</P>
<P>
   The maitre d'hotel had obviously been briefed. ``No,'' she
replied. ``the chef eats the same food every day and just wanted
something different.''
</P>
