<SLUG> BC-AIR-FORCE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ENLISTMENTS SAGGING, AIR FORCE PLANS FIRST TV RECRUITING ADS
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY and TIMOTHY R. GAFFNEY
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time in its history, the Air Force
will buy television time to run recruiting ads in hopes of
reversing enlistment declines caused by an enticing job market and
the increasingly hectic military life, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with NCAA basketball games at the end of this month,
the Air Force Recruiting Service will pour $17 million into
big-market TV buys using ads that previously ran on donated time as
off-hour public service announcements.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Air Force is in the early phase of
developing a brand-new ad campaign that will open with the fall
television schedule with another $37 million to spend.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden change in philosophy, and the influx of cash to
advertising accounts, follows poor recruiting performance in the
first months of this fiscal year. Starting in October, when the
federal budget for 1999 began, the Air Force has failed to meet
enlistment goals in three of the past four months, raising the
specter that the service could miss year-end goals for the first
time since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel our competition is with local corporations and
colleges,'' said Tech Sgt. Jeff Bowser, who runs the Air Force
recruiting office in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is twofold: the robust economy has given potential
recruits lots of alternatives to military service, and those who
opt to serve find the work pace difficult to take because the armed
forces have been shrinking at the same time that worldwide
peacekeeping missions have increased.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the quality of life for military service members has
been highlighted in Washington as all branches of the military have
seen enlistment and re-enlistment figures sag. President Clinton
proposed a 4.4 percent pay raise for all military personnel in his
2000 budget, and last October the Air Force set up an enlistment
bonus program offering up to $9,000 for prize recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement follows years of holding steady on the Air
Force advertising budget, which hasn't been raised to accommodate
higher media costs since 1990. The $17 million and $37 million
allotments for broadcast time will be spent in addition to the Air
Force's regular $16 million advertising budget, which already was
boosted by $6 million this year. The extra money was made available
by the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   One reason why the Air Force is struggling with recruiting is
because many people only enlist to learn skills such as computer
programming, then leave after four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of folks do use the Air Force as a stepping stone,''
Bowser said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
