<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-WORDS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 A JOB WITH NEW MEANING: UPDATING THE DICTIONARY
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a snapshot of our times, a word can be worth a thousand
pictures _ especially if you're in the dictionary biz.
</P>
<P>
   Just think of the difference between, say, ``flower power'' and
``power suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Jump ahead to the '90s, a time so filled with ambivalence that
we have both ``casual Fridays'' and the non-stop work ethic implied
by the expression ``24/7.''
</P>
<P>
   These new twists of phrase haven't escaped the notice of
lexicographers. At this very moment, an army of word sleuths is
scouring pop lyrics, movies, trade journals, billboards and even
grocery coupons for new words and usages.
</P>
<P>
   A mere handful will end up in the Oxford dictionaries,
considered by some to be the last word on language.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're doing in a dictionary is trying _ at one given
time _ to take a picture (of the language),'' says Frank Abate,
editor-in-chief of U.S. Dictionaries, Oxford University Press.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford has been studying the spread of global English for 50
years and claims to have the world's most ambitious language
research program.
</P>
<P>
   Its army of paid and volunteer readers throughout the
English-speaking world collects an average of 18,000 new words and
meanings every month. These go into an electronic database that
provides the raw material for dictionary revisions.
</P>
<P>
   Only a small fraction of new words make the cut. Abate,
(pronounced Uh-BOT-ay) said the decision is based on the word's
history, how frequently it pops up in conversation or writing and
how much staying power it has.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the dictionary is another factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the words on the list are amusing, but they won't make
it into smaller dictionaries,'' said Abate, speaking from his
office in Old Saybrook, Conn. ``There is a bit of the
lexicographer's intuition involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent Americanisms that Oxford is tracking include ``24/7,''
``duh!'', ``plus size,'' ``slamming'' (the illicit switching of
someone's long-distance phone service), ``laser pointer'' and
``mouthfeel'' (used to describe the texture of food in the mouth).
</P>
<P>
   Oxford is still reserving judgment about some coinages that have
been around a lot longer. They include ``class act,'' ``designated
driver,'' ``fat city,'' ``hissy fit,'' ``nowheresville,
``time-out'' (a discipline approach for young children) and ``worst
nightmare,'' (a threat that typically begins, ``I am your ... etc.,
etc.'')
</P>
<P>
   E-mail not only speeds the spread of new words, it also helps
lexicographers stay abreast of global trends.
</P>
<P>
   As Abate said, ``We can contact colleagues all over the world
and say, `Do you guys use this word or not?'''
</P>
<P>
   Oxford has begun publishing separate editions of its dictionary
to reflect regional idioms such as ``Asianization,'' a new buzz
word in Australia; and ``blackwater rafting,'' a New Zealand term
for riding the rapids of dark, underground waterways.
</P>
<P>
   As with so many trends, however, fashionable words more often
spread from the United States to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Abate said pop culture and electronic technology spawn a huge
amount of inventive language. There's been a virtual explosion of
words that begin with the letter ``e'' or the prefix ``cyber.''
</P>
<P>
   Medical technology and health care are bigger issues in the
United States than in Britain, he said, and ``it's reflected in our
dictionaries.'' He cites ``eldercare'' as a typical Americanism.
</P>
<P>
   In the high-tech arena, he notes that the word ``computer'' has
become universal except for France, where the language purists of
the Academie Francaise insist on calling it an ``ordinateur.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to carefully guarded French, he said, ``English just
does its thing and comes out however it comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't flinch at the results, even when he encounters a
linguistic car wreck like ``irregardless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people roll over and retch when they hear it,'' Abate
said. ``What we've done in our dictionary is say, OK, there's a
word, `irregardless.' It's in the i's. But we also give advice. We
recommend people avoid the word.''
</P>
<P>
   Abate said the same guideline applies to offensive words such as
ethnic slurs. If the terms are widely used, they're listed, along
with an admonition that the words are considered derogatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that we're reporters of the language and how the
language is being used,'' Abate said. ``But we don't try to
legislate. We don't really feel it's ours to take a moral
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest change in modern word coinage is the
influence of movies, TV, commercials and other forms of popular
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 47,'' Abate said. ``When I was a kid, rock music was
considered, by my parents, some kind of side thing that kids did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's mainstream. So it's much easier for pop terms to come
into the language. It's more democratic now, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sample of some of the new words and usages that turned
up in Oxford's global sieve in 1998. While only a handful will
become dictionary entries, they offer a fascinating glimpse of
society in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   achiever fever: Ambition that reduces life to an incessant round
of work-related activity.
</P>
<P>
   analysisparalysis: When decision-making ability is paralyzed by
information overload.
</P>
<P>
   backward compatibility: Ability of new products to be used with
old technology.
</P>
<P>
   biopiracy: The plundering of developing nations by
multinationals in search of natural products with potential
commercial value.
</P>
<P>
   Buteyko: Technique of controlled breathing to control asthma.
</P>
<P>
   cybersquatter: Someone who registers well-known company names as
Internet addresses in order to sell them to the companies later.
</P>
<P>
   cyberwidow: Unfortunate partner of a habitual Internet user.
</P>
<P>
   ego-surfing: Searching the Internet for occurrences of your own
name.
</P>
<P>
   digger-diving: Direct-action protest, such as blocking the path
of large construction machinery.
</P>
<P>
   elk test: Evaluates a car's response to sudden, high-speed
turns. First adopted in Scandinavia to assess reaction to animals
straying onto roads.
</P>
<P>
   gorge walking: New adventure sport where participants walk or
wade up the entire course of a river or stream.
</P>
<P>
   gravy: Short form of ``gravy train,'' widely used last year in
South Africa to refer to government corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Hansonism: Political policies of Pauline Hanson, leader of the
Australian ``One Nation'' party, opposed to immigration and the
``Asianization'' of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   hoarding: New meaning in Indian English specifically referring
to the illegal stockpiling of staple foodstuffs, made scarce in
1998 by failed harvests in India.
</P>
<P>
   irritainment: Highly irritating but nonetheless compulsive
viewing.
</P>
<P>
   liquid funk: New subgenre of drum and bass music, often using
excerpts from '70s funk records to create a less aggressive sound
than recent tech-step or darkside sounds.
</P>
<P>
   meatspace: The physical world, as opposed to the ``virtual''
world of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   microphobes: Opponents of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   muti murder: A term that got international attention after last
year's spate of killings in Johannesburg related to ``muti,''
traditional African magic.
</P>
<P>
   orthorexia: Obsessive elimination of foods from the diet in the
belief that they are harmful.
</P>
<P>
   poke: Slang term for Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   post rock: Eclectic, experimental music, originally from
Chicago, combining rock, jazz, avant-garde classical, etc. (Also
math rock, which emphasizes unusual combinations of music and time
signatures.)
</P>
<P>
   rage: Besides road rage on our increasingly hostile highways,
1998 brought Web rage, provoked by slow Internet access. An online
counseling service was set up last year to address the problem ...
if you can get through.
</P>
<P>
   Shibuya-kei: Style of Japanese pop music, now successful on the
international scene. It copies Western styles in an unorthodox way.
</P>
<P>
   uplift anxiety: U.S. term for the psychological problems that
arise from being cured of depression.
</P>
<P>
   walk the dog (also milk the cow, split the atom, reach for the
moon): old terms made newly popular by last year's yo-yo craze.
</P>
<P>
   zippergate: Also known as Monicagate or fornigate.
</P>
<P>
   Enough said.
</P>
</TEXT>
