<HEADER>
A6603 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIRL-BURNED-COX     02-08 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRL-BURNED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Girl hurt while playing on city park slide; methane gas may have
caused injury
 &HT;    By Carlos Campos
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A southeast Atlanta playground remains closed while
city officials try to find out how 8-year-old Delores Norman was
burned on her arms and hands in what appears to be a freak accident
involving methane gas.
</P>
<P>
   Delores and other children playing at D.L. Stanton Park in the
Peoplestown community Jan. 18 said they heard a loud bang and then
a hissing sound, like escaping steam, come from the ground near the
plastic slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sliding board just popped up,'' said Delores at her home
within walking distance of the park. The pig-tailed second-grader
was treated at Hughes Spalding Children's Hospital for second and
third-degree burns on her left forearm and right hand, said her
mother, Michelle Norman. Norman doesn't expect Delores' injuries to
leave permanent damage. Another 8-year-old girl was also slightly
injured.
</P>
<P>
   Norman said she's frustrated because she doesn't know how her
daughter was burned, and claims the city has been short on answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked at her arms I wondered how could this happen on
a sliding board,'' said Michelle Norman. ``They're not telling me
everything. I want to know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gary, acting commissioner of parks, said it's possible
methane gas _ generated by decomposing organic matter such as
discarded food _ was trapped between the top and bottom levels of
the one-piece, plastic spiral slide. Gary said a testing company
has confirmed dangerous levels of methane gas underground at the
playground.
</P>
<P>
   Gary said city records don't show there was ever a landfill on
the site, but he and community residents say the area may have been
used as an illegal dumping ground many years ago. Gary said static
electricity produced by the friction of children on the slide may
have created the spark necessary for an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The state Environmental Protection Division will review the
city's report on the matter, and help if needed, said Christy
Easter, a geologist in the solid waste management division.
</P>
<P>
   Easter said it is uncommon, but not impossible, for an explosion
of methane gas to occur outdoors, because the gas is easily
dispersed. She said it's possible the slide could have provided a
place for the methane to build up to explosive levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have to have some way to concentrate that gas,''
Easter said. ``And I just don't know how that happened with those
little girls. It's something I've never heard of in this scenario,
but strange things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Community activist Columbus Ward said he's trying to organize an
informational meeting on the matter this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously one of the most unusual events that has
happened that I'm aware of,'' said Councilwoman Debi Starnes, who
represents the area. ``And we're doing everything we can to
investigate what caused it.''
</P>
<P>
   The playground is closed off by plastic webbing, and tape that
reads ``Hazardous Area Keep Out.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Campos writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
