<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6604 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWT-SEAT-COX     02-08 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWT-SEAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cash-poor hopefuls take on well-heeled Isakson
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If TV ads mark the start of a political campaign, the
race for the 6th District congressional seat has officially
started.
</P>
<P>
   But the only one on the air is Johnny Isakson.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one example of how the campaign to replace Newt
Gingrich in Washington has become a two-week sprint that pits one
``have'' against seven ``have-nots.''
</P>
<P>
   Isakson, chairman of the state school board who has financed two
previous statewide races, claims a war chest of about $1.5 million.
He expects to spend at least $470,000 on television, cable, radio
and direct mail ads for the special election Feb. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Of the other seven candidates who hope to drag him into a March
runoff, only one has raised a tenth as much as Isakson _ Christina
Jeffrey, a 51-year-old Kennesaw State University professor.
</P>
<P>
   Some are spending nothing except the $4,100 qualifying fee.
Others are digging into their life savings and investments _
deeply, considering the odds stacked against them. ``It's hard to
sell your wife on spending $10,000 that you need,'' said Marco
Longo, a 27-year-old salesman who has never before run for office.
``We needed that 10 grand. But we're young.''
</P>
<P>
   When they get their messages out, the conversation is likely to
dwell on close-to-home issues _ nothing like the futuristic visions
Gingrich used to thrill voters. Most candidates, including Isakson,
are talking taxes, the federal surplus, Social Security, and
education.
</P>
<P>
   But while this is a nonpartisan race, the 6th District remains
heavily Republican. And several candidates will be testing whether
abortion, an issue that has proved fatal to Isakson in the past,
still has the power to determine the outcome in what is likely to
be a low-turnout contest.
</P>
<P>
   For cash-poor candidates, the effort to get a message out
cheaply and quickly has resulted in several innovations, including
reliance on the Internet. At least four of the eight candidates
have put up Web sites, and others are hoping the cheap, strategic
use of cable TV, direct mail or yard signs will provide the magic
bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to get into a runoff with Johnny,'' said Leigh
Baier, a 57-year-old attorney. ``I plan to get there with 50 cents
a vote and I figure Johnny is going to get there at $100 a vote.''
He's personally set aside $50,000 for the race.
</P>
<P>
   But breaking into the public consciousness will be hard. Even
``free media,'' what some people might call news, will be scarce.
The 6th District candidates are competing for attention with a new
governor trying to put a forceful, early mark on his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we think we know is that voters aren't
likely to vote for candidates that they don't know anything
about,'' said Charles Bullock, a political scientist at the
University of Georgia. ``Most of the people haven't done anything
that gives them name recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   At least three forums featuring all candidates are scheduled
between now and Election Day. One of them, sponsored by the Atlanta
Press Club, will be televised Feb. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Of seven candidates on the ballot and one write-in, Isakson is
by far the best known. The 54-year-old president of Northside
Realty ran for the U.S. Senate in 1996 and for governor in 1990. He
served 17 years in the Legislature representing Georgia's Cobb
County, which provides half the voters of the 6th District.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson's television ads take the homey, soft-sell approach of
depicting him as a pro-business supporter of eduction who also
favors a 10-percent tax cut. He doesn't back away from his past
support for a woman's right to an abortion, but now emphasizes his
opposition to partial birth abortions and his support for parental
notification and informed consent requirements.
</P>
<P>
   By budgeting only a third of his treasury for advertising,
Isakson will have a reserve to respond to any attack ads.
``Obviously we have a large cushion there,'' said Heath Garrett,
campaign manager for Isakson. ``If Christina Jeffrey goes negative,
we can respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey, too, is a name many Republicans recognize. She was
named House historian by Newt Gingrich in one of his first acts as
House Speaker, and was quickly fired by him, too, over a
misinterpretation of some comments she made about the Holocaust.
Her campaign says she's raised $200,000, some of it through the
Internet via e-mail appeals to pro-gun groups. Alan Keyes, the
former U.N. ambassador and conservative commentator, will appear at
a fund-raiser for her Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign manager Tom Campbell expects to start TV ads this week,
but the campaign may save its biggest punch for the final days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is plenty of time to get our message out,'' Campbell
said. ``I think typically a lot of people make up their mind late
even in a normal election.'' And she does plan to attack, on
abortion and on Isakson's leadership role in the Cobb County
campaign for a sales tax to build schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christina is unashamedly pro-life and it's going to be an
important issue. . .We have to say that Johnny Isakson is
campaigning as a Reagan Republican, when his record is of a
tax-and-spend liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Doublestein, the 44-year-old GOP chairman for the 11th
District, is emphasizing his anti-abortion stance in his fliers and
on his Web site. He brings to the race a core of Gwinnett County,
Ga. voters.
</P>
<P>
   Gary ``Bats'' Pelphrey, the only declared Democrat in the race,
also may linger in the minds of voters. He ran against Gingrich in
November, getting 29 percent of the vote. His advertising budget is
nearly zero, except for some campaign stickers. But he has the most
sophisticated Web site of any candidate _ and is the only one whose
site includes Internet links to the other candidates, so that
voters can comparison shop.
</P>
<P>
   Pelphrey is trying to circumvent his cash disadvantage by
encouraging forums and town meetings. He rented a theater on Monday
night for a town meeting under the Gingrich-like theme, ``The
Challenges of Maturing America.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two candidates are Andrew Naples, a 46-year-old
electrical engineer and businessman, who said he has budgeted about
$70,000 in personal money for the race, and write-in candidate
Kelly Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 6th District candidates, particularly those with no
campaign experience, are trying to figure out where to spend their
scarce _ and often hard-earned _ dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The Web sites offer the cheapest way of advertising the
candidate's views to the public _ but they reach a limited
audience. Candidates can't target their message to likely voters
or, more importantly, use it to push likely supporters to go to the
polls. Bullock noted that candidates still had to advertise their
Web sites to the public to make them semi-helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't reach the vast hundred of thousands of people who
live in that district by word of mouth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Perdue is a longtime Georgia political consultant who
specializes in the campaigns of conservative candidates. His
advice? Those trying to defeat Isakson would be best served by a
direct-mail campaign. Cable television and radio are the next-best
mediums for reaching the anti-Isakson voters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For my money, direct mail is the most potent use of your
resources,'' he said. ``A small, dedicated base can swing that
election. And you don't get to that dedicated base by television
that goes all over. You go directly into their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Visser writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
