<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITTING HOME BASE FROM A FISHING BOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dusty Baker reared back with his fishing rod,
then sailed a long, seamless cast into the murky flows of the San
Francisco Bay. It was a dark, rainy day, and few others were out on
the water, figuring there was no hope. But Dusty smiled at what
that cast might bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 23 on the Braves, Luke Appling took me aside and
told me, `To be lucky, you've got to think lucky,''' he said.
``That goes for anything. If you don't think lucky in fishing, you
don't catch any fish. Am I lucky? It's true, I'm lucky. If you
think you're lucky, that's what you get.''
</P>
<P>
   He was in a state of relaxed focus on the boat, poising his
fishing rod in his hands, ready to set the hook on a rare bite from
a sturgeon the same way he once awaited a rare fastball in the
batter's box. Baker not only believes in himself, you quickly
discover, but he's a believer in the hope that every day can bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I can remember, the outdoors is where everything
has started for me,'' Baker said. ``My dad is 74 years old, and I
love him, and I really love him for turning me on to fishing when I
was a kid. We fished almost every weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   For quite a while, Dusty and I have been talking about putting a
fishing trip together, and every time the subject comes up, the
conversation always turns to sturgeon _ the often elusive prize
fish that can grow to hundreds of pounds, capable of 200-yard power
runs and pirouetting, whale-like jumps. So we hooked up at Loch
Lomond Harbor in San Rafael, aboard the custom charter boat
Imagine, then headed south, under the Richmond Bridge, anchoring in
20 feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   And there the fun started. As he settled in, waiting for his
bite, he explained on one recent trip he contracted a new ailment
called ``fishing elbow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went up on the Columbia River, and got together with Trevor
Wilson and Tom Lampkin, who live up there,'' Baker said, referring
to players now with the San Francisco Giants and the Seattle
Mariners, respectively. ``We fished 4 1/2 hours and caught (and
released) 28 sturgeon. Next morning I was so sore, and it hit me, I
had `fishing elbow' for the first time in my entire life.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he grinned, and you don't know if he's putting you on or
not. But that's fishing. And that's Dusty.
</P>
<P>
   You discover there are two sides to him, and they aren't even
friends. On one side is this tough-love guy with an all-consuming
drive to build the Giants into a perennial big winner, a guy who
takes no guff from anyone, including Barry Bonds, and whose concept
of presence is to lead, follow or get the hell out of his way. On
the other side, though, is this relaxed, playful character who
fishes to blow off steam and to have fun, often sharing his
adventures with players.
</P>
<P>
   Put the two together and you have a man with a straight-ahead
approach, a man with both smarts and a sense of magic about him.
The qualities have made the Giants manager one of the most popular
leaders in San Francisco Bay sports history among both fans and
players.
</P>
<P>
   Many Giants, past and present, often join him on fishing trips.
The best known are Mike Jackson, Darren Lewis, Robby Thompson, Kirt
Manwaring, Matt Williams, Steve Reed and batting coach Gene Clines,
heading out with one of Baker's best friends, Armand Castagna, a
professional skipper who owns and operates the Imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armand's looking forward to the new stadium where he can come
and pick me up at the dock right at the park,'' Baker said with a
smile. ``Especially with a 12:30 game, you could be out of there by
4 or 4:30, hopefully with a victory, then fish four or five hours
until dark. I mean, that is awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Castagna grinned. ``We already got it planned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going for the grand slam of fishing in the Bay,
sturgeon, halibut, striped bass and salmon,'' Baker added. ``We get
three of them, but we always seem to miss one.''
</P>
<P>
   The outdoors teaches how hope can be rewarded, and Baker learned
his most memorable lesson on a late summer evening off the Marin
coast, on a trip with Castagna, Lewis, Manwaring and Galen Onizuka,
a longtime fieldscout.
</P>
<P>
   As Castagna tells it, Baker hooked a big salmon at 6:45 p.m. off
Stinson Beach, and battled that fish past sunset and into darkness.
Over and over, the fish surged off on runs and power drives in a
fight that spanned 2 1/2 miles of water, all the way to Muir Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``At dusk, Bake had it close enough to the boat to see its tail,
and it was like 12 inches across, a 50-pounder for sure,'' Castagna
said.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:30 p.m., as darkness was taking over, the big salmon
suddenly powered off on a big run straight into the surf, made it
to some rocks, and was able to break the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing was unbelievable,'' Dusty remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, `The Old Man and the Sea' was one of my favorite
books, because I didn't know whether I was pulling for the old man
or the fish,'' he said, referring to the book by Ernest Hemingway.
``That day that fish got me, took me in the rocks, and he won. You
want to win all the time, but you have to tip your hat to the
opposition. I didn't lose. He beat me. There's a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled, baited his hook, then cast out again, ready for
whatever the day might bring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
