</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCOM-CHINA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Co. plans to invest thwarted
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Plans by Southern Co. to invest in a state-owned
Chinese power company were set back Monday when Shandong
International Power Development Co. withdrew an overseas stock
sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed that we are not able to make a strategic
investment in the company at this time,'' said Southern spokesman
Chuck Griffin. ``We hope the market will rebound quickly and give
Shandong an opportunity to complete the offering.''
</P>
<P>
   Shandong, uneasy about the Chinese economy, said it shelved
plans for an initial public offering on the Hong Kong Stock
Exchange ``after considering the recent highly volatile market
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., had been handling the sale of 25 percent
of the regional power entity to raise $285 million. Southern was
expected to buy 40 percent of the shares being sold for $114
million. That would have given the Atlanta-based company a 9.9
percent stake in Shandong.
</P>
<P>
   Shandong became third major Chinese firm in one month to cancel
a stock offering amid growing concerns by foreign investors about
the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The withdrawal reflects investors' caution toward emerging
markets worldwide,'' said Peter Rose, a Goldman Sachs spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Shandong International owns 13 electric power plants in Shandong
province, which is 300 miles north of Shanghai on the Yellow Sea
coast. It plans to build more.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin said Southern will continue to look for opportunities to
expand its Chinese holdings. Southern operates one power plant in
Guangdong Province and is part of a joint venture that plans to
build another unit in Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew C. Quinn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Bloomberg News contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
