<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ANTARCTICA-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTARCTICA ISN'T ORLANDO, BUT CROWDS ARE A WORRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 14)  
(mk) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite Antarctica's ice, snow, isolation, high winds and raging
seas (and for hardy types, precisely for these reasons), the
continent will be visited by an estimated 11,200 people this
tourist season, all but about 130 of them on cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   While that total is only about 400 more than the number of
visitors last season (mid-November through February), it is 70
percent higher than the 6,585 visitors during the 1992-93 season.
Some Antarctica watchers, including Neil Plimmer, a past president
of the Pacific Asia Travel Association, are concerned about its
environment have warned there could be 14,000 annual Antarctic
visitors by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of Antarctic cruises can easily reach $20,000 a person,
and the average 14-day cruise is a still-hefty $6,000 to $7,000,
plus round-trip air fare to Ushuaia, Argentina, in Tierra del
Fuego, from which 90 percent of the trips depart. But while
Antarctica appears insulated from tourist hordes because of cost
and its formidable geography and climate, some environmentalists
contend that it may already have reached its capacity to absorb
tourists without suffering lasting ecological damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should have an opportunity to see Antarctica's beauty,
but there should be a cap on the number of visitors and a ban on
any new sites,'' said Beth Clark, director of the Antarctic
Project, the Washington-based secretariat for more than 200
conservation organizations in more than 40 countries. ``It's true
that once people visit Antarctica they come back committed to its
conservation, but the downside is that there are so many visitors
and Antarctica is so fragile that there's a danger they're loving
it to death.''
</P>
<P>
   A major concern of Ms. Clark, who favors a limit of 6,000
visitors a year, is that most tourists visit the same few places on
the 800-mile-long Antarctic Peninsula, which has the continent's
biggest concentration of penguins, seals and birds. Though tour
groups setting foot on land rarely exceed 100 visitors at a time,
``The animals don't get much rest between visits and don't have
much time to get food for themselves or their young,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Science doesn't yet know whether this will have long-term
impact,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Among the concerns are that tourists will touch plants and leave
garbage behind.
</P>
<P>
   Darrel Schoeling, executive director of the 8-year-old
International Association of Antarctica Tour Operators, whose 16
members account for most of the visitors, said those operators are
also concerned about the long-term impact on the environment. He
said that most of them are environmentalists and that it is in
their long-term financial interest to protect the continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why when visitors go ashore, there are large and
experienced staffs to insure they have minimal impact,'' he said,
``and why the tour operators adhere to the guidelines for visitors
adopted by the Antarctic Treaty System.''
</P>
<P>
   That series of agreements includes the 1959 Antarctic Treaty,
since signed by 43 nations, plus an environmental protocol that
since Jan. 14, 1998, has banned mining and oil drilling and
provided other environmental safeguards, including fishing limits.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the tour association, which is based in New York,
voluntarily adopted the 100-person limit for shore visits, for
which they use motorized rubber boats called Zodiacs, and wrote
into their bylaws a 400-passenger limit on cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   The eight U.S. members of the association are Abercrombie &AMP;
Kent, Clipper Cruise Line, Quark Expeditions, Mountain Travel
Sobek, Society Expeditions, Travel Dynamics, Zegrahm Expeditions
and Special Expeditions. Also, Radisson Seven Seas is one of 13
associate members offering occasional Antarctic cruises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the 15 vessels in Antarctica this season, nine fly Russian
flags,'' said Schoeling, who explained that the breakup of the
Soviet Union made a number of small ships available to tour
operators like the ones in his group. Those ships, including an
icebreaker and several other vessels whose hulls were hardened
against ice, carry from 40 to 80 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The Marco Polo (known as the Aleksandr Pushkin while still a
Russian ship) can carry 800. But even after its owner, Orient
Lines, was acquired last year by Norwegian Cruise Line (which does
not belong to the tour association), the Marco Polo has continued
to limit passengers to 500, and otherwise complies with the tour
association's self-imposed limits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though, concern about Antarctica's environment
persists. ``It's possible that in the future, we'll look back and
say, `No problem, we worried about it needlessly,''' said Ms. Clark
of the Antarctic Project. ``But until science comes up with the
answers, we owe it to Antarctica and to ourselves to put limits on
our travels there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
