<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: BEAUTY SECRETS OF YORE; PASSPORT TO ENTERTAINMENT;
LANDMARK FILMS; ON THE FRINGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pear's Soap was endorsed by the diva Adelina Patti
and the Brooklyn preacher Henry Ward Beecher. Hunter's Invisible, a
face powder, was favored by the actress Lillie Langtry. And in the
days when these people were celebrities, others in search of good
looks could buy Laird's Bloom of Youth (which treated the
complexion with lead paint) and Dupin's Arsenic Complexion Tablets
(taken internally).
</P>
<P>
   Such products _ marketed, packaged and promoted for men and
women much as their counterparts are today _ enhance ``Secrets of a
Beautiful Face.'' Timed for Valentine's Day, the exhibition of
beauty product advertisements and related artifacts opens Tuesday
and runs through April 11 at the New-York Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Bargain Days
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From Uma Thurman in Moliere's ``Misanthrope'' and
James Naughton in his solo show ``Street of Dreams'' to Betty
Buckley in Nicky Silver's ``Eros Trilogy'' and Kathleen Chalfant in
``Wit,'' more than 200 events in theater, dance, comedy and
improvisation are available at a discount through April 30 by means
of the free ``Passports to Off Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by the Alliance of Resident Theaters, the trade and
service organization for Off Broadway, the passports and a schedule
of attractions and discounts may be obtained by calling (888)
625-5129.
</P>
<P>
   Celebration Sightings
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Call them a reverse anniversary present. Among the
attractions are ``The Bridge on the River Kwai'' (1957), ``Close
Encounters of the Third Kind'' (1977), ``It Happened One Night''
(1934), ``Lawrence of Arabia'' (1962), ``On the Waterfront'' (1954)
and ``Taxi Driver'' (1976). These landmark films are among a dozen
coming from Columbia Pictures as it observes its 75th anniversary
this winter and spring.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen from Columbia's features on the American Film Institute
list of the 100 greatest American films, these selections form part
of a festival that opens on Friday and runs through Feb. 25 at
Sony's Lincoln Square in Manhattan and Pacific's Cinerama Dome in
Los Angeles before moving to other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Show Time
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Applications for the third annual New York
International Fringe Festival, which plans to present nearly 200
productions by emerging theater companies and performing artists
from Aug. 18 to 29, are now available.
</P>
<P>
   The festival will include not only theater and performance art
but also dance, children's theater, buskers and multimedia
presentations from 3 p.m. to midnight daily at downtown Manhattan
sites. The applications, due March 5, are available by calling
(212) 420-8877 or writing to Fringe NYC at 198 Stanton St., New
York, N.Y. l0002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
