<HEADER>
A6618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-microsoft09-cox     02-08 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-microsoft09-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT: NETSCAPE CAUSED ITS OWN WOES
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington queues
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Netscape's reversals in its browser wars with
Microsoft stemmed from a shortsighted business strategy that sought
to ``gouge'' Internet service providers, according to the antitrust
testimony of a key Microsoft Corp. executive released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron Myhrvold, who is due to take the stand at the landmark
federal case Tuesday, contends that Netscape Communications Corp.
``sought to charge (providers) very high prices for distributing
Netscape's Web browsing software,'' called Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   Myhrvold's direct attack against Netscape marks a shift of
strategy on the part of the Microsoft defense team in the trial,
which has entered its 15th week.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends that Microsoft launched a predatory
attack against rival Netscape by cutting illegal deals.
Specifically, the government alleges, Microsoft gave its browsing
technology away as it sought to leverage its huge Windows market
power into a commanding position in the newly booming realm of
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeking to gouge (the providers) was shortsighted and
encouraged them to explore alternatives,'' Myhrvold wrote in 57
pages of direct testimony. Myhrvold, 37, is a Microsoft vice
president charged with managing the software giant's business
relationships with firms that operate public networks.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape's browser prices were set when the high-flying company
had ``a commanding 80-90 percent usage share, and Netscape did not
adjust its prices downward until (providers) refused to pay them
any longer,'' Myhrvold maintained.
</P>
<P>
   Turning the government's argument on its head, Myhrvold said it
was Microsoft that came to the industry's rescue when Internet
providers ``were no longer forced to agree to (Netscape's) price
when alternatives appeared on the scene that were equal (or
superior) to Navigator.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, on the witness stand, William Poole, senior director
of business development for Windows, defended the Microsoft
practice, since abandoned, of signing contracts that obliged
Windows-based software developers to break their promotional ties
to Netscape when joining the Microsoft camp.
</P>
<P>
   For example, under a 1997 accord, Intuit Inc. got a ``platinum''
deal to appear in the business portion of the so-called Channel Bar
on the Windows 95 desktop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds to me like you're trying to give us the impression
that Intuit came to you and said 'We'd like to use your browser,'''
David Boies, the lead government attorney told Poole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not implying that,'' Poole replied, ``It's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies then pulled out a stack of internal Microsoft e-mails that
appeared to refute that claim. In one of them, Microsoft chairman
Bill Gates said Intuit could get favorable placement in the Windows
operating system only by agreeing to use its browser.
</P>
<P>
   That approach goes to the heart of the government's charge that
Microsoft used unfair tactics to compete against Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in the courthouse plazas, Boies, recounting
previously-introduced testimony, referred to a $1 million payment
from Microsoft to Intuit proposed by Gates in his message as a
``bribe.'' But Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray said the payment,
had it been made, would have served merely as compensation for
``sunken costs'' that Intuit had incurred when it switched to
Internet Explorer, the Microsoft browser.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
