<HEADER>
A6633 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     02-08 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIFIC GOALS CAN EXCEED YOUR MILDEST DREAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Q In my performance review a few weeks ago, my
manager told me to come up with some goals for myself. We just had
a meeting to go over them, and he said he was disappointed that my
goals were so vague and poorly thought out. We are supposed to meet
again, but I am not sure my goals are going to be any different.
What am I supposed to do? A.K. &QL; 
A In a word, it sounds like one of your goals is to come up with
better goals. Although it would have been nice for your manager to
be less vague in terms of what he expects, the fact is that the
goals at work do need to be rather specific.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you indicated to your manager that your goal is
to be a more productive employee, it is possible for your manager
to indicate that this is not a goal. Rather, this type of statement
is better called a hope or a wish.
</P>
<P>
   If your goal is to be more productive, you need to include the
specifics. For example, you should spell out the actions you will
take to improve your productivity, the priorities and deadlines,
and how you will measure the productivity increases.
</P>
<P>
   When you are establishing work goals for yourself, it is
important to look at each and be able to answer the questions of
who, what, where, when, why and how. Wishes, hopes and dreams are
important, but if you want to make them come true, they need to be
recast as goals. &QL; 
Q Many companies in this area have ``casual Fridays'' where the
employees can dress more casually. Our company does not do this,
and I am annoyed about it, and so are many of my fellow employees.
We have talked to management, and they adamantly refuse to change.
Do you have any suggestions? S.F. &QL; 
A The only suggestion at this point is that you should not go out
and stock up on casual attire. This change has to come from
management, and it sounds like management is not interested in
changing policies or changing clothes.
</P>
<P>
   It may be helpful to look back at the strategy you used in your
meeting with management. For example, if you used more of a
complaint mode than a sales mode, it is not surprising that
management responded with an inflexible mode. It is important to
let management see the advantages and benefits associated with
casual Fridays. You can even suggest that they be implemented on a
trial basis.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to determine how to approach management from this
point, it will be helpful for you to understand whether the refusal
to budge is a reflection of corporate rigidity, emphasis on
tradition, refusal to follow the herd, or any other number of
factors. You should tailor a presentation with such factors in mind
and revisit management, remembering that management often strives
to make decisions that wear well with the employees. &QL; 
Q Our human resources specialist just sent me the new application
blanks we are now supposed to use. This new form she developed is
very bland and does not ask the kinds of questions that are
important to us. None of us want to use it. What do you think we
should do now? E.C. &QL; 
A Since you feel that your application blank is better described as
an application bland, you should meet with the human resources
specialist to discuss your concerns. Every change that she made may
be warranted, but what is unwarranted is her lack of communication
associated with the development and introduction of the new form.
</P>
<P>
   One reason why you may not like the new application blank is
that all of the questions are job related, just as the law
requires. However, these questions can generate a wide range of
very important information. Through a well-designed application
blank, you can get a picture of the applicant's work history, along
with insight into his or her training, skills and abilities that
relate to the job, and this is highly predictive data.
</P>
<P>
   You can also learn something about an applicant through the way
that he or she completes the application blank. After all, this is
the first work assignment. Did the applicant approach it thoroughly
and carefully?
</P>
<P>
   If there are job-related or technical questions that you would
like to see included in the application blank, be sure to mention
these to the human relations specialist. But, if the questions you
would like to add include issues such as race, religion, sex, age,
national origin, or any other issues that have nothing to do with
the job, the human relations specialist is going to have questions
about you. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
X X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
