<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulls' home opener not as much cause for celebration as in years
pastBy Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ At one point Friday in the Chicago Bulls'
opening-night game at Utah, Ron Harper sensed his team about to
drop out of contention and needing help.
</P>
<P>
   As he told the story later, Harper looked around for Scottie
Pippen and Michael Jordan and at that moment realized he was
staring at the rest of his basketball career without them. ``Oh,
God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Chicago's fans haven't accepted that already, the new state
of the Bulls will be brought home tonight when they play their home
opener against the Atlanta Hawks. The game is sold out, but
attendance is not compulsory.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the '90s, the home opener has been an evening of
celebration for the Bulls. This is the evening in which they handed
out the rings that represented five other championships won the
previous spring. Then they raised another banner and started
another championship quest.
</P>
<P>
   That won't happen, because four principal architects of the
Bulls' sixth championship in eight years have departed the stage,
and neither chairman Jerry Reinsdorf nor general manager Jerry
Krause wants to face a hostile audience since allowing the team to
be torn apart after Michael Jordan retired last month.
</P>
<P>
   But for the banner, it will be a routine opening night, and the
Hawks will walk out to see rival players who evoke the memories of
David Greenwood, Dave Corzine and Orlando Woolridge, featured
players on mediocre Bulls teams of the '80s. Already, the Bulls are
being treated as just another mediocre team. Sunday night in the
Los Angeles Sports Arena, they barely held on to beat the Clippers
before an announced 6,118.
</P>
<P>
   A chance for a little revenge? Steve Smith was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep. I'd rather play against Mike and Scottie because you want
to compete against the best, but it won't bother me if we beat 'em
by 30,'' Smith said. ``They used to do it to everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Toni Kukoc and Ron Harper, key figures in recent
years, the Bulls who will labor on your television screens tonight
are journeymen.
</P>
<P>
   Starting center Andrew Lang, cast off by Milwaukee to open
salary-cap room, started his career in Phoenix and also has served
stints in Philadelphia, Atlanta and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Starting power forward Mark Bryant played off the bench in
Portland and Phoenix. He was a throw-in to the sign-and-trade deal
that allowed center Luc Longley to join the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   The one bright light new to the team is Brent Barry, who came
aboard as a free agent, much sought after he decided he would never
again play for Pat Riley in Miami. But this is his third team in
four seasons. A clever passer, Barry, with a frame that is all
skin, bone and sinew, plays Jordan's position, but he is neither a
particularly good shooter nor physically strong enough to defend
well.
</P>
<P>
   Again, none of that will disturb the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Five times, Jordan &AMP; Co. knocked the Hawks or Lenny Wilkens'
Cleveland teams out of the playoffs. That cannot happen again.
``They had a great run,'' the coach said, implying that now it is
someone else's turn.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks, 2-1, would like to be that someone. They have
completed their single assignment of three games in three nights
and now can settle into a schedule that is merely arduous, no
longer ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to the Knicks to face three sets of three in a row and
others to do it at least twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me mad we had to start the season like that,'' Dikembe
Mutombo said. ``It was ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, then having the opportunity to face a weakened Bulls team
takes the Hawks to the opposite circumstance: the sublime.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
