<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Browns look to rebuild franchise with big-name veterans
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The resurrection of one of the NFL's most storied franchises
moves another significant step forward this afternoon when
Cleveland Browns officials are expected to acquire 30 to 35 veteran
players in the NFL's special expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   While the pool of 150 available players includes several
high-profile performers, most notably all-time sack leader Reggie
White, the only connection between players selected by the Browns
and the Hall of Fame is that the lottery is being conducted at the
pro football shrine in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is toward (taking) younger players, guys we can build
with and who should be able to help us two or three years down the
road,'' Browns general manger Dwight Clark said Monday. ``There are
several players who fit that description and who excite us.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules of the expansion draft stipulate that the Browns can
select between 30 and 42 veterans or expend 38 percent of the
projected $58 million salary cap, about $22 million. Officials said
Monday the club won't come close to the $22 million mark in cap
designations for the players taken today. In the most recent
``mock'' draft, the Browns took 30 to 33 players, at an aggregate
cap total of about $15 million, a team official acknowledged
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The league's free-agent signing period begins Friday, and the
Browns are expected to pursue some of the better-known unrestricted
veterans ardently.
</P>
<P>
   When Carolina and Jacksonville entered the NFL in 1995, they
took 35 and 31 players, respectively. Only 15 of those players made
the Panthers roster in '95 and just one, wide receiver Mark
Carrier, still is with the team. The Jaguars kept 22 veterans from
the expansion draft on the roster, but only three remain now.
</P>
<P>
   High on the Browns list are safety Charles Mincy (Tampa Bay);
offensive linemen Todd Rucci (New England), Jeff Buckey (Miami) and
Jerry Reynolds (N.Y. Giants); and defensive linemen Ferric Collons
(New England), Jose White (Jacksonville) and Marcus Jones (Tampa
Bay).
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
