<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-JONES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daytona debut disappointing for Jones and crew
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The life of a rookie on NASCAR's Winston
Cup circuit is tough enough, but Buckshot Jones of Tucker, Ga. has
had more than his share of obstacles in preparing for Sunday's
Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a University of Georgia graduate who now lives in
Spartanburg, S.C., decided not to participate in second-round
qualifying for Thursday's Gatorade 125 twin races, which determine
positions 3 through 30 of the Daytona 500 field.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 28, also won't drive his No. 00 Pontiac in today's
third-round qualifying, so he'll stand on his speed from Saturday,
which was 44th out of 57 drivers at 189.641 mph. That means Jones
will start one of the 125s near the back row.
</P>
<P>
   And Jones will have to finish in the top 14 of his qualifier to
make the field for his first Daytona 500. Jones pulled out of
qualifying after another slow practice time on Monday. Now, his
crew will have two additional days to dissect the car's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Monday's practice) was worse,'' Jones said. ``We thought that
maybe we were really doing something wrong. That's why we got the
people from Hendricks Motorsports (which owns Jeff Gordon's team)
to look at our car. We kind of got a setup from them, and we went
back out, but the car actually ran a little bit slower.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just leaves us to believe that we've got a serious
problem with the chassis or the body somewhere. The thing that's
frustrating is that I don't think you could bring in an expert and
he could tell you exactly what's wrong with our car.''
</P>
<P>
   Daytona's Speed Weeks have been a disappointing start for Jones,
the most popular driver on NASCAR's Busch Series last season. After
finishing ninth in points and winning one Busch race, Jones thought
his Buckshot Racing team was ready for the jump to Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones already has faced a number of obstacles, including the
car's problems and his team's inability to pick up a primary
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have sponsors in Winston Cup,'' Jones said. ``In
Busch, you could get by for a while. It's not just the money
aspect. I think the guys on the team feel better when there's a
sponsor (logo) on their jackets.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckshot Racing is owned by Billy Jones, the driver's father and
owner of Crown Fiber Communications, a Norcross-based fiber-optic
construction company. The team moved its headquarters to a new $3
million facility in Spartanburg in November.
</P>
<P>
   Buckshot Racing enters this season with Crown Fiber as the car's
primary sponsor. Billy Jones spent much of the offseason
negotiating a sponsorship with United Parcel Service but never
reached an agreement. Jones denies a widespread rumor on the
circuit that UPS axed the deal after he shipped contracts back to
UPS using Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   ``If UPS would have sent me that contract, they would have never
had to worry about it being shipped back by UPS or Federal
Express,'' Jones said. ``I would have hand-delivered it. Even if I
had made that mistake, UPS isn't the type of company that would
have killed the contract for that kind of mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckshot Jones will be fighting for more than a sponsor and a
spot in the Daytona 500 when he drives in Thursday's qualifiers. He
also will be trying to shed his label as an aggressive, and
sometimes reckless, driver. He earned that reputation during his
much-publicized feud with driver Randy LaJoie on the Busch Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect the good with the bad,'' Jones said. ``I think a lot
of the stuff came from me and Randy. . . . I am aggressive. But
there's a difference between being aggressive and reckless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll put the bumper to somebody. If you're running in the
back, no, you don't need to be aggressive. But if I'm behind you
and I bump you a little bit because I'm faster, that's racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracks on the Winston Cup series can be lonely for rookies, as
veterans often are reluctant to draft or drive side by side with
new drivers. Some veterans are waiting for Jones to prove himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a lot of Busch races for ESPN as a commentator,''
veteran driver Kyle Petty said. ``I saw some of the stuff that's
gone on on the race track with Buckshot. Some of the stuff, I'm
going to tell you, has been his fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm still willing to give him the benefit of the doubt on
a lot of it, because with a lot of things that have happened and a
lot of the things that he's been blamed for, he was white as the
driven snow. It was not his fault, but everybody instantly went,
`Buckshot.' He's got that reputation, but he's got an opportunity
to come here and start all over. Hopefully, he'll make the best of
it and not put himself in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his team's struggles at Daytona, Billy Jones predicted
that his son would win a Winston Cup points championship in three
years. Buckshot Jones predicted he'd win rookie of the year over
Elliott Sandler and Tony Stewart, who are driving for more
established teams.''
</P>
<P>
   With his car struggling, Jones will get a shot Thursday at
proving his driving ability _ and an opportunity to earn the trust
of NASCAR veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always though Buckshot was the minus on our team,'' Billy
Jones said. ``Right now, our car is the minus on our team. We just
can't figure it out. We're getting outside help, and we can't
figure it out. But when it comes to racing, Buckshot can race with
the best of them. He's our plus in this deal right now. This won't
be the first time he's started in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
