<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auburn could make history in game against Ole Miss
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Auburn basketball that has gone where no other SEC team had
gone before could add another historic accomplishment to its resume
tonight when the Tigers host Mississippi at 9:30 p.m. (ESPN).
</P>
<P>
   Auburn (22-1, 10-1 SEC) already has earned distinction as the
first SEC team to win 20 games by the end of January. Mighty
Kentucky won 19 games before February four times, but it never hit
the 20 mark.
</P>
<P>
   With Cincinnati, Stanford, and Kentucky all losing last week,
Auburn enters tonight's game ranked No. 3 behind Duke and
Connecticut. It is Auburn's highest ranking since 1959, when the
Tigers started 19-0 and were ranked No. 2 for one week. The next
week they lost to Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   If Auburn can get by Ole Miss (17-7, 7-4) tonight, it will be
the first team in school history to post 23 victories. Sonny
Smith's teams in 1985 and 1986 were 22-12 and 22-11, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, we're really not talking about all that
kind of stuff,'' said Cliff Ellis, now getting some support for
national coach of the year. ``It's good for the fans, but I'm not
sure it's healthy for the players to get caught up in all that
stuff. When you get on a ride like this, it's really important to
just focus on one game at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis doesn't want to look ahead, but the Auburn fans can't
resist. Starting tonight, the Tigers play their next three games at
home, where they have won 13 in a row. Auburn then finishes the
regular season with road games at Arkansas (16-7) and Mississippi
State (16-8).
</P>
<P>
   It is not inconceivable that Auburn could run the table and
then, barring an early exit in the SEC Tournament in Atlanta, they
could grab yet another piece of history: A No. 1 seed in the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The odds are in Auburn's favor. After a three-game suspension
for violating team rules, junior Chris Porter came off the bench
Saturday night to score 23 points and pull down 12 rebounds in an
80-54 thumping of LSU. Included in those 23 points was a putback
dunk that will make everybody's highlight reel.
</P>
<P>
   Porter will be back in the starting lineup tonight, which can't
be good news for the Rebels, who are fighting to get an NCAA bid.
Mississippi has won five of its last six, including Saturday's
79-68 upset of Florida in Gainesville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI AT AUBURN
</P>
<P>
   When: 9:30 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Beard-Eaves Memorial Coliseum, Auburn, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   TV: ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Records: Mississippi 17-7, 7-4 SEC; No. 3 Auburn 22-1, 10-1 SEC
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
