</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside pro tennis: Chang, Gambill sign on for AT&AMP;T
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Michael Chang and Jan-Michael Gambill are the first
players confirmed for the AT&AMP;T Challenge, April 26-May 2 at Atlanta
Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, who bypassed Atlanta last year, is a two-time AT&AMP;T
champion (1994-95) who suffered through wrist and knee injuries
last year, resulting in his worst campaign of the decade. The
former No. 2 player is now at No. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, who will turn 27 later this month, showed signs he can
still be a top-10 player at the Australian Open, where he took
Goran Ivanisevic five sets before losing 7-5 in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill, ranked No. 37, is the best young American player on
tour and had wins last year over Andre Agassi, Alex Corretja, Tim
Henman and Mark Philippoussis.
</P>
<P>
   Not his best on clay, Gambill made his Atlanta debut last year
and lost in the second round. He beat Mariano Zabaleta in the first
round after trailing 6-0, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ProServ, which owns the AT&AMP;T Challenge, is still pursuing
defending champion Pete Sampras and Boris Becker.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras back on court
</P>
<P>
   Sampras makes his 1999 debut this week in San Jose, Calif. and
has an easy draw to the semifinals, where he could face
Philippoussis. Sampras' 10-week break was his longest since he
returned to finish the 11th grade in 1988. Sampras last week
officially declared himself unavailable for the first-round Davis
Cup match in Great Britain. Expect the U.S. to field a lineup of
Gambill and Todd Martin, perhaps Vince Spadea, against the Brits'
Henman and Greg Rusedski. ``I'm not going to enjoy the criticism,''
Sampras said, ``but at what price are you going to sacrifice your
goals? . . . I can't finish the year No. 1 and play Davis Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose points
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis is No. 1 again, as of Monday's new WTA Tour
rankings. Lindsay Davenport had ended Hingis' 75-week reign at the
U.S. Open. Hingis is 14-1 this year, including last week's
tournament title in Tokyo. . . . The decision by the Czech Republic
to ban Petr Korda from playing in his home country won't have any
practical effect, because Korda wasn't likely to play there,
anyway. He wasn't planning on playing Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Holcomb writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
