<SLUG> BC-OLY-SURVEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Majority blames IOC for current Olympics scandal
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) general news and (s) sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The ongoing Olympic bribery scandal appears to be
taking a toll on the public's perception of the Games as the
embodiment of success, high standards and fair play.
</P>
<P>
   The Games now are all about ``big business and money,'' say more
than half of 200 Americans surveyed in an independent study on the
public's attitudes about the Olympics since the influence-peddling
scandal surrounding the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City broke
late last year.
</P>
<P>
   And about four of 10 respondents said their overall impression
of the Games has been lessened by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted Feb. 1-5 by Performance Research of
Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are the Games tainted by the stain of commercialism,
but more than half of the public now says it thinks they are
``becoming just like big professional sports events filled with
strikes and controversies.''
</P>
<P>
   Although negative impressions about the Olympic ideals have been
created, the public mostly blames the International Olympic
Committee rather than the cities that compete aggressively to host
the Games.
</P>
<P>
   And corporate sponsors, who are paying the billions to stage the
sporting extravaganzas, generally are forgiven. Fewer than
one-fourth of the respondents said they were less likely to support
Olympic sponsors because of the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, for all the sort of beauty and altruism associated
with the Olympic ideal, people recognize there is a cost associated
with that,'' said Susan Rosenberg, spokeswoman for Atlanta-based
United Parcel Service, a worldwide sponsor of the Games. ``And in
the United States, that cost is not going to be borne by the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   But just under half would join in the resounding call for the
resignation of IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch. Nearly six in
10 placed blame for the scandal on the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I don't think the taint will be removed until
Samaranch goes,'' said Gene DeWitt, a New York-based consultant who
buys advertising time on Olympic broadcasts for sponsors. ``It
happened on his watch, and he has run this like a dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey did find that more than one-fourth thought that Salt
Lake City should not be able to hold the Games because of
allegations that the bidders handed out $800 million in cash,
scholarships and lavish gifts allegedly to try to lure votes.
</P>
<P>
   An internal ethics panel of the Salt Lake City Organizing
Committee is scheduled to make public today its report on bidding
improprieties for the 2002 Winter Games. Nine IOC members have
resigned or tentatively been expelled as a result of the IOC's
internal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the negative responses, three-quarters say they have not
lost trust in the Olympics and what they stand for.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American public looks at things and makes up their own
mind, whether it's what's going on in Washington the last 18 months
or this,'' said Dick Ebersol, president of NBC Sports, which has
invested $3.5 billion in the television rights to the next five
Olympics. ``They see athletes struggling in competition. All they
care about is, 'Do the competition sites work. Is the city pretty.
Are the competitions going to start on time.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
