<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CALLS-PA </SLUG>

 &HT;        PENNSYLVANIANS FLOOD SENATORS WITH CALLS, AS IMPEACHMENT
TRIAL WRAPS UP   By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Feb. 8 -- Of the thousands of Pennsylvanians who
have called their Senators, most say they've had enough of
President Clinton's impeachment trial. But they are split on
whether he should be convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Since the House voted to impeach Clinton in December, Sen. Rick
Santorum's office received 40,000 responses from constituents.
About 70 percent of the calls, e-mails, and letters have been in
favor of a speedy end to the trial. ``The calls have swung back and
forth on whether to convict,'' said Robert Traynham, a spokesman
for Santorum, R-Pa. ``It's like a pendulum ... One day they run
way, and the next it's the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Staffers for Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., report half the calls
he's received are for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Senate impeachment trial is expected to end this
week, calls to the Senators' offices have not picked up, their
staff members said.
</P>
<P>
   Specter's office received ``tens of thousands'' of calls since
the trial began, said his spokesman John Ullyot.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the trial, Specter's office received about 300
calls a day, but the average has since dropped to about 100. ``But
the feelings have been just as intense as from the beginning of the
trial,'' Ullyot said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
