<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6655 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-AMAZON-BOOKS-ART-12     02-08 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-AMAZON-BOOKS-ART-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLISHERS PAY FOR PLAY AT THE AMAZON SITE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating from Sunday for all needing)  
 ATTN: Wash., Calif., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The E-commerce pioneer Amazon.com strives for a clean look for
its online bookstore. That is why executives consider it
unnecessary to clutter its World Wide Web pages and pithy book
recommendations with notices that publishers are starting to pay to
have titles featured as ``New and Notable'' or ``Destined for
Greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapidly growing company began charging publishers modest
fees last summer in a limited experiment. But this year, Amazon
increased the offerings to publishers so that now $10,000 is the
price tag for a premium package for a newly released computer book
_ consideration that includes the top slot on the computer home
page, an author profile or interview and ``complete Amazon.com
editorial review treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice _ which involves using money from publishers called
cooperative advertising allowances _ is a sign of Amazon's growing
power in the book industry, which appears eager to pay tribute to
promote titles ranging from John Grisham's new novel, ``The
Testament,'' to Roy Blount Jr.'s photo book of canine poetry, ``If
Only You Knew How Much I Smell You: True Portraits of Dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a rather delicate move for Amazon, which has distinguished
itself with its thoughtful editorial voice and its staff of
editors, whose recommendations are featured prominently in terse,
one-paragraph blurbs on its home pages for a variety of topics.
From its crowded Seattle offices, Amazon has sought to create a
community of book lovers, who have responded to the bookseller's
advice about ``What We're Reading'' with grateful testimonials
lauding the company for avoiding hype.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's executives insist that their virtual territory is not
for sale because the company reserves the right to reject books for
the program that do not meet their standards of quality. And they
stress that they still feature a majority of titles without charge,
frequently turning down submissions from publishers. However,
several participating publishers said that the titles backed with
advertising dollars were rarely rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't take real estate on our home page and sell it,'' said
Mary Morouse, Amazon's vice president for purchasing. ``I can't
just let anybody believe that you give us a check and we're going
to put it up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the new program has evoked a variety of responses from
publishers. Some are reluctant to discuss the blurring line between
editorial and advertising. Others view the practice as an exciting
new opportunity that is no different from the terrestrial custom of
selling display space in bookstore chains and supermarkets. And
then there are the doubting publishers who view Amazon's move as an
ominous signal that the David in the competitive Internet book wars
is starting to lumber like Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon does have this kind of karma, as if it were a big
independent store and now they're putting that at risk,'' said
Daniel Simon, publisher of Seven Stories Press in Manhattan.
``They're booksellers, but in some respects they're like a book
review, with people turning to them to see what's good. They have a
very special relationship with their readers and you think they
should recognize that they're putting it up for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's fierce No.2 competitor, Barnesandnoble.com, is also
preparing to offer cooperative advertising this year to publishers
although it has not publicly released any details. Its new chief
executive, Jonathan Bulkeley, promises clear distinctions between
editorial material and advertising, possibly by graphically
separating advertising from editorial text.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are areas of editorial that are never for sale at any
price,'' Mr. Bulkeley said, adding that Amazon is ``messing with
the consumer's brains if they're trying to play both sides, but
maybe they can execute it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it will always be a question in my mind: Is this `destined
for greatness' or is this paid for?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Amazon, there was considerable discussion about how to design
the program that the company labels ``E-merchandising.'' Mrs.
Morouse said that a critical concern ``was that we might have a
perception that we're selling placement,'' but she said that the
company believed it had resolved that issue by giving editors the
power to reject books that were nominated by publishers. The
company is also experimenting with a cooperative advertising
program for videos and compact disks, which it also sells online.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to list the specific benefits available to publishers,
Mrs. Morouse declined, saying that the material is ``confidential''
for competitive reasons.
</P>
<P>
   However, internal price documents obtained by The New York Times
indicate that Amazon has increased the scope and price of its
cooperative advertising program since it started offering
opportunities in June.
</P>
<P>
   The company does not accept advertising dollars for its basic
listings of books, which include information about the price and
various reviews from critics and readers. With its expanded
merchandising program, it offers packages that include a wide
variety of features such as its E-mail alerts to customers about
not-yet-published books or placement in the ``What We're Reading''
slots of category pages for cooking or mysteries and thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   In the early experimental stages of its cooperative advertising
program, Amazon listed a price of $500 to put a title on a list
labeled ``What We're Reading'' for two to three days. With its new
price list for the first half of the year, it can cost as much as
$5,000 a title to promote a children's book in the program, which
offers coverage in the ``Destined for Greatness'' slot on a Web
page devoted to best sellers or a top position in Amazon's Kids
Superstore home page.
</P>
<P>
   For a popular adult trade book, $10,000 is the price of a ``Tier
1'' premium package that among other things includes an author
profile, feature coverage in the ``Destined for Greatness''
category and announcements on the home page touting the book's
on-sale date.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster sought such treatment for its marquee author
Stephen King, whose novel of haunted love, ``Bag of Bones,'' was
also promoted as part of the package with ``Best Sellers Delivers''
E-mail alerts to thousands of customers. Typically, publishers are
more generous with money for well-known authors because they have
larger marketing budgets to spend on best-selling, brand-name
writers like King and Grisham. In coming months, John le Carre's
new novel, ``Single &AMP; Single,'' will be featured in a similar
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Such promotions do not contain any notice or visual clue to
indicate that publishers have backed the recommendations with
advertising dollars.
</P>
<P>
   During the development of its merchandising program, Amazon
decided not to include tags because executives believed that they
could provide adequate protection for customers through screening
of books by experienced editors, who specialized in particular
subject categories and often signed their names to E-mail messages
suggesting worthy books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be more distracting to have a book tagged,''
Amazon's Mrs. Morouse said. ``I think that would clutter it up. The
customer experience is really clean and I want to keep it clean.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Amazon's advertising opportunity has been limited to
about 20 to 50 publishers, many of them large companies like Random
House, Simon &AMP; Schuster, Penguin Putnam, HarperCollins, IDG and
Warner Books. But Amazon has plans to expand its offerings to the
next tier of 500 publishers with efforts planned to promote the
program at the book industry's annual trade convention in April.
</P>
<P>
   The program is as much of an experiment for publishers, who are
also trying to determine the effectiveness of this approach.
</P>
<P>
   IDG Books Worldwide, in Foster City, Calif., is so pleased with
the results of its participation that it is increasing its online
marketing. For $2,500, it placed its ``Tax Guides for Dummies'' on
a special seasonal tax center Web page and watched its sales
increase 56 percent after it was posted Jan. 15 and highlighted in
the ``Amazon.com Recommends'' feature, which lauded the title as
one of a handful of ``bellwether'' guides. The Dummies tax guide
also appeared in the ``New and Notable'' category of Amazon's
business and investing Web page.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a virtual world, placement is critical,'' said Steven
Berkowitz, president of IDG, who said the company had paid to
feature at least 20 titles and would continue to do so. The program
works well, he said, because customers feel ``the titles are
recommended.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Books and its sister company, Little, Brown &AMP; Co., are
still evaluating the best strategies for advertising online after
promoting more than 15 books through the program, according to
Sarah Ford, who manages online accounts for Warner.
</P>
<P>
   They paid to feature Roy Blount Jr.'s book of puppy poetry
(``What does that mean `expensive shoe?' I ate it because it
smelled like you.'' ) in Amazon's gift center during the holiday
season and saw sales soar to 1,000 copies a week from about 100.
Amazon's reviewer had advised readers, ``You'll never be able to
resist this entertaining and affectionate look at our canine
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ford said results were also significant for an online
promotion of ``Spyder Web,'' a techno-thriller from Warner Books
that appeared in the ``What We're Reading'' and ``New and Notable''
slots of Amazon's mystery and thriller home page.
</P>
<P>
   In its review, Amazon lauded ``Spyder Web,'' for its ``cool,
careful structure'' and the promise of its first-time author, Tom
Grace, who may represent ``the next generation of Tom Clancys.''
Other critics were more reserved; Kirkus Reviews, which also
appeared on an Amazon listing, labeled the book ``a spirited if
clunky techno-thriller.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's reviewers also praised other books placed by Warner and
Little, Brown. They called Michael Connelly's ``Angels Flight''
``another masterwork'' and featured it on its mystery and thriller
page under the heading ``Amazon.com Recommends.'' They also
commended ``Toyer,'' a featured title placed by Little, Brown, as a
``driving (sometimes melodramatic) suspense novel.'' The New York
Times Book Review panned the same title, about a lunatic who
disabled a series of female victims with a gruesome surgical
procedure, as a ``macabre first novel'' that was ``stunning at
first glance, but hollow at the core.''
</P>
<P>
   The merchandising of featured books can come at a cost, but
Amazon stresses that there are still books worthy of highlighting
without charge. For example, it gave prominent placement free to
``Careless Love,'' the second volume of Peter Guralnick's biography
of Elvis Presley, and the novel ``Amy and Isabelle'' by Elizabeth
Strout.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our home page, the overwhelming majority of featured
books in a given month do not have co-op dollars behind them,''
said Bill Curry, a spokesman for Amazon, who noted that Amazon's
list of top 20 titles last Friday contained at least nine that were
featured without advertising support.
</P>
<P>
   That assurance, though, is not entirely comforting to smaller
publishers who lack large advertising budgets to back their books.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible, because I've been in love with Amazon,'' said
John Oakes, the publisher of Four Walls Eight Windows in New York.
``They're very efficient. They really do a good job. You can't tell
me that they would pick the same books. If they went to people and
said, `We've chosen these books,' there's obviously no independent
publisher who's going to pay 12 grand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
