<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONIC TOLLS PICK UP SPEED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's nothing more annoying than waiting in line, unless it's
waiting in line to pay a toll,'' said Kimberlee Poulton,
spokeswoman for the Florida Department of Transportation, operator
of Florida's Turnpike and other toll roads.
</P>
<P>
   Driving this turnpike its entire 314 miles from Wildwood,
northwest of Orlando, to Florida City in the southeast costs $16.65
in tolls, mostly in 25- and 50-cent bites. Last month, Ms. Poulton
said, the agency began testing Sunpass, an electronic toll-paying
device, on windshields of 5,000 cars using part of this road. By
the summer of 2000, the state hopes to have electronic readers on
all toll roads.
</P>
<P>
   Toll-taking probably predates coins: Herd your flock across my
land, give me a sheep. Comes now the postcoin era: Drive over the
bridge and our zapper will bill you. State and interstate agencies
are moving this way. Florida, New York, Oklahoma, New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, Delaware, Massachusetts, Georgia, Illinois,
Louisiana, Colorado, California and others have electronic systems
either in place or in the works. Not all are compatible with those
of neighboring states, but some are working on a seamless system.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic systems are demonstrably faster: According to the
Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, which uses the E-Z Pass
at its six interstate crossings, a human can collect tolls from 350
cars an hour; the electronic scanner can process up to 1,000 an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the New York Metropolitan Transportation Authority
had its smoothest Thanksgiving Day ever on the Bronx-Whitestone
Bridge, according to Frank Pascual, the agency spokesman: On a
holiday where delays of an hour in toll plazas have been common, he
said, traffic was held up only a minute or so in the morning, and
no more than 10 minutes in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The big change was the E-Z Pass. Pascual says his agency is the
largest electronic toll collector in the world, with 1.5 million
E-Z Passes going through its nine bridges and tunnels. He said the
passes were used by 68 percent of cars using these crossings on
weekdays and 58 percent on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the speed, the electronic pass in some cases is cheaper:
The Port Authority and the Bridges and Tunnels Division of the New
York Metropolitan Transportation Authority, among others, provide
discounts to electronic toll-payers. It also reduces petty
annoyances: No need to fumble with cash, drive a precise distance
from the collection window or wait for a receipt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truckers think Pikepasses are better than sliced bread,'' Jim
Beach, a spokesman for the Oklahoma Turnpike Authority, said of
that state's version. Thirty-eight percent of commercial vehicles
on the 10 state toll roads use them. Some of these roads have no
collection gates at all, only sensors on poles that read the
electronic gadgets, or transponders, as vehicles whip by at 75
miles an hour, the legal limit.
</P>
<P>
   While technophobes and others who fear state intrusion into
their lives may stay forever in the slower lane, MTA figures
indicate that New York area commuters grasp the lesson upon seeing
cars backed up in the cash lane. The agency reports it is still
sending out 7,000 transponders a week.
</P>
<P>
   This means the bulk of ``others'' are those who have come a long
distance to get to New York and are now trapped in the cash lane on
the Henry Hudson Bridge or the Lincoln Tunnel, and those in taxis
traveling over a bridge or through a tunnel, probably to get to an
airport.
</P>
<P>
   In both areas, help is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   All the E-Z Pass agencies in the Northeast say the goal is a
seamless journey: ``One tag, one account.'' This requires
compatible technology: The Florida Sunpass, for example, will not
work in New York, nor will the E-Z Pass in Florida. But the 12
agencies in the E-Z Pass Interagency Group, which come from six
Northeast states _ New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Delaware,
Maryland and Massachusetts _ have set mid-2000 as the time to have
all their toll roads electronic.
</P>
<P>
   The E-Z Pass came to life in 1993 on the New York State
Thruway's Tappan Zee Bridge after an arbitrator rejected an appeal
by toll-takers worried about their safety. A five-mile speed limit
was set in the plaza. The pass is now in use all along the New York
Thruway; on Hudson River crossings; on toll-charging water
crossings into New York City; on the Atlantic City Expressway; on
I-95 in Delaware; on the Massachusetts Turnpike Extension east of
Route 128 around Boston, and in the two Boston Harbor tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Last month Delaware increased tolls on I-95, to $2 from $1.25.
But the E-Z Pass toll, by legislative act, remains at $1.25,
according to Michelle Ackles, a spokeswoman for the State
Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Turnpike Authority, according to James J.
Kerasiotes, the chairman, expects to have the rest of the turnpike
collecting electronic tolls by late June. The transponder is the
same one used in New York, the Mark IV made in Amherst, N.Y., but
it is called the Fastlane there.
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, compatible electronic readers are being installed
on bridges. The New Jersey Turnpike Authority and the Garden State
Parkway have set completion dates for 2000 but are grappling with
difficulties in meeting the deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond Massachusetts, there's Maine, which has put in
noncompatible technology. Rena Barta, program director of the
Interagency Group, said that right now the group was concentrating
on ``intraoperability'' among its own members. But Lynn J. Fleeger
of the New Jersey Turnpike Authority, spokeswoman for the group,
said it had ``heard from'' Virginia and New Brunswick, Canada,
about possibly joining.
</P>
<P>
   If Virginia came in, the squeeze would eventually be on the
bistate authority that operates the Delaware Memorial Bridge, which
connects the New Jersey Turnpike to Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   A special case is posed by those who ride in New York City's
12,187 medallion taxis. Yellow cab fleet owners have had no way to
keep track of how many tolls were paid electronically each day or
which cabbie was on duty at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The city's taxi and limousine commissioner, Diane McGrath
McKechnie, said passengers in hired cars had voiced such distaste
for the cash lane that almost all owners of private livery cars had
installed E-Z Pass devices.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McKechnie said that talks were soon to resume with the MTA
about modifying the recording system to help taxi fleet owners get
the daily accounting of tolls paid that they need. She said the
matter should be cleared up this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some people carry Mark IV transponders with them to hold up at
the windshield so the taxi, rental car or friend's car can use the
E-Z Pass lane. If you use a credit card to get it and keep $25 in
your account to pay tolls with, the gadget is free, just as it is
for car-owners who meet the same criteria.
</P>
<P>
   The number to get an E-Z Pass is (800) 333-8655. If the
expectation of Neil Schuster, executive director of the
International Bridge, Tunnel and Turnpike Association, is correct,
you may one day be able to charge your McDonald's fajita on the
turnpike to your E-Z Pass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
