<SLUG> BC-FRATERNITY-DEATH-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHWEST TEXAS STUDENT, 21, DIES IN BEATING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 21-year-old Southwest Texas State University sophomore from
the Houston area died Monday of injuries he suffered in a beating
at a San Marcos fraternity house.
</P>
<P>
   San Marcos police said Nicholas George Armstrong of Baytown was
found unconscious at 3:15 a.m. Sunday in the Tau Kappa Epsilon
house a short distance from the university campus.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's murder is the first for the Central Texas community
in 1999 and the first death associated with fraternities in at
least 24 years. More than 20,000 students attend Southwest Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Steve Griffith said authorities are looking for two
of four men, alleged ``party crashers,'' who had been involved in a
fight at the fraternity house late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Dean of Students John Garrison said the violence occurred as Tau
Kappa Epsilon and 11 other fraternities that comprise the
Interfraternity Council were holding their acceptance night
festivities. Those parties cap a weeklong alcohol-free ``rush'' or
recruitment period.
</P>
<P>
   The dozen fraternities, some of which were accused of permitting
under-age drinking during the Saturday event, have been suspended,
pending investigation, Garrison said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the groups will be allowed to continue philanthropic
activities, but will not be permitted to recruit members.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the university suspended the Sigma Phi Epsilon
fraternity because of alcohol infractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're calling a halt to it,'' Jim Studer, vice president for
student affairs, told The Associated Press. ``We have a systemic
problem here, and we have to address it as it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a history. We've had problems in the past. We
talked with each of the fraternity presidents (last week) to tell
them to make sure they had things under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrison said no alcohol-related problems were reported at Tau
Kappa Epsilon. Fraternity chapter president Jonathan English could
not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison said university staffers joined by campus police
visited a number of fraternity houses early Sunday to ensure
alcohol policies were being observed.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison said they found one underage student at the local
hospital as a result of drinking; several other students were cited
for underage drinking. About 12:30 a.m., he said, authorities
decided to end the parties.
</P>
<P>
   When they arrived at the Tau Kappa Epsilon house, they were told
that four men, unknown to fraternity members and pledges, had
attempted to crash the party. When they were asked to leave, a
fight broke out and police were called.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong reportedly was not involved in that altercation.
Garrison said after officers left, the student went to sleep on a
sofa. Few if any fraternity members reside in the building full
time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers responding to the second call at 3:15 a.m. found
Armstrong badly beaten on the head. An unidentified witness told
police he had seen two of the earlier intruders in the building
about 15 minutes before Armstrong was found.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects were described as being about 18 years old. One was
about 5-feet-8, weighing about 170 pounds. He had a shaved head,
dark eyes and a severe stutter. The second man was described as
being about 6-feet. He was clean-shaven and had blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith said officers are interested in reviewing videotapes or
photographs made during the party.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
