<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW KOSOVO TALKS A EUROPEAN PRODUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Last week, Hubert Vedrine, the French foreign minister
known more for his candor than discretion, said that the United
States must stop unilaterally imposing its will on the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Ensconced at Rambouillet, a chateau 35 miles southwest of Paris,
Vedrine now has the opportunity to put his words into action.
</P>
<P>
   While the framework document for a settlement being circulated
among the warring factions in Kosovo is largely a product of US
envoy Christopher Hill, the ability to sell the settlement and then
police it will be primarily a European challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The peace talks at Rambouillet are fundamentally different from
those that ended the war in Bosnia in 1995, not simply because the
French chateau is as luxurious as the US air base in Dayton, Ohio,
was spartan. While the Dayton peace deal was led primarily by
Americans, the initiative to end the war in Kosovo is being driven
by the Europeans _ a change that US officials find pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If what Vedrine was saying is that Europeans should take more
responsibility for problems in their own back yard, I don't think
we're going to have a problem with that,'' an American diplomat
said on Saturday, hours before the talks began.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of World War II, when American troops and money
led the reconstruction of Europe, Washington has refused to allow
US troops to serve under the command of European generals. But the
White House has signaled it is prepared to end this rule to keep
the US troop commitment in Kosovo to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   If mediators, including Hill, are able to persuade ethnic
Albanian and Serb negotiators to allow Kosovo limited autonomy
while keeping the province part of Serbia, the Europeans will then
have primary responsibility to implement the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Britain and France, who are sponsoring the talks at Rambouillet,
would provide the bulk of the 30,000-member peacekeeping force sent
into Kosovo if a deal is reached. German troops would also be
deployed there, marking the first time since the end of World War
II that they have been stationed beyond their borders. American
involvement would be minimal _ between 2,000 and 4,000 troops _
compared with some 8,000 British soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Vedrine has not been alone in his blunt calls for new limits on
American power. For the last few months, Jacques Chirac, the
conservative French president, and Lionel Jospin, the socialist
French prime minister, have complained that the United States has
become more than a superpower.
</P>
<P>
   Vedrine describes the United States as a ``hyperpower,''
dominating the world economically, militarily, and culturally. As
bad as the Cold War was, the French say, the emergence of a
hyperpower could be worse, as America arrogantly imposes its
self-interest on the rest of the globe.
</P>
<P>
   But Europeans are divided on the merits of Vedrine's campaign to
dilute American power. While many of his counterparts elsewhere on
the continent agree that Americans can be arrogant, some think
Vedrine has gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   Joschka Fischer, the German foreign minister who as the former
leader of the Green Party has been sharply critical of American
positions on nuclear power, environmental protection, and the
military, took issue with the French. Fischer said that if American
unilateralism exists, it does so because Europeans have been
reluctant to assume responsibility for their own region.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Moisi, deputy director of the French Institute for
International Relations, considers anti-Americanism in Europe to be
part of an inferiority complex. He believes the new single European
currency and the pledge by France and Britain to forge a united
defense policy will lead to a more confident Europe, which will be
good for all concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The talks at Rambouillet present Europeans with the opportunity
to assert themselves against the Americans. If a deal is reached,
Europeans will for the first time lead Americans and prove to the
rest of the world that the European Union is an entity of
substance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
