<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6679 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      02-08 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNERAL A CHANCE FOR CLINTON TO MAKE POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Surrounded by three of his White House
predecessors, President Clinton bade farewell Monday to King
Hussein, praising the world leader for his ability to bring sworn
enemies together.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral created a rare opportunity for Clinton to spend some
time with the former presidents.
</P>
<P>
   As former Presidents George Bush, Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter
shared the stage in a hotel ballroom, Clinton said, ``Here we are,
two Democrats, two Republicans. We've agreed on many things, we've
disagreed on a thing or two over time. But we know that America's
interest and America's heart were close to this king and this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The four presidents flew here together on Air Force One, with
Clinton coming back into their cabin for 2 1/2 hours to discuss
foreign policy in the Middle East, Kosovo and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   They were close to one another Monday, standing in line outside
Raghadan Palace, waiting to pay their respects. Once inside, they
paused in front of Hussein's flag-drapped casket and bowed their
heads almost in unison.
</P>
<P>
   After the funeral, the four, joined by Hillary Rodham Clinton
and four members of Congress, addressed a group of Jordanian and US
Embassy officials at a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the funeral, Clinton said, ``Hussein really did bring
people together.'' He said he could ``hardly believe my eyes'' when
he looked up and saw the Israeli delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the candidates for prime minister were there. They were
all walking together. I don't know if they talk at home, but they
were all talking here,'' Clinton said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, it was as if Hussein was hugging them all, you
know? Clinton recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein's rule began in 1952, when Harry Truman was president,
had he has known US presidents since Dwight D. Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   Former Secretary of State James A. Baker III, in his 1995 book,
``The Politics of Diplomacy,'' wrote that Bush's relationship with
Hussein was strained when Hussein became the only major Arab leader
who sided with Iraq during the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   Baker wrote that Bush viewed Hussein's behavior then as a
``personal betrayal.'' When Hussein came to the United States to
mend fences after the war, Bush kept him waiting more than three
hours, then saw him only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Bush did not speak of his personal feelings about
Hussein. Instead, he kept his comments more general, mentioning the
``outpouring of affection in our country for your king.''
</P>
<P>
   Hussein had forged the closest bond with Clinton. The two talked
frequently by phone. They visited a few weeks ago when Hussein and
his wife, Queen Noor, were in the United States for the king's
cancer treatment at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who met with the queen Monday at the palace, said
the friendship ``between our families on a personal level and
between our countries is very, very deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton recounted his conversation with Hussein last fall when
he asked him to jump-start the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks at the Wye Plantation in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein, who was frail and ailing, told Clinton, ``I would be
willing to come down there if you think it would help,'' the
president said, quoting Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said if I think it would help? This whole thing is about to
come apart; of course it would help. I said, if you come down, they
won't have the courage to walk away here without an agreement. And
so he did,'' recalled Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the emotional White House celebration that followed the Wye
accord, Hussein told Clinton that of all the presidents he has
known ``on the subject of peace, the peace we are seeking, I have
never _ with all due respect and all the affection that I held for
your predecessors _ have known someone with your dedication,
clear-headedness, focus and determination to help resolve this
issue in the best possible way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President,'' Hussein continued, ``permit me to say what I
feel _ I was mentioning it more than once in the last few days. You
have the tolerance and the patience of Job, and you are the subject
of our admiration and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hussein not only helped Clinton move along the Wye accord
peace process, he also was boosting the presidency as the House
Judiciary Committee was moving to adopt articles of impeachment
against Clinton, and the November congressional elections were just
weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was Monday. Hussein's funeral fell on the day the
Senate heard closing arguments in the president's impeachment
trial. Two senators, Patrick J. Leahy, a Democrat of Vermont and
Ted Stevens, a Republican of Alaska, joined Clinton for the
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy told reporters that sitting on Air Force One exchanging
rememberances about Hussein was better than sitting in the
impeachment trial. ``I was so tired of that trial,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met briefly with about 50 heads of state who traveled
here for the funeral. National Security Adviser Samuel R. Berger
quoted Clinton as saying the delegations represented ``the
kaleidoscope of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   When Russian President Boris Yeltsin saw Clinton enter a room in
the palace, he said in a loud, booming voice, ``Bill Clinton!''
according to Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also met for 25 minutes with King Abdullah, the
37-year-old son of Hussein and his successor. ``He clearly
understands his mission,'' Clinton said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said in the most moving way. . . . `I and all of my
brothers and sisters have absorbed our father's teaching. We know
what we are supposed to do, and I intend to do it,' '' Clinton
said. ``And he said it in a way that exuded the quiet, humble
confidence that I saw so often in his father.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left no doubt that he would always treasure his
relationship with Hussein: ``He made us all a little better, and he
always will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
