<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6688 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-LAWS-NYT     02-08 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-LAWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGIA LEGISLATORS APPROVE BILL TO BLOCK SUITS AGAINST GUN MAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: La., Fla., Ill., Conn.)   (fe) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gun manufacturers and their supporters began a long
and expensive counterattack on Monday on the growing number of
lawsuits that cities are filing against the gun industry by
successfully pushing the Georgia Senate to pass the first bill in
the nation intended to block such suits.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's governor, Roy Barnes, who was endorsed by the National
Rifle Association in his recent campaign, is expected to sign the
bill this week, which was passed by the House late last month and
moved through the Legislature at high velocity. Although Atlanta
joined other cities across the country by filing suit against the
gun industry in state court last Thursday, the bill contains
language that would explicitly quash all pending gun litigation by
Georgia cities, as well as any in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-gun lobbyists were delighted at the strong show of support,
saying the Georgia effort marks the beginning of a campaign against
city gun lawsuits that gun makers and the NRA intend to fight in
dozens of state capitals. With their conservative traditions and
easy access for lobbyists, statehouses have traditionally been the
stronghold of the industry, with nearly 40 states, including
Georgia, already having laws that prohibit their cities from
enacting any form of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of a long, arduous process that we wish
we didn't have to engage in, but we are going to devote a lot of
time and resources to it,'' said James Baker, director of the NRA's
lobbying arm, the Institute for Legislative Action. ``In the next
year, I think we can probably get 25 or 30 more states to do the
same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The next stop, he said, is Louisiana, where the organization
plans to have a bill filed the first day the state Legislature
opens in March.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans was the first of several cities to file lawsuits
against the gun industry, seeking millions of dollars to reimburse
local treasuries for the cost of the police and hospital services
required because of gun violence. Other cities that filed such
suits include Miami, Chicago and Bridgeport, Conn., and many others
are preparing or contemplating such litigation, modeled after
similar successful efforts against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's suit, brought against 14 manufacturers and three trade
groups, accuses the companies of failing to install safety devices
or provide adequate warnings of the dangers of guns. It seeks
unspecified damages to compensate the city for the cost of mopping
up after gun violence. Mayor Bill Campbell, who has championed the
suit in defiance of the Legislature, vowed on Monday to fight the
industry's bill on constitutional grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Having watched the tobacco industry first fight and then
eventually settle liability lawsuits around the country, the
far-less-prosperous gun industry has vowed not to let the same
thing happen to its members. But without many friends in the White
House or in city halls, the firearms lobby is concentrating on
statehouses like the one here, targeting legislators who have used
NRA endorsements as badges of anti-crime toughness. With about
90,000 active members in the state, the NRA contributes heavily to
Georgia politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes back to when I was driving in my car back in
December, and I heard something on the radio about the Chicago
suit,'' said state Rep. Curtis Jenkins, a Democrat from rural
Forsythe, who introduced the bill. ``It crossed my mind that
Atlanta might look at this, and I had a talk with the NRA, which
has been a great help with this bill. They had all kinds of
suggestions as we were drafting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins and other legislative leaders said lawmakers voted for
the bill because they believe the lawsuits are a backdoor form of
gun control, trying to restrict access to guns by putting gun
manufacturers out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia is a strong Second Amendment state,'' said Sen. Eric
Johnson, the Republican minority leader from Savannah. ``People
here see any attempt to sue gun manufacturers as an attempt to
restrict the citizen's right to keep and bear arms.'' Both houses
passed the bills with strong bipartisan majorities, the Senate
voting 44-11, the House 146-25. Barnes has not commented publicly
on the bill, but legislative leaders said they have been assured by
his office that he will sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers were particularly annoyed that Atlanta filed its
suit while the gun industry's largest trade show, known as the Shot
Show, was entertaining 30,000 visitors at the Georgia World
Congress Center here. The industry has pulled next year's show out
of New Orleans because of that city's suit.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, the NRA lobbyist, said he knew there are many states,
including Illinois, where the lobby will not be nearly as
successful. But by undermining lawsuits in friendly states like
Georgia and Louisiana, he said, the industry will be able to narrow
the playing field and concentrate on the 20 or so states posing the
greatest threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to prove that the firearms industry is
responsible for the criminal misuse of firearms,'' he said. ``It's
ludicrous _ totally outside the realm of existing product liability
law. They're trying to do with the court system what they've been
unable to do with state legislatures.''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-gun lobbyists say the NRA will probably be successful in
several state capitals but predicted that enough city lawsuits
would go forward unimpeded to keep the industry busy in court. Many
of the cities that have filed suit are being guided by a group of
the same private lawyers who brought the original suit against the
tobacco companies, and the lawyers say they are ready for the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be working with cities to fight these bills on
constitutional grounds,'' said Daniel Abel, a partner in the New
Orleans firm of Gauthier, Downing, LaBarre, Beiser &AMP; Dean, which
helped originate the tobacco litigation and drafted New Orleans'
suit against the gun industry. ``These bills violate the right to
self-determination of a city, many of which have home-rule
charters. You'll be seeing a lot of constitutional scholars come
out and address this issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
