<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6695 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      02-08 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S IMPEACHMENT TRIAL HEADS TOWARD SECRET DELIBERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL, JUDY HOLLAND And JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN   
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton
headed Monday toward secret deliberations and an expected vote for
acquittal that left Senate Democrats scrambling for a way to
censure the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Many Senate Democrats, led by Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
have been working to craft a bipartisan censure resolution to
condemn Clinton's conduct in part to offset the political
repercussions of their expected votes to acquit the president on
two articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   However, some Republicans oppose the censure effort, contending
that the Constitution only gives the Senate two choices _ acquit
the president or convict and remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a GOP filibuster against censure threatens to
keep the censure issue alive long past the week-long congressional
recess that starts this weekend..
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republican House prosecutors made their final,
sometimes impassioned appeals to the Senate to convict and remove
Clinton from office for perjury and obstruction of justice for a
13-month sex-and-cover-up scandal involving former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. F. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., urging senators not to be
``fooled by the president's excuses and spin control,'' warned that
the impact would be ``felt for generations to come'' if the
president evaded the consequences of his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., urged the senators to disregard national
public opinion polls showing Clinton's high popularity. ``Your
duty, which I know you recognize today, is and must be based not on
polls or politics, but on law and the Constitution _ in other
words, on principle,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Charles Ruff countered demands for Clinton's
ouster by acknowledging ``the pain the president has caused'' the
nation, but insisting that Clinton's transgressions fall short of
the threshold for impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans have focused on ``retribution,'' with a case
built to ``achieve partisan ends'' rather than serving the needs of
the nation, Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., leader of
the 13 House prosecutors, had the last word. Noting that the nation
was ``blessedly coming to the end of this melancholy procedure,''
Hyde appealed to the Senate to convict and remove a popularly
elected president for the first time in American history rather
than acquit and turn to a resolution of censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now let us all take our place in history on the side of
honor and, oh yes, let right be done!'' Hyde implored.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde had earlier conceded the likely failure of House
Republicans garnering the 67 Senate votes needed to convict and
remove the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always am hopeful that logic, the facts, the law will change
people's minds,'' Hyde said somewhat ruefully. ``I think you have
to wait until the Fat Lady sings.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators said they expected the Senate to reject a proposal on
Tuesday to open up the final deliberations to public scrutiny. Sen.
Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said that she had only about 60 of
the 67 votes needed to overturn Senate rules to permit public
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., agreed: ``It's certainly still uphill.''
said
</P>
<P>
   Plans called for the 100 senators to meet behind closed doors
Tuesday and Wednesday, with each to speak for between 10 minutes
and 15 minutes before casting their votes on the two articles of
impeachment in public session as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Senators seeking Senate action on a post-trial resolution of
censure condemning Clinton's conduct also were encountering
problems.
</P>
<P>
   If the impeachment trial ends Thursday or Friday as expected,
backers of censure will not have enough time to bring the
resolution up before the Senate recesses for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said the threat of a
filibuster by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, to block Senate action on a
censure resolution before the Senate's scheduled recess may force
Senate Democrats to seek to attach the censure resolution to
legislation in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that the sooner we can get this done, the
better,'' Daschle said. ``Our preference would be to get it done
this week, but if that isn't to be, we will certainly get it done
this spring.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., warned that if a censure
resolution was not adopted later this week, it probably would not
happen because there is so much legislative action ``waiting in the
wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoed Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.: ``The way to censure is a
really difficult trail.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors, who had once weighed asking the Senate to
hear live testimony from as many as eight witnesses, tried once
again to expand the scope of the trial to admit sworn testimony
from journalist Christopher Hitchens, his wife Carol Blue and
journalist R. Scott Armstrong who have challenged the veracity of
sworn testimony last week by White House staffer Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, in a letter to the Senate leadership, said the new
evidence indicated that Blumenthal ``may have testified falsely
before the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republican leader Trent Lott tried to introduce two
affidavits at the outset of Monday's proceedings that sought to
challenge a portion of Blumenthal's testimony. But Daschle, the
Senate Democratic leader, blocked Lott's effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
