</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-DAD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCTUPLETS FATHER GETS PROBATION AFTER PLEADING NO CONTEST IN
ATTACK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The father of the seven surviving Houston octuplets
was placed on two years deferred-adjudication probation Monday and
ordered to undergo a psychological evaluation after pleading no
contest to a charge he attacked his mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Iyke Paul Louis Jr., 42, will have to enroll in whatever kind of
counseling program that is recommended for him and he will also
have to pay the rest of Janet Chukwu's medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County Criminal Court-at-Law Judge Michael A. Peters did
not fine Louis, who is also known as Iyke Louis Odobi, or order him
to do community service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your community service is that you be a good father and role
model for those seven children,'' Peters told Louis, who was
flanked by his wife, her mother and his attorney.
</P>
<P>
   As he left court, Louis referred all comment to his lawyer
except to say he was going to see his children in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   One child was born Dec. 8 and seven others Dec. 20. The smallest
baby died of heart and lung failure a week later. Currently, four
of the babies remain in critical condition and three others have
been upgraded to serious condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to resolve this case without a terrible tragedy
happening in that courtroom, which would have been to line
everybody up against everybody and watch the accusations fly,''
defense attorney Rick Castleberry said.
</P>
<P>
   According to police reports, Louis was arrested early Sept. 22
and charged with misdemeanor assault after officers were called to
his home in Southwest Houston about 11:25 p.m. Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Louis assaulted Janet Chukwu, who lives at the home
with Louis and his then-pregnant wife, Nkem Chukwu, 29.
</P>
<P>
   Louis told police he and his wife were arguing when she began to
nag and pinch him. Janet Chukwu became involved in the argument, he
said, and began hitting and biting him.
</P>
<P>
   Louis told officers he defended himself by hitting and biting
her, then hitting her with a chair.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Chukwu told police a different story.
</P>
<P>
   She said Louis threatened to break his wife's hands and kick
her. When Janet Chukwu told her daughter to get away, Louis got
angry, according to police. Janet Chukwu said he then cracked a
chair over her head and began to beat and bite her.
</P>
<P>
   In court Monday, Janet Chukwu told Peters through an interpreter
that Louis has since apologized and that she was satisfied with
that apology.
</P>
<P>
   Castleberry pointed out later that the apology was ``for the
incident'' and that Louis' plea of no contest did not mean he was
admitting to any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Chukwu still lives with the couple and Peters suggested
the family get counseling together, but he also had a warning for
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be watching you like a hawk in this case because these
kids need to be raised in a family unit, not in an environment
where you are at odds with each other,'' Peters told Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of deferred adjudication, Louis was not found
guilty and thus will have no felony conviction on his record if he
lives up to the probation terms and stays out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Pat McNelis said he agreed to the deal only after
Janet Chukwu approved and only after he felt sure she would be safe
in the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking he's got seven kids coming into this house and
does not have a prior criminal record and I wanted to consider her
safety and wanted also to consider the needs and safety of his
family,'' McNelis said.
</P>
<P>
   The needs of the family and the demands seven children will
place on the parents were cited as the reasons McNelis agreed not
to ask Peters to impose a fine or community service on Louis.
</P>
<P>
   State law allows Peters to waive such punishments, which are a
usual adjunct to probation, in extraordinary circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   McNelis said he also accepted the deal because Louis' case will
be handled by probation officers who deal with domestic violence
officers. That means he will be under more intense supervision than
the average probationer.
</P>
<P>
   Peters accepted the plea on the day the case was set for trial.
That is also a deviation from his normal policy, but McNelis said
the exception was made because the judge was briefed on the deal
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, hospital officials said the first born of the
infants received her first series of immunizations and that two of
the other babies are now completing full bottles at feeding time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
