<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6703 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARAUCTION-SFCHRON-CA     02-08 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARAUCTION-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - CAR AUCTION  
 Online Auction for Used-Car Dealers  &HT;     By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR; Autobytel.com, the Internet car-buying service for consumers,
plans to enter the online business-to-business market by offering
the first online auctions for used-car dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The Irvine (Orange County) company now operates a Web site,
 &LR; www.autobytel.com,  &LR; that lets consumers get information about car
performance, ratings, features and pricing, then hooks shoppers up
with nearby dealers to make a purchase. It said it will launch a
new site,  &LR; www.wholesale.autobytel.com,  &LR; this spring to be used for
transactions between car wholesalers and the 2,700 car dealers
associated with Autobytel.com.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, these transactions involve at least one middleman.
Autobytel.com said it will let dealers save money by dealing
directly with the wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lorimer, Autobytel.com president and chief executive
officer, said dealers could cut costs by as much as $2,000 on some
transactions by using an online auction.
</P>
<P>
   The company previewed the site at the National Association of
Auto Dealers convention in San Francisco over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Vernon Keenan, a San Francisco Internet analyst, said
wholesalers frequently sell cars via ``real world'' auctions, but
that he didn't know of an Internet car auction other than that to
be offered by Autobytel.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just moving that business to the Internet,'' Keenan
said. ``Autobytel.com is attempting to use the Internet to take the
place of the middleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Autobytel.com does most of its business with consumers,
business-to-business e-commerce is actually a much larger market _
nearly 10 times consumer online retail spending, according to
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The new site will be a sort of car dealer's version of eBay, the
popular online person-to-person auction site, and will offer many
of the same features, including photos of the cars, descriptions
and seller profiles.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Autobytel.com revived plans for an initial stock
offering. The company, formerly known as Auto-by-tel Corp.,
initially planned to go public in January 1997, selling 4 million
shares at between $9.50 and $11 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Now sporting a ``.com'' as part of its name, the company plans
to raise about $72 million by selling 4.5 million shares for an
estimated $16 apiece. The public offering is planned for next
month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
