<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIDEMAN-RETRIAL-ART-2     02-08 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIDEMAN-RETRIAL-ART-2TAKES(1,100)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETRIAL REOPENS OLD WOUNDS FOR FAMILIES OF SLAYING VICTIM AND
ACCUSED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mass.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By   WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Robert Wideman's part in a 1975 killing might have
been forgotten by now except by the family of a 24-year-old man who
was shot in the back on that November night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the crime became one of the enduring literary images of
black America, as a subject of an acclaimed 1984 book, ``Brothers &AMP;
Keepers,'' by Mr. Wideman's brother, John Edgar Wideman.
</P>
<P>
   One brother, the author, had escaped the ghetto; the other was
the street tough who embodied the cycle that claims many young
black men. At 25, Robert Wideman was imprisoned for life without
parole after an accomplice fired a fatal shot in a failed street
swindle.
</P>
<P>
   And now Robert Wideman's case is no longer alive only in
literature. Surprisingly, it is alive again in the courts, not only
reopening old wounds here, but also altering a story that has been
portrayed around the world as representative of the fate of black
men in America.
</P>
<P>
   In November, a county court judge, James R. McGregor, ordered a
new trial for Wideman, who has been in prison for 23 years. A
second chance is warranted, the judge ruled, because new evidence
showed that the victim would not have died if he had received
proper medical care after an ambulance took him to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere I knew,'' Wideman said in a recent long conversation
in the prison visiting room, ``that I was going to make the system
see: `Listen, I am not that bad.' Isn't there a point when you say,
isn't there a second chance?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because John Wideman's writing made Robert Wideman's
story seem larger than life, the debate set off by McGregor's
ruling has been outsized as well. Angry prosecutors are appealing.
Questions about the effect of race and fame on justice have been
mixed with fury. And McGregor has asserted that politics have been
injected into the case by a heated Democratic primary for district
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   To some residents, the new trial ruling showed that the cycle of
hopelessness born on the streets can be broken. To others, the
decision showed only that infamous people can get special
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my son wouldn't have been shot in the back, he wouldn't
have needed that medical care,'' said 68-year old Clara Morena, the
mother of Nichola Morena, who died that night in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, the Allegheny County District Attorney, Stephen
A. Zappala Jr., said McGregor's ruling had been based on ``an
absurd theory.'' Zappala said he would fight to see that Wideman
serves his life sentence. `` `Life' is life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wideman was convicted in 1976 of second-degree murder. If he is
retried with the new evidence, lawyers say, he could be convicted
of a lesser crime. If so, he would have already served more than
any sentence he could receive, and he would walk free.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wideman was one of three armed men who told Morena and
two friends that November day long ago that they had 10 television
sets for sale. There were no television sets.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Wideman's supporters have contended without solid
evidence that Morena was a ``fence'' for stolen property who had
been preparing to cheat Wideman and his friends by taking their
television sets and not delivering the $800 they had promised to
pay. Mrs. Morena said she was offended by the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, the evidence of years ago suggested, Morena and
his associates had reason to suspect that the television sets they
had been offered would not have been from a legitimate source.
McGregor suggested as much in his order granting Wideman a new
trial. ``On Nov. 15, 1975, six men were committing a felony,'' the
judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   When the two groups confronted each other, Morena ran. According
to trial testimony, Wideman shouted, ``Get him'' or, ``He's getting
away,'' and one of his associates fired.
</P>
<P>
   For the Morena family, a painful fact of the latest turn in the
case is that the family's own lawyers gathered the information that
could free Wideman. In a civil suit in 1981, the family said that
Morena died in part because the hospital emergency room to which he
had been taken had been inadequately supplied and lacked a chest
surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   The suit charged that doctors did not perform standard treatment
for chest injuries and ambulance crews delayed in transferring
Morena to a suitable hospital. Two of the doctors settled the case
for $100,000. Years later, said Mark D. Schwartz, one of Robert
Wideman's lawyers, Wideman learned about that civil case.
Prosecutors have suggested Wideman knew about the civil case much
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, new lawyers for Wideman, financed by his brother,
investigated the Morenas' suit. Last fall, they presented testimony
before McGregor.
</P>
<P>
   One witness who testified for Wideman was the coroner here, Dr.
Cyril H. Wecht. ``He would have lived,'' Wecht said of Morena in an
interview, ``if competent, appropriate, timely medical care had
been rendered to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts on criminal law say McGregor's ruling relies on
established legal principles. But they also say that appeals courts
resist reopening long-closed cases. One factor courts weigh is
whether the delay would unfairly disadvantage prosecutors. In
Wideman's case, the prosecutors say witnesses are gone, memories
hazy and files lost.
</P>
<P>
   Wideman was convicted of murder, even though he did not pull the
trigger, under centuries' old ``felony murder'' rules that say if
someone dies in the commission of a felony, all the participants in
the felony can be responsible for murder.
</P>
<P>
   Wideman's accomplice who fired the fatal shot was also convicted
of murder and is serving a life sentence. He is seeking a new trial
based on the information Wideman's lawyers presented. The third
accomplice, convicted of a lesser degree of homicide, served 20
years and was freed.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wideman, now 48, said he long ago accepted that his own
bad choices led him to be there when Morena was shot. He said he
was sorry. But he said he was not a killer.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wideman brothers said they had a special understanding of
the loss suffered by Mrs. Morena. Robert Wideman's son was killed
in revenge after a Pittsburgh bar fight. John Wideman has a son who
is serving 25 years to life for stabbing to death a fellow summer
camper when he was a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   John Wideman, 58, said their mother, who still lives in
Pittsburgh, had suffered, too. ``If Mrs. Morena carries a burden
because of a lost son,'' he said, ``my mother has lost many sons _
literally and figuratively _ as an African-American mother in
Pittsburgh.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In any murder case, jurors must decide whether the defendants'
actions caused the death, said David Rudovsky, a criminal law
professor at the University of Pennsylvania Law School. He said
that if a shooting causes injury, but something else, like poor
medical care, actually caused death, a jury could conclude the
defendant did not cause the murder.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors say they are confident Pennsylvania appeals
courts will agree that Wideman should not have a new trial. Death,
they say, is one foreseeable consequence of a shot in the back.
``They wanted to murder that man,'' Zappala said. ``They shot him
and left him for dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Zappala himself has become an issue, as he opposes a retrial
while running for his first full term as district attorney. The son
of a prominent justice of the Pennsylvania Supreme Court, he was
selected by the county judges to fill an unexpired term last fall,
despite having little experience in criminal law.
</P>
<P>
   On his first day on the job, Zappala dismissed his chief
homicide prosecutor, W. Christopher Conrad, who had sought the
appointment himself.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad, who is now running against Zappala in a Democratic
primary, said he had been ``absolutely shocked'' when Zappala was
named to the post. Conrad has sat with the Morena family in court
while publicly criticizing Zappala as too lenient in at least one
other case.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan.14, after a series of battles with the district
attorney's office over the Wideman case, McGregor said from the
bench that most prosecutors confronted with the new evidence would
agree that fairness dictated a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The manner in which your office has approached this case has
everything in the world to do with the race for district attorney
of Allegheny County,'' said McGregor, a Republican who was once
proposed for a federal judgeship by President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Chris Conrad attacking him for being soft on crime,''
the judge said, the case against Wideman would be closed as a
result of a plea deal. Zappala angered McGregor particularly by
blocking an order by the judge that would have freed Wideman on
bail. An appeals court later overturned McGregor's order.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Zappala said he was offended by suggestions
that he was making decisions on the case for political reasons. He
said the judge had been influenced by the Wideman family's view of
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Wideman, the convict, said that his family's fame was ``a
blessing and a curse.'' A blessing, he said, because his brother's
success as a writer meant he had the means to help him. It is a
curse, he added, ``that because of the fame, Zappala feels a need
to make a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Wideman, the writer, said the case illustrated what he called
the bias of the justice system, a theme in many of his books, which
describe the toll of life in Pittsburgh's black Homewood section.
His brother, he said, had changed in prison, overcoming a drug
problem, earning the equivalent of a junior college degree, and
teaching other inmates. But the prosecutors' resistance to a new
trial showed they were unwilling to see him as an individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironically,'' John Wideman said in a recent interview in his
comfortable suburban home in Amherst, Mass., ``here we are a
quarter of a century later and we have a situation where Robby
Wideman, whoever he is, whatever he has accomplished, is not up in
front of the court. What's up in front of the court is a black male
who committed a crime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 1931EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6707 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENTAL-TREATMENT-BOS &LR;      02-08 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-TREATMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US CITES SCHOOL, HOSPITAL FOR PSYCHOSIS RESEARCH FLAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mount Sinai Medical School in New York and an affiliated
Veterans Affairs hospital did not properly protect the mentally ill
in research conducted in the 1980s and 1990s, leading to ``at least
some short-term harm'' in one psychosis-inducing study, a federal
agency has found.
</P>
<P>
   The Office for Protection from Research Risks, which monitors
US-funded research, documented a series of violations, ranging from
the failure to adequately inform subjects of the risks and nature
of the research, to the deliberate exacerbation of psychotic
symptoms among patients who had been stable.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, part of the National Institutes of Health and known
as OPRR, issued its determination in a January 28 letter to Mount
Sinai and Bronx Veterans Affairs Medical Center, which was obtained
by The Boston Globe Monday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the studies _ which withheld antipsychotic medications
from stabilized schizophrenia patients and gave them L-dopa, known
to induce psychosis in the mentally ill _ was cited in a four-part
series that ran in the Globe three months ago, highlighting
psychiatric research abuses.
</P>
<P>
   OPRR found that while that study, published in 1987, resulted in
no long-term adverse effects, people ``suffered at least some
short-term harm or discomfort as evidenced by documentation of
schizophrenia relapse in all 28 patients.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one of the patients in that study, after being off
medication for four weeks, ``became violent and struck a doctor.
Another patient. . .expressed suicidal ideation; and another
patient's symptoms worsened significantly after only one day of
being off medication . . . ,'' according to OPRR, citing documents
it reviewed as part of its investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The study was led by Dr. Kenneth L. Davis, according to the OPRR
letter. Davis is Mount Sinai's chairman of psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   OPRR's finding comes five years after a New York-based mental
health advocate first filed a complaint with OPRR about the 1987
study and raised concerns in the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really am questioning why it took them so long. What kind of
obstacles were there that prevented them from investigating it and
determining it sooner?'' said Vera Hassner Sharav, president and
co-founder of Citizens for Responsible Care in Psychiatry and
Research.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-page OPRR letter also found violations of federal
regulations to protect human subjects of research in two other
now-completed studies of schizophrenia, both of which began in the
early 1990s and were led by Dr. Michael Davidson. The violations
primarily concerned informed consent procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Monday, Mount Sinai School of Medicine said it
has already addressed concerns now being outlined in the OPRR
letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994, when a news report raised questions concerning
certain studies that had been conducted in previous years, Mount
Sinai immediately and voluntarily conducted an in-depth evaluation
of the manner in which that research was conducted, and voluntarily
implemented appropriate corrective actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are gratified that in the assessment that it has just
completed, the Office for Protection from Research Risks has
acknowledged Mount Sinai's immediate response to the issues when
they were raised, recognized the corrective actions that Mount
Sinai implemented four years ago, and praised Mount Sinai for its
`commitment...to the protection of human research subjects,' ''
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
   OPRR acknowledged that the studies in question ``have been
completed for at least several years,'' and that both Mount Sinai
and the Bronx VA conducted their own evaluations and ``instituted a
number of corrective actions,'' requiring no further action on the
agency's part.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to the letter by Dr. Michael A. Carome, acting
chief of the compliance oversight branch for OPRR's division of
human subject protections, the agency must be informed of any new
information that could lead to future OPRR action. In addition, he
wrote, the agency will be visiting the institution to make sure the
corrective actions are being implemented adequately.
</P>
<P>
   Carome and other OPRR officials did not return phone calls
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hassner Sharav said that while she was glad to see OPRR document
the violations in its determination letter, she criticized the
agency for failing to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This determination does not in any way hold anyone accountable
for worsening the illness of these people, of causing them
unnecessary, unjustified suffering,'' Hassner Sharav said. ``Are
they just discards? Shouldn't the researchers and the institutions
be held accountable? Shouldn't there be penalties for violating
these. . .ethical standards?''
</P>
<P>
   In its statement Monday, Mount Sinai School of Medicine said it
``is committed to conducting clinical research in accord with the
highest ethical and scientific standards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
