<HEADER>
A6708 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETFILES-SFCHRON-THEN     02-08 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET FILES/JON SWARTZ  
 NET FIRMS LOOKING TO PARTNER UP
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - THE NET FILES   &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Internet companies, the past few months have been like the
week before the big prom.
</P>
<P>
   Once the homecoming king and queen _ AOL and Netscape _
announced that they were an item, everybody else had to scramble to
get a partner before there were none left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's been talking to everyone else,'' said George Bell,
CEO of Excite.
</P>
<P>
   America Online's announcement in November that it would take
over Netscape Communications for $4.2 billion set off a chain of
other Internet mergers. AtHome decided to buy Excite for $6.7
billion, which prompted Yahoo to offer $4.6 billion for GeoCities
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Industry wags say the mating frenzy will continue until there
are no major Web sites left to buy, which might not take long.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 15 most popular Web sites, the only ones that are
still independent are Lycos, a Waltham, Mass., search engine, and
Xoom.com, a San Francisco e-commerce company. Odds are that they'll
be gobbled up by this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Industry Standard, a trade magazine, reported last week that
NBC is close to a deal to buy Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   What's behind the trend? Internet companies are trying to build
the biggest audience they can as fast as they can. And the quickest
way to do that is to use their inflated stocks to buy other
companies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The potential payoff: billions of dollars in advertising and
e-commerce deals.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-Netscape ``was the starting gun,'' Bell said. ``It's a
version of hyper musical chairs, and when music stops, the
companies left sitting'' will have more power than the three major
TV networks.
</P>
<P>
   The information superhighway is following the same path as the
car industry, which narrowed from 200 automakers to the Big Three
between the 1940s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Both industries went through massive periods of innovation,
followed by consolidation and specialization.
</P>
<P>
   Although the car industry took decades to boil down into three
companies, the fast-moving Internet by the end of next year
probably will be dominated by just four major portals _
AOL/Netscape, Yahoo, Microsoft's MSN and AtHome/Excite.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller players like Cnet, ESPN.com and E Online, will provide
specialized content.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``Businesses go through cycles, and the Internet is going through
its consolidation cycle,'' said Barry Schuler, president of AOL
Interactive Services. ``The smaller companies, which develop
specific features, are being bought up by the bigger players, who
are running full-fledged companies.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lycos and Xoom.com, possible takeover targets
include Cnet, the San Francisco online news organization, and
Theglobe.com, a New York operator of Web communities.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner, NBC and Microsoft are the most frequently mentioned
suitors for these companies and others.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Xoom.com Chairman Chris Kitze said his company is not for sale
but that he's obligated to consider all offers. ``As long as the
market keeps going crazy and some Internet companies pick up $5
billion in market value overnight, you are going to see them put
their stock to use before it burns a hole in their pocket,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies with inflated shares, like AOL, Yahoo and AtHome, have
a more potent currency than companies whose shares are more
reasonably priced. For example, Ford Motor Co. acquired Volvo AB
for $6.25 billion the same week AtHome paid $6.75 billion in stock
for Excite.
</P>
<P>
   However the wheeling and dealing shakes out, the pace will be
dizzying.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the rest of the world, this must be pretty amazing
stuff,'' Bell marveled. ``How is it that a guy who is 25 and owns
only two pairs of shoes and used to eat noddles out of a bowl is
worth millions within a couple of years? That's the Internet for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PUTTING LUSK, WYO., ON MAP: &QL; 
The hinterlands have met high tech in a series of Microsoft
national TV ads promoting the technical savvy of Lusk (population
1,600), a rural ranching community near the Nebraska border. In one
spot, bespectacled 13-year-old Dan Henry Hansen uses the Internet
to study dung beetles; in another, Margy Brown relies on software
to operate a beeswax hand-cream business from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A town like Lusk, and a state government, couldn't afford this
type of publicity,'' Lusk Mayor Mark Lohr said. ``The town is
getting calls and e-mail from all over the country from people and
businesses who would like to move here and lead a rural life.''
</P>
<P>
   Why Lusk, a stark outpost on the plains where cows outnumber
people 100 to 1?
</P>
<P>
   Eric Koivisto, Microsoft's director of advertising, said the
software giant became aware of Lusk after reading about its bid to
establish a fiber-optic connection for faster Internet access to
City Hall, the school district and library. &UR;  &LR; ``It fit the profile
of a community using technology in amazing ways to improve people's
lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokeswoman declined to say how many millions of
dollars it has spent on the commercials. The people of Lusk didn't
get anything other than a free marketing campaign from perhaps the
greatest marketing company on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SITES OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Curious about the Top 10 national and regional Internet service
providers? In its annual poll, computer magazine PC World lists the
best of the best at &LR;  www.pcworld.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of lists, check out  &LR; www.geekweek.com &LR;  for an online
jobs center for the slide-rule sect. Happy hunting.
</P>
</TEXT>
