<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALE-CENSUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS SHOWS REBOUND IN HUMPBACK WHALE NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Humpback whales, whose dramatic leaps and dives have made them
the star attractions for New England's whalewatching industry, are
more numerous _ and possibly less endangered _ than biologists
previously believed, according to the results of a new six-year
study.
</P>
<P>
   Using sophisticated photography and genetic analysis, an
international team of researchers estimated that 10,600 humpbacks
inhabit the waters stretching from the West Indies in the south to
Norway in the north _ almost twice the 1980s estimate of 5,505.
</P>
<P>
   But biologists called it premature to conclude that the
endangered species is finally recovering from a legacy of whaling
and other human-induced injuries. The higher estimate may largely
reflect better whale-counting techniques, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new population estimate is the first step in a long and
careful process of assessing the population before we can decide if
the species is out of the woods,'' said study co-author David
Mattila of the Center for Coastal Studies in Provincetown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the improved humpback count is a bright spot in a field
where bad news is more the norm. David Morin, a biologist at the
Cetacean Research Unit in Gloucester, Mass., said the number of
humpbacks in the North Atlantic has almost certainly increased
after decades of protection from whale hunters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, it's better rather than worse news,'' added Teri
Frady of the National Marine Fisheries Service, which oversees
protection of endangered whales. She said the agency must learn
more about the overall well-being of humpbacks before it could
consider removing the animal from the endangered species list.
</P>
<P>
   The new study, the results of a six-nation effort called the
Years of the North Atlantic Humpback project, marks the most
elaborate attempt to count a tough-to-track animal that thinks
nothing of traveling hundreds of miles in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Originally conceived at the Center for Coastal Studies, the
study took researchers to the whales' West Indies breeding ground
as well as five major feeding areas such as the Gulf of Maine.
During 666 days at sea in 1992 and 1993, the team got pictures of
4,207 whale flukes as well as 2,327 skin samples.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the researchers need to figure out how rapidly the whale
population is growing and the severity of threats such as
entanglement in fishing gear, collisions with ships, and water
pollution. Mattila of the Center for Coastal Studies said an
overview of the humpback's health could be done next year.
</P>
<P>
   If the whale numbers have increased enough, the National Marine
Fisheries Service could list the humpback as a ``threatened''
rather than ``endangered'' species, giving the animal less
protection. However, it would still be protected from killing and
harassment under the Marine Mammal Protection Act.
</P>
<P>
   Though North Atlantic humpback population estimates of the past
are unreliable, researchers believe that the whales reached their
lowest point in the early 1900s after more than a century of
whaling. Since then, their numbers have increased, making them a
fairly common sight for New England whalewatchers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
