</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-FUNERAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMBER JORDANIANS LINE STREETS TO BID FAREWELL TO KING HUSSEIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Issam Abu Shannab and his two small sons slowly
made their way Monday to the wide boulevard on which King Hussein's
casket was to pass in a few hours. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Abu Shannab held one end of a black flag, as the small hands of
his 5-and 7-year-old sons gripped the other.
</P>
<P>
   Around them, grieving Jordanians were coming from all
directions.
</P>
<P>
   Gesturing toward his children, who were bundled in ski jackets
and knitted hats to fend off the cold, Abu Shannab said, ``I've
been telling them that (King Hussein) is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they just don't believe it,'' he said. They say, `Just a
few days ago, he was here.'''
</P>
<P>
   As world leaders gathered at Raghdan Palace to pay homage to a
ruler hailed by many as a peacemaker, an estimated 800,000
Jordanians lined the streets of Amman. Some stood in somber
silence. Many recounted fond memories of a king who, they said, was
more like a member of their family than a lofty monarch.
</P>
<P>
   Emad Hamaydeh, a 20-year-old law student, recalled the time he
was sitting with a friend at Mount Nebo, the desert mountain where
many people believe Moses is buried. The king and his sister,
Princess Haya, showed up without bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein ``sat down on the stone next to us and talked to us
about being young,'' said Hamaydeh, waving his hand in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us how lucky we were to have our youth and said he
never felt like he had (experienced) his youth, because he was
always working,'' Hamaydeh said. ``It was something special.''
</P>
<P>
   That personal touch, many Jordanians say, was the secret to
Hussein's enduring popularity during nearly five decades of rule.
</P>
<P>
   Many people said Monday they still cannot believe the king, who
died at the age of 63 on Sunday of complications stemming from
lymphatic cancer, is really gone. Even as they waited for his
casket to pass, they spoke of Hussein in the present tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The king touches people,'' said Basel Qubain, a 31-year-old
software engineer. ``You know a king is approaching by the aura
around him but, when he talks to you, you feel you are talking to
an ordinary human being.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other countries, you cannot approach a ruler,'' Qubain
continued. ``He is shielded by bodyguards, or he extends his hand
to be kissed. When King Hussein comes to you, he calls you `sidi'
(my master), even though it should be the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people placed bouquets of flowers in front of a mural
showing Hussein standing next to his royal jet. Others crouched on
the cold pavement and hung their heads in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the funeral procession appeared. Thousands of young
men ran alongside the cortege, trying to get a glimpse of the
casket perched on a beige army jeep and draped with a Jordanian
flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allahu akbar!'' people shouted. ``God is great!''
</P>
<P>
   The women in the crowd of mostly men began to sob. Men covered
their faces with their red headdresses. Soldiers standing guard
wiped their eyes with their red berets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love King Hussein,'' said 11-year-old Mohammed Hilu with
tears in his eyes. ``I cried when he died. My teacher cried when he
died.''
</P>
<P>
   But soon, the procession was gone. The king's casket arrived at
Raghdan Palace, where President Clinton and other world leaders
paid their last respects.
</P>
<P>
   Streets opened to traffic, and the people who had converged for
a few brief hours to say good-bye to their king went home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We belong to God, to God we return,'' said Qubain, reciting an
Islamic prayer. ``This is the way people console themselves. They
say, `He sacrificed his life for us.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
