<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-SCENE-ART-960&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THEY MOURN THEIR KING, JORDANIANS WORRY ABOUT THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(See related stories: JORDAN-FUNERAL, JORDAN-ISRAEL,
JORDAN-CLINTON, JORDAN-PALESTINIANS) 
(nk) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ In a cold winter mist, with tears and prayers
and anxiety about their future, Jordanians lined the streets Monday
for a last fleeting look at their fallen king.
</P>
<P>
   The convertible desert-camouflage jeep bearing King Hussein's
flag-draped coffin moved quickly across town to the Rhagadan Palace
compound, where past and present heads of state attended the
closed-door burial. Breaking through barricades into the streets,
people thronged after the hearse as it slowly accelerated out of
reach.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the route, a crowd had begun gathering long
before, waiting for the royal motorcade to emerge from Beb
al-Salam, the ``house of peace'' that had been the king's family
home. The crowd was a small cross-section of modern Jordan: factory
workers and taxi-drivers earning $200 a month, wealthy bankers from
the exclusive neighborhood across the street, married women in
traditional robes and single secretaries in smart skirts and
jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all were dressed in black, and most had been crying.
Students from the Al-Yobeal High School had been standing for hours
in the fog and wind beneath their silver-scripted black banner:
``We are alone without you, King Hussein.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the final moment of waiting for a nation that had been
anticipating the end of the Hussein era with grief and disbelief
for many days.
</P>
<P>
   With hovering helicopters kicking up dust, the parade of silver
Mercedes town cars and open red military Land Rovers suddenly
pulled around the corner, their royal passengers and military
chauffeurs resplendent in scarlet kaffiyehs.
</P>
<P>
   The car with the king's coffin was almost last. ``Did you see my
king? I lost my king!'' a sobbing man yelled out as it passed.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from conversations in the waiting crowd Monday, many
people here were trying to adjust to the prospect of Jordan without
Hussein, and wondering how this would affect their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   Though the overwhelming emotion Monday was deep sadness, the
sorrow was laced with fear that a vulnerable Jordan had lost an
irreplaceable guardian. For others, there was inchoate anger at a
world they felt had consigned them to undeserved poverty, despite
the late king's good works.
</P>
<P>
   And there were complaints about rising crime, taxes and food
costs _ often combined with the suggestion that had Hussein lived,
he might have found a way to resolve these problems.
</P>
<P>
   The pain of loss was leavened with pride, however. The king's
death put this small desert country of 4 million at least briefly
at the center of world attention. The four-hour state funeral was
broadcast overseas by foreign cable networks, and _ of greater
significance to many here _ by state television in most of the
divided Middle East, from Syria to Egypt to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more foreign leaders here than for the Kennedy
funeral,'' one man at the roadside said as he waited for the coffin
to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than for Churchill,'' a friend added.
</P>
<P>
   There was an almost poignant hope that this moral support would
translate into the financial aid that Jordanians say they need and
deserve. The outpouring of international affection for the late
king was seen as a testimonial to Jordan's support of Middle East
peace, and many Jordanians say they paid too steep a price for the
king's policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace killed our economy,'' said Ghazi Imraish, a 33-year-old
businessman who now lives in Dallas, but returned ``to see my king
one last time.''
</P>
<P>
   His is a common view here, though a better case can be made for
war as the cause. It was Iraq's invasion of Kuwait that ultimately
led to the punishing loss of Jordan's Iraqi trade and of billions
of dollars from expatriate Jordanians working in the Persian Gulf
who fled back to Jordan during the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan's support for peace has reaped it few countervailing
rewards. Per capita income has stagnated at $1,500, below the level
of the Palestinian West Bank. Unemployment is 15 percent and
climbing. Steep food prices have triggered riots. And the country
is burdened by an $8 billion foreign debt, bigger than its gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to find work here _ too hard,'' said Abed Yusef,
47, a stocky one-time oil worker in Kuwait who came home to years
of unemployment. ``We are looking to the leaders of the world to
stand beside Jordan, to help Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was spontaneously praised for the recent
near-tripling of American military and economic aid, with Jordan
slated to get $225 million in 1999 and $325 million next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the United States will help us,'' said Hana Taufik, a
34-year-old taxi driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's friendship with the king was a very special
relationship. You could tell from the speech he gave on television
last night,'' he added, referring to the president's eulogy Sunday
from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Businessmen in the crowd said they welcomed a Saudi Arabian
offer to shore up Jordan's foreign reserves with short-term loans.
Still, with banks closed and currency trading suspended during this
national week of mourning, investors will be watching nervously
when the markets reopen on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   People interviewed on the street here Monday were spontaneously
and uniformly critical of the U.N. sanctions against Iraq, which
the government says has cost Jordan $3 billion in lost transport
and tariff revenue alone since 1990. All seemed to view the
sanctions issue as an integral part of the regional peace efforts,
contending that the Western powers punishing Iraq should compensate
Jordan for lost income.
</P>
<P>
   ``King Hussein taught us how to survive our many difficulties,''
said Kamal Ali, a 35-year-old cement-factory worker. ``But we still
have a problem, because of the siege of Iraq.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A successful merchant, elegantly attired in a three-piece suit
and flowing kaffiyeh, spoke with moist eyes of his admiration for
the late king as the coffin passed by.
</P>
<P>
   A breath later, he said the death and royal succession had been
very bad for business. ``I haven't sold a thing in 15 days,'' he
said, and he faced the prospect of shuttering his small chain of
clothing shops for the coming week for the official mourning
period.
</P>
<P>
   Later, over tea inside his spacious home, he said he might be
forced to close two or three of the six stores he had opened with
high hopes in 1991, after returning home from a successful retail
career in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until 1993, things were all right, but since then it has been
very difficult,'' said the businessman, who spoke on the condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the downturn was no coincidence, in his view. The
1994 peace treaty with Israel failed to generate expected business
opportunities in Israel and the West Bank, and it alienated other
Jordanian trading partners in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His most serious business problem, he said, was the embargo
against Iraq, which once imported billions of dollars in consumer
goods through and from Jordan. He said he hoped that the new
American aid would help restore economic confidence.
</P>
<P>
   His wife rolled her eyes. ``You hear these figures on
television, like $300 million, but the people won't see any of
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people whose meals are tea and bread. The new king
needs to prove that that he can make the economy better, and he
needs to do it soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
