<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6716 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIRCUS-ONE-RING-ART-2     02-08 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRCUS-ONE-RING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER THE LITTLE TOP: ONE OF THE COZIEST SHOWS ON EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Mont., Texas, Calif., N.Y., Canada)  (ART ADV: Two photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Clowns wept. The ringmaster actually sobbed. A
thousand roustabouts, aerialists and equestrians began looking for
work. When ``The Greatest Show on Earth'' played under canvas for
the final time on July 16, 1956, it was a front-page story in
newspapers across the land.
</P>
<P>
   But here in the city that was its winter home from 1927 to 1959,
the Ringling Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus has raised its
tent for the first time in 42 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a parking lot at the Sarasota Fairgrounds right off Ringling
Drive, flameproof polyvinyl has superseded canvas. Traditional
circus fare like popcorn and cotton candy will be supplemented by
designer sandwiches and cappuccino. And the new show will be
performed in but one 38-foot-wide circus ring.
</P>
<P>
   This is not intended to replace the three-ring extravaganza that
shed its tents and began performing in air-conditioned arenas after
the circus regrouped in 1957. The year before, the tented show was
a victim of television, red ink, labor difficulties and bad
weather.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of being the greatest show on earth, the new show
will qualify as one of the coziest: an intimate, upscale circus in
a million-dollar custom-made Italian tent, tentatively titled
``Barnum's Kaleidoscape: The Magical One-Ring Experience From
Ringling Brothers.'' Previews begin here on Feb. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a sure thing,'' said Greg Parkinson, a circus
historian who is the executive director of the Circus World Museum
in Baraboo, Wis. ``In a tent of this size they'll have to have a
high percentage of sales to break even. And there will be
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Paul Binder, the founder and artistic director of
the Big Apple Circus, warned that ``the economics of a one-ring
tent are tight and very nasty.'' Nevertheless, Parkinson said,
``it's a historic moment for this circus, given the words of John
Ringling North,'' referring to the statement by North, then the
show's president and board chairman, from his private railroad car
in 1956 that ``the tented circus as it now exists is in my opinion
a thing of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Paraphrasing those words, Kenneth Feld, Ringling's producer and
chief executive, said that for his show, ``tented entertainments
will be a thing of the future.'' He added: ``Ringling's statement
was valid in its time, but the tent now gives us the ability to
practically deliver circus to the door of people who ordinarily
can't, or won't, come to arenas. We want to reach new suburban and
exurban communities.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ringling also seems to be trying to capitalize on the
growing audience for one-ring circuses, ``a large market as
demonstrated by the popularity of the Cirque du Soleil and the Big
Apple Circus,'' said Parkinson. Feld acknowledged that ``it's hard
to say that we've ignored Cirque du Soleil,'' adding, ``If a market
is out there, we feel we should get more of our fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   Feld estimated the new show's initial production costs to be $8
million, but several circus veterans put them closer to $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite a gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary to put such a big bet on the power of circus to
move people in an era of virtual entertainment,'' said Tim Holst,
the Ringling vice president for talent and production.
</P>
<P>
   Another risk is that the new show could cannibalize demand for
Ringling's traditional three-ring extravaganza, which will continue
to crisscross the country with its two separate touring units. ``We
see the shows as complementary,'' said Feld, ``and we think the new
circus will augment our basic business,'' which brought revenues of
$500 million last year into his privately held company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1872 P.T. Barnum's circus went to two rings. (His three rings
came along in 1881; the Barnum and Ringling troupes became a single
show in 1919.) ``In the 1920s Ringling had five rings,'' Parkinson
said, adding that with the new show Ringling was trying to upgrade
the circus in a different way, countering negative preconceptions
about ``the traditional carnival or tent show.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Holst said, ``We want this show to be the balsamic
vinegar of circus.''
</P>
<P>
   And so ``Kaleidoscape'' is attempting to lure an affluent
audience of mall mavens into its new champagne-colored tent with
its red stars and stripes, free of obstructed views and offering
the comfort of roomy crushed-velvet padded seats with backs. To
protect audience members' shoes from mud, the tent will have
red-carpeted hardwood flooring. The traditionally seedy, disheveled
ticket takers and part-time ushers will be replaced by fresh-faced,
costumed full-timers who will travel with the show.
</P>
<P>
   And because market research showed that ticket holders at artsy
tent circuses are dismayed by the porta-potty experience, Ringling
has designed two sleek bathroom trailers that will be staffed with
attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Feld said he would be targeting 30-year-old parents who were
more affluent than the typical audience at its mass-market
three-ring shows. Feld estimated that premiere ``couch'' seating
would be in the $40 range, and other ticket prices would average in
the mid-$20 range.
</P>
<P>
   It was to Sarasota that the silver, 80-car Ringling train _
forever dubbed by circus folk ``the funeral train'' _ returned 42
years ago with its folded tent and grieving cargo of circus
veterans after the circus had ended its annual run four months
early.
</P>
<P>
   But these days an international company of 48 performers is
rehearsing the new tent's 2-hour 15-minute show, with an 8-member
band performing in highly stylized red-and-gold Art Deco-ish sets.
The show is a potpourri of trapeze flyers, acrobats, variety
performers and animals _ including 27 geese, 10 horses, four ducks
and two foxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an all-star show, and we hope it will create a
sensation in the world of the circus,'' said Alex Petrov, a
26-year-old second-generation wire walker.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The intimacy of the single ring, said Parkinson, the historian,
``enables audiences to focus on one act at a time, and to better
identify with performers who are human beings doing extraordinary
things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For two hours we want to throw a party for the audience,''
said Raffaele DeRitis, 32, the show's Italian director, who has
created circuses, theatrical productions, operas and magic shows in
Europe. The show is a narrative that introduces the audience to a
group of ``ordinary'' people who become performers in the ring
before the ticket holders' eyes. They appear again as ordinary
people who bid the audience farewell after the show's finale. ``And
we want to encourage the audience to wonder about what happens
behind the scenes, to imagine the characters in the show, their
romances and their hatreds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Barnum's Kaleidoscape'' was coined by Feld, 50, a kaleidoscope
collector who wanted to build a quirky show about a circus that was
a tribute to P.T. Barnum. The name is also a reference to ``an
escape from everyday reality,'' Feld said.
</P>
<P>
   David Larible, 41, the new show's featured performer, said,
``The audience will get to meet me as a person, before the show,
then witness my transformation to David the Clown in the ring.''
Larible has spent eight years as the star clown on the Ringling Red
Unit, one of the circus' two touring shows that crisscross the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the new show is ``a breakthrough for a generation of
seasoned American circus people who have never performed in a tent,
or even a one-ring circus, like me,'' said Jon Weiss, 36, a former
clown and juggler who spent seven years being shot from a Ringling
cannon, always in an arena. He is now not only a manager of the
show but also will play himself, as the manager.
</P>
<P>
   One creator of the new show is a living link to the old tent. In
1955, as an 11-year-old in Butte, Mont., Brian Liddicoat, now the
show's general manager, was hired with dozens of other boys as a
day laborer to help put up the 12,000-seat, three-ring Ringling
tent in Stodden Park.
</P>
<P>
   His fee? ``A free pass to see the show,'' he said with a laugh.
``I'll never forget how thrilling it was to be part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   After its Sarasota debut, the circus will head to Austin, Texas,
and then to Irvine Meadows in California. If it proves to be a
critical and financial success, Ringling hopes to re-create it
around the country and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Ringling's largest competitor in the tented world was
magnanimous toward the interloper. ``We wish them a lot of luck,
and we respect them as serious people,'' said Jean David, vice
president for marketing at Cirque du Soleil, which has become the
worldwide one-ring phenomenon to which Ringling aspires. ``But you
know, I think Cirque du Soleil competes more with `The Phantom of
the Opera' than with other circuses.''
</P>
<P>
   But a smaller competitor was less sanguine about the increased
competition. ``My sense is that Ringling will borrow more from us
than from the Cirque du Soleil, and that Kenneth's show will appeal
more to family audiences, like our show does,'' said Binder of the
Big Apple Circus, which began in 1977 in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Kenneth decides he wants to come into our markets, there
will be a competitive situation,'' Binder added. ``Audiences will
have to decide, `Which one do I go to?'''
</P>
<P>
   If Cirque du Soleil provides Ringling with a business model for
one-ring success, it has demonstrated that the rewards can be
immense. Since 1984 more than 18 million people have bought a
ticket to one of Cirque du Soleil's productions (there are
currently six worldwide), and the company has founded an empire of
multimedia souvenir merchandising. Published reports have estimated
that the privately held Montreal company's revenue exceeds $119
million, with profit averaging 15 to 20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Cirque du Soleil's tents seat 2,500 people with an average
ticket price of more than $50, selling out 93 percent of the time.
Big Apple has an average ticket price of $23 during its multistate
tour in a 1,980-seat tent (except at Lincoln Center, where the
average ticket costs $36.)
</P>
<P>
   Since many circus performers live permanently in Sarasota, there
has been tremendous interest here in the new show. All the
curiosity was rewarded on a recent Sunday, when passers-by
witnessed a sight no American has seen for four decades: a Ringling
crew putting up a tent.
</P>
<P>
   Ten workers, including performers like Weiss and Petrov, toiled
where once 200 strained to ``fly,'' or raise, a three-ring tent.
And instead of work elephants, electric winches whined as they
ratcheted the new tent upward on four 60-foot steel masts.
</P>
<P>
   As roustabouts leaped to install the tent poles, Weiss surveyed
his handiwork. Smiling triumphantly, he said, ``I think Ringling's
back in the tent business again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
