<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONBONS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 
 When you lust for nuts and all you get is cremes ...   By Holly Ocasio Rizzo 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
O n Sunday, Valentines will turn the 35 million lovely heart-shaped
candy boxes expected to be sold this year into wrecks of cockeyed
paper frills and half-bitten, poked-at chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   Where's the caramel, and which one's the champagne truffle? If
only we had X-ray vision.
</P>
<P>
   Without a map, not even experts can be sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have boxes and boxes of chocolates here, and we're forever
guessing what's inside each candy,'' says Karen Louie, a publicist
for the American Boxed Chocolate Manufacturers in New York City.
``You see people in the office biting into them, shaking their
heads and saying, `No, that's not it.'''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always such a guessing game. In the not-distant past
when chocolates were handmade, it was easy to tell which was which.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a certain extent, there are traditional patterns,'' says
Terry Richardson of Hayward, a British-trained chocolate
technologist and candy-industry consultant. ``English toffee, for
example, is chocolate-coated and rolled in nuts. If the candy had a
lemon-cream center, the candy maker would traditionally mark it
with an `L' on top. Raspberry was an `R.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Some small-scale chocolate makers who make everything by hand,
still mark their candies in this way, he says, and vestiges of the
code crop up in some mass-made boxes: a curl like a ``C'' on a
round cherry cordial or a square caramel, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But mass-marketers using candy-coating machines (the first ones
were developed in the 1920s to keep up with increasing consumer
demand for chocolate) can't re-create the marks. Instead, many use
locator maps tucked into the boxes _ an idea pioneered by Whitman
Co. (now owned by Russell Stover) in 1912. After Whitman's first
map, imitators quickly surfaced, giving rise to the myth that candy
makers secretly code their chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember as a kid seeing a diagram with squiggles and marks,
a chart that maybe came out of a box, to tell what was inside a
chocolate candy,'' says Beth Klein, librarian at the California
Culinary Academy in San Francisco. She searched the school's
extensive library for a similar key but came up dry.
</P>
<P>
   She's not alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call recently from the people working on reviving the
TV game show `I've Got a Secret' who had thought, `What a great
idea if we could crack the See's candy code,' '' says Richard Van
Doren, vice president of marketing for See's in South San Francisco
and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It's no dark secret: See's includes a photo guide to its candies
in the back of its mail-order booklets. The pictures are side views
of sliced-open chocolates; they don't show the top markings, which
are specified in fat three-ring binders of candy measurements See's
executives keep in their offices.
</P>
<P>
   The specs call for particular marks: caramel, ``smooth with 1
mark''; buttercream, ``smooth''; cherry, ``4 marks''; orange,
``smooth with O mark.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was all done by hand, the candy makers would dip the
chocolate and put a mark on it with a piece of copper wire,'' Van
Doren says. See's now makes few marks by hand. Most are applied by
machinery that lightly touches the sticky tops of the candies after
they've passed through a sheet of liquid chocolate. Then the
candies move by conveyor belt through a cooling tunnel that
solidifies the marks.
</P>
<P>
   However, many chocolate companies long ago gave up the handmade
look. They make candy by coating molds with chocolate, pressing
fillings into the coatings, then sealing the backs with more
chocolate. The result: shiny identical shells, starfish, dollar
signs, hearts and other shapes. The advantage: a lot more perfect
chocolates turned out of molds a lot quicker.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of BONBON 2 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The only way to tell what's inside is to bite.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what chocoholics do.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent survey for Russell Stover Candies, customers 'fessed
up to surprising filling-detection techniques: 43 percent decide
based on a candy's shape; 30 percent eat whatever they touch; 27
percent nibble before taking for keeps; and 14 percent scratch or
poke the surface to try the filling. Because of that high
willingness to destroy pretty chocolates, this year the company
puts a candy map in boxes of its Russell Stover line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet I can figure out half the box, but that's no better than
most people,'' says Tim Moriarty, features editor at Chocolatier
magazine, aimed at amateur chocolate makers. In each issue, the
magazine takes the lid off a box of molded chocolates, photographs
it and identifies the filling in each piece.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies are devising similar chocolate IDs. Laderbach, a
Swiss company whose chocolates sell for $50 a 15.2-ounce box,
prints a guide inside the lid. Joseph Schmidt Confections, of San
Francisco, puts its guide on box tags. Bernard Callebaut
Chocolaterie of Calgary, Alberta, includes a tiny photo guide in
its mail-order brochures. Brown &AMP; Haley, in Tacoma, Wash., just
moved its photo guide from the bottom to inside the lid after
customers complained about having to pick up the box to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps such guides won't be needed for long _ not since Mike
Bursk of San Clemente started selling the Sneak-Peek Candy Sampler.
The 31/2-inch-long device, sold by mail order, is made of nickel
and resembles a pogo stick.
</P>
<P>
   Bursk, a charter fishing boat operator, was inspired by a dinner
party at which he encountered a box of chocolates with all the
bottoms poked and scratched. ``My wife and I laughed about it, and
finally I decided to make something that would take a more
surgically clean sample,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   One method is even more sanitary. ``Usually you can tell by the
shape and size,'' says Carole Bloom, author of ``All About
Chocolate'' (Macmillan, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not foolproof.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of BONBON 2 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
