<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTEMPTS TO CENSURE CLINTON INTENSIFY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Efforts to censure President Clinton for his
conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair intensified Monday as it
became increasingly clear that House prosecutors will not be able
to muster the 67 votes they need in the Senate to convict and
remove the president from office.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the prospect of letting Clinton off without being
punished at all, Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said
he hopes to introduce a resolution of censure as early as Thursday
that would make ``a historical statement of record'' condemning the
president's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, has threatened to filibuster any
censure motion, contending that it would be unconstitutional for
the Senate to take any action against Clinton other than voting to
convict or acquit him of the charges of perjury and obstruction of
justice filed against him by the House.
</P>
<P>
   It takes 60 votes to overcome a filibuster in the Senate.
Daschle told reporters Monday that he needs support from at least
20 Republicans, because ``four or five'' of the 45 Senate Democrats
agree with Gramm that it would be unconstitutional to do anything
else in the case other than to vote for or against conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we need 20 Republicans to join with Democrats.
Democrats, I don't think, will be united on censure,'' Daschle
said.
</P>
<P>
   If Gramm succeeds in holding off a vote on censure during the
trial, which is scheduled to end Friday, Daschle said he would try
to bring it up in late February when the Senate returns from a
10-day recess to resume its regular business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that Phil Gramm has the 40 votes to sustain his
position. But if he does, we will just look for appropriate
(legislative) vehicles when we come back and keep amending those
vehicles so long as it takes to (pass) the censure,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   But some lawmakers who would probably vote to censure Clinton
are concerned that members will lose interest in it after a long
recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really doubt if people are going to want to turn to this
again,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who has tried to win
support for his own idea of adjourning the impeachment trial for a
brief period to allow senators to adopt a censure resolution, and
then resuming the trial again.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., and Robert Bennett, R-Utah,
have been leading an effort to fashion a bipartisan censure
resolution that would condemn Clinton's behavior. But it has failed
to attract widespread support because it does not say that Clinton
actually lied about his relationship with Lewinsky and tried to
hide it.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the lead prosecutor for the House, said
in his closing arguments Monday that he was ``dumbfounded'' by some
of the drafts of the censure proposals being circulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sound tougher than the articles of impeachment,'' he told
the senators.
</P>
<P>
   But he warned senators that if they vote for censure it would in
effect amount to a dereliction of their constitutional duty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
