<SLUG> BC-PRISON-GANGS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE MEMBERS OF TEXAS PRISON GANG SENTENCED TO LIFE IN INMATE'S
DEATH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three members of the white Aryan Circle prison gang have been
sentenced to life in prison for murdering a rival white gang member
with a 6-inch-homemade knife during an attack at Livingston's
Terrell Unit.
</P>
<P>
   The three were the first of nine to face charges in the Oct. 6,
1997, attack on Ryan Osgood, a 20-year-old member of the White
Knights.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood had been serving a life sentence for the 1994 capital
murder of Houston convenience store clerk An Phu Le, 38. Le was
shot in the back after he refused to give money to Osgood and
another robber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually white gangs attack other races,'' said A.P. Merillat,
an investigator with the Texas Department of Criminal Justice's
Special Prosecution Unit. ``Here you have two white supremacist
groups going after one another. That's somewhat unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Merillat said the attack on Osgood was motivated by revenge over
earlier conflicts between the groups. Merillat said both groups,
though relatively small, have cells inside and outside state
prisons. Like other prison gangs, he said, the two white groups
compete to control the penitentiary market for tobacco, drugs and
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Prison authorities said the White Knights bear no link to the
White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan other than sharing some beliefs
and symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in 1997, witnesses testified in last week's trial, Aryan
Circle vice president Terry Rayborn obtained a master key to
inmates' lockers, using it to ``plant'' homemade weapons in those
assigned to members of the White Knights.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, Merillat said, Osgood retaliated by attacking
Rayborn with a sharpened piece of wire in the prison dining hall.
Rayborn was only slightly injured, but his Aryan Circle responded
by ordering ``hits'' on Osgood.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood was attacked as he and a cellmate, fellow White Knights
member Marc Ashbrook, left their cell for the dining hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That cellblock had been under lockdown for several weeks,''
Merillat said. ``This was the first meal they were to eat in the
chow hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Merillat said two groups of Aryan Circle members attacked the
men. Ashbrook successfully fought off his attackers, but Osgood was
fatally beaten and stabbed with a 6-inch knife made of Plexiglas
near the third-floor showers.
</P>
<P>
   Guards used tear gas to disperse the combatants.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood was taken to Hermann Hospital in Houston, where he
lingered 13 days on life support before dying. Merillat said the
weapon was broken in half. Part was thrown from a prison window; an
unsuccessful attempt was made to flush the other half down a
toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Sentenced for the murder in Livingston state district court were
Thomas Armstrong, serving 10 years for a Travis County burglary;
Stephen Brumfield, 15 years for aggravated assault with a deadly
weapon in McLennan County; and Robert Campbell, 40 years for
attempted capital murder in Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   Merillat said no date has been set for trial of the remaining
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
