<HEADER>
A6733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPEN-DELIBERATIONS-CO     02-08 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEN-DELIBERATIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vote on open deliberations may give way to written statements
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators pushing a bipartisan plan to open the
Senate deliberations on President Clinton's fate say they don't
have the votes to overturn a 131-year-old rule keeping them secret.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is scheduled to vote on the motion to open the
deliberations today when it reconvenes at 1 p.m. to begin the final
phase of the impeachment trial. The bid to open the closed session
lost ground Monday when Majority leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) said
through his spokesman that he opposed changing Senate rules to open
the deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate at this moment is as close to a jury as it gets,''
said Lott spokesman John Czwartacki. ``In 2600 years of trials,
jury deliberations have not been open.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lott and other key Republican leaders remain opposed to
opening the deliberations, several Republican senators said there
is a growing willingness to release a transcript of the closed-door
session after the impeachment trial is over.
</P>
<P>
   But making the transcript public, a departure from impeachment
precedent, would also require a vote of the Senate and that vote
may not come for several weeks, said Sen. Larry Craig (R-Idaho), a
member of Lott's leadership team.
</P>
<P>
   In place of opening the deliberations, Lott and other leaders
are pushing an alternative that would simply allow senators to
introduce into the impeachment record written statements on why
they voted for or against the impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone (D-Minn.), a Democratic backer of the open
deliberations proposal, said he believes no more than one of the 45
Senate Democrats will vote against opening the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't get opened, it will be because Republicans voted
against it,'' said Wellstone.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment rules adopted in the 1868 impeachment trial of
President Andrew Johnson stipulate that a two-thirds vote of the
Senate is required to add a new rule to open the deliberations.
About two dozen Republicans say they will vote for the motion to
open deliberations, but backers are still about seven votes short
of the 67 needed to change the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is historic,'' said Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison (R-Texas),
a GOP backer of the proposal. ``I cannot imagine that we would
impeach or not impeach the president of the United States in a
closed session. It's too important to our country, and I think it
is a precedent that needs to be set for the future that we were
open in our final deliberations.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison noted that there is no record of the deliberations in
Johnson's impeachment. ``I think that is a loss for history,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Johnson's impeachment, Senate deliberations were open.
Critics of the plan to reverse the Johnson precedent note that Sen.
Robert Byrd (D-W.Va.) and then-majority leader Bob Dole revised the
impeachment rules in 1986 and did not change the clause on closed
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also point to the two-closed door sessions the Senate
has already had, praising the open and candid discussions that took
place outside the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do feel that a closed deliberations creates a frankness and
a clarity to the debate,'' Craig said. ``If it's open, then it
really becomes the final speeches of senators prior to their vote.
That's not a deliberation. That would be two and a half or three
days of political statements.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders are also worried that the open deliberations
would offer Democrats one last opportunity to attack House
prosecutors and Independent Counsel Ken Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``We risk a very high profile partisan debate and I think to
date we've avoided that,'' Craig. ``I think some of my colleagues
on the other side might be drawn to that flame.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
