<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-PILOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN AIRLINES TRIMS FLIGHTS IN PILOT DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Airlines was forced to call off 16 percent of its 2,250
flights Monday in a dispute with its 9,200 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   American officials, who said they were flooded by public
inquiries, referred all media questions to a recorded message that
said American was shuffling its passengers into later flights or
onto other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Airlines sincerely regrets that a disagreement
between the company and the Allied Pilots Association has impacted
our customers, and we apologize for the inconvenience,'' said
airlines spokesman Tim Smith on the recording. ``We remain
optimistic that this situation can be settled promptly.''
</P>
<P>
   The recording provided passengers with a toll-free number to
call to check the status of their flights. A customer service
representative who answered the phone reported that, as of Monday
 &UR; afternoon &LR; , none of Tuesday flights had been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones, an American Airlines passenger whose flight to Lima
from Boston's Logan International Airport was canceled Monday, said
he didn't buy that message. The airline Monday shifted his travel
to a Delta Air Lines flight leaving Boston three hours after his
original flight was supposed to depart and gave him a $15 dinner
voucher.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not persuade Jones, a computer consultant from
Middleton, to keep his Thursday return flight to Boston on
American. After switching his return flight to Continental
Airlines, Jones said: ``I'm not sure these guys will have it
straightened out by Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   An American Airlines ticket agent said rescheduling passengers
was not a problem Monday because of relatively slow travel traffic.
But, he added, if problems persist into next week, passengers could
face havoc finding alternative flights during the busy school
vacation week.
</P>
<P>
   American was forced to cancel flights throughout the weekend as
pilots called in sick or refused to work overtime to register their
unhappiness with AMR Corp., the Fort Worth-based parent company of
American.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Allied Pilots Association, which represents
American Airlines pilots, said the pilots' dispute centers around
American's refusal to give equal pay to pilots of Reno Air, a West
Coast carrier purchased by AMR late last year. Pilots of Reno Air
earn roughly half of the $150,000 average annual salary of American
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fondest hope is that we get things resolved quickly,''
said Gregg Overman, aunion spokesman. ``We don't like to see our
passengers caught in the middle of the dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   Overman, however, said the airline has not responded to the
union's overtures to negotiate a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AMR Corp. fell 2 15/16 Monday to close at 57.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
