<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-500&AMP;A     02-08 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO AVOID BONGOS AND CIGARS WHEN TRIAL ENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-PERJURY,
IMPEACH-DEBATE, IMPEACH-CENSURE, IMPEACH-SCENE) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will bang no bongo drum.
</P>
<P>
   When his impeachment trial ends _ probably later this week and
almost certainly in acquittal _ Clinton will not surround himself
with grinning Democrats and declare himself exonerated, his aides
say.
</P>
<P>
   And, notwithstanding any past exuberance by this serial
political escapist, count on this: He will not be glimpsed in
public over the weekend chewing a cigar.
</P>
<P>
   With Republican Congressmen fretting that Clinton will ballyhoo
the outcome of his trial, his aides have begun debating whether he
should say anything at all after the Senate votes on two articles
of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   That debate is a proxy for a broader discussion over how Clinton
should act in public _ and govern _ after the trial ends, but while
the cloud of impeachment, lies and proven caddishness lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the president's spokesman, has declared the White
House a ``gloat-free zone,'' and he insisted no one would feel
jolly, only relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to celebrate here,'' Paul Begala, the
president's counselor, said Monday. ``Saying that you win this is
like saying you win an earthquake. You survive it and you
rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Clinton advisers are bemoaning two trips the president
plans to make shortly after the expected vote _ first to Mexico
(``All right, tequila!'' declared one Clinton adviser, doing a
passable Clinton imitation) and then to New Hampshire to rally
Democrats. No matter what the president says or does, some aides
believe, critics will complain that he does not seem contrite
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can he do?'' one senior aide asked, insisting that
Clinton recognized the error of his ways. ``It's almost as if
people want him to curl up in a ball and be catatonic.''
</P>
<P>
   Another aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said: ``We're
just going to get pounded. There's nothing we can do about it. And
we're probably going to drop in the polls, too, because a lot of
the people who are for us now just hate what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The image of Clinton as snickering scapegrace, reveling like
Bugs Bunny in the flummoxing of his pursuers, has become embedded
not only in Congress but also in the popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a gloating dance!'' an actor portraying Clinton
insisted last weekend on the NBC program ``Saturday Night Live,''
as a comedian playing his secretary, Betty Currie, boogied in the
Oval Office. ``It is a serious dance of soul-searching and
contrition.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Clinton has no one to blame but himself, or his
Republican critics, depending on one's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, after a federal judge threw out Paula Corbin Jones'
sexual misconduct lawsuit against the president, he was
photographed through a hotel window in Dakar, Senegal, with an
unlighted cigar in his mouth and a bongo drum in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   The president was just examining native wares as he did some
private shopping, aides said. But the drum has become a metaphor,
often invoked these days on Capitol Hill, for Clintonian gloating.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Senate Republicans and even some Democrats also complain about
what they call Clinton's ``pep rally'' on the White House lawn
after he was impeached on Dec. 19. Clinton stood before two
busloads of applauding Democratic members of Congress to say that
he accepted ``responsibility for what I did wrong in my personal
life'' but that he intended to serve ``until the last hour of the
last day of my term.''
</P>
<P>
   The event's tone was actually fairly somber. The conservative
American Spectator editorialized this month that it was ``more like
a wake where sadness was diluted by consternation owing to the
corpse's insistence that he be allowed to mix with the bereaved.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was trying to underscore the partisan nature of the
split impeachment vote in the House of Representatives. He also
wanted to demonstrate that he had political support against the
argument that because he had been impeached, he should resign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides claim that Republicans are misrepresenting the
lawn event as a pep rally so they can build support for a strong
censure resolution, even though some Democrats have taken the same
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans have been using this for political cover,''
Lockhart said. ``It's an easier argument than saying, `We have to
punish him because we like to punish him.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Clinton's advisers are also interested in punishment.
Indeed, besides exhaustion, one emotion that is likely to snuff
elation is the anger some feel toward House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not on the forgive-and-forget battalion,'' said James
Carville, Clinton's one-time campaign manager. ``I'll go ahead and
let the true visionaries move on to the next millennium. I have
some unfinished business in this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Carville cautioned that the end of the trial did not mean the
end of the controversy surrounding Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't over till it's over, that's No. 1,'' he said, ``and
No. 2, it'll never be over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
