<HEADLINE>
BRUINS HOPE WESTWARD SWING WILL BE REFRESHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ Last fall, when the Bruins left town with a
goal of taming the West, it was nearly a three-week journey that,
because of the Olympics, combined what is normally two trips, in
October and February.
</P>
<P>
   Their 6-2-0 showing set them up favorably for the rest of the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with a normal schedule, the Bruins are hoping to use
a three-game swing to turn their fortunes around.
</P>
<P>
   This area has been rather prosperous for the Bruins in the
1990s. Beginning with the 1990-91 season, Boston has played 21
games in Edmonton, Calgary, and Vancouver and has gone 12-7-2,
including a mark of 7-2-0 over the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   After winning just one game in their last nine (1-6-2), the
Bruins were looking forward to heading out on the road. Life is
simpler, there are no distractions, and they don't feel compelled
to put on a show. That's the home team's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very big,'' said right wing Rob DiMaio, who hails from
Calgary. ``These are three solid road games we have to put
together. It could do a lot for our confidence if we come back
successful from this road trip and gain some ground as opposed to
losing ground on some teams. I think everyone understands how
important it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The last couple of weeks has been a grueling stretch for the
Bruins, who arrived here Monday after playing four games in six
days. Beginning with Tuesday night's contest against the Oilers,
the Bruins will play three games in five nights before heading
home.
</P>
<P>
   After going winless in eight, Boston has a modest unbeaten
streak going _ 1-0-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three out of four points on the weekend is good,'' said Ray
Bourque, referring to a 2-2 tie with Philadelphia and a
heart-in-your-mouth 3-2 victory over the Rangers. ``It wasn't an
easy win. We were in pretty good shape, up, 2-0, and then Brian
Leetch scores a nice goal and then they get a fluky bounce and then
it's a tie game. It was nice to see Joe (Thornton) score the winner
and things break our way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're looking forward to the challenge. We're all
aware of where we are right now at this time in the standings.
Going on the road can be a good thing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton has stepped up his play a great deal lately. That has
coincided with the top line of Jason Allison, Sergei Samsonov, and
Dmitri Khristich getting back on track after a significant period
of struggling.
</P>
<P>
   If there remains a weak point with the Bruins, it's the
inability to hold a lead. Last year, the club was remarkably
reliable when ahead going into the third period. This year, it's
been one adventure after another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's like you don't feel you have a big enough lead
at any time in the game,'' said Bourque. ``We're up, 2-0 (against
the Rangers), then it's 2-1 and we were thinking, `Come on, let's
get that third one and make it a little bit easier on ourselves.'
Then they tie it up but you've got to try to stay positive and
believe things are going to go your way and they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the record hasn't shown it, Bourque said the turnaround
has been coming for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the last 10 days where we did play well _ the New
Jersey game (a 2-0 loss), the Carolina game (a 0-0 tie), the
Colorado game (a 3-2 loss) and in Philly, and they were all games
where we stuck to basics and did the little things really well and
especially away from the puck,'' he said. ``(Against New York), we
played pretty well, but their first goal, it was a mis-coverage and
a point guy jumps in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be focused, you've got to be on, you've got to
be aware of what's going on at all times. When we're sharp, we pick
up those guys. We don't give up any real quality chances. The games
I mentioned, we did that really well, so by doing that you give
yourself a good chance to win. Obviously, you have to score goals
to capitalize on playing that way, but the goals are going to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been times _ too many _ when one group of players
might be performing well on a given night but others have had an
off-night. The games in which everyone plays together for the whole
contest have been very few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   The talent on offense has proven thin, and the defense, partly
because of age and injury, has been even thinner at times. So
Thornton stepping up would give the Bruins a sorely needed
dimension. Because he's still only 19, it's unrealistic to think he
can do it every night, but if he does it more often than not, the
team will breathe much easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good player,'' said DiMaio. ``When he has the
confidence, he can do a lot of good things. It was good to see. I'm
sure he likes to be in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was impressed with the youngster Sunday, both on his
winning goal and with the way he played against Wayne Gretzky in
the first period while Tim Taylor was taking stitches for a facial
laceration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's matured a lot and his game has matured a lot,'' Bourque
said. ``He's doing a lot of little things consistently well. He's
taking charge out there a lot more than he did last year. He wants
it. He was into it, you could see it. He wanted to make a
difference and he went out and certainly did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Sunday's finish is the beginning of a positive trend
will better be answered Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's turning a little bit now for us,'' said DiMaio. ``Things
are getting better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
