<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIDRUG-PLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW US ANTIDRUG STRATEGY HIT BY CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House, unveiling its latest antidrug
strategy Monday, promised a new approach, a novel vision, and more
money _ $17.8 billion _ but critics charged it is a repackaging of
failed policies of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must mount an all-out effort to banish crime, drugs and
disorder and hopelessness from our streets once and for all,'' said
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Health policy advocates said they supported the effort _ and the
overall thrust of the adminstration's five-part strategy _ but they
criticized the administration's attempt to make it seem
significantly more money is being dedicated to drug abuse
prevention and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Clinton administration proposed spending the same
two-thirds of the drug control budget on domestic and international
law enforcement efforts this year as it did last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a betrayal of what the White House says it's doing,
promising a balanced strategy when it is lopsided,'' said Eric
Sterling, former counsel to the House Judiciary Committee and
president of the Criminal Justice Policy Foundation, a Washington
research group.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling said the government was ignoring its own research,
citing a Rand Corp. study that showed prevention and treatment
were, dollar for dollar, the best way to cut down drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Coinciding with the administration's announcement was the
release of a Boston University School of Public Health survey of
1,500 community leaders working to reduce substance abuse around
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that those surveyed, while supporting a strong
law enforcement presence, called for a change in federal policies
and reversal of spending priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a disconnect between what leaders see as necessary to
help their communities and what they see coming out of
Washington,'' said David L. Rosenbloom, director of Join Together,
BU's anti-substance abuse initiative.
</P>
<P>
   It is easier and more effective to focus on preventing and
curing drug abuse rather than on halting the flow of drugs into the
country or on criminalizing substance abuse, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the new strategy would give a boost to programs that
worked and repair those that didn't by establishing new standards
to measure successs and failure. Another cornerstone of the
strategy is the $195 million anti-drug advertising campaign
launched this year, as well as a program to funnel more money into
drug treatment in prisons.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's plan involves a five-prong approach:
educating children, decreasing the addicted population, breaking
the cycle of drugs and crime, securing the nation's borders from
drugs and reducing the drug supply.
</P>
<P>
   The blend of strategies is aimed at reducing the use and
availability of drugs by 25 percent by 2002 and 50 percent by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Additional goals for the period ending in 2007 are to reduce by
30 percent the rate of crime associated with drug trafficking and
use, and cutting the health and social costs associated with drugs
by 25 percent. As of 1995, the social costs of drug use were
estimated at $110 billion, a 64 percent increase over 1990.
</P>
<P>
   White House drug policy director Barry McCaffrey also lauded the
administration's success in the war against drugs, noting that
cocaine crop production had fallen in South America and drug use by
adults is at half what it was in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   National surveys, however, show drug use among youth aged 12-18
has climbed steadily since 1992, and only began to level off last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Not all avocates were critical of the plan. Arthur T. Dean,
president of the Community Anti-Drug Coalitions of America, which
represents 4,000 groups around the nation, said the new budget
shows the administration is starting to listen to advocates who
work to battle drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased with this truly comprehensive approach,
which laid out prevention and treatment as well as supply
reduction,'' he said. ``I see a shift and a recognition that demand
reduction is the key element in the strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
