<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computer Generation Inc. gets Bahrainian investor
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Middle East investment bank has acquired a
``substantial interest'' in Computer Generation Inc., and the
infusion of capital will fuel an aggressive acquisition program for
the Atlanta telecommunications company.
</P>
<P>
   Crescent Capital Investments Inc., the Atlanta-based subsidiary
of Bahrain-based First Islamic Investment Bank, paid about $175
million for an unspecified stake in Computer Generation. Jackie
Ward, CEO, said she remains the largest individual shareholder in
Computer Generation, but ``as a group, they will own more.'' Ward
said she will continue as CEO, a position she has held since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Ward is one of the few women in Georgia to head a major company
and in 1997 she became the only woman to serve as chairman of the
Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce. She is a director of BankAmerica
Corp., Premier Technologies Inc., Equifax Inc., SCI Systems, TRIGON
(Blue Cross/Blue Shield of Virginia and Matria Healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   Computer Generation, founded in 1968, makes telecommunications
hardware and software, primarily for the telephone industry. The
company had estimated 1997 revenue between $75 million and $99
million, according to a list of privately held firms compiled last
fall for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution by Arthur Anderson LLP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie will continue to be the strategic leader of the
company,'' said David Crosland, president of Crescent Capital and
an executive of First Islamic Investment Bank. ``This is her
company of 30 years, and the most important thing to Jackie was the
well-being of her employees.''
</P>
<P>
   The business combination will allow Computer Generation to
inaugurate a stock option plan for employees. Ward said the option
program ``will help CGI grow by enabling the company to retain and
recruit personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward said she agreed to the transaction so that Computer
Generation would have the capital to embark on an aggressive
acquisition program. ``We are in an acquisition mode _ domestically
and internationally,'' Ward said. ``We don't want capital
restraints in our quest of putting together the organization that
will be the leader in our markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward said Crescent Capital and Computer Generation are
``evaluating several intriguing acquisitions'' that would expand
the company's products and presence in its markets.
</P>
<P>
   First Islamic was founded in June 1997 by prominent individuals
in the Middle East, who initially invested $100 million in the
bank. This is the second major transaction for Crescent Capital,
which purchased Watermark, a kayak and canoe manufacturer, in July
1998 for $40 million. Crosland met Ward at an Atlanta Chamber event
and explained that he was interested in joining with companies run
by founding shareholders. Ward and Crosland started exploratory
talks last March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are focused on doing transactions in the Southeast,''
Crosland said. ``We are looking to do transactions in the middle
market _ $50 million to $300 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Saporta writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
