<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Canada Wants to Speed Airport Clearance &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   International travelers passing through some of Canada's major
airports to the United States may soon have fewer bureaucratic
hurdles to jump.
</P>
<P>
   Under a recently introduced Canadian bill called the
Preclearance Act, which would expand the scope of existing law, air
travelers would no longer be required to clear Canadian customs for
connecting flights to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is awaiting a vote in the Senate and would then
have to be considered by the House of Commons, but it is widely
expected to gain government approval this spring.
</P>
<P>
   It is based on a one-year pilot project at Vancouver
International Airport that enabled more than 70,000 passengers
bound for the United States to bypass Canadian customs and
immigration checks and proceed directly to American officials at
that airport.
</P>
<P>
   The streamlined process makes it faster and easier for a
traveler returning to the United States from Asia to land in
Vancouver and catch a connecting flight. He only needs to show his
passport to American officials before boarding.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, some non-Americans even needed a Canadian visa just
to walk to the boarding gate.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson International Airport in Toronto and the Aeroport de
Montreal (Dorval) expect to implement the program this year, once
the legislation is passed. Airports in Calgary, Edmonton, Ottawa
and Winnipeg would be eligible for this so-called preclearance
after 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement is expected to be reciprocal in the United
States, once inconsistencies in American immigration and Customs
laws are worked out. Then Canadian officials at United States
airports could ease entry into Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of preclearance facilities in San Francisco and
Anchorage are being discussed by officials of the two nations.
</P>
<P>
   Kalyani Vittala &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the Las Vegas Strip, Luxury but No Casino &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With 3,000-room casino hotels sprouting up along the Strip in
Las Vegas, a new 424-room hotel with no gambling areas in this
valley of the giants might seem curious. But the Four Seasons, a
luxury hotel scheduled to open March 2 on Las Vegas Boulevard,
isn't what it seems to be at first glance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is a small luxury hotel with no casino, but it shares a
building with the new 3,000-room Mandalay Bay casino hotel. The
Four Seasons' rooms occupy the 35th through the 39th floors, which
will be served by three elevators accessible only with Four Season
room keys. And the Four Seasons will have its own entrance, lobby,
restaurants, spa, meeting rooms and pool (with free cold towels and
spritzing service).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if the spirit moves, the Mandalay Bay's gambling den
is just down the hall from the Four Seasons' elevators. But the
Mandalay Bay will not give high rollers free lodging in Four
Seasons rooms. Just to make the distinction between the hotels
absolutely clear, the Four Seasons will avoid another favorite
policy of casino hotels: changing the room rates based on demand.
Rooms cost from $200 to $700 a night, suites $400 and up, and those
prices will stay in place all year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information, contact the Four Seasons Hotel Las Vegas, Post
Office Box 98881, Las Vegas, Nev. 89193; (877) 632-5200, fax (702)
632-5222.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Siano &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The `Mighty Mo' Opens To the Public in Hawaii &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The battleship Missouri, on which the Japanese formally
surrendered to end World War II, opened as a permanent memorial
last month at Pearl Harbor, next to the Battleship Arizona
Memorial. Visitors can now walk the deck and bridge and see the
guns of the ship, which was in service from 1944 to 1955 and 1986
to 1992. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tours begin at the Bowfin Submarine Memorial. A shuttle bus
takes visitors to Ford Island at the Pearl Harbor Naval Base, where
the Missouri is docked.
</P>
<P>
   A short film and exhibits can be seen on board, in the
orientation center, including photographs of the Missouri in
action. The tour takes visitors through the crew's quarters, and
the so-called Surrender Deck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Battleship Missouri Memorial is open daily, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Admission: $10, $6 ages 4 to 12. For information and reservations:
(877) 644-4896. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baseball Fans Need Spring Training, Too &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Majorleague baseball players are about to head to training in
Florida and Arizona, and fans unable to wait for opening day can
join them on a spring-training package.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Travel, a Massachusetts company specializing in travel to
sporting events, offers spring training vacations, both custom and
pre-packaged. A four-night, five-game package that includes
accommodations, some meals, game tickets and bus between the hotel
and ballparks is available March 10 to 14 in Phoenix and March 18
to 21 in the Tampa Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   The package using the Crowne Plaza Hotel in Phoenix costs $775 a
person, double occupancy, and the package at the Doubletree Guest
Suites Tampa Bay $695. Air fare is extra. Among the teams whose
games are included are the Yankees, Mets, Red Sox, Braves and Cubs.
Information: (800) 662-4424, www.4sportstravel.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sargent's Elegant World Unfolds in Washington  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The largest retrospective of the work of John Singer Sargent
since 1926, the year after his death, will go on view at the
National Gallery of Art in Washington next Sunday. It brings
together more than 100 paintings and watercolors from museums and
private collections to show his full range: portraits, landscapes,
Impressionist works and figure sketches.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1856 to American parents living in Florence, Sargent
spent winters in places like Nice and Rome and summers in the Alps
or cities like Biarritz. Sargent studied art in Florence, Dresden,
Berlin and Paris, and his works chronicle the elegance of his age.
</P>
<P>
   He is best known for his portraits, both boldly experimental and
classically formal. Rich and prominent personalities on both sides
of the Atlantic clamored to sit for him. Sargent was acclaimed for
capturing their physical presence, social position and
psychological state.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the notorious ``Madame X,'' the exhibit includes a 1906
self-portrait and a group of works depicting Sargent's illustrious
American contemporaries, like Henry James, John D. Rockefeller and
Frederick Law Olmsted.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent knew most of the Impressionists, and he briefly
experimented with Impressionism in the 1880s. A gallery is devoted
to this period, with works like ``Claude Monet Painting at the Edge
of a Wood'' and ``Paul Helleu Sketching With His Wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by his extensive travels in Europe, North America and
the Middle East, Sargent painted many landscapes. Among those on
view are ``Corner of the Church of San Stae, Venice'' and ``The
Rialto, Venice.''
</P>
<P>
   Sargent made watercolors mostly for his own amusement, never
trying to sell them. He nevertheless gained fame in the medium when
the Brooklyn Museum and Museum of Fine Arts in Boston made large
purchases in 1909 and 1912, represented here by examples like ``On
the Grand Canal'' and ``Graveyard in the Tyrol.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition remains at the National Gallery's West Building
until May 31, then travels to the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston
June 23 to Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery of Art, Constitution Avenue, N.W., between
Third and Seventh Streets, is open Monday to Saturday 10 a.m. to 5
p.m., and Sunday 11 a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: (202) 737-4215, www.nga.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Judith H. Dobrzynski
</P>
</TEXT>
