<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TOUGH TIGHTROPE FOR TOM THE TUTOR  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tom Seaver was back where he belonged, in Shea
Stadium. He wasn't where he really belonged, of course, on the
mound. But at age 54, he was finally working for the Mets again.
And now, in the Diamond Club upstairs, he was being formally
introduced as the Mets' new part-time broadcaster, part-time
marketing ambassador and part-time professor of pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Other than to say, ``Criticism in the booth goes along with
being positive when the team is doing well ... there's a difference
between being a network and hometown broadcaster,'' and ``Tim
McCarver is a darn good broadcaster, a fans' favorite and a good
guy,'' he hardly talked about how he hoped to succeed McCarver in
the Mets' television booth.
</P>
<P>
   And if he has a marketing plan, he didn't mention it.
</P>
<P>
   But the more the Hall of Famer once known as Tom Terrific talked
Monday, the more he sounded as if he hoped to be known primarily to
these Mets, especially their young and impressionable pitchers, as
Tom the Tutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be involved in the pitching,'' he said. ``I get a
joy out of it. I want to be available to help them. I loved what I
did, and I was darned good at it. One of the responsibilities we
have is to pass along our knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be a tough tightrope to walk. He's not the manager;
Bobby Valentine is. He's not the pitching coach; Bob Apodaca is.
He's not the minor league pitching coach; Al Jackson is.
</P>
<P>
   But he's Tom Seaver, who won 311 games with a career 2.86 earned
run average and 3,640 strikeouts, who was voted three Cy Young
awards, who had a 25-7 record in 1969 when those Miracle Mets won
the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   So he knows what he'll be talking about. He also knows he'll be
talking to his baseball descendants _ Mets pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't work if I tried to do this with the San Francisco
Giants; there's no bond there,'' he said. ``I will be forever
etched in New York City. I will be forever etched with the New York
Mets. You go to the Hall of Fame because of what you did in a
certain city with a certain organization. That organization is
tattooed to your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver knows the tightrope is there. But as an ex-Marine, he
professes to understand the chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm not on the same page as the manager and the pitching
coach,'' he said, ``I'll only confuse the kid.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows there's more to pitching in the big leagues than a good
fastball or slider. He remembered the late Gil Hodges, then the
Mets' manager, teaching him that in 1968 after the Mets had held on
for a 7-6 victory after he had nearly blown a 7-0 lead against
Willie Mays, Willie McCovey and the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gil was huge, with those big hands; he could really put the
fear of God in you,'' Seaver said. ``He called me into his office
and told me, `Close the door.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sitting behind his desk, and he told me, `You acted
very unprofessional in your approach to this game.' To use my
mother's phrase, I had gotten too big for my britches. Then he
said, `For the rest of your career, I don't care if there's 5,000
or 50,000 people in the ball park, if it's Tuesday in Los Angeles
or Saturday in Wrigley Field, if we've got a 19{-game lead or a
half-game lead, your effort on the field should be exactly the
same.'''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver added: ``I benefited from that lesson for 19 years. I
learned from that. That's a huge issue with me. Everybody makes
mistakes. It's when you don't learn from your mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver passed that lesson along to a young member of the Chicago
White Sox, whom he declined to identify, after the Mets lost their
most famous pitcher in the 1984 free-agent compensation pool draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This young player had acted very unprofessional on the
field,'' he recalled. ``In the runway to the clubhouse, I
confronted him. I picked him up by his jersey, slammed him against
the wall and told him, `Don't you ever conduct yourself on the
field like that again.' He hasn't. And every time he sees me, he
gives me a big hug.''
</P>
<P>
   But as merely a part-time pitching professor, would Seaver be
able to be that harsh with a young Mets pitcher?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said, quickly and firmly. ``If you see a gem of a
player, if you don't do that, it's a disservice to that young man
not to get him back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like Tom the Tutor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
