<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ The Senate impeachment trial of
President Clinton heads toward secret deliberations and an expected
vote for acquittal, leaving Senate Democrats scrambling for a way
to censure the chief executive. By STEWART M. POWELL, JUDY HOLLAND
And JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CENSURE (Washington) _ Efforts to censure President
Clinton for his conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair intensify
after House prosecutors make a final plea to senators to remove the
impeached president from office for perjury and obstruction of
justice. By GREG McDONALD. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-FUNERAL (Amman, Jordan) _ Some 800,000 Jordanians line
the streets of Amman to pay respects to King Hussein, who died of
cancer Sunday. By DEBORAH HORAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HUSSEIN (Amman, Jordan) _ President Clinton joins an
international cast of mourners at the funeral of King Hussein, then
sees a few fellow leaders privately in sideline meetings. By NANCY
MATHIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-CONSERVATION (San Vicente del Caguan, Colombia) _ After
a night of fishing, Nilson Rojas' skiff was filled with bass and
catfish. ``Two years ago, you couldn't catch anything,'' he says.
``But since they imposed the new rules, you can catch enough to
make a living.'' Rojas was referring to environmental decrees by
Colombia's largest Marxist guerrilla group, which has banned
fishing with explosives, unfettered logging and hunting endangered
animals. Their conservation crusade appears to be paying off. By
JOHN OTIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OCTUPLETS-DAD (Houston) _ The father of seven surviving
octuplets is placed on two years probation and is ordered to
undergo a psychological evaluation after pleading no contest to a
charge he attacked his mother-in-law. By STEVE BREWER. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   FRATERNITY-DEATH-TEXAS (Undated) _ A Southwest Texas State
University sophomore dies of injuries he suffered in a beating at a
fraternity house. Nicholas George Armstrong, 21, was found
unconscious Sunday in the Tau Kappa Epsilon house near the
20,000-student campus in San Marcos. By ALLAN TURNER. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-GANGS-TEXAS (Undated) _ Three prison inmates have been
given life sentences for their role in the murder of a 20-year-old
prisoner at the Terrell Unit in Livingston, Texas. The beating and
stabbing of Ryan Osgood in October 1997 was the result of a feud
between rival white supremacist gangs. Trial dates have not been
set for the six other inmates accused in the attack. By ALLAN
TURNER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Houston) _ For those who run a business from home,
there are steps that can be taken to increase the chances of
getting individual disability insurance, protection that is tough
to buy. By PAMELA YIP. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The polls indicate the Republicans
may be hurt by the impeachment charade in the year 2000 elections.
But public memory is short. Can the Democrats keep the rumpus alive
by denouncing the GOP as the party of intolerant snoops and the
Republicans neutralize their image by calling the Democrats the
party of immorality? By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
