<HEADER>
A6751 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-BOS &LR;      02-08 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PROSECUTORS WRAP UP CASE AMID BITTERNESS, FRUSTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For weeks, the House managers in President
Clinton's impeachment trial have straddled the line between being
both politicians and prosecutors. But Monday, as they took their
last shot at Clinton in closing statements, their political
frustration seemed to boil over as it looked inevitable they would
lose their case.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Toensing, a former deputy assistant attorney general in
the Reagan administration, said she became convinced during the
trial that Clinton obstructed justice and should be convicted. But
she said Monday's arguments by the House managers were ineffective
because they seemed more personal than legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was all their personal reasons'' for convicting the
president, she said. ``You could see they were expressing their
frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Toensing said, the House managers made a strategic
error by allowing 13 lawmakers to deliver the closing argument,
making it difficult for senators to ``bond'' with a single
prosecutor, an effect lawyers strive for with their most powerful
closing statements. While many of the House managers made
effective, if familiar, arguments, some used their time to complain
about the restrictions imposed on them or the way television
commentators dismissed them.
</P>
<P>
   The task was easier for the lone attorney closing for the White
House, Charles F. C. Ruff, who had every reason to believe he was
about to win the case because the Senate would fall short of the
two-thirds vote necessary to convict the president. Speaking calmly
from his wheelchair, Ruff rebutted the prosecution using charts and
videotape, including the most favorable clip from the Monica S.
Lewinsky testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff spun a series of physical analogies, telling senators that
the prosecution's case was carried in ``empty pots'' and was made
up of ``pillars'' that, he pronounced, the defense had succeeded in
turning into dust.
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Tribe, professor of constitutional law at Harvard Law
School, said before the trial began that Clinton should not be
impeached because the alleged crimes of perjury and obstruction of
justice did not amount to impeachable offenses. But having watched
the trial, Tribe said, he concluded the case was even weaker than
he had thought. Tribe said the White House defense arguments
convinced him that Clinton did not commit perjury, ``although he
came incredibly close,'' and did not obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   The managers went into the trial believing they had to clear two
hurdles to win conviction of the president. First, they had to
prove Clinton committed perjury and obstructed justice. Second,
they had to demonstrate that such acts were ``high crimes and
misdemeanors,'' which under the Constitution would lead to a vote
to convict and remove the president.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, the managers found that the much-esteemed Senator
Robert C. Byrd, the West Virginia Democrat, had added a third
hurdle. Byrd said in an interview aired Sunday that he had ``no
doubt'' Clinton committed high crimes and misdemeanors, but the
issue is whether the president should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``That . . . does not square with the Constitution or the law,''
an exasperated Representative Stephen Buyer, the Indiana
Republican, told the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Even Tribe, who opposes conviction, said he was dismayed by
Byrd's statement. ``He would violate his constitutional oath if he
were to believe that the president were guilty of these charges,
and these charges were high crimes and misdemeanors,'' and yet vote
against conviction, Tribe said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the managers' frustration was the growing perception
that a number of Republicans would join Democrats in voting against
the article accusing Clinton of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   As for the obstruction of justice charge, it is unclear whether
at least a majority will back it.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration was most evident when Representative Chris
Cannon, a Utah Republican, used his closing statement to explain
why the managers were likely to lose their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The managers had to cut very important portions of our limited
case,'' Cannon said. ``We had a limited number of witnesses,
limited videotape appearances.'' Then Cannon went on to blame the
``new media environment, the Internet with its immediate and often
unvetted content, and cable television with its perpetual talking
heads.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove Cannon's point, one of those talking heads,
Michael Gerhardt, a College of William and Mary constitutional law
specialist, promptly said on CNN that he noticed ``self-pity on the
part of the managers. Their case lacks a certain coherence today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
