<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6752 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-08 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BLINDED BY RIGHTEOUSNESS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rep. Lindsey Graham's voice trembled as he ended the
Republican prosecutors' presentation of evidence. ``For God's
sake,'' he told the Senate, ``figure out what kind of person we
have here in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the trembling emotion? Frustration, I think. Graham and the
other Republican managers are true believers. They believe that an
evil president is about to be acquitted of the impeachment charges,
and they cannot understand why.
</P>
<P>
   If they could only see it, one reason is their very certainty:
their absolute conviction that they are right. Most Americans do
not want to be governed by men who know they are always right. We
believe that life has to have room in it for uncertainty, for
change, for mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are wise to be uncomfortable with absolutism. Sir
Isaiah Berlin, the great British historian-philosopher, showed us
that certainty about everything has been the hallmark of
totalitarian movements.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican managers did not understand how their zealotry
troubled their audience. As Philip Stephens of The Financial Times
put it, they were ``blinded by their moral righteousness.''
</P>
<P>
   An uninformed person who wandered into the Senate gallery and
heard the managers excoriating President Clinton might have thought
they were prosecuting him for mass murder. That is how far their
heightened rhetoric was from the reality here: that the president
tried to conceal illicit sex.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans made the same mistake that they and Kenneth
Starr did in videotaping Clinton's Aug. 17 grand jury testimony and
playing it to the country. They thought Americans would be outraged
at the president's sexual misbehavior. Instead they were offended
at the prurient, invasive effort to make a legal mountain out of
his folly. People could imagine themselves in the hands of
relentless partisan prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   There was a moment in Monica Lewinsky's deposition, not much
noticed, that showed how out of touch the Republican managers were
with reality. Rep. Ed Bryant asked her why she wanted to avoid
testifying in the Paula Jones case about her relationship with the
president. Her answer, devastating in its obviousness, was:
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I thought it was nobody's business. Second of
all, I didn't want anything to do with Paula Jones or her case.''
</P>
<P>
   The managers dripped with sympathy for Ms. Lewinsky. The
president ``threw her life on the ash heap,'' Rep. James Rogan
said. Yes, if Clinton had had the sense to turn away when she first
flirted with him, he would have done himself and her a great favor.
But it was Starr and the House Republicans who made her life into a
public spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Hyde repeatedly sneered that the Democrats had called
``professors'' to testify, a piece of anti-intellectual demagoguery
worthy of George Wallace. He never mentioned the five career
prosecutors, Democratic and Republican, who said they would never
have prosecuted such a case.
</P>
<P>
   That goes to the heart of the Republican failure here. The
extremists on the House Judiciary Committee insisted that the
president had committed crimes, and that removal from office must
follow. They would not even allow the House to consider the penalty
that would have fit the character of the offense, a censure motion.
</P>
<P>
   The charges of perjury and obstruction of justice are supported
by nothing but surmise and conjecture. As White House counsel
Charles Ruff said, neither charge would survive a motion to dismiss
in any court. But the managers kept saying that they were just
doing their constitutional duty _ as if the Constitution required
them to press a partisan case for impeachment on flimsy grounds.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republican Party wants to win national elections, it is
going to have to do something about the party elements, in and out
of Congress, that took the country into this endless impeachment
process. As the Duke of Wellington said when he looked at some of
his own forces, ``I don't know what effect these men will have on
the enemy, but by God they terrify me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 2001EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6754 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-CAMPBELL-COLUMN-C     02-08 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CAMPBELL-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Column: Secret files on '96 Games not such a mess after all
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General news and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Colin Campbell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Attempts by Atlanta's Olympic insiders to keep their
financial records secret are becoming less and less defensible.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic insiders claim that hundreds of boxes of Olympic files
dating back to the late 1980s cannot be exposed to public scrutiny
because they are still too disorganized.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Payne and his associates also insist that Atlanta's
Olympic bidders did not go over the line in doling out gifts to
members of the International Olympic Committee who voted in 1990 to
award the '96 Games to Atlanta. Presumably, the financial records
would shed some light on such assertions _ but the records are
supposedly too confused for us to look at.
</P>
<P>
   After I wrote last week that such stonewalling seemed outrageous
in light of the fact that other cities evidently have bribed the
IOC, I've learned that the records are better organized than
Olympic insiders have been claiming.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, hundreds of the standard white storage boxes that I
wasn't allowed even to look at from a distance have been cataloged
in an elaborate inventory prepared by Payne's own Olympic
organization.
</P>
<P>
   That organization, remember, had a librarian and an archivist in
addition to many clerks. Of course it's possible that some files
were lost, destroyed or taken home by their authors. Yet hundreds
of boxes of these files (which are said to be owned by the Georgia
Amateur Athletics Foundation and which are now locked up at the
Atlanta History Center) contain folders with ordinary labels and
dates on them. Moreover, these folders are mentioned in detailed
inventories that were originally stored in Olympic computers.
</P>
<P>
   Box No. 1, for example, is said to contain 38 folders from
Payne's files dealing with the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation
and the Atlanta Organizing Committee in 1987 and 1988, when Atlanta
was actively bidding for the Games. The inventory of Box No. 1
covers more than one typed page. Inventories of similar boxes cover
hundreds more pages.
</P>
<P>
   Other easily accessible folders contain financial records and
correspondence on topics such as a ``budget summary'' for 1987-91;
a trip to Georgia's Callaway Gardens in 1988; a golf trip to
Augusta, Ga. in 1988 and ``gifts'' in 1989 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, years ago, when the Atlanta Historical Society
(organizational parent of the Atlanta History Center) offered to
store and catalog the whole growing mountain of Olympic records. On
June 17, 1991, the society's acting director, Katharine Farnham,
wrote to Payne's Olympic aide, Ginger Watkins, proposing to
finalize an agreement concerning the records. Farnham also offered
to ``restrict access'' to some of the files. ``Your staff,''
Farnham wrote to Watkins, ``should not feel obligated in any way to
straighten files or weed materials. We will provide this service.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a copy of a related document, Watkins scribbled the
following note to Payne about Farnham's letter:
</P>
<P>
   ``WPP (William Porter Payne) _You started this project. My
discussion with them is that they catalog it _ not release one
paper to the public or anything to the public until after your book
_ But it needs to be cataloged. They will sign confidentiality
agreement and/or will not send over sensitive materials. This is
general history _ rewrite it the way you want it. But someone has
to catalog all the AOC files.''
</P>
<P>
   Below that, Payne has evidently scribbled a response to Watkins:
</P>
<P>
   `` . . . No way _ you must be crazy or drunk. Total files must
be reviewed by us first.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne said Monday that he had ``no recollection'' of this memo.
Watkins did not return a request to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Olympians have been rather secretive about information
for a long time. Now it's time to make those secret records
generally accessible.
</P>
<P>
   I think it would also be prudent for someone to lock the records
up more securely _ so that even their supposed ``owners'' (the
Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation) and their lawyers stop
fiddling with them until the principle of public access is
established.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Campbell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: ccampbell(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
