<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-ONTIME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta makes on-timely jump to No. 3 in industry
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Call it a worst-to-third performance.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines jumped from last to third place in on-time
performance among the 10 major carriers in 1998, according to
figures from the U.S. Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta posted a 79.6 percent on-time rate, up from
74.1 percent in 1997. On-time flights are defined as those arriving
within 15 minutes of the scheduled time.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest and American airlines led the industry for the year.
Replacing Delta at the back of the pack was America West, tumbling
from sixth place a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Major airlines collectively posted a 77.2 percent on-time rate,
almost unchanged from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, airline passengers were angrier, the DOT figures
suggest. Consumer complaints to the agency about the major U.S.
carriers totaled 5,808, or 1.08 per 100,000 passengers, up from
4,550, or 0.86, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Delta had a complaint rate of 0.79, third-lowest for the second
year in a row. Southwest and Alaska airlines had the lowest rates,
while Northwest brought up the rear with a rate of 2.21.
</P>
<P>
   Delta improved one notch in mishandled baggage, placing fourth
with a rate of 4.27 mishandled bags per 1,000 passengers. In 1997,
it was fifth. America West had the best bag-handling performance,
while United was worst with a rate of 7.79.
</P>
<P>
   The industrywide rate of mishandled bags rose to 5.16 from 4.96.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's new management team promised better on-time performance
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Bill Berry said one key is a more intense focus on
getting early morning flights out on time, reducing the domino
effect when they run late.
</P>
<P>
   Berry also acknowledged Delta has added time to flight schedules
on some routes. The airline's executives defend the tactic by
saying it's better to extend the schedule than to publish arrival
times that aren't usually met.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT's consumer report is available on the Internet at
http://www.dot.gov/airconsumer/.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
