<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Class consciousness can cut across racial lines, author says
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does a people, stymied by prejudice, perpetuate that prejudice
within its own community? Yes, says Lawrence Otis Graham's new
book, ``Our Kind of People: Inside America's Black Upper Class,''
which traces the creation of a separate black elite to slavery
days, and discovers, unsurprisingly, that African-Americans can
still be just as class conscious as white people. U.S. News &AMP; World
Report ($2.95) excerpts the book, in which we meet black Americans
who celebrate such distinctions, and others who seem chagrined, or
at least ambivalent, by the infighting. An Atlanta surgeon claims
he prefers to be referred to as ``working class'' because he
doesn't want to draw the enmity of the larger black population.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Diary of a Fat Journalist: Greg Critser writes for Worth ($3)
about taking the new weight-loss drug Meridia, which lists ``taste
perversion'' among its several side effects. (That means a falafel
sandwich might start tasting like your thumb.) It is an honest,
funny, and unsettling look at an enthusiastic eater who risks high
blood pressure and other serious health problems to shed 45
recently gained pounds.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Deepak raps: Holistic healing guru Deepak Chopra talks to Vibe
($2.99) about his CD, ``A Gift of Love,'' which features
translations of writings by 13th century Persian poet Rumi, read by
such Deepak devotees as Madonna and Demi Moore. In the tradition of
other non-musical recording artists such as William Shatner and
Leonard Nimoy, Chopra also lets on that he's done a hip-hop album
for the Tommy Boy label, but isn't sure if he wants to release it
or not. Our suggestion: Don't.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Whitman sampled: The sick joke on the cover is a clue to the
New Yorker's ($3) unromantic view of Valentine's Day. Inside is an
affecting look at suicide notes by writer Alec Wilkinson, and a
short greeting card from Salman Rushdie. In ``My Unfunny
Valentine'' Rushdie reminisces about the February 20 years ago,
when his book ``The Satanic Verses'' was received poorly by the
Ayatollah Khomeini, who ordered Rushdie executed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The real Olympic scandal: The device used by drug testers at
the 1996 Atlanta Games could detect 100 types of steroids, but
there were apparently 101 ways to get around it, according to
Newsweek's ($3.50) cover story on sports and drugs. One American
coach, who says he developed drug regimens for athletes in Atlanta,
contends that creating a drug that will slip through the cracks is
as easy as changing one molecule.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the list: Ebony ($2.50) names the 100 most fascinating
black women of the 20th century, including former Spelman president
Johnnetta Betsch Cole, Coretta Scott King and her daughter the Rev.
Bernice King.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Checkers and cyberspace: All things Georgia are in a special
Georgia Living feature in Southern Living ($4.95). The 39-page
section includes visits with plum-voiced WABE announcer Lois
Reitzes and MindSpring's Charles Brewer, a look at the
heart-stopping action of a checkers tournament in Murrayville and a
chat with John Stephens of Theater Gael.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ballroom blitz: Sports Illustrated ($2.95) delivers the
post-mortem on the Falcons' Super Bowl loss to the Broncos, giving
credit to Denver's exotic repertoire of defensive plays, including
the Inverted Double-Double and the Two-Deep Squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
