<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daily blackouts cause down time
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The revisions looked right, the spelling had been
checked and double-checked, the whole thing was ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   Move the mouse to print, click once and it was finished. He was
doing just that when, without warning, it disappeared from his
screen. Gone in an instant. Vaporized.
</P>
<P>
   For an 11-year-old, Max Flick is articulate and composed, but
his mother will tell you he wasn't his calm self when the power
went off _ again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was near tears,'' Beth Flick of Sandy Springs (GA.) says.
</P>
<P>
   Grown men have been awash in them, and not because the Super
Bowl suddenly was something they were going to have to read about
the next day. In some parts of metro Atlanta, momentary power
interruption is a regular occurrence, so regular that many folks
have been keeping logs.
</P>
<P>
   In Debi Schneider's kitchen is a calendar crowded with the usual
reminders _ a Brownies field trip, an appointment with the dentist,
another with the vet, an appliance repairman coming by.
</P>
<P>
   But the most common notations are these:
</P>
<P>
   Jan 10. ``10:20 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 19. ``Sev x.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 22. ``Ga. Power (while out)''
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 27. ``1:13 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 31. ``12:19 blink.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And there were a lot I didn't even record,'' Schneider says.
``There were six in one day once.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many these days, Schneider works out of her home, spending
much of her time on a computer and on the Internet. She traces a
person's whereabouts _ an old high school boyfriend, a biological
parent, someone a client knew two marriages and three jobs back.
``One day,'' she says, ``I was on the Internet _ you know how you
have to go through a bunch of steps when you're not sure what
you're looking for _ and I thought I found something. I said, `Oh,
this is good. I've got a lead.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Zap! Off went the power, for just a second but enough to cancel
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know lightning will strike and a car's going to hit a pole
now and then _ I don't have a problem with that,'' Schneider says.
``I have a problem when it's an almost daily occurrence.''
</P>
<P>
   At Georgia Power's substation in Alpharetta (Ga.), engineer Doug
Bailey has been hearing from people who wonder why the power fails
so often when the skies couldn't be bluer and there's not a storm
within 300 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to realize that a problem for you is not necessarily
a problem for us,'' Bailey says, not quite meaning what his words
suggest.
</P>
<P>
   He means only that an interruption is one thing to Georgia Power
and another to customers. Even so, there are people who are
surprised _ to say the least _ by an explanation like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's outrageous,'' says Janice Levetan, a media specialist
at Spalding Drive Elementary School in Sandy Springs. ``I've talked
with Georgia Power and I don't think they understand how bad the
situation is. Last year we had multiple power failures almost every
single day.''
</P>
<P>
   But she especially remembers one day last month. It was Jan. 19,
a teacher workday. ``We had seven (interruptions) in a row. It kept
going off and on, off and on. Every time it happens we have to
physically remount the servers. The county sent electricians out
last year and they inspected this place with a fine-toothed comb.
The problem's not in the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rivers, a pharmacist at Wender &AMP; Roberts drugstore in the
North Springs Shopping Center, recalls a recent week when ``it went
off almost every day. When it goes down, we can't write
prescriptions. It takes our computer 10 or 15 minutes to reboot.
The insurance guy next door, his takes 45 minutes to reboot. He's
furious.''
</P>
<P>
   To Georgia Power's customers, it's cold comfort to hear that
it's proof that the system is working, the big circuit breakers
functioning according to design. A tree limb is blown onto a power
line and the breakers open. A squirrel ventures where it shouldn't
and again they open, bringing headache for humans and calamity for
a squirrel.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Georgia Power says almost a third _ 31 percent _ of all
interruptions cannot be attributed to weather, to squirrels, to
contractors cutting underground cable or to drivers hitting power
poles. But Bailey and John Gay, a senior engineer, suspect many
interruptions in the unknown category were caused by wind-blown
limbs that briefly touched a power line and then sprang back into
place.
</P>
<P>
   A public utility has easement rights that allow it to trim trees
whose limbs are too close to power lines. But there are a lot of
trees in Atlanta and only so many trimmers. Not only that, but
residents complain loudly. ``A lady told me once, `I don't mind the
blinks, just don't cut my trees,' '' Bailey says.
</P>
<P>
   And if her beautiful trees cause interruptions for others _
well, that's their problem. In the northern suburbs, it's become a
silent civil war. No one's crying ``Power to the People,'' but many
are beyond the tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they know what the problem is,'' Schneider says.
``When I called Georgia Power, a guy told me he might find the
cause tomorrow or he might find it five years from now. I don't
think he saw it as a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
