<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN09-COX     02-08 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PBS' `The Execution' has few signs of life
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Frontline'' correspondent Alan Austin spent three years
burrowing around the life of death row inmate Clifford Boggess.
Austin believed his digging would take him ``into the heart of the
death penalty in America.'' Austin wanted to learn everything he
could about Boggess and his crime, to finally see ``if it still
made sense to kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   But the result, tonight's well-done but nowhere-leading
90-minute PBS documentary ``The Execution'' (10 p.m. on WGTV ),
never takes us anywhere we haven't been before. The only epiphany
is that there is no epiphany. By the end, there's only the profound
sadness of the victims' survivors, a sadness that makes Austin's
existential musings _ ``Did it make sense to execute Clifford
Boggess? . . . Had the execution actually punished this killer?'' _
feel like a profoundly flimsy copout.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Boggess is executed in Texas by lethal injection,
Austin phones one victim's 97-year-old brother. Austin asks this
man, who'd earlier sobbed at the memory of finding his dead brother
with his chest caved in and his throat cut, what he thinks of
Boggess' execution. The brother is almost disbelieving. ``What do I
think about it?'' he says. ``I think it was OK, don't you? He was
entitled to what he got . . . (it was) too easy compared to what he
did to my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to locate the point of ``The Execution,'' other than
the evergreen fascination we have with staring into the face of
this sort of evil _ evil that can paint and play the piano and look
a lot like us.
</P>
<P>
   Austin first finds in Boggess that rare death row inmate willing
to admit his guilt. In 1986, Boggess needed some cash, so he walked
into a store in his hometown of St. Jo, Texas, with a knife he
meant to use, grabbed a few hundred dollars from the cash register,
and cut the throat of the old man he knew working there. He told
his girlfriend about the murder, and she recalls how it made
Boggess ``enjoy sex more. Talking about the sound of the blood; the
feeling of the warm blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Boggess liked it so much, he murdered another elderly shopkeeper
three weeks later. After bragging about it, he was arrested,
convicted and sent to death row.
</P>
<P>
   Austin meets Boggess there and finds him a willing specimen for
inspection. Boggess details the murders. (``I said, `This is it,
Frank.' As I grabbed him around the throat with my arm he said,
`Ooooo.' There was pain in the sound of it that only an old man can
make.'') Austin finds family members who speak of Boggess' abusive
mother, an adoptive mother who regrets her divorce, an uncle who
saw something ``crazy'' in Boggess' eyes early on.
</P>
<P>
   He also speaks to the victims' survivors, who talk of their
lives being shattered forever. When the granddaughter of one victim
writes Boggess and asks him to explain himself, Boggess details his
crime, then lectures her on the nature of forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in death row and he's preaching to me?'' she exclaims.
</P>
<P>
   Austin is always thorough, always thoughtful. But it's his
journalistic conceit here never to be visceral, and he winds up
seeming as detached from this story's real horror as Boggess was.
So he leaves us empty, let down and feeling a little used.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   `Sports Night's' mix
</P>
<P>
   For years, most network sitcoms have all seemed the same. ``The
Single Guy.'' ``Suddenly Susan.'' Anything with Tony Danza.
</P>
<P>
   They're all a bore. So it's nice when a show like ABC's ``Sports
Night'' comes along and does what it seems to frequently do so
well: mix comedy and drama at a breakneck pace.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's ``Sports Night'' (9:30) does move with feverish
adrenaline. It's a tale of love lost and love won as Dana and Casey
(Felicity Huffman, Peter Krause) continue their fumbling two-step
and Dan (Josh Charles), after crashing and burning 17 times, tries
once more to snag the pretty woman he's after.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be the subject of your mockery,'' Dan asserts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I think you shall,'' Casey counters.
</P>
<P>
   It's a well-written, well-acted show that possesses some of the
same endearing sensibilities as ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Longino, TV critic
</P>
<P>
   Overhype on `The '60s'
</P>
<P>
   Can anything be as overblown as NBC's two-part movie ``The
'60s''?
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe WXIA's three-part news series on ``The '60s.'' On
Saturday, Sunday and Monday, WXIA's news team aired shameless
stories, hyping their network's film.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBC's movie is a powerful look back on those days that
dramatically reshaped our country and our culture,'' anchor Brenda
Wood said in a three-minute story on ``The '60s'' during Sunday's
11 p.m. newscast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Powerful'' isn't the word many TV critics chose while
reviewing ``The '60s.'' The New York Times' Caryn James called it
at times ``conspicuously idiotic.'' Atlanta Journal-Constitution
critic Drew Jubera labeled it ``laughable.'' Metro Atlanta viewers
hardly flocked to the film. Sunday's Part 1 trailed Fox's ``The
X-Files'' in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Longino, TV critic
</P>
<P>
   Tripp talks
</P>
<P>
   It's the story that never ends. Linda Tripp will appear Friday
on ``Today'' and Monday on ``Larry King Live'' (9 p.m. on CNN) to
talk about (what else?) Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino and Drew Jubera write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
