</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-FUNERAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DEATH, KING BRINGS A DAY OF PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan -- As world leaders descended on this small desert
nation Monday to mourn King Hussein, the Middle East's most bitter
enemies suspended their differences for a day.
</P>
<P>
   In his death as in his life, the monarch brought hostile
countries like Israeli and Syria, the United States and Iraq,
together and reminded them of the need for a lasting peace in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein's funeral was a somber and extraordinary gathering of
nearly 50 heads of state and hundreds of dignitaries and
delegations from 75 nations who came to honor a man who ruled this
pivotal nation through a half century of turmoil, conflict and
tenuous peace before dying of cancer Sunday at the age of 63.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not since the death in 1965 of French President Charles
de Gaulle has a funeral bound together so many nations.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who bowed in prayer along with three former
American presidents, later commented on the unique, if emphemeral,
harmony of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a beautiful sight,'' he said. ``People coming
from all around the world -- countries that are at each other's
throats -- here meeting in peace and friendship and the sanctity of
the umbrella of this great man.''
</P>
<P>
   Male leaders and dignitaries were invited under that umbrella.
According to Islamic custom, only men attend funeral ceremonies.
While there were a few exceptions Monday, US Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright did not attend for this reason. Even some female
heads of state, such as Ireland's President Mary McAleese, mourned
with Queen Noor along with her female relatives, the wives of heads
of state and female dignitaries in a gathering in a separate room
in Raghdan palace.
</P>
<P>
   The day was drenched in ceremony and symbolism. Hussein's
casket, draped in the Jordanian flag, was carried on the flat bed
of a Range Rover that slowly wound its way through Amman from the
king's palace, Baab el Salaam, or ``Gate of Peace,'' named after
the historic peace agreement with Israel that may be the king's
most historic legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of Jordanians holding posters of the king
and black mourning flags flanked the route. Most wept and murmured
prayers as the cortege moved toward the Raghdan Palace, which is
used for official functions.
</P>
<P>
   Walid Abaddi, 15, held back tears and waved a black flag that he
had fashioned out of a curtain rod and one of his mother's scarves
as the cortege passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a father to us, and a teacher,'' said Abaddi. ``He made
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the cortege arrived at the Raghdan Palace, military pall
bearers carried the casket into a polished brown marble foyer where
it was placed on a platform facing Mecca in the Throne Room.
</P>
<P>
   Then the long line of mourners clad in costumes from around the
world filed past. There was the basic black suit of the West, long
Arab robes trimmed in gold, and military uniforms with black arm
bands. There also was a panoply of headdress: fez, turbin, beret,
red-and-white checked kaffiyeh, Jewish skull cap, the tall hat of
Eastern Orthodox Christian clerics, and the red felt cap of Islamic
scholars.
</P>
<P>
   From the palace, the casket was towed behind a cannon chariot
festooned in white flowers down a hillside to the royal cemetery,
led by the bagpipes and slow pounding drums of a military band.
Following along the cortege was a white Arabian horse named
``Amre,'' the king's favorite, and in the tradition of a fallen
leader, the king's riding boots faced backward in the stirrups. The
horse will never be ridden again.
</P>
<P>
   Under a green canvas tent, the casket, now draped in a simple
white shroud, was lowered into the ground. The sound of the slow,
mournful chanting of the Koran mingled with the roar of Jordanian
Royal Air Force fighters overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, enemies shared common ground. Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Syrian President Hafez al-Assad stood in the
same line, albeit 40 minutes apart. This marked the first time that
the leaders of the two opposing states had ever attended the same
public event.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation led by Iraqi Vice President Tahaa Marouf kept its
distance from Clinton and George Bush, the two American presidents
who have fought Iraqi aggression.
</P>
<P>
   The Crown Princes of Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, the oil-rich Arab
countries that had shunned Jordan for years because of its lack of
support in the 1991 Persian Gulf War were also there. Their warm
embrace of the new King Abdullah, Hussein's oldest son to whom the
crown of the Hashemite dynasty passed upon his father's death, was
a significant sign that the rift was healing.
</P>
<P>
   In a surreal moment, Netanyahu, flanked by body guards, milled
briefly in the same outdoor crowd that included Khaled Mashal, the
political leader of Hamas, the militant Islamic group. Netanyahu's
intelligence agency had ordered Mashal's assassination in the fall
of 1997. The operation was botched, causing a deep rift between
Netanyahu and Hussein. The incident came dangerously close to
unraveling the historic peace agreement the two nations signed in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all admired him deeply,'' said Netanyahu of Hussein,
despite the fact that Israel fought wars with Jordan in 1948 and
1967.
</P>
<P>
   Even Israel's vitriolic political debate was quieted, albeit
briefly, as Netanyahu, and Labor Party and Centrist Party rivals
arrived in three separate intervals to offer condolences. But the
bitter squabbling resumed by the time their helicopters had
traversed the short stretch of desert back into Israeli territory.
</P>
<P>
   Upon landing in Israel, Netanyahu lashed out at Israeli
President Ezer Weizman for shaking the hand of Nayef Hawatmeh, a
notorious underground leader of a Palestinian guerrilla faction. In
1974 Hawatmeh's men commandeered a school in the Israeli village of
Maalot. The hostage operation left 24 Israelis dead and shaped the
attitudes of a generation about the Palestinian leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Libya's Moammar Gadhafi, accused of plotting a failed
assassination attempt in 1983 of King Hussein, sent his son Saadi,
who had to fly from Tunisia because U.N. sanctions bar flights from
Libya. The new Jordanian king Abdullah is said to have met with
Saadi recently -- yet another sign that new generations in the
Mideast can move beyond the past.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral had the feel of a watershed, the beginning of an end
of an era in the Middle East. The region's ailing and aging leaders
will soon quite the scene, leaving the future open. Syria's Assad,
who is reportedly ailing, was feeling faint, according to a palace
source, and his 68 years were showing. The hands and lips of
69-year-old Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat trembled as he saluted
and then bowed to King Hussein's casket. Arafat is believed to be
suffering from Parkinson's disease. Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak looked fit at 71, but the lines of age on his face have
deepened.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the polite diplomacy of the gathering, there were
some problems with etiquette in the funeral's reception line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of pushing,'' according to one palace
official. ``It's very hard to get that many people together and
have everyone behave, especially when there are no women there to
remind them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
