u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DAYTONA-NOTES-COX     02-08 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DAYTONA-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daytona notebook: Chevy waits for NASCAR to approve new Monte
Carlo
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Chevrolet hoped to introduce its Monte
Carlo Winston Cup car at the Coca-Cola 600 in Charlotte May 30.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it appears that NASCAR fans and Chevy teams might have to
wait until next season to see the car in competition.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup director Gary Nelson, who oversees the garage area,
said Monday the car still hasn't been approved by NASCAR and that
Chevy's goal of getting the Monte Carlo on the tracks by May might
be unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's process to approve a car . . . requires much more
data, plus a crystal ball that tells you if we approve a car on a
(particular) date, by the time it hits the racetrack, how much
better is it going to be after they've built the thing?'' Nelson
said. ``We have to look at that steep learning curve that's going
to take place.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials are trying to avoid a situation similar to last
year, when Ford replaced the Thunderbird with its Taurus. After
placing five cars in the top 10 at the season-opening Daytona 500 a
year ago, Ford followed with six top-10 finishers at Rockingham the
following week.
</P>
<P>
   After Ford dominated the Las Vegas 400 on March 1, placing nine
cars among the top 10, NASCAR officals cut back the Taurus' spoiler
about 1 inch and raised the car's front-valence heighth to equalize
the car's downforce with the Chevys and Pontiacs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were cutting their spoilers because they were
aerodynamically better,'' Nelson said. ``We're trying to avoid
that. The more data we can collect, the better decision we can
make. . . . We want a car that fits what's on the race track now.
We just have to get to a point where we have enough information to
say it's going to run side by side when it debuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Chevrolet teams, including two-time defending Cup champion
Jeff Gordon and the No. 24 car, have said they'd be apprehensive
about changing cars in midseason, especially if they're involved in
another points race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even seen the thing, let alone sat in one,'' Gordon
said earlier this year. ``We're excited about the car coming out,
but it definitely is a concern for it to be coming out when it is.
I think we'd rather have been working on it over the offseason and
bring it out at the first of the year, but at the same time, we're
pretty comfortable with our current Monte Carlo.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrick Motorsports, which owns Gordon's team and two other
teams, is developing the superspeedway version of the Monte Carlo,
which will run at Daytona and Talladega. Richard Childress Racing,
which owns Dale Earnhardt's team, is preparing the ``downforce''
model, which will run at the remaining Cup tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The car reportedly has been tested at Talladega Superspeedway
and Miami-Dade Motorsports Complex and also has made several trips
to the wind tunnel for anerodynamics tests.
</P>
<P>
   Provisional qualifier changes
</P>
<P>
   After veteran driver Darrell Waltrip used 20 provisionals to
enter races he did not qualify for last season, NASCAR changed its
provisional rules. In 1999, a past-champion provisional will count
toward the season maximum of eight provisionals per car owner.
</P>
<P>
   A past-champion provisional, which is the last position to start
in the 43-car field, is available to the most recent Winston Cup
champion who was unable to make the field on time, provided that
his owner hasn't used the maximum number of provisionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it has become a real source of aggravation to me,''
Waltrip said. ``Quite frankly, I don't know why they don't just
start the 43 fastest cars and be done with it. But if you did that,
then there are people, and my self included, who would miss the
race. It would be people who run all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you'd have people showing up occasionally, who only run
every now and then, who knock out people who run every week. I
think there has to be some loyalty by NASCAR to the people who run
every week, and there certainly has to be some loyalty by NASCAR
champions who are still out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rules changes?
</P>
<P>
   Nelson says NASCAR is close to a decision whether to implement
new air-dam and spoiler-size rules beginning with the North
Carolina 400 on Feb. 21 at Rockingham.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, which would give all three car makes -- Chevy, Ford
and Pontiac -- the same air-dam clearance and change the spoiler
size in non-restrictor-plate races, were first used in the Nov. 8
race at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nelson, NASCAR got positive reactions from most
teams. Teams were told by NASCAR to use both sets of rules during
testing at Rockingham last week. Nelson said NASCAR would evaluate
the teams' test results in making its final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Second-round qualifying
</P>
<P>
   Only eight teams participated in Monday's second-round
qualifying, meaning that the remaining qualifying field, except
front-row sitters Gordon and rookie Tony Stewart, will stand on
Saturday's times.
</P>
<P>
   Derrike Cope, who leased an engine from owner Felix Sabates for
his No. 30 Pontiac, had the biggest improvement, covering the lap
nearly four-tenths of a second faster. Dave Marcis and the No. 71
Chevy, running with Mike Skinner's qualifying engine, improved by
more than two-tenths.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The engine) definitely picked us up,'' Cope said. ``That's
four-tenths better on what's a worse day, I think. We're 30th or so
in the overall speed category, which is not great. We'll do the
best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Dick Trickle, who didn't run in first-round qualifying
because of mechanical problems, covered the track in 47.075
seconds, an average speed of 191.184. That would have placed him
34th on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we had a little too much bottoming out, trying that
last-minute effort,'' Trickle said. ``We didn't get to qualfy on
the first day, so we just had to get a lap in so we could get the
car ready to go racing now. Our speed isn't good at all, so we're
just going to have to get our way into the race through the
(qualifiers on Thursday).''
</P>
<P>
   Ain't life grand
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR president Bill France Jr. says NASCAR officals were
contacted by Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas about serving as
grand mashal of Sunday's Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   France Jr. says that NASCAR and Thomas share the same law firm
in Washington, D.C., and that stock-car racing wasn't using Thomas'
appearance solely as an opportunity to attract African-American
fans to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I understand, he's a big NASCAR fan,'' France Jr.
said. ``Anytime, you've got a Supreme Court justice who's
interested in doing something like this, of course you're going to
be interested.''
</P>
<P>
   MoonPies for rookies
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga Bakery, which produces MoonPie marshmallow
sandwiches, announced Monday that it's introducing a ``MoonPie
Rookie Dash for Cash,'' which will award both rookie drivers and
consumers for every Winston Cup, Busch and Craftsman Truck race won
by a rookie driver.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR fans will enter the contest by mailing in an entry form
found on MoonPie cartons. Every time a rookie wins, a random
drawing will held.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
