<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-SPEECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE PRESENTS HERSELF AS UNIFYING FORCE IN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Elizabeth Dole, inching toward a presidential
run, Monday night described herself as a refreshingly different
Washington leader: one who could restore confidence and integrity
in the White House, return civility to national politics, and build
consensus where there is now ``a cacophony of conflicting voices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent most of my life trying to bring people together,''
Dole told a sellout audience of 1,200 at the annual dinner of the
Greater Manchester Chamber of Commerce. ``I have never confused
civility with weakness, nor do I mistake the pursuit of consensus
for surrender. Quite simply, I would rather bridge differences than
exploit them.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech was Dole's first since she left her post as head of
the American Red Cross Jan. 4 to ``seriously consider'' running for
the Republican presidential nomination, and it was billed by aides
in this first-in-the-nation primary state as a major, political
overture to a possible campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it not only touched on issues Dole would be likely to
stress in a campaign _ improving public schools, strengthening the
national defense, reducing illicit-drug use, and lowering taxes _
but it also articulated the theme that she has the common sense and
moral character to bring Washington to its senses and restore trust
in government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one overriding theme to my 30-plus years in public
life, it lies in placing service over politics, to try consensus
before confrontation, and to count on the deep desire of my fellow
countrymen to do what is right,'' Dole said. ``In what is sometimes
a cacophony of conflicting voices, I have tried to raise mine in a
call to our better nature, always sure that America would
respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, 62, is a two-time Cabinet secretary and married to former
Senator Bob Dole, the GOP's 1996 presidential candidate. She told
reporters Monday night she is still ``talking and listening'' to
supporters to determine if she will form a presidential exploratory
committee. So far, she said, the response has been ``very
encouraging. A number of people have called to volunteer,'' Dole
said, ``and money is coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, not since former New York Representative Geraldine
Ferraro was tapped for the second spot on the Democratic ticket in
1984 has a woman with high political ambitions generated as much
interest in the country and excitement in the GOP. Polls among
Republicans show she already has bolted to the top tier of
Republican presidential hopefuls, and a survey last week by the Los
Angeles Times has both Dole and Texas Governor George W. Bush
beating Vice President Al Gore in head-to-head races.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Dole, noting she is methodical and controlled, say they
do not expect her to announce intentions until next week at the
earliest, after Dole assesses the political and financial support
in New Hampshire. Tuesday Dole will meet with nearly 100 backers at
a breakfast in Bedford before returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't want to run just to go through the motions,'' a
senior Dole adviser said Monday. ``She has done that too many times
already,'' referring to former senator Dole's unsuccessful national
campaigns in 1996 and 1988. ``She wants to know that she can win.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Dole has opened an office in the Watergate complex,
where she and her husband live, and she has hired both New
York-based political consultant Kieran Mahoney and pollster Linda
DiVall to run a campaign. Later this week, Dole visits Texas,
Bush's home territory. Over the weekend, she will be in Colorado
and then travels to Iowa, where the first GOP caucuses will be held
next year. Aides could not immediately explain Dole's remarks about
raising money; candidates are not allowed to do that before an
exploratory committee has been set up.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who has never held elective office but has served as both
Labor and Transportation secretary, has long, strong ties to the
Republican establishment. As a born-again Christian, she is also
popular among social conservatives. Her message Monday night was
that she could bridge the differences that frequently divide the
GOP while sidestepping the hot-button issues such as abortion,
affirmative action and school vouchers _ she did not mention any of
them _ that polarize the electorate and have hurt the party in
general elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Americans prefer solutions to soundbites,'' Dole said.
``This makes us naturally suspicious of what I call either/or
politics. Liberal versus conservative. Public schools versus
private school. Us versus them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole came into the state with local polls showing her name
recognition at more than 90 percent, her favorability rating at
more than 70 percent, and her ``negatives'' at 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Dole is a phenomenon,'' said Toni Pappas, a GOP activist
in Manchester who heads a committee in New Hampshire to draft Dole.
``I have not spoken to a single person who isn't interested and
doesn't want her to run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
