<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6781 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE-NYT &LR;      02-08 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSURE RESOLUTION GAINS SUPPORT BUT STILL FACES SERIOUS OBSTACLES
</HEADLINE>
   (See related stories: IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-PERJURY,
IMPEACH-DEBATE, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CLINTON) 
(sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Support among senators for a bipartisan rebuke of
President Clinton increased on Monday, but in a uniquely Senate
twist, the chances the measure will pass this week, or ever, dimmed
because of procedural roadblocks thrown up by opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's two main sponsors, Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
and Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, worked furiously by phone and in
corridors and private Senate dining rooms to buttonhole their
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Both senators said interest in a sharply worded rebuke was
growing as it became clear the Senate may not only acquit Clinton,
but could fail to get even a simple majority for either of the two
impeachment articles. It would take two-thirds of the Senate, or 67
votes, to remove the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people are telling me they are now open to it, and they
were previously closed to it,'' Bennett said. ``It's a very fluid
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans, many of whom voice concern that Clinton will
gloat if he is acquitted without a reprimand, will debate the
censure resolution at a caucus meeting on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Censure supporters not only are trying to build bipartisan
support but are doing so under a Friday deadline. After voting on
the impeachment articles, the Senate is scheduled to go into a
one-week recess, and opponents and supporters alike say that
momentum for a rebuke will diminish greatly after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a White House with a much different
attitude about censure if the president is in fact acquitted on
both articles,'' said Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, who rejects
censure. ``Within a week, they'll have a majority on their side who
would be opposed to censure.''
</P>
<P>
   Censure supporters say they can count on about 40 of the 45
Democrats. The resolution requires a simple majority, 51 votes. But
under Senate rules, it would take 60 votes to break a filibuster
that Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, is vowing to wage. That means that
at least 20 of the 55 Republicans would have to back the measure to
bring it to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Such tactics are a staple of the Senate's legislative diet. But
the filibuster threat is even more potent now with the Senate
recess looming, and senators eager to move on to regular
legislative business when they return.
</P>
<P>
   To circumvent Gramm's filibuster and sustain support for censure
through the break, Sen. Tom Daschle, the Democratic leader, on
Monday set in motion a chain of procedural votes, which if approved
after senators dispense with the impeachment articles, would allow
them to go directly to the censure resolution itself.
</P>
<P>
   But for this parliamentary manuever to get off the ground, 67
senators would have to agree to suspend the rules of the Senate.,
which normally requires consent from all 100 senators to proceed to
a specific bill. Debate on the actual resolution could start as
early as this week, but because of the filibuster, might have to be
put until after the recess.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the procedural votes would become test votes on
support for censure, especially among Republicans. Proponents
conceded on Monday that the tactic was a long-shot. But if
successful, it could pave the way for senators to approve a censure
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're simply doing now is trying to make an historic
statement of record about our views of the president's actions,''
Daschle told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., who is working closely
with Feinstein, said the fate of censure this week rests largely
with Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Trent Lott wants to do it, we'll do it, Moynihan said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott and his aides have said repeatedly that it is
``premature and inappropriate'' to discuss censure before senators
vote on the impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   Off the Senate floor, however, many Republicans were mulling
over censure. ``It's something that people would be well served to
keep among their options,'' said Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Many others, including Sens. Susan Collins and Olympia J. Snowe
of Maine, Connie Mack of Florida, and Ben Nighthorse Campbell of
Colorado, said in interviews they were still open to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm and his allies, including Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma,
the majority whip, were also out in force to defeat what they said
was an unconstitutional motion that would give Democrats political
cover for their likely acquittal votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sets a constitutional precedent that when we disagree
with a President Truman in the future who fires MacArthur, we
censure him,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over censure, while fierce, was not all-out war.
Hardly anything ever is in the Senate, where, unlike the House,
collegiality keeps the place running.
</P>
<P>
   In the subway tunnel between the Capitol and the Senate office
buildings on Monday morning, Feinstein spotted Gramm. The two sat
next to each other on a Sunday talk show, and exchanged acid
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Any ill will seemed forgotten, or at least forgiven, when
Feinstein called out to her antagonist with a smile, ``Hey, tough
guy!'' Gramm grinned and blew her kisses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
