<HEADER>
A6784 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-READING-NYT &LR;      02-08 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-READING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY LOOKS AT BEST WAYS TO READ TO CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By ERICA GOODE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A mother pulls her 4-year-old daughter onto her lap, opens the
book ``Madeline'' and begins to read. ``Do you see the 12 little
girls in a line?'' she asks, pointing at the picture.
</P>
<P>
   At preschool, the teacher takes a different approach: She reads
the book all the way through, then asks the children, ``Did the
little girls like Miss Clavel?''
</P>
<P>
   Which style of interactive reading is most likely to increase a
child's vocabulary skills? According to a study by New Zealand
researchers, it depends on the child.
</P>
<P>
   Children whose vocabulary skills are already fairly advanced
seem to benefit most from a more demanding ``performance-oriented''
interactive style, said Dr. Elaine Reese of the University of Otago
in Dunedin, a co-author of the study. In this format, Dr. Reese
said, the adult introduces the book _ explaining what it is about
and asking the child to predict what will happen in it _ then reads
through the pages, and afterward poses a series of questions that
explore the book and relate to the child's own life.
</P>
<P>
   Less advanced children, on the other hand, seem to profit more
from a less demanding ``describer'' style of reading, Dr. Reese
said, in which the adult interrupts the narrative frequently,
pointing to and labeling pictures and commenting on the story.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-eight New Zealand 4-year-olds, recruited from state-run
preschools, participated in the study, which was published in a
recent issue of the journal Developmental Psychology. Adults read
the boys and girls 32 books over a six-week period using one of
three different reading styles. Researchers tested the children's
vocabulary skills at the beginning and the end of the study.
</P>
<P>
   Children who entered the study with higher initial scores on the
vocabulary test showed greater gains when adult readers used the
performance-oriented interactive style. Those with lower initial
vocabulary scores gained most from the describer style of
interaction.
</P>
<P>
   A third reading style, called ``comprehender'' by the
researchers, in which the adult interrupted the reading to ask the
child higher-level questions, was not as beneficial as the other
two styles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH09-COX     02-08 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Impeachment trial winds down as Lott opts against open
deliberations
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A yawning, fidgeting Senate heard the last words
from both sides in President Clinton's impeachment trial Monday at
the beginning of the final week of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   With senators all but certain to keep Clinton in office, the 13
House prosecutors delivered one last appeal to oust the president
for lying under oath and obstructing justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Infidelity is private and non criminal. Perjury and
obstruction are public and criminal,'' said Rep. Henry Hyde
(R-Ill.), the lead prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Sensenbrenner (R-Wis.), another prosecutor, offered a
plea that seemed intended as much for the viewing public as the
Senate. ``The rule of law should apply to everyone. Senators, don't
be fooled by the president's excuses and spin control.''
</P>
<P>
   But White House counsel Charles Ruff was equally emphatic in
denying that Clinton's conduct merits his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating the defense team mantra that the prosecutors want to
win too much, Ruff said their vision is ``more focused on
retribution, more designed to achieve partisan ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Paraphrasing baseball great Yogi Berra, Ruff alluded to the
repetitive nature of Monday's closing arguments, which saw senators
in both parties unable to stifle yawns after a lengthy Saturday
session and four weeks of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's deja vu all over again and all over again and all over
again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trial resumes at 1 p.m. today with an expected vote on
whether to conduct the Senate's final deliberations in public.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) dealt a setback to
proponents of open deliberations when he came out Monday for
closed-door sessions.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Republican senators also worked Monday with
Democrats to draft a censure resolution that would be acceptable to
a couple of dozen GOP senators. Lott has not made known his
position on censure.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors and some GOP senators, hoping to keep pressure
on their colleagues, want to squelch talk of censure, at least for
the time being. Their fear is that giving senators the middle
ground of censure as an option would reduce the number of votes to
convict Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really cleanse the office as provided in the
Constitution or do you use the Air Wick of a censure resolution?''
Hyde said at the end of a long afternoon of lawyerly rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also asked for a delay in the trial to present evidence
that White House aide Sidney Blumenthal ``testified falsely''
before the Senate when he denied telling reporters that Lewinsky
was a ``stalker'' who had set up the president.
</P>
<P>
   Affidavits from journalist Christopher Hitchens and his wife,
Carole Blue, allege that Blumenthal referred to Lewinsky as a
stalker during a March 1998 lunch. Blumenthal has denied the
contention.
</P>
<P>
   Senators from both parties said they oppose delaying the trial.
Several suggested that the affidavits be turned over to the Justice
Department or independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Lott tried to insert the affidavits into the Senate record
Monday, but Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle (D-S.D.) objected.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the last week, the House prosecutors have been
relentless in their argument that the president is not fit to be
president _ well after it became clear that they would not win the
67 votes required forcibly remove him.
</P>
<P>
   And their finale was no different.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's second impeachment trial, the prosecutors argued,
is not about the president's adulterous affair with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky. The trial is about what the president
did to conceal that affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obstruction of justice and perjury must not be allowed to
stand,'' said Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) ``Perjury and obstruction
cannot stand alongside the laws and the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr struck a theme that was repeated again and again in the
prosecutors' three-hour presentation, urging senators to ignore
polls and public relations and instead act according to their
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Looking sternly at the senators, Barr asked if the principles
embodied in the Constitution would be affirmed or whether they
would left in the ``pallid hands of pollsters and pundits and the
swarm of theorists surrounding these proceedings?''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde spoke of death threats, hate mail and ``insults shouted in
public,'' as he quoted from Saul Bellow, Gibbon and Shakespeare to
portray the prosecution team as a ``band of brothers,'' in the
words of Henry V.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but ``tumult'' has followed since the House voted to
impeach the president on Dec. 19, Rep. George Gekas (R-Pa.) said.
</P>
<P>
   But he suggested that senators try to shut out the noise and
focus on one question: Did the president utter falsehoods under
oath? If so, he said, he must be removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To violate the oath as a witness in a civil case or a criminal
case . . . smashes against the integrity of our system of
government,'' Gekas said .
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Chabot (R-Ohio) made an effort to undermine the
Clinton team's contention that the president is contrite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know the president's behavior has been reprehensible,''
Chabot said. ``President Clinton, however, refuses to admit what
all of us know is true. To this day, he continues to deny and
distort. He continues to dispute the undeniable facts that are
before the Senate and before the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came time for the White House closing argument, Ruff sat
in his wheelchair in the well of the Senate and spoke for 1 and 3/4
hours in an unstinting critique of the prosecutors' case.
</P>
<P>
   The White House defense has all along not conceded one point of
the House case against Clinton, and Ruff was no different on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   About as much as Ruff would acknowledge is that Clinton behaved
poorly in conducting his affair with Lewinsky and then trying to
conceal it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has asked for forgiveness from his family and the American
public,'' Ruff said. ``And he has asked for the opportunity to earn
back their trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff asked senators if leaving Clinton in office ``would put at
risk the liberties of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can honestly say it would not,'' he continued, ``then
you must vote to acquit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff took frequent, pointed jabs at the prosecutors, saying the
allegations are ``moving targets'' and ``empty pots.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that he previously called the charges against the
president ``empty vessels,'' Ruff said, ``That's much too
flattering. It might even suggest they have the capacity to float,
which they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman and Rebecca Carr write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
