<HEADER>
A6794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      02-08 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES MAKE ORDERLY RETREAT IN LIGHTEST TRADING OF 1999 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices were mixed Monday as bellwether
technology issues rebounded after falling last week, but blue-chip
securities and shares in small companies, including Internet
stocks, slid.
</P>
<P>
   Traders and analysts said the market's performance was
impressive in light of the sharp run-up in prices since October and
several new pressures that could lead to a sharp selloff.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty orderly way to digest a good run,'' said
Michael Clark, head of U.S. stock trading at Credit Suisse First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe that while inflows are fairly strong, a bit
more attention is being paid to valuation, so people are starting
to take some profits,'' he said. ``I think this is a healthy way to
slowly let a little of the air out of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, a big drop in United
Technologies helped to push the Dow Jones industrial average down
13.13 points, or a tenth of a percent, to 9,291.11. But the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, led by rebounds in the
technology giants Microsoft and Intel, gained 4.37, or nearly
four-tenths of a percent, to 1,243.77.
</P>
<P>
   Led by technology companies, the Nasdaq composite index rose
31.30, or 1.3 percent, to 2,404.92. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 1.39, or 0.3 percent, to 411.33. And
Thestreet.com's index of 20 Internet companies slumped 26.67, or
5.2 percent, to 504.85.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the Big Board was 705.4 million shares, the slowest
day so far this year. On the Nasdaq, just fewer than 883 million
shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and others suggested that the threat of higher interest
rates and a spate of new and secondary stock offerings would most
likely constrain market indexes for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``New supply will hold the market back,'' said Michael Molnar, a
managing director in retail sales and trading at Salomon Smith
Barney.
</P>
<P>
   ``But interest rates are clearly the biggest deterrent'' to
higher prices, he said. ``If the Fed were to pop the liquidity
bubble by either tightening monetary policy or changing their bias
toward tightening, that could do it. No one has questioned the
interest rate environment for months.''
</P>
<P>
   Among individual stocks, Microsoft was the biggest gainer in the
S&AMP;P 500, rising 5 1/4, to 165 1/4, after it said it would develop
wireless Internet services with British Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which was hammered last week, rebounded Monday, rising 4
7/16, to 132. United Technologies was the biggest loser of the Dow
stocks, falling 5, to 120.
</P>
<P>
   But big bank stocks also sustained losses. J.P. Morgan, a Dow
stock, fell 2 7/8, to 99 1/4. And Chase Manhattan dropped 3 5/16,
to 73 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Internet-related companies and online brokerage firms
also fell. America Online dropped 5, to 159. Yahoo lost 14 1/8, to
158 5/8. And Amazon.com declined 6 3/4, to 109 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritrade Holding fell 15 1/2, to 80, after its Internet and
touch-tone trading services crashed for nearly half an hour Monday
morning. J.B. Oxford Holdings, another online broker, fell 3 9/16,
to 8 3/16. And Siebert Financial fell 7 5/8, to 27 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Executive Risk, a specialty insurer, rose 21 1/8, to
65 1/8, after Chubb announced that it would buy the company for
$71.71 a share. Chubb, the nation's 14-largest property and
casualty insurer, fell 2 5/8, to 55 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   AMR, the parent of American Airlines, fell 2 15/16, to 57. The
airline was forced to cancel 22 percent of its flights Monday after
pilots failed to show up for work in a dispute over AMR's purchase
of Reno Air.
</P>
<P>
   And Boeing fell 11/16, to 36 3/8, after it was reported that
China had ordered a freeze on new aircraft purchases and postponed
aircraft deliveries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
