u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALAYSIA-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      02-08 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUSTED MALAYSIAN TALKS DARKLY OF POLITICAL FOES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Five months after he was ousted and
jailed on corruption and sex-related charges, Malaysia's former
deputy prime minister, Anwar Ibrahim, finally took the stand in his
defense Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by his lead lawyer, Anwar depicted himself as
the victim of a political conspiracy sanctioned by his former
mentor, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have political foes who would stop at nothing to
achieve their agenda,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government has accused Anwar of quashing a police
investigation of charges that he had illicit sexual relations with
women and men. But Anwar testified that he encouraged the police to
look into the allegations, even though they were made in letters
that he said were written by his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have done that if I had the slightest worry or
suspicion as regards the truth of the allegations,'' Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
   In a trial that has mesmerized this Southeast Asian nation and
become a referendum on its government, the central player emerged
as a relaxed witness, smiling easily and sprinkling his comments
with sardonic observations about the police, high society figures
and even his own plight. When the judge asked Anwar, 51, to run
through his resume, he listed a series of increasingly powerful
government posts that culminated in the No. 2 job under Mahathir.
Then Anwar switched from Malay to English to add a wry coda, ``Now
jobless.''
</P>
<P>
   The comment drew laughs from the gallery, which included foreign
journalists, diplomats and members of human-rights organizations.
If Anwar seemed to be playing to the gallery, political analysts
here said that reflected how this trial had become as much a
political battle as a criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir dismissed Anwar in September after the two feuded
bitterly over Malaysia's economic policy. After removing his
protege, Mahathir imposed strict controls on Malaysia's currency
and foreign investment, which effectively cut the country off from
the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's ouster galvanized people, who took to the streets
calling for Mahathir to resign. Vice President Al Gore drew world
attention to the unrest in a speech at an economic summit meeting
here in November, when he praised the protesters and chided
Malaysia for suppressing political freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The political nature of the trial was underscored Monday when
Malaysia's attorney general turned up unexpectedly to lead the
prosecution team. The attorney general, Mohtar Abdullah, had not
appeared during the prosecution phase of trial because he was named
by the defense as a potential witness. But after Anwar's lawyers
did not call him, he promptly took charge.
</P>
<P>
   Mohtar wasted no time in scoring a political point against
Anwar. When Anwar began answering questions in English, he said,
``May I just note that the champion of Bahasa is electing to speak
in English.'' Bahasa Malaysia is the formal name of the Malay
language.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar came to prominence as a Muslim student leader who pressed
for his country to cast off its British colonial roots, in part by
using its native language. But most of Anwar's lawyers were trained
in Britain and they are more comfortable speaking English. Despite
desultory efforts to conduct the trial in Malay, the judge and the
defense lawyers typically lapse into English.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, Anwar was on the offensive. As head
of a Cabinet committee on government management, he testified, he
heard lots of incriminating details about high-level officials. He
implied that those officials would have ample reason to engineer
his ouster.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar also set out to rebut accusations that he interfered in an
investigation of his alleged sexual affairs. The prosecution
asserted that he had misused his power to force his former driver,
Azizan Abu Bakar, to retract an affidavit stating he had been
sodomized by his boss. But Anwar said Azizan recanted on his own,
and later begged for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Augustine Paul, dealt Anwar a setback two weeks ago
when he approved a motion to amend the corruption charges so that
the government does not have to prove Anwar had illicit sex. That
means Anwar's lawyers cannot contest the sexual evidence already
laid out. As a result, they say, they cannot clear their client's
reputation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
