<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOY-MERGERS-ART-2TAKE     02-08 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOY-MERGERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTEAD OF MAKING THEIR OWN, TOY MAKERS NOW PREFER TO BUY RIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on recent acquisitions by Hasbro and Mattel is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a hot toy hits the market, frantic parents rush to buy one
while it is still on the shelf. Toy makers, it seems, are adopting
a similar shopping strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Ever on the lookout for top-selling toys to add to their mix,
industry giants like Mattel and Hasbro are increasingly looking not
to their own workshops but to their smaller rivals. If they did not
come up with the latest plaything to catch the eye of those fickle
4-year-olds, they simply buy the company that did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our industry thrives on new products, and where that comes
from is not necessarily always going to be from the big
companies,'' said David Miller, president of the Toy Manufacturers
of America, the trade group, which this week is putting on the 96th
annual American International Toy Fair in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Mattel, maker of Barbie and Hot Wheels, will soon
be the biggest producer of consumer software behind Microsoft, but
it is paying $3.8 billion do so by acquiring the Learning Co. And
Hasbro, known for G.I. Joe dolls and Tonka trucks won the latest
toy war with Furby, but only after it bought Furby's maker, Tiger
Electronics, last year for $335 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is something out there that we think can add to our
brand portfolio,'' said Wayne Charness, a spokesman for Hasbro,
``we do everything we can to go get it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fiercely competitive and cyclical toy business,
manufacturers and retailers have long struggled with how to achieve
the consistent revenues and earnings growth that investors demand.
By buying rivals, they hope to minimize the risk of wild earnings
swings from new toys that fizzle fast or classics that lose their
luster. And snapping up a competitor's expertise or best-selling
brands enables manufacturers to respond more rapidly to
ever-evolving consumer demands.
</P>
<P>
   That is just what has happened with electronic games and
multimedia software, which have become increasingly important to
the industry. While the overall industry had flat results last
year, with $15.2 billion in wholesale shipments to retailers, a $41
million decline, the total market for video game software grew a
third, to $2.8 billion, while the market for electronic games grew
20 percent, to $456 million, according to the toy industry group.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to achieve such gains with a wider array of educational
and interactive toys, Hasbro and Mattel have been trolling for
companies that would give them more of an edge. Last year, Hasbro
bought Microprose Inc., Tiger Electronics and the Atari video game
division of the JTS Corp. Mattel, not to be outdone, followed with
the largest deal in the industry in recent years by announcing that
it would acquire the Learning Co. The deal is expected to close by
the end of April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mattel recognizes enormous opportunity in Learning Company's
relationships with schools and hot specialty stores like Zany
Brainy,'' said Eric Johnson, a professor at Vanderbilt University's
Owen Graduate School of Management. Zany Brainy is a fast-growing
specialty retailer that sells multimedia educational products.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to gaining even greater visibility at such specialty
toy sellers, ``Mattel can now leverage its distribution and brands
to grow the Learning Company's products, while integrating
education and multimedia into its own line of toys and games,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are likely to benefit, too. For one thing, toys that
once required jaunts to specialty stores will now be more widely
available at places like Kmart and Toys ``R'' Us. And economies of
scale usually generated from these transactions often produce cost
savings for the manufacturers that, in theory, could mean cheaper
prices at the check out lane.
</P>
<P>
   Money managers and analysts said they expected the consolidation
to continue as toy makers look to diversify not just through
international expansion and internal creativity but also through
shopping sprees that combine the creative talents of smaller, niche
operators with the huge distribution and other resources of the
industry giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically this has been a very fragmented industry,'' said
Timothy Ghriskey, a senior portfolio manager at the Dreyfus Corp.,
which owned 190,000 shares of Mattel last year but has since sold
its stake. ``There is ease of entry, and it is driven by the
creative types. Along with all of corporate America, the toy
industry is beginning to benefit from consolidation and the
benefits of size, especially with the retail channel consolidating
into a couple of very strong hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, without the marketing resources and the influence to
secure coveted shelf space at Wal-Mart and Toys ``R'' Us, one-hit
wonders risk being shut out of the game no matter how hot their
products may be. And for larger manufacturers, paying for new
talent is often more cost-effective than waiting for the next
Cabbage Patch doll to come from within.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for the acquired company because they often get a
good price and they lower the risk of having a one-shot item,''
Ghriskey said. ``And it's good for the acquirer because they can
fold it right into their existing structure, with few if any
additional costs other than the purchase price.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the thinking behind a string of mergers the last two
years. Besides the Learning Company and Tiger Electronics, other
transactions include Radica Games Ltd.'s acquisition last year of
Kid Active and the merger in 1997 of Leapfrog and Knowledge Kids
Enterprises, a unit of Knowledge Universe LLC..
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition by Radica gave the manufacturer of hand-held
casino theme games the Girl Tech line of electronic products for
girls. Radica also got Kid Active's Girl Tech Web site, which
broadened the company's marketing capabilities because it can now
promote directly to youngsters who visit the site. And the Leapfrog
transaction combined Knowledge Kids' financial resources with
Leapfrog's award-winning educational products, like Word Wizard, an
interactive system that teaches word recognition and reading
comprehension.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are still plenty of independent niche
companies left, like Ty Inc., maker of the wildly popular Beanie
Babies. But for many others, giving up some autonomy is a small
price for the potential these deals provide to make the most of
their products.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Roger Shiffman, Tiger's president, said that had it not
been for the sale of his company to Hasbro last year, Tiger would
have been unable to capitalize fully on Furby's potential. Tiger
obtained the rights to Furby from the inventor in October 1997 and
rushed to get a rough prototype ready for last year's toy fair.
Retailers' interest was greater than the company expected, and
Tiger soon found itself trying to fill orders in eight months for a
million Furbys, whih would typically take about two years.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger supplied the concept for Furby, and Hasbro provided the
computerized drafting, mechanics, working samples and ultimately
the production operations to create the finished product. ``They
made things happen faster for us and helped us get the product out
because of how late we were,'' Shiffman said. The Furby frenzy
reflects just how these deals are designed to work _ teaming an
entrepreneurial company's risk-taking with a large company's might
to push the toy into the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Furby, ``We are going to benefit from their international
sales, and that is an area in which we were underperforming.,''
said Shiffman, who now runs Tiger for Hasbro. And, he said,
Hasbro's marketing resources and licensing agreements gave Tiger
the ability to create products tied to properties it would
otherwise not have access to, like Barney and toys tied to the new
Star Wars movie coming out in May.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel, too, has made several recent acquisitions that it says
have increased its competitiveness. In its case, Mattel was looking
for companies with established brands that also provided strategic
benefits. ``We've both benefited from the competencies we are
seeking and acquired related brands,'' said Glenn Bozarth, a
spokesman for Mattel.
</P>
<P>
   Through its purchase of Tyco Inc. in 1996, for example, Mattel
snagged the Fisher-Price line, which is popular with preschoolers.
The line includes Blue's Clues and Sesame Street plush products as
well as classics like Magna Doodle and View-Master. Then the
purchase last year of the Pleasant Co. gave the company the popular
American Girl dolls, plus some strategic advantages.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, while Barbie is popular with girls between about 3
and 8, the American Girl line expands the age spectrum to girls in
their early teens. And the American Girl line is sold primarily
through catalogs, allowing Mattel to use the Pleasant Co.'s
expertise in direct-to-consumer distribution to sell its other
brands. If successful, the approach would enable the company to be
less dependent on key retailers, an increasingly important factor
for toy makers, whose business suffered mightily last year when
Toys ``R'' Us slashed its orders to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mattel's recent disappointing financial performance,
including a 69 percent earnings decline in the fourth quarter of
1998, highlights the need for toy makers to further consolidate in
an attempt to reduce their dependence on few powerful retailers as
well as the whims of often finicky consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toys are an inherently risky business,'' said Johnson of
Vanderbilt. ``The only way to insure stable earnings growth and the
kinds of things the Wall Street guys look for in a consumer product
company is through acquisition _ to buy successful products and
brands to keep diversifying all that massive risk they face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
