<HEADLINE>
GENZYME LICENSES FOLKMAN ANTI-CANCER PROTEIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Genzyme Molecular Oncology Monday said it has licensed a
cancer-fighting protein developed by Dr. Judah Folkman, director of
the surgical research laboratories at Children's Hospital, which it
hopes to start testing in humans next year.
</P>
<P>
   Although financial terms of the Genzyme-Children's Hospital
agreement were not disclosed, Genzyme Molecular Oncology president
Gail Maderis said the protein is essentially the ``next
generation'' of Folkman's earlier controversial research.
</P>
<P>
   ``What excites us is that we have the capability to produce the
protein in one of our facilites,'' said Maderis.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Maderis nor Children's would reveal any details about
the new protein except to add that Dr. Michael S. O'Reilly, a
research fellow at Children's who co-discovered the protein, will
consult to Genzyme Molecular Oncology. Both researchers are
expected to publish their initial preclinical findings, she added.
</P>
<P>
   The paucity of information did not deter Wall Street, as Genzyme
Molecular Oncology shares closed at 3 1/2, up 5/8 in heavy trading
_ nearly four times its average daily volume. Shares of Genzyme
Corp., its parent company, closed at 53 up 1n 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman gained worldwide attention last spring when Folkman's
group said that two other compounds the reserchers had developed,
endostatin and angiostatin, could make cancerous tumors in mice
shrink and disappear by stopping the flow of blood to the growths.
A controversy arose when other researchers tried and failed to
reproduce Folkman's results. However, last month a new independent
research group confirmed that the endostatin protein halted the
growth of kidney tumors in mice.
</P>
<P>
   Both endostatin and angiostatin, which were first discovered in
1994, were licensed by Children's to EntreMed Inc., a small
biotechnology company in Bethesda, Md., which is planning to launch
human testing later this year with its corporate partner,
Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.
</P>
<P>
   Maderis said the two EntreMed drugs pose no conflict with the
new Genzyme licensed protein, although both companies would compete
against each other if the drug compounds are successful in clinical
trials and obtain US Food and Drug administration marketing
approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
