<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6804 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DELIBERATE-BO     02-08 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DELIBERATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL DELIBERATIONS LIKELY TO BE SECRET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After days of haggling, and despite powerful
arguments about public accountability, the Senate Monday night
appeared poised to hold its final impeachment deliberations behind
closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties had been pushing a ``sunshine plan'' for
nearly a week, and at first it seemed to be building momentum.
Several Republicans who rejected similar plans earlier in the
proceedings _ including Senator Chuck Hagel of Nebraska _ said they
believed the Senate should cast open its doors for the final debate
over whether to oust the president.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, Senator Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas, a Republican
sponsor of the plan, said she could find only 60 votes _ seven shy
of the two-thirds majority needed to change the century-old rules
governing the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are mixed and torn,'' Hutchison said after the morning
GOP caucus, in which senators spent nearly an hour debating the
proposal.``I think it's going to be hard.''
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the opposition are conservative Republicans,
including Senators Phil Gramm of Texas and Orrin Hatch of Utah, who
for days have cited precedent and constitutionality as reasons why
the deliberations must stay shut.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott told members of the party
Monday that he would oppose opening the debate, creating an
obstacle that most senators admitted would be nearly impossible to
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you right now, we're not going to open the
proceedings,'' Gramm said after the caucus meeting. ``We have
public witnesses and closed jury deliberations every day in every
town in America. Why wouldn't we want to do it that way?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the impetus to open the proceedings could
overpower Lott's opposition, Senator John F. Kerry said flat-out:
``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's not likely to happen,'' said Kerry, who strongly
supports open deliberations along with nearly all the Democrats.
``But I think it's a great shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy also said prospects for an open
deliberation process were grim, predicting ``a close vote'' on the
issue. But Senator Tom Harkin, a Democrat from Iowa and a sponsor
of the motion, held out hope that ``Lott would let people vote
their conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that Republicans will think deeply about why we are
closing the deliberations,'' Harkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Rules governing impeachment, which date back to the 19th
century, were reviewed and revised in 1986 by Senator Robert C.
Byrd, a West Virginia Democrat, and then-Senator Bob Dole, a Kansas
Republican. They decided at that time to keep the closed-door
deliberation provision intact.
</P>
<P>
   Lott cited those rules and historic precedent in making his
decision, and the ``sense was that the precedent was preserved then
(in 1986) and should be preserved now,'' said a spokesman for the
senator.
</P>
<P>
   But the majority leader, according to the spokesman, was also
mulling a way to address one of the Democrats' biggest concerns:
public accountability. Once the impeachment trial is concluded,
Lott is likely to file a motion that would allow senators to
discuss their remarks made behind closed doors. He also might file
a motion to add all the deliberations, which will be recorded, into
the public record at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison said she discerned serious opposition during the GOP
caucus, although she was joined publicly by Republican Senators
Olympia Snowe, Susan Collins, both of Maine; Arlen Specter of
Pennsylvania and Hagel in publicly supporting the measure, as well
as by Senator Thad Cochran of Mississippi, who said he was
``inclined to support it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most sincere argument is that some people have not made up
their minds and that there would be no deliberations if it were in
open session. It would be 100 speeches,'' Hutchison said. ``Some
people feel that if you have more authority to talk back and forth,
perhaps it would make a difference in the decisions people make.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were far more cynical objectors, among them Senator
John H. Chafee, a Rhode Island Republican, who said open
deliberations would encourage senators to use up their allotted 15
minutes to talk before the television cameras, instead of striving
to finish the trial as quickly as possible. Senator Conrad Burns, a
Republican from Montana, agreed, saying the ``Senate operates much
better in closed session.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kennedy, that was precisely the point. The public should be
allowed to see senators at their best, he said, particularly ``if
we're going to expect the American people to accept the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, he said, ``We had two closed meetings. There
wasn't a word during those two closed meetings that the American
people couldn't have listened to or understood.''
</P>
<P>
   And on that point, at least, Kennedy had support from Republican
Senator Mitch McConnell of Kentucky. Asked whether the public
should be allowed to see the deliberations, McConnell cracked:
``The public's not going to miss anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
