<SLUG> BC-SKI-WORLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERNAN MASTERS BIRDS OF PREY TO TAKE WORLD ALPINE LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ Had it been another downhill at the Alpine World
Championships here Monday, Switzerland and Norway would be crowing
about keeping skiers from the Austrian juggernaut off the top-3
podium.
</P>
<P>
   But the downhill on the fearsome Birds of Prey track on Beaver
Creek was part one of a two-leg race that combines a slalom with
the speed race _ an event for skimeisters adept at both the
technical and speed ends of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss ace Bruno Kernen smoked down Birds of Prey, holding a high
line, nailing the tough turns and long 150-foot jumps, to put in
the fastest run of the day at 1 minute 13.40 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   His time was enough to knock Norwegian Andre Kvetjil Aamodt out
of the lead by 12 hundredths of a second and push teammate Lasse
Kjus into 3d, another six hundredths back. Tuesday at Vail, the
slalom end of the race will be run down the International course
that finishes in a stadium at Vail village, where some 20,000 fans
have gathered to cheer the world's best skiers. Crowds here,
according to race officials, have been the largest to watch live
ski racing in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for US fans, their best hope, 23-year-old Bode
Miller of Franconia, N.H., a product of Maine's Carrabassett Valley
Academy, spun off course in a spectacular crash after skiing nearly
the entire run in top-10 time.
</P>
<P>
   Had he finished, Miller would have been a strong contender for a
top-10 combined finish. Even as he finished, Miller, whose
strengths are in the technical end of racing, thought he would
still be eligible to race the slalom end of the race for a combined
time.
</P>
<P>
   But the jury ruled that Miller had missed a gate duing his fall
and disqualified Monday's run. He is still eligible and, at this
point, healthy enough to race in the slalom and GS competitions
coming up later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really bummed,'' said Miller, who, in his best event,
GS, has beaten the vaunted Austrian Hermann Maier in two runs this
year on the World Cup. ``I just got back a little, and my ski
delaminated. But that's how this sport goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Kernen's run was the first ray of light for the Swiss men's team
at these games, though he has yet to negotiate the slalom course he
will face Tuesday on International. ``I think if I will ski safe,''
said Kernan, ``I can have a good result. The Vail course is much
tougher than the (Worlds combined course) at Sestriere (Italy).''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Kernen's slight lead, Tuesday's odds-on favorites are
the two Norwegians, Kjus and Aamodt _ the first champion to clinch
medals in all five alpine disciplines (When Jean Claude Killy won
all the Olympic races at Grenoble, there was no Super-G or
combined, events Aamodt has medalled in.) Aamodt is the reigning
combined champion from the 1997 Worlds in Sestriere.
</P>
<P>
   Aamodt and Kjus are products of a Norwegian training philosphy
that focuses on technical racing, which makes them better turners
on technical downhil courses and gives them the flexibility to ski
GS and slalom. The Austrians also hold to this philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's slalom, the women's GS will run Thursday,
followed by the men's GS Friday, then women's slalom Saturday, and
mens' slalom Sunday to close the games.
</P>
</TEXT>
