<HEADER>
A6810 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-STUDENT-ROBBER-C     02-08 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-STUDENT-ROBBER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Student charged with armed robbery alleged to have connections
to gang
 &HT;    By Wes Hills
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A Wright State University student, charged Monday
with committing an armed bank robbery with a university vehicle,
was associated with a gang that committed seven armed bank
robberies in the Columbus, Ohio area, according to federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   William Bolling, a senior in biological sciences, is charged in
the Nov. 12 armed robbery of Star Bank, 7560 Reading Road,
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate Judge Michael R. Merz in Dayton ordered Bolling,
who faces a maximum 20-year prison term if convicted, bound over to
authorities in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   In a sworn statement attached to Bolling's arrest warrant, FBI
Special Agent Kevin R. Horan described the robbery scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Two masked men, each with a handgun, entered Star Bank, screamed
obscenities and ordered everyone to the floor, Horan said. The pair
escaped with $26,942.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the robbery, Horan said, the FBI was
investigating three men wearing Halloween masks involved with seven
armed bank robberies in the Columbus area between August 1997 and
October 1998. Eyewitnesses described the robbers as black because
of ``voice characteristics, language and mode of dress,'' according
to Horan's statement.
</P>
<P>
   The three suspects in these robberies were Michael Kadunc, Shane
Connors and Michael Magliocca, Horan states. All three are white.
Kadunc was arrested in the robberies Oct. 30. Magliocca was picked
up on other charges, then bonded out.
</P>
<P>
   After Magliocca was arrested again Dec. 5, charged with robbing
the Star Bank in Cincinnati with Bolling, he provided information
regarding eight bank robberies.
</P>
<P>
   According to Horan:
</P>
<P>
   Magliocca said he came to Dayton to stay with Bolling after he
bonded out of jail in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Magliocca and Bolling were driving around in
Bolling's car and Magliocca complained he was broke and had no
vehicle because the FBI had taken his possessions when he was
arrested Oct. 30 .
</P>
<P>
   ``Bolling said he had always wanted to rob a bank but did not
want to do it alone or could never find the right person to do it
with,'' Horan said. Bolling also said he had stolen the keys to a
WSU car that they could use as a getaway vehicle, Horan said.
</P>
<P>
   Bolling and Magliocca bought ``Scream'' and ``Alien'' Halloween
masks, two semiautomatic pellet guns, matching grey hooded
sweatshirts and two blue duffel bags.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 11, Magliocca and Bolling went to Cincinnati to case
banks.
</P>
<P>
   After returning to Dayton, Bolling and Magliocca went to the WSU
motor pool lot and stole a Pontiac Grand Am, using keys provided by
Bolling.
</P>
<P>
   Bolling was no stranger to the neighborhood where the bank was
located.
</P>
<P>
   While he and Magliocca were parked near the bank to put on their
robbery gear, a man walked beside their car, recognized Bolling and
asked him what he was doing in his old neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Bolling told the man he was visiting his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses to the Star Bank heist described the robbers as being
black based on their voice characteristics, Horan said. Bolling is
black.
</P>
<P>
   After the robbery, Magliocca and Bolling divided the money, and
Magliocca went to Greenville, N.C., where he was arrested Dec. 5,
Horan said.
</P>
<P>
   The WSU Grand Prix was recovered at the Wyoming Hills Apartments
in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Hills writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
