<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REORG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT REORGANIZATION TO STRESS CUSTOMERS OVER PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Microsoft Corp. is moving to reorganize itself into
divisions focused on different customer groups rather than on
products, analysts and people close to the company said Monday.
Such a change would be a big shift in orientation for a company
that has long emphasized engineering over marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It clearly signals a refocusing on the customer rather than on
the technology,'' said Rob Enderle, an analyst at Giga Information
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Allison, a spokesman for Microsoft, said the company
periodically reorganized, but she insisted that no decision had
been made on a move this time.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Allison declined to either confirm or deny an article in The
Seattle Times that first reported a coming reorganization. She said
that any change ``wouldn't be for weeks or months from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is now organized around different product areas. One
division, for instance, deals with the Windows operating system,
while another deals with applications and another with online
services.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed reorganization, one group would focus on big
corporate customers and another on consumers. Other groups would
focus on knowledge workers, meaning small-business users and mobile
professionals, while a fourth would focus on software developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have always viewed their technology as generic _ anybody
can use it,'' said Andrew C. Brosseau, an analyst with SG Cowen.
The reorganization, he said, ``is a recognition by them that the
customer they are serving has become more varied,'' ranging from
consumers to big corporations. Still, he said, the reorganization
sounds ``more evolutionary than revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   One consequence would be that responsibility for Windows could
end up being split between the corporate group, which would
concentrate on Windows NT for corporations, and the consumer group,
which would inherit Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   That could make it more difficult for the company to divest
itself of its operating-system business if the federal government
prevails in its antitrust suit against the company and the court
orders such a move. Ms. Allison, the Microsoft spokesman, said the
possible reorganization ``has nothing to do with the lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a reorganization might also signal a delay in the company's
announced intention to unify the core software of Windows 2000, the
program for large corporations once known as Windows NT, and the
consumer version of Windows for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization is being led by Steven Ballmer, who was named
president last year and given responsibility for day-to-day
operations by Bill Gates, the company's chairman. Ballmer, whose
background is in sales and marketing rather than programming, has
been intensively reviewing operations.
</P>
<P>
   To head the consumer group, Microsoft is seeking to lure back
Brad Silverberg, who led the development of Windows 95 and Internet
Explorer, the Web browser. Silverberg, 44, has been on leave from
the company since June 1997, though he has consulted for it
occasionally and has attended some company retreats.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Allison said the company had been talking to Silverberg and
others about leading the existing interactive media division, which
focuses on online services. The position has been vacant since the
former head of the division, Pete Higgins, resigned in November.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, because of Silverberg's background, that division
would be expanded in the reorganization to have responsibility also
for Windows and other software for consumer personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   When he was at Microsoft, Silverberg favored making the
company's Internet Explorer browser compatible with all computers,
not just those running Windows. He argued that the company had to
prepare for the time when the Internet might displace Windows as
the locus of personal computing.
</P>
<P>
   His view was opposed by James Allchin, who contended that
Windows should remain the core of the company. Gates backed
Allchin, and Internet Explorer was integrated into Windows.
Silverberg went on leave and Microsoft was revamped into the
current structure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
