<HEADER>
A6812 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT &LR;      02-08 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEARY BUT ATTENTIVE, THE SENATE LISTENS TO FINAL ARGUMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-PERJURY,
IMPEACH-DEBATE, IMPEACH-CENSURE, IMPEACH-CLINTON) 
(sw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The senator sighed and asked that his name not be
published as the price for candor. In return, he expressed the
common sense of perseverance triumphant on what he characterized as
this ``Much Ado'' day _ the closing round of arguments in the
national ordeal of President Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're telling us today is basically `Much Ado About
Nothing' because we've heard everything they have to say many times
over,'' said the senator, a Republican whose final impeachment
verdict is far from clear. He then went on into the chamber and,
far from idly cruising through the familiar, proceeded to take very
careful notes throughout the day's argumentation, repetitious as it
all was.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer attentiveness of the Senate impeachment court has been
noteworthy through the weeks of the trial. And on Monday, it seemed
exemplary as the vying lawyers proceeded through the oft-told tale
of the president and the intern, down through all those details:
the gifts, the affidavit, the fleeting White House sex, the
denials, and, even, videotaped appearances of Monica Lewinsky and
the president in his mid-summer recantings that confirmed his
misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   At the Capitol steps, a few outlandish incidents took place. A
man in his underwear played the guitar; another intruder put on a
gorilla mask and actually managed to have his picture taken with
two passing senators who looked taken by surprise in their
weariness.
</P>
<P>
   Any excitement in the air seemed related to the simple fact that
the Senate court finally was rounding onto the promised closing
date of Friday. Under the circumstances, after the year-long
scandal's erosion of the nation's patience, the actual approach of
``closure,'' as therapists would have it, seemed a stunning
novelty, as if Dickens could be rewritten and his interminable tale
of the Jarndyce vs. Jarndyce lawsuit in ``Bleak House'' could
actually be ended.
</P>
<P>
   Out in the corridors, the prosecutors were spreading fresh
affidavits, claiming new evidence, but there seemed no appetite for
11th-hour tangents in the chamber. Senators were dutifully jotting
down summary notes, leaning forward to measure the final
performances of the lawyers, and keeping their own counsel.
</P>
<P>
   By the closing hours, the sense of weariness was being conceded
even by some of the Republican prosecutors, all 13 of whom took
this final opportunity to address the Senate and the nation beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like we're performing and every day we get a
review,'' Rep. Ed Bryant complained of the attention of the news
media. Actually, the Tennessee lawmaker, like his colleagues, shied
not all from copious television time, especially on the Sunday talk
shows, in arguing far beyond the Senate court for the president's
banishment.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, some senators were literally slouching toward Friday
at their desks. A dozen or more took the unusual posture of
standing up and moving discreetly about the chamber during one
midafternoon bout of argumentation, as if fearing some fresh
scandal of drowsiness.
</P>
<P>
   The White House defense lawyers, their argument time done, could
only sit as mute as the senators while the prosecutors reserved two
final hours for denunciations of the president.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton lawyers looked spent. They sat stonily as one
prosecutor visited for one more time a familiar area of allegation
(``I did not touch those parts...''). They looked near glassy-eyed
as Rep. Charles Canady's summation approached a Johnny Cochran
couplet (``There was no way to explain away the DNA''). They failed
to appreciate the back-handed compliment to their lawyering from
the chief prosecutor, Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois. (``You may dress
the shepherd in silk, but he will still smell of the goat.'')
</P>
<P>
   The senators were exhorted to ``muster their courage'' to remove
the president. Hyde himself mustered a veritable Bartlett's
Familiar Quotations in offering his last impassioned plea for
conviction. ``We happy few,'' he said, turning in Shakesperean
tribute to his fellow House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting the 18th-century historian, Edward Gibbon, Hyde acidly
denounced the president by comparing him to a corrupt Roman
emperor, Septimius Severus: ``Severus promised, only to betray; he
flattered, only to rule; and however he might occasionally bind
himself by oath and treaty, his conscience, obsequious to his
interest, always released him from the inconvenient obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, with a final burst of the grinding passion that marked the
past year of scandal investigation, the case against the president
was completed at 6:35 p.m. before the Senate court.
</P>
<P>
   Senators left quickly, looking eager to at last break their
silence and deliberate Clinton's fate. No one claimed this day
proved crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that any senator's mind will be moved one way or
another on the final votes,'' said Sen. John Warner, R-Va., ``That
could only take place behind closed doors in a full deliberation of
all 100, listening carefully to one another.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled at that looming duty. ``No TV, no newspapers,'' he
continued rather happily, moving toward Friday as if toward
deliverance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
