<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMO-CLINICAL-TRIALS-6     02-08 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-CLINICAL-TRIALS-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMO PLANS AGREE TO HELP PAY MEMBERS' COSTS IN CLINICAL TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)  (mk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of resistance, health maintenance
organizations have agreed to help pay the costs of care for members
who enroll in clinical trials evaluating new drugs and medical
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, thousands of patients could receive promising new
treatments they were denied in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, ``for support of clinical trials,'' was
negotiated over the last year by the National Institutes of Health
and the American Association of Health Plans, the trade group of
the managed care industry, but has not yet been announced.
</P>
<P>
   For years, patients and federal officials have complained that
HMOs refused to help cover the costs of clinical trials. Many
patients have successfully sued HMOs that refused to pay for
certain treatments on the ground that they were experimental.
</P>
<P>
   With about half of all Americans now in some type of managed
care, this refusal threatened to become a major hindrance to
biomedical research, even as scientists said they were entering a
golden age of medical discovery, with many new therapies on the
horizon. Dr. Harold Varmus, director of the National Institutes of
Health, pushed for the new agreement as a way to bring the fruits
of basic research to bear on medical practice.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, managed care plans will try to increase the
number of their patients who participate in clinical trials
approved and financed by the National Institutes of Health. The
institutes subsidize hundreds of research projects to study the
effectiveness of new treatments, preventive measures and diagnostic
techniques for cancer, heart disease, AIDS, arthritis and dozens of
other ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledgeable patients often want to participate in clinical
research to gain access to promising new medications long before
the drugs are approved for the market. But many managed care plans
have refused to pay even the routine medical costs for people who
enroll in such trials.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new agreement, the American Association of Health
Plans says, it will encourage managed care plans to ``reimburse the
routine patient-care costs associated with NIH-sponsored clinical
trials, provided those costs are not substantially higher than the
costs a plan would incur in the course of standard treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers contend that the costs of care for people in
clinical trials are essentially the same as those for patients
receiving standard therapies, but that is a question to be studied
in trials that will now be enrolling HMO patients.
</P>
<P>
   United Healthcare Corp., a big managed care company based in
Minnetonka, Minn., said it would start by covering the costs of
care for cancer patients in clinical trials. ``Only 2 percent of
eligible cancer patients across the nation are enrolled in clinical
trials,'' said Dr. Lee Newcomer, chief medical officer at United.
``There may be many reasons for that, but we are removing the
payment barrier.''
</P>
<P>
   United, with 13 million members in 32 states, has agreed to pay
for any of its members who enroll in clinical trials sponsored by
the Coalition of National Cancer Cooperative Groups, which consists
of six nationwide networks with a total of 12,000 cancer
researchers supported by the NIH.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Comis, president of the coalition, said: ``So often
patients and their physicians do not consider entering a clinical
trial for treatment because most managed care organizations and
health care insurers typically do not pay the costs. United
Healthcare is helping to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from Congress, Medicare officials are also
re-examining their policy.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare's stated policy is to deny payment for services that
are not reasonable and necessary for the diagnosis and treatment of
illness or injury. The purpose of clinical trials is, by
definition, to test treatments that are unproven, so they are
generally excluded from coverage, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Academy of Sciences is studying whether Medicare
should cover some of the costs of clinical trials and, if so, what
the criteria should be.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Medicare officials have said they do not want to pay for
treatments in poor-quality trials, and they are also reluctant to
pay research costs beyond the costs of routine patient care. The
extra costs may result from the purchase of new technology, the
additional monitoring needed for patients in research studies, and
the work of compiling and analyzing data, though typically it is
the sponsors of clinical trials that pay these costs.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomer, of United Healthcare, said he doubted that his
company's new policy on cancer trials would increase costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intuition, my guess, is that this will not add to our
costs,'' he said, ``but that's the reason we are doing these
studies, to find out whether there are added costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Comis, the president of the coalition of cancer research groups,
said, ``There is growing evidence that the costs of care for people
in clinical trials are essentially the same as the costs for
patients receiving standard therapies.''
</P>
<P>
   In a report to Congress last year, Dr. Richard Klausner,
director of the National Cancer Institute, said the reluctance of
HMOs to help pay for the care of people in clinical trials had
become ``a serious barrier to progress'' in cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the legitimate responsibility of the insurance
industry,'' he said, ``to reimburse the costs of routine medical
care of cancer patients in all phases of high-quality research
trials.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
