</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKA-FIGURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGURE SKATING RULES ARE RIFE WITH PROS AND CONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The cards and letters have been coming in for
weeks now. (itals)``Best of luck . . . I know you'll have a
wonderful pro career.''(unitals) ``I'm like, what? You think I'm a
professional?'' Michelle Kwan says.
</P>
<P>
   She may be the world pro figure skating champion, but Kwan is
also the amateur champion. Or, as they say around the International
Skating Union, she's both the eligible and ineligible champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that weird?'' says Kwan, who's in town this week to
defend her US amateur/eligible crown. ``It does confuse people. It
confuses the skaters, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In sport's ``open'' era, which is open some of the time to some
of the skaters, amateurs and pros can compete against each other
today but not tomorrow, here but not there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's, like, chaos,'' Kwan says.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, TV viewers watched Russia's Maria Butyrskaya skate
under one set of rules in the European championships in the
afternoon and another set of rules in the Japan Open in the
evening. And neither event was live.
</P>
<P>
   Skating now is like tennis used to be, and nobody seems very
happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolute confusion as to what it all means,'' says
James Disbrow, president of the US Figure Skating Association.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic champion Tara Lipinski turned pro and didn't compete at
all this season. Todd Eldredge and Ilya Kulik stayed amateur but
didn't skate in amateur events. Kwan skipped the Grand Prix but
will compete in the World Championships. And Alexei Yagudin
competed in everything.
</P>
<P>
   The post-Olympic year is usually unsettled, as skaters stay
amateur (i.e. eligible for ISU events), turn pro (ineligible), or
take a breather to sort out options. But this season has been more
turbulent than ever since the ISU sanctioned 10 open events in
addition to its Grand Prix series for eligible skaters.
</P>
<P>
   That meant that Kwan and Yagudin, the world amateur titlists,
could compete against the likes of Oksana Baiul and Kurt Browning
in the World Professional Championships. What it doesn't mean is
that skating will follow ice hockey and basketball and tennis and
open the Olympics to all comers.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've crossed the threshold into the ineligible funhouse
of made-for-TV exhibitions, you're on the wrong side of Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot work for Coca-Cola and sell Pepsi-Cola,'' says ISU
president Ottavio Cinquanta. ``This is life.''
</P>
<P>
   The only reason the ISU let its top stars perform in pro events
was to entice them to stay eligible. After watching Baiul and
Lipinski cash in their gold medals shortly after the Games, the ISU
wanted to make sure it kept its marquee names on board for 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not so stupid to lose another talent like Lipinski,''
says Cinquanta. ``Do you think I want Kwan to leave?''
</P>
<P>
   The ISU couldn't care less about the pros, whom it views as
defectors, and sees no reason to let them opt back in when the
Olympic year comes around.
</P>
<P>
   ``They left intentionally,'' says Cinquanta. ``We are not
available to temporarily enhance every four years their
reputations. This is not a supermarket.''
</P>
<P>
   Why should the pros be allowed to skate in glorified exhibitions
judged by ``Cindy Crawford and Mr. Schwarzenegger,'' Cinquanta
argues, and still be eligible for the Games? If they want an
admission ticket to Olympus, the ISU says, let them play by
eligible rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want a Harvard or a Yale degree, you cannot say: `I
have studied in Japan. I want a diploma,' '' muses Cinquanta.
``They take you to the mental hospital in an ambulance.''
</P>
<P>
   An open Olympics is probably a moot point, anyway. When the ISU
allowed pros to compete in Lillehammer in 1994, they won the pairs
(Ekaterina Gordeeva and Sergei Grinkov) and took a bronze in the
dance (Jayne Torvill and Christopher Dean), but were soundly
thwacked in the individual events. Viktor Petrenko and Brian
Boitano, the previous champions, finished out of the medals, as did
two-time gold medalist Katarina Witt. Even if the ISU threw the
Games open next time, few pros would probably opt in.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, skating is the only sport in which the amateurs not
only usually beat the pros but also make more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The terms professional and amateur have no financial
meaning,'' concedes Cinquanta. ``When they say the professional is
Mr. Boitano, I laugh. He may make less money than Mr. Kulik.''
</P>
<P>
   The pros and amateurs may mix it up in the opens but they might
as well be living in different universes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the entertainers versus the competitors,'' says Disbrow.
</P>
<P>
   The amateurs skate much more difficult technical routines _ a
quadruple-triple combination is standard in the short program and a
quad (or two) and seven or eight triples are all but mandatory in
the long. The pros, many of whom are over 30, skate more artistic,
interpretive programs with limited jumps.
</P>
<P>
   The opens are a stylistic compromise. Even so, the idea of
skating more demanding programs against younger amateurs in front
of ISU judges was enough to keep several pros _ most notably
Boitano and Kristi Yamaguchi _ on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the amateurs dominated the opens and Kwan and
Yagudin breezed to the US Pro titles, which merely added to the
confusion and infuriated ABC, which is paying the ISU $100 million
for a 10-year TV package that includes the Grand Prix circuit and
the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected to be the exclusive eligible-skater network,''
says Robin Stratton Rivera, ABC's sports programming director.
``But you could see it eroding with the opens.''
</P>
<P>
   Though some eligible skaters like Yagudin and Nicole Bobek
performed in both Grand Prix and open events, most opted for the
opens, which were less taxing and involved far less travel.
Virtually all of the opens were held in the US; the Grand Prix
circuit had skaters hopscotching from North America to Europe to
Asia back to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Eldredge, the five-time US champ who's abdicating his throne
this week and giving up a chance to regain his world title, stuck
to the opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, I'd be counting down the days until Nationals,'' he
says. ``But I'm really enjoying this year. I've competed against
the same guys I would have competed against _ just under different
rules. They've kept it so open that you could do whatever you
wanted. It was fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been fantastic for Eldredge, whom the ISU considers
to be on ``active rest,'' but it was frustrating for Kwan, who was
kept from defending her Skate America title because she wouldn't
commit to the Grand Prix circuit. And it was bewildering for the
skating public, which isn't sure who can skate when against whom
and for what anymore. Not even in boxing can someone hold both the
amateur and pro titles.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that skating has morphed into such a hybrid of sport
and show biz (Kwan has a Disney contract) that competitive clarity
is both impossible and irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for the Olympics, I don't think you watch skating to
really care about who's coming out where,'' muses ABC analyst Dick
Button, who directs the World Pro Championships. ``It's really an
exhibition with the extra added attraction of having someone win.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the post Nancy-and-Tonya era, with TV channels glutted
with a mishmash of live and taped competitions and exhibitions, the
spectator can no longer be sure who's winning what _ or whether
anyone's winning at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The customer is confused,'' says Disbrow. ``We need to
identify what it is that the customer is going to see. What are the
skaters competing in and how do they qualify for it?''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants a repeat of this season, when the ISU seemed to
change its mind every other week about whether it wanted opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very bumpy path,'' says Button, who directed four of
the events.
</P>
<P>
   So when next month's Grand Prix final and amateur world
championships are done, the ISU and the USFSA and the pros and the
networks hope to sit down and hash out a system everyone can live
with _ and recognize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the restaurant business for 16 years,'' says
Disbrow. ``And the bottom line has always been: What do the
customers want and how can I bring it to them?''
</P>
</TEXT>
