<SLUG> BC-RAINIER-BEER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAINIER BEER BRAND SOLD, FATE OF SEATTLE BREWERY UNCERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL VIRGIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Stroh Brewery Co. said Monday it is selling the
Rainier beer brand _ but not the Seattle plant that makes it _ to
Pabst Brewing Co.
</P>
<P>
   Pabst already owns the Olympia brewery at Tumwater, Wash., and
is expected to move production of the Rainier brand, one of the
best selling in this region, there.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the fate of the Rainier brewery, with its landmark
red R visible along Interstate 5 just south of downtown Seattle,
and its 230 employees in doubt. Stroh said it would look for a
buyer for the plant, as well as for Portland's Blitz-Weinhard
brewery; the Henry Weinhard brand made there is being sold to
Miller Brewing Co.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not clear yet who in an industry marked by overcapacity
and little sales growth might want the Seattle plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really no need for any more capacity at this point,''
said Tim Swanson, an analyst at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Stroh itself only said it would sell the Seattle plant as an
operating brewery or ``for alternative use.''
</P>
<P>
   Stroh spokeswoman Lacey Logan said the deal won't close for 60
days, pending Justice Department approval. After that, Stroh
expects to sign nine-month contracts to make beer for Pabst until
the conversion is complete.
</P>
<P>
   For Rainier employees, the limited prospects for a buyer means
that ``as of January 2000, they don't have jobs,'' said Lee Watson,
business representative and treasurer for Operating Engineers Local
286 in Renton.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit-based, family-owned Stroh said it is selling its
portfolio of brands including Stroh, Rainier, Old Milwaukee,
Schlitz, Schaefer, Old Style, Schmidt's and Lone Star to Pabst, but
just one brewery, in Pennsylvania. It is selling Weinhard and
Mickey's to Miller; Pabst in turn is selling its Hamm's and Olde
English 800 brands to Miller. Stroh doesn't have buyers yet for its
breweries in Seattle, Portland, Texas, North Carolina and
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Stroh is the nation's fourth largest brewer in an industry that
may have room for a few national players such as Anheuser-Busch,
Coors, Miller and a consolidator like Pabst. Stroh had hoped to be
one of those consolidators _ someone who buys brand names and shuts
excess production capacity, often contracting out production to
others _ but said the state of the beer industry and the offer from
Pabst and Miller made it a good time to get out of the business.
</P>
<P>
   The big problem for the industry is that Americans aren't
drinking enough beer. There's been little growth in overall beer
consumption _ ``You could make a case that there's not been growth
since the 1970s,'' said Paul Shipman, chief executive officer of
Seattle-based Redhook Ale Brewery Inc.
</P>
<P>
   That means the popularity of microbrews and specialty or craft
beers like Redhook came at the expense of the major national brews,
and even in the specialty category sales growth has stalled and
brewers are suffering financially.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson said it's a telling point that Miller, the nation's
second-biggest brewer, has enough excess capacity that as part of
this latest deal it agreed to expand its contract brewing for
Pabst.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the beer business is going look like other American
industries, such as banking, which are characterized by giant
national players and some small local companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either you're a real small specialty (brewer) or you're real
big and have the marketing muscle,'' said George Hancock, chief
executive of Seattle's Pyramid Breweries. ``We don't see anyone in
the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Rainier Beer dates back to 1878, when German imigrant Andrew
Hemrich founded Seattle Brewing &AMP; Malting. After prohibition,
Canadian brewers Fritz and Emil Sick licensed the name, which had
been sold to a California company, and eventually acquired full
ownership. For a time Sicks' Breweries Ltd. was a part of Canadian
beer giant Molson; later it was a publicly traded company which
included the Robert Mondavi winery.
</P>
<P>
   Rainier Beer became a part of the Pacific Northwest cultural
landscape not only through the Sicks' community involvement (a
Seattle baseball park bore the name and was home to the
minor-league Rainiers and major-league Seattle Pilots). The brand
was also featured in some of the region's quirkiest and popular
advertising, such as the running of the RainBeers (basically a herd
of bottles with legs sticking out of them) and a motorcycle whose
gears shifted to the whine of the product's name.
</P>
<P>
   Rainier Brewing was bought by G. Heileman in 1977, which in turn
was bought by Australian financier Alan Bond in 1987. Overloaded
with Bond's debt, Heileman filed for bankrupcy court protection in
1991. Dallas investment firm Hicks, Muse &AMP; Co. bought Heileman and
Rainier in 1993; Stroh bought Heileman in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said the latest in a string of sales for the Seattle
brewery was another example of ``corporate America taking the money
and running.''
</P>
<P>
   Pabst, headquartered in San Antonio, owns such brands as
Olympia, Falstaff, Ballantine, Lucky Lager and Pearl.
</P>
</TEXT>
