<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-PILOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THIRD DAY, AMERICAN CANCELS FLIGHTS IN DISPUTE WITH PILOTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Donald J. Carty took over as chairman and chief executive
of the AMR Corp. in May, he said that his first priority was to
improve the bitter labor relations at American Airlines, the
country's second-largest carrier, that had developed under his
combative predecessor, Robert L. Crandall.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Carty is learning just how big a challenge that is.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, American was forced to cancel 22 percent, or 500, of
its 2,250 daily flights as scores of pilots called in sick for the
third day in a row. The pilots are angry about American's plans to
integrate Reno Air, a small Western carrier it bought in December,
into its larger network.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has inconvenienced thousands of passengers and
threatens to disrupt the coming President's Day holiday weekend,
when flights all over the country will be full. But before that
happens, Carty hinted strongly at a news conference on Monday,
American would seek a court injunction ordering the pilots to stop
their job action.
</P>
<P>
   That the airline is facing such difficulty came as a surprise to
executives at other carriers and to Wall Street analysts. Shares of
AMR, American's parent company, fell $2.9375 a share Monday to
close at $57 on the first day of trading since the disruption
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should never have happened,'' said Samuel C. Buttrick, an
industry analyst with Paine Webber in New York. ``Other airlines in
the past have worked out pilot-integration issues on much larger
mergers without this unnecessary disruption to operations.'' He
estimated the impact on AMR's earnings this quarter around 5 cents
a share.
</P>
<P>
   Carty expressed dismay Monday, asserting: ``It is hard for me to
believe that this is really about the Reno acquisition. I wish I
knew what it was. But I think it is clearly about more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that American was willing to reopen talks at any time
with the Allied Pilots Association, the independent union that
represents American's 9,200 pilots. The union has said the same
thing, though no new talks have been scheduled since negotiations
broke off on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Overman, an association spokesman, said Monday that the
disruption was a ``grass-roots initiative'' that was not led by the
union.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two weeks, union leaders had debated asking members
to refuse to fly voluntary overtime if an agreement with the
company could not be reached. That would have taken several days
before it began seriously affecting American's operations. But
after negotiations ended without a resolution on Friday night,
scores of pilots apparently took it upon themselves to call in sick
beginning Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would really like to see a more collegial and cooperative
atmosphere established at American Airlines,'' Overman said. ``I
guess it is fair to say that we look at this negotiation as an
opportunity to see where the rubber meets the road, and it doesn't
seem to be happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the pilots current anger can be traced back to their
abortive strike two years ago, which was ended only minutes after
it began when President Clinton, exercising his executive powers,
ordered the pilots back to work. An agreement was later worked out
under the auspices of an emergency board appointed by Clinton, but
even though a majority of the pilots voted in favor of it, many
felt it was imposed on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a feeling that our pilots didn't have the say that
they should have in the process,'' Overman said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, several members of a group of hardline pilots that
was instrumental in the defeat of a tentative contract between
American and the union that preceded the strike have been elected
to the union's 18-person board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Reno Air, which has 300 pilots and 25 jets, has been a sensitive
issue with the pilots union because the airline was founded soon
after American scaled back its operations on the West Coast in 1992
and laid off 610 pilots. Reno Air, which pays its pilots roughly
half the average salary at American, picked up many of the recently
abandoned routes and entered into a marketing partnership with
American.
</P>
<P>
   Carty said Monday that he decided to buy Reno partly to
eliminate the resentment felt by the pilots. The acquisition, he
added, would allow American pilots to rise to captain's rank faster
and would offer new flying opportunities in the West.
</P>
<P>
   But the pilots say that Carty's plan to take up to 18 months to
integrate Reno into American's operations violates their contract.
And they are eager to set a precedent in case American acquires a
much larger airline, such as US Airways or Alaska Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Carty said that the union's integration proposal would cost and
additional $40 to $50 million a year, greatly inflating Reno's $124
million purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Railway Labor Act, the law that governs labor
relations in the airline business, job actions such as a partial
strike are severely proscribed. Carty implied that he would seek a
court order ending the job action if the disruptions continued. But
it is not clear whether the pilots would continue to call in sick,
citing their right under federal rules not to fly if they do not
feel physically fit.
</P>
<P>
   That does not bode well for happier relations between labor and
management at American, but Carty is still hopeful. ``Our objective
is to be the airline with the best labor relations in the
industry,'' he said. ``We obviously have some ways to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
