u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BENZ-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-08 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENZ-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MERCEDES-BENZ OF NORTH AMERICA DISMISSES AD AGENCY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fraying ties between Mercedes-Benz of North
America and its agency since November 1993, Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS in
New York, finally snapped Monday when Lowe and two affiliates were
dismissed, effective April 30.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to dismiss Lowe, part of the Lowe Group unit of the
Interpublic Group of Companies, set off an acrimonious dispute that
included a statement from Lowe describing agency executives as
``appalled.''
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal also puts up for grabs a marquee-name automotive
account with billings estimated at $125 million. Mercedes-Benz
joins a growing list of large marketers, particularly in
competitive consumer product categories, to have recently dismissed
or changed agencies; others include Dell Computer, Gateway,
Mastercard and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz will initially concentrate its search for a
successor shop at two giant agency companies that work for its
parent, DaimlerChrysler AG. One is the Omnicom Group, with agencies
handling brands like Dodge, and the other is True North
Communications, with agencies handling brands like Chrysler, Jeep
and Plymouth.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal of Lowe had been expected since last week, when
this columnist reported that Mercedes-Benz executives had met with
Lowe officials to express concerns about issues deemed detrimental
to continuing their relationship. One concern centered on changes
in top management at the agency, the executives said, and the other
centered on potential conflicts stemming from the work performed
for a major DaimlerChrysler rival, the General Motors Corp., by
Lowe sibling agencies under the Interpublic umbrella like
McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unhappiness with Lowe dates back well into 1998,'' said
Michael Jackson, president and chief executive at Mercedes-Benz in
Montvale, N.J. ``And it became clear that the situation was
becoming more difficult, not better.''
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal seems puzzling because Lowe's campaigns for
Mercedes-Benz have been among the most honored in advertising and
sales have increased substantially since the agency gained the
account. Lowe did outstanding work, achieved results in the market
_ yet will soon be on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not lose the account because of the quality of the work
or the quality of service we provided to Mercedes-Benz,'' said Lee
Garfinkel, chairman and chief creative officer at Lowe. In addition
to Lowe, the affiliates losing Mercedes-Benz business are Lowe Fox
Pavlika, which has handled direct marketing accounts, and Diamond
Promotion Group, the promotional agency.
</P>
<P>
   There had been persistent speculation that Mercedes-Benz
executives were miffed about the retirement of Marvin Sloves, who
until Dec. 31 had served as chairman at Lowe along with Garfinkel.
Sloves had been particularly close to executives at Mercedes-Benz
since his previous agency, Scali, McCabe, Sloves in New York, was
awarded the auto marketer's account in 1992. The account _ and
Sloves _ came to Lowe in November 1993 when Scali, McCabe was
acquired and merged into Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson acknowledged that there were ``a lot of factors
involved'' in the dismissal, primarily ``concerns about the
business process and the creative process,'' and ``Marvin is one of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had a relationship with the agency that I would
call incredible,'' Jackson said, ``resulting from a tremendous
investment on both sides starting with Marvin.''
</P>
<P>
   Garfinkel said that ``the only concerns Michael Jackson ever
expressed to me'' about the account ``were about Marvin leaving,''
which were meant to be addressed by a two-year contract for Sloves
to serve as a consultant to Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone call to Sloves on Monday was not returned. Monday
was two months to the day that Sloves announced his retirement from
Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Draznin, a spokesman for Lowe, said that the agency was
``considering its position, including the pursuit of legal
remedies.'' Lowe sued five top executives of a predecessor to Lowe
Fox after they left in October 1996 to start their own agency; the
suit was settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   Two advertising trade publications, Frohlinger's Marketing
Report and Adweek, reported last month that Sloves was talking to
executives at other agencies about joining them along with the
Mercedes-Benz account.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jackson said that Sloves ``is not part of this
process'' in searching for a successor to Lowe, adding, ``Marvin
does not enter into the equation whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Eberhardt, vice president for marketing at Mercedes-Benz,
said that the search ``will not start with discussions with
individual agencies,'' but rather with the parents.
</P>
<P>
   If that does not yield a new agency, he added, ``we are also
prepared to go into a review.''
</P>
<P>
   Omnicom agencies working for DaimlerChrysler include
Clemenger/BBDO in Australia and BBDO Detroit, units of BBDO
Worldwide; Pentacom; Rapp Collins Worldwide, and GFMO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within Omnicom, there are probably a number of options,'' said
John Wren, president and chief executive in New York. ``I have to
sit and listen to the client first before I speculate about where
the account should go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never met nor have I ever spoken with Marvin,'' he
added, ``which some people find amazing.'' Wren did, however,
disclose that ``I have a Mercedes; that's what I'm driven around in
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   True North agencies working for DaimlerChrysler include Bozell
Worldwide. Bruce Mason, chief executive at True North in Chicago,
referred inquiries to David Bell, president and chief executive at
Bozell in New York, who was out of the country. Trade publications
have suggested that Mercedes-Benz could be handled by the other
worldwide True North agency network, Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding.
</P>
<P>
   About 65 of the estimated 450 employees at Lowe are assigned to
the Mercedes-Benz account. ``We are evaluating the situation as we
move forward,'' Draznin said, adding, ``obviously, we have to
service the account for the next 84 days.'' That service includes a
campaign for the new models of the S-Class Mercedes-Benz, due early
next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
