<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-NOOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR QUEEN NOOR, A DELICATE BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Dressed in all black and a white veil as is the
custom of mourning in Islam, Queen Noor stood far off to the side
of the burial ceremony for her husband King Hussein Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Women are not permitted to attend funerals or burial services in
the Muslim religion, so she watched from a distance as her sons and
the rest of the men of the Hashemite clan lowered the casket and
said their final goodbyes.
</P>
<P>
   The American-born, Princeton-educated queen who has worked
tirelessly for women's rights was in that moment delicately
balancing her own grief, her strong Western views, and her respect
for Jordan's very traditional and religious society, say palace
sources and women who know her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has handled this very difficult time with grace and poise.
I think the Jordanian people have grown closer to her through the
last few days. The mourning has brought them together,'' said a
female palace official close to the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing captured this new bond more than when the king lay dying
on Saturday and Noor ventured out into a chilly rain to greet the
throngs of Jordanians who had gathered at the hospital. She thanked
them for their concern. And she never left the king's side through
his final seven-month battle against cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But for most of her reign, Noor, a high-school cheerleader who
also protested the Vietnam War in the early 1970s, has had a
strained relationship with the traditional clans and Muslim
clerical order in Jordan. They see her as too American, too
outspoken, and too enthralled with her life among the glitteratti.
</P>
<P>
   There was even sniping against her in the late 1980s for
spending the kingdom's wealth on jewels and designer clothes on
shopping sprees in Europe and America. She has always denied the
allegations, and insists she is much more likely to shop out of
catalogues than fly off to Fifth Avenue boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old mother of four, who was married to Hussein for
more than 20 years, faces an uncertain future in the palace,
although most royal watchers believe she will retain her title as
queen.
</P>
<P>
   Born Lisa Halaby to a Christian Arab-American family, she took
the name Noor al-Hussein -- ``the light of Hussein'' -- when she
converted to Islam and married the monarch on June 15, 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein's passion for flying brought the couple together. Noor,
an aspiring architect, was working on an airport project in Jordan.
The king was immediately smitten.
</P>
<P>
   Her beauty and charm and ease with the limelight make her the
babyboomer's answer to another American who married royalty, Grace
Kelly. Others thought the way she comforted a bereaved nation
Saturday, dressed modestly in a scarf, was an Arab version of the
widowed First Lady Jackie Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The new King Abdullah, 37, is not her son. He is the king's
oldest son from his second marriage to Princess Muna, which ended
in divorce. Some Jordanians quietly grumbled that Noor was pushing
Hussein, in the final stages of his cancer, to name their
18-year-old son Hamzah as the heir to the throne. Abdullah Sunday
made Hamzah Crown Prince.
</P>
<P>
   Noor and Hussein had three other children: Hashim, 17; and
daughters, Iman, 15, and Raiyah, 12.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, on the steps of Raghdan Palace she stood surrounded by
all of the women of the Hashemite clan and watched the men make the
procession to the grave. Noor received condolences in a chamber of
the palace where she was gathered with her female relatives, the
wives of heads of state, and women dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   They included First Lady Hillary Clinton, the widow of slain
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, and the wife of Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat. As is the tradition, the women sat in
chairs and drank bitter coffee.
</P>
<P>
   For a woman who has campaigned against land mines and supported
environmental protection and ecotourism, the strictures of Islam
might seem confining. But women who know her say that she has found
many ways in which Islam also empowers women and creates bonds
between them in a way that Western culture often does not.
</P>
<P>
   Salwa Al-Sukhon, 31, who works with a women's cooperative funded
by the Queen Noor Foundation, said that Noor often travels into the
remote Bedouin villages and poor Palestinian refugee camps to see
first-hand how she can help better their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has done so much to empower women,'' she said. ``I think
women are counting on her to continue her work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
