<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6823 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-ART-2TA     02-08 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS AND DEFENSE MAKE CONCLUDING ARGUMENTS IN CLINTON TRIAL
IN SENATE
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: IMPEACH-PERJURY, IMPEACH-DEBATE,
IMPEACH-CENSURE, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CLINTON) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr. 
 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the acquittal of President Clinton all but
assured, the chief prosecutor demanded Monday night that the Senate
``cleanse the office'' by convicting him rather than resorting to
``the Air-Wick of a censure resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, the last of 13 Republican
prosecutors or ``managers'' to speak, concluded their case by
accusing the defense of resorting to ``a theater of distraction and
misdirection.'' He said his side's ``most formidable opponent'' had
been cynicism _ ``the widespread conviction that all politics and
all politicians are by definition corrupt and venal.''
</P>
<P>
   In his closing statement, the main White House counsel, Charles
F.C. Ruff, urged the senators to focus not upon the minutiae of the
lawyers' arguments but upon ``voices of greater eloquence than any
of us can muster, the voices of Madison and Hamilton and the others
who met in Phildelphia 212 years ago, and the voices of the
generations since, and the voices of the American people now, and
the voices of generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff concluded as he had begun on Jan. 19: ``William Jefferson
Clinton is not guilty of the charges that have been brought against
him. He did not commit perjury. He did not commit obstruction of
justice. He must not be removed from office.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly drained of emotion and resigned to defeat, Hyde ended
with the words, ``And now let us all take our place in history on
the side of honor, and, oh, yes, let right be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will begin its deliberations on Tuesday, probably
behind closed doors. The votes on the two articles of impeachment,
charging Clinton with perjury and obstruction of justice in an
effort to conceal his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky, are
scheduled for Thursday or Friday. Consideration of a censure
resolution could follow.
</P>
<P>
   For all the historical rarity of Monday's session _ only once
before, in the case of Andrew Johnson in 1868, has a presidential
impeachment proceeding reached this stage _ there was little drama
in the chamber. Having gone over the same ground so often, most
recently on Saturday, the lawyers could offer little but reheated
evidentiary and rhetorical leftovers. And the outcome has been
taken for granted for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff and Hyde conceded that they, too, like the senators and the
nation at large, were weary of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking the last steps along a path that for most of us
has seemed to be unending,'' Ruff commented, and more than three
and a half hours later, Hyde echoed, ``We are blessedly coming to
the end of this melancholy procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   The session was filled with allegations, exhortations and
complaints, lots of complaints, mainly from the prosecutors drawn
from Republican members of the House of Representatives but from
Ruff, too, about the trial procedures and about the nonstop
coverage provided by television.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Republicans, there was a certain fatalistic self-pity.
Hyde spoke bitterly of indignities he said he and his colleagues
had endured, enumerating ``the media condemnations, the patronizing
editorials, the hate mail, the insults hurled in public, the
attempts at intimidation, the death threats and even the
disapproval of our colleagues, which cuts the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois legislator compared his team of managers to Henry
V's ``band of brothers'' at Agincourt, and he dipped deep into his
oratorical reservoir for quotations from Charles de Gaulle and
Terence Rattigan, Septimius Severus and Horace Mann, Edward Gibbon
and Saul Bellow.
</P>
<P>
   He compared the text of one of the proposed censure resolutions
with that of the impeachment articles and said, ``We aren't half as
tough on the president.'' But he continued to express strong
opposition to censure, which is favored by most Democrats and some
Republicans as a means short of conviction to put the Senate on
record as condemning Clinton's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A failure to convict will make the statement that lying under
oath, while unpleasant and to be avoided, is not all that
serious,'' Hyde declared. ``We have reduced lying under oath to a
breach of etiquette, but only if you are the president.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll, as several of the lawyers observed, showed that
more than half of Americans thought the president guilty but did
not wish him removed from office. The defense drew comfort from
this, and the prosecutors expressed frustration at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt there are many people on the planet who doubt the
president has repeatedly lied under oath and has obstructed
justice,'' Hyde said. ``The real issue doesn't concern the facts
but what to do about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr of Georgia, who was the first House member to
introduce an impeachment resolution (over the president's campaign
fund raising), lectured the senators about polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polls played no part in the great and glorious decisions,
decisive decisions, that made America a nation and kept it free and
strong,'' Barr asserted. ``Will the principles embodied in our
Constitution and our laws be reaffirmed, wrested from the pallid
hands of pollsters and pundits and the swarm of theorists
surrounding these proceedings?''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans devoted relatively little time on Monday to the
details of the case. Instead, they flung swords of words at the
president and his defenders. Rep. Bill McCollum said angrily,
``William Jefferson Clinton is not a king.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Floridian, Rep. Charles Canaday, warned senators they
were about to set ``a pathetic, low standard of integrity.'' Rep.
Lindsey Graham of South Carolina heaped scorn on the defense
contention that President Clinton had been ``truthful but
misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you be both?'' he demanded, his voice dripping
contempt.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the last Republicans to speak before Hyde was Rep. James
Rogan of California, a former Democrat whose district leans
Democratic. His leading role in the drive for conviction has
convinced some politicians his seat is in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``So be it,'' he said on Monday, in one of several attempts by
Republicans to demonstrate that principle, not politics, motivated
their behavior. ``That revelation produces for me no flinching. I
can live with the concept of not serving in Congress. I cannot live
with the idea of remaining in Congress at the expense of doing what
I believed to be right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff was the only speaker on the president's side, and he
stopped well short of his three-hour limit.
</P>
<P>
   But he went methodically through his arguments on the two
articles and on the larger point that he has consistently pressed:
even if the senators were to find Clinton had committed the offense
charged, this by itself would not justify their voting to convict
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one question before you, albeit a difficult one,
one that is a question of fact and law and constitutional theory,''
Ruff said. ``Would it put at risk the liberties of the people to
retain the president in office? Putting aside partisan animus, if
you can honestly say that it would not, that those liberties are
safe in his hands, then you must vote to acquit.''
</P>
<P>
   He was sarcastic in his treatment of the managers' case. ``Nice
try, no facts,'' he commented at one point. And at another, only
moments later, ``Somebody's been watching too many reruns of the
X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the end, after discussing Blackstone and Sidney
Blumenthal, perjury and obstruction, after pointing at charts with
a long wand and cuing up videotape clips, he entered a general
defense of Clinton's conduct of his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manager Hyde questioned whether this president can represent
the interests of our country in the world,'' he said. ``Go to
Ireland and ask that question. Go to Israel and Gaza and ask that
question. If you doubt whether he should here at home continue in
office, ask the parent whose child walks safer streets, or the men
and women who go off to work in the morning at good jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he said this: ``We are together, I think, weavers of a
constitutional fabric in which all of us now are clothed and
generations will be clothed for millenia to come. We cannot leave
even the smallest flaw in that fabric, for if we do, one day
someone will come along and pull a thread, and the flaw will
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the classic summation of a defender. Do no unnecessary
harm to a man and a system, Ruff was contending, if both of them
work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
