<HEADLINE>
OLYMPICS WATCHERS AWAIT ETHICS REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The second wave of fallout from the Olympic
payoff controversy will hit the beleaguered Salt Lake Organizing
Committee Tuesday morning when its ethics panel releases a detailed
internal report.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's top two officers, Frank Joklik and Dave Johnson,
have already stepped down amid the most embarrassing scandal in
modern Olympic history. Others may follow if the panel finds that
they knew about nearly $1 million in inappropriate gifts and cash
provided to International Olympic Committee members before and
after the Utah capital landed the 2002 Winter Games in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the committee reportedly hopes to name a new chief
executive when its board meets Thursday. Though Mitt Romney, the
Belmont, Mass. venture capitalist and former US Senate candidate,
is the top contender, others are being considered. Madison Square
Garden chief Dave Checketts, the former Utah Jazz president who was
approached for the SLOC job two years ago, spoke with Utah Gov.
Mike Leavitt last week.
</P>
<P>
   Though a source close to Romney said Monday that Romney had not
yet been offered the job, his name is expected to be proposed to
the SLOC board Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   If Romney takes the position, he will be working with an larger
board (from 33 to 50) that will have been reduced to advisory
status and an expanded executive committee (from 12 to 20) that
will focus on tighter management. Both of those reforms were urged
last week by Leavitt and SLOC board chairman Robert Garff, who
believed that the board needed to be more diverse and the executive
committee more hands-on.
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt and Mayor Deedee Corradini are expected to name 17 new
board members Tuesday. On Thursday, the board will add eight new
committee members, some of whom may be state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Though a new Deseret News poll found that 60 percent of Utahans
still want Salt Lake City to host the Games, fewer than a quarter
want any more public money used. The state is already contributing
nearly $60 million of SLOC's $1.45 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   Though the ethics panel report has been anxiously awaited here,
it is only one of five inquiries into the payoffs. The IOC
investigation, completed last month, resulted in the resignation or
expulsion of nine members. The US Olympic Committee will complete
its own probe by the end of the month, and investigations by the US
Department of Justice and the state attorney general are ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   Though former chief executive Tom Welch has charged that
Leavitt, Corradini, and other bid committee members were aware off
the payoffs, sources said that the ethics panel (which does not
have subpoena power) will report that a small number of SLOC
members were involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
