<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SBC-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SBC SET TO BECOME FIRST BELL TO INVEST IN A LONG-DISTANCE CARRIER
</HEADLINE>
  (nk)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to become a national communications provider, SBC
Communications Inc. on Monday said it would buy up to 10 percent of
the Williams Companies Inc.'s communications unit, which is
building a coast-to-coast fiber-optic network.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between SBC, the No. 2 local phone company, and
Williams could be worth as much as $500 million and would be the
first significant investment in a long-distance carrier by one of
the Bell local phone giants. While none of the Bells _ Ameritech,
Bell Atlantic, BellSouth, SBC and US West _ are allowed to sell
long-distance service in their core markets, the Telecommunications
Act of 1996 allows them to own up to 10 percent of a long-distance
operator.
</P>
<P>
   But SBC would get more out of the deal than an investment.
Williams has agreed to meet all of SBC's long-distance needs once
SBC is allowed into the long-distance market, and at favorable
prices. Williams' roughly 1,000 salespeople would sell
long-distance service under the SBC brand.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, none of the Bells have had the gumption, or perhaps
the motivation, to invest in a long-distance carrier, a move that
could be described in regulatory terms as aggressive, if not
provocative. This is, however, SBC, which since the 1996 act's
passage has consistently been the most aggressive, if not
provocative, member of the Bell family. And quite often, SBC's
cheek has paid off.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, SBC, known to many consumers as Southwestern Bell,
became the first Bell to acquire another Bell (Pacific Telesis
Group, known to many customers as Pacific Bell). The same year, SBC
tried to negotiate a merger with the AT&AMP;T Corp. before that concept
was shot down by regulators. After SBC's first long-distance
petition was rejected, the company sued to invalidate the act's
cornerstone provision and won, though that judgment was later
reversed. And last October, SBC became the first Baby Bell to
acquire a big independent phone company (the Southern New England
Telecommunications Corporation, which serves most of Connecticut).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along that we want to be a global
telecommunications player and we're a regional player now,'' Edward
E. Whitacre Jr., SBC's chairman, said in an interview. Referring to
SBC's pending acquisition of the Ameritech Corp., he added: ``Along
with the acquisition of Ameritech, the alliance with Williams gives
us the line to connect all these dots.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now SBC cannot fully exploit Williams' long-distance
lines, because SBC is not allowed to sell long-distance service to
its core local phone customers. Each of the Bells, however, may
sell long-distance calls in connection with its wireless telephone
business. The Bells are allowed to sell long-distance calls with
their wireless offerings because they have not historically held a
monopoly in the wireless business.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, SBC had a wholesale long-distance deal with the
Sprint Corp. That deal contained a provision that allowed SBC to
terminate the agreement if SBC had not won entry to the
long-distance market by the beginning of 1999, executives close to
the agreement said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By investing in Williams, which plans an initial public offering
of shares in its communications unit in the second quarter, SBC can
exert more control over the product development plans of its
long-distance supplier than it could over Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   The other Bells, however, remain linked to long-distance giants.
Once Bell Atlantic enters the long-distance market, it has agreed
to primarily use Sprint. BellSouth has a deal with AT&AMP;T. Ameritech
has pacts with both AT&AMP;T and MCI Worldcom Inc. and U S West is set
to use AT&AMP;T (though U S West now uses the Frontier Corp. to carry
most of its wireless traffic).
</P>
<P>
   Once SBC wins long-distance approval from the Federal
Communications Commission in one state, SBC will take a seat on the
board of Williams' communications unit. SBC would also then almost
surely become Williams' biggest customer.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between SBC and Williams allows SBC to terminate the
agreement and move its traffic to another carrier if Williams is
taken over by another company. SBC executives said they had other
rights that would help prevent Williams from falling into the hands
of a competitor, but they refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of a number of conditions that we're not going to
wake up to see that Williams has been acquired by Worldcom or
AT&AMP;T,'' said James S. Kahan, SBC's senior vice president for
corporate development.
</P>
<P>
   As the stock in the communications unit is initially offered to
the public, SBC will receive 10 percent or $500 million worth of
the operation, whichever is worth less. If SBC's stake is less than
10 percent, it will not be able to increase its investment until a
later public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   SBC said Monday that the deal would not require regulatory
approval. Some federal and state regulators agreed, citing SBC's
apparent compliance with the 10 percent limit. They added, however
that the deal could raise concerns if it already included
arrangements for SBC to increase its stake after it wins
long-distance approval across its region.
</P>
<P>
   Even though SBC would be allowed to increase its stake after
winning long-distance permission, the regulators said that if such
an arrangement existed now, it could push SBC over the 10 percent
limit.
</P>
<P>
   Whitacre said that under the deal SBC would not hold options for
additional Williams stock. But referring to the possibility of
SBC's increasing its investment in Williams, he added: ``We have a
path where that probably could be done.''
</P>
<P>
   He refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   SBC's shares rose 43.75 cents, to $51.375, Monday while shares
of Williams rose $1.6875, to $36.625. Shares of IXC Communications
Inc., another new long-distance company, which seems ripe for a
deal similar to that of Williams, rose 75 cents, to $46.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
