<SLUG> BC-FREEPC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Company Giving Out Free PCs  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A Southern California company said yesterday it will give free
Compaq personal computers and Internet access to users who accept
continuous targeted advertising on their screens.
</P>
<P>
   The offer, by Free-PC Inc., marks the first attempt to subsidize
computers in return for revenues generated from advertising. As
prices for PCs continue to tumble, cable and telephone companies
are expected to start giving away computers or charging almost
nothing for them in order to get users to pay for high-speed
Internet and other services.
</P>
<P>
   Free-PC, which is operated by closely held IdeaLab of Pasadena,
said it will ship its first 10,000 computers this spring. It began
taking online applications for the PCs yesterday, and by
midmorning, its Web site  &LR; (www.free-pc.com) &LR;  was swamped and could
not be accessed.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers applying for a free PC are asked to fill out a
detailed questionnaire providing the company with demographic
information such as age, income and family status, personal tastes
and interests.
</P>
<P>
   The information will be used to determine which consumers will
get free PCs. The company said it wants consumers who will appeal
to advertisers, but eventually, it hopes to give a PC to anyone who
wants one.
</P>
<P>
   People who receive the free PCs _ Compaq Presarios with 15-inch
monitors _ will be required to go online at least 10 hours a month.
They also must sign a contract agreeing to have the Free-PC
advertising on their screens for three years. After that, they'll
be able to keep the PC free and clear.
</P>
<P>
   Free-PC's targeted ads will appear in a frame surrounding the
work area of Windows. Ads will be shipped on the hard drive of each
computer, so they can be displayed continuously, even when the user
is offline. When the user goes online, ads will be automatically
updated.
</P>
<P>
   Don LaVigne, chief executive of Free-PC, said the new concept
would benefit both consumers and advertisers. ``By providing us
with information about themselves, consumers will not only get a
free computer, it will also allow us to customize their experience
by delivering the most relevant content and advertising directly to
their desktop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the concept ``represents the first real opportunity
for advertisers to reach a mass audience via the computer.'' The
company said advertisers may include Disney, ESPN and Autobytel, an
Internet car-buying service.
</P>
<P>
   Users will get free dial-up Internet access from NetZero, a
Thousand Oaks (Los Angeles County) Internet service provider in
which IdeaLab is an investor.
</P>
<P>
   Free-PC said safeguards will be built into the computers to
prevent users from erasing the programming that displays the free
ads. In addition, the company will be able to monitor online
connections to make sure users are getting the ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect a lot of fraud, and we're going to do our best
to avoid it,'' LaVigne said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expressed cautious optimism about Free-PC's plans.
``It's an interesting experiment, one that represents an
interesting new channel of distribution,'' said Scott Miller of
Dataquest. ``But it's not clear to me that advertising alone can
support this kind of model.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing that's unclear is how giant Microsoft will react
to Free-PC's idea. Historically, the software giant has fought
companies that usurp the real estate of the Windows desktop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
