<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 What AOL's Split Means For Merger  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I am a Netscape Communications shareholder. As you
probably know, the company is being acquired in an exchange of
stock by America Online. The terms announced in November call for
0.45 shares of America Online to be exchanged for each share of
Netscape, with the deal to be completed this spring. However, I
noticed that AOL has since announced that it is splitting its stock
2-for-1 during February. Does that mean the stock I get will be
worth only half as much when the merger takes place?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  No way! That would be pretty outrageous, and
Netscape's board of directors certainly wouldn't stand for it.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange ratio will be adjusted to take the AOL stock split
into account. After the split, you will be entitled to 0.9 of the
new AOL shares for each share of Netscape you hold.
</P>
<P>
   Based on AOL's presplit closing price of $159 yesterday, you
would get $71.55 worth of AOL stock per Netscape share. That is
nearly 80 percent more than the $40 per share the deal was worth
when it was announced less than three months ago. So far, you are a
very fortunate shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, you can't rule out the possibility that AOL will
split its stock again before the merger date. It splits about as
often as rabbits have babies. The coming 2-for-1 split will be
AOL's third in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Trading Process
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've discussed online and other discount brokers several
times in your column. I know that some discount brokers offer
``no-frills'' trades _ that is, less or no telephone contact,
little or no investment advice, etc. But what about the trading
process? Do full-service brokerage houses have the ability to
execute trades more quickly? Or is it pretty much even among
brokers? Also, are there any qualitative differences in terms of
how the trade is accomplished?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: I hesitate to reply to your question just now, because
online brokers are having a lot of technical problems these days,
thanks largely to the tremendous surge in Internet trading.
Investors are sometimes being forced to wait many minutes to gain
access to broker Web sites. Once they gain access, they may
experience delays in getting to the trading page. Sometimes they
get signed off inadvertently instead. When they finally do enter a
trade, there may be still more delays before it goes through.
</P>
<P>
   These problems may or may not be temporary. If they persist,
then online investors who require rapid execution may want to
consider using a full-service broker like Merrill Lynch, or perhaps
an online broker that handles transactions by telephone, such as
Charles Schwab or Fidelity Investments.
</P>
<P>
   When everyone's technology is working just fine, market experts
say there is no significant advantage in speed and quality of
executions from one broker to another. Some brokers that charge
relatively high commissions like to hint vaguely about their
execution advantage. But when pressed to prove it, they back down.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MONEYBAG () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mixed Roth IRAs
</P>
<P>
   Q: Early in 1998, I converted my traditional Individual
Retirement Account to a Roth IRA. Later that year, I made a $2,000
annual contribution to the new Roth account. The broker that
administers the account said this was OK, but I've done some
reading on the subject and I'm not so sure. The rules are
confusing, but I get the impression that I should have opened a
separate account for the $2,000 contribution. Please tell me
whether what I did was legal, and if not, how I can rectify the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Relax. What you did was legal, but it's easy to
understand why you are perplexed. Initially, many financial
institutions _ although not your broker _ required customers to
open separate and distinct Roth accounts for conversions and
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The Roth program took effect at the beginning of 1998, but the
Internal Revenue Service never issued guidelines spelling out how
withdrawals from mixed Roth accounts should be taxed. The financial
institutions that administered Roths feared that mixed accounts
would produce an accounting nightmare, sowing hopeless confusion
among their customers at tax time.
</P>
<P>
   But last summer, Congress passed a law containing a clear set of
guidelines, and now the financial institutions know exactly what to
tell their Roth account-holders in their year-end statements.
</P>
<P>
   Congress established a pecking order for withdrawals from a
mixed Roth account. The first money you withdraw consists of your
contributions to the account, which can amount to no more than
$2,000 per year. Next in line is the money you converted from your
traditional IRA. After that, all that's left is your earnings from
the account.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, withdrawals from Roth accounts are tax-free.
However, they are subject to tax if you withdraw investment gains
within five years after opening the account or before you reach age
591/2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
