PREVIEW THE SWIMSUIT EDITION ON CNNSI.com 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That soft clicking you'll hear at 5 p.m. Tuesday will probably
be the sound of swimsuit enthusiasts all over the 'Net clicking
their mice to configure their monitor to show a swimsuit model as
wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, it's time for Sports Illustrated's annual swimsuit edition.
</P>
<P>
   Before the magazine hits newstands Wednesday, CNNSI.com _ the
24-hour sports site operated jointly by Cable News Network and
Sports Illustrated _ plans to post photo galleries of the models at
its site. As a sneak preview Monday night, the magazine cover was
unveiled on CNNSI.com and Yahoo! conducted a live chat with Rebecca
Stamos, this year's cover model.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second consecutive year that CNNSI.com has posted an
exclusive online preview of the magazine cover.
</P>
<P>
   CNNSI.com also plans an online gallery of more than 100 photos
of this year's models and behind-the-scenes video clips from a
Turner Network Television special on the swimsuit edition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put stuff online that can't fit in the magazine,'' said
Hart Hooton, general manager of CNN/SI Interactive. ``The editors
have about 70,000 photos to go through. So what we do is take some
of the great photos that swimsuit editors don't get in the
magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't all sexist hyperbole. Tuesday, CNNSI.com also plans to
unveil its ``Hits and Mrs'' section, which is a collection of
images of athletes with their spouses. It includes more than 100
photos, some of which are from the magazine and others exclusive to
CNNSI.com.
</P>
<P>
   Swimsuit '99 on CNNSI.com will also link to three previous
online editions of the swimsuit issue, featuring more than 250
additional photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no concern that what we're doing online will
cannibalize what we're doing in the magazine,'' Hooton said.
``Newstand sales are incredibly strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine is an institution and people want to buy it, Hooton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, photography on print is better than photography on the
computer screen,'' he said. ``People who see the online site will
still want to buy the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win-win situation.''
</P>
<P>
   FROM THE HOME OFFICE ...: Sport Magazine's March edition rates
the top 40 sports sites, according to navigation, content, design
and unobtrusive advertising. No. 1 is not ESPN.com or CBS
SportsLine. Total Sports (www.totalsports.com), described by
editors as ``low on glitz; high on substance'' is the top choice.
The rest of the top five: hockey site In The Crease
(www.inthecrease.com), Athlete Daily (www.athletedaily.com),
CNNSI.com and CBS SportsLine. ESPN is No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   FROM THE NBA WITH LOVE: The courting of fans continues for the
NBA. Beginning this week, NBA.com, as part of a league-wide
Valentine's Day promotion, plans to send out 400,000 electronic
Valentine's Day cards to fans worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   GARAGE-CAM: NASCAR Online (www.nascar.com) plans a
behind-the-scenes look at the garage area on race weekends as part
of new features it is debuting for the 41st running of Sunday's
Daytona 500. The site also plans Crew Chief Corner, where the top
crew chiefs explain racing strategies with the help of interactive
elements. Garage Cam will provide updated color images from the
track's garage area ... Texas Motor Speedway
(www.texasmotorspeedway.com) has added a Latest News Section, which
features news releases, digital images taken at the track during
testing and race events.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO PLAY OF THE WEEK, MON: For those soccer fans who continue
to be on a high after the U.S. national team's 3-0 victory against
Germany, try the Jamaica-Puerto Rico game at 6 p.m. tomorrow on
Radio Jamaica (www.radiojamaica.com).
</P>
<P>
   POLL OF THE WEEK: Of 80,187 respondents in an ESPN.com survey,
59.8 percent said Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway should
retire on top after two Super Bowl titles.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
