<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-JOURNALISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE MORE JOURNALISTS ARRESTED IN ZIMBABWE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Two days after President Robert
Mugabe of Zimbabwe went on national television threatening ``very
stern measures'' against the independent press, three more
journalists were arrested Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests come just weeks after the detention and reported
torture of two journalists for writing about an alleged coup plot
within the military.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's arrests began when detectives took Grace Kwinje from
the offices of the weekly Zimbabwe Mirror, apparently to question
her about an article she wrote in October on the return of bodies
from Congo. Some 8,000 Zimbabwean troops are there, backing
President Laurent Kabila in his fight against rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kwinje's article described how the family of one Zimbabwean
soldier had been given only his head to bury. The military denied
the report.
</P>
<P>
   Later, police returned to The Mirror and arrested the news
editor, Fernando Goncalves, and another editor, Farai Mungazi.
</P>
<P>
   The two journalists arrested last month, Mark Chavunduka and Ray
Choto from The Sunday Standard, said they were stripped, beaten and
tortured with electric shocks before they were finally released.
The paper obtained a court order for their release, but the
military repeatedly ignored it.
</P>
<P>
   The episode set off an outcry among human rights advocates and
journalists. On Jan. 25, three members of the Supreme Court wrote
Mugabe asking him to ``confirm that the rule of law is accepted as
a necessary ingredient of a democratic Zimbabwe.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter also asked that he confirm that the army had no power
to arrest civilians and that the government would not tolerate
torture, and to reassure the judiciary that the government would
act in accordance with Zimbabwe's constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Mugabe took to the airwaves Saturday night and attacked
the ``impudence'' of the judiciary. He suggested that the members
of the Supreme Court resign, attacked independent newspapers and
warned of stern measures against ``acts of sabotage'' by opponents.
</P>
</TEXT>
