<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT EXECUTIVE DROPS FEW BOMBS IN TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the Microsoft trial Monday, the biggest news was
what did not happen: For the first time since the company began
presenting its defense against federal antitrust charges last
month, a major company witness did not leave the courtroom with his
head on a platter.
</P>
<P>
   All through the government's presentation of its case against
the Microsoft Corp. last year, company executives counseled
patience. When their time came, they promised, they would present a
robust, effective defense.
</P>
<P>
   But David Boies, the government's lead trial lawyer, has managed
to force the first three significant Microsoft witnesses to make
damaging statements or to admit embarrassing mistakes, throwing
serious credibility questions before Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson,
who is hearing the case without a jury.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's witness _ William Poole, senior director of business
development for the company's Windows operating system _ managed to
hold his own, though Boies did leave him mumbling and stammering
and even backpedaling a few times.
</P>
<P>
   When Poole returns on Tuesday, he will try to hold his ground
while Boies tries to push him back even further.
</P>
<P>
   Poole oversaw the negotiation of contracts in which Microsoft
required Internet companies to limit business dealings with the
Netscape Communications Corp., maker of Navigator, the Web browser
that is the chief competitor to Microsoft's Internet Explorer
browser. In exchange, Microsoft awarded the companies advertising
space on Windows' opening desktop screen.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning, Poole acknowledged that Microsoft had
estimated in 1996 that it could earn about $100 million a year by
selling that advertising space but decided to charge nothing.
Instead, the companies had to sign binding contracts to promote
Internet Explorer and to cease all significant dealings with
Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Poole said one major company, Intuit Inc., maker of the popular
personal finance program Quicken, had approached Microsoft ``and
asked us to let them use our browser'' instead of Netscape's.
Quicken uses links to Web pages for many of its services.
</P>
<P>
   But that testimony contradicted earlier testimony of Intuit's
chief executive, William H. Harris. And Boies displayed an internal
Microsoft e-mail from 1996 that told another story.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Bill Gates, Microsoft's chairman, summarized for Brad
Chase, another senior executive, a conversation with Intuit's
chairman at the time, Scott Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was quite frank with him that if he had a favor we could do
for him that would cost us something like $1 million, to do that in
return for switching browsers in the next few months, I would be
open to doing that,'' Gates wrote. But Cook was reticent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, Chase reported back to Gates: ``I talked to
them again today. I just don't think they are prepared to jump this
hurdle. I suggested that at least they ship both browsers.''
</P>
<P>
   Poole said he had never seen the e-mail exchange, even though it
was entered into evidence in the trial many weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your lawyers didn't show this to you?'' Boies asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember seeing it,'' Poole said.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokesman later said the company had issued a new
and improved version of Internet Explorer between the time Gates
negotiated with Intuit and when Poole worked out a contract.
</P>
<P>
   With some help from the judge, Boies also got Poole to admit
that the restrictive contracts with Intuit and others were not
standard practices for the company or the industry, as Poole had
asserted in his direct, written testimony.
</P>
<P>
   After Boies repeatedly posed the question, only to get rambling
off-point responses, Jackson finally interrupted, shaking his head
as Poole set off again, saying: ``No, No, No. Try to answer, Mr.
Poole. Yes, no or I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies was in the middle of asking his final question as court
ended for the day, challenging Poole's assertion that ``only 4.7
percent of users surveyed stated that they first became aware of a
Web site that they now frequently visit through a pre-configured
browser setting or start page.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is important because Microsoft and Netscape both ship
their browsers with links already pre-loaded to important,
money-earning Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson adjourned court before Poole could find the reference he
needed in the survey data.
</P>
<P>
   Poole will complete his testimony on Tuesday. The next witness,
Cameron Myhrvold, a Microsoft vice president in the Internet
Customer Unit division, stated in written testimony that Netscape
has thrived despite competition from Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' Myhrvold wrote, ``Microsoft has acted as a
pro-competitive force in restoring competition'' in the browser
business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
