<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Todd Oldham said Monday that he had sold his
trademark to Jones Apparel Group, making him perhaps the only
designer of his generation to set up a viable structure that could
position his signature as a major brand in the next millennium. The
purchase price was not disclosed, but Oldham will receive income
based on the profitability of his labels.
</P>
<P>
   Jones Apparel, a public company and one of Seventh Avenue's most
successful businesses, produces Todd Oldham jeans and two of Ralph
Lauren's lower-priced collections, Polo Ralph Lauren jeans and
Lauren by Ralph Lauren, all under license. The company took over
the Todd Oldham jeans business last year when it purchased Sun
Apparel, which had held the license.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new agreement, Jones Apparel will have the right to
use the Oldham name for all fashions and fragrances for men and
women worldwide. It will also get the designer's two stores, one in
SoHo, the other in South Beach, Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Oldham, through his design studio, will oversee creative aspects
for the brand, from design to advertising. He retains ownership of
his name for all other endeavors, like architecture, film, video
direction and interior design, all of which he has already been
involved in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so many other interests,'' Oldham said. ``I don't want
to be more involved than I am, working on designing. We'll continue
to supply design in all the areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Designers who followed Halston were loathe to give up their
names after Halston saw his cachet drop precipitously when he sold
his name to the mass market. Rather than being forlorn about
selling his signature, Oldham says that doing so will let him have
the kind of market reach he has always wanted. ``You can't ever do
this alone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones Apparel, which is better known for collections that cut
with the dull edge of the fashion knife, like Jones New York and
Lauren, plans to go after a younger crowd, said Eric Rothfeld, the
president of the company's Sun Apparel division. ``Our focus is to
build Todd Oldham Jeans into a mega brand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal may well give Oldham the wherewithal to reintroduce his
top line, which he closed last year. But he said that that was
unlikely. ``I don't ever go back,'' he said. ``When it's done, it's
done.''
</P>
<P>
   ACTRESS TO TOUT MEN'S WEAR
</P>
<P>
   There may be no more appropriate time to announce a men's-wear
advertisement featuring a woman than this week, when the combined
New York men's and women's shows commence. Mondo di Marco, an
Italian men's-wear company, has signed the actress Ellen Barkin to
appear in print advertisements for its fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements, to be photographed next month, will be
created by the Laspata/DeCaro Studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately when it was brought to our attention, we had
visions of sexiness, of someone everybody knows, someone everybody
likes,'' Warren Katz, the president of Mondo Inc., said, referring
to Ms. Barkin's appropriateness for a men's-wear promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisements, which will include a male model, may provide a
nice segue into Mondo's first foray into women's wear, scheduled to
be in stores in the fall. Ms. Barkin will not wear Mondo women's
clothing in the ads, however, because the collection will not be
ready in time for photography, Katz said. In fact, Katz could not
say whether Ms. Barkin, known for her steamy portrayals in movies
like ``Sea of Love,'' would be wearing anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``She may not be wearing much,'' Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   With Ms. Barkin on board, the campaign may also help raise
Mondo's low profile. The company last year had about $60 million in
worldwide sales, Katz said, and is carried in stores like
Bloomingdale's and Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are to expand the company's advertising beyond the usual
men's magazines to include publications like Vanity Fair and In
Style. ``We've been advertising in men's magazines a lot, and I
never thought we got the recognition we deserved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
