<HEADLINE>
FOR THE EYES, COOL GEOMETRY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Oversized glasses, like oversize jewelry, look rather
passe. Chic men and women today tend to favor small frames not only
for reading, but also for all corrective lenses and for tinted
glasses (except, of course, when they are out in bright sunlight
and require maximum protection).
</P>
<P>
   Oval shapes had their moment. Now, the coolest people choose
horizontal rectangles and other geometric shapes that just cover
the eyes, baring the brows, says Robert Marc, who owns five
fashionable optical stores in Manhattan. The lines he carries
include Lunor, Proksch and Retro Specs. The glasses may be rimless
or have very thin frames of gold or platinum or of colored acetate
or buffalo horn. The buffalo horn comes in shades from pale blond
to almost black, while the acetate can be a solid color or subtly
layered with a second tone. Lenses may be tinted many colors,
including cobalt, yellow, rose, olive, mint, orange or violet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 2127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
