<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6860 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT     02-08 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HMOS AGREE TO HELP PAY MEMBERS' DRUG TRIAL COSTS
</P>
<P>
   After years of resistance, health maintenance organizations have
agreed to help pay the costs of care for members who enroll in
clinical trials evaluating new drugs and medical procedures. As a
result, thousands of patients could receive promising new
treatments they were denied in the past. The agreement was
negotiated over the last year by the National Institutes of Health
and the American Association of Health Plans, the trade group of
the managed care industry, but has not yet been announced.
</P>
<P>
   SELLING MUSIC VIA THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Major recording companies will begin marketing albums as digital
information transmitted over the Internet. A new system to be
tested this spring is intended to sell authorized recordings in a
medium where most of the music now circulates for free.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY SHARES REBOUND
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices were mixed as bellwether technology issues such as
Microsoft and Intel rebounded after falling last week, but
blue-chip securities and shares in small companies, including
Internet stocks, slid in value. Traders and analysts said the
market's performance was impressive in light of the sharp run-up in
prices since October and several new pressures that could lead to a
sharp sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices snapped a five-day decline, ending little changed
ahead of a Treasury refunding auction. The 30-year bond yield fell
to 5.34 percent from 5.35.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER YEAR 2000 PROBLEM
</P>
<P>
   Year 2000 project managers and other authorities are warning
that Americans fearing the worst may end up inflicting more serious
damage on themselves, their neighbors and the economy than anything
their computers do. Planning experts say those scenarios could
include bank runs, hoarding of food and gasoline, fires caused by
misuse of newly acquired wood stoves and generators and a rise in
gun violence stemming from the surge in firearm sales to those
fearing civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA RESTRAINS AIRLINE GROWTH
</P>
<P>
   Chinese authorities asked suppliers of commercial aircraft to
delay deliveries to the nation's airlines, which have been
expanding aggressively. Fare wars and half-empty flights, unknown
in China until recently, are now common among China's two-dozen
airlines. It now seems unlikely that any new orders will be made
this year _ bad news for Boeing and Airbus, which compete for
China's business.
</P>
<P>
   Shandong International Power Development shelved a $285 million
initial public offering, the third major Chinese company in a month
to call off an overseas stock sale.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE COMPANIES TALK WITH AT&AMP;T
</P>
<P>
   Mediaone Group, Comcast and Cox Communications, the third-
through fifth-largest cable providers in the United States, joined
forces in talks with AT&AMP;T regarding local telephone-service
joint-ventures.
</P>
<P>
   3 EXCHANGES PLAN VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange, the Bourse in Paris and the
Singapore International Monetary Exchange signed an agreement that
would allow futures and options to be traded as part of a global
electronic network that would operate around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   BMW SHARES RISE DESPITE TURMOIL
</P>
<P>
   Shares of BMW rose 8.6 percent on the possibility of a sale,
despite a bitter board room dispute over the company's strategy
that led to the ouster of BMW's top two executives and losses at
its Rover subsidiary. Ignoring speculation that it would be taken
over by a larger rival, the company said again that it intended to
stay independent.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RULES FOR INTERNET ADDRESSES
</P>
<P>
   Companies wanting a piece of the lucrative business of issuing
Internet addresses will need at least $100,000 in the bank,
$500,000 in liability insurance and a proven computer
infrastructure, under requirements proposed by the nonprofit
corporation that has been tapped to take over administration of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHENED AUDIT RULES PROPOSED
</P>
<P>
   A panel created by the leading stock exchanges and markets
recommended rules that would strengthen the role of audit
committees at public companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
