<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING THE NORTH BEACH BEAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bear that resides in San Francisco's Marini Plaza, the
triangular park at Columbus Avenue and Union Street, has not gone
to Florida for the winter. It's recovering from an act of nature
and an act of vandals, and it's being restored deliberately slowly
by conservator  &UR; Genevieve Baird &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture, made of cast metal with a concrete interior,
received a nasty concussion when a tree limb fell on it; shortly
thereafter, its feet were messed up when vandals ripped it from its
concrete pedestal and threw its in the plaza pool.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the pace of Baird's work is that _ despite the
preponderance of gold leaf elsewhere in town _ the city monuments
fund doesn't have the estimated $5,000 for the repair. Baird, who
has worked closely before with the Art Commission's monuments
expert,  &UR; Debra Lehane &LR; , agreed to work on the job between other
jobs until the community came up with the money. Lehane drove the
bear to the conservator's workshop in the foothills of the Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   Jars placed in North Beach stores and bars have so far collected
$1,000, including a $100 bill left in one jar after the makers of
``EDtv'' used the jar as a prop. Another $1,000 was collected at a
fund-raiser at Little City in January. Several restaurateurs have
kicked in, but community organizers are disappointed that the most
obvious ones have not.
</P>
<P>
   The Repair the Bear Committee is at 722 Filbert Street &LR; ., San
Francisco, Calif. 94133.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10TH ANNIVERSARY OF THE RUSHDIE FATWA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after the publication of his ``Satanic Verses,'' and
the order from  &UR; Ayatollah Khomeini &LR;  to kill him,  &UR; Salman &LR; 
 &UR; Rushdie &LR;  describes the threat, now disavowed by the Iranian
government, ``as a spear in the stomach which somehow doesn't kill
but turns and twists.''
</P>
<P>
   In an essay in the New Yorker, Rushdie writes of a ``sense of
violation'' that lingers. He also said that his writing has
changed, &LR;  and that his most recent books ``are my funniest. The
attacks have evidently improved my sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   That new lightness wasn't much in evidence in a Rushdie story
just published in India Today, a few days after the author was
granted a visa to return to his native country. Turning from
controversial remarks about Muslims, he made controversial remarks
about Christians. Noting that a commemoration on January 1 ``will
put Jesus in the odd position of having two birthdays in the space
of a week,'' he goes on to criticize the proponents of ``faux
Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hardline but essentially counterfeit Christian `values' have
been the driving force behind the rabidly partisan attack by U.S.
Republicans'' on  &UR; President Clinton &LR; , he wrote. ``Down into the
dirt we tumble, in the name of the gentle Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIGARETTES AND COFFEE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Postal Service has altered the image of  &UR; Jackson &LR; 
 &UR; Pollock &LR;  on its new 33-cent stamp, removing the cigarette that was
dangling from the artist's mouth in the photo on which the stamp is
based. The Postal Service's Bill Paul explained to Personals that
the photo was only inspiration for the stamp image and that the
Postal Service has ``no stated philosophy'' on smoking. But the
Pollock image is the second deliberately made smoke-free: a
cigarette was removed from musician  &UR; Robert &LR; 
 &UR; Johnson &LR; 's mouth five years ago. The 20-cent FDR stamp issued in
1982 pictured him with cigarette in holder.
</P>
<P>
   _ The British royal family has withdrawn its 122-year-old seal
of approval from Gallaher Ltd., the company that makes Benson and
Hedges cigarettes. A palace spokesman said royal warrants are
rescinded if the product is no longer used, but the director of
Action on Smoking and Health, a British group, called the
withdrawal ``an important symbolic breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   _ How many megacorporations can be crammed into one item?
Starbucks and Time Inc., a subsidiary of Time Warner, have
announced the creation of Joe, a magazine that will ``reflect the
thought-provoking conversations of the coffeehouse tradition.'' A
preliminary press release says ``General Motors has made a major
commitment to all three issues in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really inspired by wannabe gangsters. Guys who go to
malls and get the gangsta rap clothes. Guys on `Ricki Lake' who
won't listen to their moms.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dexter Holland of the band Offspring, telling Spin magazine
about the group's hit ``Pretty Fly (For a White Guy cq).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
