<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6867 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      02-08 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Exit23b's E-Mail Promise of Free Stock Sounds Like a Dead End  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
You get what you pay for.
</P>
<P>
   So don't be surprised if e-mail spam promising free shares of an
Internet stock you never heard of doesn't materialize into riches
beyond your wildest digital dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you are among the scores of computer users who have
received unsolicited e-mails promoting Exit23b, a Web page at
 &LR; www.exit23b.com  &LR; whose seemingly invisible parent company intends
on going public.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly isn't the first time free stock has been promoted
via the World Wide Wait, but this particular electronic-mail offer
is multiplying faster than rabbits.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the half-dozen or so versions that have crossed our
screens at Street Smarts, this alleged Exit23b cyberstock giveaway
has been disseminated as far as Boston, Chicago and Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   What appears to be giving this e-mail a creepy Amway-like life
of its own is the mere mention of the search directory Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   One of the e-mail letters goes like this:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  For those of you who follow stocks, Yahoo (YHOO) eclipsed &LR; 
 &LR; $400 a share a few weeks ago. When this company was just &LR; 
 &LR; starting out, they gave away stock as a promotional item.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Nice to have been a part of that, right? Well here's your &LR; 
 &LR; chance because I'm letting you in on the scoop. The new company &LR; 
 &LR; is ..Exit23b.. (and) they will be going public in March. They &LR; 
 &LR; will be an online store for electronics, interactive games, &LR; 
 &LR; music and videos. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``To celebrate their launch, (Exit23b) is giving away &LR; 
 &LR; 100,000 shares of their pre-IPO (to be split among) 10 lucky &LR; 
 &LR; winners _ 10,000 shares each. You will receive no junk mail, &LR; 
 &LR; just an announcement of the site launch with the drawing rules &LR; 
 &LR; and regulations. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There is much that is troublesome about this e-mail beyond its
rather poorly written and incomplete text. The most bothersome of
which is the fact that it's spreading false information.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET09 (93125 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``We never, ever gave away free shares of stock,'' says Yahoo
Chief Financial Officer Gary Valenzuela.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela would not comment on what actions the company might
take in response to the apparently fraudulent use of Yahoo's name.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that very sticky wicket aside, is this a legitimate
offer? Is there a real company behind the Exit23b Web site?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? But judging by a cursory look at the available
evidence, this operation smells awfully foul. First of all, the Web
page provides very little information about Exit23b and what the
people behind the page intend to do with the names and e-mail
addresses that it is has been amassing.
</P>
<P>
   It states that Exit23b will launch some kind of operation in
March, and it describes how people who register for the chance to
win free stock get credit for an additional entry each time they
refer someone else to the site. (And that explains why this offer
has proliferated like a chain letter.)
</P>
<P>
   According to Internic.com, an Internet domain registrar, Exit23b
is headquartered in Redmond, Wash. Telephone calls to the number
listed by Internic were answered by a recording, which identified
itself as Exit23b but would not accept recorded messages.
</P>
<P>
   There is no company registered with the Washington secretary of
state with the name Exit23b. Of course, a company registered with a
different name could operate a Web site called Exit23b. But what
kind of business is this anyway if it can't be readily found?
</P>
<P>
   If that isn't persuasive enough to stay away, it sounds by its
own company description as if Exit23b has picked the wrong niche.
The last time I checked, a few major booksellers were duking it out
with online music-sellers in this very crowded retailing segment.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of STREET09 (93125 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Finally, what kind of company gives stock away? Probably not one
worth owning.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the record, it is not necessarily illegal to give
away stock for free over the Internet. A Securities and Exchange
Commission spokesman would not comment on the legitimacy of Exit23b
or whether it is investigating the stock offer. However, he
provided copies of published letters from the SEC to companies that
wanted to give away free securities.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of those letters indicated that issuing securities
``in consideration of a person's registration on or visit to an
issuer's Internet site'' would constitute a sale under SEC laws.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, those shares essentially are being sold, which
seems to mean that Exit23b would need to meet all regulatory
requirements for a public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Something tells us this isn't likely to happen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; UNVEILED &LR; : It's official.
</P>
<P>
   W.R. Hambrecht, the new investment bank founded by financier
Bill Hambrecht, is open for business.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's electronic auction for securities offerings, OpenIPO,
has begun accepting bids for its first initial public offering:
Ravenswood Winery of Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   As first reported in Street Smarts, the online underwriter wants
to level the playing field by making IPOs accessible to a wider
group of investors via the Internet. Using a Dutch auction system,
Hambrecht also hopes that companies going public will fetch
offering prices closer to share prices paid on the open market,
says W.R. Hambrecht President Ian Zwicker, who once helped his new
boss build Hambrecht &AMP; Quist into a full-service investment bank
and brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's different, of course, is that we price and allocate
differently than anyone before,'' says Zwicker, who left Donaldson
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette to join W.R. Hambrecht.
</P>
<P>
   Zwicker noted that Wall Street's established investment banks
aren't going to take lightly this latest challenge to their clubby
system. ``They're not going to cede market share willingly,''
Zwicker says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
