<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6869 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOFA-SFCHRON &LR;      02-08 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Former BofA Exec Says Bank Does Back Women  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
One of the seven top female executives who quit BankAmerica after
North Carolina's NationsBank took it over said the new bank is
serious about promoting women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   In the first public comment by one of the seven senior women who
left, Mary Wikstrom, the former executive vice president who ran
BofA's telephone service centers, praised the new bank for a new
diversity initiative. The plan includes several measures Wikstrom
suggested before she resigned in December.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``The bank quite frankly is moving on the path I, as well as
other people, recommended,'' Wikstrom said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure two months ago that six of BofA's top 10 female
executives quit after NationsBank bought the bank touched off a
furor in California. The departures included Vice Chairman Kathleen
Burke, who was the bank's human resources chief and highest-ranking
woman.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco and state officials demanded investigations and
asked pointedly whether the mass exodus was caused by NationsBank
bias against women.
</P>
<P>
   Wikstrom thought otherwise. In a memo obtained by The Chronicle,
she described the resignations of the six top-ranking BofA women as
``an unintended situation,'' not the result of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Wikstrom sent the memo to Kenneth Lewis, the bank's No.2
executive, December 10, a week after a Chronicle story disclosed
the departures of senior women.
</P>
<P>
   In the memo, Wikstrom proposed a four-point program to make sure
women rose to positions of power, eventually filling the vacuum
created by the departures.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after drafting her proposal, Wikstrom herself resigned,
becoming the seventh top-level woman to leave.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Wikstrom, who was offered a job combining the two banks'
telephone operations, said she left for personal reasons. Wikstrom
was eligible for a severance package that included more than a year
of salary and bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the right time for me to make a career switch,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of BOFA09 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  In her memo, Wikstrom wrote that she wanted to shift attention
away from press coverage of the female executive departures to what
could be done to fix the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have a `problem' in terms of the organization's
sincere support of ... promoting our female management talent. What
we have is ... an unintended situation that emerged as a result of
management selection decisions. Those decisions produced an
unfortunate result _ a reduction in ... female line senior managers
by 80 percent. It is our problem. We intend to remedy it,'' she
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Wikstrom's proposal called on the bank to fill 30 percent of its
top management slots with women within two years, create a
diversity task force reporting to Chief Executive Officer Hugh
McColl, set specific women and minority hiring goals for all senior
managers and build ties to outside women's advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, the bank has adopted a diversity plan
incorporating several of Wikstrom's ideas.
</P>
<P>
   BofA Chairman and CEO McColl set up a council chaired by
Northern California retail banking chief Barbara Desoer to oversee
the bank's programs for promoting women and minorities. And he
instructed the bank's top executives to develop plans in each of
their business units for advancing women and minorities to
senior-level jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The bank rejected Wikstrom's two-year, 30-percent target for
female managers companywide, though it committed itself to
year-over-year increases in the percentages of top jobs held by
those groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the points that Mary articulated are up and running in
the new company,'' said Lorraine Stimmel, who heads BofA's
diversity programs.
</P>
<P>
   Desoer, the new head of the bank's diversity council, was one of
three top women at the old BofA to stay with the bank after
NationsBank took over.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Desoer said the departures of her female
colleagues reflected individual decisions and didn't reflect
discrimination by NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   ``My perception was the former NationsBank team was more diverse
than the old BofA,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of BOFA09 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  BofA's top management included 10 women and 34 men when
NationsBank bought the bank and took its name in September. The new
bank won't say how many of the men quit, but the proportion is
apparently lower than the seven of 10 women who left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
