<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-BOMBINGS-NYT &LR;      02-08 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BOMBINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DENIES BAIL TO SUSPECT IN EMBASSY BOMBINGS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Texas)  
(See also SUDAN-BOMBING) (sw) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge in Manhattan refused on Monday to
grant bail to a suspect in the investigation of the U.S. Embassy
bombings in Africa in August, finding that prosecutors had made
``an overwhelming case'' that the man was dangerous and might flee
if released on bond.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Wadih el Hage, a naturalized American citizen, has
been described by the authorities as the former personal secretary
to Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile believed by the government to
be behind the deadly attacks.
</P>
<P>
   El Hage, 38, who last lived in Arlington, Texas, has been
charged with conspiracy to kill Americans abroad and with lying to
government investigators. El Hage is imprisoned in the Metropolitan
Correctional Center.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, el Hage's lawyer, Bruce McIntyre, told Judge Leonard
B. Sand of Federal District Court in Manhattan that his client was
a devout family man who ``categorically denies'' being a member of
any terrorism group. He said that el Hage had worked only as a
secretary in bin Laden's legitimate commercial enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been any tie to show that el Hage had anything
to do with any violence,'' McIntyre said, ``or any of the other
crimes which have been attributed to bin Laden.''
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors cited evidence that el Hage was a critical
operative in the terrorist conspiracy who was able to travel freely
with an American passport. They said he used codes to communicate
with suspected bombers and lied to agents from the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short, Your Honor, el Hage has served as a front man for
the bin Laden organization for years,'' Patrick J. Fitzgerald, a
federal prosecutor, told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, both sides offered new details about el Hage
and the government's investigation into bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre revealed that his client had come to the United States
in 1997 _ about a year before the bombings in Tanzania and Kenya _
after he was warned by the FBI in Africa that he or his family
might be in danger.
</P>
<P>
   The government disagreed with part of that account. But outside
court, McIntyre said el Hage had been warned by the FBI that he
might be in danger because of his knowledge of bin Laden's
enterprises, which if revealed could harm bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Disputing the defense arguments, Fitzgerald gave new details
that he said linked el Hage to ``both violence and violent
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald said that el Hage admitted to investigators that he
had met about 10 years ago with Sheik Omar Abdel Rahman, the
Egyptian cleric who is serving a life prison term for his
conviction in 1995 in a conspiracy to blow up the United Nations
and other New York City landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald also publicly asserted for the first time that there
was a link between bin Laden and a Muslim leader, Moataz Al-Hallak
of Arlington, Texas, who has been described as a supporter of el
Hage. Last week, McIntyre told Sand that his client wanted to call
Al-Hallak, the imam at the Islamic Society of Arlington, the mosque
where el Hage was a member.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Fitzgerald portrayed Al-Hallak as more than a
religious leader. ``Moataz Al-Hallak has served as a contact
between members of the bin Laden organization,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Without elaborating, Fitzgerald said, ``This is a case about
murder and conspiracy to murder, not about religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Hallak, reached by phone on Monday night, said he had no idea
what the prosecutor was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very strange,'' he said, reiterating what he said in
an interview last week, that his mosque is educational and
religious and that he condemns violence.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre said after the hearing that he was disappointed in the
judge's denial of bail, and would continue to seek ``avenues of
redress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
