<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6879 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-PALESTINIANS-N     02-08 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-PALESTINIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MANY ON WEST BANK, RESENTMENTS LINGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: JORDAN-FUNERAL, JORDAN-SCENE,
JORDAN-CLINTON) 
(af) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Palestinian men chatting in the clothing store
Monday on East Jerusalem's main shopping thoroughfare were no fans
of King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, a store displayed a black-bordered picture of
the late monarch. Another shopkeeper put out a large framed picture
of the king. But there wasn't much sympathy for him in the clothing
shop.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men, when asked about feelings, said, ``It would be
better if we didn't say anything.'' Still, the conversation rambled
on and resentment sputtered out.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has he done for his people?,'' asked another man, who
said he had relatives in Jordan and refused to be named.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many can barely afford bread, and he sent his Bedouin troops
against them when they protested. He sold out the West Bank to the
Israelis in the 1967 war. He comforted Israeli parents whose girls
were killed by a Jordanian soldier, but did he ever visit
Palestinians who lost children in the intifada? Like all Arab
leaders he looked out for himself, and he did the bidding of the
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   In another store, Fayez Natsheh said he would never forget how
the king unleashed his army against PLO guerrillas in Jordan in
1970, killing hundreds and driving them out of his kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``History can't be erased,'' Natsheh said.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat saluted the king Monday as his body lay in state,
but conversations with ordinary Palestinians showed mixed feelings
toward the monarch, who had a long and checkered relationship with
the Palestinian national movement.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan lost the West Bank in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war, and for
decades afterward, Jordan and the PLO competed for influence in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   For a long while the king cultivated religious and
administrative links to the territory. Tracing his descent from the
prophet Muhammad, he saw himself as the guardian of the Islamic
holy places in East Jerusalem. He paid salaries to religious
functionaries there and other civil servants in the West Bank, and
supported newspapers and institutions sympathetic to his rule.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1988, after the outbreak of the Palestinian uprising and
in recognition of Palestinian claims to the West Bank, King Hussein
formally cut administrative and legal ties to the territory, and
stopped payments to civil servants.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he relinquished his claim to the territory and
consistently supported Palestinian demands for an independent state
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Yet strong links remain between both banks of the Jordan. Many
people in the West Bank have relatives in Jordan, where
Palestinians form the majority of the population. The king financed
the re-gilding of the Dome of the Rock shrine in Jerusalem's Old
City in 1994, and his peace agreement with Israel ensures that
Jordan's role as protector of Muslim holy places in Jerusalem will
be given ``high priority'' in any agreement with the Palestinians
on the future of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues to be negotiated between Israel and the
Palestinians, such as water, refugees and borders are considered
vital national interests in Jordan, and it is certain to seek a
role in any future agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials say that they expect continued strong
support for their cause from King Abdullah, the new monarch,
reflecting a continuity of policy that transcends individual
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jordan is a state of institutions,'' said Tayeb Abdel Rahim, a
close aide to Arafat. ``The relations between Jordan and the
Palestinian Authority are solid and will remain stable. We are one
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the officials concede that the commanding authority of King
Hussein will be sorely lacking in the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   That sense of loss was evident Monday in the Palestinian press,
which reported sympathetically on the death. ``We have lost a
guide,'' said the Al Quds newspaper in an editorial.
</P>
<P>
   As he read over a newspaper down the street, Iyad al-Qaisi, a
Palestinian, said that the Palestinians' troubled history with King
Hussein was now a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone dies all that is forgotten,'' he said. ``God have
mercy on him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
