<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 2/08/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- NY-FASHION-2, 2-08 -- John
Bartlett, right, works with model Michael Harder as stylist George
Cortina looks on at left. Designers will be showing their autumn
collections this week and next in New York's Bryant park. (Marilynn
K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- NY-FASHION, 2-08 -- Oscar de
la Renta, the fashion designer, puts the finishing touches on a
dress. Designers will be showing their autumn collections this week
and next in New York's Bryant park. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) SAVANNAH, Ga. -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- BLACK-DOCTOR, 2-08 --
Dr. Debbie Phoenix-Davis talks with her patient Mary Gray during an
office visit last month. Dr. Phoenix-Davis is a pioneer in the
practice of minority and indigent medicine. She works in a
neighborhood that like many other poor urban and rural communities,
is short of physicians, black or white. (Alan Hawes/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) SPOKANE, Washington -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- MILLENIUM-PANIC,
2-08 -- Larry Shook, left, and Judy Laddon have stocked a variety
of canned foods in the basement of their home in preparation for
any problems caused by the Y2K millenium bug. A chorus of
regulators, Year 2000 project managers and other authorities are
warning that Americans fearing for the worst when the year comes up
may end up inflicting more serious damage on themselves, their
neighbors and the economy than anything the computers do. (Jeff T.
Green/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) TRENTON, N.J. -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- NJ-WHITMAN, 2-08 --
Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey greets a supporter before
returning to her office after a news conference on Monday to
discuss her recent leg injury. Heading off to ski after attending
the annual meeting of the World Economic Forum in Davos,
Switzerland, Whitman said she wiped out while skiing from sunlight
to darkness in zero-degree weather a week ago Sunday ending up with
a broken leg. (Laura Pendrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- NY-DOG-SHOW, 2-08 -- Bay
Breeze Maestro, a Standard Poodle, gets groomed by her co-owner
Lynn Synder before competion at the Westminster Dog Show on Monday.
There were 2,500 dogs entered in competition this year. (Keith
Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- MCGWIRE-BALL, 2-08 -- Todd
McFarlane, a Canadian businessman who produces comic books and
heavy-metal magazines, holds Mark McGwire's record-breaking 70th
home run baseball on Monday. Ending speculation as to the buyers
identity, McFarlane stood before a crush of cameras in a Manhattan
hotel and said that had delayed his announcement several days ago
due to tax and security issues surrounding his $3 million purchase.
(Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) ASSYNT, Scotland -- Feb. 8, 1999 --
SCOTLAND-CLEARANCES-2, 2-08 -- In Assynt in the Scottish Highlands,
Allan MacRae banded farmers together to buy the land. The first
order of business of the new Scottish Parliament in May will be
reform of the country's ancient land-holding system. (Jonathan
Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) ASSYNT, Scotland -- Feb. 8, 1999 --
SCOTLAND-CLEARANCES-1, 2-08 -- A crofter's cottage in Assynt in the
Scottish Highlands, where farmers banded together to buy the land.
The first order of business of the new Scottish Parliament in May
will be reform of the country's ancient land-holding system.
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) OXFORD, England-- Feb. 8, 1999 -- OBIT-MURDOCH, 2-08 --
Iris Murdoch at her home last December. Murdoch, one of the
greatest British novelists of the 20th century, died Monday at the
age of 79, her husband said. Murdoch, who had been suffering from
Alzheimer's Disease for the past five years, died in a nursing home
in the central English city of Oxford. (Jonathan Player/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) SARASOTA, Fla. -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- CIRCUS-ONE-RING-2,
2-08 -- The clown David Larible, one of the stars of the new
one-ring show, ``Barnum's Kaleidoscape.'' In a parking lot at the
Sarasota Fairgrounds here, flameproof polyvinyl has superseded
canvas. Traditional circus fare like popcorn and cotton candy will
be supplemented by designer sandwiches and cappuccino. And the show
will be performed in but one 38-foot-wide circus ring. (Todd
Anderson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SARASOTA, Fla. -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- CIRCUS-ONE-RING-1,
2-08 -- The new tent created for ``Barnum's Kaleidoscape.'' Here in
the city that was its winter home from 1927 to 1959, the Ringling
Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus has raised its tent for the
first time in 42 years. (Todd Anderson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) AMHERST, Mass. -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- WIDEMAN-RETRIAL, 2-08
-- Robert Wideman in his home during a recent interview. Wideman
was the street tough who embodied the cycle of violence that claims
many young black males. At 25, Wideman was imprisoned for life
without parole after an accomplice fired a fatal shot in a failed
street swindle. The crime became one of the enduring literary
images of black America as the subject of an acclaimed book,
``Brothers &AMP; Keepers,'' by Wideman's brother, John Edgar Wideman.
(George Ruhe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- NY-TRASH-ART, 2-08 -- Andrew
Foster's portrait at the Museum of the City of New York. The
painting - worn, punctured and loose on its stretcher - had been
rescued six months earlier from a trash pile by John W. Nichols,
the director of museum services for the American Federation of the
Arts, a nonprofit group that organizes art exhibitions. But when
Foster was last seen, in July 1997, he was homeless. (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- IMPEACH-SCENE-2, 2-08 --
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott heads toward the senate chamber
on Monday accompanied by Elizabeth Letchworth, the senate majority
secretary. Both sides in President Clinton's impeachment trial
began their final arguments on Monday. Senators said they hoped to
wrap up the trial by the end of the week. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- IMPEACH-SCENE-3, 2-08 --
Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, center, is prepared for a
television interview before the start of Monday afternoon's session
of the impeachment trial of President Clinton. Both sides in
Clinton's impeachment trial began their final arguments on Monday.
Senators said they hoped to wrap up the trial by the end of the
week. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- SCI-HERBS, 2-08 -- Is it soup
yet? Hain's familiar paper-wrapped metal cylinder actually contains
``herbal supplement.'' (Igor Vishnyakov/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SOUTH PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Feb. 8, 1999 --
SCI-HERBS-DRUGS, 2-08 -- John Kovarik's insurance company refused
to pay for a prescription drug to treat a life-threatening illness
because the drug is also available over the counter as a
supplement. ``I was flabbergasted,'' says Kovarik, a lawyer in
South Palm Beach suffering from a genetic disorder known as
Wilson's disease. (Susan Greenwood/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- SCI-FITNESS-PLAY, 2-08 --
Deborah Leipzig combines play with getting in shape on a trampoline
during the recess exercise class at a Crunch Fitness club in New
York. Other fitness clubs around the country are offering similar
kinds of classes, hoping that this trend of play as exercise can
make fitness more fun and entice people into the gym. (Barbara
Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) GREENCASTLE, Ind. -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- SCI-MATH-CRANKS,
2-08 -- Dr. Underwood Dudley, a mathematician at DePauw University
in Indiana and author of ``Mathematical Cranks,'' says that even
though he cannot pin down what makes a crank a crank, ``you can
tell a crank when you see one.'' (Mary Ann Carter/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) GREENCASTLE, Ind. -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- SCI-MATH-CRANKS,
2-08 -- Dr. Underwood Dudley, a mathematician at DePauw University
in Indiana and author of ``Mathematical Cranks,'' says that even
though he cannot pin down what makes a crank a crank, ``you can
tell a crank when you see one.'' (Mary Ann Carter/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CHICAGO -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- SCI-COSMOS-4, 2-08 -- Dr.
Wendy Freedman, an astronomer at the Carnegie Observatories in
Pasadena, Calif., attending the Pritzker Symposium and Workshop on
the Status of Inflationary Cosmology in Chicago. Dr. Freedman may
be close to determining the age of the universe. (Todd Buchanan/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) CHICAGO -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- SCI-COSMOS-3, 2-08 -- Dr.
Michael S. Turner, left, with Sir Martin Rees at a conference on
the universe involving the world's leading cosmologists. ``Two
years ago, we couldn't have had this meeting - we didn't have the
data,'' says Turner, who organized the Pritzker Symposium and
Workshop on the Status of Inflationary Cosmology. ``Now we do, and
the data say we have a flat universe.'' (Todd Buchanan/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CHICAGO -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- SCI-COSMOS-2, 2-08 -- At a
conference on the universe involving the world's leading
cosmologists, Dr. Stephen W. Hawking says cosmic inflation theory
``does a good job'' supporting the Big Bang, but notes that by
itself inflation places no limits on matter, the energy vacuum or
the amplitude of the density fluctuations out of which galactic
structure grew. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CHICAGO -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- SCI-COSMOS-1, 2-08 -- Dr.
Andrei Linde, addressing the world's top cosmologists in Chicago,
explains his theory of eternal inflation, in which countless
universes are born every second. ``Only the anthropic principle
plus inflation will explain the universe as we see it,'' he says.
(Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- PENGUIN-NURSE-BOS, 2-08
--Heather Urquhart gets ready to feed a baby penguin in the New
England Aquarium recently. Urquhart is senior aquarist at the
aquarium and the chick is the smallest of the 61 penguins in her
charge. Ever since Urquhart, 35, was a girl growing up, watching
Jacques Cousteau on television and snorkeling in Cape Cod's Waquoit
Bay, she dreamed of a career tending marine animals. (David L.
Ryan/Boston Globe Photos) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- IMPEACH-SCENE, 2-08 --
Charles Ruff, the White House counsel, is followed by President
Clinton's personal lawyer David Kendall and Cheryl Mills, deputy
White House counsel, on Monday as they arrive on Capitol Hill. Both
sides in President Clinton's impeachment trial began their final
arguments on Monday. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) AMMAN, Jordan -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- JORDAN-FUNERAL-7, 2-08
-- President Clinton is flanked by the Sultan of Brunei, left, and
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, during the funeral procession for
King Hussein on Monday. Others in the procession include French
President Jacques Chirac, background left, and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat, right. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) AMMAN, Jordan -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- JORDAN-FUNERAL-6, 2-08
-- Jordanians mourn King Hussein near his burial site in the
Jordanian capital on Monday. United in loss and grief, thousands
gathered to bury King Hussein who died on Sunday from cancer. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) AMMAN, Jordan -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- JORDAN-FUNERAL-5, 2-08
-- Israeli Prime Minister Bejamin Netanyahu, second from left,
walks with unidentified Muslim representatives during the funeral
procession for King Hussein on Monday. United in loss and grief, a
vast array of presidents, prime ministers and princes gathered
Monday to join the late King Hussein on his final journey. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) AMMAN, Jordan -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- JORDAN-FUNERAL-4, 2-08
-- Israeli President Ezer Weizman, second from right, surrounded by
by aides and security agents, is followed by Jordanians during the
funeral procession for King Hussein on Monday. United in loss and
grief, a vast array of presidents, prime ministers and princes
gathered here Monday to join the late King Hussein on his final
journey. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) AMMAN, Jordan -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- JORDAN-FUNERAL-3, 2-08
-- Mourners near the entrance to Raghadan Palace during funeral
services for King Hussein on Monday. Hussein was taken to his final
resting place on a gun carriage from the Throne Hall of the
Raghadan Palace where dignitaries and heads of state paid their
last respects. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) AMMAN, Jordan -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- JORDAN-FUNERAL-2, 2-08
-- Jordanian soldiers escort King Hussein's body during the funeral
procession on Monday. United in loss and grief, a vast array of
presidents, prime ministers and princes gathered to bury King
Hussein who died on Sunday from cancer. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) AMMAN, Jordan -- Feb. 8, 1999 -- JORDAN-FUNERAL, 2-08 --
President Clinton, background left, is followed by French President
Jacques Chirac during the funeral procession for King Hussein in
the Jordanian capital on Monday. Hussein's son and successor, King
Abdullah II, is at right, third from bottom. (Rina Castelnuovo/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
