</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-AIR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American Airlines cancels flights in wake of disagreement with
pilots
 &HT;    By Peter Donald
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A dispute between American Airlines and
its pilots led to the cancellation of 16 percent of the airline's
flights Monday and stranded some passengers at Palm Beach
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The work slowdown started on Saturday, forcing the cancellation
of nearly 100 flights nationally. On Sunday, 240 flights were
cancelled and the number had climbed to 360 by Monday, airline
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines spokesman Tim Smith said the company normally
operates about 2,250 flights each day.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon Monday at PBIA's Gate C9, Dick and Ann Travis
stretched out in chairs near an American ticket counter,
exasperated at their lack of progress since 7:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to get American on the phone since last
night,'' Dick Travis said. ``I've got to get back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Their 11:15 a.m. flight to New York's LaGuardia Airport was
cancelled, they'd been bumped from alternative flights and they
were hoping to get on a 5:30 p.m. flight.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Waters of the Palm Beach County Department of Airports said
two flights that were supposed to arrive at PBIA Monday morning _
one from LaGuardia and one from Dallas-Fort Worth _ were scrapped.
As a result, two return flights _ Flight 1328 to LaGuardia and
Flight 483 to Dallas-Fort Worth _ were also cancelled. Waters said
that the four cancelled flights had a combined total of 556 seats.
</P>
<P>
   On a normal day, eight American flights leave from PBIA, airline
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   American was trying to place passengers on later flights or
other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for American Airlines said that 45 of its 188
flights from Miami Monday were called off, as were two of the 15
flights leaving Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is over American's acquisition of Reno Air Inc. and
how Reno's 300 pilots will be absorbed into the pilot pool at
American. American's parent company, AMR, closed a deal at the end
of 1998 to purchase Reno Air for $124 million.
</P>
<P>
   American's 9,400 pilots are represented by the Allied Pilots
Association, or A.P.A. The union says its contract specifies that
only A.P.A. pilots can fly American planes, and that American is
trying to create an airline within an airline that will effectively
lower pilots' salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Reno pilots _ represented by another union called the Air Line
Pilots Association _ were making half of what their American
counterparts earn, American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, union and management negotiators broke off their
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   A recorded message by President Rich LaVoy on an A.P.A. hotline
urged pilots not to fly if they don't feel physically or mentally
up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   An American pilot dressed in shorts and a T-shirt who was
picking up a parking permit at PBIA covered his I.D. badge on
Monday and explained that he had the flu. He said the slowdown was
not a strike, but that lots of pilots were calling in sick or not
volunteering to work extra hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just a lot of unhappiness,'' the pilot said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Donald writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
