<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6900 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-LOTTOWINNER-COX     02-08 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-LOTTOWINNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life is forever changed for lucky lottery winners
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIGHTHOUSE POINT, Fla. _ It's tough enough being Broward
County's first female police chief, mother of a 7-year-old, and a
widow too soon.
</P>
<P>
   But Kim Tierney's luck changed suddenly when she and five of her
officers won a $23.6 million piece of a $67 million Lotto jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   The six had one of three winning tickets for Saturday night's
jackpot, the fifth largest in the lottery's 11-year history. The
others were bought in North Miami Beach and Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll just be easier to get out of bed knowing our bank
accounts are a little more plump,'' Tierney, 43, told reporters
Monday morning at Town Hall as city employees and residents
applauded.
</P>
<P>
   The six: Tierney, with 18 years at the department and chief
since June; Sgt. Jack Vaccaro, Commander Michael Oh, and Detectives
Alan Nestor, Joseph Tavares, and Larry Hawkins. All have worked
there for at least seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The group hasn't decided whether to take annual payments or a
lump sum, but Tierney said she didn't anticipate a squabble. Before
taxes, they could each get $130,000 a year for 30 years _ a total
of $3.9 million each _ or one payment of $1.95 million each.
</P>
<P>
   All said they plan to keep working for the 2.5-square-mile
oceanfront town of about 10,500 east of Pompano Beach, although
some said their spouses might quit their jobs. Nestor said his wife
gave notice Monday at the Boca Raton apartment complex where she's
a leasing manager.
</P>
<P>
   Tierney, 43, now earns about $68,000 a year. But she faced
financial challenges after her husband, Thomas Richow, a detective
sergeant, died of cancer at 41 in August.
</P>
<P>
   After she won, she said, her 7-year-old daughter Ashley asked,
``Can we buy Nintendo instead of renting it?''
</P>
<P>
   Other officers' shopping lists include a new car for Nestor and,
for his 6-year-old, ``The biggest Lego he can get;'' a new pickup
truck for Hawkins, another one for his father, and a new Pontiac
Firebird for his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Tavares said he'd pay off some bills. And Oh: ``I'm going to
Disney World!'' He meant it.
</P>
<P>
   Nestor organized the pool two weeks ago. Each person threw in
$2.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the chief took a pass. Then, she said, she told the
group, ``If you guys win I don't want to be alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Nestor bought 12 tickets last week. The officers said they did
not remember if they picked their own numbers or let the computer
do it. The winning numbers were 4-12-20-32-42-47.
</P>
<P>
   None of the six watched the drawing at 11 p.m. Saturday. Nestor
checked the newspaper Sunday morning. He called Tierney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be playing games with me,'' Tierney told Nestor.
</P>
<P>
   Town officers had done pools in the past and hit five of six a
few years ago, and another group of officers had a pool for
Saturday's big drawing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish everyone had won,'' Tierney said. ``It would make
contract negotiations easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Kleinberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
