<HEADER>
A6906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-PHOTO-DONATION-CO     02-08 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-PHOTO-DONATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gift makes Norton 'a force in photography'
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post Art Writer
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Christina Orr-Cahall was curator at
the Norton Museum of Art in the '70s, she asked the board for
$100,000 to acquire photography.
</P>
<P>
   She was turned down. Two decades later, she's the Norton's
director and just got her photographs _ for free.
</P>
<P>
   Norton officials announced Monday the gift of 670 photographs
from Jeane Wahl von Oppenheim, a German baroness who winters in
Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The donation more than quadruples the museum's collection of
roughly 150 images.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the collection one of the leading in Europe, Orr-Cahall
said the gift ``catapults the Norton into a force in the field of
photography.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials declined to reveal the collection's appraised value.
</P>
<P>
   The Norton plans to organize an exhibition for late next year,
and then send it to other museums. They also plan to publish a book
of the pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly two-thirds of the works are by European photographers,
and the rest by Americans. Noted artists include Berenice Abbot,
Henri Cartier-Bresson, Walker Evans, Man Ray, Edward Steichen,
Robert Mapplethorpe and Andre Kertesz. The earliest photos date
from the 1890s.
</P>
<P>
   The collection also includes works by Germans better known as
painters or conceptual artists, such as Joseph Beuys, Sigmar Polke
and Gerhard Richter. Von Oppenheim is an American who married Baron
Alfred von Oppenheim in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Trained in art history, she said she began ``accumulating''
photographs at antiquarian bookshops and flea markets in Europe,
refining her taste and befriending many artists.
</P>
<P>
   She lives in Cologne, Germany, and Palm Beach, and is active
with German museums, including the Museum Ludwig. But she offered
the collection only to the Norton, where she worked as a volunteer
in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began acquiring works without a theme or without a time
period, which is sort of a lazy way of doing things,'' she joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to give (the works) to a museum that had almost
nothing than give it to one that is well-stocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
