u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DEBATE-843&AMP;AD     02-08 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEBATE-843&AMP;ADD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJORITY LEADER OPPOSES OPENING SENATE DELIBERATIONS ON CLINTON'S
FATE
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: Subs 2d graf to explain that Senate rules call for closed
deliberations. Breaks off final sentence as new 3rd graf. Subs 10th
graf to specify the articles of impeachment at end of graf. Subs
11th graf to add ``to public view.'' Subs 13th graf to add ``while
voting against convicting and removing him from office.'' Subs 17th
graf to make it ``that'' instead of ``hat.'') 
 (See related stories: IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-PERJURY,
IMPEACH-CENSURE, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CLINTON) 
(fe) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority
leader, came out on Monday against opening the Senate's final
deliberations over the charges against President Clinton, virtually
guaranteeing that senators' speeches in the climactic hours of the
trial will be made behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Lott's spokesman, John Czwartacki, announced the
majority leader's position Monday afternoon, proponents of an open
debate acknowledged they were more than a half-dozen votes short of
the 67 they needed to amend Senate impeachment rules, which call
for closed deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   They said they had hoped to draw some undecided Republicans to
their side, but Lott's stance made this highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of Democrats support opening the
deliberations, which are expected to begin on Tuesday and last for
two to three days. Most Republicans favor keeping the discussion
closed, and many say they see no reason to let Democrats use oral
condemnations of the president to reduce the political risk of
voting to acquit.
</P>
<P>
   A similar political motive was in play as the effort to reach
agreement on a strong censure resolution faltered. Some Republicans
assailed it as an effort to find political cover, and their threats
of a filibuster and other procedural complications became clearer,
even as the number of senators expressing support for a censure
resolution seemed to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Czwartacki said Lott had decided to oppose opening the
deliberations because he wanted the Senate to adhere to
longstanding rules governing impeachment trials and to an even
longer tradition of allowing juries to hash out the facts _ and
their feelings about them _ in private.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lott has fought to keep as much of this trial in the open as
possible,'' Czwartacki said. ``But now he feels that the Senate
must act like any jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats, however, said the Senate is not like a real
jury, a viewpoint that resurrected previous arguments over the
precise roles that senators, as both triers of fact and elected
officials entrusted to safeguard the nation's interests, are
supposed to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been sequestered in the Hilton Hotel for the last
month and a half,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn. ``It's kind
of a false argument that we are a jury and these are
deliberations.''
</P>
<P>
   The next phase of the trial, whether open or not, is not
expected to be a free-wheeling, informal back-and-forth between a
panel of peers sifting through the evidence and searching their own
souls. It will probably take the form of a series of formal
speeches, limited to 15 minutes apiece, in which senators state
their views and foreshadow how they will vote on the two articles
of impeachment: perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The final phase _ in which senators cast those votes without
explanation _ will be open to public view.
</P>
<P>
   As the dispute between Republicans and Democrats over
deliberations heated up in the last few days, it was fueled in part
by pure political gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   By seeking to open the deliberations, Democrats were looking for
a way to make sure they had a public forum for stating their
disapproval of Clinton's actions while voting against convicting
and removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   By seeking to keep the discussion closed, Republicans were
trying to thwart that effort and to prevent Democrats from using
the deliberations for a public attack on the House managers and
their case.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans were far from unified in their views on the
deliberations. One of the most vocal and persistent advocates for
opening the discussion was a Republican, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison
of Texas, who maintained that the trial was simply too important to
be concluded in secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is historic,'' Mrs. Hutchison said on Monday after
leaving a two-hour Republican caucus devoted almost entirely to a
discussion of the issue. ``I cannot imagine that we would impeach
or not impeach the president of the United States in a closed
session.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hutchison said she had suggested that the maximum time
allotted for each senator's remarks by reduced to 5 or 10 minutes
from 15. This proposal was intended to allay the concerns of some
fellow Republicans that open deliberations would prolong the
proceeding because senators would try to maximize their time in the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   But she said that, according to her arithmetic, she still had
just 60 supporters in all. Because opening the debate would require
suspending Senate rules, a two-thirds majority, or 67 senators,
would have to vote for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be a high hurdle,'' Mrs. Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   Twice during the Senate impeachment trial, senators have moved
to open debates over procedural motions, and twice they have
failed, with most Republicans favoring closed sessions and most
Democrats favoring open ones.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans said on Monday that it was partly because
those closed sessions were so productive _ and so free of the
posturing and preening that occur when reporters and television
cameras are in attendance _ that they did not want to open this
final phase. They also noted that opening it would violate
tradition and create a new precedent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``What I want to do is maintain the sanctity of the interplay
and the discussion,'' said Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats and some Republicans like Mrs. Hutchison said most
senators, if not all, know how they are going to vote, so the
remarks they make are less important for each other than for the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., noted the cynicism that many Americans
feel about government and said that keeping the discussion closed
``is going to feed the fires of frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   To address many senators' concerns that a closed debate would
leave the formal trial record bereft of explanations about
lawmakers' reasons for their votes, senators suggested a variety of
remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators said they were studying the possibility of a vote,
after the verdict, about making the transcript of their
deliberations public.
</P>
<P>
   Alternately, Czwartacki said that Lott would make a motion,
probably immediately after senators vote, to allow them to submit
written explanations of their decisions to be put into the trial
record. Similar explanations were published after the Senate voted
to acquit Andrew Johnson in 1868.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
