<SLUG> BC-FRIVOLOUS-PROSECUTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN PURSUED BY IRS WINS $75,000 TO PAY HIS LAWYER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla.)  (mk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, the government indicted Richard Gardner on 21
counts of tax and bankruptcy fraud, after a raid in which armed
agents of the IRS seized all the computers and files at his
income-tax preparation business in Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   But in January of last year, the Justice Department withdrew the
charges, which Gardner described as ``unlawful actions designed to
punish me for having the temerity to exercise my constitutional
rights'' as a way of delaying payment of back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gardner has become the first person to have his legal
defense fees paid by the Justice Department under a 1997 law
intended to curb prosecutions that are ``vexatious, frivolous or in
bad faith.'' Without admitting wrongdoing, the department last week
paid $75,000 to Gardner's lawyer, R. Thomas Seymour, for the cost
of the case. The two men had sought $102,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Gardner case was extraordinary because once an indictment is
handed up in a tax matter, the Justice Department routinely insists
on either going to trial or obtaining a guilty plea to at least one
charge. Elliot Kajan, a prominent criminal tax lawyer in Beverly
Hills, Calif., said that ``there must have been other cases in
which all charges were withdrawn in a tax case, but it is so rare
that I have never heard of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The payment for Gardner followed a finding in his favor last
July by Judge Sven Erik Holmes of the U.S. District Court in Tulsa.
Ruling on the effort to show that the prosecution had been
frivolous, Holmes held that given the withdrawal of all charges,
Gardner had ``prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department then began negotiating how much it would
pay under the 1997 law, which expanded to frivolous criminal
prosecutions the provisions of the Equal Access to Justice Act that
already applied to civil cases.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials had no comment Monday. The IRS,
whose discussion of tax cases is limited by law, also declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner is the sixth-largest income-tax preparer in Oklahoma and
also runs a store selling used books and comics. By his own
account, he was chronically late turning over income and Social
Security taxes withheld from the paychecks of his seven employees.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1994, court records show, an IRS collection agent
demanded $20,000 that was overdue. Gardner said he would pay in a
few weeks, after receiving expected payments from clients. The
collection agent, the court records show, then threatened a
``jeopardy assessment,'' in which cash, bank accounts and property
can be seized. Gardner replied that he could place his two
businesses in bankruptcy, which would stall the IRS collection
efforts for 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later Gardner did indeed place his two businesses in
bankruptcy. Only days after that, he paid the overdue taxes and
canceled the bankruptcy actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local IRS officials,'' said his lawyer, Seymour, ``took
this lawful, routine business action, this exercising of a
constitutional right, as a personal affront and set out to destroy
Richard's business.''
</P>
<P>
   In March 1995, armed agents raided Gardner's tax preparation
office, seizing records as clients scattered. That night, Gardner
said, he bought new computers, and the next morning was back in
business when Bob Walter, an IRS criminal agent, telephoned.
According to court records, Walter said: ``I'm surprised you're
open. We thought we'd put you out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner says two things have changed since the raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not late paying my taxes anymore,'' he said. ``And my
business is doing better than ever, because my customers stood by
me and told others about me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
