<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PAPARAZZI-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHOOTING STARS: THE PAPARAZZI': SYMBIOSIS YES, LOVE NO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time and station are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the creators of ``Shooting Stars: The Paparazzi'' set out to
present their subjects as a bunch of tiresome whiners, they
succeeded. Tuesday night's installment of ``Inside Story'' on A&AMP;E
follows three of New York's celebrity photographers as they mix
street talk and street stalk. The stentorian voice-of-history
narration by Bill Kurtis, contrasting so dramatically with the
photographer's own self-serving gripes, gives the hour a
tongue-in-cheek air that may be unintended but is certainly
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day is a fight for access to stars who shun them to get
pictures for a public that hates them,'' Kurtis intones. But then
the paparazzi hate the public, too. They hate security guards,
public relations people and the drivers who clog Manhattan streets.
They're not too crazy about one another, and they're at best
ambivalent about the big-name entertainers they pursue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average person only gets to see a celebrity on TV or in a
movie,'' says R.J. Capak, one of the program's featured
photographers. ``I get to see them in real life.'' If hanging
around for hours outside some club or ballroom is your idea of real
life. All that waiting gives a guy time to think. And Capak has
come to the conclusion that the stars are ``no better than us,''
and that ``they're not gods.'' He adds, ``The only thing I see
above their heads is dollar signs.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurtis adds the numbers after the dollar signs. One of the
paparazzi's pictures can bring $100 to $100,000, ``for a scandalous
photo of a top star.'' That kind of golden image is neither shown
nor described.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Capak, the documentary trains its own camera
primarily on David Allocca, a self-described ``inside guy'' who is
hired by publicity agents to shoot premieres, parties and other
events, and Steve Sands, another dedicated outsider who fiercely
jostles for space just beyond the police barricades. ``I used to be
in it for the art,'' Sands says.
</P>
<P>
   These three professionals and a lynch mob of their peers descend
on the premiere of the film ``Celebrity,'' where they capture the
likes of Kenneth Branagh, Lauren Bacall, Wynona Ryder and Uma
Thurman. But their prime objective is Leonardo DiCaprio, who is
notoriously uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
   A few days before, Capak says, he was attacked by members of
``Leonardo DiCaprio's posse,'' who took his camera so he could not
shoot the actor. This time, Capak says, ``we're going to hunt him
down like the dog he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the poor, abused photographers get the kind of thrilling
pictures of DiCaprio that will win them big checks from People
magazine? If not this time, they'll keep trying. That's what they
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a thinking person wouldn't do this,'' says Sands. You
think so?
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `INSIDE STORY: Shooting Stars: The Paparazzi'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Tuesday on A&AMP;E
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Broadcast News Network for A&AMP;E; Steven Rosenbaum,
executive producer for Inside Story; Michael Cascio, executive
producer for A&AMP;E; narrated by Bill Kurtis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
