<HEADER>
A6913 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      02-08 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
  
 house managers make their last stand 
(For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing imminent defeat, President Clinton's
accusers Monday made their last stand in the impeachment trial,
clamoring in their closing arguments for the Senate to summon the
``political courage'' to defy overwhelming public opinion and oust
Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican managers, portrayed by one of their number
as ``13 angry men,'' unloaded bursts of frustration, indignation,
and resignation as they pleaded with senators to convict Clinton on
two articles of impeachment arising from his affair with Monica S.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour appeal, and a summation by White House lawyers,
cleared the way for the Senate to begin deliberating Tuesday
whether Clinton should suffer the disgrace of being the first
president removed from office for ``high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   The deliberations are expected to last until Thursday, when the
Senate is tentatively scheduled to cast the first impeachment votes
on a president since 1868.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no denying the fact that what you decide will have a
profound effect on our culture as well as our politics,'' said
Representative Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, the lead manager, in the
House team's last words in the monthlong trial.
</P>
<P>
   In a scathing denunciation of Clinton's actions, Hyde said the
impeachment has become the main battlefield in a national struggle
over respect for the law and morality. Clinton is charged with
lying under oath to a federal grand jury and obstructing justice to
cover up his affair with Lewinsky and thwart a sexual harassment
lawsuit filed against him by Paula Corbin Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if, after this culture war is over that we're engaged
in, an America will survive that is worth fighting to defend,''
said Hyde, who was representing at least 211 House colleagues who
had voted for one or both of the impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Charles F. C. Ruff assailed the closing
statements by the House managers as the last blow of a partisan
attack aimed at undoing the 1996 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe their vision to be too dark, too little attuned to
the needs of the people, too little sensitive to the needs of our
democracy,'' Ruff said of the managers. ``I believe it to be a
vision more focused on retribution, more designed to achieve
partisan ends, more uncaring about the future we face together.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost every senator has indicated that Clinton is likely to be
cleared of the impeachment charges when the final roll is called. A
two-thirds majority, or 67 votes, is required to convict a
president, and each article may receive as little as a simple
majority, or 51 votes.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the Senate deliberations, prospects for opening
the session to public scrutiny diminished Monday, as the Senate
majority leader, Trent Lott, announced his opposition to open
deliberations. Longtime impeachment rules call for each senator to
speak up to 15 minutes behind closed doors during the
deliberations, although Lott and the Senate minority leader, Thomas
A. Daschle, were poised to recommend reducing each senator's time
to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   At that rate, the deliberations would end by Thursday, setting
up a final vote the same day, and leaving Friday for a possible
debate on a censure resolution, whose outcome remains highly
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers, defiant to the end, asked the Senate to
pursue new evidence in the case by authorizing subpoenas to
determine if White House adviser Sidney Blumenthal lied under oath
last week when he denied spreading to the news media a Clinton
assertion that Lewinsky was a ``stalker.''
</P>
<P>
   In affidavits last week, two journalists, Christopher Hitchens,
and his wife, Carol Blue, said Blumenthal related the ``stalker''
reference several times to them last year in describing Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, in a letter to Lott and Daschle, asserted that if
Blumenthal lied about the ``stalker'' allegation, ``it would reveal
that the White House as an institution may have been used by the
president to obstruct justice for his legal and political
benefit.'' He continued, ``We hope that you do not choose to ignore
this important information.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott made a motion before the closing arguments began Monday to
permit the affidavits to be submitted into the trial record. But
the rules required Lott to obtain unanimous consent, and Daschle
objected.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there was little bipartisan agreement during the
session, as one House manager after another unleashed parting shots
at Clinton, and Ruff returned the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments unfolded five months after the independent
counsel, Kenneth W. Starr, effectively began the impeachment
process by delivering to Congress the results of his eight-month
investigation into the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is still the truth and a lie is still a lie, and the
rule of law should apply to everyone,'' said Representative F.
James Sensenbrenner Jr. of Wisconsin, one of the managers.
``Senators, don't be fooled by the president's excuses and spin
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as they spoke, however, the managers acknowledged the
futility of the exercise. Launching an early autopsy on their
expected defeat, some managers criticized the Senate for
restricting their ability to present their case. Others blamed
public cynicism, the news media, raw partisanship, and other
factors.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the managers had endured ``the media condemnations,
the patronizing editorials, the hate mail, the insults hurled in
public, the attempts at intimidation, the death threats, and even
the disapproval of our colleagues, which cuts the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   A few managers questioned the character of the senators
themselves, as Representative Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas invoked
President John F. Kennedy's book, ``Profiles in Courage,'' and
Representative Bob Barr of Georgia sought to put the senators'
characters in question.
</P>
<P>
   Barr said the final impeachment votes ``will tell us in this
nation whether these seats in this chamber will continue to be
occupied by true statesmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also had harsh words for Clinton's lawyers. ``This entire
saga has been a theater of distraction and misdirection,
time-honored defense tactics when the law and the facts get in the
way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff lashed back, countering the managers' assertion that the
White House had presented a ``so-what'' defense, that the charges
were not serious enough to warrant an impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to see so-what in action, look elsewhere,'' Ruff
said. ``So what if the House Judiciary Committee didn't quite do
their constitutional job if they took the independent counsel's
referral and added a few frills and washed their hands of it. So
what if the House approved articles that wouldn't pass muster in
any court in the land. So what if the managers have been creating
their own theories of impeachment as they go along.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also blasted the censure initiative as a weak alternative
to convicting Clinton. ``Do you really cleanse the office as
provided in the Constitution, or do you use the Air Wick of a
censure resolution?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican senators praised Hyde's speech as a powerful
final chapter of the House presentation. ``I've been a censure
supporter, and I agree that Hyde's comments didn't help us,'' said
Senator John H. Chafee, a Rhode Island Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Anne E. Kornblut of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
