<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING TRADITION, FUNERAL WAS AN AFFAIR FOR MEN ONLY
</HEADLINE>
   (See related stories: JORDAN-FUNERAL, JORDAN-SCENE,
JORDAN-CLINTON, JORDAN-PALESTINIANS) 
(nk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ The funeral of King Hussein on Monday was almost
entirely a male affair, in keeping with what the royal palace
called an Arab Muslim tradition that mourning occasions be
segregated by sex.
</P>
<P>
   The tradition is followed rigorously in Jordan, which behind its
pro-Western image is a deeply conservative Arab society. It meant
that Queen Noor, widow to the late king, stayed at home, with other
female relatives, to accept condolences from female visitors,
including Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said in Washington that
she had stayed away from the funeral in deference to Muslim
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Some women did break with the tradition by paying last respects
to the king, as his body lay in state at Raghadan Palace. They
included Rima Khalaf, a member of the Jordanian senate who had been
invited in that capacity, and Queen Beatrix of the Netherlands and
President Mary McAleese of Ireland, in their capacities as heads of
state.
</P>
<P>
   At least two other women filed past the king's body, but they
could not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   A palace official said women had not been barred from paying of
respects, but had been encouraged to respect Jordan's traditions.
Heads of state were an exception, a protocol official said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no women were seen later at the king's gravesite, in
apparent deference to the tradition that burials in particular are
moments so weighty that they should be single-sex affairs. The
tradition is rooted in Muslim teachings that discourage the mixing
of unrelated men and women. Even Arab Muslims who ordinarily attend
mixed-sex gatherings say they draw the line at funerals, on the
ground that it would be unwise at such an occasion to give offense
to God.
</P>
<P>
   Once a man is buried, the established practice in Jordan is that
women should visit his grave separately, usually the day after the
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   A royal palace official said that Queen Noor and the king's
daughters would probably visit his grave for the first time on
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
