<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6917 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      02-08 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAUDS KING HUSSEIN AS MAN OF VISION AND SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (See related stories: JORDAN-FUNERAL, JORDAN-SCENE,
JORDAN-PALESTINIANS)  
(af) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ President Clinton came here Monday to bury King
Hussein of Jordan and to praise his son Abdullah, the new king.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton led an American delegation including three former
presidents to this grieving and gloomy capital. He met briefly with
King Abdullah Monday evening in the king's office at the Raghadan
Palace after his father was buried.
</P>
<P>
   The president offered American moral and financial support as
the new king begins his reign facing domestic economic trouble and
recurrent strains in efforts to fashion a lasting Middle Eastern
peace.
</P>
<P>
   The president and Hillary Rodham Clinton also paid a condolence
call on King Hussein's widow, the American-born Queen Noor, before
returning to Washington late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke in public only once Monday, delivering brief
remarks to American Embassy employees Monday evening at a local
hotel. He said of King Hussein: ``He really was driven not by the
title he had, but by the responsibilities it bore. And he was
ennobled not by the title, but by the strength of his own character
and his vision and his spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton described the new king as embodying the strength and
humility of his father. And he spoke of King Abdullah's commitment
to domestic development and regional peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``He clearly understands his mission,'' Clinton said. ``He said
in the most moving way: `I and all of my brothers and sisters have
absorbed our father's teaching. We know what we are supposed to do,
and I intend to do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Former presidents Gerald Ford, Jimmy Carter and George Bush
accompanied Clinton aboard Air Force One to pay their respects. The
four presidents filed into the throne room of the Raghadan Palace
just after 2 p.m. and paused in tribute for about seven seconds
before Hussein's coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Kings and queens, presidents and prime ministers flew into Amman
Monday in a dramatic display of respect for the late king. Israeli
and Syrian leaders came to the same place for the same purpose for
the first time in memory, senior American officials said. Iran and
Libya sent delegations, as did Iraq and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said, ``I don't think I have ever seen a greater
outpouring of the world's appreciation and the world's love for a
human being than I've seen today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli delegation, led by President Ezer Weizman and Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, was itself a study in how the death of
one man can serve, for a day at least, as a unifying force: all
major factions of Israeli politics were represented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hardly believe my eyes,'' Clinton said with a laugh,
describing the Israeli entourage. ``All the candidates for prime
minister were there. They were all walking together. I don't know
if they talk at home, but they were all talking here. I thought it
was as if Hussein was hugging them all, you know?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a beautiful sight: people coming from all around
the world, countries that are at each other's throats, here meeting
in peace and friendship and the sanctity of the umbrella of this
great man.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the current and former American presidents was
intended as ``an extremely strong statement to the people of Jordan
that America stands with them during this difficult period,'' said
Samuel R. Berger, Clinton's national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact that three of the four former presidents
chose to come here,'' Berger said, ``and that four American
presidents will be standing together should be a powerful statement
to the Jordanian people about how strongly we feel about the
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the American delegation were two senators, Ted Stevens,
R-Alaska, and Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt. In Washington Monday, the
rest of the Senate heard closing arguments in the impeachment trial
of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy said the king's funeral provided a welcome relief from the
trial, now entering its fifth week of detailed and redundant
testimony. ``I was so tired of that trial,'' Leahy said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's party also included two House members, Benjamin
A. Gilman, R-N.Y., and David E. Bonior, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Najeeb and Doris Halaby, Queen Noor's parents, also traveled
with the president.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral provided an occasion for Clinton to meet briefly
with a rare gathering of world leaders, including Netanyahu, Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, and President Hafez Assad of Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the meetings had been brief and had not involved
extended substantive discussions of the stalled Middle East peace
negotiations. But in each, Clinton asked that Jordan's neighbors
provide help during a time of transition, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   To Assad, the president said: ``I'm glad you're here. I hope
you'll help Jordan,'' Berger said. Assad replied enigmatically,
according to Berger: ``He sort of said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also greeted Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain,
President Jacques Chirac of France, Queen Beatrix of the
Netherlands, Crown Prince Abdullah of Saudi Arabia, President Hosni
Mubarak of Egypt, King Juan Carlos of Spain, Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder of Germany and Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also met briefly with President Boris Yeltsin of Russia,
whom American officials had not expected to attend the funeral
because of failing health. Yeltsin needed assistance to climb the
stairs of the palace where Hussein's body lay in state before
burial and left quickly, accompanied by aides who appeared to be
carrying bags of medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin rose when Clinton approached him, bellowing, ``Bill
Clinton!'' presidential aides said. He embraced Clinton, but
without the bearlike strength of heartier times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously very ill,'' a senior American official said.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the president was confident that King Abdullah would
remain engaged in the Arab-Israeli peace negotiations, even as he
tries to consolidate his power and address serious domestic
economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent considerable time with his predecessors, both on
Air Force One and during the daylong funeral observances. Aides
said the four men had spoken for 90 minutes aboard the aircraft,
sharing reminiscences about King Hussein and discussing the Middle
East, Kosovo and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the subject of Clinton's impeachment trial had not
come up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
