<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECT-SHOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INQUIRY INTO POLICE SHOOTING DRAWS THE GAZE OF GUINEA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As friends and family made funeral arrangements on
Monday for an unarmed street peddler shot dead by New York City
police, a diplomat from the victim's homeland of Guinea in West
Africa said his countrymen were concerned that the four officers
involved had not been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Aboubacar Dione, the first consul of Guinea's permanent mission
to the United Nations, said the police shooting of Amadou Diallo,
who was killed Thursday in a barrage of 41 bullets, has drawn
considerable attention in his country, a nation beset by desperate
poverty and convulsed by eight months of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``People back home _ the entire African continent _ is following
this case. They don't understand why these four are still free,''
Dione said at the mission's four-story town house on East 39th
Street. As he spoke, he received a call from Guinea's minister of
foreign affairs, one of many he said he gets about the case each
morning from officials in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Dione said Guinean officials hope that justice will be done in
the case, which has led critics of the Police Department to
question whether New York's much-lauded crackdown on crime has
created a climate that fosters police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   To reassure Diallo's family, the Bronx district attorney, Robert
Johnson, met Monday afternoon for 30 minutes with six of the dead
man's relatives and friends, including his uncle, Mamadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very good meeting,'' said Kyle Watters, a lawyer for
the Diallo family. ``The district attorney assured us he was doing
everything he can to see that justice is done. He told us that an
investigation was going forward and that they were interviewing
potential witnesses today.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's office is expected to begin presenting evidence and
witnesses to a grand jury later this week. Since there were
apparently no eyewitnesses, aside from the four officers,
prosecutors are likely to begin any presentation with a series of
witnesses who would establish the broad circumstances of Diallo's
death, such as the fact that he was hit by 19 of the bullets fired
at him as he stood unarmed in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment
building.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, who were searching for a rape suspect, have not
spoken to investigators. But their lawyer, Stephen Worth, has said
they thought Diallo had a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Worth has said he will probably allow the officers _ Edward
McMellon, 26, Sean Carroll, 35, Kenneth Boss, 27, and Richard
Murphy, 26 _ to testify without immunity before a grand jury if
certain conditions are met. As of Monday, he said, he had not begun
those negotiations with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo's father and mother were scheduled to arrive in New York
on Tuesday, and the family is planning to hold a memorial prayer
service on Friday at the Islamic Cultural Center of New York on
East 96th Street. The family is then expected to arrange to fly the
body of Diallo home to Guinea, which he left for New York two years
ago. Before leaving, the family is expected to meet with Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, according to city officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to lose a child,'' Giuliani said at a news
conference Monday, ``and the idea of even talking to the father and
talking to him about his losing his son in a foreign country is a
terrible, terrible thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparations were also being made for a rally at noon Tuesday
outside U.S. District Court in Manhattan. A rally was held Sunday
outside the Wheeler Avenue apartment building where Diallo, 22, was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   The four officers involved in the case have been removed from
patrol but three returned to administrative assignments Monday,
according to their lawyer. The fourth called in sick, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor spent two hours at City Hall Monday with members of
the United African Congress, his second meeting in as many days
with representatives of New York's West Africans. Giuliani told
reporters later that he had tried to explain the slow pace of
careful justice. ``Investigations, as you know, take longer than
anybody expects,'' he said. The mayor urged all parties to await
the outcome of the investigation, although he said it would not
support the contention of some critics that the force routinely
brutalized citizens.
</P>
<P>
   `I feel terrible about what happened,'' he said. ``We're working
very, very hard to assist the family and everyone in the community
to understand it. But I am not going to subscribe to a notion that
the police officers in New York City as some general matter are
acting improperly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
