</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINE-AVIATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT-MARTIAL BEGINS FOR MARINE PILOT IN SKI LIFT CABLE DEATHS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. _ A year after an electronic warfare jet
severed a ski lift's cables in the Italian Alps, leading to the
deaths of 20 people, a Marine Corps jury Monday began hearing
arguments about how much of the blame should fall on the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution has charged the pilot, Capt. Richard J. Ashby,
with 20 counts of negligent homicide, which could carry a prison
sentence of 200 years, saying that he broke rules on altitude and
speed.
</P>
<P>
   The defense says that the Marines were poorly trained, poorly
equipped and misinformed by the squadron, and that Captain Ashby
was only the last in a chain of people who made tragic errors.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby, 31, sat between his lawyers in a spare military courtroom
here as experts began a public dissection of his troubled squadron
and of his own actions. Nearby, 29 civilian witnesses were waiting
to testify about what they saw from the ground, while a roomful of
Belgian and German families of the victims watched over
closed-circuit television, with simultaneous translation.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby was ``a good stick,'' a good pilot, said Lt. Col. Carol
Joyce, head of the prosecution team, and he knew the rules that
would have kept him safe. ``Whether it's because he was
overconfident in his ability or whether he was just plain cocky,
Ashby chose to breach those rules and regulations,'' she told the
jury of eight officers.
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Joyce also said that a crew member in the back seat of
the jet would testify that Ashby put the plane through a barrel
roll, which is against regulations, before it hit the cables.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Jon Shelburne, a defense lawyer, said that the crew
members were ``professional in the conduct of this flight, and they
were professional in the planning of this flight, and they were
just doing their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an accident, and as you'll see, it was an accident
waiting to happen,'' Shelburne said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that almost no one in the squadron knew that the minimum
legal altitude in the area was 2,000 feet above ground level. The
ski lift cables were at 360 feet. He also said that the cable, then
31 years old, was not marked on American maps.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the government is trying to show is that information that
nobody in that squadron knew, Captain Ashby should have known, and
therefore he's guilty,'' Shelburne said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby faces 10 years in military prison for each of 20 counts of
involuntary manslaughter, a crime that requires a finding of
culpable negligence. But he could be found guilty of negligent
homicide, a lesser crime. In July a hearing officer who conducted a
seven-day inquiry into the case against all four crew members of
the plane found ``substantial doubt'' that the men could be
convicted, because of failures by others in the squadron and
elsewhere in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   And a month later, the commander of Marine Forces in the
Atlantic relieved the squadron commander of his command and
inserted a letter of reprimand in the file of the squadron's safety
director. The men acknowledged that the papers they maintained for
the navigators to use in flight planning were out of date and
inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Charges against two officers in the rear cockpit have been
dropped, leaving only Ashby and his navigator and flight planner,
Capt. Joseph P. Schweitzer, still facing charges. Schweitzer is to
be tried next month.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, a topographic expert presented two
large-scale models of the valley where the accident occurred. One,
a diorama of the mountain slope, showed the streams, some buildings
and the ski lift. It also showed the 1,000-foot altitude that the
crew believed was the lowest allowed, rendered as a yellow line on
a plexiglass sheet at the side of the model. The cables, at about
360 feet, were obviously far below.
</P>
<P>
   The crew members deny having intended to fly under 1,000 feet.
One of the tasks for the defense is to convince the jury that
knowing how to fly low and at high speed is essential for pilots of
such a plane, an EA-6B Prowler. The plane carries missiles for
destroying radar sites, but no other armament. The jury includes
one helicopter pilot and two cargo plane pilots but no combat
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby and Schweitzer also face charges of obstruction of
justice. Prosecutors say they hid or destroyed a videotape that
they used to record portions of the flight before the leg on which
the accident occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The families of some of the victims spoke to reporters at court
on Monday. ``We don't expect that it must be the pilot who has to
be convicted,'' said Rita Wunderlich, whose husband of 20 years,
Jurgen, was killed when the cable car fell. ``We expect that the
ones who were responsible in the end will be convicted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
