<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HOLDING FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial on Tuesday, Feb. 9: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the movies, a fusillade of 41 bullets is nothing, a
Schwarzenegger second. In real life, the storm of police gunfire
that killed an unarmed West African immigrant last week was a
brutal human tragedy that has left a Bronx neighborhood shaken and
angry about the aggressive Street Crimes Unit that is supposed to
be making their community a safer place to live.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred shortly after midnight last Thursday when
four plainclothes officers from the Street Crimes Unit saw a man in
the vestibule of a Bronx apartment building. For reasons that are
still unclear, they suddenly emptied their guns at Amadou Diallo, a
22-year-old street merchant from Guinea. Diallo, who spoke halting
English and had no police record, died at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the policemen told journalists that ``fair-minded
people'' would recognize that ``this shooting, although tragic, was
proper.'' He said that the four had been seeking a serial rapist
who resembled Diallo, and that they thought he was acting
suspiciously and was reaching for a weapon. They found only a
wallet and a beeper in his pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office is reviewing the case, which is under
investigation by the Bronx district attorney. One police official
told The New York Times that ``it looks as though one guy may have
panicked and the rest followed suit.'' What makes that disturbing
is that while the city says that more than 90 percent of New York's
police officers never fire their guns, three of the four officers
in this case have been involved in shootings before, with two found
to have acted properly and one incident still under review by the
Brooklyn district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has wisely counseled New Yorkers not to
rush to judgment, and he has offered assistance to Diallo's family
through the city's Community Assistance Unit. The mayor has also
assured African diplomats including the Guinean ambassador that the
case is being investigated properly. That is a good start, but the
mayor must find a way to assure the city's immigrants and
minorities that policemen from outside their neighborhoods do not
reflexively suspect a person of color and resort to force too
readily.
</P>
<P>
   Despite efforts by the mayor and the police commissioner to
encourage community relations and hold precinct commanders
responsible for complaints, there is a long history of suspicion
that makes it difficult for many to forgive the fusillade as a
simple ``mistake.'' It is critically important that city and
federal investigators find answers as quickly as possible to the
troubling questions raised by this case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
