<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-ALBERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBERT BACK IN THE BASKETBALL BOOTH  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The voice sounded as if it had never disappeared into exile. The
staccato rhythm, the familiar phrases, the completeness of the
play-calling and the wisecracking were in midseason form Sunday
when Marv Albert called his first basketball game in 20 months and
his first Knicks radio game in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although Albert has been host of ``MSG SportsDesk'' since
September, his comeback _ from pleading guilty to a misdemeanor
assault charge that caused him to lose his MSG Network and NBC jobs
_ seemed incomplete until he described which team was shooting at
the Eighth Avenue end of Madison Square Garden, questioned why
Patrick Ewing shot a layup rather than kick the ball for a
3-pointer with seconds left and teased his sidekick, John
Andariese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, this completed it,'' Albert said Monday. ``What
was nice was the reaction from the people, which was great. Some of
it was even heartwarming. I'm around here all the time, but I
haven't been in that type of situation. Kids were waving. It was a
great reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   For a week before the Heat-Knicks game, Albert listened to some
of his radio calls from the 1970s ``to hear the rhythm and the
phrases.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I've always loved radio. It's so different. In TV,
you have time to breathe. Radio's a completely different
mind-set.'' For part of Sunday's first half, the action was so
intense, Albert had little time to catch his breath. ``It was like
a hockey game, with end-to-end rushes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, Andariese begged for a foul merely to say
something. ``I'm here, Marv,'' he said. ``I thought I'd say that.''
Said Albert, ``I want you to know that sometime in the second
quarter, we'll expect some analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the layoff, Albert remains extremely confident about his
ability to call basketball. Sunday's game was more a chance to
release pent-up anxiety than to wonder whether he still possessed
the verbal aptitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to be overconfident, but once the game started, I didn't
think it would be a problem,'' he said. ``Just going through the
process was what the anxiety was about. It was a wonderful day. It
felt like old times, with John.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for his legal problems, he might have been at courtside
for NBC calling the game. ``I've come to grips with that,'' Albert
said. ``I was too focused to think about it. It didn't strike me
that I could have been calling the game on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIFFORD NEXT? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   With Dan Dierdorf gone from ``Monday Night Football,'' ABC
Sports is considering downsizing to a two-in-the-booth setup with
Al Michaels and Boomer Esiason. But Esiason is not ready to fly
solo. ABC should shift Paul Maguire from ESPN's Sunday night
National Football League booth to recreate the role he played
beside Phil Simms on NBC's No. 1 football team.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire is smart, funny and generous; he would help nurture
Esiason's development, and would fit in better than ESPN's Sterling
Sharpe, whose name has been mentioned as a successor to Dierdorf,
but who has never called a pro game.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it looks as if Frank Gifford will not return to the
almost inconsequential role he played on the Monday night pre-game
show last season. His contract expires in June.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
