<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GLENN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAN GLENN, MAGAZINE PUBLISHER, DIES AT 89
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif., Texas, S.C.) (nk)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Norman R. Glenn, the publisher of two advertising and
broadcasting trade magazines, died on Friday in New York City. He
was 89.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from a stroke, said his wife,
Roberta.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, Glenn worked in executive positions at WLS, a
Chicago radio station. In 1946, he founded Sponsor magazine, which
covered advertising on radio and television.
</P>
<P>
   After selling Sponsor, he started Media Decisions in 1966, a
publication dealing with the planning and placement of
advertisements in communications media. He sold that publication in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, he founded Community Action Network, a nonprofit
group in New York City that provided information on urban problems.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Glenn is survived by two children from
his first marriage, Robin Day Glenn, of Rancho Santa Margarita,
Calif., and Geoffrey, of Myrtle Beach, S.C.; two stepchildren,
Robin Okun, of Zurich, and Todd Brewster, of Dallas; and five
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 2232EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DERIVATIVES-NYT &LR;      02-08 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DERIVATIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 MARKETS JOIN IN ELECTRONIC OPTIONS TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In yet another signal that technology and
globalization are changing the way that financial markets operate,
three large financial exchanges said Monday that they would form an
alliance to offer electronic trading in futures and options across
three continents.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange, the Bourse in Paris, which
operates Matif, the French derivatives exchange, and the Singapore
International Monetary Exchange said they had signed an agreement
that would allow futures and options to be traded as part of a
global electronic network that would operate around the clock in
Asia, Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is the latest effort by big markets to find
cheaper and more efficient ways to trade stocks, bonds and
derivatives in an increasingly electronic financial world.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, several large exchanges have merged or formed
alliances as a way to share in the cost of developing new
technology and to offer customers a broader range of financial
products. The exchanges also aim to create technology platforms
that may some day supplant the traditional ``open outcry'' system,
where traders shout out bids on a cluttered trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   The new venture that was announced in Paris Monday is being
called the Globex Alliance, after the electronic trading system
called Globex, which was founded in 1992 by the Chicago Merc and
Matif.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of trading here in Chicago is still done in
trading pits. But electronic trading of derivatives, like futures
on interest rates and currencies, is growing on the periphery of
that activity, and many of those financial products already trade
after hours on the electronic Globex system.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the three exchanges _ which expect to begin trading
together in the third quarter _ said they might ask other markets
to join the alliance, while also looking at alliances independent
of one another.
</P>
<P>
   M. Scott Gordon, chairman of the Chicago Merc, said his exchange
had been in partnership and alliance talks with just about every
other major market, particularly with regard to technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't do this alone; it's too costly to build a
proprietary system in a world that wants connectivity,'' Gordon
said. ``Given that we are going to expand our electronic platforms,
it's important we have partners. This is all about creating
efficiencies and lower costs for our customers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
