<HEADLINE>
BROWNS CHOOSE FROM EXPANSION LISTS TUESDAY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last three seasons, there has been no Cleveland Browns
team because the club with that name moved to Baltimore and became
the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the new Cleveland Browns, who will start playing in
the fall, will become more of a reality when they choose 30 to 42
players in an expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 other National Football League teams have exposed five
players each (no kickers or punters allowed). Some, like Reggie
White, are about to retire. Some, such as Neil Smith (with a salary
of $3.5 million), Michael Jackson ($3.2 million), Antonio Langham
($3 million), Tito Wooten ($2 million) and Mike Fox ($1.8 million),
may be too highly paid to be selected. Some are well past their
prime. Some are fringe players.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns must spend almost $22 million, which represents at
least 38 percent of their salary cap, on the salaries of the
players they choose on Tuesday. The team will get most of its
players through free agency and the college draft.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland can choose experienced quarterbacks in Glenn Foley,
Gus Frerotte and Heath Shuler. The Browns are more likely to turn
to offensive linemen such as Andy Heck, Todd Rucci and Jim Pyne.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I initially looked at the list it didn't blow me away,''
General Manager Dwight Clark of the Browns said. ``Some of the
players I had not been that familiar with. Ultimately, you start
digging in and finding more information about them. That's when you
start getting excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Browns made one move Monday, signing Ray Perkins as the
tight ends coach. The 57-year-old Perkins had been an assistant
coach with Oakland and spent four years as head coach of the Giants
(1979-82) and four as head coach of Tampa Bay (1987-90).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARENA FOOTBALL UP FOR GRABS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League is expanding, more or less. Monday,
it acquired an option to buy up to 49.9 percent of the Arena
Football League within the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL said it would decide in the next 12 to 24 months whether
to exercise the option, which would give it a voice in the
operation of the Arena League. Such a move by the NFL would take a
three-quarters vote of its club owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to support football at all levels,'' Paul
Tagliabue, the NFL commissioner, said.
</P>
<P>
   He and others said there was no plan for the Arena league to
become part of an NFL farm system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIANTS DROP MILLER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In his eight years with the Giants, five of those years as a
starter, Corey Miller became a solid strongside linebacker,
especially against the run. But his relationship with Coach Jim
Fassel turned acrimonious last year.
</P>
<P>
   Miller failed a recent physical examination, and Monday the
Giants terminated his contract, which had a year to run at a salary
of $1.8 million. If Miller does not sign with another team, the
Giants must pay him an injury settlement of $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; $5 MILLION RAISE, OF SORTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League salary cap was officially set
Monday at $57.288 million, up some $5 million from last season. The
setting of the salary cap now allows teams to move forward with
free-agent plans and the signings of their own players.
</P>
</TEXT>
