<SLUG> BC-RUN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINTERS PROVE THEY CAN ALSO RUN OFF AT THE MOUTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Running is the no-frills way to fly. You don't
have to have a ball in your hands, a helmet on your head, pads on
your shoulders or even shoes on your feet.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinting, in particular, can be as uncomplicated as a child.
You lift your knees, pump your arms and the next thing you know
you're soaring like a human glider. And if one day you become a
Concorde, that's when you learn the paradox of winged feet:
</P>
<P>
   The swifter you are, the more bogged down you get.
</P>
<P>
   Take Maurice Greene and Jon Drummond. They love to fly and it
shows. When they sprint, their feet land on the track like
snowflakes. They barely make a sound when they're in motion, but at
rest they are loud and proud.
</P>
<P>
   Greene and Drummond _ along with their HSI training partner Ato
Boldon _ not only can run with the best of them, they can run their
mouths like a young Muhammad Ali. Left to their own devices, they
could talk up a ton of interest in track and field.
</P>
<P>
   So why is it the sport is on the wane in the U.S.? The answer
lies partly in the awkward situation that presented itself the
other day at an arranged press conference at UCLA's Drake Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, 24, and Drummond, 30, are bringing their
fierce-yet-friendly rivalry to the Sports Arena on Saturday for the
39th L.A. Invitational. They were eager to talk about it, not least
of all because it kept them from having to join a manic Monday
training session in progress. They had ample motivation and an
attentive audience. There was just one thing missing. Fifteen
minutes after the press conference was scheduled to start, the
assembled audience learned what it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you wait until my manager gets here?'' Greene cried out
from the track.
</P>
<P>
   Greene was only doing what he was told. But it bears noting that
not once during Super Bowl week did Denver quarterback John Elway
wait until his agent was around to answer any questions. And a lot
of us would never know what Shaquille O'Neal was thinking if we had
to get Leonard Armato's permission to approach him.
</P>
<P>
   If track and field completely collapses in the U.S., it surely
will be under the weight of the athletes' entourages, which have
grown in proportion to the sport's over-the-table purses.
</P>
<P>
   The L.A. Invitational is proof that the fast lane is paved in
gold. It is the second of four indoor meets on the Golden Spike
series, which was initiated this year to stem the migration of this
country's best athletes to Europe for the winter's lucrative indoor
season.
</P>
<P>
   As they did last week at the Millrose Games in New York, Greene
and Drummond will make money simply for showing up. They can
collect more cash for finishing among the top six in the evening's
featured event.
</P>
<P>
   They are scheduled to run the 50 meters. But L.A. meet
organizers Al and Don Franken sounded amenable to setting up a
60-meter course so the runners can secure a 50 split and still
challenge Greene's indoor world record of 6.39 in the 60.
</P>
<P>
   At Madison Square Garden this past Friday, Greene, the reigning
world champion in the 100, overcame a slow start and pulled away
from Drummond in the last 10 meters to prevail in the 60, 6.51 to
6.54. After the race, an ebullient Greene blanketed the crowd with
T-shirts that had a single word silk-screened on them:
</P>
<P>
   Phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, who lives in Woodland Hills, came by his superstardom
honestly. He has sweated endlessly for it, relocating from his
hometown of Kansas City three years ago to train under coach John
Smith and alongside Drummond and Boldon.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when the top sprinters regularly go to great lengths
to avoid competing head-to-head, Greene, Drummond and Boldon boldly
put their egos on the line every day. It's at once a great and
grating way to measure their progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, there are a lot of days when you don't feel that
great,'' Greene said. ``Then you see one of your teammates run a
good time in practice and you say, `Dang, now I have to do that.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Joined in Drummond, ``You have to have a thick skin to be part
of the group. Because if you mess up, we'll talk about you. You'll
be the brunt of jokes for the whole week.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene and Drummond professed not to care which one of them wins
Saturday, as long as they finish 1-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not afraid to compete against each other,'' Drummond
said.
</P>
<P>
   They're not averse to being affable, either. Their quick wit and
fast-twitch muscles could be an unbeatable combination for USA
track. But only if the people around the runners are willing to let
go a little. Build a rapport with the public and they'll come to
the track. That's something Drummond seems to recognize even if his
handlers sometimes need a gentle reminder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loves watching people run,'' Drummond said. ``The
problem has been they haven't had a reason to come out. In the
past, sprinters were stone-faced. They'd run their race and leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show that we have emotions. We laugh. We cry. We
get disappointed. Entertainment-wise, we want people to say,
`Forget basketball, let's go to a track meet because those guys are
real.''
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to just really fast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
