<SLUG> BC-IBM-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADING RECORDING COMPANIES TO TEST ON-LINE DIGITAL SALES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (nk) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The five major recording companies said Monday that
they would, for the first time, begin to test selling albums as
digital information transmitted over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A new system to be tested this spring is intended to sell
authorized recordings in a medium where most of the music,
legitimately copied and otherwise, is now available free.
</P>
<P>
   The system was announced Monday in New York by IBM, which
created the software, and the five major recording companies _
Sony, Time Warner, the Universal unit of the Seagram Co., EMI Group
and Bertelsmann Music Group. The system would let consumers pay for
an album by credit card, download it with a cable modem in less
than 10 minutes, and play it back through computer speakers or
record it on tape, digital minidisks, recordable compact disks or
other devices now on the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   A booklet would also be downloaded, to be printed on a color
printer.
</P>
<P>
   The test, to begin between April and June, will involve 1,000
subscribers to Time Warner's Roadrunner cable modem service in San
Diego. Initially, 1,000 album titles and several hundred singles
will be available, the companies said; the number of selections is
to more than double in the six to nine months the test will be
conducted. The companies have not announced their pricing for the
digital products.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of music recordings are already available on
the Internet free, as files that have been copied without
permission from CD's in a format called MP3. Music companies have
scrambled to find a way to sell legitimate copies of their products
on line in what they call a ``secure'' format.
</P>
<P>
   In this test, they will employ a digital watermark containing
information on where the music came from and who owns the rights;
the data will be encrypted so that only a legitimate user can play
it back.
</P>
<P>
   The music companies also want the online music to be ``copy
protected,'' enabling them to determine the number of digital
copies a consumer could make.
</P>
<P>
   In December, recording and technology companies said they would
collaborate on the Secure Digital Music Initiative, a uniform
standard for codes to be included with music transmitted digitally.
The San Diego test does not supplant the initiative, which is
intended to set standards for a new generation of digital players.
</P>
<P>
   The MP3 files now found on the Internet can be copied freely,
but are of unpredictable quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you compete with something that's free?'' said Larry
Kenswil, executive vice president of the Universal Music Group.
``Obviously you can't compete on price. Instead, you have to offer
higher quality, customer service and ease of use.''
</P>
<P>
   The recording industry is counting on the spread of cable modems
and other high-speed, or ``broadband,'' connections, because
conventional dial-up modems receive information too slowly to make
digital distribution practical. Kenswil predicted that in five
years, 20 percent of American homes would have broadband
connections. In fact, he said, digital distribution of music would
be an incentive for consumers to subscribe to cable modem systems.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Vidich, executive vice president of Warner Music Group,
said that the industry ``most enthusiastic about this, second only
to the music industry, is the cable industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The recording companies have no intention of abandoning plastic
disks. They plan to announce specifications soon for DVD Audio, a
CD-sized disk that will offer multichannel sound and be encoded to
prevent digital copying. DVD audio disks will hold considerably
more music than audio CD's, making them very hard to transmit over
the Internet even at today's fastest speeds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
