<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JUDICIARY-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP NEW YORK JUDGE CALLS FOR EASING SOME DRUG LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York state's chief judge, Judith Kaye,
proposed several changes to the state's drug laws Monday that would
reduce sentences for some defendants found guilty of selling or
possessing narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   New York's drug laws, commonly called the Rockefeller drug laws
and enacted in 1973 under Gov. Nelson Rockefeller, carry some of
the stiffest sentences in the country. For years, critics have
contended that the laws were too harsh, but the
Republican-controlled state Senate has resisted change. Someone
convicted of selling more than two ounces of cocaine, heroin or
other controlled substances _ or possessing more than four ounces _
must be sentenced to a minimum of 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Kaye proposed legislation that would permit state
appellate judges to reduce the 15-year sentence, on a case-by-case
basis, when the judges believed that such a long minimum sentence
would represent a ``miscarriage of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposed statute would require the Appellate Division to
consider the nature and circumstances of the offense, the history
and character of the defendant and public safety concerns in
determining whether an injustice has occurred,'' Judge Kaye said in
an annual speech on the state's judicial system delivered in the
ornate courtroom of New York's highest court, the Court of Appeals,
in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the appellate courts could reduce the
minimum sentence to no less than five years in prison. Judge Kaye
said only a limited number of defendants would have their sentences
adjusted. She noted that in wading into a highly disputed area of
the criminal law, she was not asking the state Legislature for
broad revisions in the drug laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not presume to take on the larger policy issues,'' Judge
Kaye said. ``But we do seek to address aspects of the law that can
work unjustly, and to supplement the law with some of the lessons
we in the courts have learned over the past decade on effective
responses to drug-based crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief judge also proposed expanding experimental court
programs that allow nonviolent, drug-addicted defendants accused of
low-level drug violations to defer prosecution or to defer serving
a prison sentence by entering and completing drug-treatment
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Under her plan, people accused of possessing or selling very
small amounts of narcotics would be eligible for drug treatment
instead of prison terms, provided that both the trial judge and the
prosecutor agreed. As many as 10,000 low-level drug defendants a
year could be permitted to defer prosecution or jail time if the
proposal became law, court officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki called the proposal thoughtful and
intelligent. ``I'm not at this point prepared to endorse it, but
it's certainly one that warrants further review,'' the governor
said.
</P>
<P>
   John McArdle, a spokesman for the Senate majority leader, Joseph
Bruno, said Bruno was open to discussing the chief judge's ideas
but in the context of other proposed changes to the justice system,
including expansion of state prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Lynch, a spokesman for the Assembly speaker, Sheldon
Silver, declined to comment. The Assembly, controlled by the
Democrats, traditionally has been the branch of the Legislature
most critical of the Rockefeller drug laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 2248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADOPTION-RULES-NYT &LR;      02-08 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPTION-RULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS IN ALBANY BACK NEW ADOPTION AND FOSTER CARE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Seeking to comply with federal law, Gov. George
Pataki and state legislative leaders agreed Monday night on a bill
that would overhaul regulations governing adoptions and foster care
in New York, including requiring criminal background checks for
prospective parents.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is intended to help speed up adoptions and to give the
authorities more tools for removing children from abusive parents.
It signals a shift in the way the government supervises the
adoption and foster care systems. Instead of focusing on reuniting
children with their birth parents, even if the parents have harmed
them, the authorities are now supposed to make decisions based on
what is in the best interests of the child.
</P>
<P>
   Congress told the states in 1997 that they had to adopt these
changes in order to continue receiving certain federal grants, and
had Albany balked, it would have jeopardized nearly $600 million in
annual disbursements from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children are New York's most valuable resource,'' Pataki said
in a statement, ``and we need to do everything we can to insure
children live in the safe, caring environment they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly approved the legislation Monday night, 148-0, and
the Senate is expected to do so on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration and lawmakers had been negotiating the
legislation for several months, but had repeatedly hit snags over
the scope of when it would be permissible to remove a child from a
parent's care. Democrats, who have generally supported an emphasis
on keeping families intact, had fought to narrow the circumstances
under which a parent's rights would be terminated. Pataki and
Republican lawmakers had sought to give the authorities more
leeway.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, the state would no longer have to
consider preserving and reuniting families if a parent had
subjected the child to severe _ including sexual _ abuse, or if the
parent had been convicted of murder, assault or other serious
felonies.
</P>
<P>
   The bill requires all prospective foster and adoptive parents to
undergo criminal background checks before children can be placed in
their homes. Parents would be rejected if they had been convicted
of certain felonies.
</P>
<P>
   All people older than 18 residing in the home of a person
applying to adopt a child or take care of a foster child would also
be required to undergo criminal background checks.
</P>
<P>
   To insure that children do not languish in foster care, the
authorities would have to terminate parental rights after a child
had been in a foster home for 15 of the previous 22 months _ and
almost immediately if there was evidence of severe abuse or if the
child had been abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The bill includes some provisions that are not required by
Congress, including rewriting the definition of severe abuse, which
had been so narrowly defined under state law that local authorities
had rarely been able to use it to end a parent's legal rights to a
child. The bill expands the definition to include sexual abuse
against the child and several other felony offenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
