A6936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-LAWSUIT-COX     02-08 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate OKs bill to kill gun suit
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Legislation to block Atlanta's liability lawsuit
against gun manufacturers won approval Monday after Georgia Senate
leaders narrowly overcame Republican stalling tactics.
</P>
<P>
   The bill backed by the National Rifle Association that
originated in the House now returns to that chamber for approval of
minor Senate changes. House approval and Gov. Roy Barnes' signature
are considered mere formalities.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bill Campbell predicted the bill would be overturned in
court as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The key Senate vote Monday came on a motion to revive the bill
after it had been tabled Friday by a coalition of Republicans and
Atlanta-area Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   It passed 28-26 after seven senators _ four from metro Atlanta _
changed their minds and voted to bring the bill to a vote. Lt. Gov.
Mark Taylor acknowledged calling several of the switchers, and
Senate Majority Leader Charles Walker (D-Augusta) lobbied Democrats
to support the bill early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. David Scott (D-Atlanta) criticized Democrats for caving in
to the NRA at the expense of Atlantans who were instrumental in
electing Barnes, Taylor and other Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``To turn around and stab (those voters) in the heart by taking
away their constitutional right to sue is abominable,'' said Scott,
chairman of the powerful Senate Rules Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor disagreed. ``That (Atlanta) constituency is not speaking
to the state Senate on that issue,'' he said. ``David's
representing himself. He's a fanatic on gun control.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said Republicans stalled the bill ``as a payback to the
NRA'' for endorsing Democrats Taylor, Barnes and Attorney General
Thurbert Baker in their campaigns last fall. Taylor claimed
Congressman Bob Barr (D-Ga.) was orchestrating the maneuvering by
Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Eric Johnson (R-Savannah) called that
theory ``pure fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson acknowledged he'd called Barr, an NRA board member,
Sunday night to explain plans Senate Republicans had to try to
amend the bill Monday morning to cover not only gun manufacturers,
but all manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson stressed that 21 of 22 Senate Republicans had always
supported the bill to block Atlanta's lawsuit. But they wanted
more, and his call to Barr was a courtesy to prevent any
misunderstanding with the NRA, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   An amendment by Sen. Bart Ladd (R-Doraville) to ban liability
lawsuits against all manufacturers (except for product defects)
lost by 33-22 Monday. After that, all Republicans except Sen. Mike
Egan (R-Atlanta) voted for the original House bill, with minor
amendments. It passed 44-11.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the seven Democrats who voted to revive the House bill
voted against it, including Sen. Connie Stokes (D-Decatur). ``I
didn't want to let it linger most of the session,'' Stokes said.
``We have a lot of other work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mantius writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
