<SLUG> BC-NY-SEX-PREDATORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI AGAIN URGES CONFINING SEX OFFENDERS AFTER PRISON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Kan.)  (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki on Monday renewed his call for
a law that would allow the state to confine violent sex offenders
in mental hospitals after they have served their criminal
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would give New York officials the power to forcibly
commit people who are deemed mentally abnormal and likely to carry
out violent sex crimes if they are released from custody. Several
states, including New Jersey, have adopted such laws over the
objections of some civil liberties groups, which contend that
involuntary commitments amount to unfair extensions of punishment.
The U.S. Supreme Court has generally upheld the laws.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki proposed similar legislation last year, but it died in
the Assembly, which is controlled by Democrats. This year, though,
the governor has garnered support from the state's new attorney
general, Eliot L. Spitzer, a Democrat who has long promoted tougher
criminal justice measures and who pledged to try to get the
Assembly majority to agree to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual violent predators must be kept off our streets,''
Spitzer said at a news conference held with Pataki. ``Our society
and our children, who are so often the victims of sexual violent
predators, must be protected. This is, of course, the first
obligation of our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Carrier, a spokesman for the Assembly speaker, Sheldon
Silver, a Manhattan Democrat, declined to say whether the Assembly
majority would back the legislation. ``We'll take a look at it,''
Carrier said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate, controlled by Republicans, is expected to
approve the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's proposal is modeled after one passed in Kansas, which
has been at the forefront of the movement among states to confine
sex offenders. It would allow the attorney general of New York to
request that a sex offender be sent to a mental hospital if the
state can prove at a civil hearing that the person meets the legal
definition of mentally abnormal or has another disorder that
suggests a likelihood of committing sexual violence again.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal applies only to people convicted of one of a list
of serious sex crimes, including forcible rape or sodomy. There
would be periodic reviews of the person's condition to determine
whether the confinement should continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
