<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-DRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE THE SHOWS, EAVESDROPPING ON SEVENTH AVENUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From a fashion point of view, which is the only one
on Seventh Avenue, the autumn shows taking place this week and next
on the tented lawn at Bryant Park are already two sandwiches shy of
a picnic. It isn't that anyone expects to have fun: there are more
than 75 men's and women's shows on the official roster, some 25
others in SoHo and Chelsea, and that means ... what? ... 8,000
outfits to be absorbed before all the hoopla ends a week from
Friday. As Michael Kors said the other day in a tone heavy with
fatigue: ``I feel like the Dunkin' Donut man. Time to make the
fashions.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what really keeps the spectacle from being a glamorous
event _ full of models, clothes, celebrities, editors racing around
like Shriners _ is the question of whether anyone will make money.
That has always been the unabashed, undisguised goal of Seventh
Avenue, making money. But these days, with Isaac Mizrahi out of
business, fashion stocks in the dumps and pink slips at Ralph
Lauren, it is almost a taboo subject.
</P>
<P>
   As one department store executive said last week, speaking on
condition of anonymity, ``There is very little money being made,
and that's a problem for designers whose core business is
fashion.'' The executive went on to say he thought the shows
themselves were becoming increasingly irrelevant and existed mainly
to affirm the status and opinions of a few. ``It's the fashion
world talking to itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the shows might be poor indications of who's making money
and who might be going to make money. Nonetheless, the sound of
designers yammering, in the inimitable language of Seventh Avenue,
can still produce a noise you can't ignore. In the hectic days
before the shows begin, a journey through the workrooms of
designers, famous and unknown, found a surprising chaos so close to
fashion's show time.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan, the head of a multimillion public company, still
had designed only a handful of looks last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the entire fall collection,'' she told a visitor,
sweeping an arm toward uncut bolts of fabric leaning against a wall
in her studio in 550 Seventh Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Karan designs by draping fabric on her fitting model. ``I
would say this is probably the toughest season I've ever had,'' she
said. ``Nothing is as it is. And it gets harder. What can I do to
make a difference?''
</P>
<P>
   Alex de Betak, a producer of fashion shows for John Bartlett,
Donna Karan and Michael Kors, was also working down to the wire.
``To be honest, the only thing I've seen are sketches,'' said de
Betak, who casts models and helps choose music for his clients.
``Nobody has a piece of clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, de Betak was utterly serene. Each morning when he
arrived at his Greene Street office, there was usually a fax from
Bartlett, who was working in Italy, imparting some new thought
about his New York show, which will be seen on Saturday night. ``In
Italy, especially, because I don't sleep,'' Bartlett said later,
``I just write everything in a fax to him, and that makes me go to
sleep. I just write about all these things _ whether it's a song or
about hair or a model.''
</P>
<P>
   On his return to New York, Bartlett was in his studio, a big
loft on West 15th Street, with his dog, Sweetie, and a couple of
assistants. ``The inspiration this season is a very Midwestern,
`steel town' thing,'' he said. ``That, and Alfred Stieglitz and
Georgia O'Keeffe _ their relationship, New York and the
Southwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Up at KCD, the fashion production and publicity company, which
is in Bartlett's building, Ed Filapowski, a partner, was
auditioning models and going over seating for the Marc Jacobs show,
which will be seen on Monday night. KCD receives 5,000 requests for
seats to the shows it handles for Jacobs, Richard Tyler, Calvin
Klein and others.
</P>
<P>
   Filapowski and several colleagues were studying a large seating
chart for Jacobs' show. When an invited guest RSVP'd, a colored dot
with his or her name was stuck onto a seat on the chart _ orange
for the designer's friends, another color for celebrities. But few
of the celebrities had responded yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not into celebrities or anything,'' Marybeth Schmitt of
KCD said dryly, holding up sheets of dots with names of celebrities
invited on behalf of Jacobs, including Marilyn Manson, Courtney Cox
and Matt Dillon. ``Every celebrity there possibly is, we have a dot
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more than in past seasons, it seems, a flood of unknown
young designers are vying for the attention. On Friday, Harper's
Bazaar will be host for a store opening for Christine Ganeaux, 34,
on Crosby Street. The magazine sent out 650 invitations, but when
word got out that the magazine was touting a new designer, 150
extra requests for tickets came in. ``I mean, we're always sitting
around at Bazaar saying, `Are we going to wait for Bernard Arnault
to discover the next new talent?''' said Annemarie Iverson, fashion
and beauty director of Bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ganeaux, a former makeup artist, has captivated the
magazine's editors by creating what they consider the perfect pair
of shapely, hip-hugging pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of similar to how Daryl K started,'' Ms. Iverson
said. ``Christine changed the pattern like 40 times before she got
it right. It's hard to find a trouser that makes your butt look
good. And isn't that what defines a trouser right now?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
