<DOCNO> NYT19990208.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6940 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FASHION-ART-2NDTAK     02-08 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: right now?''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sandy Dalal, who won an award for new talent in men's wear last
year from the fashion industry's trade group, was shuttling between
a midtown garment factory and his design headquarters, in the
apartment he grew up in on West 58th Street. Unlike some of Seventh
Avenue's biggest names, Dalal had nearly all of his samples done _
trousers and shirts in old-school fabrics like Harris tweed, loden
and waxed cotton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live to be in the factory,'' said Dalal, a young man of 22
with a ponytail. ``Men traditionally _ forever, I think _ are just
not used to showing who they are. They just like stones. They're
just there, until you get to know them. I like my clothes to
express the same sentiment.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on West 39th Street, at the headquarters of Calvin
Klein, the designer was looking at a fitting model in different
women's trousers _ mostly narrow, low in the waist, with a felted
feel, which is turning up so many places this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all felted,'' Klein said. ``We've been felted for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   He got to talking about Gwyneth Paltrow, whom he had dressed in
a much-photographed silvery skirt with a strapless black top and
cardigan for the Golden Globes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking the Golden Globes is probably, like, a suit,''
he said. ``I didn't think it was that dressy, because I never watch
those things.''
</P>
<P>
   But the actress had fallen for the skirt. ``I was showing her
that possibility for later, but nobody wants to hear `later,''' he
said. ``She said, `No, I want to wear it now.' And now, all of a
sudden, we're getting stores saying they want it. Gwyneth is as
modern as they come.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at 550 Seventh, the garment district's most prestigious
address, Oscar de la Renta was in his studio, staring at a pair of
tobacco-brown pants and a little cropped sweater on his fitting
model. de la Renta believes in making the kind of clothes that
women wear. Last month, after his couture collection for Balmain in
Paris, the house sold 64 pieces the next day. ``Apparently, it was
like a basement sale,'' said de la Renta, who returned to New York
with a cold.
</P>
<P>
   A few floors higher in the building, Bill Blass, who had a mild
stroke in December, seemed to be back to his former grumpy self.
``You don't have a cigarette do you, kid?'' he asked a visitor, who
didn't. Blass, who will skip this month's fashion week and show in
April, has been told by his doctors to quit smoking, but he wasn't
entirely reformed. ``It tastes so much better when you sneak
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the 15th floor, Ms. Karan, draping fabric on a model last
Friday night, still seemingly far from having a collection ready,
nonetheless predicted that she will, once again, be ready when the
lights go up on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   She looked at a piece of crinkled off-white cotton. ``Now, this
is how the whole collection started, off this piece,'' she said.
``This is the original inspiration. So we are just playing.'' She
smiled wryly. ``It's about a lot of cotton. The big `C' _ cotton,
cashmere and candles.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
