<SLUG> BC-AIR-FORCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air Force to advertise on TV to boost recruiting
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery and Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time in its history the Air Force
will begin buying television time to run recruiting ads in hopes of
reversing enlistment declines caused by an enticing job market and
an increasingly hectic military life.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with a college basketball game at the end of the
month, the Air Force Recruiting Service will pour $17 million into
big-market TV buys using ads that previously ran on donated time as
public service announcements. At the same time, officials said
Monday, the Air Force is in the early phase of developing a
brand-new ad campaign that will open with the fall television
schedule and involve another $37 million in spending.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden change in philosophy and influx of cash to
advertising accounts follows poor recruiting performance in the
first months of this fiscal year. Starting in October, when the
federal budget for 1999 began, the Air Force has failed to meet
enlistment goals in three of the last four months, raising the
specter the service could miss year-end goals for the first time
since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel our competition is with local corporations and
colleges,'' said Tech Sgt. Jeff Bowser, who runs Dayton, Ohio's Air
Force recruiting office.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is twofold: The robust economy has given potential
recruits lots of alternatives to military service, and those who
opt to serve find the work pace difficult to take because the armed
forces have been shrinking at the same time that worldwide
peace-keeping missions have increased.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the quality of life for military service members has
been highlighted in Washington as all branches of the military have
seen enlistment and re-enlistment figures sag. President Clinton
proposed a 4.4 percent pay raise for all military personnel in his
2000 budget, and last October the Air Force set up an enlistment
bonus program offering up to $9,000 for prize recruits.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force advertising budget hasn't been raised to
accommodate higher media costs since 1990. The $17 million and $37
million allotments for broadcast time announced Monday will be
spent in addition to the Air Force's regular $16 million
advertising budget, which already was boosted by $6 million this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Bowser, a 20-year veteran, said the Dayton office usually meets
its recruiting goals, though it has been difficult.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the Air Force is struggling with recruiting is that
many people only enlist to learn skills such as computer
programming, then leave after four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of folks do use the Air Force as a stepping stone,''
Bowser said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery and Timothy R. Gaffney write for the Dayton
Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
