<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-WINDFALL-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK GETS WINDFALL FROM U.S. WELFARE-MONEY SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Pataki administration has quietly built up a
$500 million surplus in federal welfare money over the last two
years as a result of the dramatic decline in the number of people
on public assistance, and expects that sum to grow to $1.4 billion
in the next budget year.
</P>
<P>
   The administration acknowledged the existence of the surplus in
the text of the budget that Gov. George Pataki proposed two weeks
ago, but it went largely unnoticed by the Legislature. The budget
called for spending $1 billion of the welfare money on a range of
programs to help people make the transition from public assistance
to work. It also proposed keeping nearly $400 million in a reserve
fund to hedge against a downturn in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The $500 million in federal welfare money that the state has
already stockpiled means that the state's current budget surplus is
not $2 billion, as had been widely estimated, but $2.5 billion. The
revelation of this pot of money is likely to touch off a fierce
battle in the Legislature over how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   The amount that has piled up in New York's coffers dwarfs that
of neighboring states. In Connecticut, for example, state officials
have used almost all of its $534 million in federal welfare grants
over the last two years on child care and other programs for the
poor. In New Jersey, officials have a welfare surplus of $280
million for the two years but plan to use about $60 million of that
total to provide child care for the poor and to pay for
administrative costs associated with running poverty programs. The
rest will be kept in a rainy-day fund.
</P>
<P>
   The savings that New York has accumulated stems from extensive
changes that the federal government made to its welfare program in
1996. Under those changes, the government ceased paying states
according to the number of welfare recipients they have. Instead,
it provides states with block grants based on years when their
caseloads were high.
</P>
<P>
   Because most states have reduced their welfare caseloads in
recent years, the grants provide them with a financial windfall. In
the case of New York, where the welfare rolls have dropped
dramatically over the last four years, state officials receive
about $2.33 billion a year from the federal government. The money
can only be used to pay benefits or to establish programs that help
welfare recipients find work _ from job training to child care.
</P>
<P>
   Of the roughly $4.6 billion that New York has received over the
last two years, it has spent all but $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   The savings that the state has on hand, along with the $900
million it expects to save next year from its federal block grant,
places New York in a strong position to expand programs intended to
help recipients enter the work force. Advocates for the poor say
such programs are critically important now that the federal
government has set strict limits on the amount of time that people
are allowed to receive public assistance grants.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Karen Schimke, the executive director of the State Communities
Aid Society, an advocacy group for the poor, said the need to
expand such programs was particularly pressing because many of
those people who remained on the welfare rolls had inadequate
education and other problems that have made them difficult to
employ.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who are going to need lots of extra support
and services,'' she said. ``This money could be invaluable to
helping many recipients find and retain jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's welfare rolls have dropped by roughly 500,000 people
over the last four years, to about 978,000. Many experts credit the
decline to increased job opportunities that have come with a
booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the poor have been urging the state to use this
time of prosperity to rechannel money it is saving in decreased
welfare benefits to expand programs that will help poor people find
and keep jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal the governor submitted in his budget represents a
major commitment to that end, his aides said. But advocates for the
poor assert that the state should have already been investing that
money in such programs, instead of salting it away. Of the $1.4
billion that the state expects to save from its federal welfare
grant, the administration intends to spend $388 million next year
for a variety of programs that would provide additional day care
for poor parents.
</P>
</TEXT>
