<HEADER>
A7069 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      02-08 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSING ARGUMENTS GIVEN AS SENATE DELIBERATIONS TO BEGIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Struggling to revive their flagging impeachment
case during final arguments Monday, House prosecutors repeated
their plea to ``cleanse the office,'' by removing President
Clinton, then asked Senate leaders to extend the trial and consider
new evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful that the historic proceeding is likely to end this week,
White House lawyers countered by again poking holes in the
impeachment case, saying Republicans who want ``to win too badly''
are pushing the charges to ``achieve partisan ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators sitting in judgment of the president are set Tuesday to
begin deliberating, probably behind closed doors, whether to
convict Clinton on the charges contained in either of the two
articles of impeachment, which deal with perjury and obstruction of
justice.
</P>
<P>
   With the odds against two-thirds of the senators voting to
convict and remove the president, negotiations were under way among
Republicans and Democrats on a resolution to censure or condemn the
president for his affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky and his admitted effort to keep it secret.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to making their final plea to convict the president,
frustrated House prosecutors complained to senators about being
barred from presenting a full-blown case and challenged senators to
ignore the polls and Clinton apologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you decide will have a profound effect on our culture and
our politics,'' said Illinois Rep. Henry Hyde, the lead House
prosecutor, as he ridiculed senators' private discussions of a
censure resolution before voting on the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, do you really cleanse the office as provided in the
Constitution? Or do you use the Air Wick of a censure resolution?''
Hyde asked.
</P>
<P>
   In a last-ditch effort to keep the case against Clinton alive,
Hyde wrote to Senate leaders Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., asking them to allow prosecutors to investigate whether
White House aide Sidney Blumenthal committed perjury in videotaped
testimony shown Saturday on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde pressed the two leaders to have the Senate subpoena three
journalists who have submitted sworn statements claiming that
Blumenthal lied under oath when he testified that he never passed
on to reporters the president's claim that Lewinsky was a stalker.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, journalist Christopher Hitchens and his wife,
Carol Blue, signed affidavits stating that Blumenthal told them
that the former White House intern was a stalker. Journalist Scott
Armstrong signed an affidavit Monday saying that he was told by
Hitchens and Blue about their conversation with Blumenthal and the
``stalker'' comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president may have engaged in an intimidation campaign''
against Lewinsky in January 1998 and Blumenthal ``may have
testified falsely before the Senate,'' Hyde wrote, adding that it
could indicate a pattern by the Clinton White House of ``devising
schemes to undermine'' the credibility of potential witnesses
against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, who successfully blocked Lott's effort Monday to add
the Hitchens and Blue affidavits to the trial record, said
Democrats are prepared to object if any GOP senator seeks approval
of Hyde's request.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need additional witnesses,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   With deliberations to begin Tuesday in only the second
presidential impeachment trial, a move to allow the public to
observe the proceedings faded Monday when Lott announced his
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, who is working with
Democrats to open the debate, said ``it's going to be hard to meet
the two-thirds'' vote requirement to suspend a rule requiring
impeachment deliberations to be conducted in secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be difficult, but I have not given up hope,''
Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   The roll call votes on the two articles of impeachment _ which
Senate leaders say will be held no later than Friday _ will be in
public session.
</P>
<P>
   During almost six hours of closing arguments, Hyde's prosecutors
and White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff debated the fine points
of the charges against Clinton and whether the allegations, if
true, rise to the ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' standard for
removing a president as outlined in the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, a Florida Republican and House prosecutor,
challenged senators to run counter to the polls that show that most
Americans want Clinton to stay in office although they believe
Clinton lied under oath and obstructed justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the consequences of failing to remove this president
from office if you believe he's committed the crimes of perjury and
obstruction of justice?'' McCollum asked. ``Your vote to acquit
under these circumstances may well mean that no president in the
future will ever be impeached or removed for perjury or obstruction
of justice. Is that the record that you want?''
</P>
<P>
   Another prosecutor, Rep. Steve Chabot, R-Ohio, asked senators
how they want to be remembered by history. ``Will the final chapter
say that the Senate turned its back on perjury and obstruction of
justice by the president?'' Chabot asked. ``Or will it say that the
Senate took a principled stand and told the world that no person,
not even the president, stands above the law?''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, a former federal prosecutor and law professor, argued that
removing Clinton on the evidence presented by House prosecutors
would debase the intentions of the Founding Fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would it put at risk the liberties of the people to retain the
president in office?'' he asked. ``Putting aside partisan animus,
if you can honestly say that it would not, that those liberties are
safe in his hands, then you must vote to acquit.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Republicans who have argued for Clinton's removal, Ruff
said: ``I believe their vision to be too dark, a vision too little
attuned to the needs of the people. I believe it to be a vision
more focused on retribution, more designed to achieve partisan
ends, more uncaring about the future we face together.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to evidence and testimony that contradicts the
prosecutors' allegations and inferences, Ruff said: ``The stubborn
facts will not budge, nor will the stubborn denials by every
participant in their mythical plot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who had the last word in the debate, defended his team of
Republican prosecutors. None of them ``has committed perjury nor
obstructed justice nor claimed false privileges; none of us has
hidden evidence under anyone's bed nor encouraged false testimony
before the grand jury,'' Hyde said, referring to actions Clinton
allegedly instigated.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls show Americans growing tired of the
impeachment saga which grew out of a sex-and-lies scandal almost 13
months ago. Ruff and Hyde conceded that they too have grown weary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking the last steps along a path that for most of us
has seemed to be unending,'' Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, his voice betraying his resignation to the president's
impending acquittal, said: ``We are blessedly coming to the end of
this melancholy procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
