<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-EDUCATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PATAKI RETREATS ON EARLY EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Feb. 9: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki asserts that his budget for early-childhood
programs will give local school districts more flexibility in
spending. In fact, his budget would dismantle New York state's
fledgling universal pre-kindergarten program and harm efforts to
reduce class sizes statewide, with the worst impact on New York
City schools. Legislation passed in 1997 would have provided about
$245 million for several key programs, including pre-kindergarten
for 4-year-olds, smaller classes in the early grades and school
building maintenance. Pataki will trim that to $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   New York City's loss would be particularly painful. The $140
million it would otherwise have received will drop to $77 million
under Pataki's plan. The city has undertaken a tremendous effort to
create a citywide pre-kindergarten program that is now serving
about 14,000 children. It had hoped to receive increased state
support to serve 28,000 children next year, and to serve all
112,000 4-year-olds in the city by 2002, a goal set by the state's
1997 universal pre-K law. The Pataki cuts wipe out the possibility
of expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki insists that the city will not see any less money. He
says he can use $100 million in new federal class-size-reduction
money to substitute for the loss of state funds. But the federal
government may not allow that to happen. The federal law clearly
says that federal money may be used only to supplement state and
local aid, not supplant them. Even using both state and federal
class-size money, New York City will not be able to reduce class
sizes in kindergarten through third grade from an average of 27 to
20 until 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the worst aspect of Pataki's plan is that it would
replace the various early-education programs with a general block
grant. That would eliminate all state leadership in those reforms,
and make it likely that districts will pull back on those programs
and simply use the block grants to fill holes in their budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the governor boasted of the state's efforts to expand
pre-kindergarten to all children. Investing in early education and
smaller classes returns high dividends in academic achievement. He
has a few weeks to amend his budget. He needs to reverse course and
make good on those commitments now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
