u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITRUS-CANKER-COX     02-08 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITRUS-CANKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Citrus canker feared in Hendry
 &HT;    By Sanjay Bhatt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Asian citrus canker, lethal to citrus
trees but harmless to people and animals, might have struck the
state's largest citrus-growing county for the first time, officials
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The suspected infection of 200 grapefruit trees in a 300-acre
commercial grove in Hendry County, just west of Palm Beach County,
could compromise a state plan to halt the spread of the disease.
The only way to stop the disease is to destroy infected trees.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture officials are expected back in the Hendry County
grove today to conduct more tests.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, state officials had proposed spending $18
million for uprooting about 54,000 citrus trees and creating a
mile-wide buffer zone in Broward County from the Atlantic Ocean to
the Everglades. The idea was to keep canker, which already has been
found in Miami-Dade and southern Broward counties, from spreading
northward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to have to reevaluate the tactic,'' said
Ron Hamel, general manager of the Gulf Citrus Growers Association,
which represents 181 citrus growers.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's discovery marked the first time canker has been found
in Hendry County, Hamel said.
</P>
<P>
   Once canker infects a tree, it spreads rapidly, causing fruit to
drop prematurely and lesions to appear on the leaves, stems and
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Canker also might have infected about 80 properties in Broward
County over a 3-square-mile area in southeast Coral Springs, state
agricultural officials said Monday. A district plant inspector
initially found signs of canker in a single grapefruit tree in a
residential yard during routine inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Plant pathologists with the state's Department of Agriculture
and Consumer Services made the canker diagnosis during the weekend
and will return to the Hendry County grove today to confirm their
suspicions, said Jack Neitzke, a spokesman for the eradication
project in Immokalee.
</P>
<P>
   Growers express concern
</P>
<P>
   If the grove is infected with canker, a quarantine area will be
established and movement of workers, citrus and equipment will be
restricted, Neitzke said. After a canker infection in Collier
County last July, officials set up a quarantine zone covering 27
square miles.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria could have been carried to the grove by grass
clippings, leaves, equipment, people or rain from an infected area,
Neitzke said.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Florida in Gainesville, U.S. Department of
Agriculture and a private Indiana laboratory also are conducting
tests to confirm the findings, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Following news of the outbreak Monday, industry officials urged
state officials to spend $166 million during the next 3 1/2 years
for more canker-eradication efforts. Reports of the disease could
force trading partners to reject shipments of Florida citrus, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The virulent bacterial disease could wipe out the industry,
which generates an economic impact of $8.55 billion, employs
121,000 people and covers 845,260 acres,'' said Andy LaVigne,
executive vice president of Florida Citrus Mutual, the state's
largest citrus grower organization, with 12,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   In the early to mid-1980s, the state's largest outbreak of
canker forced agriculture officials to destroy 20 million citrus
trees in nurseries throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Sanjay Bhatt writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
