<HEADLINE>
DRIVER WILL FACE MURDER CHARGES IN CRASH THAT KILLED 3 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERHEAD, N.Y. _ As part of an emerging statewide trend toward
tougher prosecution of drunken drivers, the Suffolk County district
attorney filed second-degree murder charges Monday against a
36-year-old motorist for the deaths of three people in a fiery
crash on the Long Island Expressway on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Rodriguez of Medford, N.Y., a jail guard in New York City,
was arraigned in a 21-count indictment in Suffolk County Criminal
Court here Monday morning and was ordered held without bail in the
Suffolk County jail by Judge Louis Ohlig.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, drunken drivers who killed people in accidents have
been charged with vehicular homicide. Under New York law, that
means they showed a ``reckless disregard'' for life. But in a
series of independent decisions by prosecutors, drunken drivers
have recently been charged with second-degree murder, which
requires proof of a ``depraved indifference to human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeanine Pirro, the Westchester County district attorney and
president-elect of the New York State Association of District
Attorneys, said Monday that ``an automobile is essentially as
dangerous as a knife or a gun if it is used with depraved
indifference to human life.''
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of the second-degree murder charges, Rodriguez
could be sentenced to a maximum of 25 years to life in prison. A
charge of vehicular homicide carries a sentence of 5 to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses have told investigators that Rodriguez was speeding,
possibly going as fast as 90 miles an hour, and was weaving across
the expressway when his 1997 Kia rammed a Chevrolet Chevette in the
rear about 11:40 p.m. The impact cut fuel lines in the Chevette,
which burst into flames, killing three of the people inside the car
and critically injuring a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who pleaded not guilty, had been on his way home from
work at Rikers Island, investigators said. When tested several
hours after the accident, they said, his blood alcohol level
measured .13 percent, above the level of .10 percent at which a
driver is legally intoxicated in New York State.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pirro and James M. Cattertson, the Suffolk County district
attorney, are urging district attorneys throughout the state to
consider a similar upgrading of charges against drunken drivers
involved in vehicular homicides.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Fisher Riccardella, the president of the New York State
chapter of MADD, or Mothers Against Drunk Driving, said there had
been five prosecutions and convictions for second-degree murder
statewide in cases involving drunken drivers since 1997. She said
the convictions indicated that juries were willing to support the
tough charges.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald L. Kuby, a Manhattan trial and civil rights lawyer,
likened ``depraved indifference'' to firing a gun into an occupied
building. ``Similarly, this could be applied to someone who is
drunk who gets behind the wheel of a car and drives at a high rate
of speed,'' he said. ``There does not have to be an intent to kill,
just a conscious disregard of the risk, knowing it's wrong but
doing it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen family members and friends of the Long Island
victims attended Monday's arraignment. They said they were pleased
with the tough charges brought against Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not an accident. It was murder,'' said the Rev. James
Trent, the grandfather of one of the victims, Pascal Lee Trent, 16,
of Riverhead.
</P>
<P>
   The other two people who died in the crash were Matthew
Marcotrigiano, 21, of Wading River, N.Y., and Norma Vestal, 17, of
Riverhead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
