<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREAK HAS PROVEN IT'S A FLYERS' MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Of course, if they bomb once again in the
playoffs, none of what the Philadelphia Flyers have done in the
past two months will matter much at all.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, however, it's getting a little scary.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers visit the Anaheim Mighty Ducks on Wednesday and the
Los Angeles Kings the next night, and right now they are the
hottest team in hockey, and that includes the Colorado Avalanche,
12-game winning streak and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're intimidating by their skill,'' Kings center Ray
Ferraro said of the Flyers, who are 16-1-7 in their past 24 games.
``You know if you don't play very well against them, they're going
to hand it to you. You have to respect them. But you can't give
them any more room than anyone else. If you do, they're better than
most teams and they'll shove it down your throat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers have been shoving it down people's throats since this
remarkable stretch began with a victory at Toronto on Dec. 12.
Philadelphia began a 15-game unbeaten streak that night, lost at
home to the Maple Leafs on Jan. 16, and are unbeaten in eight games
since then.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive as it is that Eric Lindros is second in scoring with
70 points and that teammate John LeClair is tied for third with 66,
what is even more significant is that in terms of scoring at even
strength, Lindros and LeClair are first and second in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   They have plenty of help in a deep lineup, and goalie John
Vanbiesbrouck has been everything Philadelphia hoped he would be
when the Flyers signed him last summer as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see,'' said Kings coach Larry Robinson, whose team lost
4-2 to the Flyers eight days ago, ``is that they've gone from being
a team that used to go into buildings and try to intimidate you
with big forwards, who could bang but weren't that gifted, to a
team with four balanced lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to them is still Lindros and LeClair. You have to
respect that. But if you contain that line, you still have to worry
about their other players. You've got to be at the top of your game
against them. They don't have a lot of weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Jolted bolts: Tampa Bay's miserable season hit a new low last
week when the Lightning allowed eight second-period goals in a 10-1
loss at Washington. The Capitals had 25 shots on goal in the period
and scored five of their goals in a 3:54 span.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Demers, the Lightning's coach and general manager, had
the good fortune to miss the game because he was attending GM
meetings in Palm Springs. Associate coach Rick Paterson served as
the interim coach, a role in which he has posted a perfectly
horrible record of 0-10 over the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know what to say anymore,'' said the Lightning's
Mikael Andersson. ``It's getting old. I've been here since the
beginning _ seven years _ and I can't ever remember it being this
bad. It was an embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Iron Man: Detroit's Larry Murphy, who began his career with the
Kings in 1980-81, surpassed late Toronto great Tim Horton for games
played by a defenseman when he appeared in his 1,447th game last
week. He's missed only 26 games in his 19-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no secret to it, I promise,'' Murphy said. ``I've been
through some injuries, but it's either been over the All-Star break
or something like that. It's always worked out where I haven't
missed too much. I've just been extremely fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy has played seven seasons in which he didn't miss a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be that durable for that amount of time in this league is
very special,'' Boston defenseman Ray Bourque said. ``I know how
tough it is to keep your health in this game when you're getting
hit left and right and the wear and tear of the schedule and the
grind of things and what it takes to go out and compete every
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murph has played one less year than I have and has played more
games than me, and I haven't missed all that many. To be where he
is now and the amount of years he's played is pretty scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting Ducks: The Mighty Ducks have two marquee players in Paul
Kariya and Teemu Selanne. The Kings are still looking for one,
since Luc Robitaille for some strange reason doesn't seem to
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   There's been much talk about the Kings making a move to acquire
a gate attraction and little talk of the Ducks making a move, even
though their record isn't much better than the Kings'. But it
doesn't sound as if the Ducks are likely to make a significant
transaction before the March 23 trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 365 days a year we try to improve the club,'' general
manager Pierre Gauthier said. ``I tell you today, patience is very
important. It's also a very tough thing _ patience _ because I have
emotions, too. I want to do something. But what can I do today that
can make the team better? A lot of times the best thing to do is
nothing.`
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Buffalo's Matthew Barnaby has been the subject of
numerous trade rumors, and the No.1 rumormonger has been Barnaby
himself. He is likely to be traded, but perhaps not quite as
quickly as he'd like. Chicago, Detroit and Calgary are believed to
be among the interested.... The Sabres claim they are on pace to
lose $15 million this season and are looking to restructure their
lease at their county-owned arena.... Former Calgary Flame Hakan
Loob, who returned to his native Sweden in 1989 at age 28 only a
year after a 50-goal season, has a 17-year-old son, Henrik, who is
eligible for this year's draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
