<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cleveland to stock its team in today's expansion draft
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ It's the NFL's version of an archeological find
and Cleveland Browns Coach Chris Palmer is ready to do some heavy
excavating.
</P>
<P>
   His goal is to uncover some gems among the 150 veterans left
unprotected by their clubs when the Browns expansion draft unfolds
at 4 p.m. today at the Canton Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   As the next step in the rebirth of pro football in Cleveland,
the Browns _ who make their NFL return Aug. 9 against Dallas in the
Hall of Fame game here _ must select between 30 and 42 players with
total salaries not to exceed 38 percent of the estimated $58
million salary cap. An existing club can recall one player from its
five-man list after one of its players is selected. After a second
player is selected from a club, that club can pull back both of its
remaining players.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer gave every indication that he may pass on most of the
high-priced players _ whose contracts the Browns would inherit _
and take younger, hungrier and cheaper talent as he stockpiles his
roster for the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expansion draft is not going to give you anyone you're
going to write home about,'' Palmer said. ``The talent level will
not be what we want to start with. They're giving someone up, so
there is a problem there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are diamonds in the rough. We just have to be lucky
and hit on those guys. If they come in here, see an opportunity and
are treated right, they'll want to be part of the situation and
they'll step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer warned Browns fans not to get too excited about an
expansion list that includes nine players who have been selected to
a total of 32 Pro Bowls, and 13 former first-round draft picks. He
said he'd be happy to draft five guys who could make an impact in
'99.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message to those guys will be: `You're going to prove that
somebody made a mistake putting you on that board or they were
right,''' Palmer said. ``That's my job as a motivator. It's not
going to be a long message, but it's going to be to the point. You
can prove that team wrong, or prove them right.''
</P>
<P>
   The ex-Pro Bowlers on the list are Washington's trio of tailback
Terry Allen, cornerback Cris Dishman and quarterback Gus Frerotte;
Seattle center Kevin Glover; Dallas fullback Daryl Johnston; Green
Bay's kick returner Roell Preston and defensive end Reggie White;
Pittsburgh guard Will Wolford; and Denver defensive end Neil Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Denver cornerback Darrien Gordon, who had two interceptions in
the Broncos' 34-19 victory over Atlanta in Super Bowl XXXIII, and
White _ a 13-time Pro Bowler and the NFL's career sacks leader _
top the list of former first-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   The others are Seattle tailback Steve Broussard, Oakland's
defensive end Aundray Bruce and wide receiver Desmond Howard,
Jacksonville defensive back Deon Figures, Cincinnati linebacker
James Francis, Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
