u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NASCAR-STEWART-CO     02-08 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-STEWART-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stewart set to impress in WC debut
 &HT;    By Ron Ware
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Five days still remain before Tony Stewart
officially makes his NASCAR Winston Cup debut in the biggest race
on the schedule. But he's already learning exactly what it's like
spending life in the fast lane.
</P>
<P>
   And if he needed any reminding, there it was the other day in
the pages of the Charlotte Observer, his adopted hometown
newspaper. In a story previewing the Daytona 500 and the coming
season, the paper decided that unless the 27-year-old wins rookie
of the year honors, ``whispers of overrated might start.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart reacted in the same way anyone who has ever see him
hustle a midget around a Midwestern dirt track might expect, which
is to say his jaw jutted, a glint appeared in his eyes and you
half-wondered if he was going to take off after the writer right
then, a la A.J. Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just gives me something to shoot for,'' he responded, the
words coming in a rush. ``I know I have to prove myself. There's a
lot of people in this part of the country that don't know a lot
about me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to go out and do what I've done in every other
series I've been in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   So there. If you don't like him, fine, cram it up your tailpipe.
But keep those stopwatches handy.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, the 1997 Indy Racing League champion, promises to do
every he can to win friends and influence people in Sunday's 41st
Daytona 500 (12:15 p.m., CBS-TV). He surprisingly qualified on the
outside of the front row at 194.599 mph, alongside none other than
Jeff Gordon, flashing the talent former NFL coach Joe Gibbs spotted
when he hired him to drive his No. 20 Home Depot Pontiac as a
teammate to Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart, whose brash confidence often is mistaken for
arrogance, knows he still has a lot to learn, especially in driving
a 3,400-pound stock car in the draft. Gordon warned him that
drivers like Dale Earnhardt will be trying to ``school him,'' and
he quickly agreed, joking that he was trying to figure out how to
mount a pad and pencil in the car so that he can take notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to take this first season to gain as much knowledge as
I can,'' Stewart said. ``I don't want to be the guy who causes the
20-car pileup on Sunday. I'm going to need to be real patient. If
that means going to the back and coming back up later in the race,
I'll do that if I have to. I want to be around at the end of the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he'll be driving like the typical Floridian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be a rookie in Winston Cup racing,'' said Stewart, who
started out in go-karts and won four USAC national championships on
the way up, ``but this is my 20th year. When they drop the green
flag, I'll go.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart is one of six drivers who'll chase rookie honors this
season. His chief rivals are Elliott Sadler, 23, who's with the
fabled but fading Wood Brothers, and Roy ``Buckshot'' Jones, 28,
driving for a team assembled by his father, Billy, who's already
poured an astonishing $14 million into his career.
</P>
<P>
   None of the others qualified better than 29th for Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm the underdog to Stewart, honestly,'' Sadler
said. ``He's done amazing things in his IRL career and in midgets
and so forth. I'm a big Tony Stewart fan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really think until you get a couple races in that
you'll have a favorite (for the rookie award),'' Jones said. ``But
Tony, coming right out of the box like that, he's sure to be the
fan favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he plans to compete again this year in the Indianapolis
500 _ he'll also race the same day in the Coca-Cola 600 at
Charlotte _ Stewart intends to spent the rest of his career in
Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   As much as he wants to impress on Sunday, he also wants to earn
the respect of his fellow drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time working my way up to this point,'' he
said. ``This is the best series in the world, and I plan to be here
a long time. This is where I want to spend the next 20-30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Ware writes for the Springfield News-Sun, Springfield, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
