<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-NOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR NOTES: Marcis improves Daytona chances
 &HT;    By Ron Ware
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Of all the current streaks in big-time
stock car racing _ from Jeff Gordon's two straight titles to
Michael Waltrip's 394-race winless drought _ one of the most
remarkable has sprung from one of the least likely sources.
</P>
<P>
   For 31 consecutive years, Dave Marcis, now 57 and still
virtually broke, has qualified for the Daytona 500. And after
Tuesday's second round of time trials for the 41st edition of
NASCAR's premier event, there's a much better chance the streak
won't go bust.
</P>
<P>
   Marcis, driving the No. 71 Team Realtree Chevrolet that he owns,
jumped to 23rd overall after turning a lap of 192.794 mph at
Daytona International Speedway, moving up nine spots. Under the
unique qualifying format used here, that likely will be good enough
to earn him a spot in Sunday's 12:15 p.m. race, even if he falters
in Thursday's Twin 125s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I want to continue if I can,'' said Marcis,
whose streak becomes even more remarkable considering he qualified
for only 13 of 33 Winston Cup races last season. ``My goal is just
to get (the car) better if I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Jeff Gordon and Tony Stewart, who qualified 1-2 in
Saturday's first round, have clinched their starting positions. All
other drivers faced a choice of standing on their time or
forfeiting it and requalifying Tuesday or today. The speeds
determine the starting order for Thursday's qualifying races, with
the top 14 finishers in each filling positions 3-30 on Sunday. The
remainder of the 43-car lineup will consist of the six fastest
qualifiers who otherwise didn't make it, plus seven provisionals,
based on 1998 car owner points.
</P>
<P>
   Marcis, who won five Winston Cup races between 1975-82, picked
up 2/10ths of a second over his first-round speed of 191.955 but
was looking for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt that that's good enough, but it could be,'' he said,
erring on the side of caution. ``It depends on how clean the 125s
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight drivers participated in second-round qualifying, with
Steve Park inching up one spot to 25th and Derrick Cope moving up
six places to 31st after leasing an engine from Team Sabco. Making
insignificant progress were Robert Pressley, Dick Trickle, Ted
Musgrave, Jim Sauter (in Marcis' backup car) and Norm Benning.
</P>
<P>
   STRAIT SHOOTING: Bob Strait's spirits were sagging following
Sunday's ARCA race, but they may be getting a boost. He said it's
``90 percent certain'' that he'll attempt to make his Winston Cup
debut in the April 25 DieHard 500 at Talladega, driving a car
fielded by ARCA veteran Mark Thompson. His brother, Don, is co-crew
chief for Thompson's team.
</P>
<P>
   Strait, who drives for Harmony's Jack Bowsher on the ARCA
circuit, owns 14 career wins in that series and finished 11th in
the NASCAR Truck standings in 1995. But he's never driven in a
Winston Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'd be pretty neat at my age, wouldn't it?'' said Strait,
who'll turn 50 two weeks before the Talladega race. ``I drove in
the Twin 125s here one year (1992), but I've driven been in a
Winston Cup points race.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Trickle could serve as Strait's inspiration. He was 48 when
he won Winston Cup rookie of the year honors in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ON TO ATLANTA: Josh Baltes has found his sugar daddy _ in his
own household.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton, Ohio native's season was in doubt following his
crash in practice for Sunday's ARCA race, but his father, Terry,
said the cash-strapped team definitely would compete March 12 at
Atlanta Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of their season remains in doubt, however, unless
sponsorship is secured.
</P>
<P>
   Baltes, who relocated to Mooresville, N.C., in December, was the
1997 ARCA rookie of the year but is still searching for his first
ARCA victory. He's driving for a new team headed by Tom Sokolosky,
who guided Tim Steele to two of his three series titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how thrilled and excited I am to be a part of
this organization,'' said Baltes, grandson of Eldora Speedway owner
Earl Baltes. ``They're kind of going out on a limb with me. (I)
haven't proved a lot in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think now I've got the team to do it with.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Ware writes for The Springfield News-Sun, Springfield, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
