</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUFF-MOTHER-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROUD PRESS AGENT WITH AN EYE FOR FLAIR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ohio, Utah)  (nk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Margaret Carson is the proud mother of Charles F.C.
Ruff, the chief White House counsel, who made the closing argument
Monday for President Clinton in the Senate impeachment trial, so it
is understandable that his performance moved her to hyperbole and
tears. ``I think he has a sense of drama that's extraordinary,''
she said. ``Laurence Olivier couldn't do it any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carson does understand dramatic flair. She was Leonard
Bernstein's longtime press agent, which is what they called them
before the word publicist walked in on high heels. But when she was
called the other day for an interview about her son and her life,
she declined at first. ``I'll just be a maternal bore,'' she said.
With cajoling, she relented. Mrs. Carson turned out to be maternal,
but not a bore.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting thing she said, before we get to how she
raised a White House counsel, was that Theodore Dreiser once made a
pass at her. It was the mid-1940s, Mrs. Carson was handling the
press for the American Academy and Institute of Arts and Letters,
and Dreiser, who was in his 70s, the author of ``An American
Tragedy'' and ``Sister Carrie,'' was there for an award. He took an
instant liking to Mrs. Carson, who was in her 30s and sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so cornball, I can't tell you,'' Mrs. Carson said. ``He
wrote me the corniest letter, and made the corniest pass at me.
Clumsy, I should say, rather than corny. But we girls knew how to
take care of that in those days. We didn't call it sexual
harassment. But you know something? He made a pass at everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carson, 87, is now a consultant to Amberson, the Bernstein
production company, and still represents conductor Michael Tilson
Thomas. ``My other genius,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York music world, people call her a force of nature.
``Somewhat larger than life,'' said her son, Ruff, on Sunday. Mrs.
Carson was also the press representative for the Metropolitan Opera
under Edward Johnson and Sir Rudolf Bing, and so took her son to
see ``Aida,'' his first opera, when he was 5. ``I got to spend my
Saturday afternoons behind the scenes at the Met,'' Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   It comes as no surprise to his mother that Ruff, in a passing
mention in the Senate to Linda Tripp on Jan. 19, wickedly referred
to Iago's use of a handkerchief to betray Desdemona.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends called and said, `I see Chuck is quoting
Shakespeare,' '' Mrs. Carson said. ``I said that I didn't think he
was referring to Shakespeare. I think he was referring to Verdi.
Because he knows the opera `Othello.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Ruff said his reference ``encompassed both,'' but that his
pronunciation of Desdemona was from the play rather than from the
Italian opera. Then he said, ``but this gets too fancy.'')
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carson spoke in her Upper East Side apartment, which is
filled with Japanese screen paintings and dreamy pictures of a
young Leonard Bernstein. She wore a sweater with tigerlike stripes
of taupe and black, had a theatrical manner and looked good.
``Thanks, I need that,'' she said when told. ``My memory's fine and
dandy, but I can't see very well.'' She has macular degeneration, a
progressive eye disorder. She loves music and musicians _ ``they're
hearty and lusty'' _ but is private about her own life.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sketchy outline. She was born in Salt Lake City, where
her father owned a small department store; moved to Ohio when she
was 9, majored in political science at the University of Toledo and
received a master's degree in social administration at Ohio State.
She married and was divorced from Charles Carson, a reporter and
editor in Cleveland; found work as a press agent in New York, then
married and was divorced from Carl N. Ruff, also a press agent who
died last year. She has two children: Charles Ruff, 59, who is the
son of Carson but was adopted by Carl Ruff, and Carla, her daughter
with Carl Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing up Charles was easy. ``Chuck read at an early age, and
that was the blessing of all time,'' Mrs. Carson said. She saw to
his education, got a good housekeeper and did not feel guilty about
working. Ruff started out in public school on the Upper East Side
in the 1940s and by 12 was at boarding school at Phillips Academy
in Andover, Mass. He went on to Swarthmore College and Columbia
University School of Law. He knew Leonard Bernstein from childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lenny used to come over to the apartment and play the piano,
and play Chopin, and Debussy, and then jazz,'' Mrs. Carson said.
``He was wonderful. And he was wonderful with my son.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1965, while teaching in Africa, that Ruff, by then
married and awaiting the birth of his first child, came down with a
poliolike virus that has left him in a wheelchair ever since. ``He
was taken to a hospital in the wilds of Liberia,'' Mrs. Carson
said. ``I learned of it through a ham operator on Long Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Her reaction was maternal. ``I did a couple of things,'' she
said. ``I went to woodworking class, which was physical labor. And
I took up golf, which is hitting a ball very hard against the wall.
It makes a big noise.'' A pause. ``Which is better than hitting
people.'' Another pause. ``He's handled it extremely well. Better
than I.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carson has been spellbound watching her son's professorial,
emotional and at times sarcastic performances in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say you must be very proud,'' she said. ``I'm bursting
with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
