<HEADER>
A7091 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SALT-LAKE-NYT &LR;      02-08 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SALT-LAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHICS PANEL WILL REPORT ON OLYMPIC PAYMENTS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Three years from the start of the 2002 Winter
Games, local Olympic officials Monday prepared for a watershed week
in which they will detail improprieties involved in securing the
Olympics and perhaps name a leader who can begin to repair the
tarnished image of their Games.
</P>
<P>
   A lengthy report by the local Olympic organizing committee's
internal ethics panel is scheduled for release on Tuesday morning.
According to Olympic officials who have been told about the report,
it was expected to say that there was limited knowledge among Salt
Lake City officials about improper cash payments, tuition aid,
medical treatment, jobs and lavish gifts provided to members of the
International Olympic Committee and their families.
</P>
<P>
   An official who saw the report said Monday that it would
primarily target two top officials of the bid committee, Tom Welch
and Dave Johnson, and accuse them of hidden payments and deceptive
practices that kept other members of the committee from knowing
what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   Such a conclusion was foreshadowed last week by Utah Gov.
Michael O. Leavitt. Without naming names, the Governor portrayed
the payment of improper inducements as a ``pattern of deception''
by a small group of rogue officials of the bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to hide it, because I didn't see it and I don't know
at this point of anybody else who did,'' Leavitt said at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt has also acknowledged that the report would not provide
a complete picture of the corruption scandal. The five-person
ethics panel, headed by Gordon R. Hall, a former chief justice of
the Utah Supreme Court, did not have subpoena power, and some top
Olympic officials, including the bid committee's chief
administrative officer, declined to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Welch was president of the bid committee and Johnson head of its
international relations. Both Welch and Johnson have resigned, but
they have denied wrongdoing and have said that details of the
aggressive campaign to win the Games were widely known. Welch has
said that Leavitt, Salt Lake City Mayor Deedee Corradini and Frank
Joklik, the chairman of the bid committee, were all aware of at
least some aspects of the extravagant efforts to secure the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Documents of the Salt Lake bid committee have shown that
programs for tuition aid and grants to national Olympic committees
were detailed in open budget documents. Leavitt has acknowledged
giving out expensive gifts to IOC members. But he also said he did
not know of rules limiting the price of gifts or that the bid
committee had made cash payments or paid for scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported last week that Joklik and another
member of the board of trustees of the bid committee wrote letters
seeking employment for the husband of an international committee
member from Finland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to say Welch and Johnson were off the
reservation, but it's going to be hard to say that no one had any
idea what was going on and they engaged in a cover-up,'' said
Stephen Pace, who heads a group called Utahans for Responsible
Public Spending and who has been a longtime critic of the Salt Lake
City bid process.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the IOC and the U.S. Olympic Committee scrambled
Monday to obtain advance notice of the contents of the ethics
panel's report. Richard Pound, the Montreal attorney who is
handling the investigation of the IOC's involvement in the scandal,
said that he would not conclude his investigation until the Salt
Lake City report is issued.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen international committee members have so far been
implicated in the scandal. Six have been expelled, three have
resigned, three remain under investigation, one has been issued a
warning and one has died. The cost for lavish favors, as well as
legitimate travel and accommodation expenses, may have reached $3
million.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three members remaining under investigation, the most
powerful is Kim Un Yong of South Korea, a member of the IOC's
executive board who has often been mentioned as a possible
successor as president to Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's future is now in jeopardy and a stinging rebuke of his
actions by the Salt Lake City ethics panel could lead the IOC to
try to expel him. Kim is not likely to go quietly, and his
departure could lead to political infighting and charges and
countercharges of further improper conduct.
</P>
<P>
   It has previously been reported that Kim's son was employed by a
local satellite communications company, which was reimbursed for
his salary by the Salt Lake City bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   David Simmons, the former chairman of Keystone Communications,
which has since been sold, said Monday that the bid committee paid
about $45,000 of the $75,000 salary that Kim's son received for a
year's work and that the rest was covered by other local companies.
The amounts were first reported Monday by USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics panel report is also expected to deal with subjects
such as other jobs provided for relatives of international
committee members; whether money intended for tuition aid was used
for other purposes; whether money was pocketed from airline-ticket
reimbursement schemes; the extent of lavish gift-giving, and
conflicts of interest that existed among members of the bid
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of conflicts were underscored by an outside audit
performed last August by Deloitte &AMP; Touche. The audit showed out
that approximately $50 million of a $68.3 million commitment for
construction and professional services is with entities controlled
by individuals who are, or who have officers who are, members of
the organizing committee's board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prevailing opinion is that the report will implicate
people we already know about, under the theory that if you get rid
of them, you solve the problem,'' said one investigator, speaking
on the condition of anonymity. ``But that doesn't solve the
systemic problem. The IOC is set up in a structure of quid pro quo
and patronage. There are no controls in place, no accountability.
That is what really has to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Also this week, the Salt Lake Organizing Committee is expected
to undergo structural changes designed to increase representation
by community members and athletes, to reduce secrecy and to create
more reliable oversight. The organizing committee is expected to be
expanded from 33 to 50 or 51 members, though some officials have
complained that its size will make the committee too unwieldy.
</P>
<P>
   A new president of the organizing committee could also be named
this week. Joklik resigned on Jan. 8, but is remaining in the
position until a successor can be found. The leading candidate is
Mitt Romney, 51, the son of the former Michigan governor George W.
Romney and a political aspirant himself who lost a U.S. Senate race
to Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who takes over the organizing committee must be
prepared for further buffeting. The U.S. Justice Department is also
investigating the scandal, and its results are not expected for
five or six months. If criminal wrongdoing is found, Salt Lake City
would suffer another blow to its image, public confidence could
wane and sponsors would become even more nervous than they are now.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
