<HEADER>
A7093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TRASH-ART-NYT &LR;      02-08 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TRASH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. FOSTER, RECENTLY HOMELESS, FINDS ONE THAT FITS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Museum of the City of New York hung a painting of
Andrew Foster Esq. on Monday morning with an unusual amount of
fanfare, considering that the mid-19th-century portrait is a lot
like 100 or so others owned by the museum. Several visitors, two
photographers and the museum's director, Robert R. Macdonald, were
on hand when workers placed the portrait in a light blue gallery on
the second floor. It was too early for Champagne, but there was
coffee, breakfast rolls and speeches.
</P>
<P>
   When Foster was last seen, in July 1997, he was homeless. The
painting _ worn, punctured and loose on its stretcher _ had been
rescued six months earlier from a trash pile on East 65th Street by
John W. Nichols, the director of museum services for the American
Federation of the Arts, a nonprofit group that organizes art
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols had noticed, inscribed on the back, Foster's name, the
date 1848 and the mark of the renowned portrait studio of Samuel
Lovett Waldo and William Jewett (many of whose works are owned by
museums, including the Metropolitan Museum of Art). When he
researched Foster, he discovered that he was one of the wealthiest
New Yorkers of his era.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nichols found no takers when he tried to sell the work at
auction or donate it to several museums, including the Museum of
the City of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, he mentioned his story to a reporter for The New
York Times, which ran an article about it. At the time, Barbara
Ball Buff, a curator at the Museum of the City of New York, said:
``It's one of the more beautiful Waldo and Jewett paintings. Sadly,
we can't take anything in that condition.''
</P>
<P>
   No one wanted to spend the cost of conservation, estimated to be
at least $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Foster got another chance to become a museum piece when
Margaret Holben Ellis, chairwoman of the Conservation Center at the
Institute of Fine Arts at New York University, read the article.
``I remember thinking it would be perfect for the Museum of the
City of New York,'' she said. ``I have very loyal feelings for that
museum. I had worked there when I was in college.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ellis called Jan Ramirez, the museum's deputy director for
programs and collections. She volunteered to have a student repair
the painting, free, if Nichols would agree to donate it to the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   He did, and Elise Effmann, a third-year graduate student, got to
work. She carefully repaired the tears, stabilized the paint to
prevent further flaking, filled in the areas where paint had been
lost and added new canvas to the painting's edges so it could be
restretched.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ms. Buff and others at the museum were doing
research. They found that Foster had lived in a house on Bowling
Green in lower Manhattan near Stephen Whitney, a cotton trader
whose American Empire-style furniture is on display at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   They also discovered that although Bowling Green had only about
dozen houses at the time, the museum owns a Waldo and Jewett
portrait of another neighbor, Peter Remsen.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's portrait now hangs around the corner and down the hall
from the Whitney period alcove; Remsen's likeness, now in storage,
will be hung near Foster's. ``It's a reassembling of the
neighborhood,'' Ms. Ramirez said. ``The painting was destined to be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Macdonald, who was furious when he learned that his staff had
initially rejected the painting, was buoyant Monday as he thanked
Nichols with a seal created for the museum's 75th anniversary and a
catalog of Berenice Abbott's photographs of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years a lot of things have been abandoned on the
streets of New York, including people,'' he said. ``But this was a
great moment of being able to save a painting of some consequence.
And it is a great example of collaboration among institutions and a
testament to the importance of conservators to museums.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols, who visited the conservators several times, marveled at
Foster's new appearance. ``So much was revealed by their work,'' he
said, pointing out the initials on Foster's cane, the veins in his
hand and the column behind him.
</P>
<P>
   To the museum, the story seems so compelling, in fact, that it
is constructing an exhibition on its Web site about the painting's
history. It is set to be available on Friday at www.mcny.org under
``Behind the Scenes.'' Part 2 of the story, illustrating the
portrait's conservation, will go up later this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
