<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOISO FEELING ROUGHED UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Bruins face their most difficult challenge of
the season Thursday at Stanford with one of their best players in
poor form and poor health.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Moiso is beaten up and it shows.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-foot-10 freshman from Guadeloupe who attended high school in
France, Moiso has a skinny frame and a finesse game. The Pac-10's
rugged schedule and physical play have left him bruised and
battered. He has developed tendinitis in his right foot and felt a
few twinges in his left foot, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The effects are apparent: After scoring 68 points in a four-game
span (USC, Louisville and the Washington schools) Moiso scored just
11 points last weekend against the Oregon schools.
</P>
<P>
   Limited practice time has disrupted his conditioning and timing.
His shooting accuracy has suffered. His decisions are wrong.
Everything is a struggle. The game has suddenly gotten difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking about (the foot) too much and that's taking me
out of my game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Can he get it back? For UCLA to maintain its current pace and
thrive in the NCAA Tournament, he'd better. When in sync, Moiso is
a nearly impossible matchup for opponents: He has the wingspan of a
7-footer, the athleticism of a small forward and the jump shot of a
guard.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence the Bruins' best games _ Kentucky, Arizona,
Louisville _ were also Moiso's best games. If he struggles
Thursday, if he's timid and does not shoot well, if he falters on
defense and refuses to rebound, his team might struggle, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to be ready,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So do the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   __ In reserve: The injuries to Moiso and center Dan Gadzuric
(knee tendinitis) are not as crippling as they would have been in
recent years when the Bruins had a thin bench. This season, Travis
Reed and Matt Barnes provide adequate depth.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this is UCLA's deepest team since 1995, when the Bruins
won the national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like is I don't feel we're going to get blown out by
48,'' coach Steve Lavin said. ``I don't feel like the bottom is
going to fall out if the Scotch tape breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not one player, one foul-out, or one suspension from
getting blitzed by 38 or 40.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Coming home: It's a big weekend for freshman guard Ray Young,
an Alameda native who considered Stanford and Cal before choosing
UCLA. Young expects to have 40 to 50 friends and family members at
the Cal game Saturday at the Coliseum Arena in Oakland, a few miles
from his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to seeing my family,'' he said. ``Even the
older guys talk about how they like to go home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-08-99 2341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
