A7098 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-WINTERNATIONALS-L     02-08 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-WINTERNATIONALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN FOR DUNN ENDS NIGHTMARE RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA, Calif. _ Mike Dunn's racing nightmare is over.
</P>
<P>
   The La Mirada native, who hadn't won a NHRA national event in
more than two years, ended a 54-race losing streak by winning the
rain-delayed 39th Winternationals on Monday afternoon before a
small crowd at Pomona Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, who set a national record for elapsed time during Sunday's
eliminations, easily defeated defending champion Larry Dixon with a
4.522-second pass at 313.88 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon, who hadn't run slower than 4.57 during the first three
rounds of eliminations, smoked his tires before the 60-foot marker
and coasted to a 13.595.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Pedregon, who won two events in 1998, defeated veteran Gary
Densham in the Funny Car final. Jeg Coughlin beat brother Troy in
Pro Stock and Randy Daniels bested Brad Jeter in Pro Stock Truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a while since we tasted victory, and this one is
even sweeter,'' said Dunn, who hadn't won since the 1996 Penzoil
Nationals. ``To qualify No. 1, set the national (elapsed time)
record (4.503) and win the race all in the same weekend is as good
as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably should have had two or three wins last year. The
car was that good. But you learn from your mistakes. We changed our
attitude. Last year, we probably would have backed it down and been
on the trailer second round.''
</P>
<P>
   That showed as Dunn, who opened qualifying with a 4.63 on
Friday, made six runs in the 4.50s, including the final's 4.522.
</P>
<P>
   ``The front end came up and carried the front wheels over 100
feet past the starting line,'' said Dunn, who now owns the three
quickest runs in NHRA history. ``I had to grab the brake a little
bit to keep from getting too high.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon, who qualified sixth, was trying to become the first
driver to win the Winternationals back-to-back.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, who had a slight disadvantage on the start, was way ahead
when his engine blew just past 1,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Pedregon, coming off a 4.88 pass in the semifinals, felt the
same after his 4.970 at 311.49 mph beat Densham's 5.047 at 282.13
mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did my whole procedure like it was a Sunday,'' said
Pedregon, who was not concerned about being one of the first pair
of cars on a cold track. ``I wanted to run when it was sprinkling.
I know the conditions are just the same as the next guy and you got
Gary Densham, who has over 25 years more experience than me, but I
felt confident that my crew chief (John Medlin) was going to tune
the car close to the conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Densham was seeking his first national event victory in six
final rounds and had a slight advantage at the eighth-mile mark
before Pedregon drove around him to take the win light.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pro Stock final, Jeg Coughlin, who finished second in
points last season, drove his Oldsmobile Cutlass to a 6.969 pass.
He easily defeated Troy Coughlin, who slipped out of the groove
before the 60-foot mark and slowed to a 11.667.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, of Grantsboro, N.C., earned his first national event
victory in any category with a 7.652 in Pro Stock Truck. Jeter, who
won the Winston Finals here in November, had a 7.705 pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tickled to win it (Monday) as much as Sunday,'' Daniels
said. ``It's just a great feeling. I waited so long for this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
