<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-08 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      02-08 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland: No Invitation for Mitchell
</P>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Political leaders rejected a proposal to ask former
Sen. George Mitchell to return to Belfast to try to advance the
stalled peace effort. Mitchell supervised talks between Protestants
and Roman Catholics that led to approval last year of an agreement
to end sectarian violence. The proposal was made by Mary Harney,
the Irish deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   France: Farmers Protest in Paris
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ Farmers protesting planned changes in the European
agricultural system and proposed French taxes on pesticides broke
into the office of Environment Minister Dominique Voynet, turning
furniture upside down and throwing wheat, flour and chickpeas at
aides of Mrs. Voynet, who was out of town. About 20 people were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: War Crimes Jurors to Belarus
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Jurors in Britain's first full-scale Nazi war crimes
trial will be sent to Belarus, where Anthony Sawoniak, now 77, is
said to have murdered four Jews in 1942, to examine the scenes of
the reported crimes. Sawoniak, who lives in southern London, denies
the charges. He was a police officer in Domachevo, then under
German occupation, at the time of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Treason Charge in Uranium Case
</P>
<P>
   KARLSRUHE _ An engineer has been charged with treason for
reportedly providing Iraq with details of how to make weapons-grade
uranium, the general federal prosecutor's office here said. The
engineer, Karl-Heinz Schaab, 62, is accused of having sold the
Iraqis diagrams of equipment that would have allowed them to draw
up plans for a centrifugal device used in gathering weapons-grade
uranium.
</P>
<P>
   Armenia: Threat to Dissolve Parliament
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Kocharian said he would dissolve Parliament if
it continued to reject his efforts to strip a deputy of immunity so
that he could be tried on charges of arranging contract murders.
``I cannot reconcile myself to the fact that criminal forces may be
influencing the legislative branch,'' Kocharian said in a televised
address. The deputy, Vano Siradenyan, is a former interior
minister.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Extradition Request Denied
</P>
<P>
   Renewing its criticism of an American undercover operation that
resulted in U.S. money-laundering charges against three Mexican
banks and 26 bankers, Mexico has rejected an American request to
extradite five Mexicans implicated in the sting. Mexico also said
it would drop repeated threats to charge American agents who
extended their investigations on Mexican soil without permission.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia, Eritrea: Conflict Widens
</P>
<P>
   The border conflict between the two countries on the Horn of
Africa widened to a second front, as Ethiopian warplanes attacked
an Eritrean position near Tsorona. It was the first time that
either side had used planes in battle since they agreed to halt air
strikes in June. After an eight-month cease-fire, the two nations
resumed fighting over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Albanian Pretender Held
</P>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ King Leka, the pretender to the Albanian throne
who has lived in South Africa for nearly 20 years, was ordered held
for a week pending further investigation into arms seized in a raid
on a farm outside Johannesburg. The king and his four bodyguards
were arrested in the raid, and police seized 70 weapons, 14,000
rounds of ammunition, hand grenades, land mines and other
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: 2 Christians Slain
</P>
<P>
   ORISSA STATE _ The bodies of a young woman and boy, both tribal
Christians, were found here. Police said there was no evidence to
indicate that their killers had acted out of religious hatred. In
another case in Orissa, witnesses said Hindu militants killed a
Christian missionary and his two sons last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
