<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN HOBBLES BACK TO WORK
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Walking with aluminum crutches and a pronounced
limp, Gov. Christie Whitman returned to the New Jersey State House
on Monday for her first public appearance since breaking a leg on
Jan. 31 while skiing in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman was attending the World Economic Forum in Davos,
and was skiing with her husband during a break between meetings
when she caught the edge of her ski in hard snow and lost control,
she said. Mrs. Whitman swerved uphill, twisted and fell, snapping
both bones in her lower right leg.
</P>
<P>
   The break was so severe that Swiss surgeons used seven metal
screws to attach a titanium rod to steady her tibia, the larger
bone, as it heals. Mrs. Whitman had to cancel her trip to visit
NATO troops in Stuttgart, Germany, and a speaking engagement before
the New Jersey Chamber of Commerce at its annual excursion to
Washington last Thursday. She returned to the United States on
Thursday night and worked from her home on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman, an avid skier and gifted athlete who appeared
slightly abashed by the accident, said she was resuming her normal
schedule, with a few minor adjustments to her wardrobe and speaking
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a lot more pant suits and very short
speeches,'' she said. ``It hurts to stand in one place too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman's leg did not require a cast, but her private
physician, Dr. Robert D'Agostini, said he had urged her not to
place more than 20 percent of her weight on the leg to allow the
bone to heal. D'Agostini, flanked by before-and-after X-rays of the
governor's broken bones, said she could probably resume many of her
athletic activities in six weeks, but he said the titanium rod
would not be surgically removed for a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is scheduled to make another public appearance at
the State House on Tuesday, to sign an energy deregulation bill
into law.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman plans to stick to her busy schedule of business travel
as she recuperates. This weekend, she is to fly to Florida for a
Republican leadership event, and later this month is to attend the
National Governors' Association conference in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Whitman is to conduct a three-country swing through
South America in an attempt to strengthen trade relations between
New Jersey businesses and Latin America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
