<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DOG-SHOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSETS BECOME THE RULE AS WESTMINSTER OPENS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Fla.)  (nk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Upsets and upstarts sent shock waves through the
rarefied air of this champions-only canine competition Monday when
the 123rd annual Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show got under way at
Madison Square Garden. It was amateur hour in the Working and
Terrier groups when the first two of the seven finalists eligible
to compete for Best-in-Show were identified.
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned troopers like Ch. Toledobes Serenghetti, the Doberman
who has been among the top five success stories on the all-breeds
list for the past three years, and Ch. Sweetsound's King O' Rock N
Roll, the West Highland white terrier who was top terrier in the
nation in 1998, found themselves in the doghouse instead of their
accustomed penthouse.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Sera, the sleek red Dobe, she was evicted from
the Garden by a three-year-old Bernese mountain dog, Ch. Mentmore's
Windy Meadow, in the Working group last night. The 3-year-old
Windy, a 95-pound smiler who sleeps with her handler, Diane Kiester
of Warrenton, Va., has 15 group victories, but none as vaunted as
this one.
</P>
<P>
   Although Windy plays second fiddle at home and on the road to
Kiester's bossy Chesapeake retriever, ``She's No. 1 tonight,'' said
the handler, who termed Windy a slow starter in show business.
``She had some issues; she was a little shy, but now she's feeling
right at home with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Elvis, the Westie who was expected to take center
stage in the Terrier group, comeuppance descended in the form of a
total tenderfoot, the two-year-old, 18-pound Welsh terrier, Ch.
Sunspryte's Just in Thyme. One of a phalanx of top prospects owned
by Bill Cosby and Jean Heath, Moxie, as the terrier is known
informally, is at the beginning of her show career: this was her
third group victory in her first real season on the campaign trail,
and her handler, Doug Carlson, had never been at the other end of
her leash before. He was filling in for Cosby's main trainer, Clay
Coady, who handled Cosby's Lakeland terrier Ch. Revelry's Awesome
Blossom, the fourth-place finisher.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Moxie, the judge of the Terrier group, Elaine Rigden,
admitted that she experienced something akin to love at first
sight: ``She was just so exciting to watch. I thought she showed
her heart out.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the breed ring at the Garden is every incumbent's
Armageddon, where the reputation you made for yourself last year
can be shattered in an instant by a judge who prefers novelty to
nostalgia, 90 breed winners from 1998 returned to tempt fate by
attempting a repeat. And the breed judges, too, pointed their
fingers in some unexpected directions Monday, particularly among
the pint-size toy contingent.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest upset occurred in the Maltese ring, where 17 lapdogs
pitter-pattered through their paces for judge Gilbert Kahn, who
then instigated something of a family drama when he homed in on a
two-year-old novice, Ch. Merri Bentley, at the expense of the
four-year-old incumbent, Ch. Ta-Jon's Tickle Me Silly. Silly, as
she's known when she's off-duty, which has not been often in the
last two years of hard campaigning, didn't much feel like living up
to her nickname after being knocked off her pedestal by her own
nephew.
</P>
<P>
   ''We beat Aunt Silly, and she's not too happy about it,'' said
Bentley's ebullient 28-year-old handler, Jason Hoke of East Berlin,
Pa. According to Hoke, Bentley simply presented Kahn with a more
refined silhouette than his celebrated aunt.
</P>
<P>
   The silky white Maltese bitch, who has accumulated nearly 100
bests-in-show to her nephew's none, was fourth overall on the
all-breeds list in 1998 and came into Westminster semiretired due
to impending motherhood. Still, Silly, who belongs to Sam and
Marion Lawrence of Orlando, Fla., owners of Westminster's
Best-in-Show wire fox terrier in 1992, had been touted as a
potential favorite to defend her breed title and also claim the Toy
group. Instead, she settled for being the runner-up to Bentley, who
seemed oblivious to the insult he had dealt his aunt and her human
support squad.
</P>
<P>
   While Silly stewed, Bentley trotted back to his crate for a
reunion with his favorite toy, a stuffed rat. And Hoke explained
why he didn't really feel like a rat for ousting Aunt Silly: ``I'd
never shown him against her before; we kind of feel like she had
her time, and now it's his turn in the spotlight.'' Hoke spent
three hours fine-tuning Bentley's white coat for the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a pretty lively guy, so he messes his hair up more than
the calm ones do,'' Hoke said of Bentley, who earned his champion
status 10 shows ago and has accumulated three group victories.
</P>
<P>
   Hoke added: ``They're a hard breed to show; you have to keep
their hair wrapped. It's a lot of work and a lot of time spent on a
five-pound dog; that's why people hate to lose. Keeping white dogs
white is a real job.''
</P>
<P>
   Propriety reigned in the poodle ring once the breed competition
switched to the Standard size: Ch. Lake Cove That's My Boy, the
55-pound beauty who captured the Non-Sporting group here last year
and finished 1998 as the top dog all-breeds, endured five hours of
primping on his white pompadour before floating into the breed ring
and reprising his performance from last year. Tre-son, as the
poodle is known, owns 110 career bests, defeated 95,723 canines in
1998, and will call this show his swan song should he manage to
emerge top dog from the 2,500 champions who entered.
</P>
</TEXT>
